<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SUNS-HNS &LR;      04-26 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SUNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHOENIX _ For today's Rockets quiz, we play ``Pick the worst
loss.'' Is it worse to:
<TEXT>
<P>
   A. Lose to the Mavericks at home;
</P>
<P>
   B. Lose to the Clippers anywhere; or
</P>
<P>
   C. Lose to the Suns by 24?
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets don't know, and really don't care, having completed
all of the above with a 95-71 loss to the Suns on Sunday at America
West Arena to send them home with their longest losing streak of
the season and their worst loss since a 40-point blowout in
Portland on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   That loss was understandably blamed on a back-to-back schedule
complicated by travel problems in Vancouver. This time, the Rockets
could only credit the Suns and blame themselves, having lost most
of their offensive touch and all of their defensive intensity in
the past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere, we're going to have to make a stand, looking in the
mirror, looking within and saying, `What can I do?''' Rockets coach
Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``You've got to do it with defense, which is
nonexistent. We're not doing anything well right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got an empty feeling watching us play right now. I don't
see that fire. I don't see that fight.''
</P>
<P>
   One week after leading the Spurs by 23 in a game to take a share
of third place in the Western Conference, the Rockets are just a
half-game ahead of the similarly struggling Lakers heading into
their likely playoff preview tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have slipped so precipitously, they matched their
worst scoring game of the season, finishing with the fewest points
anyone has scored against the Suns. And the Rockets considered
offense the bright spot.
</P>
<P>
   They were dominated by Jason Kidd, who began the day sick to his
stomach, was still asleep 30 minutes before tipoff, turned an ankle
and smashed his arm into a television monitor. He was two-thirds of
the way to a triple double by halftime, grabbed his 10th rebound to
a standing ovation with 1:47 left and, when not in the training
room, added 22 points and 14 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before our pre-game meeting in the locker room, he was
sleeping,'' Suns coach Danny Ainge said. ``We had to wake him up.
Then he came out and played the way he did. The guy is amazing.
Then he fell on his shoulder. The guy is unbelievable. He finds a
way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Rockets left America West Arena on Sunday, their
fortunes had changed so radically, the problem on offense had
become getting Scottie Pippen some help.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had a second consecutive 20-point game for the first time
this season, getting 21 points and eight rebounds after his triple
double in the loss to the Clippers on Friday night. Hakeem Olajuwon
and Charles Barkley were each three points below their averages,
scoring 16 and 13 points, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problem offensively, as it was in Los Angeles on
Friday, was that the Rockets got so little from their shooters
circling the Big Three outside. The Other Eight combined to make
just nine of 41 shots and just three of 18 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, against a team that ranks 25th in opponents' field-goal
percentage, the Rockets made just 26 of 74 shots (35.1 percent),
their worst shooting night since the rout in Portland, which was
their season low.
</P>
<P>
   As with the Clippers on Friday, the Suns double-teamed inside
rapidly and confidently, unconcerned that the Rockets' shooters
would burn them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed a thousand shots,'' Tomjanovich said. ``When you
shoot that bad, it makes you look like you're playing really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake, defensively, they were really bad _ and
have been since the start of the second half against Seattle on
April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns did not have a particularly scorching shooting night,
making 48.6 percent. But they had no trouble getting the sort of
good, open looks that would prevent any sustained Rockets comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we came out and set the tone of our style of
play,'' Pippen said. ``That has to be set on the defensive end.
Teams are coming out and just scoring too many points. It's an
uphill climb from the start of the game because we're not stopping
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our offense is a problem now. We're not stopping
teams. If you keep it in the 90s or the high 80s, you have a chance
of beating teams. We have to come out and lay it all on the line.
Right now, we're in a dogfight.''
</P>
<P>
   But they are not fighting back. Three of the Rockets' past four
opponents have surpassed 100 points. In the first 40 games, the
Rockets allowed more than 100 points eight times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not challenging anybody (defensively),'' Pippen said.
``We're not pointing fingers. We all have to step up. But we have
to go and double-team and rotate on every play we run. We have to
take on the (man-to-man) challenge. We're not defending night in
and night out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, that prevented the Rockets from putting real heat on the
Suns' lead. They moved to within 12 or 11 points with the
basketball several times but never could get consecutive stops.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Rockets were as close as 11, after a Michael
Dickerson jumper to start the fourth quarter, Kidd was off getting
X-rayed. But Rex Chapman made consecutive 3s and the lead was back
to 17 within one minute of Dickerson's basket.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley and Antoine Carr hit jumpers to move the Rockets within
13. But Danny Manning flicked the ball away from Pippen and pulled
up on a break for a short jumper. Pippen was called for a technical
foul for arguing that Manning had smacked his arm, and George
McCloud's free throw pushed the lead back to 16.
</P>
<P>
   With that, Kidd returned and the Rockets never challenged again,
making their fourth loss in five games complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started with the bad loss to Dallas and has been downhill
from there,'' Olajuwon said, though it might have seemed at the
time that there was nothing further down the hill than losing at
home to Dallas. ``We just have to stop the bleeding and build it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   But at this point, the more difficult question is, ``Can they do
it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
