u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-HNS &LR;      04-26 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ The Los Angeles Lakers don't want to hear any of the
Rockets' sad songs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Lakers, the preseason favorites to win the Western
Conference, limp into Houston for tonight's game against the
Rockets at Compaq Center with some sad songs of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the theme of tonight's game could be, ``You've got your
troubles, I've got mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The wilting Rockets have suffered embarrassing losses to the
Mavericks and the Los Angeles Clippers over the past week, but
their situation isn't worse than the plight of the Lakers, who have
tried everything _ firing a coach, signing Dennis Rodman, making a
major trade and then releasing Rodman _ in their quest to get over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   Changes like that in a season like this, with no practice time,
no training camp and games crammed together in an unending
procession, make for potentially disastrous results.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are far from a disaster _ they take a 27-18 record
into tonight's game _ but they are widely viewed as a
disappointment. They are a team in search of wins, rhythm,
chemistry and, most of all, stability, all the things the Lakers
have not had of late, especially over the past couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 11, the Lakers have lost to Seattle, Portland (by 27
points), Utah (by 16), Portland again and San Antonio (another
27-point blowout).
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play (tonight) like we have in some games, then we have
no chance for a title,'' Shaquille O'Neal said Saturday. ``If we
can continue to improve, then we have a chance. We have to play
smart. We've been doing some stupid things, like not getting the
ball to shooters. I have no idea why.''
</P>
<P>
   So Lakers coach Kurt Rambis, who took over Feb. 26, two days
after Del Harris was fired, comes to Houston looking to improve his
team. If the Lakers win the game, fine. But Rambis is looking at a
bigger picture, which means getting ready for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of all the changes we've gone through, all the
disruptions that have happened on our ballclub and the struggling
phase that we're going through right now, I'm just looking to make
the team improve,'' Rambis said. ``I want to help the team improve
to give us the best chance in the playoffs. Regardless of whether
we win or lose ballgames, we have to get to the point where we're
improving as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it was kind of disappointing that we didn't take a
step forward in (Saturday's) game, but that's part of the learning
curve. You never learn on a straight, upward motion. You learn a
little bit, fall back and make some mistakes, then you move forward
again and learn from your mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, numbers-wise and all that stuff, it (tonight's
game) is a big ballgame. But to me, if we don't use it as another
game to improve, then we're defeating the purpose of playing right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is how the Lakers' season has gone.
</P>
<P>
   A 61-win team last season, the Lakers were viewed as somehow
wanting this season. Out went Harris, and in came Rambis, a
reminder of the Lakers' glory Showtime years.
</P>
<P>
   Also coming in and making himself at home was Rodman, who was
viewed as the ``thug'' power forward O'Neal had been demanding for
so long. With so much of the offensive burden falling on his
shoulders, O'Neal craved a tough-minded power forward who would
rebound and play post defense. That has always been the bulk of
Rodman's rsum.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers weren't done.
</P>
<P>
   Out went longtime Lakers Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell, shipped
to Charlotte for disgruntled sharpshooter Glen Rice. But while the
Lakers' super team was being assembled piece by piece, Rodman
appeared just as intent on tearing down everything, missing
practices, refusing to report into games and requesting leaves of
absence for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the brass had enough of the oddball forward, waiving
him April 15.
</P>
<P>
   It has made for interesting watching, and the television
networks took advantage, televising 26 of the Lakers' 50 games
nationally. Included in the package was Saturday's game against the
Spurs, a 108-81 loss that underscored all that is wrong with the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed with our effort (against the Spurs),''
Rambis said. ``They outworked us. We're not going to do anything or
go anywhere if we get outworked, so I was disappointed that our
overall, 100 percent, all-the-time effort wasn't there. There were
guys who did it sometimes, other guys who did it other times, but
that's not the way you improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way you play against playoff teams, and it's
not the way you play against teams that are extremely hot, like the
Spurs. You have to go out there with the maximum effort all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even tonight, against the slumping Rockets, who have dropped
consecutive games to Dallas, the Clippers and the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go in there and play well,'' O'Neal said. ``You
know, we match up pretty well with those guys. We're a similar team
_ dominant big men, dominant (small forwards), a lot of role
players around; they have shooters, and we have shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to play with a lot of fire. We know that they're
going to be pumped up. We just have to be ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   And O'Neal is ready to renew his battle with Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hakeem is the best big man ever, to me,'' O'Neal said. ``Of
course I have to be on my P's and Q's when I play against him, and
I usually play well against him. He's going to do his thing, and
I'm going to do my thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
