<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT NAACP DINNER, GORE PRAISES AFFIRMATIVE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Proclaiming that his father had been voted out of the
Senate largely for his support of civil rights legislation, Vice
President Al Gore on Sunday night affirmed his commitment to
fighting ``the cruelties of the heart that have been attributed to
prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the annual dinner of the Detroit chapter of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, Gore
drew a standing ovation as he belittled critics of affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know in your heart, as I know in mine, that there is
absolutely nothing more important to the future of the United
States of America than taking us past the burden of history, taking
us past the barriers of injustice, taking us past the cruelties of
the heart that have been attributed to prejudice,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech at the annual civil rights dinner _ an event so
large that there are four separate daises for honored guests, one
in each corner of the hall _ drew particular attention because it
came at a time when racial discord has emerged as an early issue in
the Democratic presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, the only prominent
Democrat seeking the presidential nomination besides Gore, has
moved to seize the issue of race relations. In a speech last week
at Cooper Union in New York, Bradley said ending racial inequities
would be a recurring topic of his campaign and, if he were elected,
a central concern of his White House.
</P>
<P>
   With the speech, Bradley moved to embrace an issue that has been
closely identified with President Clinton during his years as a
national figure. This clearly concerned Gore's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president made clear on Sunday night that he shared
Bradley's concern about what both men had described as the
continuing racial turmoil in the country. And like Bradley, Gore
drew on his family history to illustrate that point.
</P>
<P>
   In his New York speech, Bradley recounted the story of an aunt
who had repeatedly used racial epithets. In Detroit on Sunday
night, Gore recalled that his father, who like Gore had served as a
U.S. senator from Tennessee, had voted for civil rights laws _ a
stance, Gore said, that had probably cost his father his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sacrificed his career because he was willing to stand for
what he believed,'' Gore said. ``I thank God my father taught me to
love justice. I thank God that my family taught me to hate
discrimination as the evil that it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were clear differences between what Gore and Bradley
said. Bradley mentioned affirmative action only in passing in his
speech at Cooper Union. By contrast, Gore gave it a full-throated
endorsement in his remarks to this mostly black audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the critics of affirmative action,'' Gore said as
the audience rose to its feet, hooting and cheering. He added:
``They talk about a color-blind society. Give me a break! Hel-lo!
They use their `color-blind' the way duck hunters use their duck
blind. They hide behind it and hope the ducks won't figure out what
they're up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides had disparaged Bradley's speech for failing to
offer detailed ideas on how the nation might deal with racism. The
vice president appeared to make the same point on Sunday night,
without mentioning Bradley's name, by suggesting that he had more
substantive proposals to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Gore called on Congress to finance new empowerment zones, urban
areas that use tax reductions and other measures to promote job
development. And he decried the use by police of racial profiling
in identifying suspects for questioning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
