</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TAYLOR-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS FUTURE IS TAYLOR-MADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Clippers ambassador to
``SportsCenter'' is moving through a diplomatic channel connecting
the dressing room and the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   His young constituents hail him as the rim-slaying ``Mo,'' and
he is wading through them without immunity or a spotter. But an
entourage is not in the current budget. The lead role for
Tinseltown's B-rated NBA franchise requires the 6-foot-8, 260-pound
power forward to perform his own stunts.
</P>
<P>
   They include writing and rewriting, so he scribbles ``Maurice
Taylor'' over and over on typical treasures of memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the market value of one Maurice Taylor autograph may
exceed $70 million scoots.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers should be offering him the pen in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a very big summer for this team,'' says
the 22-year-old Taylor, who is hammering stardom's door with one
season remaining on the three-year Clipper contract he signed after
leaving Michigan one year early. ``I would love to stay here, but
that's for them to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Never fear; those Clipper minds hired for the purpose of casting
already have decided. If they had absolute control of the payroll,
Taylor would be offered the league's maximum contract extension of
six years for the aforementioned 70 mil and change.
</P>
<P>
   But until team owner Donald T. Sterling endorses that decision,
Clipper fans (with a success rate of 9-35, they're more like cult
members) won't breathe until the coast is clear. With a dread
constructed by history, they realize their emerging go-to guy could
go to another city. And it's impossible to have a crowd favorite
without a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the go-to guy wouldn't mind staying put here in Mo-town
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we've been playing shows promise for next year,''
Taylor says of the uprising (6-5) the Clippers hope to continue
when the San Antonio Spurs step into the Sports Arena tonight.
``Things are falling into place. Now management has to step up to
the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Sterling refuses to part with the prevailing simoleons,
there will be no shortage of teams eager to take a swing at Taylor,
whose first hoop deal was worth a cool $100.
</P>
<P>
   The offer was made seven years ago by his grandfather, Leroy
Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice had been a football lifer who stood 6-1 as a freshman at
Detroit's Henry Ford High, but was pushing 6-8 midway through his
sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor winces at the recollection of his personal growth: ``My
knees were killin' me all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't prevent him from exploiting his new altitude in the
heady politics of playground basketball.
</P>
<P>
   His personal review: ``I thought I was pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   But Leroy Taylor wouldn't be impressed until Maurice made his
mark in organized ball. The coach at Ford had noticed the kid's
pituitary bonanza and had been pestering him to grab a uniform, so
all young Mo needed was clinical incentive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather bet me one-hundred dollars that I couldn't hang
with the guys on the high school team,'' Taylor says. ``A little
reverse psychology. So I played the last eight games.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Mo's hang time force his grandfather to pay up?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no doubt,'' Taylor says. ``He had to.''
</P>
<P>
   After Leroy Taylor passed away in 1993, his grandson paid him
back.
</P>
<P>
   You may have noticed Maurice Taylor in moments of glory, tapping
his right fist on the No. 23 stitched to his Clipper jersey. What
you probably haven't seen is the picture of Leroy Taylor tattooed
on Mo's chest, or the letters spelling out ``Leroy Taylor'' on each
heel of his Nikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it,'' Maurice explains ``to have him with me, because he
wouldn't be able to see me play anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Taylor's $100 has bought the NBA another precocious turk
with sizzle and enough skill to help bury Clipper tradition. In the
last lap of a tight game, he'll stroll past the skid row of
courtside reporters, sigh in a demonstration of profound fatigue
and announce, ``They're killin' me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has drawn a parallel between questionable officiating and the
animated sitcom ``South Park.'' After a WWF-style run-in with power
forward barometer Karl Malone, he dismissed ``The Mailman'' as
``...just another (compound expletive) on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   He scored 14 consecutive points to rally the Clippers - the same
0-17 bunch that threatened to have its own chump chapter in the NBA
record book - to victory over the mighty Trail Blazers ... in
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a good player,'' Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich said
after Taylor put a career-high 29 points on his Rockets three
nights back, ``he's a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   But his decision to leave Michigan with one year of eligibility
remaining did not inspire absolute joy in the NBA. Marty Blake, the
league's official arbiter of talent, announced that Taylor's choice
was a tactical blunder.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers disagreed. They were stunned when he was available
at pick No. 14 of the 1997 NBA Draft, so they wadded up their
point-guard shopping list and selected Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   He produced 11.5 points per game last season under Coach Bill
``The Rookie Killer'' Fitch, and was named to the All-Rookie second
team.
</P>
<P>
   After the lockout didn't include an embargo on his kitchen,
Taylor reported to this season's abbreviated training camp as more
of a player than he needed to be. His weakened knees recovered in
time for a 21-point, 20-rebound effort in the season's sixth game,
a double-overtime loss to Vancouver. He sprained his right knee
nine days later, bounced back after two games in street clothes,
and played in 19 more before surrendering to double Achilles
tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   He missed two more Clipper defeats, but has provided several
``monster games'' - often the subject of pre-game prediction -
since. This Godzilla pantomime includes a 26 points-per-game
average over the last five screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo's just been playing great basketball,'' first-year Clipper
coach Chris Ford says. ``He has the potential to be an outstanding
player.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential is obvious as Taylor attacks the basket like
someone busting curfew at the ATM. And his face-up game now
includes a trusty jump shot that is released at full (contract)
extension.
</P>
<P>
   One area of improvement in Ford's crosshairs is rebounding.
Along with his 17 points per game, Taylor averages a tick over five
rebounds, not enough for a talented power forward who otherwise is
as bashful as the underdog in Round 12.
</P>
<P>
   After tracking down eight rebounds in a recent game, he was
informed that the effort was not lost on Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really? I thought it was more than eight,'' Taylor said.
``Well, if it's eight, then he (Ford) has to take what he can
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald T. Sterling should be advised to do the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
