<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES26-CO     04-26 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    C. Jones to sit with groin pull
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Third baseman Chipper Jones has a strained adductor
(groin) muscle in his left thigh and is expected to miss at least
one game.
</P>
<P>
   Jones pulled up in pain in the third inning Sunday running from
first to third base on a ground ball by Brian Jordan. Jones
continued playing for the next four innings but came out after
hitting into a fielder's choice in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like I had a knot in my groin,'' Jones said. ``It
didn't really hurt that bad, but as more and more time went by and
it moved farther down my leg, it started to hurt. ... It's sharp.
It's tugging pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jones is unable to play today, he'll be replaced by Keith
Lockhart, who made his second start of the season at second base
Sunday and went 2-for-4 with one RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Playing time
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Ozzie Guillen, like Lockhart, started for the second
time Sunday. The last time they started was 11 games ago. They each
have one pinch hit this season, in four at-bats for Guillen and
seven at-bats for Lockhart, and have driven in a pair of runs.
</P>
<P>
   But by getting them back in the lineup now, Cox hoped to help
get them more comfortable at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sit them too long,'' Cox said. ``You start smelling
when you need to get them in there. It's a feel thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, Lockhart had only 12 at-bats. Besides his three
hits in two starts, he's had one other hit, pinch-hitting on April
12. Guillen had only 10 at-bats and went hitless in four that April
11 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work harder when you don't play every day,'' said Guillen,
who was the starting shortstop for the Chicago White Sox for 13
years. ``You take extra batting practice, take ground balls in
different places. When you start, you just show up and play. I just
try to stay focused and stay in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart has had to readjust to life on the bench with the
arrival of Bret Boone. In 1997, when he was used primarily as a
pinch hitter until Mark Lemke got hurt in August, Lockhart was
second in the majors with 18 pinch-hit RBIs and tied for fifth in
Atlanta history with 15 pinch hits.
</P>
<P>
   On hitting No. 8
</P>
<P>
   Sunday might not have been the off day Walt Weiss wanted, but he
could relax and enjoy it, having solved some of the hitting
problems that stifled him to start the season. Weiss is on a
seven-game hitting streak, including two-hit games in each of the
last three, to raise his average from .160 to .269.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss attributes the streak to getting back in the groove of
being a No. 8 hitter. Despite all his experience at hitting eighth
in Oakland and Colorado, he had to remind himself how to go about
doing it best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I went overboard,'' Weiss said. ``I tried to expand my
strike zone too much. As an eighth hitter you've got to do that at
times with runners on base and the pitcher coming up behind you.
You have to avoid a walk to make sure they're not pitching around
you. Other times you do want to go deep in the count to turn the
lineup over.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said he made an adjustment in his stance during spring
training, holding his hands higher and further back in his stance,
that was allowing him to drive the ball more. ``Unfortunately I was
successful with it,'' said Weiss. ``It got me away from what I do
best, which is making people pitch deep in the count, get on base
and make contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer update
</P>
<P>
   Russ Springer continues to pitch well on his rehabilitation
assignment in Class AAA Richmond as he recovers from back surgery.
He pitched another scoreless inning Saturday night against
Louisville, giving up his first hit and striking out one. In three
innings, he walked none and struck out two.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
