<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS &LR;      04-26 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-REDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CINCINNATI _ If you subscribe to the theory that the same things
that make you laugh can also make you cry, it's safe to assume the
Astros could have shed enough tears to float themselves home after
Sunday's loss at Cinergy Field.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day after having a few chuckles at the expense of the
Cincinnati bullpen, they got a lesson in turnabout as the Reds
added to Doug Henry's miseries in beating the Astros 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 5-1 through four innings, the Astros tied
the game with four runs in the fifth, only to see their comeback
bid foiled when the Reds scored twice off Henry in the sixth. After
the game, Henry revealed that his season-long struggles have been
associated with discomfort in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making excuses,'' he said. ``I'm not 100 percent, but
this is the best my elbow has felt. The bottom line is that when I
go out there, I should get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was easier said than done Sunday, not just for Henry
(0-1) but also for starter Sean Bergman, who lasted just four
innings and left the Astros with a four-run deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense did their job, and the defense did their job,''
Bergman said. ``But I didn't do mine. When you score six runs, that
should be enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning the first two games of the road trip at Chicago,
the Astros dropped two of three to the Reds before returning to
Houston, where tonight they will open a four-game homestand against
the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Astros' record to 9-8 _ the identical mark
they posted after 17 games in 1998, when they finished with a
franchise-best 102 victories and won their second National League
Central title in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not satisfied with playing .500 ball, and I don't think
any of our players are,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``We
can play better than we've been playing, and I believe we will.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the criticism the bullpen has taken in the first three
weeks of the season, Sunday was the first time an Astros reliever
has been charged with a loss. The Astros' relievers have combined
for a 3-1 record and a 3.75 ERA, with seven saves in seven
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The most inconsistent performer of the group has been Henry,
whose ERA jumped to 8.64 after Sunday's outing. Henry entered the
game in the sixth inning and gave up a leadoff homer to Reds second
baseman Pokey Reese, who is known more for his slick fielding than
his pop at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the next six batters reached against Henry, including
Mike Cameron, who hit a one-out triple and scored on Greg Vaughn's
single to left. Considering how Henry has struggled this season, it
was somewhat surprising Dierker decided to use him in such a
crucial situation.
</P>
<P>
   Why not stick with Brian Williams, who had retired the Reds in
order in the fifth inning?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about that,'' Dierker said. ``But Brian was pretty
sore. He threw 60-something pitches (Friday) night, and he was
having trouble getting loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Scott Elarton had worked two innings Saturday, it made
sense to save Jay Powell for the late innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had wanted me to go back out there, I could have,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Reds got a strong effort from their bullpen as
Friendswood native Scott Williamson pitched the final three innings
in relief of starter Pete Harnisch. Williamson retired nine of the
10 batters he faced, including four on strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell's two-out solo home run gave the Astros hope in the
ninth, but Williamson struck out Jeff Bagwell to end the game and
pick up his first big-league save.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some chances,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio
said. ``We had the tying run at the plate when the game ended; it
just wasn't meant to be. Williamson pretty much got everybody
out.''
</P>
<P>
   After setting down the first three batters he faced, Bergman had
trouble getting just about anybody out. Sean Casey led off the
Cincinnati second with a single and scored on a wild pitch, while
Eddie Taubensee and Cameron each produced RBI singles in the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Boone plated another run with a sacrifice fly in the
third, and Vaughn singled home a run in the fourth. The most
un-Bergman-like aspect of Sunday's game was the fact he walked four
batters _ a total he exceeded only once in 27 starts last year. He
also threw two wild pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't being as aggressive as I should have been,'' Bergman
said. ``The walks are frustrating, because I consider myself to be
a pitcher who is not going to walk a lot of guys. I just didn't
find the strike zone very often.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored four runs in a fifth-inning outburst keyed by
Ken Caminiti's two-run homer off Harnisch (2-2). Bagwell hit his
team-leading fifth home run in the fourth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
