u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICS-WIZARDS-B     04-26 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-WIZARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUGHER LIFTS CELTICS' SPIRITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sunday afternoon began with a joke and ended with a
series of them. Before anyone had taken a shot on the FleetCenter
parquet, Rick Pitino approached injured Celtic Antoine Walker. The
smiling coach picked up a towel and draped it over the player's
suit, a two-toned sky blue number with checkers.
</P>
<P>
   Both men laughed at the gesture. They would do that a lot over
the 48 minutes that followed. And so would Paul Pierce, Damon
Jones, Walter McCarty, Dana Barros, Ron Mercer, and most of the
17,211 fans. Everyone was involved. All of their laughter led to
the raucous punch line of the day: Celtics 113, Wizards 84.
</P>
<P>
   With two minutes remaining and the Celtics ahead by 28, Pitino
once again approached the end of the bench. Walker, Pierce, and
McCarty all were telling jokes. Pitino wanted McCarty to go in the
game, but the forward was laughing so hard that he didn't hear the
request.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter,'' Pitino called again. ``What are you doing,
socializing?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. What else was there to do? The Wizards were no fun.
They shot 40 percent, handled the ball as if they were playing the
old childhood game of ``Hot Potato,'' and reinforced their pregame
advertising as a team that will get coaches (see Bernie
Bickerstaff) fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not here today,'' Jim Brovelli said after the game. In
most cases, that comment would elicit some laughter, too. But
Brovelli is the unfortunate man given the title of Wizards interim
coach. Keep him in your prayers; he is required to watch this team
for six more games.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics didn't make things easier for him. Barros was on the
court for 26 minutes and produced 20 points, 8 assists, and 6
rebounds. He had only one steal, but even that was memorable: He
stripped the ball cleanly from Rod Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was a game from which you walked away talking about
favorite plays rather than key possessions. One of those plays was
by Mercer, who finished with 18 points. In the third quarter, the
6-foot-7-inch guard drove the baseline and saw Mitch Richmond in
his face. Both men jumped and suddenly Richmond was looking at
Mercer's chest while the Celtics guard was eye-to-eye with the rim,
finishing a ferocious dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't jumped like that since, probably, last year,''
Mercer said. ``I don't know if I could do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercer had missed four games with back spasms. He also had
missed some time with a sore knee and ankle. He said the four-game
layoff bored him but probably helped the strength in his legs.
</P>
<P>
   When Mercer wasn't dunking, he had plenty of entertainment
opportunities. He could have watched Barros, Vitaly Potapenko (16
points), the 15 points and six assists of rookie Jones, or the 17
points of his college teammate, McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   ``His shooting was like a Florida State kicker,'' Pitino said of
McCarty's early-season shooting. ``You know: wide right, wide
left.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarty laughed when he heard that. ``I haven't even played that
much this year,'' he said, referring to knee and toe injuries.
Before Sunday's season high in points, McCarty's highlight had been
signing a three-year, $8.4 million contract extension on his
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   A 23-year-old guard from Houston wouldn't mind a contract like
that. A few days ago, Jones was sweating over his next 10-day deal
with the Celtics. Sunday, he was cracking his teammates up by
diving on the floor in the fourth quarter and doing a little dance
while on his belly. He was asked the name of that dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the Rick Pitino Dance,'' he said. ``You got to get on
the floor or you'll be on the bench. Y'all know how that goes
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff likes Jones because of his hustle and
shooting. The players like him because he specializes in breaking
up a quiet room with a funny comment. And he likes everybody
because, he says, they take care of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm staying in a hotel right now,'' he said. ``These guys come
by and take me to practice, take me to dinner. It's nice to know
there are guys like that; I love these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the afternoon, most of the Celtics had a feel-good
story. Pitino was saying again that he wished the season could be
extended. Mercer was saying that ``I'm sure we can turn it around''
and that he has wanted to remain a Celtic since the day they
drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the fourth quarter, when it was obvious the Celtics were
going to win their 18th game of the season, Walker shouted to the
court, ``Get the ball to Shin Man.'' He was talking about Dwayne
Schintzius, who averages 0.6 points per game. But Sunday, even
Schintzius scored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
