<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-JAZZ-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS ON OUTSIDE, LOOKING IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Don MacLean could hardly get off the team bus
before having a camera thrust into his face.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the national television crew tailed the suddenly popular
Sonics forward down the halls of the Delta Center. MacLean, who has
played well in the absence of All-Star Vin Baker, was Sunday's
pregame fodder. That alone speaks volumes about how much the Sonics
are stretching to grab a playoff spot this late in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, cameras barely got a glimpse of MacLean because he
was so far at the end of the team's bench.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, though, NBC had a vision before the Sonics were
flattened by the Utah Jazz 98-81 Sunday at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   MacLean was the only one who heard the call for action when the
spotlight came on.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Sonics were blinded by it.
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain a game where only two Sonics _ MacLean
had 23 points and Dale Ellis had 10 _ score in double figures, and
the team shoots 38 percent?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't make baskets, you can't beat the Jazz in Utah,''
Sonics coach Paul Westphal said. ``The Jazz are too good. If you're
not sharp, you're not going to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Sonics, MacLean was the only player who
could score. He finished with his third straight 20-plus scoring
night, which had been a great compliment in two previous outings.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gary Payton scored a season-low five points on 2-of-11
shooting, and every other starter was held below 10 points. It is
hard to imagine the Sonics would have beaten many teams with such
little production.
</P>
<P>
   The timing was just as bad.
</P>
<P>
   With Sacramento idle and Phoenix's win against Houston, the
Sonics snuggled up to the ninth seed in the Western Conference
playoff picture. They are one-half game behind Minnesota for the
eighth and final playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had their two-game winning streak snapped. Sunday's
game was so lopsided, the starters had plenty of time in the fourth
to look at the scoreboard for scores of games involving the other
playoff hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the season is over because we lost today,''
Hawkins said. ``If we continue to play good basketball, the
playoffs will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are on the outside looking up in the playoff
standings for the first time this season. They are in jeopardy of
missing the postseason for the first time since the 1989-90 season
if their position stays the same through the final six games.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday does not get any easier because the Sonics face Utah in
a rematch at KeyArena. Seattle then travels to Portland on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what the Sonics will do immediately is forget about
Sunday's loss. They led 4-2 after two minutes expired in the first
quarter. The Sonics fought to overcome a double-digit deficit the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   How bad was the game?
</P>
<P>
   Near the end, the Jazz mascot stood by the Sonics' bench dressed
in a Grim Reaper costume. Payton, Detlef Schrempf, Olden Polynice
and Hersey Hawkins refused to pay attention to the fourth-quarter
mockery.
</P>
<P>
   They instead watched Utah hold on to most of its 24-point,
fourth-quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we were playing the Clippers or somebody,'' said
Hawkins, who was 2-for-7 from the floor with eight points. ``We are
playing the best team in the league. The Jazz are as solid
defensively as any team in the league. You don't come in here and
expect to shoot a high percentage.''
</P>
<P>
   However, that does not address the Sonics' inability to slow
down Utah's Karl Malone (21 points, eight rebounds) and their poor
rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of energy on the glass allowed Utah to outscore the
Sonics 19-5 in second-chance points. The Sonics were unable to run
their fast break and create easy shot attempts, which accounted for
eight fewer shots than Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team has been inconsistent all year,'' said MacLean, who
hit a few jumpers but mostly drove the lane looking for baskets.
``We've got to make some shots and rebound. With the (small lineup)
we have now, the key is getting out in transition.''
</P>
<P>
   They also need Payton. When he is off as much as Sunday, the
Sonics usually don't have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, Payton was not his usual aggressive self.
He passed up shots but dished out 10 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Payton did not talk to the media after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he'll say it, but I think he was ill,''
Westphal said. ``He just didn't have the energy and he couldn't
make shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton missed five of his first six shots, and the Sonics shot
just 30 percent in the first. They trailed 25-16 after the period.
MacLean scored nine points in the second and kept the Sonics
relatively close at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Utah extended its 50-39 halftime lead to 15 points,
the Sonics charged back. Trailing 62-54 with 5:02 left in the
third, Hawkins had a chance to get the Sonics within five. But he
missed a wide-open 3-pointer in front of the Jazz bench.
</P>
<P>
   Utah then took off. The Jazz led 74-60 heading into the fourth.
The Sonics then fell victim to Utah's 14-2 run that started the
final period.
</P>
<P>
   Game over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
