</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S HOPING CHANCES AREN'T FLEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON _ If Monday night you're coming to the Vault, the
Hub's hockey home of bountiful profit but dwindling fortune, the
Bruins hope you'll wear something black, something gold. Borrow it,
if you must.
</P>
<P>
   For their sake, they'd like to borrow something old: a
postseason victory on home ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have won only one of their last 11 playoff games on
Causeway Street, dating back to Round 2 in '94, in the beloved
bygone days when the Garden was in its death rattle and a trip to
Boston in the springtime was no tiptoe through the tulips for the
visiting team. In the opening round of the '94 playoffs, the Bruins
bumped off the dreaded Canadiens, clinching the series with a
thrilling 5-3 win over the Habs in Game 7 at the Garden. The Bruins
haven't won a series since then.
</P>
<P>
   Now, enter the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have more life now,'' said Boston netminder Byron Dafoe,
following Sunday's workout, ``and we gave it to them. Now we have
to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins stood on the verge Saturday night of taking a 2-0
series lead over the former Forever .500s. But a third-period
turnover in their own zone led to overtime, and another miscue in
OT led to Ray Sheppard's winner. Now here they are, dead even with
their one-time New England rivals and in need of re-establishing
the kind of offense that made them the NHL's hottest club in the
last month of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Even to think about getting to Round 2, the Bruins need a
handful of their forwards to wake up and smell the postseason.
Dmitri Khristich was dreadful in Games 1 and 2, but he was hardly
alone. Anson Carter wasn't a factor. Ditto Sergei Samsonov. Steve
Heinze, hindered by a groin problem in Game 1, too often looked
like a man falling up a staircase. Jason Allison, their No. 1
center and playmaker, never got his game out of second gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to start kicking guys,'' said coach Pat Burns,
assessing the failure of his forwards in the two games in
Greensboro. ``But, yeah, Khristich and Heinze _ those guys really
concern me; they've got to be better. Allison, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In two games, the Bruins' attack was led by their ever-reliable
checking line _ Rob DiMaio, Tim Taylor, and P.J. Axelsson _ and two
of their supertankers, Ken Belanger and Landon Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger matched hit for hit with Carolina behemoth Keith
Primeau and also scored a goal in Game 1. While most of his fellow
forwards only thought about skating, looking as if they were
playing in the midseason All-Star no-hitter, Belanger popped the
transmission into overdrive and played with total emotion and grit.
He wasn't exactly Terry O'Reilly, but he resembled old blood 'n'
guts. When was the last time we said that here? Heck, not since Cam
Neely gave Claude Lemieux that facial in the Garden, banging his
noggin nose-first into the Boston Globe ad in the corner boards,
giving Lemieux a certifiable nose for news.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson shook his ``Landon of the Lost'' tag in Game 2 _ Burns
anointed him the team's first star for the performance _ and played
like a bona fide big boy in Game 2. If Wilson could come with that
performance every time, he would factor among the top nine forwards
of just about any team in the league, save perhaps the Wings and
Avs. He not only dished out some heavy hits, he set up a Samsonov
goal with a dash down left wing and quick pullup, turning Glen
Wesley inside-out and wristing a perfect shot on Arturs Irbe from a
tough angle. Sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you'll see from the 'Canes in Game 3: a ferocious
opening 10 minutes, a stretch when they'll roll four lines over the
boards and hit everything in a black-and-gold sweater (in which
case you might want to reconsider wearing the team colors Monday
night). They come fast and hard. They lack touch and their
offensive attack is metronomically predictable _ corner to behind
the net to out front, jam, jam, and jam some more _ but they're a
sight to behold for their revving legs and stinging hits. Whenever
their Cup run ends, they can package themselves as a demolition
derby act and work theme parks around the country this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins like to say they've got a more controlled attack by
comparison. That's another way of saying they couldn't match the
'Canes for intensity, skating speed, and true hunger in Games 1 and
2. If victories were awarded solely on man-for-man effort, the
Hartford-Greensboro-Raleigh Hurricanes would have a 2-0 series
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a lot more to it than just wanting it, just
going for it. The Bruins do have the skill among their forwards to
outperform the 'Canes. What they need to do now _ and this should
be easier on home ice _ is match Carolina's will and determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team's got to play better,'' said Allison, who
should find more room to work with the Bruins getting the last line
change as part of the home-ice adantage. ``We weren't making
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   As they say in 'Cane country, Allison ain't whistlin' Dixie. If
the Bruins don't start making plays, they won't be playing at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
