<SLUG> BC-BBA-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA QUESTIONS MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ People's choice Lou Merloni was optioned to Pawtucket
after Sunday's game. The Red Sox Monday will recall
lefthanded-hitting first baseman Brian Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   That's the small news. The bigger story is Nomar Garciaparra's
stand against management on the Merloni demotion. It was downright
Vaughn-esque.
</P>
<P>
   Merloni was upset about the demotion, saying, ``This is pretty
much (expletive), but it's something I've got to deal with. It
makes no sense. No one can convince me that it makes sense. I'm
shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, never before one to speak out against management,
took his teammate's objections a step further. ``He should be
upset,'' said the franchise shortstop. ``I don't know what you
gotta do. He does everything right. I'm not a numbers guy, but I
think he is doing better than all of us (Merloni is hitting .333, 6
for 18 in six games). I'm sure he has nothing to work on. Why
people do what they do, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality guy in the clubhouse, and you see what he does
on the field. Everybody knows what he's capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   So why send him down?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' answered Garciaparra. ``You're asking the
wrong guy. Here's a guy I played with growing up. We played in the
minors together. I know what he's done. They tell you you've got to
do all this stuff to get to the big leagues, and he's done
everything asked of him and he gets up here and he's got to get
sent down _ for who knows what reason? What do you tell him? You
can't tell him anything. `You belong up here, but you can't be up
here'? It doesn't make sense. What am I gonna tell my boy? I can't
tell him anything. I was speechless.''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni, a 28-year-old Framingham native, said, ``No doubt we've
got a numbers problem in the infield, but I've done the job. I
don't need any more at-bats. I don't need to go work on my defense.
There's no reason to go down. You can't justify this at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, standing about 25 feet
from where Merloni was speaking, said, ``It makes sense for the
balance of the ballclub. With Jose Offerman playing second, we have
Jeff Frye, Donnie Sadler, and Merloni. That's three extra
infielders, and you only need two. This is more for balance, to
give (manager) Jimy (Williams) a lefthanded hitter on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette may have to deliver his next explanation to
Garciaparra. In the tradition of Mo Vaughn, Boston's best player
has a problem with one of management's moves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 0036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
