<HEADER>
A2905 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-26 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHNER BOOSTS MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ There are so many things to keep track of
as a hitter, Jay Buhner said, that it's almost as if you need a
checklist every time you come to bat. If you lose a few pounds and
miss a few games, as Buhner did on this road trip, one small part
of a finely tuned swing could go unchecked.
</P>
<P>
   So it helps to have others notice the flaws you miss. And after
Buhner struck out in his first at-bat this weekend against the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays, center fielder Ken Griffey Jr., a teammate
for 11 years, told him he was dropping his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner brought his hands up, and that slight adjustment brought
a major payoff Sunday. Facing dominating Tampa Bay closer Roberto
Hernandez in the ninth inning, Buhner ripped a two-run homer to
lift the Mariners to a 6-4 victory before 27,163 at Tropicana
Field. It was his fourth hit of the day and sixth in 10 at-bats
since correcting the mechanical error.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I got my hands back up there, it was amazing,''
Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, who also homered Saturday, had a pair of singles and a
double in the early innings Sunday. He came up in the ninth with a
man on second and two outs in a tie game and wondered if he would
be walked or pitched around by Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he blew the first one right by me about 100 (mph), that
took care of that idea,'' Buhner said. ``But I knew he had a good
split-finger and he still hadn't thrown one yet. It's not a real
comfortable at-bat being down 0-2, then 1-2 off a guy like that,
especially as hard as he was throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez hit 98 and 99 mph the first three pitches, then threw
another fastball high and outside that Buhner put just over the
right-field fence. Hernandez said he had no intention of giving
Buhner anything but his best pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their whole dugout knew how I'm coming after them in that
situation,'' Hernandez said. ``I wouldn't change a thing. I got a
fastball up in the zone; he's just a good power hitter, and he beat
me on it. I'd take my chances that way every time. I'd rather get
beat with my No. 1 pitch the opposite way than have him pull a
slider 450 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   The blow brought an end to an eight-game road trip in which the
Mariners went 4-4 but, as manager Lou Piniella noted, had a chance
to win every game. Three of the losses came by one or two runs, and
the other was close until the late innings.
</P>
<P>
   The M's never trailed, but they lost the lead twice. Leading
2-0, the Mariners made three errors in the second inning, bringing
home just the second and third unearned runs of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the errors were by third baseman Russ Davis, who bruised
his hand on the first one. Davis told Piniella he might have
problems gripping the bat, and Piniella inserted John Mabry, who
made a pair of sparkling plays. Davis said he did not expect to
miss any time because of the bruise.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners re-gained the lead in the third, when Dan Wilson
singled home a run, then helped another score with heady
baserunning. With Butch Huskey headed for a close play at the plate
on David Bell's two-out single to left, Wilson, who was at first,
kept running. Third baseman Bobby Smith cut off Quinton McCracken's
throw and trapped Wilson in a rundown, allowing Huskey to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``(First base coach) Sammy Mejias told me if it was going to be
close, make sure to get in a rundown,'' Wilson said. ``I thought it
was going to be close enough to where it warranted that. I just
kept going, and they cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays designated hitter Jose Canseco evened things with an
RBI double in the third and a solo homer off Jeff Fassero in the
fifth. But Mariner pitchers allowed only one single after that, and
Buhner took care of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey would not take credit for the assist Buhner revealed
after the game. But Mariners hitting coach Jesse Barfield was
grateful for the extra pair of eyes on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys help each other all the time,'' Barfield said.
``When I played in Toronto, Cito Gaston was the best batting coach
I ever had, but guys like George Bell, Willie Upshaw, Fred McGriff,
Kelly Gruber _ we all knew each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The batting coach is watching everybody, and that's a lot of
guys to keep track of. You may miss something sometime. That's
where your teammates pick you up. We're all in this thing. I don't
care who gets the credit as long as we get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
