<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITNA REFINING MIND-READING SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Forgive Jon Kitna if he did not spend a lot of
time Sunday lauding the epic career of John Elway. The Seahawks'
young quarterback does not have the detailed history.
</P>
<P>
   And frankly, now that Denver will be without its quarterback,
who is set to announce his retirement this week, Kitna thinks the
AFC West might be a bit more wide open.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a heretical mindset, even if you think Terrell Davis
keeps the Broncos unstoppable. Confidence comes if you are a
Seahawk whose new head coach is already at work installing the
NFL's latest version of Super Bowl juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for me, who finished as the starter here last season,
every other team in the AFC West is going to have a new No. 1
quarterback starting for them this season,'' Kitna said, running
down a list that included Rich Gannon now starting at Oakland, Jim
Harbaugh in at San Diego and Elvis Grbac in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Say anything you want about Bubby Brister as the Bronco's new
No. 1 QB and how Brister went 4-0 in Elway's injured absence last
season. Or about how Mike ``The Mastermind'' Shanahan can get
anyone plugged into his system and make it come out AFC champion.
The Seahawks seem a serious step or two closer to Bronco-like
respectability, thanks to new franchise leader Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   (If Shanahan has been dubbed The Mastermind by Denver
sportswriters, it is time to come up with a title for Holmgren. How
about The Guru? We base that on his ability to get quarterbacks and
offenses to learn and execute his brand of simple-but-complex
formations and plays.)
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, in the event that there is a tilt of power in the
AFC West, the key now is to get Kitna able to execute the Seahawk
offense, which means getting him to start thinking like Holmgren _
a task Holmgren and his staff worked on this past weekend during
the second spring minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jon Kitna's biggest goal is going to be to think like the head
coach,'' quarterbacks coach Mike Sheppard said after the Hawks
wrapped up their three-day crash course.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna did some homework on this subject of ``Being Like Mike.''
For Christmas, Kitna's wife gave him a copy of Brett Favre's
autobiography, which detailed the early career of the Green Bay
Super Bowl MVP and Favre's experience with Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they hired (Holmgren,) I thought to myself, `I better
read that book,' '' Kitna said. That turned out to be a good move
because Favre wrote that it took about two years before Holmgren's
thinking and play-calling had infiltrated Favre's cerebral cortex.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna may never do what Favre has done, but the charismatic
Tacoma native certainly gives you reason to hope the football
comparisons are for real. Sheppard said the Hawks' new coaches
believe Kitna need only be ``an efficient quarterback'' for their
system to work.
</P>
<P>
   But as far back as last spring, during Dennis Erickson's
minicamps, Kitna has shown the toughness, leadership, command and
touch of a starting QB. Now, under these suddenly glorious
conditions, he is ravenously hungry for all this Holmgren-esque
synergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of room in this offense for the quarterback to
have some freedom to throw the ball here or throw the ball there,''
Kitna said. ``But when (Holmgren) calls certain plays, he wants us
to think like he does so we know where he wants us to go with the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   After last season, when the Seahawks' offense fell to 23rd in
the league (24th in passing), there is an extra eagerness for the
offense to click again, to establish an identity _ something
brutalized when Erickson and his staff vacillated between
establishing a Ricky Watters-led running game and making the Hawks'
offense a wide-open passing game designed around Joey Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the final day of this minicamp, a cornucopia of
offensive formations were on display. Holmgren clearly has a
penchant for using his tight ends, an area sorely lacking in
Erickson's offense. Now Shannon Sharpe won't be the only AFC West
tight end keeping opposing defenses honest.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren also is using speedster Galloway in passing patterns
that allow him to catch the ball closer to the line and over the
middle, giving Galloway more opportunities to break off long runs
after the catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many different variations of formations. We may
have six or seven base formations, but there are so many different
alignments off of formations for each play. Guys are never really
lining up in the same spot,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great. It's great because it causes problems for the
defenses. They never know when you're coming out of the huddle
which way you're going to line up.''
</P>
<P>
   The variety and potential mismatches and crossing routes are
what will give Holmgren the pieces to play his sideline chess
matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the whole thing,'' Kitna said. ``Just
knowing how good of grasp (Holmgren) has on the offense just gives
everyone a sense of calmness. Hey, if this guy calls a play, he
knows it's going to work. We just have to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna is busting to make it all work.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
