<HEADLINE>
THE END IS NEAR: ELWAY LIKELY TO RETIRE THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ John Elway entered the NFL not as an icon but
an irritant.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1983, and the brash young quarterback with the howitzer
arm and toothy grin was thumbing his nose at the league.
</P>
<P>
   Select me with the first pick overall in the draft, Elway told
the then Baltimore Colts, and I'll play baseball instead.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's edict forced the Colts to trade the pick to the Denver
Broncos, and the rest, well, it has had a historic impact on the
entire league, not just those two franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen seasons and 51,475 yards later, Elway is all but gone.
</P>
<P>
   A retirement that was anticipated after he led the Broncos to
their first Super Bowl championship 15 months ago and has been
expected since the Broncos defended their title and Elway was named
Super Bowl MVP in January should become official this week.
</P>
<P>
   The usually elusive Elway tipped his hand over the weekend when
he told a Denver TV station, ``I really accomplished everything I
wanted to. There's no real upside to coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost gone, but never forgotten, especially for those who have
played against him and grown to admire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``John made a decision (in 1983) that was best for him, and he
was in a position to execute it. Not everyone has that leverage,''
Seahawks guard Pete Kendall said Sunday after the fifth and final
practice in the team's three-day minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you look at the whole picture of what John has done and
what a good guy he is and what a good player he has been,'' Kendall
said. ``That was an isolated incident where a lot of people thought
he was being petty and stubborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway apparently has made another decision that is best for him.
This time, no one can blame him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At age 38 and doing what he has done, what does John have to
prove?'' said Seahawks safety Mark Collins, who first played
against Elway in 1986. ``He's won his championships. He's earned
his money. It's time for him to enjoy his family and his
retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway's departure will complete a quarterbacking alchemy in the
AFC West. A division that featured Dan Fouts (Chargers), Jim
Plunkett (Raiders), Bill Kenney (Chiefs), Dave Krieg (Seahawks) and
Elway in the mid-80s will now be armed by Jim Harbaugh (Chargers),
Rich Gannon (Raiders), Elvis Grbac (Chiefs), Jon Kitna (Seahawks)
and Bubby Brister (Broncos).
</P>
<P>
   Transition? Or transgression?
</P>
<P>
   It is easy and accurate to say there never will be another John
Elway, but the league somehow managed to muddle along despite the
retirements of Roger Staubach, Terry Bradshaw and Joe Montana.
Their old clubs not only continued to field teams but won
championships after the departures of the best quarterbacks of
their eras.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are currently doing a multimillion-dollar expansion
and renovation of their headquarters. Not included in the plans is
a place to hang the 1999 AFC West championship banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shift in power?'' Sinclair asked with a laugh. ``First,
you've got to make yourself a contender. I could see it if we were,
say, the 49ers and all of a sudden (Green Bay quarterback Brett)
Favre was out of the picture. But we haven't even established
ourselves as a power.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kendall pointed out, Brister was 4-0 last season when Elway
was out with injuries and actually had a better passer rating
(99.0) than Elway (93.0). Also, Elway might be retiring, but
All-Pro running back Terrell Davis is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver is still a great team,'' Sinclair said. ``Last time I
checked, No. 30 (Davis) is still back there running the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elway has been especially lethal against the Seahawks. He
has more victories (20) and more touchdown passes (44) against them
than any other QB. In the Broncos' 28-21 victory over the Seahawks
in last year's regular-season finale, Elway threw for four TDs. In
a 1985 game at the Kingdome, Elway undressed the Seahawks' defense
for a career-high 432 passing yards.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, Elway always has driven the Seahawks nuts. And he
always seemed to take a particular delight in beating the team from
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always remember his smile,'' Sinclair said. ``Even if he
makes a mistake, he'll smile and hit himself on the head because he
knows he's going to beat you the next time. So many guys are always
tense out there, but John was a guy who basically smiled after
every play.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair, who led the NFL with 16{ sacks last season, cherishes
the times he was able to get to Elway because it was so difficult
to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is like Houdini,'' Sinclair said. ``You think you have
him, then you're laying on the ground looking out of one eye as he
fires a 60-yard pass. He's the kind of guy you're glad you got to
play against.''
</P>
<P>
   In a violent game where few ever leave on their own terms, Elway
walks away with nothing left to accomplish or prove. Not to
himself, to his teammates or to those he has tormented over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always marveled at his talent,'' Collins said. ``As with
any great player, you want him to stay around as long as possible.
But you don't want to see that great athlete stay there too long
and erode. I want to remember him as a great athlete, not a guy
who's just hanging on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
