<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS AGAIN HAVE BACKS AGAINST WALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Whether it's a rookie orientation or a
mandatory veteran camp, the focus of the Patriots' preseason is
going to be squarely on who will replace Robert Edwards as the
starting running back.
</P>
<P>
   With the weekend rookie orientation over, coach Pete Carroll
acknowledged Sunday there was no ``flag-bearer'' among a trio of
backs who will contend for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was impressed with veteran free agent Lamont Warren and
second-round pick Kevin Faulk, and even threw last year's
sixth-round pick, Harold Shaw, into the mix of backs who could take
the starting job with a strong training camp.
</P>
<P>
   While many Patriots fans may feel unsure about the position,
Carroll says he's not as uneasy about it as he was after the
Patriots lost Curtis Martin last year. The reason? He's been
through having to break in a rookie running back and now feels more
confident that, whether it's Faulk, Warren, Shaw, or a combination
of the three, the Patriots will run the football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more comfortable entering this unknown period,'' said
Carroll, who worked with 60 players, including most of the veterans
except for the starting defensive and offensive lines and Ben
Coates, whose wife is having a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the addition of Lamont,'' said Carroll. ``He's fast and
quick and can really catch the football. He's going to help us.
Whether it's as the feature back, I don't know. He'll get the
chance. I know that Kevin is definitely going to contribute. Kevin
is very durable. We had talked last year about Robert's physical
problems in college, and he turned out to be very productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin hasn't had problems a lot. He's been the lead featured
back. I'm not going to put any limits on it right now, how much
he'll wind up carrying the ball. He can run fast and catch the
ball, and shows excellent moves. He's got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said most of the rookies were in ``college shape,''
meaning they were not at the level of many of the veterans, who
have been involved in Johnny Parker's strength program. He said
having the veterans on hand gave the staff and the rookies a good
indication of where the rookies need to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed them their conditioning test to show them how far
they have to come to get to the shape we're expecting,'' Carroll
said. ``We are able to learn their ability to absorb the
information. We spent a lot of individual time with the younger
guys, and we're able to see what they're able to handle. It seemed
good across the board. We don't have any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We begin to see how they look in our schemes _ can we plug
them into certain roles? _ and start to formulate an idea of that.
We did a lot of special teams work to determine which guys are
catchers or play some roles on special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious by Carroll's comments that Faulk, Ohio State
linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer, Kansas State quarterback Michael
Bishop, and Brown receiver Sean Morey were the most impressive
rookies. Both first-round pick center Damien Woody from Boston
College and Baylor offensive tackle Derrick Fletcher have natural
ability but need some work with Jenny Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll continued to gush over Katzenmoyer, a player he
described as ``quiet, trying to absorb everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He made strong first impressions,'' said Carroll. ``He
understands football. He has a knack for learning the game. He's a
physical presence, and it's unusual a large man like that can move
that quickly. He looked well-conditioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thought Katzenmoyer could step in and start,
Carroll said, ``I think he's taking a lot in right now. We'll have
to see when the time comes. He has to be a great hitter for us, and
if he can run sideline to sideline, he'll threaten to play right
out of the camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach said Bishop would stick to quarterback for now but
maybe in time will grow into a ``Slash'' type role. ``Michael is a
quarterback,'' Carroll said. ``It's going to take all of our focus
and attention to get him to understand it. He showed some very good
things. He has a tremendously strong arm; it's gonna be interesting
to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said Morey, who is from Marshfield, competed hard. ``He
was a guy who gave us great effort, who laid out for balls, worked
hard on special teams, and hustles,'' said the coach. ``He's going
to give himself a chance to make the team. He can really catch the
football. He has tremendous hands. He has good speed. He also
caught the ball well on kick returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said Woody got used to snapping the ball to Drew Bledsoe
in drills before each of three sessions. The coach said it's
important Woody get into camp as soon as possible and learn the
playbook and the calls he needs to make at the center spot if he
intends on starting immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
