<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN SHOT BY OFFICER AFTER PROM: HOTEL PARTY WENT OUT OF CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The post-prom party broke up when police knocked on
the hotel room door, but as one student tried to scramble out the
window to avoid being caught past curfew with beer, an officer's
bullet struck his head.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Franco, 18, a junior at Barry Goldwater High School in
north Phoenix, is expected to recover fully from the wound _ the
bullet entered his cheek and lodged near his spinal cord, his
father said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Patrick Brutto, who has been on the Phoenix police force
for three years, told investigators he didn't intend to fire his
gun at the teenager Saturday night. He'll work behind a desk while
the department investigates, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin stuck his head out and the cop shot him. No warning,''
said Adrian Rivera, 16, of Phoenix, who attended the party at
Homewood Suites Hotel at Interstate 17 and Peoria Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Officers showed up at the hotel about 11 p.m. because security
wanted the roomful of teenagers kicked out, police said.
</P>
<P>
   When the two officers knocked at Room 119, they heard the teens
planning to scurry out the ground-floor window, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The officers went outside to the back of the room where they saw
Franco leaning halfway out. Both officers pulled their guns
thinking that something shiny they saw was a weapon, police said.
</P>
<P>
   As Brutto drew closer, he realized there was no weapon and
started putting his gun back in its holster, police said. With his
other hand, he tried grabbing Franco, and as he did so, he pulled
the trigger, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The department is investigating whether Brutto squeezed the
trigger out of a natural reflex to his other hand grabbing
vigorously for Franco.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not say what the shiny object was.
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers in the hotel room described a chaotic scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't hear any warnings or nothing. A bullet came through
the window and my eye gets cut up,'' said Bryan Zahariades, 19, of
Phoenix, who was sporting a white bandage around his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Justin) fell back in and kids were going crazy,'' said Cara
Graulich, 15, a freshman at Goldwater High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there was blood everywhere. Kids thought they got shot
because there was blood on their faces and everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Graulich and her brother, Corey Graulich, knelt by Justin.
She said she grabbed a pillow and held it to his head. Soon it
became soaked with blood, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cara said her brother was angry and she told him to keep cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `This may be the last chance to talk to him. Calm
down.' So he stayed there, rubbing his back.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara said she made sure Justin didn't lose consciousness by
repeatedly asking his name and telling him to focus on her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't talk,'' said Corey Graulich, 17, a junior at
Goldwater. ``He was trying to talk, but couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   An officer came through the window and told everybody to move
back from Justin, Cara Graulich said.
</P>
<P>
   Brutto was a paramedic before he became a police officer and he
tended to Franco until paramedics arrived, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives rounded up the partygoers and interviewed them
through the early morning.
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers said there was beer in the room. Police said they
also found marijuana. The teenagers said there were about 20 people
at the party.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the hotel told them there were about 50 in the
two-bedroom suite, and that only a dozen remained when officers
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The partygoers kept pressing police for the reason the officer
shot Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them . . . about 20 times and they would never give us
a straight answer,'' Zahariades said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Police Chief Harold Hurtt planned to meet with the
Franco family, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tragedy comes on the heels of too many violent events
involving officers these past weeks,'' Hurtt said in a written
statement. ``Our concern is for Justin to recover quickly and
completely from his injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   The bullet lodged right at the teenager's spinal cord, said his
father, Cruz Franco, 47, of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some effects, but we don't know what yet,'' Cruz
Franco said, standing outside John C. Lincoln Hospital &AMP; Health
Center. ``The doctors said if it had been 1 inch over on either
side, I wouldn't have no more son.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin Franco, a fullback who wore No. 35 on his football
uniform for the Goldwater Bulldogs, had thoughts of playing for a
college team, but his father said he might not be able to put on
the pads next year.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Cruz Franco said his son is strapped to his hospital
bed, a brace holding his neck, his reconstructed jaw wired shut.
Doctors told him not to move.
</P>
<P>
   He was able to smile and open his eyes on command for a doctor,
a promising sign, his father said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to be the same, but he'll be all right,'' Cruz
Franco said. ``He's alive.'' &QL; 
Richard Ruelas can be reached at 444-8473 or at
richard.ruelas(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 0053EDT &QL; 
