<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2917 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     04-26 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ Tonight will be telling. Tonight's the night when we find
out who's sicker, the Rockets or the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Until they actually play this almost certain preview of the
postseason's first-round pairing, it seems a wash. Los Angeles
staggers into Houston reeling from a 27-point blowout bashing at
San Antonio. The Lakers have dropped five of seven, leaving them
6-7 in April. The friction and finger-pointing is omnipresent in
their tense, divided locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times' headline Sunday morning: ``Laker Mystique
is Now Mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Sight unseen, Scottie Pippen suggests the Rockets are
in a bigger jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine anybody struggling more than we are right
now,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   His case is a strong one. At least the Lakers' sudden slump
could be passed off as the not-unexpected byproduct of a brutal
patch of scheduling, or perhaps a touch of melancholy over the
firing of Dennis Rodman. Regarding the former, five of LA's last
six losses have been inflicted by Portland, Utah and the Spurs, who
stand a combined 64 games over .500.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the latter ... just kidding.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, on the other hand, have suddenly gone due south
against a trio of teams well to the south of them in the standings
(although Phoenix, 7-3 of late, is gaining ground rapidly). And in
their own recent loss to San Antonio, they found a way to succumb
after leading by 23 points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   While there isn't necessarily great shame in taking a header
here _ as opposed to going face down consecutively against the,
ouch, Mavericks and the, double ouch, Clippers _ how they did it
was rather shocking. The only thing worse than the Rockets' anemic
71 points of offense _ which equaled their season low _ on dismal
35 percent shooting against a somewhat sorry Suns defense was the
Rockets' own lazy defense.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Phoenix didn't score more than 95 points is
because to do so would have been pointless. The Rockets never
competed. Their final lead _ by one point _ came in the middle of
the first quarter. From there, the Suns gradually left the Rockets
in the desert dust.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rockets appear to be in the midst of a lack-of-heart
attack. As do the Lakers, who have yielded an average of 105 points
over their last seven games with indications of a disintegrating
relationship between Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant becoming more
pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys know the real problem,'' Shaq complained to reporters
recently. ``You're just scared to write about it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal believes the precocious Bryant's immature, undisciplined
play is the real problem, as opposed to the mess the failed Rodman
experiment left behind. The Rockets, for all their own chemistry
concerns wrought by Pippen's difficulties fitting in, have at least
maintained a united front when questioned about same.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley was asked Sunday to reflect on the internal
discord in LA. He demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my own stuff to worry about,'' Barkley said, refusing
to analyze LA's stuff. ``I don't have time to be worrying about
them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For public consumption, however, the Chuckster went on to insist
he isn't that bothered by what has befallen the Rockets just as
they looked to be on the brink of a major breakout. A shrink would
likely suggest he's in total denial. Also, a straw poll of coach
Rudy Tomjanovich and Barkley's fellow players reveals he's
definitely in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not doing our jobs,'' Hakeem Olajuwon admitted, his
brow furrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have already backed into the playoffs, securing a
berth when Seattle lost to Utah on Sunday, the Rockets are well
aware they have lost their edge. They are a mediocre 5-8 in April,
which is no way to prepare for May. Asked to explain why this is
happening, Tomjanovich thumped his chest. No, he was not mimicking
the Phoenix gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any fire and fight in us on the court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was more specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not challenging anybody on defense,'' he contended.
</P>
<P>
   How the trend can be reversed overnight _ literally _ remains to
be seen. The Lakers will be more rested, having slunk into town
Sunday from San Antonio. And they figure to hold something of a
psychological advantage in light of their 2-0 head-to-head record
vs. the Rockets. A season sweep would leave them a half-game up on
the Rockets in the competition for home-court advantage with nine
days remaining in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Which matters just a bit, because the Rockets haven't won a road
game against a team currently over .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest game of the year,'' Tomjanovich called tonight's
matchup. ``We're fighting for our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important for us, this game,'' Hakeem added. ``It can
be a steppingstone.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, should they lose again, further reduce them to doormat
status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
