<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARITEK HITS HIS STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-VARITEK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jason Varitek didn't want to talk about his three hits,
or that he had bunted for one of them, or that his two-run double
in the seventh inning was the winning hit in the Red Sox' 3-2
victory over the Indians Sunday at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek says he concentrates on defense first and foremost.
</P>
<P>
   One can't help but discuss his hitting, however. Varitek, after
going 3 for 4, is hitting .333 lifetime against the Indians (6 for
18), with his biggest blow the double down the right-field line
with the bases loaded in the seventh Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a split-finger,'' said Varitek, who connected on a 1-1
count. ``(Bartolo) Colon left it up a little bit, and I was able to
get a good part of the bat on the ball. He was trying to get a
ground ball, and I'm trying to get it somewhere in the outfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Varitek's bases-loaded hit, the Red Sox were only 3 for
19 this season in such situations. And Varitek had entered Sunday's
outing having gone 0 for 9 in the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been facing some quality pitchers and you're not always
swinging at your best in the game. Stats can be thrown out the
window. The game changes every day,'' said Varitek, who has caught
nine of the last 10 games with Scott Hatteberg on the 15-day
disabled list with right elbow inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   On Varitek's bunt single down the third-base line in the fourth
inning, he noticed Indians third baseman Travis Fryman was playing
deep. ``We were getting guys on base with one out, so I figured I
might as well try it with no out, to see if I could get something
started,'' Varitek said. ``Fryman was playing in left-center, so I
figured I had the third-base line.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek is batting just .234, but he's enjoyed being in the
lineup lately. ``It's fun to play every day,'' he said. ``I knew I
can hit, and it's frustrating when things don't go the way you want
them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had 12 hits Sunday in taking the rubber game of the
three-game series. ``It's a good feeling to go out and beat a team
like Cleveland,'' Varitek said. ``We have guys who have hit .300 in
their careers, and we haven't hit .300 (as a team) yet. That will
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played three quality games this weekend. It's just taking
time to get our hitting going a little bit. I think we're on our
way.''
</P>
<P>
   During warmups, Varitek didn't believe Pedro Martinez would
allow just seven hits and strike out 10. ``Pedro didn't have his
best stuff, and that shows you his competitiveness,'' Varitek said.
``If you asked early in the game if he'd pitch a whole game, I'd
say you're crazy, but his competitiveness kept him in that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He fell behind a lot of hitters, which is unlike him. He just
competed and got them out on 3-2 or 2-2 counts rather than 1-2 or
0-2 counts. I was just trying to (call pitches) to Pedro's strength
and he was able to mix in all four pitches and effectively use the
breaking pitch. I don't think he threw quite as many changeups as
he has in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek tried to keep the Indians hitters off balance, and it's
helped that he's seen them a lot over the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   But ``that's Pedro's pitching,'' too, the catcher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
