<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA MAKES STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 WOMEN-CHINA-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ They've been saying that the road to
Pasadena, and the World Cup final in July, won't be any fast-lane
cruise. And now the US women's soccer team knows it for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is a disappointing loss,'' coach Tony DiCicco
said Sunday, after China had handed the Americans a 2-1 defeat on
Zhang Ouying's goal four minutes into added time at Giants Stadium
and ended their 50-match unbeaten streak on home soil. ``But China
right now is the best they've been since I've been with the
national team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time the Chinese had beaten the Yanks in their
last three meetings and it was a fitting turnabout for Thursday's
finish in Hershey, Pa., where the United States won by the same
score on Tisha Venturini's goal in the 94th minute.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was Ouying, an 82d-minute substitute, who caught
the Americans' back line flat-footed with their attackers pressing
upfield and blasted the winner past keeper Briana Scurry from just
past the penalty spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sending everyone forward like we were losing,'' said
DiCicco. ``This team thinks a tie is a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese had been playing for a tie on Thursday when
Venturini stung them on a rebound off a Mia Hamm cross. Since they
won't have another shot at the United States before the Cup final,
the Chinese wanted badly to lay a parting trump card on the hosts
in their ongoing head game.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first 10 minutes Sunday, the Americans toyed with
their guests like they do with most of the world's teams, setting
up housekeeping in the Chinese half and creating a couple of
scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   Then Michelle Akers, still a midfield mainspring after 14 years
and 135 caps, rolled an ankle and came off the pitch for four
minutes and her teammates lost their rhythm. Just after Akers
returned, Sun Wen, who scored China's goal in Hershey, took a ball
from Liu Ailing off a restart, blew into the US area and roofed the
ball over Scurry in the 14th minute.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the second half, after the Chinese had nearly
gone up, 2-0, on a Sun boomer that Scurry deflected off the
crossbar, that the Americans regained their balance and drew even
on a goal by midfielder Julie Foudy off a Cindy Parlow feed in the
58th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lucky deflection,'' said Foudy. ``That's what happens
when you have that many bodies in the area. The keeper was off her
line and I snuck it by her.''
</P>
<P>
   So it came down to added time again, with Venturini coming off
the bench again in the 90th minute looking to stick in the dagger.
``She almost did it, didn't she?'', said DiCicco, after Chinese
keeper Gao Hong tipped Venturini's header off Hamm's free kick over
the bar.
</P>
<P>
   So determined were they to pull out the victory that the
Americans forgot about preserving a draw and the domestic streak
that had created an aura of invincibility around them. Zhang, who
had played only 23 international matches and only scored two goals,
dashed past defenders Carla Overbeck and Christie Pearce as referee
Kari Seitz was considering the final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, the hosts were left shaking their heads, hands on
hips as the Chinese leapt and wept for joy, then bolted from the
stadium without bothering to shower. After seven weeks on the road,
they just wanted a ``W'' and an exit visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we learned from this is, anything can happen,'' said
Kristine Lilly. ``We have to remember it's a 90-minute game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2923 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      04-26 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION HAVE REVERSED FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution struggled to establish an
identity in their first three years. Losing became a habit and
fatalism a doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Revolution seem to be reversing those trends. Their 3-2
win over D.C. United Saturday gave them five successive games
without a defeat over 90 minutes, the best regulation-time record
in the Eastern Conference. Officially, the Revolution are 2-3, with
all three defeats in the shootout, but even this shows significant
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three-plus years of Major League Soccer, the
Revolution had failed to win at RFK Stadium and had not defeated
D.C. United in regulation time in 12 matches.
</P>
<P>
   This victory was the result of the Revolution's positive
mindset, combined with a weakened United team, which lost defensive
midfielder Richie Williams (ankle sprain) and no longer has John
Harkes (now with the Revolution), Tony Sanneh (Hertha Berlin), or
the team's creator and inspiring force, Bruce Arena, who has been
replaced by Thomas Rongen as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Most encouraging, though, was the Revolution's transformation
into a possession team, with nearly every player suddenly
comfortable on the ball and willing and able to string together
passes in midfield, at least during the first half, when they took
a 3-1 advantage. They might have been taking the example of D.C.
United, which normally control games by turning their ball-control
game in swift attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution players credited the change in tactical mindset
to their work in practice under the direction of Giuseppe
Galderisi, who recently joined player-coach Walter Zenga as an
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   If this continues, it indeed will be a revelation for a team
that seldom had displayed such awareness and skill in its first 100
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a great game for the first 45 minutes,'' Joe-Max
Moore said. ``That was because of our ability to keep the ball in
midfield. When you can stay composed on the ball, it makes a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be far less tendency to panic than in the
previous week, when midfielder Edwin Gorter complained vociferously
about the Revolution's unwillingness to keep the ball on the
ground. Ironically, Gorter missed the United game because of a
stomach virus, but Jair and Kris Kelderman set the tone in the
central midfield, the Moore-Giovanni Savarese strike combination
was effective, and Ivan McKinley provided two goals from the left
side of midfield. The coherency of play became contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter is never overly critical about mistakes,'' Moore said,
``especially in the attacking third. He wants us to be smart. If we
keep the ball moving, we'll find holes in the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution survived the last three weeks, playing twice
against two-time MLS Cup champions United, plus the Columbus Crew.
The situation could become complicated now, as Gorter, Imad Baba
(groin), and Harkes (right knee ligament) are scheduled to return.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is available, they will be part of an evolution toward
the style of play of Galderisi and Zenga, who bring more than 30
years of experience, combined, in Italy's top divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mentality is different,'' Zenga said. ``But if we mix it
with the USA mentality, maybe we will arrive at the top level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
