<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ALLISON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLISON'S WINNING FORMULA SELF-EVIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ The Greensboro Coliseum ice was as smooth as
giblet gravy and the Hurricanes were on them like a nagging spouse
and the hotel housecleaning staff forgot to leave mints under their
pillows . . .
</P>
<P>
   Whoa.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Allison readily acknowledged that the Bruins lacked a
smoking gun on Tobacco Road as they split the first two games of
their best-of-seven Eastern Conference quarterfinal playoff series.
But he would tolerate no alibis involving the conditions, the
opponent, or the venue. The Boston offense's problems, he believes,
were self-generated.
</P>
<P>
   And as the team's scoring leader the past two seasons, the
23-year-old center realizes that, rightly or wrongly, much of the
burden to produce falls on him. He did contribute an assist in each
game as the Bruins won the opener, 2-0, before suffering a
deflating 3-2 overtime loss Saturday night. But he knows that
something's not quite right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get frustrated when things don't go well because of
something I'm not doing,'' he said Sunday at Ristuccia Center,
where the Bruins held an optional practice on the eve of Game 3 at
the FleetCenter. ``I've got to get in the flow better.''
</P>
<P>
   He's hardly alone, as coach Pat Burns emphasized. ``The
difference is that their forwards are skating and ours aren't,'' he
said, exempting only Rob DiMaio and Landon Wilson from culpability.
``They've got to skate, not just stand around. They've got to skate
the way Keith Primeau is skating, the way Ray Sheppard is
skating.''
</P>
<P>
   While Burns was giving the Hurricanes deserved credit, Allison
feels the Bruins were extending their hosts too much of it. ``They
came out hard and we kind of panicked,'' he said. ``We started
throwing the puck off the glass, dumping it. We've got to relax,
pass the puck three or four times if that's what they give us. It's
one of those things where Carolina is coming at us and we say, `We
don't want to let them score,' instead of saying, `What can I do to
put us in better position?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were rarely in position to do much damage against
Carolina goaltender Arturs Irbe. But while their lack of finishing
touch is being generally decried, Allison believes the problem is
at the other end of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind not scoring,'' he said. ``We can't get anything
started when we're throwing the puck around like that. I think some
days we go out there almost scared, scared to lose. We're still a
young, inexperienced team as far as the playoffs go. Maybe we were
a little jittery the first two games. In their building, with the
ice so bad, it was as if we didn't want to make a mistake, give up
a goal, so we'd just dump the puck. We were always wanting to do
the safe thing, worried about them scoring instead of us attacking
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the trick, of course: transferring the concern to the
other guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to move the puck, make the passes,'' said Allison.
``Then they say, `Oh no, here come the Bruins.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Bruins left North Carolina in good shape, having
seized the home-ice advantage from the Hurricanes. ``If you go on
the road and you're 1-1,'' said Allison, ``you're not
disappointed.'' The flip side in this case was that a Carolina
sweep was well within the Bruins' grasp until they squandered a 2-1
lead Saturday on Robert Kron's goal with 5:32 left in regulation
before being done in by Sheppard's second score of the night at
17:05 of OT. ``When you have the lead with six minutes left in
regulation and lose,'' said Allison, ``we're disappointed we lost
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Allison is more determined than daunted. If anything, he
believes that excess adrenaline, not nerves, betrayed him in
Greensboro _ ``I think I might have been overexcited, wired, in the
first game,'' he said _ and he's over that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a little better in the second half of yesterday's
game,'' said Allison. ``I was in the flow better. I know I have to
play better, I can play better, and I will play better. I'm not
worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been too much of that already.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
