</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON HAS BIG IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ He is a player they had banked on. He is a
guy they had hoped somehow would reach his potential at a critical
time. He was Toronto's second pick in 1993, then traded to Quebec,
then Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins dealt for him Nov. 22, 1996, in a trade with
Colorado (where the Nordiques moved), they were hoping
6-foot-2-inch, 216-pound Landon Wilson, now 24, would make a big
difference.
</P>
<P>
   After a career of fits and starts, when management wasn't sure
if it had done the right thing by trading its No. 1 pick for
Wilson, he did make a difference in Game 2 against the Carolina
Hurricanes Saturday night. Despite Boston's loss, coach Pat Burns
talked about Wilson, a player he seemed to have a hard time warming
up to, as the Bruins' best forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was our best forward, by far,'' said Burns. ``He and Robbie
DiMaio were uncontestedly our two best forwards. If he plays like
that, he'll play. That's what I told him.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns, who throws around compliments like manhole covers, said
he felt it was a measure of maturity. ``It takes a while for young
players to realize that,'' said Burns. ``He's a big, strong kid and
if he wants to play that way, he's going to play. The only
difference between us and their forwards was they were skating and
ours weren't. That's the only difference. Our forwards have to be
skating. We were sort of waiting for something to happen instead of
going to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he is hoping to take advantage of the most recent
opportunity. ``I was playing with Sergei Samsonov and Dmitri
Khristich and Joe Thornton and Shawn Bates and Kenny Belanger,'' he
said. ``When you go out there, you've got to be physical because
it's playoff hockey, get your nose dirty. Go to the net hard and
work as hard as you can, just banging away.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems to have been a hard lesson for Wilson to learn, but
like Thornton before him, it might be that Wilson is finally
getting it. He thinks he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing hockey,'' he said. ``Anything I can do to help
the team, I'm going to try. I just feel like I have more confidence
over the last couple of weeks. That one game I played with Sammy
and Joe in Buffalo, that was the starting point there. I felt
strong after that. I felt confident that I know I can play at this
level. I want to prove that when I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was a focal point of the Bruins' attack in Game 2,
whereas in previous games he was more of a role player, given more
to spot duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen that much ice time since that Buffalo game,''
said Wilson, referring to the game just shy of the end of the
regular season. ``I understand my position on the team: I'm a
fourth-liner and whatever happens happens. But if I have an
opportunity to play as much as that, I'm going to make the most of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he has met with the coaching staff and understands
what it expects. He said Burns knows when a player is on his game.
``I think the whole coaching staff does,'' said Wilson. ``When guys
have it, they usually stay with them. You've just got to be
focused. When I first got called up, I was only playing a little
bit, and that's very tough on your confidence. Mentally, it's
really kind of devastating because you're expecting to play but you
know you've just got to accept your role. The role I was in was
that of a fourth-line player _ keep it simple, get the puck in or
out. I'm not satisfied. I want to continue to stay here and play
well here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
