<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WIZARDS-RICHMOND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHMOND A WIZENED WIZARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He adorns the cover of this year's Wizards media guide,
supposedly a symbol that times have changed for him and for the
franchise. Mitch Richmond may now be with Washington instead of
Sacramento, but that is not the change he'd hoped for in his
basketball life.
</P>
<P>
   With another season winding down, the soon-to-be 34-year-old
guard and his team are in a very familiar spot: out of the playoffs
and in a lather.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be this way, not this time. That's what
Richmond thought when he was liberated from the drudgery that was
Sacramento. He had had one four-game playoff experience with the
Kings. That was it. Washington, with Rod Strickland as a running
mate, was supposed to change all that.
</P>
<P>
   You know by now that things are worse in Washington than they
are in Sacramento. The Kings totally have rebuilt themselves and
may well make the playoffs with a dynamic, running team that has
one missing piece: a quality shooting guard. Washington? The
Wizards were a flat-out disgrace Sunday at the FleetCenter,
submitting a pathetic effort that resulted, not surprisingly, in a
113-84 loss to the Celtics. They're going to a very familiar place:
Secaucus for the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond was as guilty as anyone; he had a Rotisserie League 18
points in 35 minutes but basically went through the motions like
everyone else in blue. He wasn't pointing fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose, you point at a lot of things,'' he said.
``That's why you don't try to lose too much. We're all sulking.
It's a difficult time. We just gotta play, including myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through periods like this, it's easy to hang your
head. I think I've been at fault for some of that, hanging my head,
getting down. A lot of guys have. We know it's a tough time. We're
out of the playoffs, and these losses add up. It gets to you. I've
been through a lot of them; it's a hard period. You see a lot of
negativity going on. Hopefully, we can try to pick it up. That's
all we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   As an NBA fan, there's a part of you that feels a little for
Richmond and his plight, forgiving the occasional pig-like
performance he's been known to submit. He deserves better. It was
difficult to listen to him try to explain away a totally
humiliating experience. In between sighs and a lot of head-shaking
_ at one point, he blurted, ``I don't know, man, ask me some
questions'' _ he owned up to being utterly exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating, because my expectations were a lot
higher than what's happening now,'' he said. ``It's a tough time, a
tough period. I never thought anything like this would happen to
this team. We're going through a real difficult period. It's really
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Richmond doesn't have a lot of quality time left; his hoop
biological clock is ticking. His career has been one of individual
excellence (1996 gold medal from Atlanta, six-time All-Star,
five-time All-NBA) but lacking in the one area where the great ones
measure themselves against the others: team success. His four-game
playoff series with the Kings in 1996 represents his only
postseason appearance since 1991, when he was with the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   He's a free agent at the end of this season and he will have a
couple choices: Take the money and stay, or go elsewhere for less
and be on a contender. Washington would like to think it could be a
contender and, having traded Chris Webber for Richmond, will do all
it can to make its argument. But we know better. The Wizards have
been in one playoff series this decade _ as the No. 8 seed two
years ago, losing, 3-0, to Chicago _ and haven't won a playoff game
since May 4, 1988, or a seven-game playoff series since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't hear Richmond say he was going to stick around and
see this one through, albeit with a fatter wallet. That, in itself,
could be a signal. But he also didn't say that he's fed up with
what he's seen, which would have been understandable given the way
the Wizards are mailing in the season; Sunday was their fifth
straight loss, the last two by 19 and 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to wait until the end of the season to make a
decision,'' he said. ``I didn't want to make my decision the first
game I played here, and I don't want to make it now. I'll look at
the alternatives, weigh everything, and see what's best for
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do is look at the playoff elite and see how many
of them lack what Richmond provides: San Antonio, the Lakers,
Miami, Houston, even Utah with a hobbling Jeff Hornacek. All could
use help at shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   That's the dilemma that Richmond soon will face. For all of
these players, basketball at one time in their life was a sport. It
was about playing and winning and nothing else. Richmond finally
has a choice for the first _ and last _ time in his career: How do
I want to go out?
</P>
<P>
   Based on what he and we saw Sunday, it's hard to imagine him
adorning the cover of the Wizards media guide for the 1999-2000
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
