<HEADER>
A2932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-WARNINGS-     04-26 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-WARNINGS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGE SUSPECTS SIGNALED VIOLENCE TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, rewriting throughout) (sw) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON and JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Something in Dylan Klebold's voice had
spooked his mother that morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goodbye had an edge to it,'' the mother, Susan Klebold,
told a family pastor, describing her son's tone last Tuesday
morning as ``almost fatalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought, maybe he's in a bad mood,'' the Rev. Don
Marxhausen said. ``Maybe he's got a test today or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Dylan's father, Thomas Klebold, 52, a former geophysicist who
runs a mortgage business from his house, told the pastor he had
detected ``this slight tension'' in his son a few days before the
attack. Klebold made a mental note of it and thought he would get
back to it, the pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold never did. On Tuesday, Dylan Klebold, 17, and his best
friend, Eric Harris, 18, ambushed their classmates and teachers at
Columbine High School with a storm of gunfire and pipe bombs,
taking 13 lives before fatally shooting themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As new details of the young men's behavior come to light, there
is an emerging portrait of their friendship and of their
relationship with their families. It is a portrait that remains as
puzzling as their attack on their school.
</P>
<P>
   Many students in the school have described the young men as
being obsessed with Nazi history, and the police now say that the
two planned the attack for Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But Klebold is the great-grandson of a prominent Jewish
philanthropist. His father is Lutheran, and for a time the family
attended a church. At Passover this year, the Klebolds had a seder,
Marxhausen said, and Dylan Klebold asked the traditional four
questions at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances of the gunmen have said they detested athletes
because of the way they were treated by them. But Klebold played in
a baseball fantasy league, a game in which participants form teams
of Major League players and compete based on the players' actual
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   A fan of the Boston Red Sox, he was one of a dozen students who
took part recently in a fantasy baseball draft party, said one of
the participants.
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent display of his penchant for slurs, Klebold called
his team the Border Hoppers and chose the Taco Bell logo as his
team symbol.
</P>
<P>
   While Klebold, 6-foot-4 and lanky, was often outgoing, Harris
was much quieter. Other students say Harris often scowled in
response to a greeting.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The New York Times, Marxhausen said
Klebold's parents described Harris as having an ``incredibly strong
personality with a lot of rage.''
</P>
<P>
   A former teammate of Harris' in youth baseball when the family
lived in Plattsburgh, N.Y., said young Eric lacked self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't really like baseball a lot but said his dad pushed
him to play Little League because every kid in Plattsburgh played
it,'' said the former teammate, Brendon LaPier. ``He was the kind
of kid who didn't mind being alone, and he spent a lot of time in
the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harris family also lived for a time in Oscada, Mich. The
Rev. William Stone, a neighbor there, said he recalled the father,
Wayne Harris, putting up a basketball backboard in the driveway and
playing ball with Eric and his brother, Kevin, who is two years
older. Kevin would go on to play football for the Rebels of
Columbine High. He was seen as popular with the athletic crowd,
``just the kind of guy his brother was gunning for,'' said Steve
Berg, a classmate of the elder Harris brother.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said that the Harris family ``cared for each other'' and
that the parents ``seemed to enjoy their children.''
</P>
<P>
   In Littleton, the Harris family lives in a newer two-story house
at the end of a cul-de-sac. The Klebold home is much grander, a
sleek glass-and-cedar house that backs up to the spectacular Dear
Creek Canyon. The Klebolds also have a carriage house that they
rent out.
</P>
<P>
   Marxhausen said the Klebolds had bought the house for a low
price and fixed it up.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of both boys, described by friends as decent and
caring people from stable homes, have issued statements of sympathy
over the attack. But the authorities have come to the conclusion
that the parents should have had some idea of what was going on in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff John P. Stone of Jefferson County said on Saturday that
the sawed-off barrel of a shotgun and bomb-making materials were
``clearly visible'' in the bedroom of one of the young gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said the weapons were in places where stuffed
animals might be found in the bedrooms of other teen-agers. ``The
parents should have known,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Marxhausen, one of the clergymen who conducted a private funeral
for Klebold on Saturday, said the young man's father told him he
``felt Dylan was his soul mate, and felt that he knew what was
going on all the time.'' The pastor said Klebold had told him, ```I
thought I was ready to let him go _ he was a finished product.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marxhausen said Klebold was not a ``gun man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've just got a BB gun to shoot the woodpeckers.''
</P>
<P>
   The day before the shootings, Mr. and Mrs. Klebold had mailed a
deposit for their son's dormitory room at the University of
Arizona, where they believed he planned to enroll in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the diary found by the police shows that the two young men
expected to die in the attack they had been plotting for a year, an
act of revenge on the popular crowd they blamed for making them
feel like outcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Most young people who knew Klebold and Harris were shocked at
the shootings. But some friends said they had heard Klebold and
Harris comment about blowing up the school.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend before the shootings, neighbors said the two
young men had made such a ruckus smashing glass in the Harris
garage _ making shrapnel for bombs, residents now suspect _ that
the noise disturbed children playing in the nearby cul-de-sac.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to think you'd be aware that kids are building
bombs in your house,'' said Debbie Wilder, who lives a few doors
from the Harrises.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold were fond of role-playing games
and the violent computer games Doom and Quake. They listened to
German techno-rock, music tinged with sadomasochism. They were
arrested last year for breaking into a car to steal tools, and were
placed in a diversion program for juveniles, where they earned high
marks in an evaluation for being bright and cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   But these young men were also good students with jobs, who had
caused no problems for school officials.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lau, who owns the Blackjack Pizza franchise where
the young men worked three to five nights a week, said they always
showed up on time and worked hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's looking for answers and looking for answers,'' Lau
said. ``There's no clear answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Valentine, who runs a computer store in Littleton, said
Klebold had applied for a job, sending a resume that claimed he
``built my personal computer and helped build those of friends and
family.'' He said he offered the young man a job _ ``He has all the
right stuff to be a technician'' _ but that Klebold did not show up
on the day he was supposed to start work.
</P>
<P>
   Marxhausen said that the Klebolds came to his church about five
years ago for about nine months. ``It didn't work for them,'' he
said. ``They just didn't get into it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the families in his church is close to the Klebolds, so
Marxhausen told them to let the Klebolds know he would conduct the
funeral if they wanted. The Klebolds called him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them how they were doing. They used the word
`devastated,''' the pastor said. ``I didn't want to ask them any
more.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the funeral home, he first saw Mr. Klebold,
who seemed to say, simply, ``This was not my son. What you see in
the papers was not my son,'' Marxhausen said. Mrs. Klebold, he
said, ``just fell apart.''
</P>
<P>
   She was ``sobbing for about a minute and a half in my arms,
which is a long time,'' the pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started to come. I felt this terrible need not to have
a service but to talk,'' he said. So he shut the door to the wake
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this one couple, they just poured out their hearts,
they loved Dylan,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The dead youth's brother sat between the parents and was mostly
quiet, Marxhausen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finally just said, `I want to thank you all for being here
today for my parents and myself. I love my brother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
