<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OILERS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Stars rally, takes 3-0 series lead 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Maybe the Stars' alternate sweaters do have
some magical power after all.
</P>
<P>
   After lucking out all game against a determined bunch of
Edmonton Oilers, the Stars fired in three third-period goals and
took a stunning 3-2 victory in Game 3 of the best-of-seven Western
Conference quarterfinal series.
</P>
<P>
   With 7:28 left, Joe Nieuwendyk zipped in a 50-foot shot past a
stunned Tommy Salo to give the Stars their second come-from-behind
victory in the series and a three-games-to-none lead.
</P>
<P>
   Getting third-period goals from Mike Modano and Mike Keane, the
Stars somehow crawled back into a game they appeared to have lost
three times over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought \REdmonton\S played really well,'' Keane said. ``I
thought we pushed back when we had to. We battled back. We got some
not pretty goals and stuck to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers had a 2-0 lead in the third period and probably
should have had two more that were disallowed by referee calls.
</P>
<P>
   Getting two power-play goals from winger Ryan Smyth, who was a
healthy scratch the game before, the Oilers grabbed their lead
before a frenzied crowd of 17,100 that threatened to overturn the
Skyreach Centre after the Oilers lit the lamp three times and saw
none of the goals count.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars lucked out on all three _ maybe it was the snappy
``green star'' jerseys they were wearing for the first time in the
playoffs _ and entered the third period trailing, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   With the Oilers skating in a 4-on-3 situation, Smyth picked up a
loose puck off the end boards and shoveled it past Stars goalie Ed
Belfour, who had laid out to try to make a save. However, it took
officials another two minutes to decide that Smyth did not have his
skate in the crease _ allowing the goal to stand.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team had much luck in the injury department as Stars
defenseman Richard Matvichuk left with a strained groin in the
second period and will be re-evaluated today. It is the same groin
that kept Matvichuk out for the final 14 games of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers also lost a defenseman, Roman Hamrlik, with a knee
sprain. However, it never seemed to affect their energy. Despite
the low score, the Oilers were in control for most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was luck that the Stars weren't down by more as the Oilers
had three goals negated for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The worst transgression, as far as Oilers fans were concerned,
came at the 12:53 mark of the second period. With Belfour wandering
far from the net to break up a potential breakaway opportunity, the
puck was rimmed around to the blue line where Oilers winger Rem
Murray was able to whip it into a vacated net from 50 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   However, Oilers winger Pat Falloon and Stars defenseman Darryl
Sydor collided with Belfour, who had skated all the way out to the
right circle. Falloon was called for goaltender interference on the
play, meaning the puck was dead as soon as Murray touched it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the game, Falloon missed pushing the puck over the
goal line by inches. The goal light went on, but the goal was
overturned on review. In addition, the Oilers had another goal
overturned on review when Todd Marchant chipped in a loose puck
with 57.1 seconds remaining in the first period, but Oilers winger
Ethan Moreau was called with the tip of his skate blade in the
crease.
</P>
<P>
   No offensive player is allowed to precede the puck into the
crease.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers worked their plan almost perfectly as they backed off
slightly on the physical play and concentrated more on making
offensive plays. Neither team was able to stay away from the
physical stuff, and referees Dan Marouelli and Dave Jackson sent a
procession of players to the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Stars continued to squander chance after chance on
the power play _ and the Oilers simply fed off that energy. With
the Skyreach Centre _ one of the loudest buildings in the NHL _
humming from the start, it was clear this was a different Oilers
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers received great efforts from Smyth, Falloon, Marchant
and Doug Weight as they had twice as many scoring chances as they
created in the first two games combined.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars threw plenty of shots at Oilers Salo, but he continued
to prove himself a frustrating figure for the Stars until Keane
beat him on a freaky 40-footer that was screened and Modano chipped
in a rebound to tie the game.  &LR; tagtop:Mike Heika, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
