<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Modano starts to contribute just in time 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ For the first 170 minutes of the playoffs,
Tom Hicks deserved a refund. He hadn't been getting his $12 million
worth.
</P>
<P>
   That, give or take a few Jaguars, is what the Stars owner is
paying Mike Modano and Brett Hull to take his team to the Stanley
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock was on the verge of filing missing
persons reports on his two leading scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Stars once again found a way to win, getting the
game-tying goal from Mike Modano with about 10 minutes to play in
the final period and the game-winner from Joe Nieuwendyk less than
three minutes later as the Stars took a commanding 3-0 lead in the
best-of-seven first-round playoff series with Oilers at Skyreach
Centre.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, the pretty boys had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, if you're going to win, your scorers are going to
have to score,'' Hitchcock had prophesied at yesterday morning's
pregame skate. ``I think both teams scorers are going to have an
impact on these games in this building.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Hitchcock was right.
</P>
<P>
   Modano scored 34 goals and Hull 32 to lead the Stars this
season, but until Modano's shot found the net midway through the
third period, they hadn't had a sniff of a goal in the first three
games of this series.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this style of rough-and-tumble hockey isn't exactly
the flavor they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Their impact in these three games had been, to put it mildly,
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Mildly is how the Stars' two leading scorers have played in a
series marked by crashing hits, flying bodies and grind-it-out
offense. Until the third period last night, they had been totally
upstaged by little-known Oilers goalie Tommy Salo.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had been on the verge of allowing the Oilers to get
back on their skates with a chance at taking it to six or seven
games, which has been their humble goal all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``As important as Game 2 is for the home team \Rthe Stars\S, I
think Game 3 is equally important for the home team \Rthe
Oilers\S,'' Hitchcock said. ``If \Rthe Oilers\W win Game 3, then
you know there's a race on. If \Rthe Oilers\S lose Game 3, then the
distance can become pretty deep.''
</P>
<P>
   It has long been an NHL axiom that teams who are truly Stanley
Cup bound don't waste time or energy in the early rounds of the
playoffs. It is to their great advantage to dispose of lesser teams
quickly, thus saving themselves for the tougher challenges ahead.
</P>
<P>
   That is a particularly cognizant point in this rugged series,
where the Stars, even if they prevail, can ill afford to allow the
Oilers to beat them to a green pulp and go helplessly staggering
into the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars lost inspirational leader Guy Carbonneau at the end of
Game 2 in Dallas with a torn ligament in his right knee and saw
defenseman Richard Matvichuk limp off last night with a groin
injury.
</P>
<P>
   They came into the series already missing Derian Hatcher
(suspended) and Pat Verbeek (knee sprain).
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year when the Stars particularly need Modano
and Hull to step up their games, especially in igniting a power
play that has now gone 0-for-17 in the first three games of the
series, including a disgusting 0-for-7 last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things concern me,'' Hitchcock had said before the game.
``We haven't been able to spread the gap offensively \Rin Games 1
and 2\S, even though the shots and opportunities have been there.
And we haven't played a full 60 minutes yet. We've gotten away with
40 and we're going to have to play 60 to win in this building.''
</P>
<P>
   His words turned out to be more than prophetic, even before the
first period had concluded. Though they couldn't get the puck in
the net, the Stars dominated the first 10 minutes of the game and
at one point held a 7-1 advantage in shots.
</P>
<P>
   But gradually their malodorous power play sucked the energy out
of their game. They refused to benefit from three manpower
advantages. Not so the Oil.
</P>
<P>
   Given a 5-on-3 opportunity after Shawn Chambers and Richard
Matvichuk both took penalties inside the five-minute mark, veteran
center Doug Weight bided his time, spotted Ryan Smyth breaking to
the net behind Darryl Sydor and put the puck on Smyth's stick with
a perfect pass.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth easily deflected the puck past Ed Belfour and into the net
for a 1-0 Edmonton lead.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth and the Stars' Mike Keane swapped goals before Modano and
Nieuwendyk shocked the Oilers with two goals down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the game, an Oilers' fan waved a pointed sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modano,'' it read, ``wears panties.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's back from the dead, it's at least something we can
check.  &LR; tagtop:Jim Reeves, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:revo &LR; star-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
