<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-OILERS-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONTON TURNS UP AGGRESSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ The Edmonton Oilers had this problem in
Games 1 and 2. They were getting hardly any shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   They were shooting, mind you, but not enough, and the shots they
were getting weren't getting to Stars goalie Eddie Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a team to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot more,'' Oilers captain Kelly Buchberger said before Game
3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot more,'' Oilers winger Rem Murray repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot more,'' Oilers winger Todd Marchant echoed.
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what they did in Game 3 last night at
Skyreach Centre. They were much more aggressive offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers finished with 22 shots on goal and lost, 3-2, to the
Stars, putting them down 3-0 in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   The problem?
</P>
<P>
   They shot more, and the shots actually reached Belfour. He
simply stopped enough of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we have to get those shots through and then get
in front of \RBelfour\S and not let him see the puck,'' Murray
said, laying out Edmonton's plan before the game. ``He's too good
of a goaltender for that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the main reason the Oilers' Ryan Smyth was back in the
lineup after being a healthy scratch in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they needed me to stand in front of the net,'' Smyth
said when informed he had been reinserted in the lineup for Game 3.
``That's my job: Stand in front of the net and wreak havoc and pick
up the garbage goals.''
</P>
<P>
   One man's trash turned out to be the Oilers' treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Smyth scored with 4:25 remaining on the first period, a tip-in
of a Doug Weight pass to give Edmonton a 1-0 lead. It was the first
power-play goal in the series.
</P>
<P>
   He scored another ``garbage'' goal 24 seconds into the third
period, also on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The power play was one of the main reasons the Oilers were
finally able to register first-period shots. They had eight last
night, double their first-period totals in Game 1 (4) and Game 2
(4).
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the first period last night, the Stars had
outshot the Oilers, 7-1. Penalties to Shawn Chambers, Richard
Matvichuk, Joe Nieuwendyk and the ensuing power plays near the end
of the first period helped to even that up in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the period ended, the Oilers had one more shot than
the Stars, 8-7. It was the first time the Oilers had outshot the
Stars in any period in the playoffs. Belfour faced 13 shots in Game
1 and 19 in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between then and last night?
</P>
<P>
   ``The shots we have gotten,'' Murray said, ``the traffic hasn't
been there.''
</P>
<P>
   The traffic was there last night. Belfour couldn't see the blue
line with Smyth and Ethan Moreau constantly in his face.
</P>
<P>
   The shots slowed considerably for the Oilers in the second
period. They were without a shot until Marchant's short-handed
breakaway with less than 10 minutes remaining in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   By then, though, the Oilers had made their point.
</P>
<P>
   They were going to shoot more. They were going to be aggressive.
They were going to make Belfour win the game for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   They, at least, made him work.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
