pro and con, tried to turn the Littleton shootings to their
advantage in the days following the killings. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON-CRAZE (Langhorne, Pa.) _ Pokemon, a video game that
features 150 monsters, or Pokemons, is the new craze among
schoolchildren across the country. Introduced in Japan by the
Nintendo Corp. just three years ago, Pokemon has already grown into
a $5-billion international industry that includes comic books,
plastic figurines, virtual pets, bean-bag toys, lunch boxes,
T-shirts, a television cartoon show and compact disks. By Sharon R.
King.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-DEATHROW-VET (San Quentin, Calif.) _ Little more than a
week until his appointment with the state executioner, Manny
Babbitt has more friends now than in all his nearly 50 miserable
years. The list of those rallying to save his life is long and
growing. It includes at least two of the jurors who sentenced him
to death, his trial lawyer, who says his defense was inept, and a
retired police officer who Babbitt saved as a Marine in Vietnam.
For Gov. Gray Davis, who is waiting for a recommendation from the
Board of Prison Terms before deciding whether to commute Babbitt's
sentence to life in prison, the case poses a unique dilemma. Davis
promised to be a tough-on-crime, pro death-penalty governor. But he
has also pledged to give veterans their due respect. Babbitt, who
was awarded the Purple Heart in a rare prison ceremony two years
ago, has become a rallying cry for Vietnam veterans of all
political stripes. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-GROUP-PRATT (Washington) _ Public Lives profile of Larry
Pratt, director of Gun Owners of America, who believes there should
be absolutely no restrictions on gun ownership and use. By Frank
Bruni.
