   PATENTS (Undated) _ With the recent success of Viagra, the
impotence drug for men, a number of companies are scurrying to
develop sexual-dysfunction therapies aimed at an even larger
market: women. The weekly patents column. By Teresa Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-GOVERNMENT (Mountain View, Calif.) _ As the worlds of
politics and high technology increasingly come together, Virginia
Governor James S. Gilmore III is a man who would like to be at the
nexus. In recent years, Virginia's high-technology economy has
surged and Gilmore has made Internet policy central to his 18-month
stint in office. Now he is seeking to parlay his efforts into a
national role. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   SUN-MICROSYSTEMS-SOFTWARE (San Francisco) _ Sun Microsystems
Inc. plans to introduce a software product on Monday that is
designed for companies that want to let their employees use various
devices to connect to corporate computer networks, secure from
unauthorized access. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   BIZJOURNAL-MAKEOVER-MEDIA (Undated) _ The Journal of Commerce _
which was founded in 1827 by Samuel Morse, the inventor of the
telegraph _ is jettisoning most of its policy coverage and all of
its commodity price listings to devote itself to ``those who
control the movement of goods.'' It will also convert from a
broadsheet to a tabloid format on June 1. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-SITE-MEDIA (Undated) _ The niche market for
business-oriented sites on the World Wide Web is getting a little
more crowded. Dow Jones &AMP; Co. is introducing dowjones.com, a free
site for business users. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ A new handbook on television reporting
offers a timely chapter on how to cover hostage situations; a
publicity stunt offends some journalists. The Media Talk column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIAN-WRITER (Undated) _ For three decades Pramoedya Ananta
Toer, Indonesia's greatest modern writer, felt the full force of
President Suharto's military state. He is a free man now, on his
first visit to the United States and his first trip abroad since
1959. When he speaks there is no mistaking his inner strength, and
no sign that his tormentors ever came close to breaking his will.
By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SMILEY-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ The wholesale transformation of my
writing life began, I suppose inevitably, with just a notion. I was
beginning a new novel, a comic novel about horse racing, and I have
to say I was inordinately pleased with it. The American Letters
series; this week by Jane Smiley.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR-DOCUMENTARIES (Undated) _ Earlier this year, the board of
governors of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, which
administers the Oscars, voted to eliminate the award for short
documentaries. The vote provoked an outcry from documentary
filmmakers, who say that short documentaries, which were first
recognized by the academy in 1943, are an art form in themselves.
By Terry Pristin.
</P>
<P>
   LEXUS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``The Lexus and the Olive
Tree,'' a spirited and imaginative exploration of our new order of
economic globalization, and the instant technological and financial
networks that have brought it about, the author, Thomas L.
Friedman, is upbeat. Reviewed by Richard Eder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire writes about NATO's
dilemma in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ARATON-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports column on Joe DiMaggio
day. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on Penguins-Devils
playoff series. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Miami) _ Sports column on Knicks in Miami. By
William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN East Rutherford, N.J.) _ Sports column on
U.S.-China women's soccer game. By George Vecsey.
</P>
