<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2970 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIGIL-AZR &LR;      04-26 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIGIL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATHERING AT ARIZONA CAPITOL MARKS VICTIMS' RIGHTS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Lori Clarke crouched over the grass, carefully setting
each cardboard steppingstone around a pine tree outside the state
Capitol on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, she wrote the names of 432 dead children, each
in her perfect elementary schoolteacher penmanship in thick black
felt-tip pen on the cardboard stones.
</P>
<P>
   MARGIE MENDOZA. CINDY CHANDLER. RICHARD W. BOECK.
</P>
<P>
   She continued setting the stones until they stretched out 7
feet, circling the tree, each representing a child lost from
someone in her group, Parents of Murdered Children.
</P>
<P>
   She hopes the symbolic gesture will help people remember crime
victims this week during the National Crime Victims' Rights Week.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke doesn't need this special day to remind her of what is
now gone from her life _ her 18-year-old son, Matthew _ shot to
death when he tried to walk away from an argument five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never goes away,'' said Clarke, a teacher at Rose Linda
School in Phoenix and a member of Parents of Murdered Children, as
she straightened out the stones.
</P>
<P>
   SEDONA PERRY. PATRICK PENNINGTON. BRIAN SETH PATTISON.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 members of the support group and their friends gathered
near the stones Sunday evening, reciting poems, listening to songs
and telling stories for their annual Victims' Rights Vigil. They
spoke of the pain of the families in Littleton, Colo., where two
students killed 12 others and a teacher before turning their guns
on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They talked of how Arizona was one of the first states to pass a
victims' rights bill, but that there is much more to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   They hope the vigil will help encourage state legislators to
pass a bill this session that would give families of murder victims
a chance to speak at killers' sentencings.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley said the bill recently
passed the Senate and now is in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families need to be heard,'' Romley said during another
victims' rights rally where about 100 people gathered at Cesar
Chavez Memorial Plaza on Saturday afternoon. ``Murder victims feel
a real loss. This would be their opportunity to let the court know
the impact. It's horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley said only a handful of states have passed similar laws.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the same families who pinned red, white and blue ribbons
on their clothes at the afternoon rally then went to the vigil at
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   They walked around the steppingstones, searching for their loved
ones' names.
</P>
<P>
   JULIA AVANT. SCOTT HAZELIP. ROBERT OTIS III.
</P>
<P>
   The stones didn't tell the stories of how these people, some
only a few months old, others senior citizens, were killed. But the
people at the gathering did.
</P>
<P>
   There were victims of drunken-driving crashes and fathers who
shook babies. Drunken brawls and random gunshots. Stabbings and
murder-suicides.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Fiero, a board member for the support group, scanned the
stones, searching for her little boy's name, Aaron Fiero.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six years ago in Portland, Maine, her son, then 2{, was
killed by a teenage baby-sitter. And 26 years later, her pain
remains.
</P>
<P>
   The business consultant found the support group only a few years
ago. When she first attended one of the meetings, another member
said to her: ``Whatever your story is, someone else's is worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiero knows you can't compare grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I realize, at least I got to say goodbye. At least
there was a body,'' she says. ``You can take comfort in strange,
little things.''
</P>
<P>
   A snapshot of her sandy-haired boy with chubby cheeks smiles
from a big pin on her blouse.
</P>
<P>
   HEATHER SUZZANA KOENIG. JAMES MAURER. DONALD PETTIT. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laura Trujillo can be reached at 444-8891 or at
laura.trujillo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
