<HEADLINE>
ANGST OVER AIMS: TODAY IS TEST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MELISSA L. JONES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an increasingly common complaint among today's
AIMS-anxious.
</P>
<P>
   At the mere mention of the looming state graduation test,
students shriek, ``But I'm a bad test taker!''
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms include blurred vision, stomach pains, sometimes loss
of sleep and bad dreams, and, of course, a bad test grade.
</P>
<P>
   And today, when high school sophomores take the first of the
controversial new Arizona Instrument to Measure Standards tests,
some of these symptoms will reach their peaks.
</P>
<P>
   But is there really a quantifiable deficiency among so many
students?
</P>
<P>
   Or are students just afraid that their knowledge of English and
algebra is too weak to earn them a diploma under the state's new
standards?
</P>
<P>
   Educators say there is truth in both.
</P>
<P>
   Students say they are truly nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I take tests, I just blank out,'' said Red Mountain High
School sophomore Nahum Cruz. ``The words scramble all over the
place. If they didn't say it was a test, I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Davis, 16, who said he's never been good at tests, said
AIMS could hurt students like him.
</P>
<P>
   Since grade school, he has believed that so long as he shows up
for class and does the work, he'll make it to a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you bombed the test, you'd still be OK,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the Class of 2002. Not on this test.
</P>
<P>
   Today, members of the Class of 2001 will answer multiple-choice
questions, write extended answers and essays and be required to
show their work on math problems as they complete the state's
graduation test.
</P>
<P>
   This year the sophomores will guinea-pig the test and need not
worry about a passing grade.
</P>
<P>
   Although their scores will be slapped on their diplomas,
sophomores do not need passing marks on the exam to toss their
mortarboards come 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That challenge has been saved for the Class of 2002, today's
freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   They won't take the test until next year, but for them, the
stress is mounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people can do the work, but when it comes to taking the
test, their brain doesn't connect,'' said Jennifer Zimmerman, 14, a
Chandler High School freshman. ``And the bubbles, the bubbles are
the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All your teachers hype it up, your parents hype it up,'' said
Seth Sweeden, a 15-year-old freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Said freshman Chris Martin, ``I'm nervous because it determines
my whole future.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a difference between typical test anxiety and a
nervousness that keeps you from being able to read, said Maryann
Santos de Barona, associate professor of psychology in education at
Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there are physical symptoms of test anxiety,'' said
Santos de Barona. ``For some individuals, as you might imagine, it
is more severe than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking into hives and experiencing nausea are among them.
</P>
<P>
   Nervousness is normal, but some students simply do not test as
well as others, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think historically there have always been individuals who
know a lot more than they can show on a standardized test, and
certainly that is problematic,'' said Santos de Barona.
</P>
<P>
   A prepared student who blanks out and has problems simply
understanding questions might need help from a school counselor,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Special-education students or those with limited English could
have additional problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that you can assume that their level of anxiety is
going to be higher just because some of the other factors are going
to be compounding, such as language,'' she said. ``For limited
English proficiency students, the test becomes a language test more
than a knowledge test.''
</P>
<P>
   Mild learning disabilities that might not qualify a student for
special-education services could still hurt students on such a
test, said Camelback High School counselor Claudia Armer.
</P>
<P>
   Attention deficit disorder or obsessive compulsive disorder is
not uncommon on high school campuses in mild forms, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But many educators are worried about everybody taking the test,
whether they're special-education students or not.
</P>
<P>
   There is good reason, they said, to be nervous for a test for
which passing grades have not been established and the full test
has never been seen by most teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like the fear of the unknown,'' said Patricia
Tobin, director of special education for the Phoenix Union High
School District.
</P>
<P>
   If past experience on high-stakes testing is any indication,
antacid could be handled out with No. 2 pencils.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Hoopes, 16, developed stomach pains when she tried her
luck at the ACT last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the test I like totally freaked,'' Hoopes said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Todaro, 16, had a similar experience with another college
entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like the PSAT, I like freaked out on the math part,''
Todaro said.
</P>
<P>
   More knowledge of the fledgling test would calm the nerves of
school officials and their students.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler freshman Zimmerman and her friends said they would like
to see the AIMS study guide that has been circulated to sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the tests, many high school sophomores had not
seen the student guides produced by the state Department of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   In the schools, teachers said they are sharing as much as they
can about a test most of them have not seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we actually see the test, we don't know what degree of
difficulty will be on any given question,'' said Corona del Sol
math teacher Stan Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, students simply need to do their homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often some of the cause of test anxiety is related to the
fact that students are not prepared, don't know what to expect of a
test, have not covered the material extensively,'' said Santos de
Barona. ``More often than not, that plays a very large role.''
</P>
<P>
   For that, teachers said, there is help.
</P>
<P>
   After all, that is the reason kids go to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is you have to have that grounding _ one
year of algebra and one year of geometry,'' said Larry Strom, math
department chairman at Desert Vista High School in Ahwatukee
Foothills.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have the grounding, then you panic,'' said Strom,
who helped develop the recommended passing score for the math
portion of the test.
</P>
<P>
   Students not taking the right courses will have problems, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are reminding students of some universal testing tips:
</P>
<P>
   Eat a good breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Get a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the test in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   A decent attitude helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of saying, `Boy, I'm going to blow this test,' saying,
`I know this material,' '' Santos de Barona said.
</P>
<P>
   Going over the organization of the test is helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Simple things like the number of questions, format, organization
and knowledge of who will grade the test can ease a student's mind.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that AIMS is not a timed test also should alleviate
some pressure, educators said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky charms help, too.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Davis wears a lucky necklace.
</P>
<P>
   Nahum Cruz has a lucky coin with Queen Elizabeth on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray,'' said Alfreda Toddy, 16, a Chandler High sophomore.
``It calms me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools are trying to boost kids' confidence, trying to balance
stressing the importance of AIMS and simply stressing students.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe Union High School District brought in Intel Corp.
volunteers to talk with sophomores about taking the test seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's message: Get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   Students were reminded that if they ever want a professional
job, as a doctor, lawyer, engineer or accountant, chances are they
will be tested.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, even John F. Kennedy Jr. took three times to pass
the New York State Bar exam.
</P>
<P>
   These students have five chances over three years to pass the
AIMS test.
</P>
<P>
   By the third try, everyone should be a little more comfortable
with AIMS, said Red Mountain counselor Owen Rentschler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll all be a lot wiser a year from now,'' Rentschler
said. &QL; 
Melissa L. Jones can be reached at (602) 444-7951 or at
melissa.jones(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
