<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTPREP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS SEEK TEST AID, FIRMS OFFER `STUDY SKILLS' PRO GRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHRYN CRENO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ink is barely dry on the AIMS forms. Students who take the
test this year won't have to pass it to graduate. Yet the phone has
been ringing for weeks at the Sylvan Learning Center in the
Ahwatukee Foothills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are calling and saying, `The AIMS is coming up . . .
do you have something that will help my kid pass the math?' '' said
Pat Cunningham, director of the private tutoring firm in southeast
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Sylvan doesn't have a specific program to help kids
ace the AIMS.
</P>
<P>
   Neither do the Kaplan Educational Centers nor the Princeton
Review, Tempe firms that aim to help high schoolers boost scores on
college entrance exams.
</P>
<P>
   But Sylvan does have a $1,000, 30-session high school ``study
skills'' tutoring program that Cunningham says can help improve
grades and raise scores on a number of standardized tests.
</P>
<P>
   And Princeton and Kaplan have copies of the Arizona Department
of Education's AIMS study guide and expect to use it to develop
specific AIMS prep programs for high schoolers by next year _ when
the first class that has to pass it to graduate takes the test.
</P>
<P>
   State Testing Director Kelly Powell said Arizona has no policy
against programs like Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prep programs can be helpful,'' he said. ``And we wouldn't
want to cut into private enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Graham Keegan, state superintendent of public instruction,
applauds the programs _ as long as they are based on the state's
1996 academic standards, the basis for the AIMS test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support any model that helps students prepare for AIMS,''
she said. ``I don't agree that `prepping' programs defeat the real
purpose of AIMS. Instead it encourages students to do what they
should be doing, which is learning the standards in reading,
writing and mathematics.''
</P>
<P>
   But other educators question the value and ethics of test prep.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for these firms' current programs range from $75 into the
thousands of dollars, depending on the length and intensity of the
preparation that students want.
</P>
<P>
   At such programs, instructors _ who often are moonlighting
certified teachers _ show teens the formats of standardized tests
and coach them about how to best handle questions they aren't
certain how to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If students know what they are supposed to do on these tests
ahead of time they tend to do a lot better than if they just go in
cold,'' said Ben Mauk, executive director of the Princeton Review's
Tempe office.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State University West education Professor Tom Haladyna
is one of many testing experts who question the ethics of such
programs. He thinks they can lead to artificially inflated scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public and the students are deceived into thinking real
learning is going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Schaeffer, spokesman for the Massachusetts non-profit
National Center for Fair and Open Testing, thinks prep programs
``dumb down'' education.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not on the test, kids don't learn it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other educators think it's simply unfair that private programs
can give middle-class kids an edge over low-income teens on an
important test like the AIMS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can already see the carpetbaggers hawking their wares,''
sighed Bob Welton, testing director for the Bisbee Unified High
School District, who dislikes private prep programs.
</P>
<P>
   To help even the score for low-income kids, some districts are
developing AIMS prep programs of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Joe O'Reilly, testing director for Mesa public schools, said his
district most likely will have free AIMS prep by next year. &QL; 
Cathryn Creno can be reached at (602) 444-8056 or at
cathryn.creno(at)pni.com and education(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
