<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2987 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICEHOUSE-AZR &LR;      04-26 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICEHOUSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX ARTS CROWD UPSET ABOUT PLAN FOR JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When Maricopa County planners look along Phoenix's
West Jackson Street, they see a desolate corner of downtown that
could be improved by a new 10-story jail, parking garage and
morgue.
</P>
<P>
   But artists and historic preservationists see warehouses ripe
for renovation into shops, galleries, lofts and cafes.
</P>
<P>
   The two visions collide at Jackson Street and Fourth Avenue in
downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   It is a crossroads once bustling with passengers from the train
station at the south end of Fourth Avenue, trucks spilling fruit
along Jackson Street, and workers loading rail cars with produce
and 300-pound blocks of ice.
</P>
<P>
   What's left is bleak. The streets here have been forgotten by
all but homeless squatters in the alleys, a handful of businesses
and artists like Helen Hestenes, who's making a stand to salvage
remnants of the warehouse district near Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all we have left,'' she said in making her pitch for
preservation. ``You can't always take out the heart and soul of a
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County's $850 million jail project is targeting three
sites along Jackson Street for a 1,200-bed jail, six-story parking
garage, offices for the medical examiner and county records
storage.
</P>
<P>
   County planners believe the project can enhance the area, and
they are willing to work with the artists to ``do what's right for
downtown,'' said Norm Hentz, county director of facilities
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision for it is a people-friendly place,'' he said. ``It's
hard to do that with a jail. They're just not friendly places, but
we can improve its curb appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The jail would occupy the former Borden dairy block, just west
of the Madison Street Jail.
</P>
<P>
   A 1,500-space parking garage, combined with space for the
medical examiner, is planned for the southwest corner of Jackson
and Fifth Avenue. The county intends to demolish an empty freight
depot on the site.
</P>
<P>
   The county also is considering buying the Mayflower-Chambers
building, 301 S. Fourth Ave., to store records.
</P>
<P>
   County voters in November authorized up to $900 million in
funding for the jail and other adult and juvenile correctional
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Planners want to build the jail near the county courthouse at
Third Avenue and Jefferson Street so prisoners can be safely led to
court appearances in existing underground tunnels, said Bob
Williams, county criminal justice facilities development director.
</P>
<P>
   The county has not finalized its plans, but Williams insists
that the jail will be downtown. It's safer there, and it would be
too costly to transport prisoners to the courthouse from a more
remote location, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the county's plans aren't opposed to a jail downtown
but are pressuring the county to rethink the Jackson Street sites.
</P>
<P>
   Hestenes, who over the past 10 years has transformed a 1910
warehouse into the Icehouse gallery and performance art space, said
the 10-story jail doesn't belong towering over the warehouse
district.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix City Councilman Phil Gordon, a longtime historic
preservation advocate, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building a 10-story structure would literally and figuratively
be a crime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The county needs to sit down with all the interested parties _
artists, the city, historic preservationists and developers _ to
come up with a better plan, Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Skip Rimsza plans to appoint an ad hoc committee on the
warehouse district, his spokesman Scott Phelps said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the county needs a place to build near the
courthouse and there aren't a lot of options, said Joy Mee,
assistant city planning director.
</P>
<P>
   Hestenes suggested building it on the other side of the Madison
Street Jail in a block occupied by a county parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   But county officials said that would be too costly.
</P>
<P>
   Hestenes also is fighting the county's plan to tear down the
freight depot and use the historic Mayflower-Chambers building for
storage.
</P>
<P>
   Both buildings are central to plans for the area created by the
South Downtown Area group, SODA for short.
</P>
<P>
   Artists' lofts are envisioned for the Mayflower-Chambers
building along with restaurants, a farmers market, bakery and
coffeehouse. The depot, a dilapidated concrete building with
loading docks and freight doors, is targeted for retail shops, a
cafe and a sculpture garden.
</P>
<P>
   The group also envisions commuter rail service reviving the
train station, which, with an adjacent park, would be the
centerpiece of the restored warehouse district, Hestenes said.
</P>
<P>
   Artist Ed Mell has agreed to donate his services for a sculpture
titled ``Digging In'' for the Union Station park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, it's very important to me to save what little
early history we have,'' said Mell, who remembers from his
childhood the once-thriving area near the train station.
</P>
<P>
   Mell said he envisions an inviting public place in the blocks
surrounding Union Station, rather than a stark streetscape for
prisons, parking and a morgue.
</P>
<P>
   The city is supportive of the artists' ideas for southwest
downtown but funding is problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to have money to invest,'' Mee said. ``The artists
haven't had a lot of money to invest and neither does the city.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty of developer interest in the area if the
county doesn't overrun the area, Hestenes said, pointing to the
success of redevelopment along East Jackson Street near Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Artists were pushed out of warehouses near the county-developed
ballpark, and they don't want to lose out again at the other end of
Jackson Street, Hestenes added.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Arts Commission has recommended that the historic
buildings on West Jackson Street be preserved. But there is only so
much the city can do because the county has condemnation powers for
a public purpose, such as the jail, Mee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know as we have the power to stop them from doing
that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to the city, county and community is to find a way
to fit the jail downtown and protect the character of Jackson
Street, said John Meunier, dean of Arizona State's College of
Architecture and Environmental Design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to think the county isn't going to steamroll in
there with a huge jail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mayor Terry Goddard, who recently met with the county
about its plans, said he thinks it's ``important that we not slam
the door on something that could be a real important people place
for Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Santa Fe depot is a jewel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the station's heyday, travelers arriving there saw Phoenix as
a garden spot when they stepped off the train onto Fourth Avenue,
the former mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, if they get off the train and they're met by a
jail and a morgue, I don't think they'll see us as a garden
spot.'' &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at (602) 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
