<SLUG> BC-RAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROADS TO DANGER: AGGRESSIVE DRIVING ON RISE, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB PETRIE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Zabriskic, who's been driving _ and surviving _ in the
Valley since before the freeways, adheres to a simple credo
whenever he gets behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to operate under the assumption everyone on the road
is a total idiot,'' the north Phoenix resident said.
</P>
<P>
   It's Zabriskic's way of dealing with aggressive driving, a
phenomenon that quickly can ratchet up to road rage, something
police believe led to the fatal shooting April 17 of a Phoenix
youth.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials say violence resulting from traffic
altercations is rare, there's no doubt drivers in the Valley _ and
around the country _ are becoming more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can count on two or three a week, fights related to traffic
accidents,'' said Mark Jeffrey, veteran traffic reporter for
KFYI-AM (910).
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago it was kind of an odd thing, now it's kind of a
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case resulting in the death of 17-year-old Jamison
Morrison, Peoria police say the trouble started with a
vehicle-bumping incident on Lake Pleasant Road involving pickup
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   One was driven by Morrison, the other by Luis Salas, who tried
to drive away.
</P>
<P>
   But Morrison continued to follow Salas until he stopped near
104th Avenue and Beardsley Road.
</P>
<P>
   Salas, who was unarmed, got out of his truck. Jamison Morrison
and his father, William Jay Morrison, confronted Salas. The father
pulled a .357-caliber Magnum and pointed it at Salas, while the son
fired a BB gun at Salas, hitting him in the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Salas then got control of the .357 and shot and killed Jamison
Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   The father was charged Tuesday with aggravated assault and is
being held in a Maricopa County jail in lieu of $170,000 bail.
Salas has not been charged, because Peoria police believe he acted
reasonably in defending himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's episodes such as this fueling the fears of drivers that
they, too, could become road rage victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really afraid of other drivers,'' said Stephanie
Faul, spokeswoman for the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington, D.C.-based organization did a national study,
tracking 10,000 violent traffic incidents from 1990 through 1996,
concluding there's a 7 percent annual rise in aggressive driving
during that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some evidence it is getting worse,'' Faul said.
``Certainly, the public perception is it's getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Valley, one national study shows it is. In March, the
Surface Transportation Policy Project listed Phoenix the third
worst metropolitan area for death rates from aggressive driving;
9.2 deaths per 100,000 people in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature passed a road rage bill in 1998, calling
for stiff fines, jail terms and revoked licenses for motorists who
speed and endanger others with their driving behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix police also have an aggressive-driving program, which
since early 1997 has resulted in more than 3,800 citations.
</P>
<P>
   Zabriskic, a retired state employee, has had several run-ins
with angry drivers. Recently, he was followed by an aggressive
motorist on Camelback Road for several miles, before the driver
finally passed him by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't about to follow that jerk,'' he said. ``It's a
lose-lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon James, a University of Hawaii professor who has been
studying aggressive driving since 1979, says people need to change
their behavior toward others while out on the road.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly adds it takes a lot of work, and preparation, since
his own surveys show most people rank themselves as excellent
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not prepared, it catches you unexpected, and up goes
a finger,'' said James, who calls himself ``Dr. Driving,'' for his
studies on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   James suggests drivers carry a notebook, or turn on a tape
recorder while driving, to catch moments of anger toward others, as
well as eliminate their own mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Bob Stein of the Department of Public Safety says if you
inadvertently cut someone off, it doesn't hurt to say you're sorry
_ with a shrug of the shoulders or a friendly wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``People usually take that the right way,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   If not, Stein says turn the other cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody comes up to you and flips you off, you don't want
to encourage it by flipping them off back,'' Stein said. ``Just let
'em rant and rave a little, and let 'em go on their way.'' &QL; 
Bob Petrie can be reached at (602) 444-7941 or at
bob.petrie(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
