<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3538 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NATO-UNITY-REVIEW-A     04-26 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NATO-UNITY-REVIEW-ART-625(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A WONDER THIS ALLIANCE IS UNIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lh) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For most of the half-century it is celebrating in
Washington this weekend, NATO's very existence has been rooted in
the idea of a grand design _ to guarantee the safety of the West
against the East, to forge a common defense of democracy against
tyranny, to prepare, in effect, for World War III.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as NATO's forces press their first true combat mission
in a messy conflict in Kosovo, the allies and their neighbors are
discovering that war is not just about the grand design of
thwarting tyranny, but about niggling details and political line
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is more than just America's war or even NATO's war. It is
an ominous prism refracting the national interests of the allies
(and their neighbors) from the most sweeping political
considerations to the most mundane. For each of the nations
involved, the conflict has shades of meaning and ambiguity,
revealing the alliance on its 50th anniversary as an assembly of
agendas in uneasy cohesion _ and raising the question of whether it
can survive an escalation into a ground war.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, matters as basic as river traffic on the
Danube halted by NATO's bombing of bridges, or faltering tourism in
Greece and Croatia _ consequences of war that show that the
conflict's price will be paid in many coinages, from Budapest,
Hungary, to Athens, Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast those economic consequences with much bigger, almost
metaphysical themes: Germany's fraught dilemma between avoiding
embroilment in war while joining in the common campaign against
horrors all too familiar from its own past. There is also the
perennial fear in Europe _ in Italy, Germany and France in
particular _ of being overwhelmed by unwelcome refugees whose
presence, political leaders fear, would feed domestic tensions and
right-wing extremism.
</P>
<P>
   And consider the dynamics of those lands _ Italy and Greece _
that provide the ports and airfields for a war their people and
political elite do not universally approve. Then there is raw,
geopolitical ambition _ British in particular, but French, too _ to
show military leadership in a continent more used to Uncle Sam's
coattails, and to promote the idea of European cohesion, absent for
much of this decade's Balkan agony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the potential for division, the unity has been quite
amazing,'' said Gordon Adams, deputy director of the International
Institute for Strategic Studies in London.
</P>
<P>
   To say that NATO's members come to the table with varied baggage
_ both from their histories and from more modern times _ is an
understatement. And it is difficult to categorize their concerns
without oversimplification: Like overlays on a presentation board,
they overlap, cross-reference and sometimes contradict one another.
</P>
<P>
   In purely economic terms, the damage is felt not just by the
allies but by their non-alliance neighbors. At one point last week,
over 100,000 tons of waterborne freight intended for Austria,
Germany and Hungary were marooned on the Danube in Romania. An
Austrian shipping company said it was losing $77,000 a day because
of NATO bombing of Danube bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists in droves have canceled vacations on Croatia's Adriatic
cost _ much too close to the bombing for beach-lounging comfort.
Even in Greece, a tour operator said thousands of Americans had
postponed visits in case the Kosovo conflict spills southward. And
a ground war _ not to mention the likelihood of a massive postwar
reconstruction bill _ would strain budgets across Europe. Even now,
simply to keep one British Tornado warplane airborne for an hour
costs Britain's taxpayers $33,000. A single payload of bombs costs
$640,000, according to defense analysts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But economic woes may turn out to be far less intractable than
some of the political conundrums thrown up by the alliance's
embroilment in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It makes for a patchwork of uneasy bedfellows. For example,
Spain and Turkey, different in so many other ways, are both NATO
members committed to supporting the alliance's aims in Kosovo. But
both are also locked in their own conflicts against separatists _
respectively, Basques and Kurds _ who are demanding pretty much the
same things sought by the Kosovars whom the two nations purport to
defend in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The totalitarian exclusiveness of nationalism engenders
genocide and ethnic cleansing,'' warned Jose Maria Aznar, Spain's
prime minister. So why wage war in league with Kosovar
separatists? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Spain, of course, doesn't have a strategic interest in the
Balkans, but Turkey does. Its Ottoman forebears drew the very fault
lines of faith and ethnic division that have baffled Western policy
makers in the Balkans through two world wars and now for most of
the 1990s. And that legacy draws an arc of solidarity embracing
Muslim communities from Thrace in Greece to Albania and Bosnia
that, some fear, could pull Ankara toward a wider conflict.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more sensitive to that configuration of faith than the
Greeks, whose mirror-image sense of kinship with the Orthodox
Christian Serbs places the government of Prime Minister Costas
Simitis in a curious position, caught between the powerful pro-Serb
impulses of his compatriots and the broader pro-Western interests
reflected in Athens' enthusiastic drive to join the European single
currency. Orthodox Christianity, indeed, provides a critical link
of religious identities, stretching from Athens to Belgrade and on
to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Urged on by the Greek Orthodox Church, Greeks have demonstrated
against NATO's Kosovo campaign, even as the Greek port of
Thessaloniki is being used to resupply the 12,000 NATO troops in
neighboring Macedonia. At the same time, Simitis' popularity has
risen sharply in opinion surveys, underlining the keen desire of
many Greeks to see the war contained as far as possible from their
borders, avoiding a broader conflict with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here, too, is another overlay, this time from the Cold War:
If anyone within NATO supports Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan
Milosevic, it is Europe's Communists and ex-Communists, who are
usually depicted as discredited and spent. The small Greek
Communist party _ in tacit alliance with the Orthodox Church _ has
helped stage anti-Western demonstrations in Athens. Elsewhere,
ex-Communist leaders from eastern Germany and Italy have rushed to
Belgrade. Significantly, German opinion surveys show support for
the war running at 59 percent in western Germany, but only 38
percent in the formerly Communist east.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps surprisingly, this catalog of diversity has not dented
the high degree of support across Europe for the Kosovo campaign.
Almost universally, Europeans have been horrified _ even ashamed _
by images of refugees streaming out of Kosovo and into a collective
memory of the even more massive upheavals of the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, even those former central European lands that have
only just joined the alliance have not broken ranks: Hungary
hasn't, and it is on the very front line, with 300,000 Hungarian
brethren forming a minority in Yugoslavia's Vojvodina region, and
potentially vulnerable to Serbian reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   But, more cynically, it is the refugees that propel policies
that, in the words of Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, are
about moral imperatives and a ``just war.''
</P>
<P>
   No European power wants a huge influx of outsiders straining the
social fabric and state coffers at a time of widespread
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Italy thus was among the first to send 2,000 troops to Albania
to help in humanitarian relief. As on many occasions in recent
years, Rome's policy was driven by a calculation that it is
preferable to deal with refugees' distress at long range rather
than at home.
</P>
<P>
   Greece is already home to 400,000 Albanian immigrants, and the
authorities in Athens fear that a flood of Kosovo Albanian refugees
could unsettle their land.
</P>
<P>
   Only belatedly last week did France, with its uneasy immigrant
population, reverse its refusal to accept even small numbers of
refugees. And, after providing sanctuary for some 300,000 Bosnians,
many Germans feel they have done enough. Such thinking underpins
European calls for a postwar reconstruction strategy on the scale
of the Marshall Plan to stabilize the Balkans into the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priority should be to look after people in the region
where they have sought refuge and with which they are linked by
language and culture,'' said Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of
Germany. ``Any other policy would make us de facto accomplices of
Belgrade's policy of deportation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in Germany, of course, that the Kosovo campaign conjures
the sharpest dilemma of all, testing many of the nation's postwar
assumptions and straining the unity of its coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of German troops going to war _ in the Balkans of all
places _ deeply offends many Germans nurtured on postwar pacifism.
But the notion that, as a NATO member and European leader, modern
Germany should stand by is equally repellent, particularly to those
who have learned in school that they bear a special responsibility
to guard against a revival of the atrocities that mark their
nation's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given our German history,'' Schroeder said, ``we cannot leave
any doubt about our reliability, determination and steadfastness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
