<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 09:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3124 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-POLITICAL-HUMOR-REV     04-26 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-POLITICAL-HUMOR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 IN POLITICS, HE WHO JOKES LEAST LAUGHS LAST. A PITY.  (The Week in
Review) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN SOLOMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If the American people wanted Bob Hope as their president,''
Jimmy Carter once remarked, ``they would have elected him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's political demise probably had more to do with the
presence of gas lines than a lack of punch lines, but it's still
ironic that he was replaced by an ex-actor who used humor as
successfully as any politician this century. In fact, Ronald Reagan
is one of only a handful of elected officials in the nation's
history who have distinguished themselves with their wit.
</P>
<P>
   Today, alas, the pronouncements of politicians seem more
humorless than ever. That's probably because, in this era of
heightened sensitivities and ubiquitous cameras, an off-the-cuff
quip can bring you a world of grief (though politicians' private
peccadillos often provide laughs enough). So whether you're a
stolid Al Gore or a relentlessly sunny Elizabeth Dole, it's best to
stay on message while minimizing the ad-libs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, unscripted humor is an important element in the lives of
Americans. Shouldn't it be more central to American politics? Why
shunt it off to specially demarcated jocularity zones like
``Politically Incorrect'' or the Gridiron Club? Even those events
lately have been more awkward than amusing. At the White House
Correspondents Dinner next weekend, President Clinton has the
awkward pleasure of honoring a Newsweek reporter for his work
uncovering the Monica Lewinsky matter. That'll be almost as funny
as Paula Jones' appearance at last year's dinner. (``But other than
that, Mrs. Clinton, how was the meal?'')
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the voters of Minnesota were telling the political
establishment something last November when they elected a former
pro wrestler governor. Maybe they were saying that American
politics is as funny as a full Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   The political hilarity dearth cannot be denied. It was amply
illustrated recently by the publication of ``Great Political Wit''
(Nan A. Talese/Doubleday) by former Sen. Bob Dole, who has a
well-deserved reputation for being a funny guy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet _ and this is telling _ the book doesn't include any
examples of humor from his 1996 presidential campaign. Why? Because
there weren't any. His advisers felt it was too perilous to let
Dole be Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Dole was gun-shy after his disastrous yet sharply witty
vice presidential run in 1976. ``I was supposed to go for the
jugular and I did,'' he observed afterward. ``My own.''
</P>
<P>
   At such a divisively partisan time, a lighter tone could help.
Reagan knew how to deploy humor when the chips were down. Who else
could laugh off an assassin's attack with lines like, ``Honey, I
forgot to duck,'' and, in a quip directed at his surgery team, ``I
hope you're all Republicans''?
</P>
<P>
   Dole wasn't the only Senate bigwig to use laughter to grease the
legislative wheels. Everett Dirksen, the former Senate minority
leader, came up with memorable quips like, ``I am a man of fixed
and unbending principles _ the first of which is to be flexible at
all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, more funny people would run for office. Many who
snickered about the prospect of Congressman Sonny Bono soon
welcomed the sense of humor and perspective that the California
Republican brought to Washington. Rep. Morris ``Mo'' Udall was a
pro basketball player before entering politics, but he could also
have been a professional humorist. ``The public has spoken,'' Udall
declared after withdrawing from the 1976 presidential race. ``The
bastards.''
</P>
<P>
   It would help if more American originals like Jesse Ventura and
Fred Tuttle threw their hats into the ring. Ventura's successful
gubernatorial candidacy in Minnesota is by now legendary. And ol'
Fred, an endearing Vermont dairy farmer who won the Republican
Senate primary, might have done even better last November if he
hadn't gone and endorsed his opponent, Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN's coverage of the British House of Commons has provided
Americans with a refreshing view of a deliberative body where
clever repartee is required. Hail C-SPAN, beacon for the humorously
challenged!
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if politicians talked in Washington the way they talk on
``Imus in the Morning.'' If they loosened up. Were candid. Laughed
at themselves. Of course, that can't happen unless the public cuts
politicians some slack if they happen to misspeak.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jimmy Carter seemed to realize the value of humor by the
end of his term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank all the people who supported me,'' he told
the assembled press corps, waiting a beat before turning to his
wife with a grin. ``Thank you, Rosalynn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 0907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
