<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT     04-26 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS HIGHLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   China Stole Design of U.S. Nuclear Warhead
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the furor over China's theft of America's nuclear
secrets began last month, President Clinton said he wasn't so sure
any spying had taken place. But a government report seems to have
stopped the debate. The new analysis concludes that in the 1980s
China stole design information related to America's most advanced
nuclear warhead from Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican chairman and ranking Democrat on a select House
panel investigating allegations of illicit transfers of technology
to China met with Clinton Thursday to discuss incidents of Chinese
espionage, including what they described as ``current and ongoing''
problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES RISEN
</P>
<P>
   Backlash in Turkey
</P>
<P>
   Turkey turned inward as its voters favored two nationalistic
parties, one from the far right, the other leftist. Twenty years
ago the two parties, Democratic Left and Nationalist Action, fought
in the street. Now they are poised to join in a ruling coalition
under Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit. The election results reflected
anger at the European Union's refusal to accept Turkey as a
candidate for membership.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN KINZER
</P>
<P>
   Dismissed, Handsomely
</P>
<P>
   A pair of prominent corporate chiefs with similar surnames had
something else in common: Both were casualties of the Internet
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard Pfeiffer, chief executive of Compaq Computer, was
dismissed as head of the world's largest personal computer maker
after its profits failed to keep pace with Dell Computer, which
sells directly to consumers over the Internet and telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Philip M. Pfeffer, chief executive of the bookseller Borders,
also decamped, after only five months on the job. Borders has
struggled to keep up with Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble, leaders in
sales over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Smallpox Virus
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has granted a reprieve to a deadly killer
scheduled for execution.
</P>
<P>
   For ages, the smallpox virus struck humans, taking millions of
lives. World health authorities in 1980 declared the scourge
eradicated in humans, prompting calls for the destruction of
scientific samples. But the president, wary that foes may harbor
stocks, is forgoing that step and joining Russia, the world's other
destruction skeptic, in studies of new antidotes.
</P>
<P>
   _ WILLIAM J. BROAD
</P>
<P>
   Trade Gap Widens
</P>
<P>
   The American economy is booming and increasing its imports while
much of the world is drifting in economic doldrums with a
diminishing appetite for American goods. The result has sharply
increased the American trade deficit, which in February reached
$19.4 billion. The deficit renewed debate over just how ``free''
the nation's trade policies should be.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Limits on Scraping the Sky
</P>
<P>
   The zoning theory behind Manhattan's landscape since 1961 is
called ``tower in the park.'' As in: throw down some concrete, call
it a park and build the building higher. Developers move air rights
around like chess pieces, and those ``parks'' become giant ashtrays
for the shiver-and-puff crowd. Now city planners, calling the old
ways ``flawed,'' want strict limits outside midtown and downtown.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   GOP Campaign 2000
</P>
<P>
   He has never held elective office, lags behind rivals in polls
and as yet lacks the luster of a dark horse. But Gary L. Bauer's
entry into the race for the Republican presidential nomination
subtly alters the dynamic. The president of the conservative Family
Research Council, Bauer will probably bring God most forcefully
into the campaign, forcing more moderate Republicans like George W.
Bush to defend their nuanced positions on abortion and
homosexuality to the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   _ FRANK BRUNI
</P>
<P>
   Picasso the Car
</P>
<P>
   Picasso's heirs can hardly be faulted for wanting to cash in on
his name. Everyone else does, from makers of coffee mugs and
T-shirts to museums that draw record crowds to the maestro's shows.
Four heirs support the sale of his name and signature for a new
auto, the Citroen Xsara Picasso, to be launched this fall. But
Marina Picasso objects, saying her grandfather's genius is being
``exploited outrageously.'' Her share of the royalties will go a
foundation for Vietnamese orphans, she says.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALAN RIDING
</P>
<P>
   No Fond Farewell
</P>
<P>
   CNN parted ways with Peter Arnett, who helped established the
cable network's pre-eminence in breaking news with his live reports
from Baghdad during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnett also took part in the infamous ``Tailwind'' report,
which alleged that nerve gas was used in the Vietnam War. An
embarrassed CNN later retracted the report. Arnett claimed that he
had changed ``not one comma,'' apparently sealing his fate. After
first trying to ease him out quietly, CNN settled with him, rather
than deal with questions into why a one-time ace war correspondent
was nowhere to be seen in the latest living-room war.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Another Link
</P>
<P>
   Fossil hunters in Ethiopia think they have added a new branch to
the human family tree. They announced the discovery of the skull
and other fossils of a previously unknown 2.5 million-year-old
species they named Australopithecus garhi. It is, they said, ``in
the right place, at the right time'' to be a descendant of the
famed ``Lucy'' species and the long-sought immediate ancestor of
the genus Homo.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN NOBLE WILFORD
</P>
<P>
   Signs of Bygone Days
</P>
<P>
   The age of the American tobacco billboard is over as part of
last year's settlement between tobacco producers and 46 states to
resolve all state claims for health costs related to smoking.
</P>
<P>
   These signs gave smoking 50-foot-high credibility and romance,
the theory goes, tempting more people to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pollay, a marketing professor at the University of
British Columbia, says Big Tobacco will simply shift promotion
dollars elsewhere: ``It's like squeezing a balloon. You can shut
down one media, but the problem just moves somewhere else.''
Outsize tobacco signs, around for over a century, were largely
eclipsed by television spots until the early '70s, when smoking ads
were taken off the air.
</P>
<P>
   Something, though, is lost. Tobacco billboards _ whether the
Camel smoke rings in Times Square, the Marlboro Man looming over
Sunset Strip or the old Mail Pouch signs on the sides of barns _
have been a vital piece of this country's landscape, and some
people lament the passing of a genuine art form.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a time when they will be hanging in craft
museums on the wall next to patchwork quilts,'' the architect
Robert Venturi said of the billboards. Some pre-1970 Mail Pouch
signs, in fact, are now federally protected landmarks. Joe Camel,
at last report, is not.
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   May the Force ... Oh, Forget it
</P>
<P>
   You may have heard that the new ``Star Wars'' movie is supposed
to be the greatest thing since sliced bread. How could you not have
heard _ given the torrential promotion surrounding ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phanton Menace,'' coming next month to a multiplex
near you with a milelong line and maybe a couple of kids getting on
your nerves?
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's something curious about all that hype: It's showing
signs of being a little bored with itself.
</P>
<P>
   Last month CBS' ``60 Minutes'' dwelled not on the film itself,
but on the inability of the director George Lucas, a divorced
adoptive father, to find love.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has very high standards,'' the director Francis Ford
Coppola, a Lucas friend, tells Leslie Stahl. ``I mean, he wants
Queen Noor, or Grace Kelly, or someone. She can't be too tall, and
she has to be wonderful with kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vanity Fair finds Natalie Portman less than
completely fulfilled after portraying Queen Amidala in the film:
The Long Island, N.Y., teen-ager has decided that acting is
something she can take or leave. ``It's so limiting to say, `This
is it for the rest of my life,''' she says. ``There are so many
things that interest me _ I love math, science, literature,
languages.''
</P>
<P>
   Liam Neeson, who plays a Jedi master, is similarly blase about
his ``Star Wars'' encounter in an interview with Movieline: ``I'm
46 years of age. I'm married with two kids. I love to fly-fish.
That will never change. At the end of the day, you know something?
It's just a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ewan McGregor, who plays the young Obi-Wan Kenobi, told the
BBC he found making the movie ``the epitome of tedium.'' In the
magazine GQ, he as much as says that ``Star Wars'' fans should get
a life: ``Suddenly, all these people are coming to me with posters
to sign. `May the Force be with you.' People have actually said
that to me. `May the Force be with you, Ewan.' I think that's quite
batty.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TOM KUNTZ
</P>
</TEXT>
