Karen Koning AbuZayd, the refugee commissioner's Washington
representative. ``The term refugee implies a durable solution _
going home, being locally integrated, or being resettled.''
</P>
<P>
   Her agency's insistence on repatriation has sometimes been
criticized when people are encouraged to return to politically and
economically fragile countries. But Ms. AbuZayd says that it is
what most refugees want. In this respect, she said, her agency can
be proud. The numbers of people it cares for had dropped in recent
years from 27 million to 22.5 million, half of them refugees. The
agency has been closing down offices in Central America and Asia.
About 1.7 million Mozambican refugees have gone home.
</P>
<P>
   Some countries, in addition to contributing to U.N. relief
efforts, have been extraordinarily generous in taking people in.
Iran, she notes, is the world's biggest refugee host. In the
Balkans, the biggest host has been Yugoslavia, which has had to
accommodate Serbs driven out of Croatia and parts of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But taking in refugees is not what NATO has been talking about.
Getting them home is. And the Bosnian experience may be
instructive.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton accords that ended the Bosnian war in 1995 specified
that refugees could return home, but achieving safety for them in
their old neighborhoods was another matter. By mid 1997, Helton
says, about 300,000 refugees and displaced people had returned
home, but very few of these went to areas where they would be in an
ethnic minority. Meanwhile, 900,000 remained internally displaced
and another 900,000 live abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Malone thinks that if Kosovo is cleared of Yugoslav pressure,
the refugees will return. ``So it's important for NATO to decide
soon what kind of Kosovo it wants and can achieve,'' he said. ``An
independent state? An international protectorate? A combination of
the two?''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, diplomats and relief workers have begun to wonder
what precedents are being set in Kosovo. Some think the crisis is
only receiving great attention because these refugees are
Europeans, and few lessons will be learned.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Rubenstein, executive director of Physicians for Human
Rights, a private group, has another fear: ``If intervention to
save peoples' lives fails this time and people are not protected or
permitted to return, the impetus to try again next time may simply
not be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 0943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
