<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX     04-26 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The NRA's admission of guilt
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you missed it, please note that the National Rifle
Association has confessed: The prevalence and firepower of guns do
have something to do with gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   How else to take the NRA's decision to all but scrap the big
convention it had planned, and had been whooping it up for, in
Denver at the end of this week? The NRA says it is scaling back to
bylaw essentials out of respect for the Columbine High School
community.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK. But inasmuch as the NRA has always insisted guns have
nothing to do with gun crime _ indeed, has argued the more guns the
better _ wouldn't greater respect be paid by going on with its
convention as planned _ firearms exhibits, rousing pro-gun speeches
and all? The whole shootin' match, as it were.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA was stung recently when Missouri voters rejected a
proposal to let just about anyone carry a concealed gun to malls,
sports events; wherever. The lobby had looked to Denver to ease the
string.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA has been pushing in Colorado for legislation that would
cancel Denver's mild gun controls, bar other local governments from
enacting gun laws, forbid lawsuits against firearms manufacturers
and let Coloradans carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The previous, Democratic governor, Roy Romer, had blocked
passage, but with a willing new governor, Republican Bill Owens,
the lawmakers were moving briskly along and the NRA had figured its
Denver session would nail the deal, a nice little convention
finale.
</P>
<P>
   Why back off now? The NRA has two answers to gun violence. One
is more and longer prison terms. But we already have more of our
population in prison than almost every other nation, and typically
for longer sentences, and, anyway, the threat of prison is no
deterrent to the mentally disturbed _ least of all when, as at
Columbine, and awkwardly for the NRA, the shooters willingly give
themselves the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   So the NRA has been pushing its more-guns answer, too _ shooters
shooting shooters.
</P>
<P>
   Gun ownership had appeared to peak in the early '80s, but the
manufacturers came up with more glamorous-seeming, military-style
weapons, greater firepower and faster-firing guns with added
loading capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, if not exactly by coincidence, the NRA persuaded
most state legislatures to drop their traditional laws against
concealed weapons, and the industry is booming anew, huckstering
weapons that can be fired faster, with less frequent reloading and
enhanced killing power. Their easy availability gives new muscle to
the confusions, volatility and imprudence that are the natural
lapses of adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   If one answer to gun violence is for everyone to arm themselves,
then the NRA, far from shying from its own convention, should be
going ahead with it with energy and enthusiasm, comforting the
people of Colorado, and especially the wounded and grieving of
Columbine High, with the lobby's vision of the peace that would
come to a population permanently at armed standoff.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
