<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-CO     04-26 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Oh, to be late just once!
 &HT;    (For release Wednesday, April 28, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a while since I vowed that I was not going to be early
all the time. Everyone else seemingly is late but I have this awful
affliction that causes me to arrive early.
</P>
<P>
   I swore to learn to be on time. If something starts at 7 p.m., I
want to be there at 7 p.m., maybe even as late as 7:02, but not at
6:40. It was my ambition to require others to get up to allow me
into a theater aisle, instead of my having to do so, time after
time, year after year.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to be just on time or a few minutes late to weddings,
bar mitzvahs and funerals, instead of arriving preceding the
honorees _ present and passed.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this period of dedication to not being early, I am
sorry to report that I have become even earlier than before. Don't
ask me why, it's just my nature.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other night, I took my grandson to the ball game where
they were giving out souvenir pins to the first 25,000 in
attendance. Not wanting to miss out on getting a pin for my
grandson, we left the house two hours before game time. And got our
pin. Of course, there's weren't 25,000 in the ball park all night,
so I could have come in the fifth inning and still received the
pin.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the way it is for me. Much of the time, I am caused
to be early by worry over traffic. I overestimate how long it will
take me to get somewhere, thinking that some awful accident will
block the route I take and cause me to be late.
</P>
<P>
   So I leave extra early, and of course there is no traffic. I
always arrive for a weekly downtown Tuesday noon luncheon with old
buddies at 11:30 and sit there sipping iced tea until everyone else
arrives _ at 12:15.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, I do not learn from my experiences.
</P>
<P>
   I had a great experience last December in discovering how late
you can be and still be on time. I misread my airplane ticket to
London as being for a flight departing at 7 p.m. The ticket read
1700 hours but it's been so long since I was in the military that I
forgot 1700 meant 5 p.m. Arriving at the airport at 4:30 _ which I
thought was my kind of arrival time for a 7 p.m. international
flight _ I was stunned to find out the flight was boarding.
</P>
<P>
   And even more stunned to find out you can get to an
international flight 30 minutes before takeoff _ rather than 2 1/2
hours before _ and still comfortably board.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, I'm still early to everything. Usually when I arrive
too early, I drive around a bit so as not to embarrass myself. This
is particularly true when I am arriving at someone's home. I
learned that lesson when I showed up an hour early to dinner at
someone's house and stunned the hostess, whose hair still was in
rollers.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried to be on time, tried harder to be late. But to no
avail. Meanwhile, my wife, who steadfastly resists premature
arrivals, has gotten used to my problem. She's been a fairly good
sport about it, even when we arrive at hockey games seemingly
before the ice is frozen.
</P>
<P>
   My project of not being early is a failure. I will forever be
early. It is an affliction with which I will have to live the rest
of my days. And when my days are over, I would like everyone to get
to my funeral just a few minutes later than early.
</P>
<P>
   Then they could honestly say: ``He would have wanted it that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
