<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMAN-EDITOR27-COX     04-26 1623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMAN-EDITOR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR TOP WOMAN EDITOR, LEAP OF FAITH PAID OFF
 &HT;    Eds: Repeating for all needing a story first moved March 29. Pls
note that Jurgensen assumes post as editor on Saturday, May 1.
 &HT;    1180&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Va. _ Seventeen years have passed since Karen
Jurgensen, the single mom of a 5-year-old daughter, drove a
thousand miles up I-95 to start a job on a newspaper that existed
only in the minds of a few journalistic visionaries.
</P>
<P>
   Separated from her husband, she had quit a secure editorial
position on the Miami News and sold her house to ``work for
something that might or might not exist in the future. It was a
leap of faith,'' she recalled. ``I thought then and still think
that USA Today is the most exciting thing going on in journalism in
the country, and I wanted to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not a bad move.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami News folded six years after she left. She remarried,
to a lawyer named Bill Leary who works for the U.S. Interior
Department. And on May 1, Karen Jurgensen will replace the retiring
David Mazzarella as editor of USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 50, she will become the first female editor of the
country's largest general-interest newspaper, moving up from her
current post as editor of the editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   Will the 2.3 million readers of USA Today be able to tell that a
woman has taken charge?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said the soft-spoken Jurgensen. ``I'm not out
to make this a woman's newspaper. I hope that everybody will pick
up the paper and think it's relevant to their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   As for shattering a glass ceiling for her gender, ``to me it's a
natural progression of what's happened to women in the workplace,''
she explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over my professional career, which started in the early '70s
women have sort of infiltrated _ if I can use that word _
newsrooms. And I think it's only natural that women are getting to
the position where they have higher-ranking jobs. We have earned
the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurgensen started as topics editor in the Life section of USA
Today, and has since advanced to special projects editor, editor in
charge of the Life section, cover stories editor, senior editor for
special projects including polling, and since 1991, editor of the
editorial page.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, of course, there were sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In very beginning I had my daughter in a day-care center that
closed at 6 o'clock and was, at minimum, a 45-minute drive away at
rush hour,'' she said. ``Well, it very soon became obvious that
there was no way this was going to be a workable plan, so I hired
someone to come and be at the house with my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the model that we followed all through her growing up
years. There was somebody at home to take care of her until I got
home. The upside of that is that she has always been proud of what
I do, so she has forgiven me that. We have had a lot of really good
times together. I believe in quality time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, Kirsten Thompson, is now a senior at Bryn Mawr
College in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   As editorial page editor, she also sacrificed her privacy to
provide a personal perspective to a sensitive women's issue.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, when journalists were debating whether the media
perpetuates the stigma of rape by not naming victims of the violent
crime, Jurgensen wrote a chilling column describing how she had
been raped 15 years before in North Carolina after leaving work one
evening at the Charlotte News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've helped to hide ourselves away _ and to hide the
prevalence and brutality of rape,'' she wrote. ``And I thought: If
we all spoke up, you would know victims all around you.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, she heard ``from a lot of other people who had been
raped. They want to have someone to talk to and to have a sense
that they are not alone,'' said Jurgensen. ``One woman called and
said she was raped before she was married and had never had the
courage to tell her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was so supportive. It was not like I had to carry
this around by myself any more. It was a wonderful, warm feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting her Danish roots, her first name is pronounced
``CAR-in.'' Growing up in Chapel Hill, N.C., she was called
``Kardi'' by her family because her younger brothers, Mike and
Kris, had trouble with the proper pronunciation. Her father, Kai
Jurgensen, now deceased, was a drama professor at the University of
North Carolina. Her mother, Peggy, died when Karen was in the ninth
grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Kardi in 1962,'' recalled her 80-year-old stepmother,
Paquita Shafer.
</P>
<P>
   Shafer, recently divorced, had left a job at the Raleigh News
and Observer in order to return to her home town, where her family
could help care for her three small children.
</P>
<P>
   She had begun working as a reporter for the local newspaper and
was covering a dance at a teen center called the Catskeller. The
rock 'n' roll music was provided by a local band of high schoolers
led by James Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all dancing the watusi. I thought they were all
crazy,'' she said. Spotting a temporarily motionless Jurgensen, ``I
thought she was the only one with any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   So she asked the sensible one to come to the paper the next day
to identify students in photographs of the dance. She found out
that Jurgensen was a reporter for the school newspaper and host of
a local radio program and the daughter of a popular professor who
spoke eight languages fluently.
</P>
<P>
   That professor would soon become Shafer's suitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left three dozen roses on my desk and a note that said
'Let's have lunch','' she said. ``I didn't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sensible stepdaughter would go on to major in English and
graduate with honors from UNC. They get together whenever Jurgensen
returns ``to the Southern part of heaven _ which is what we call
Chapel Hill,'' said Shafer.
</P>
<P>
   As chairperson of the board of visitors for the university's
School of Journalism and Mass Communications, Jurgensen returns at
least twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is nothing short of splendid,'' said Richard Cole, dean of
the journalism school. ``She is a most astute journalist. I've
known many over the years, and she is right up there with the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a ``gutsy move'' for Jurgensen to go to USA Today, said
Paul Kaplan, who worked with her at the Miami News and is now
Sunday editor for the Atlanta Journal and Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan was metro editor at the News. Jurgensen was features
editor but became Kaplan's assistant _ technically a demotion _ to
gain ``hard news experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very savvy, but in a quiet way. She's definitely not a
screamer,'' he said. ``She treats people well, and they respond to
her management style. She is very direct in her dealings with
people. Very professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Weiss, the current USA Today managing editor for the Life
section, worked with Jurgensen in the ``early, very chaotic days''
of the section. ``She would draw people out, listen, then act,''
said Weiss. ``Her management style is a very collaborative one.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no pigeon-holing of her interests for the section,
Weiss said. ``She liked stories about ordinary people doing
formidable things, entertainment stories with real news, stories
that solve problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is an intelligent, aware human being,'' Weiss said of her
boss-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   USA Today has changed since it was dubbed McPaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning it was very much a newspaper that existed in
the heads of a few people, and they had to convey that to the rest
of us. It was very much a vision of those early leaders. Al
Neuharth. John Curley. John Quinn,'' said Jurgensen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of the paper has changed some. We tried in the
beginning to be very different. The assumption was that people had
already gotten the day's news by the time they got to us,'' she
said. ``We don't think that now. We consider that our readers are
news junkies. they have many sources of information. But we think
we have to provide a complete, thorough news report every day, with
our own kind of spark of creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the newspaper to have a thorough view of what happened
in the past 24 hours and what will happen in the next 24 hours,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   As editorial page editor, she has pressed issues involving
women's rights, such as Title IX gender equity in college sports,
health care and air travel _ ``very important to our readers.''
</P>
<P>
   Will she bring a woman's perspective to the top post?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to a degree,'' Jurgensen said. ``We have a whole mix
of people here who are male or female and minorities, and I hope we
all bring those points of view to the table when we think about
what to put in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers are already challenged in an era where information is
instantly available from the Internet, cable TV and portable
digital phones, and the competition will increase in the future,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Technological change ``is going to get much faster,'' said
Jurgensen. ``The alternatives to newspaper reading will explode.
The challenge is to create a newspaper that appeals to readers in
that environment, that serves them in that environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to help people put into context all this
proliferation of information that is coming at them. There are
many, many voices out there. I hope part of our role will be to
help people sort through that, to know what is believable or not
believable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope part of my legacy will be helping discover what is the
journalism of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
