A3208 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN27-C     04-26 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Current crop of babies will have plenty of company
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Baby Six Billion is already out there in some woman's
womb just waiting to be born, kicking, crying and looking for a
little space to grow up in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Less than six months from now, the Earth's population will hit 6
billion, according to U.N. demographers. The big day they project
is Oct. 12. But what happens after that? How much more crowded will
the world become during Baby Six Billion's lifetime?
</P>
<P>
   So much population growth has occurred in the past half-century
that some experts fear that children born in the last year of this
millennium will witness another doubling of the world's population,
leaving them to fight for elbow room amid 12 billion people. But
others say population growth is leveling off dramatically. Indeed,
in many industrial countries, the aging population is failing to
replace itself.
</P>
<P>
   So which will be the bigger problem in the next century: Too
many old people who can't work, or too many young people grasping
for food, water and jobs?
</P>
<P>
   The outlook is complicated because every statistic appears true.
Yes, birth rates are rising rapidly in some countries. And yes,
they are falling in many others. Yes, new scourges such as AIDS,
and old curses such as famine, are wiping out tens of millions of
people. And yes, new medical breakthroughs are making it possible
for people to live productively until age 100. Given all of the
contradictions, are any predictions safe?
</P>
<P>
   We do know that the world's population has been growing and, at
least for a while, will continue to grow rapidly. People who were
born before 1950 are members of the first generation to see a
doubling of the world's population. In some countries, the growth
has been spectacular. For instance, this year, India's population
will hit the 1 billion mark. That means two countries, India and
China, will have a combined population of more than 2.2 billion _
about as many people as the entire planet held in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Earth is becoming home to 80 million more people each
year. That's roughly the equivalent of piling another Germany on
top of the planet every Jan. 1. At this rate, land is filling up
fast, especially in urban areas. In 1800, London was the world's
largest city with 1 million people. Today, 326 metro areas have at
least 1 million people, and 16 cities, including Tokyo, Mexico City
and New York, have more than 10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Given such growth rates, it would seem safe to predict that the
population will double again in a matter of decades. But
demographers say the factors affecting population are changing.
They note the fertility rate _ that is, the average number of
children born to a woman _ has fallen steadily in most countries
since the 1960s for economic reasons. As people move from farms to
cities, large families become more of an expense than a financial
help.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the big news in population projections is the increase in
early deaths from disease, war and starvation. In some African
countries, for example, as much as one-quarter of the adult
population is infected with the virus that leads to AIDS. Combine
that with the slaughters in Rwanda and starvation in the Sudan, and
the population picture in Africa becomes less than clear.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in wealthier European countries, the number of babies
being born has gotten so low that cities soon may start to
depopulate. Demographers say that within a generation in
industrialized countries, one person in four will be over age 65,
up from 1 in 10 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   So what will the new millennium bring: a stressed-out planet
whose resources are being overwhelmed by a burgeoning number of
babies, or an aging world with a declining population? Baby Six
Billion, now entering the second trimester, will have to grow up to
learn the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
