<HEADER>
A3212 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN27-COX     04-26 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: They are our children
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Once again, a shooting spree in a school. We
watch, stunned, as children in Littleton, Colo., flee from the
horror. A camera zooms in on a young man, obviously injured, draped
across an open window.
</P>
<P>
   It does not help to say to ourselves, ``This cannot happen.'' Or
``This cannot happen again.'' It is all too obvious it can, and
does. It numbs us to know we are largely helpless against these
random acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, my stomach wrenches at what it must feel like to
hear the news of a school shooting and then to try desperately to
find out if your child is safe . . . or dead.
</P>
<P>
   One mother raised an even more terrifying thought: ``What if
it's my child who's doing the shooting?''
</P>
<P>
   We shake our heads and say it's impossible. Our children would
never do such a thing. They know better. We taught them to know
right from wrong. But don't we all think that?
</P>
<P>
   Whose children, then, are these who smuggle artillery into
schools and begin shooting everyone in sight? We cannot hide from
this fact: They are our children. They belong to all of us, and
somehow, as a society, we have failed them.
</P>
<P>
   Being human, we immediately seek a scapegoat. It's the media;
it's Hollywood. If they didn't produce such violent shows, if news
coverage didn't fixate on each of these horrible tragedies, if they
didn't glorify violence in movies.
</P>
<P>
   Then we blame the video games in which the only objective is to
kill the opponent, fake blood spurting out after heads have been
ripped off. It's those games. They teach our children to be
violent. They desensitize our children to the consequences of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Or it's the fault of those kids our child hangs out with. Their
parents are never home, or are lazy, or just don't care and so they
leave their children to run wild in the streets doing God knows
what. It's their fault.
</P>
<P>
   We're good at finding people to blame. We're even better at not
blaming ourselves. But I ask again: Whose kids are these? If it
takes a village to raise a child, where is the village when the
child goes dangerously astray?
</P>
<P>
   We come home to our children after yet another tragedy unfolds
and we hold them close. We wrap our arms around them, wanting never
to let them go, believing that if we can just do that, we can keep
them safe. We stroke their hair and touch their cheeks and think of
the young man hanging from a school window in Colorado. We take
deep, gulping breaths and, once again, try to find the words to
help our children understand what they have already seen on
television _ and can never be understood.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 14 years old, I watched on TV as Robert F. Kennedy
was shot down in a California hotel. I saw him lying there, a pool
of blood forming beneath his head, a stunned look upon his face. It
affected me deeply. I had been too young to empathize over his
brother's death five years before, or the subsequent gunning down
of Lee Harvey Oswald. But at 14, you empathize with everything. You
feel the whole world's pain. At 14, I was old enough to despair. I
walked around in shock for days. Finally my mother said to me,
``Vicki, why are you still so upset? It's not like you knew him.''
</P>
<P>
   But, you see, I did know him. I knew him through television.
Good or bad, that's what TV does. It makes events real and close
and ours _ an irrevocable part of our life experience.
</P>
<P>
   And so these deaths in Colorado are real to us. Every one of
them. We do know them. They are our sons and daughters, our
brothers and sisters. Every one of them is an inestimable loss. And
the loss is ours.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
