<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Easy labels made to order after killings
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The murderers were militia-types because
of their Army boots and combat fatigues and Confederate battle-flag
patches. It's obvious.
</P>
<P>
   No, they were Goth kids. They listened to Marilyn Manson,
dressed in black coats and once came to school with their faces
painted white.
</P>
<P>
   No, they were white supremacist, Nazi-skinheads types. So
fixated on Nazis they scheduled Hitler's birthday as their killing
day.
</P>
<P>
   No, just the opposite. They were anarchists. Their program was
simple destruction, then exit in a puff of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   No, they were apolitical and bought into doom culture _
end-of-the-world predictions, Y2K social breakdown, doomster rock
... .
</P>
<P>
   No, they were alienated, off-in-their-own-little-world
tech-heads. One of them had a Web site, you know. And then all
those bombs. Pretty elaborate. The white supremacist, Goth and
punk-rock stuff were frosting on the cake.
</P>
<P>
   No, they were typical of neo-punk,
Euro-death-thrash-rock-listening, ultraviolent, anarcho-Gothic,
Western white-kid Nazi wannabees.
</P>
<P>
   No, they were the Goth-core, white-power, quasi-skinhead,
industrial-punk-heads who listened to bad music from sources that
ranged from industrial oi bands to neo-metal-thrash hate-rock.
Poisonous stuff.
</P>
<P>
   No, they were gamers gone bad, lost in point-and-click gore
fantasies. They played ``Doom'' all the time. They decided to live
out the game.
</P>
<P>
   No, they were simple droogs.
</P>
<P>
   No, they were your garden-variety, angry, white gun-nuts. Those
big, square states in the West are crawling with them. They move
there from normal places. Everyone knows this.
</P>
<P>
   No, they are the harbingers of the coming apocalypse. Just what
you'd expect of a generation growing up in schools without prayer,
connected to an unfiltered Internet and raised by parents who grew
up in the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   The dead had not been removed from Columbine High School before
easy explanations began rolling in. It used to be enough for
reporters to pronounce: ``the gunman was described as a loner.''
These days, news consumers demand more.
</P>
<P>
   We want to be reassured the murderers were not like our kids.
These were Nazis, black-fingernailed Goth-kids, white punks on
dope, anarchists, doomheads, gun-nuts and alienated losers. Not
like the kids we know.
</P>
<P>
   To do this, we pick a few snippets of what other kids said about
the murderers' short lives, their likes, hates and school
reputations, then find a serviceable label.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, kids are still forming their identity from
fairly crude raw material. This sometimes makes them look alike to
the unpracticed adult eye.
</P>
<P>
   We see bad kids, punks, hippies, preps, jocks, overachievers and
the quiet kid in the back of the room. The kids, however, break
these labels into bewildering subcategories. Where oldsters see A
Quiet Kid in the Back of the Room, kids see A Quiet, Straight-Edge,
Surf-Punk in the Back of the Room.
</P>
<P>
   These nuances are lost on adults. The further we are from high
school, the broader we group the students. When we get far enough
removed from them, we group them so broadly they almost disappear.
They all become Those Kids. And when they all become Those Kids,
people get spooked easily.
</P>
<P>
   Those Kids are killing each other now. So to know that we're
safe, we find ways to make evildoers seem radically different. We'd
like to think they are mutants.
</P>
<P>
   If we blame clothing, music, the Internet or games, if we tell
ourselves mutants did this, we can rest easier. The bad kids will
be easy to spot. And what do you know? They're the same kids who
have been annoying us all along.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect in the days ahead, the troubling truth will emerge
that these were not mutants. They did not turn bad from the
Internet, video games or Marilyn Manson. Evil is not a virus
contracted by casual contact.
</P>
<P>
   When kids try very hard to look strange, they often do it
because they are frightened of how ordinary they really are.
</P>
<P>
   This suspicion scares the rest of us, too. Nazi mutants,
computer-distributed mayhem and bad music are far more reassuring.
It's easier to inveigh against these things than to talk to kids
once in awhile.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
