<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chance at bathroom pay back flushed away
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ How would you like it if someone removed your
bathroom door and then sent 20 kids in to talk to you while you
were trying to concentrate? Friendly, but not conducive to
accomplishing the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby breezes into the boys' restroom and sees his old friend
sitting in the second stall. ``Hi, Buddy, whassappening?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing much right now,'' Buddy answers candidly, wishing his
pal would bug out. Kids love to socialize, but not when their pants
are around their ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Exchanges like this could be taking place in schools all over
the country where toilet stalls in the boys' bathrooms have had
their doors offed in a '70s solution to restroom vandalism. It
doesn't work, of course, because kids aren't going to squeal on
each other and no teacher wants to spend his conference period
hanging out in the boys' bathroom to be sure little Johnny isn't
carving things he can't spell into school property.
</P>
<P>
   Girls' restrooms still have doors on the stalls, although I know
from experience, the young ladies are just as capable of
``glyphing'' a few ``hieros'' on the walls as their male
counterparts. And with fewer spelling errors.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' ``convenience'' (as our first-grade teacher so
delicately put it) in the elementary school where I spent six years
and a kindergarten, was straight out of a Bram Stoker novel.
Submerged in the bowels of a dank basement, it was every tyke's
nightmare come true. Trolls lurked around every dim corner, not to
mention the custodian who was known to chop up little kid's who had
to pee, and throw them into the boilers to make heat.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the restroom itself. A work of art _
interiors by A.Hun Design Group. Great lengths of wooden slabs with
holes cut in them every so many feet were suspended over what could
only be described as a trough with water moving sluggishly through
it. I guess it was OK for curious kids who liked to check things
out, but tough on anyone with a low gag factor.
</P>
<P>
   For seven years I put off going until my kidneys screamed for
relief. Once, I even had an accident all over the scrubbed wooden
floor in Mrs. Lenhardt's room. We were reading the play ``Heidi''
aloud. I was Aunt Deirdre (otherwise billed as the kid in the
puddle).
</P>
<P>
   In junior high school there were real toilets that flushed and
doors on the stalls. No locks, but we managed. Friends stood guard
for one another's privacy. That's how I met ``Bad Nancy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of school, I made the mistake of asking her to
watch my door. She agreed. But I had no sooner lifted what had to
be raised, and lowered what had to be dropped, than Bad Nancy
kicked the door in and smashed me in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Once I regained my senses, I began plotting revenge. Bad Nancy
would pay.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, opportunity jumped up and bit me. The art
teacher sent me to the restroom to wash out some paint pots, and
just as I pushed my way through the door, Bad Nancy disappeared
into the No. 1 stall. PAY BACK TIME!
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, I rinsed out the red paint jar and filled it with cold
water.
</P>
<P>
   Then I tiptoed into stall No. 2, stood on the seat, and dumped
the water all over Bad Nancy. If the story had ended there, I'm
sure I would have forgotten all about it by this time, but it
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   About the time I was dumping murky water all over Bad Nancy's
person, the meanest teacher in the whole school caught me midpour.
I made the long march to the principal's office and Bad Nancy had
the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news for Bad Nancy is that I have the memory of a
long-tailed elephant. It's been over 50 years now, but every time I
walk into a restroom, I'm reminded of her and that day in the
principal's office. By now she's
</P>
<P>
   probably figured out that I put a curse on her. I have willed
her days and nights to be a succession of toilet stalls with no
doors.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
