</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEAP-PCS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New breed of competitors undercutting big companies
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As Compaq Computer Corp. directors search for
ways to get the company back on track, they might get some
inspiration from its division that markets cheap personal
computers.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Houston-based computer maker badly missed earnings
projections it made earlier this year. True, its stock price is
about half of what it was earlier this year. And true, last
Sunday's ouster of Chief Executive Eckhard Pfeiffer creates
uncertainty among Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   But buried under this week's bad news about the world's No. 1
computer maker was the fact that its sales of PCs to consumers grew
at two times the industry rate in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, because of sub-$1,000 PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pfeiffer's direction, Compaq introduced some of the first
sub-$1,000 PCs about three years ago. Today, low-cost computers
account for nearly one-fourth of all consumer desktop retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Compaq accounted for nearly half those sales,
according to research group PC Data. Its closest competitor,
Packard Bell NEC Inc., had a mere 13 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
   But if post-Pfeiffer Compaq is to stay on top, analysts and
others say, the company will have to fend off a new breed of
competitor along with its more familiar rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC business is going through a very drastic change,'' said
Danny Lam, an industry analyst with the Fisher-Holstein Inc.
research group. ``We see it basically fragmenting into a low-end
consumer market and a corporate market.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting competitors is eMachines Inc., which
grew out of a joint venture between two South Korean companies. In
the past year, the company has fought its way up to become one of
the top five makers of sub-$1,000 computers. Emachines, which sells
through retail stores, recently introduced a $399 model.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Compaq, the other three are familiar names: IBM
Corp., Hewlett-Packard Co., and Packard Bell NEC Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from that list is Dell Computer Corp., which last month
introduced a $999 PC and lowered the price to $950 this week. It,
however, has avoided the low-end because it says profits, when
factoring in costs such as follow-up technical support for new
users, aren't sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the growing popularity of cheaper PCs, research group
International Data Corp. forecasts 14.3 percent growth in worldwide
PC shipments this year, to 103 million units, but only a 4.8
percent increase in revenues, to $178 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, IDC forecasts that sub-$1,000 computers will account
for 41.4 percent, or 5 million, of consumer desktop PCs purchased
this year at retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, has at least three models that sell for less than
$1,000. Chairman Ben Rosen said last week that in January and
February the company's Presario 2286 desktop PC was the top-selling
model among computers costing less than $600.
</P>
<P>
   Schelley Olhava of IDC said the machines get credit for
introducing hundreds of thousands of American households, which
couldn't afford a PC until now, to the Internet. The machines also
are popular as the No. 2 computer for families and for college
students.
</P>
<P>
   IDC estimates that half of all U.S. households have PCs, up from
46 percent last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has been helped by a steady decline in prices of
components such as memory chips, and new, low-cost processors from
Advanced Micro Devices Inc, Intel Corp. and Cyrix Corp. While they
won't power graphics-intensive games, most low-end PCs will run
Microsoft Corp.'s Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a gamer and you really care about the latest and
greatest, you're not going to buy a $399 PC from eMachines,''
Olhava said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, eMachines' success is coming primarily at the expense of
smaller companies, said Stephen Baker of PC Data. And while the top
five companies have remained the same from month to month, their
shares vary widely depending on new models they or their
competitors introduce, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very volatile category,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
