r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A27-COX     04-26 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: After encountering one at each of numerous
family gatherings, I questioned why the common buttermilk pie is
referred to as ``chess'' pie. A family matriarch was assigned the
task of determining the origin, and she hasn't delivered. If you
could help, I'm in for serious family bragging rights. _Terry K.
</P>
<P>
   A: The ``Food Lover's Companion'' from Barron's defines chess
pie as a Southern favorite ``with a simple filling of eggs, butter
and a small amount of flour.'' Some credit the name to the fact
that pies were kept in chests (aka pie safes) to keep the vermin
(flies to hungry children) away. Others _ and this I love _ credit
an unnamed Southern baker who, when asked what kind of pie she was
cooking, answered in her best drawl, ``It's jes' pie, honey.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can we find the ``Run Hillary Run'' bumper stickers?
_S.D.
</P>
<P>
   A: Neither the Democratic National Committee nor the New York
Democratic Committee has these stickers, but I did find Hillary
pins: ``Run Hillary Run'' and ``Hillary Clinton For Senate.'' Call
Political Americana at (800) 333-4555 to order.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I once read the names of the women who are queens in a deck
of cards, but months later different names were given. So I was
wondering, what are the correct names of the four queens? Also, can
you identify the kings and the jacks? _Leon Handrick
</P>
<P>
   A: Naming the deck royalty is exclusively a French thing, says
Rhonda Hawes of the 52 Plus Joker (international playing card
collectors). The French began naming cards in the 15th century.
Here are the names (in the following order of suits: hearts,
spades, diamonds, clubs): The kings (rois) are Charles
(Charlemagne), David (as in Goliath), Cesar (Julius) and Alexandre
(the Great). The queens (dames) are Judith (of Bavaria), Pallas
(Greek goddess of war and wisdom), Rachel (Jacob's wife) and Argine
(anagram for Regina, Latin for queen). The jacks (valets) are La
Hire (French for warrior), Hogier (legendary hero), Hector (any one
of many) and Lancelot (as in Sir).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a canvas seat for butterfly chairs. I tried
to reach the Algoma Net Co. but the number no longer works. Can you
put your talents to this? _E.R. Totten
</P>
<P>
   A: Call the king of butterfly chair covers, Algoma, at (800)
800-7083.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter asked me why we call grand dances ``ballroom
parties'' and why places are called ``ballrooms.'' So I told her I
really did not know, but that I would ask you. Can you find out the
origin of this phrase? She thinks people put giant balls in rooms,
hence ``ballroom.'' _L.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ball is derived from the French word ``bal'' _ dance. Not
much of a stretch to ballroom, where dancing is grand.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard somewhere about a way to keep white canvas tennis
shoes cleaner _ think it was hairspray or maybe spray starch. Do
you know for sure what it is before I do it? _Beth Harvey
</P>
<P>
   A: While some folks recommend a fabric protector such as Tana
All Protector on white canvas, Keds, the canvas king, does not. And
not just because they want you to buy more Keds. The fabric cannot
be sealed completely and you risk discoloring the fabric with
hairspray, etc. The good news is Keds are washable _ toss them in
the machine and air or tumble dry. For information on this and
other Keds products call (800) 428-6575. By the way, you could be
slipping on Peds or Veds instead of Keds. Huh? Peds was the name
first selected by U.S. Rubber when consolidating brands of rubber
footwear in 1916. But Peds (Latin for foot) was already taken and,
thank goodness, Veds did not make it. Q: Why do the overpasses on
the big mixmasters have to be so enormously high? Are they a gift
from the concrete growers of America? _Deana Newcomb
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Federal highway regulations require a vertical separation
of 16 feet 6 inches between the surface of one roadway and the
bottom of the upper roadway,'' says Texas Department of
Transportation guru John Hurt. So a four-level interchange may be
as high as 70 feet (pretty doggone high). Direct connection ramps
have replaced the old cloverleaf designs (all the rage in the 1950s
and '60s). In urban areas, it's easier and more cost-effective to
build vertical rather than horizontal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I noticed punch cup rings on my antique, marble-top table.
Nothing I've tried can remove them. Help! The punch had fresh lemon
and pineapple juice. _Dolores D.
</P>
<P>
   A: The acid in the punch probably caused the rings. Christy
Stasswender of Southwest Marble &AMP; Granite Works says a poultice may
remove them. If not, you need a professional repolishing. Here's
Stasswender's poultice prescription: Dampen the area first. Mix
powdered chalk or talc with a 12 percent hydrogen peroxide solution
(the consistency of peanut butter). After applying it thickly (
1/4- to 1/2-inch thick), cover with plastic and allow to dry (24 to
48 hours). Remove, rinse with distilled water and buff with a
clean, dry cloth. Repeat if necessary. Q: I am trying to locate a
current address for Joe Bob Briggs (aka John Bloom). He is the host
of TNT's MonsterVision. _H.V.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the man who cites ``Hellraiser,'' ``Suspiria,'' and
``Basket Case'' as favorite horror flicks in care of Marianne
Fleschman, TNT, 1050 Techwood Drive NW, Atlanta 30318. Q: I am a
divorced parent of a 12- and 13-year-old. Their father has
``standard visitation.'' When can a child refuse to go for
visitation? My kids do want to see their dad, but they want to have
some say in their schedule. My friends say when a child is 12, he
can refuse. Is this true? _L.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: The court's orders must be followed until the children are 18
and have completed high school. ``There is a common misconception
at the age of 12 years a child may refuse to go on a court-ordered
visitation,'' says family law attorney Sara Saltmarsh. While there
may be good reasons the child does not wish to go, the custodial
parent risks a motion for contempt if the visitation agreement is
not honored. What's a parent to do? Saltmarsh advises direct
communication between the child and both parents _ especially the
noncustodial parent. Or perhaps an intermediary such as a skilled
counselor should be employed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the high, starched, white hat worn by
chefs? Does one have to be a graduate of a culinary school to wear
one? Where can I get information on a charitable organization? How
much of their intake actually goes to charity and how much to
administration? _M.R. Coale
</P>
<P>
   A: In traditional kitchens the tallest toque is worn by the head
chef _ professionally trained or not. Chef Patrick O'Connell of The
Inn at Little Washington, Va., has studied the toque and offers two
origins. Pick the one you like. At one time food preparation was
the responsibility of holy men or tribal priests. With the fall of
the Roman Empire, professional cooks sought refuge in monasteries,
where they donned the habits and high hats of monks. To reduce
confusion, chefs wore white rather than black. Or the toque could
have originated with the kings of ancient Assyria, who allowed
selected chefs to wear a crown-shaped hat as a sign of trust.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that Southwest Airlines was going to have flights to
New York soon. Do you know how soon and what airport Southwest will
use? Will there be shuttle service into the city? _C.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Since March 14 the company plane has been flying to Long
Island. No shuttle service as yet to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The low fare (as low as $99 one-way) brings you to Long Island's
MacArthur Airport. But then there is the problem of getting into
Manhattan. The Long Island railroad is only a few miles from the
airport. So a short cab ride and $10 or less for a train ticket
will spirit you to the Big Apple's Penn Station. The cab ride to
Manhattan _ $105 _ can cost more than the airfare. Yikes!
</P>
<P>
   Q: My 3-year-old wrote on my comforter with a dry erase marker.
How can I save the comforter? _Celeste Hill
</P>
<P>
   A: Binney &AMP; Smith, maker of Wipeoffs Markers, reports the stain
is water based and should respond to regular laundering _ no
pre-treatment or chlorine bleach necessary. Using a dry cleaner?
Let him know the nature of the stain. More stain removal tips are
available at (800) CRAYOLA.
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar
</P>
<P>
   _ Wondering if that presidential autograph is real? If Aunt
Maisie's ring is opal or awful? The Greig Files, a consumer's best
friend, is gathering experts to help you assess the value of your
treasured antique dolls, books and paper, coins, and estate
jewelry. Discover if your bibelot is a jewel or junk on May 2. (And
find out what a bibelot is.)
</P>
<P>
   But you need an appointment for this free verbal appraisal. To
put your name in the appraisal pool, contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box
670, Austin 78767, 445-3697, jgreig(at)statesman.com or (fax)
445-3968. Include your name, daytime phone number and a brief
description of the item. Readers selected to visit with the
appraisers will be contacted with an appointment time.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
