<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web news coverage strong adjunct to TV
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Clicking back and forth among various Web sites
covering the Columbine High School shooting wasn't anybody's idea
of fun last week, but users desperate for information poured onto
the Web nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   With Web access available in most offices and desktop access
available in most mid- and large-size corporations, the news of the
tragedy sent many to their computers for details.
</P>
<P>
   Given the afternoon scramble for news from the Internet, by the
time the average American got home Tuesday evening and tuned into
the local or national newscast at 6 or 6:30 p.m., the Colorado news
on television seemed impossibly old, inadequate and dated.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may have even gone home, flipped on the TV, then
logged on the computer in a search for the latest, most-complete
information.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1995, when CNN Interactive launched its first Web site,
the company talked about the depth of information it could provide
using the Web that it wasn't able to showcase, even as a
24-hour-a-day news network.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzak Rabin was assassinated only months
after the CNN.com site was launched. It was a Saturday, and most of
the CNN.com staffers were in HTML training class. (That's the
coding language used to post stories and graphics on the Web.)
However, even in what was then a brand-new medium, CNN was able to
take audio feeds from the network, even some video that had been on
the air as well as some that hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   When ABCNews.com was launched in 1997, the network said its
correspondents around the world were excited by the Web presence
because it would allow them another venue to report on the places
and people they were covering. In the years since, ABCNews.com has
become one of the Web's most popular news sites and has developed a
reputation for providing background and explanations, glossaries,
maps and lists of key players in each breaking and ongoing news
story.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC.com, the online companion to the cable network jointly
owned by Microsoft and NBC, is virtually neck-and-neck with CNN as
the most popular source of news and information on the Web, with
its breaking-news ticker, daily news chat and stories that go on as
long as they need to. (Remember, on the Internet, you never have to
turn the page, just scroll down as little or as much as you want.)
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications analysts like to chatter on and on about
the hours between noon and 4 p.m., which they call ``The New Prime
Time.'' These are the hours they say more Web users are online
checking news, sports and stock information from high-speed lines
in their offices. Even users who don't necessarily have computers
at home are able to keep up with everything from their favorite
baseball teams to a shooting massacre in a Colorado high school.
</P>
<P>
   News of the tragedy became widespread by midafternoon Tuesday.
By Wednesday, ABCNews.com reported a 90 percent increase in online
traffic since Monday. Other major news sites probably can offer
equal statistics, with most of their traffic coming during the
daytime. A friend who was sick at home says she heard the news
first on television, then went straight to the Web to get the
latest updates.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, CNN and the other news sites were providing
``at a glance'' update boxes, where readers could see the latest
information and then read more in-depth pieces if they chose.
Unlike television, where viewers often tune into an ongoing story
in the middle and have to stick around a while to catch up, the Web
sites can pick up the story wherever you might have left off. They
also offer the ability to target the specific parts of a story that
interest a particular reader most.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to note that the Web is a worldwide medium.
Along with national reports of the shooting massacre, there are
also a variety of local resources for users to visit to provide
even more depth and analysis. Late Tuesday afternoon, the Web site
for Colorado TV station KUSA was jammed with users from around the
country, and perhaps around the world, who had seen the station's
feed on CNN. Other Colorado stations and the Web site for Columbine
High School were also available for Web users, as was the British
Broadcasting Company's Web site for users who might have been
interested in an international perspective.
</P>
<P>
   TV will always be a major player in how people receive their
news. Katie Couric and Charles Gibson's solemn and often
heartbreaking interviews with the students and their parents cannot
be duplicated on the Web, at this point. However, when news breaks
and people are eager to know immediately what happened, where it
happened and why it happened, the Web is an excellent reference
tool. It's like having the best newspapers in the world, a few
encyclopedias and the best on-the-spot TV reporting all loaded onto
the computer screen right in front of you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
