<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How's that work?
 &HT;    By Theresa Walsh Giarrusso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Have you ever wondered why boogers are sticky or which
came first, the chicken or the egg? Ponder no more! Instead, check
out the Web site howstuffworks.com to learn multitudes about the
world around you. Written by Marshall Brain, the site answers more
than 100 questions and offers ``The Inside Series,'' which examines
the insides of TV remote controls, electric motors and bathroom
scales. It also tells you how your body works and how time works.
The page was named Cool Site of the Year in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo updates for kids
</P>
<P>
   News for Kids updates you each week on the war in Yugoslavia.
But now a Web site, www.scholastic.com/scholasticnews/kosovo/,
gives daily updates on the fighting and the refugees. It includes
news reports, a glossary, a map of the conflict and where the
refugees are fleeing, biographies of the major players and a time
line of the struggle. It also lets you vote on whether the United
States should become involved in another country's civil conflict
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
