<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How strange! Software that's easy and smooth
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Something, clearly, has gone awry. I have loaded onto
my computer an item for review that appears to work flawlessly,
does something that I can actually use and is so simple to use that
its large manual has gone largely unopened.
</P>
<P>
   This has not happened in so long that whenever I take up
something new, be it software or hardware, I expect trouble. It has
ranged from a program that pigheadedly insisted the serial number
on the box was the wrong one to a piece of hardware that would not
work no matter what I did.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, granted, things got a little hinky while I was installing
this peerless program, which, incidentally, is called OneStep
Connect. When it asked for the serial number, I started looking in
all the bizarre places I've been finding them lately, including on
the CD-ROM. The installation program got confused when I ejected
the CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   The serial number was printed plainly on a card inside the
manual. What a novel idea.
</P>
<P>
   OneStep Connect is a personal organizer published by a firm
called OneStep. It is a very simple program; it doesn't try to do
so much that it gets confusing, and what it does, it does
gracefully and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   OneStep gives you an address book/phone list, a calendar and a
to-do list, and handles letters, memos, faxes and e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   When I clicked on the e-mail button, OneStep brought up the
Microsoft dialog box to dial my service provider, then summoned my
standard e-mail program, Eudora Pro. I like that.
</P>
<P>
   When I clicked on Letter, it summoned Microsoft Word and brought
it up with a fancy memo heading. I went into options and switched
to OneStep's own, much simpler editor, just because it loads
quicker and it will do those grisly personalized mass mailings,
postal or electronic.
</P>
<P>
   The address book is easy to set up and use. When you wish to add
a person, it brings up a reasonable form for the name, address, and
telephone numbers and e-mail addresses _ not one of those full-page
forms for listing the individual's favorite color, his ex-wives and
the results of his latest blood test. To be sure, there is a place
to put notes and another to put stuff like spouse's name and
birthdays, but it's a separate page you need never even see if you
don't want to mess with it.
</P>
<P>
   It will dial a number using a calling card, and you can set up
special, separate address books using the data in the main list.
</P>
<P>
   The calendar and its to-do functions are also straightforward.
You've got an appointment; you click on the day. You get close-up
view of that day; select the starting time and the time span. Tell
it what details you wish and whether you want an alarm. It marks
that day on the monthly calendar, and you're in business.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a little feature that shows the current time in
all the world's time zones. I mean, really, there's got to be
something at least a little exotic, and the time zone feature
doesn't get in the way at all.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably wondering why I'm so excited. Well, at the
newspaper we've all just gone through four hours of training to use
our new e-mail, calendar and appointment program _ the name of
which will go unsaid _ which is so muscle-bound and over-engineered
I can actually hear molars grinding all around me. It does a lot
less than OneStep and is clumsy besides.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for OneStep, which works right out of the box. If
you can't find it in a store, you can order it from
www.onestepinc.com, from which site you can also download a demo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
