<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN27-CO     04-26 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A little planning makes home-based LAN feasible
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ My wife thinks I've lost it.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, I suppose, she's right.
</P>
<P>
   You see, my plan is to wire my house with Ethernet cable and
create my own mini-LAN.
</P>
<P>
   A Yandel-LAN, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, every time I try to explain to her the method
behind my madness _ and there is method behind my madness _ the
same thing happens. Her eyes glaze over as soon as I say
``network,'' and she gets that far-away look you see on the faces
of students who sit by the window in Algebra.
</P>
<P>
   It all started when I heard the two best words a Web surfer can
ever hear: cable modem.
</P>
<P>
   You see, we are in the process of having a new house built, and
before the builders could flatten the lot, I called up MediaOne to
see if they serviced my future neighborhood. A very patient sales
rep answered all of my questions _ no matter how many times I asked
them.
</P>
<P>
   First, she gave me the good news. Cable modem service will be
available with blazingly fast connection speeds for $40 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Then she told me the bad news. Additional cable modems for other
computers cost $40 a month each.
</P>
<P>
   That's what set me wandering into the Ethernet.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I know my household is atypical when it comes to computers
(and in many other ways, too). We will have three PCs in the new
house: The P166 with a fresh hard drive for my wife to use, an old
486 I am in the process of upgrading for my 5-year-old daughter,
and a blazing new AMD450 I am outfitting with RAM, my old hard
drives and other gadgetry.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a letdown to find out it was going to cost $120 per
month for cable modem access to these machines. Add in the cost for
cable TV service (it isn't included, even though it travels on the
same coaxial cable as the Net connection), and MediaOne was gonna
be raking in the same monthly amount I pay for Montessori school.
</P>
<P>
   No way.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I decided to wire the house. I could use only one cable
modem and share it across a network with the other computers in the
house. Although I am having mine installed as the house is built,
anyone can easily accomplish the same things without having to go
inside the walls of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother, you might ask.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the obvious benefit _ saving $80 a month in cable modem
fees _ other compelling reasons are sharing programs located on
different machines, sharing one printer and monitoring what the
kids are doing on the Net by checking out their screens from a
remote location.
</P>
<P>
   Less-compelling reasons include networked family gaming or
running your own Web (or other) servers using the cable modem's
24-hour Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as PC prices continue to drop, in-house networks will
probably become as common as bathtubs in newly built homes.
</P>
<P>
   Hooking up your LAN is easy. Each computer to be networked needs
to have an Ethernet card in one of its PCI slots _ like the one you
free up by removing your old telephone modem. My network sources at
the office assure me that 10BaseT cards _ available for less than
$20 at CompUSA _ are plenty for a small network. (MediaOne offers
to provide them for $50 each.)
</P>
<P>
   You'll also need an Ethernet hub, which allows four or five
computers to run off the same connection. Again, unless you plan on
running the next Amazon.com out of your den, a 10BaseT hub ($50 and
up) is plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you'll need enough RJ-45 Ethernet cable to connect it
all.
</P>
<P>
   In my case, I plan to install the hub in the garage and have a
cable jack installed there as well. Then I'll run Ethernet cable
that terminates in wall outlets into the rooms I might one day put
a computer.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, spokesman Tom Buttermore (who enjoys talking about
Ethernets way more than my wife does) says MediaOne is more than
happy to help subscribers customize their cable modem setups. They
are also developing commercial services for people who might
generate enough traffic to warrant a 100BaseT Ethernetwork.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say, however, if they would help you beat your kids
at a networked game of ``Quake II.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
