<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lucas says gadgetry can't sell a bad tale
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   In print
</P>
<P>
   In the May issue of Wired magazine, filmmaker George Lucas talks
about his craft and the state of digital filmmaking. The mastermind
behind the ``Star Wars'' trilogy discusses how he used largely
digital editing in his latest addition to the series. He says 95
percent of ``The Phantom Menace'' was created on computer, for
example. But Lucas added that all the digital gadgetry in the world
wouldn't necessarily make his film a success. Only good
storytelling can do that. ``Astounding you is not my job,'' said
Lucas. ``My job is to tell a story.'' On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular computer games of all time is
``Civilization,'' which lets you start and guide your own group of
people. Now Microprose is releasing the latest improvement on the
game called ``Civilization: A Call to Power.'' The game continues
the same idea but adds new graphics and tools. You also can lead
your civilization for 7,000 years rather than 3,000, as in the
original game. This latest version of ``Civilization'' is available
only for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   In a different vein, Microprose has released another new game,
this one a golf simulation. It's called ``Golden Bear Challenge''
and represents the sixth title in a series bearing Jack Nicklaus'
nickname. In this latest title, players can play as Nicklaus
himself. The game features some famous golf courses, including the
Cochise Course at Desert Mountain, Shoal Creek Golf Club, Sherwood
Country Club and Sherry Montecastillo. ``Golden Bear Challenge'' is
available only for Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   Generation J is a digital magazine for young Jewish people. It
features religious articles as well as those about lifestyle and
politics. For example, the current issue has a story about the
history of Jews in Kosovo as well as one titled, ``Baseball and the
Jews: Making America's Game Our Own.'' You'll find Generation J at
www.generationj.com/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
