r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-(2ndtake)-$ADVO2     04-26 3033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-(2ndtake)-$ADVO2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   xxx on his farm.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore Jr. has been whacked on that account, for not stopping
his tobacco cultivation soon enough after his sister's death from
lung cancer in 1984. At the 1996 Democratic convention, he
delivered a wrenching speech about Nancy and her death. But the
speech stirred criticism that Gore would exploit anyone or any
circumstance for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics)
</P>
<P>
   `` ... Gore had violated the privacy of his loved ones for
purposes of exploiting the rest of us,'' Bob Zelnick writes in
``Gore: A Political Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mike Wallace, who professes high regard for Gore, says: ``I
wonder, though, at the 1996 convention speech about his sister's
death. It might have been a bit much, considering the Gore family's
continued tobacco cultivation and Gore's continued support of
tobacco subsidies. But I don't doubt that Al Gore has been deeply
moved by events in his life.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco is big in Carthage _ burley tobacco, used as cigarette
filler _ but there are no (ital) big (end ital) tobacco farmers.
The government parcels out tobacco allotments to farmers based on
projected sales data supplied by tobacco companies. A farmer can
use his allotment, lease it to another farmer, or give it back to
the government, a rarity because allotments increase land value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco pays for the new Chevy, helps pay the taxes. Three or
four acres is average in central Tennessee. Ten acres is big,''
says Billy Driver, who once worked in the Carthage post office and
now farms burley leaf on seven of his 53 acres in nearby Macon
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco ties people together here like automobiles in Detroit
or corn in Nebraska,'' says Driver. ``Around here, two farmers will
stop their trucks on a country road, one heading west, the other
east. They'll roll down their windows and talk for half an hour.
Talk tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore once grew tobacco. His father had grown it for decades.
Billy Driver knows more than most how much tobacco the Gores grew
on their farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought The Senator's tobacco sticks back in 1991 _ 6,000 of
them,'' says Driver. ``Sticks are the long poles you tie the leaf
to, to cure it in the barn. You need maybe 1,500 sticks per acre of
leaf, so maybe The Senator, Al's father, planted four or five acres
when he last grew tobacco. An acre might bring $2,000, $3,000 per
year. The Gores were comfortable. Young Al ain't rich. I don't see
him driving the hills, you know, don't see him much. But I'll tell
you this: He didn't grow much leaf, and he don't grow any tobacco
no more, because I got the sticks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gores, father and son, were devastated by the loss of Nancy.
But they didn't stop growing leaf right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see every connection between events overnight,''
Gore explained as he talked softly aboard Air Force Two. ``On my
farm, we stopped growing tobacco some time after Nancy died. We no
longer have an allotment. But my father had grown tobacco for 50
(ital) years. (end ital) This was his life. Then _ it was a few
years later _ one of his grandchildren asked, `Grandpa, do we still
grow tobacco?' He thought for a minute. `Not any more,' he said.
And that was the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore Jr. traces much in his political life to deeply moving
experiences in his personal life: ``My family, my father, his
death, my sister, her death. Growing older. My son's accident. I'm
becoming a grandparent soon. These are events that change you,'' he
says. ``Some of the changes you see right away, some take time,
some change comes over you slowly and you don't fully see or even
understand until sometime later, when you look inward. My father,
though, influenced me in so, so many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's farm sits on a hillside across the Caney Fork River from
his dad's farm, where Pauline Gore still lives. He bought the farm
and 2,100-square-foot house from his father in 1973 for $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's house is long, low, faced in reddish-brown
brick. A white rail fence surrounds the property. A gate at the end
of the long drive is closed and locked. Similar-sized farms in
Smith County are listed by real estate agents for between $200,000
and $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Up the road a few hundred yards is a general store operated by a
fellow named Walter Brown Jr. The Gores and their four children do
not shop at his store, says Brown. Farther up the road is a little
honky-tonk road house. You needn't look for the Gores there,
either. You'd have better luck at New Salem Missionary Baptist
Church, which the family attends when they come to town.
</P>
<P>
   A zinc mine operated by Savage Zinc squats near the banks of the
Caney Fork about a quarter-mile behind the vice president's home.
Zinc tunnels snake right under homes, farms and Main Street, where
retailers like Billy Markham lease mineral rights to Savage.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 30 years after his election defeat, even after his death,
people in Carthage debate The Senator's politics, but nobody
debates his character. He is not remembered as a dynasty-building,
political hard-muscle man, like Joe Kennedy Sr. There are no
stories about any behavior other than upright.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much how they talk about his son. They like him.
Often they'll preface an answer about, say, Gore's farm with
something like: ``He's never winked at another woman, you know.''
Or: ``He's a (ital) good (end ital) man, a (ital) family (end ital)
man.'' They defend him against questions not even asked.
</P>
<P>
   There's something else they make clear: They don't send anyone
but their own to Washington. ``He's one of us'' is often heard in
these parts of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore was a son of politics, a child of Washington,'' the
Weekly Standard pointed out to readers in its March 29 issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Gore is a city kid, father a senator. He grew up in
Washington,'' reported Bruce Morton on CNN's Inside Politics on
March 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, sir, in Smith County we don't elect outsiders to
Congress, and outsiders are pretty much anybody who don't live in
Smith County,'' allowed Billy Markham, owner of Markham's General
Store, Main Street, Carthage.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Son of Washington or son of Tennessee? Al Gore finds himself
defending his past because some in the media hold his truth to be
relative. All it takes is a snappy comment _ ``No farmer plows a
steep hillside'' or ``child of Washington'' _ and the (ital)
implication (end ital) is clear: Al Gore is a liar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think because Al spent school years in Washington
with his family, he's not authentic,'' says Jerry Futrell,
president of Smith County Hospital and Gore family friend for 35
years. ``Al transcended Carthage. That doesn't mean he isn't
Carthage. Of course, he lived in Washington part of the year. His
father worked there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Al won his congressional seat in 1976, he promised to
hold town meetings. He did, every weekend, in garages, stores,
diners. Hundreds of meetings. He told tobacco farmers changes were
coming. He helped put warning labels on cigarette packs. They
re-elected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he won re-election to the Senate in 1990, he carried all
95 counties in Tennessee. Either Tennesseans can't tell when a
candidate is local, or you reporters need to have your eyes
checked.''
</P>
<P>
   Followed to its logical conclusion, the knock on Gore's
geographic roots must arrive at only one place. Bob Zelnick
articulates that conclusion: ``He has had no life to speak of
outside of government save for a few years on a Nashville newspaper
_ where he covered government.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, it would seem to some, by being both a son of
Washington (ital) and (end ital) Tennessee can make no credible
claim to being the son of any place.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of his Tennessee roots, it would be only fair to
let Gore have the last word: ``When I went home on holidays from
Harvard, I went to Carthage. When I came back from Vietnam, I could
have gone to Washington, to Cambridge, California, anywhere. But I
didn't. I went home. To Carthage.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics)
</P>
<P>
   Zelnick on Gore's 1970 enlistment in the Army: ``Al Gore Jr.
would not endanger his father's political future or his own. He
would volunteer for military service and take his chances in
Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   A reporter for a national newspaper: ``Divinity school was a
good way to get out of Vietnam.'' Told that Gore was a divinity
student after serving in Vietnam, the reporter said, ``I don't
think so. Why would someone do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's Harvard roommate Bob Somerby on Gore's military service:
``I can't tell you all the reasons Al enlisted, but I can tell you
one reason that wasn't. His political future. Hell, none of us knew
in 1969 if we'd have a future.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore joined the Army in 1970. In May of that year, he and
Tipper married. In December, Spec. 5 Gore went to Vietnam, where he
served seven months as a newsletter writer in an engineering
battalion. He didn't see combat, and didn't serve the usual 12
months in Vietnam because his enlistment was up by early autumn
1971. While overseas, he sent a story about a Viet Cong ambush to
the Tennessean, Nashville's morning daily, where editor John
Seigenthaler liked what he saw. Gore's friends say he was a good
writer; his detractors say he was not.
</P>
<P>
   He smoked a little marijuana. He drank a little beer _ not a
lot, say friends. During his Army stint, he and Tipper lived in a
trailer outside an Alabama Army base. They drove an old VW bus into
the Rockies, where they camped and hiked. They listened to rock 'n'
roll. They didn't buy into the tuned-out culture, nor did they
become revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore's Army enlistment was up, he and Tipper returned to
Nashville, where he began working for the Tennessean and Tipper
studied photography. She soon began free-lancing her photos to the
Tennessean.
</P>
<P>
   Zelnick's speculation on the motives for Al Gore's Army
enlistment presupposes that he had a political future in mind when
he joined.
</P>
<P>
   Not only Somerby, but most of Gore's friends from Harvard,
Carthage and Nashville cannot recall a single discussion with Gore
during the years 1965 to 1975 _ about Vietnam or anything else _ in
which Gore alluded to a political future for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was disgusted with politics, hurt by his father's loss,''
says Frank Sutherland, long-time Gore friend and fellow reporter at
the Tennessean. ``The last thing I thought Al Gore would do is run
for office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he'd stay in journalism and end up at The New York
Times or Washington Post,'' says Seigenthaler, editor and publisher
of the Tennessean during the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envied Al's love for his parents,'' says his Harvard
roommate, Bob Somerby. ``How many kids moved back next door to
their parents after college? Al's friends were people like me and
Tommy Lee Jones. Totally unconnected people. Harvard was full of
(ital) really (end ital) connected people, but Al's friends were
just regular guys. He made decisions because his father brought him
up to (ital) honor (end ital) certain values, (ital) do things
right, (end ital) for right's sake. Not because his father was a
senator.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gore told many of his friends that if he didn't
enlist, some other Smith County boy would _ and maybe die.
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland, who is now the editor of the Tennessean, says:
``Whatever political hopes Al's father had for Al came to fruition
not because (ital) he (end ital) harbored those hopes, but because
(ital) Al (end ital) chose _ in his own time and at his own pace _
to pursue a political career.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he thought he'd make journalism a career. He had tried
law school at Vanderbilt in the early '70s but says he didn't like
the way he saw justice dispensed. He had tried divinity school at
Vanderbilt for a semester but didn't hear a loud enough call.
</P>
<P>
   Politics _ not preaching, not law, not journalism _ finally
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved journalism. But then, February 1976, John Seigenthaler
called me at home,'' says Gore. ``He said, `Al, I thought you'd
like to know Joe Evins isn't running for re-election.' I listened.
I think I said thanks. If you had asked me two days before would I
run, I'd have said no. I hung up the phone and turned to Tipper.
`Joe Evins isn't running,' I said. Then, (ital) right then, (end
ital) I knew. `I'm gonna run for Congress,' I told Tipper.''
</P>
<P>
   He beat eight Democrats in the primary, won the general election
and served four terms. In 1984, he was elected to the U.S. Senate.
By then, Gore had gained a reputation among colleagues as a whiz on
arms control. He garnered national publicity when he pushed
legislation through the House that required higher standards in the
manufacturing of infant formula. He took submarine trips to the
North Pole to further publicize his views on global warming. And he
came to Carthage almost every weekend for those town meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics)
</P>
<P>
   Terms used by some former House and Senate colleagues and
journalists to describe Gore: ``Not a team player,'' ``a Rosie Ruiz
type,'' ``self-promoter,'' ``loner,'' ``Prince Albert,''
``preppy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other congressional associates, journalists and friends suggest:
``Prepared,'' ``disciplined,'' ``regular guy,'' ``honest.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   So who is the real Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's got an opinion, friend and foe. But only Gore can
(ital) show (end ital) who he is.
</P>
<P>
   To win the hearts and minds of voters, he has to connect through
media that are disconnected, abstract. Whether Gore wins may depend
on whether he takes the risk and specifies the particulars of what
he calls his vision.
</P>
<P>
   The specifics will be test-marketed, polled, analyzed. On this
Air Force Two flight, it's not time yet for Gore to download his
theory of new technologies, their social implications, the policies
needed to manage them, the markets needed to promulgate them. He is
still thinking about how to articulate his vision.
</P>
<P>
   He may even be thinking about (ital) if (end ital) he wants to
articulate it.
</P>
<P>
   Visionaries walk a fine line. If Gore's ultimate message is too
cerebral, he'll reinforce the dreaded egghead suspiion. If it's
overly simplified, he'll be called on to show the emperor's
wardrobe. He may choose safety over risk and leave the message
unsent.
</P>
<P>
   But if he takes that route, he risks leaving unsaid the very
ideas that so engage him. And without a new Al Gore behind the
podium, he likely will come across as the old wooden one.
</P>
<P>
   Clues to Gore's vision can be found in speeches delivered at the
Chernobyl Museum in Kiev, at conferences such as those in Seattle
and Oakland and, especially, in his book, ``Earth in the Balance,''
a 385-page warning on global warming, pollution, how we made the
mess and how we can fix it. There is even a chapter on (ital) why,
(end ital) from a psychological standpoint, we made the mess, a
chapter some readers find confusing, a tad spiritualistic and
perhaps downright odd.
</P>
<P>
   Zelnick calls ``Earth in the Balance'' ``more of a nostalgic
anti-modernism than a reasonable analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in the preface, says he wrote the book for many reasons,
including the emotional change he underwent while his son, Albert
Gore III, spent months in the hospital after being hit by a car as
the family left a Baltimore Orioles game in April 1989. Gore _ who
saw his son's body fly through the air and fall to the pavement _
knelt and performed CPR, and for months, alternating with Tipper,
slept nights on hospital rollaways to be by young Albert's side.
Albert is now healthy, but his father was reminded of the
vicissitudes of life, life beyond politics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is introspective in that sense. He knows he is moved by
personal experience as well as reason. ``Earth in the Balance'' has
been criticized for not reading like a scientific treatise, but
it's not meant to be one. It's a personal statement backed up by
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore likes to make personal statements _ well reasoned but,
at a fundamental level, personal. Not what you'd expect from a man
who is thought of as stiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to write,'' he says. ``I began as an English
major at Harvard, then switched to government. But writing is a
source of so much pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   It is said by some that Gore was bred for the presidency. This
is not intended as a compliment. Yet nobody knocks Carl Ripken Jr.
for his baseball skills. Nobody is (ital) surprised (end ital)
Ripken plays baseball. The surprise would be if he played cello. Or
if Gore played baseball. Al Gore is his father's son.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says his dad was his mentor, a voice he heard and listened
to, the man who inculcated in him a sense of decorum, respect for
learning, for justice and for God.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Gore went home to bury his father. In his eulogy,
he said of The Senator: ``The night he lost in 1970, he made me
prouder still. He said defeat may serve as well as victory to shake
the soul and let the glory out. Then he turned the old Southern
segregationist slogan on its head and declared, `The truth shall
rise again.' ``
</P>
<P>
   If Al Gore can articulate who (ital) he (end ital) is the same
way he captured his father's essence, style may just give way to
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Upriver from Carthage, where the Cumberland River twists through
steep-sided valleys, Cordell Hull Lake rides high behind Cordell
Hull Dam, a concrete wonder built by the Army Corps of Engineers 60
years ago to tame the Cumberland.
</P>
<P>
   The lake holds a lesson for anyone trying to flesh out Al Gore.
It was conceived by powerful politicians more than a half century
ago, built in Tennessee with the latest technology and managed by
Washington professionals. Surface appearances do not divulge true
dimensions, and closer scrutiny is difficult because access is
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a Washington dam or a Tennessee lake? Who cares? A more
important question is, how deep is it?
</P>
<P>
   America is about to find out.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Reid is a reporter for The Palm Beach Post.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
