<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3269 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-(2takes)-$ADV02-     04-26 3482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-(2takes)-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHO IS AL GORE? NATION SOON WILL LEARN THE ANSWER
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories for release
Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    Eds: A shorter version of this story, slugged GORE-SHORTER, is
also moving.
 &HT;    By PAUL REID
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, are nestled on a couch in the
forward, private cabin of Air Force Two, eastbound 36,000 feet over
Kansas. The cabin is bare of decoration, except for a wall map of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The world: Almost 6 billion people. The president of the United
States may be the most powerful human being on the planet. The vice
president is not.
</P>
<P>
   A century from now, only professors and trivia experts will know
who was vice president in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Warm spit. A heartbeat away. Al Gore's heard them all. He smiles
as he tells the one about the man who had two brothers, one who
went to sea and one who became vice president, and neither was
heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's on a mission to make sure that doesn't happen to him,
that future generations will remember hisname and his deeds and
think well of both.
</P>
<P>
   Now is Al Gore's time to tell us who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Already, it's the Republicans' time to offer their version.
Former Vice President Dan Quayle kicked off his presidential
campaign by making clear he is running not only against Gore but
against ``Clinton-Gore'' on family values and character. The GOP
will target Gore's fund-raising practices, his environmental views
and federal insinuation into local school issues. There are plenty
of photos for attack ads: Gore with an impeached Clinton, Gore at
the Buddhist temple, Gore in China.
</P>
<P>
   And if the economy sours in the next year, if Y2K problems wreak
techno-havoc, Gore will need a team of mules to dig out from under
everything his opponents dump on him.
</P>
<P>
   How will Gore answer the opposition? Will he discard the
rhetoric of the '80s and deliver a message for the double-ought
decade?
</P>
<P>
   What sort of man is he, beyond the political? What forces forged
him as a child, young man, adult? How does he behave in informal
circumstances? Is he as stiff as the press makes him out to be?
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man,'' said Gore's boss at a recent dinner in
Sewall's Point, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if the words alone may not have fully conveyed his
meaning, Bill Clinton lowered his gaze for the briefest of moments.
He looked up, his stare intense, jaw set, right eye narrowed,
``He's a (ital) good (end ital) man.''
</P>
<P>
   Another pause. ``He has redefined the office of the vice
president. He is the most effective and active vice president in
history. A great deal of good has come out of this administration
during the last six years, and he is responsible for much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   For the next 18 months, Al Gore will tell us how he redefined
the office of vice president and what it means to us.
</P>
<P>
   He will tell us why he wants to be president. He says he has a
compelling vision of where we want to go as a nation, how we can
get there and how we can live better lives when we arrive.
</P>
<P>
   We will ask about his past. He will tell us about the future.
</P>
<P>
   If the future plays out as he hopes, he and Tipper will be
sitting in the forward cabin of another plane in less than 21
months.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   They don't see much of each other these days. He's off to
California, Palm Beach, New York raising money, lots of money.
He'll be testing his campaign message soon from Atlanta to Iowa,
Chicago to Texas. Tipper, too, is on the road, flying to or from
Bosnia, Hawaii, San Francisco, speaking about children's health
care. Once in a while, they hook up, as they did in San Francisco
on a day in early March.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you notice about them is the affection. He
drapes an arm over her shoulder. They touch fingers, smile. It's
spontaneous, warm.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the most natural woman I've met, down to earth,'' said
David Gergen of Tipper Gore during a recent visit to Palm Beach.
Gergen has met lots of first ladies as an adviser to George Bush
and Bill Clinton and as a journalist who covered eight White
Houses. ``She is well anchored,'' he says, ``and they are a lucky
couple. What you see is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Observes Bob Somerby, Al Gore's Harvard roommate and longtime
friend: ``I'm amazed at how normal they are. The life they lead _
the motorcades, everyone wants a piece of them, their status _
could swell their heads. But they're like they were 30 years ago.
Normal.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, an image of abiding love could be the contrivance of
political pros. But then, some things cannot be feigned, especially
for 33 years. Watch them speak to each other, touch, look. Everyone
knows at least one couple like this, the pair who really do like
each other.
</P>
<P>
   They're talking about life in the Gore home.
</P>
<P>
   Dinners?
</P>
<P>
   ``We laugh a lot at the table,'' says Tipper. ``You have to be
able to laugh. When the children were younger, we'd talk about
music, art, politics, but not a great deal of politics. You want to
engage the children. It's a time when a family can be a family
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Music?
</P>
<P>
   ``We like a wide range,'' she says, but she flinches ever so
slightly, just a little tightening in the jaw. Her gaze asks _
demands _ are you coming at me with this '80s censorship thing?
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Tipper Gore was excoriated by Hollywood when she
lobbied for content labels on records and tapes. Frank Zappa called
her ``the wife of Big Brother'' at the time, prompting then-Senator
Gore to declare that as a younger man, he had been a big Zappa fan.
No matter how often Tipper said she did not want to censor any
musician, she was accused of trying to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should be able to buy a record and have a reasonable
idea of what's on it. That's all it was about,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it's back to her musical tastes. ``I like Herbie Hancock,
k.d. lang, Alison Krauss. She has such a sweet, beautiful voice ...
''
</P>
<P>
   ``And plays a stunning fiddle,'' says Gore. ``There's Garth
Brooks and Ricky Skaggs. Lucinda Williams ... ''
</P>
<P>
   They trade names for a few minutes more. Dvorak, Thelonious Monk
...
</P>
<P>
   The vice president strums an air guitar when he mentions Doc
Watson, the blind North Carolina bluegrass musician. ``We used to
see Doc when he played up north in the '60s,'' says Gore. ``When I
was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Then his memory wanders back to that spring night in 1966 when
he spied a young girl at a Washington party. He was 17, a senior
academic and athletic standout at St. Albans(cq), a Washington prep
school for the sons of the rich and influential. She was 16, a
junior at St. Agnes Episcopal School in Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always be able to close my eyes and relive that
moment,'' says Gore, doing just that. ``I can see her across the
room. Blond hair, very pretty smile.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl was Mary Elizabeth Aitcheson. An only child, her
parents, Margaret and Jack Aitcheson, divorced in 1952. She was
Tipper to her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw (ital) him (end ital) across the room,'' she says. ``I
met him and liked him. Smart. Funny. He called the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are three daughters _ Karenna, 25; Kristin, 21;
Sarah, 20 _ and a son, Albert Gore III, 16. The two younger
daughters are at Harvard. Karenna is married and attends Columbia
Law School. The Gores mortgaged their 88-acre Tennessee farm to the
rafters to send the young women to Harvard and pay for young
Albert's education at the Sidwell Friends School in Washington.
Financial disclosure forms filed in 1998 by Gore show a net worth
of just under $1 million, much of it derived from royalties on his
1992 book, ``Earth in the Balance,'' and Tipper's book of
photography, ``Picture This.'' He makes $171,500 a year as vice
president. There are no blind trusts, no large stock portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   They will become grandparents in June when Karenna gives birth
to her first child. Gore, who at 51 is five months older than his
wife, was asking everyone on Air Force Two who looked over 40 if
they were grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with the years going by, with age. Since about
age 45, I've been OK with my aging,'' he says. ``Becoming a
grandparent is one more wonderful event in a 33-year relationship
with a wonderful woman.''
</P>
<P>
   They talk about sharing those years, talk about family and
faith, his parents, their children. The future. His future.
</P>
<P>
   Why does he want to be president? Why put his wife and his
children and their children on the covers of supermarket tabloids?
Why expose the smallest details of his entire life to often
frenzied and not always accurate scrutiny?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I want to do the job _ you have to (ital) want (end
ital) it _ because I can (ital) do (end ital) the job, because I
love my country and am grateful for the chance to (ital) lead (end
ital) this country. I know what that may mean for my family. I
thank God for Tipper's love. The love we share will see us through.
We're ready. I'm ready. I'm excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Excited?
</P>
<P>
   Can this possibly be the same guy who's portrayed as somber,
humorless, wooden, a policy wonk? You know, ``Al Gore's timber all
right, but is it presidential timber?''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not charismatic,'' said CBS newsman Mike Wallace before
addressing members of a private art museum in Palm Beach. ``But
maybe the country has had enough of charisma for the moment. Al
Gore is substantial, a fine and honorable man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is more prepared than any vice president I have known for
the duties of president,'' said Gergen. ``He reads all the cable
traffic _ State, CIA. But he does not get lost in details, as
(Jimmy) Carter did. He can delegate. At meetings with the
president, he is a participant, and the president makes clear his
respect for Gore. Al Gore is smart. Persistent. Very disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a peculiar thing,'' says Martin Peretz, publisher of The
New Republic, Harvard professor and Gore friend. ``The Al Gore I
have known for more than 30 years is funny, engaging, not the
sometimes somber man you see on TV. He is sincere. He is not facile
_ that's the word I'd use _ like Bill Clinton. He was a good
student. He is intellectually honest. And you know, compared to
Bill Bradley, Al's a showman.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll get another point of view by reading ``Gore: A Political
Life,'' a new _ and not flattering _ biography of Gore by former
ABC newsman Bob Zelnick: ``There is, in short, not a man behind the
robot, but quite possibly a robot behind the man.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, published by Regnery, a conservative house, quotes an
unnamed ``White House insider'' as saying of Gore: ``He wants to
script every move he makes ... to say what his handlers tell him to
say and nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Sit down and talk with Albert Gore Jr. and quickly you realize
he is decidedly not stiff. He wears an easy smile. He listens. He
looks you in the eye. He speaks with precision but drives home
points with humor, analogy, metaphor. His voice is rich yet soft.
It carries a mild Southern inflection. He gestures with his hands
in a measured sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard Air Force Two, he displayed with glee a bumper sticker:
``Nixon in 2000 _ He's still not as stiff as Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   He talks with enthusiasm about his reading interests: British
geneticist Richard Dawkins, cosmologist Stephen Hawking, physicist
Richard Feynman, historian William Manchester, books on
thermodynamics, computers, emerging markets, Darwin, chaos theory,
the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read at the expense of my sleep time,'' says Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He is a man engaged by the world and the people in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world, the universe and our place in the universe, it is
all so humbling. Some of these modern thinkers are so smart _
Hawking, the smartest man in the world. And his illness forces him
to communicate by voice synthesizer. A century ago he would have
been an outcast.''
</P>
<P>
   He speaks at length about the early years of the information
highway but does not take credit for inventing the Internet _ as he
was quoted in March as having done in a moment of hyperbole or
misstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Then he whips a subcompact notebook computer from his pocket and
starts to explicate the technology, memory capacity, cost versus
power, possible future regulatory implications of the unit's
infrared data-sending capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody could intercept my message when I send it from my
unit to yours,'' he says. ``New technologies are just pouring out
of R&AMP;D laboratories. Data processing capacities are growing
exponentially. We are truly living in extraordinary times.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, holds aloft his state-of-the art notepad for effect.
``We have to decide where we want to take technology like this, not
where it wants to take us. Our new knowledge presents an incredible
opportunity and challenge for all of mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this a guy who likes technology for technology's sake, or
will he translate his personal vision of the world into a political
vision? The campaign will tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter for a national newspaper sitting near Gore on Air
Force Two listens as the vice president wanders the philosophical
landscape. ``Geez,'' he says after the vice president leaves, ``why
can't he talk like that on TV?''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the Al Gore of the podium, the Al Gore of
the nightly news clip. Often, when Gore speaks from behind a podium
he is stiff, as if the sleeves of his dark blue suits are lined
with flagpoles. Even when reading his own words, he often manifests
a bewildering ability to perform oratorical alchemy by turning
golden concepts into lead.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the vice president call this transition from engaging
private fellow to listless public orator the ``disconnect.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is aware of the perception. He jokes about it. ``I like the
low expectations. It's funny,'' he says, ``but my father was known
as the fiddle-playing, outgoing Tennessee senator. Yet he was a
formal man. He taught me how to properly show respect, for my
elders, for the president. So I'm thought of as formal, but I don't
see myself that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers would like him to maximize his public
appearances in places where he can be informal, venues where he can
moderate a round-table discussion or lead a ``town meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast trip he used just-plain-English to tell
Seattle residents their two-hour commutes to and from work were
wrong. He told them the federal government could not and would not
become a zoning board, but would loosen the purse strings to help
cities unclog highways so workers can get home in time to have
dinner with their families. Gore calls it his ``livability
agenda.'' Gore was at ease, used no techno-jargon. He connected.
</P>
<P>
   He told Seattle high-tech executives the explosion in technology
had to reach the meekest among mankind in order to truly serve
mankind. He told them government policy lagged private sector
development. The high-tech crowd found him more prepared than
``prepped'' for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows as much as we do,'' said one. ``He (ital) knows (end
ital) his stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He had avoided podiums and scripted speeches. He was loose.
There were no handlers on hand.
</P>
<P>
   On the return trip, Gore spoke of where he may go in his
campaign. ``I believe any candidate for president must show the
American people three things. First, you must have a clear vision
of our shared future, a compelling vision. You must be able to
communicate that vision and identify within it certain goals,
destinations we want to reach as a people, and identify ways of
reaching those goals. Finally, there must be an awareness of our
shared values upon which decisions can be based while the
administration and the country work toward reaching that vision.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused. ``I believe I can do that. I want to do that. I'm
excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And when his days in Washington are done _ maybe after next
year, maybe in January 2005, perhaps in 2009 _ where will he go?
</P>
<P>
   ``Home. To Tennessee. To my farm. I'd like to write. Fiction,
non-fiction. That's what I'll do. That's where I'll go. To
Carthage. Home.''
</P>
<P>
   But in politics, home isn't a value-free word.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a boy, my father sent me out to work the fields to
learn about work, to learn about life,'' Al Gore says aboard Air
Force Two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me how to clear land with a double-bladed ax. He
taught me how to plow a steep hillside with a team of mules,'' Gore
was quoted in The Des Moines Register, March 16, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Again, you can find contrary views. ``Lyrical,'' ``tall tales,''
``gauzy,'' ``Norman Rockwell-style account'' are descriptions used
by some of the Washington media to describe Gore's memories of
Carthage.
</P>
<P>
   ``How preposterous. ... Real farmers, even poor ones, have been
hiring bulldozers to clear land since before Al Gore was born,''
wrote William Kristol's conservative Weekly Standard on March 29,
1999. ``No responsible farmer since the Dust Bowl days of the 1930s
has plowed a steep hillside.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (end italics)
</P>
<P>
   To get to Carthage, county seat of Smith County, drive about 50
miles east from Nashville on I-40. Upon arrival, certain truisms
can be learned from a cursory look at the countryside. It is hilly
hereabouts. Steep hilly. Farms look like they're about to slide
down the hillsides. Small farms. The farmers are not rich. They do
not plow land with rented bulldozers because renting a bulldozer is
expensive, and they tend to roll over and fall down the hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   Carthage sits on high land above a bend in the wide and
fast-flowing Cumberland River. It's home to the Friday night
catfish fry at the City Diner just down the block from Main Street,
where the old Walton Hotel is closed for renovation. Here, you
still park your car nose in to the curb, but dry goods stores have
been replaced by kitschy boutiques, antique shops and law offices.
</P>
<P>
   Cordell Hull's house sits just up the road. Hull _ Tennessee
congressman and FDR's secretary of state _ was mentor to Gore's
father.
</P>
<P>
   Old tobacco barns, bleached gray, hug low hillsides and lean
crazily in shaded hollows. The Smith County population has grown by
several hundred in the last few years, to almost 15,000. At dusk,
the interstate discharges commuters from Nashville onto local
roads. At night, the valley is quiet. It all looks as it did 40 or
50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was born here on March 31, 1948. His sister, Nancy, was
10. The Gores hadn't expected another child. There would be no more
after Al.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Albert Gore Sr., was the local school
superintendent, congressman and U.S. senator from 1953 to 1971.
While a senator in the mid-1950s, he was the prime mover for the
interstate highway system and an early supporter of Medicare.
Gore's mother, Pauline LaFon, was one of the first women to
graduate from Vanderbilt Law School, though she chose marriage and
a family over legal practice.
</P>
<P>
   After losing his Senate seat in 1970, the senior Gore became
chairman of Island Creek Coal Co., a board member of Occidental
Petroleum and raised beef cattle, chickens and tobacco on his
200-acre hillside farm.
</P>
<P>
   Before buying the farm, located about five miles out of
Carthage, the senator and his wife _ in Carthage he is still called
The Senator, she is called Miss Pauline _ kept house in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to sit on the porch summer evenings,'' says Janet
Jenkins, 64, a lifelong Carthage resident. ``We didn't often see
Nancy or Pauline on Main Street, but The Senator put on his
britches like the rest of us. The Senator was raised on a small
farm at Possum Hollow, and not raised rich. I heard the very first
speech he ever gave. On the courthouse steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Gore Sr. died last December at age 90. Mrs. Gore has
suffered two strokes and a heart attack since 1993, but, at 86, she
is still known for her political acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Carthage residents say the senior Gore was many things _ as good
a farmer as he was a politician _ but remained at heart a man who
loved the land of Middle Tennessee. By the late 1960s, he seemed to
be ahead of his time in casting Senate votes against the Vietnam
War, against school prayer amendments, against banning forced
school busing. His constituents thought the senator no longer
reflected Tennessee values. He was defeated by Bill Brock, then a
30-year-old candy fortune heir, in a Senate race still talked about
as downright mean.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Gore Sr. vowed never again to run for office, and did
not. He said he was going home to his farm, and did. He grew some
tobacco. Later, by the mid-'70s, his son was growing tobacco on his
farm.
</P>
<P>
   MORE MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
