<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SHORTER-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHO IS AL GORE? NATION SOON WILL LEARN THE ANSWER
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories for release
Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    Eds: A longer version of this story, slugged GORE, is also
moving.
 &HT;    By PAUL REID
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, are nestled on a couch in the
forward, private cabin of Air Force Two, eastbound 36,000 feet over
Kansas. The cabin is bare of decoration, except for a wall map of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you notice about them is the affection. He
drapes an arm over her shoulder. They touch fingers, smile. It's
spontaneous, warm.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, an image of abiding love could be the contrivance of
political pros. But then, some things cannot be feigned, especially
for 33 years. Watch them speak to each other, touch, look. Everyone
knows at least one couple like this, the pair who really do like
each other.
</P>
<P>
   They don't see much of each other these days. He's off to
California, Palm Beach, New York raising money, lots of money.
He'll be testing his campaign message soon from Ohio to North
Carolina, Colorado to Texas. Tipper, too, is on the road, speaking
about children's health care. Once in a while, they hook up, as
they did in San Francisco on a day in early March.
</P>
<P>
   They talk about family and faith, his parents, their children.
The future. His future.
</P>
<P>
   Now is Al Gore's time to tell us who he is. The vice president
says he has a compelling vision of where we want to go as a nation,
how we can get there and how we can live better lives when we
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Already, it's the Republicans' time to offer their version.
Former Vice President Dan Quayle kicked off his presidential
campaign by making clear he is running not only against Gore, but
against ``Clinton-Gore'' on family values and character.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP will target Gore's fund-raising practices, his
environmental views and federal insinuation into local school
issues. There are plenty of photos for attack ads: Gore with an
impeached Clinton, Gore at the Buddhist temple, Gore in China.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 18 months, Gore will tell us why he wants to be
president: ``Because I want to do the job _ you have to want it _
because I can do the job, because I love my country and am grateful
for the chance to lead this country ... I thank God for Tipper's
love. The love we share will see us through. We're ready. I'm
ready. I'm excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Excited?
</P>
<P>
   Can this possibly be the same guy who's portrayed as somber,
wooden, a policy wonk? You know, ``Al Gore's timber all right, but
is it presidential timber?''
</P>
<P>
   Sit down and talk with Albert Gore Jr. and quickly you realize
he is decidedly not stiff. He wears an easy smile. He listens. He
looks you in the eye. He speaks with precision, but drives home
points with humor, analogy, metaphor. His voice is rich yet soft.
It carries a mild Southern inflection. He gestures with his hands
in a measured sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   He displays with glee a bumper sticker: ``Nixon in 2000 _ He's
still not as stiff as Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   They're talking about life in the Gore home.
</P>
<P>
   Dinners?
</P>
<P>
   ``We laugh a lot at the table,'' says Tipper. ``You have to be
able to laugh. When the children were younger, we'd talk about
music, art, politics, but not a great deal of politics. You want to
engage the children. It's a time when a family can be a family
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Music?
</P>
<P>
   ``We like a wide range,'' she says, but she flinches ever so
slightly, just a little tightening in the jaw. Her gaze asks _
demands _ are you coming at me with this '80s censorship thing?
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Tipper Gore was excoriated by Hollywood when she
lobbied for content labels on records and tapes. Frank Zappa called
her ``the wife of Big Brother'' at the time, prompting then-Senator
Gore to declare that as a younger man, he had been a big Zappa fan.
No matter how often Tipper said she did not want to censor any
musician, she was accused of trying to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should be able to buy a record and have a reasonable
idea of what's on it. That's all it was about,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it's back to her musical tastes. ``I like Herbie Hancock,
k.d. lang, Alison Krauss. She has such a sweet, beautiful voice ...
''
</P>
<P>
   ``And plays a stunning fiddle,'' says Gore. ``There's Garth
Brooks and Ricky Skaggs. Lucinda Williams ... ''
</P>
<P>
   They trade names for a few minutes more. Dvorak, Thelonious Monk
...
</P>
<P>
   The vice president strums an air guitar when he mentions Doc
Watson, the blind North Carolina bluegrass musician. ``We used to
see Doc when he played up north in the '60s,'' says Gore. ``When I
was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   Then his memory wanders back to that spring night in 1966 when
he spied a young girl at a Washington party. He was 17, a senior
academic and athletic standout at St. Albans(cq), a Washington prep
school for the sons of the rich and influential. She was 16, a
junior at St. Agnes Episcopal School in Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always be able to close my eyes and relive that
moment,'' says Gore, doing just that. ``I can see her across the
room. Blond hair, very pretty smile.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl was Mary Elizabeth Aitcheson. An only child, her
parents, Margaret and Jack Aitcheson, divorced in 1952. She was
Tipper to her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him across the room,'' she says. ``I met him and liked
him. Smart. Funny. He called the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are three daughters _ Karenna, 25; Kristin, 21;
Sarah, 20 _ and a son, Albert Gore III, 16. The two younger
daughters are at Harvard. Karenna is married and attends Columbia
Law School. The Gores mortgaged their 88-acre Tennessee farm to the
rafters to send the young women to Harvard and pay for young
Albert's education at the Sidwell Friends School in Washington.
Financial disclosure forms filed in 1998 by Gore show a net worth
of just under $1 million, much of it derived from royalties on his
1992 book, ``Earth in the Balance,'' and Tipper's book of
photography, ``Picture This.'' He makes $171,500 a year as vice
president. There are no blind trusts, no large stock portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   They will become grandparents in June when Karenna gives birth
to her first child. ``I'm comfortable with the years going by, with
age. Since about age 45, I've been OK with my aging,'' says Gore,
who at 51 is five months older than his wife.
</P>
<P>
   And when his days in Washington are done _ maybe after next
year, maybe in January 2005, perhaps in 2009 _ where will he go?
</P>
<P>
   ``Home. To Tennessee. To my farm. I'd like to write. Fiction,
non-fiction. That's what I'll do. That's where I'll go. To
Carthage. Home.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   To get to Carthage, county seat of Smith County, drive about 50
miles east from Nashville on I-40.
</P>
<P>
   Carthage sits on high land above a bend in the wide and
fast-flowing Cumberland River. It's home to the Friday night
catfish fry at the City Diner just down the block from Main Street,
where the old Walton Hotel is closed for renovation. Here, you
still park your car nose in to the curb, but dry goods stores have
been replaced by kitschy boutiques, antique shops and law offices.
</P>
<P>
   Cordell Hull's house sits just up the road. Hull _ Tennessee
congressman and FDR's secretary of state _ was mentor to Gore's
father.
</P>
<P>
   Old tobacco barns, bleached gray, hug low hillsides and lean
crazily in shaded hollows. The Smith County population has grown by
several hundred in the last few years, to almost 15,000. At dusk,
the interstate discharges commuters from Nashville onto local
roads. At night, the valley is quiet. It all looks as it did 40 or
50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was born here on March 31, 1948. His sister, Nancy, was
10. The Gores hadn't expected another child. There would be no more
after Al.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Albert Gore Sr., was the local school
superintendent, congressman and U.S. senator from 1953 to 1971.
While a senator in the mid-1950s, he was the prime mover for the
interstate highway system and an early supporter of Medicare.
Gore's mother, Pauline LaFon, was one of the first women to
graduate from Vanderbilt Law School, though she chose marriage and
a family over legal practice. After losing his Senate seat in 1970
to 30-year-old candy heir Bill Brock, the senior Gore became
chairman of Island Creek Coal Co., a board member of Occidental
Petroleum and raised beef cattle, chickens and tobacco on his
200-acre hillside farm.
</P>
<P>
   He died last December at age 90. Mrs. Gore has suffered two
strokes and a heart attack since 1993, but, at 86, she is still
known for her political acumen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Tennesseeans apparently thought the senator was out of
step for opposing the Vietnam War, a school prayer amendment, a ban
on school busing. He vowed never again to run for office, and did
not. He said he was going home to his farm, and did. He grew some
tobacco. Later, by the mid-'70s, his son was growing tobacco on his
farm.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore Jr. has been whacked for not stopping his tobacco
cultivation soon enough after his sister's death from lung cancer
in 1984. At the 1996 Democratic convention, he delivered a
wrenching speech about Nancy and her death. But the speech stirred
criticism that Gore would exploit anyone or any circumstance for
political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see every connection between events overnight,''
Gore explained as he talked softly aboard Air Force Two. ``On my
farm, we stopped growing tobacco some time after Nancy died. We no
longer have an allotment. But my father had grown tobacco for 50
years. This was his life. Then _ it was a few years later _ one of
his grandchildren asked, `Grandpa, do we still grow tobacco?' He
thought for a minute. `Not any more,' he said. And that was the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's farm sits on a hillside across the Caney
Fork River from his dad's farm, where Pauline Gore still lives. He
bought the farm and 2,100-square-foot house from his father in 1973
for $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   The house is long, low, faced in reddish-brown brick. A white
rail fence surrounds the property. A gate at the end of the long
drive is closed and locked. Similar-sized farms in Smith County are
listed by real estate agents for between $200,000 and $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, home isn't a value-free word, and even Gore's roots
are being questioned: Is he from Washington or Tennessee?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is a city kid, father a senator. He grew up in
Washington,'' reported Bruce Morton on CNN's Inside Politics on
March 19.
</P>
<P>
   Former ABC newsman Bob Zelnick, in his unflattering biography,
Gore: A Political Life, articulates the conclusion: ``He has had no
life to speak of outside of government save for a few years on a
Nashville newspaper _ where he covered government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think because Al spent school years in Washington
with his family, he's not authentic,'' says Jerry Futrell,
president of Smith County Hospital and a Gore family friend for 35
years. ``Al transcended Carthage. That doesn't mean he isn't
Carthage. Of course, he lived in Washington part of the year. His
father worked there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Al won his congressional seat in 1976, he promised to
hold town meetings. He did, every weekend, in garages, stores,
diners. Hundreds of meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he won re-election to the Senate in 1990, he carried all
95 counties in Tennessee. Either Tennesseans can't tell when a
candidate is local, or you reporters need to have your eyes
checked.''
</P>
<P>
   On the question of his Tennessee roots, it would be only fair to
let Gore have the last word: ``When I went home on holidays from
Harvard, I went to Carthage. When I came back from Vietnam, I could
have gone to Washington, to Cambridge, California, anywhere. But I
didn't. I went home. To Carthage.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Gore joined the Army in 1970. In May of that year, he and Tipper
married. In December, Spec. 5 Gore went to Vietnam, where he served
seven months as a newsletter writer in an engineering battalion. He
didn't see combat and didn't serve the usual 12 months in Vietnam
because his enlistment was up by early autumn 1971. While overseas,
he sent a story about a Viet Cong ambush to the Tennessean,
Nashville's morning daily, where editor John Seigenthaler liked
what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   Gore smoked a little marijuana. He drank a little beer _ not a
lot, say friends. During his Army stint, he and Tipper lived in a
trailer outside an Alabama Army base. They drove an old VW bus into
the Rockies, where they camped and hiked.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore's enlistment was up, he and Tipper returned to
Nashville, where he began working for the Tennessean and Tipper
studied photography.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he thought he'd make journalism a career. He had tried
law school at Vanderbilt in the early '70s but says he didn't like
the way he saw justice dispensed. He had tried divinity school at
Vanderbilt for a semester but didn't hear a loud enough call.
</P>
<P>
   Politics _ not preaching, not law, not journalism _ finally
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved journalism. But then, February 1976, John Seigenthaler
called me at home,'' says Gore. ``He said, `Al, I thought you'd
like to know Joe Evins isn't running for re-election.' I listened.
I think I said thanks. If you had asked me two days before would I
run, I'd have said no. I hung up the phone and turned to Tipper.
`Joe Evins isn't running,' I said. Then, right then, I knew. `I'm
gonna run for Congress,' I told Tipper.''
</P>
<P>
   He beat eight Democrats in the primary, won the general election
and served four terms. In 1984, he was elected to the U.S. Senate.
By then, Gore had gained a reputation among colleagues as a whiz on
arms control. He garnered national publicity when he pushed
legislation through the House that required higher standards in the
manufacturing of infant formula. He took submarine trips to the
North Pole to further publicize his views on global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody _ friend and foe _ has an opinion about Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Terms used by some former House and Senate colleagues and
journalists to describe Gore: ``Not a team player,'' ``a Rosie Ruiz
type,'' ``self-promoter,'' ``loner,'' ``Prince Albert,''
``preppy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other congressional associates, journalists and friends suggest:
``Prepared,'' ``disciplined,'' ``regular guy,'' ``honest.''
</P>
<P>
   But only Gore can show who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Clues to Gore's vision can be found in his book, ``Earth in the
Balance,'' a 385-page warning on global warming, pollution, how we
made the mess and how we can fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in the preface, says he wrote the book for many reasons,
including the emotional change he underwent while his son, Albert
Gore III, spent months in the hospital after being hit by a car as
the family left a Baltimore Orioles game in April 1989. Gore _ who
saw his son's body fly through the air and fall to the pavement _
knelt and performed CPR, and for months, alternating with Tipper,
spent nights by young Albert's side. Albert is now healthy, but his
father was reminded of the vicissitudes of life, life beyond
politics.
</P>
<P>
   It is said by some that Gore was bred for the presidency: He is
his father's son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envied Al's love for his parents,'' says Bob Somerby, who,
like actor Tommy Lee Jones, roomed with Gore at Harvard. ``How many
kids moved back next door to their parents after college? He made
decisions because his father brought him up to honor certain
values, do things right, for right's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore says his dad was his mentor, a voice he heard and listened
to, the man who inculcated in him a sense of decorum, respect for
learning, for justice and for God.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Gore went home to bury his father. In his eulogy,
he said: ``The night he lost in 1970, he made me prouder still. He
said defeat may serve as well as victory to shake the soul and let
the glory out. Then he turned the old Southern segregationist
slogan on its head and declared, `The truth shall rise again.' ``
</P>
<P>
   If Al Gore can articulate who he is the same way he captured his
father's essence, style may just give way to substance.
</P>
<P>
   Upriver from Carthage, where the Cumberland River twists through
steep-sided valleys, Cordell Hull Lake rides high behind Cordell
Hull Dam, a concrete wonder built by the Army Corps of Engineers 60
years ago to tame the Cumberland.
</P>
<P>
   The lake holds a lesson for anyone trying to flesh out Al Gore.
It was conceived by powerful politicians more than a half century
ago, built in Tennessee with the latest technology and managed by
Washington professionals. Surface appearances do not divulge true
dimensions, and closer scrutiny is difficult because access is
limited.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a Washington dam or a Tennessee lake? Who cares? A more
important question is, how deep is it?
</P>
<P>
   America is about to find out.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Reid is a reporter for The Palm Beach Post.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
