<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-FUNERAL (San Francisco) _ This week, the family of Navy
Cmdr. John C. Mape, father of seven, will bury his remains _
identified late last year through DNA tests _ of the father who
perished in Vietnam in 1966. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   EVIL-TIMES (San Francisco) _ The deadly rampage at a Colorado
high school raises anew the debate about whether evil is rooted in
the human fiber or whether environmental influence accounts for its
malignant surges. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   GANG-TUTOR (Oakland, Calif.) _ Chandy May, 30, once peddled
drugs as a gang leader in Oakland. Today, May helps tutor troubled
young people from area high schools. By MICHIYO YAMADA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-HOTEL (San Francisco) _ Starwood Hotels and Resorts
Worldwide Inc. of New York, the world's largest hotel group, is
building the first new version of its W hotels here. Starwood,
which also owns the Sheraton and Westin brands, says it aims to
reinvent the business hotel with the W brand, which it is rolling
out nationally this year. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE-OFFICE (San Francisco) _ A business takes orders through
its front office. It delivers the order through its back office.
But a lot needs to happen between the front and back offices. San
Francisco-based CSE Systems Corp. is targeting that no- man's land
_ what it dubs the ``middle office'' _ with a new software product
_ the Cibon. By JOHN BERGER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SWEEPS (Albany, N.Y.) _ It's television ``sweeps'' season,
which means death, destruction and mayhem on the tube before
viewers abandond the network re-runs for cable. This season is
especially noteworthy because several longtime shows will be
leaving the air for the great syndication run in the sky. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Dear Pfizer: This is a tall
order, but the need is great. Could your biotech engineers start
working on Viagra for the psyche? You've pumped pizzazz back into
thousands of men with erectile dysfunction, how about giving
millions of us something to cure impotence of the soul? By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) It won't be easy, but steps need
to be taken to avoid another Littleton, Colo. Among them: Stricter
gun controls; urging the owners of the new media to develop
standards of restraint; and encouraging children to share with
teachers and parents impressions about their peers that they have
naturally enough kept to themselves. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-FRAUD (San Francisco) _ President Clinton has urged
Congress to approve legislation to stop telemarketers from
victimizing the elderly. Now, what can be done to protect the
elderly from mail fraud? By DAVID STEINBERG.
</P>
