<HEADER>
A3279 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISABELLE-HUPPERT-INTE     04-26 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISABELLE-HUPPERT-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISABELLE HUPPERT'S RISQUE BUSINESS 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent by mail or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By DANIEL PEREZ 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Isabelle Huppert is stumped. She just can't figure out why she's
occasionally referred to in the press as ``the little French
mouse.'' But if she'd seen herself sitting in the front row of
January's Yves Saint Laurent couture show, just one seat down from
Catherine Deneuve, she might have some idea.
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve looked like a true Movie Star, with a sweep of
salon-perfect blonde hair riding high above her head, a perfectly
fitted couture suit and a pair of Jackie O-style sunglasses
protecting her from the barrage of flashbulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Huppert, meanwhile, was slouching in a chair, nervously touching
her stringy red hair and shuffling her sneakers as she waited for
the lights to go down, for the photographers' gaze to finally shift
from her to the catwalk.
</P>
<P>
   While the timeless Deneuve may be the First Lady of French
cinema, Huppert is not far behind, just a rung above contemporaries
like Isabelle Adjani and Sophie Marceau. Yet she's much more of an
enigma than France's other leading ladies _ even to her own
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   Not unlike Garbo, to whom she has occasionally been compared,
Huppert prefers to be alone, sidestepping the spotlight and
avoiding the press as much as she can. Almost nothing is known
about her private life, other than the fact that she's married and
has three children. She's been heard to say that being photographed
without permission is like being raped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered that people compare me to Garbo,'' says Huppert.
``I don't think anyone can reach the point of mysteriousness she
has, but I'm learning.''
</P>
<P>
   She's doing a fine job. Few people have managed to maintain such
a high degree of both exposure and anonymity. In a little over 25
years, Huppert has made more than 50 films, working repeatedly with
such directors as Jean-Luc Godard and Claude Chabrol. Her
best-known movies include Diane Kurys' ``Entre Nous,'' and
Chabrol's ``Madame Bovary'' and ``La Ceremonie.'' Her latest film,
``The School of Flesh'' (``L'Ecole de la Chair''), which recently
opened in the United States, was publicized on nearly every bus
stop in Paris with a large poster of Huppert's face.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when she enters a Left Bank cafe for an interview,
crossing a crowded room to her table in a dark corner, not one head
turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some people _ more in America than here _ go after the
attention,'' she says. ``They pretend to hate it, but when they
don't get it, it kills them.''
</P>
<P>
   Over tea, Huppert projects the aloofness and mild arrogance that
we often expect from serious French actresses. She's curious about
her reputation in the United States, but despite having appeared in
several American films _ most notably in Michael Cimino's critical
disaster ``Heaven's Gate'' _ she's wary of being lumped together
with her American counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always surprised by how many American actresses,
particularly on the West Coast, aren't really actresses,'' she
says. ``It's not true for all of them, of course, but I feel like
French actresses are given more opportunities to be introspective.
We work more with intimacy and personal reflection. But cinema
shouldn't be the same all over the world, I guess. American cinema
should have its own identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Huppert is not one of those one of those Europeans who's eager
to amass American screen credits. When she does chase after a role
in the United States, it's likely to be in a small independent film
that's as complex as the those she makes in France.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, she wrote an admiring letter to director Hal Hartley
and ended up with the lead in ``Amateur.''
</P>
<P>
   When the letter first arrived, though, Hartley's assistant
didn't know who Huppert was. And while some critics suggest that
Huppert isn't as well-known in the United States as her less
talented French colleagues because ``Heaven's Gate'' was such a
colossal flop, she is quick to refute that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say that it neither helped nor hurt me,'' she says.
``Look, maybe it did change my destiny, I don't know. Yes, it was a
pure failure, but it's not an issue for me. I came over to do one
film, not to stay for my entire career.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The School of Flesh,'' Huppert plays Dominique, a chic,
successful fashion executive. When she meets a handsome young
ne'er-do-well who works as both a bartender and a bisexual hustler,
she begins pursuing him intently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about how passion affects this woman,'' says Huppert, who
turned 44 in March.
</P>
<P>
   Huppert spent weeks discussing the character with director
Benoit Jacquot before shooting began. Jacquot, who directed the
actress in 1980s ``Wings of a Dove,'' says he didn't even have a
second choice for the role of Dominique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what she wants to express,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The actress, says Jacquot, takes an intensely thoughtful
approach to both her life and her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``She uses her face as a landscape,'' he says. ``She can change
it like it's some kind of psychological climate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacquot, an old friend of Huppert's, also understands the
actress's intense need for privacy _ even on the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Filming for her is like a night of paradise,'' he says. ``It's
like she's sleeping and she hopes she'll dream right. She's acting
as she's dreaming. Sometimes when I yell `cut,' it's like I'm
waking her up. This is because acting is extremely private for her.
Isabelle has two private lives: the one in front of the camera and
the one in real life.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The School of Flesh,'' Dominique wields all of the social
and financial power. She plays sugarmama to her young boyfriend,
giving him an allowance and choosing his wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reversal of the classic roles,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But Huppert believes the film is a reflection of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older women with younger men are much more accepted now,'' she
says. ``Plus, I think women are looking younger and younger now.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress isn't the least bit concerned that the older she
gets, the fewer roles there will be for her. ``I'm not fighting
aging at all,'' she says. ``Look at Catherine Deneuve. She's always
more and more beautiful. She makes you feel like you want to get
older.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her own public persona, Huppert manages to look on the
bright side. After giving the matter some thought, she flashes her
first smile of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably better to be called a French mouse,'' she says,
``than to be called a French snake, or a French cow.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Daniel Perez is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this special one-shot feature _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
