<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3283 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV02-NY     04-26 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD-EDGED AND CUTTING EDGE ARE NERVOUS NO MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 2)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Everyone in this room,'' wrote Mark Leyner in The New York
Times, quoting a composite TV network executive, ``is committed to
developing adventurous,  &UR; edgy &LR;  material.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Risque Reading'' was the headline in The Wall Street Journal,
subheaded ``Books for young adults take on  &UR; edgier &LR;  themes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a move toward more  &UR; edgy &LR;  comedy,'' Will Miller, the
therapist-comedian, sadly told New Jersey's Record about a shift in
audience tastes, ``and I was just this yuppie with no  &UR; edge &LR;  at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   A new sense of an old word was born about a decade ago, went
through its nonce phase, has gained vogue status and bids fair to
shove the old sense over the edge of the linguistic cliff.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the '80s, when someone said, ``I feel  &UR; edgy &LR; ,'' the
response was a soothing, ``There, there _ nothing to be nervous
about.'' Or if you heard, ``The boss seems a little  &UR; edgy &LR;  today,''
you were not likely to hit him up for a raise.
</P>
<P>
   The adjective meant ``nervous, irritable, apprehensive'' _ three
different but similar states of tension _ derived from the phrase
 &UR; on edge &LR; . The metaphor was that of a cliff, with a person standing
at the very brink, or grimacing in irritation, showing teeth  &UR; on
edge &LR; , or balanced precariously in a narrow space, as on a  &UR; razor's
edge &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   That nail-nibbling sense began as the adverb  &UR; edgily &LR; , in an
1837 letter by Cardinal Henry Manning: ``Newman did not like my
joking letter. He answered rather  &UR; edgily &LR;  and defensively.''
Novelists moved it ahead as World War I began: ``Do you mind if I
come in here for a little?'' Rudyard Kipling had a character plead.
``I'm a bit  &UR; edgy &LR; .'' In 1915, in ``The 39 Steps,'' John Buchan
wrote: ``Then I could see that he began to get  &UR; edgy &LR;  again. He
listened for little noises.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally,  &UR; edgy &LR;  meant ``sharp,'' as in this 1775 use:
``Walking over broken rocks, either ragged, or cleft, or  &UR; edgy &LR; .''
The poet Leigh Hunt wrote in 1820 of a razor, ``How cold, how
 &UR; edgy &LR; , how hard!'' This is the sense that is making a comeback on
the cusp of three vogue phrases.
</P>
<P>
   One is  &UR; hard-edged &LR; , first used ringingly by the novelist J.R R.
Tolkien in 1954: ``Long slopes they climbed, dark,  &UR; hard-edged &LR; 
against the sky.'' In Britain in the early '60s it was used as the
name of a school of abstract art _ crisp, geometric and
unemotional.
</P>
<P>
   Its severe certainty was picked up in 1976 by the New York Times
correspondent John Darnton, who extended the metaphor with ``there
is no  &UR; hard-edged &LR;  sense of impending disaster in Rhodesia.'' That
meaning goes somewhat beyond ``sharp.'' Darnton, who is now The
Times' culture editor, recalled, ``I used it to mean `clear-cut'
but with a sense of violence behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   A generation later, Sen. Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, searching
vainly for consensus during the Year of Monica, shook his head and
said, ``The partisan differences have become  &UR; hard-edged &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   A more likely source of the current sense of  &UR; edgy &LR;  is  &UR; leading
edge &LR; , which the OED notes since 1877 has meant the forward side of
a moving object, like the blade of a propeller screw or a wing, and
the more recent  &UR; cutting edge &LR; . This has replaced the old  &UR; state of
the art &LR; . Funny how that popular phrase fell into desuetude; it was
once right out there  &UR; on the cusp &LR; , which has also been overtaken
by events.
</P>
<P>
   Not even  &UR; modern &LR;  stays modern, as  &UR; postmodern &LR;  becomes passe.
It's hard to keep up with, much less stay ahead of, words that
define a state of being ahead. You think that  &UR; leading edge &LR;  is all
that  &UR; with-it &LR; ? Jesse Sheidlower of Random House pointed me to this
use of computer jargon in a 1996 Wired magazine article:
``experience that combines  &UR; bleeding-edge &LR;  graphics with old-school
gameplay.'' See what happens when you play around with  &UR; cutting
edges &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   Here we are, then, with the old-new  &UR; edgy &LR; . Its first use is
derived from  &UR; hard-edged &LR; , connoting ``with an attitude.'' Jim Lowe
of Merriam-Webster has a citation from the May 1990 Elle magazine
in which Mark Schapiro writes of the white rappers Peter Nash and
Michael Berrin as ``brazen,  &UR; edgy &LR;  street poets.''
</P>
<P>
   For the sense of the new  &UR; edgy &LR;  that is more upbeat _
``innovative, precedent-shattering'' or ``avant-garde,'' as the
French have been saying for about 150 years (you'd think they'd
find a new expression for this) _ the earliest citation I can find
is this November 1993 use in The Orlando Sentinel in which Andy
Meisler, a reporter, quotes the animator John Kricfalusi about
fuddy-duddies at Nickelodeon: ``The network hated all the  &UR; edgy &LR; 
stuff. That's why it's not on the  &UR; cutting edge &LR;  anymore. Which is
too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as you read this, that sense is endangered in these
high-velocity semantics. The finger-snapping reader will note a
recent citation at the top of this column from The Wall Street
Journal suggesting a meaning of  &UR; risque &LR; , French for ``off-color,
verging on indecent.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mushnik, a columnist for The New York Post and TV Guide,
says: `` &UR; Edgy &LR;  is a euphemism for `profane.' It's a dodge for
`obscene.' We've seen the steady inclusion of words with sexual
connotations or profanity on television and radio. Now this
language is no longer described as `colorful' but as `edgy.' It's a
word in the pop culture that means `vile.' It's a very convenient
little word,  &UR; edgy &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this hottest of vogue words is that it means
(a) confrontational, (b) ultramodern and (c) lewd or profane.
Because the meaning is in flux, I don't use the word; it makes me
feel, as nervous Nellies used to say,  &UR; edgy &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3290 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-GRADUATION-KA     04-26 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-GRADUATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RITE OF SPRING RETURNS WITH THE COMMENCEMENT SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: Each year since way back when Strom Thurmond was
barely a decade or two past retirement age, Mr. Tammeus _ for
reasons now thankfully lost in the mists of history _ has written a
model graduation speech for real speakers to crib. Here is this
year's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patriots and traitors, volunteers and draftees: We gather today
under the storm clouds of war but with hope for peace still in our
spleens (or, anyway, one of those internal organs). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As we think about those two great imposters, war and peace, I am
reminded of what the mortal Winston Churchill said in a speech in
1949, three years after his Iron Curtain speech (you could look it
up). For those of you under 25, Churchill once was prime minister
of England. And England is a country in Europe sometimes known as
Britain and sometimes as the United Kingdom, even though it's now a
Queendom and not very united. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Little did we guess,'' Churchill said, ``that what has been
called the Century of the Common Man would witness as its
astounding feature more common men killing each other with greater
facilities than any other five centuries together in the history of
the world.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, your work is cut out for you if your generation
plans to top that. But you can do it. War, it turns out, is a many
unsplendored thing. Peace, by contrast, sometimes is a wolf in
wolf's clothing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For proof, look at what one of Churchill's predecessors, Neville
Chamberlain, said in 1938 after returning from negotiating with the
Nazis in Munich: ``We have preserved peace in our time.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some peace. At best it was what Cicero called ``Peace with
dishonor,'' and lasted barely an hour. (No, not Cicero, Ill., but
Cicero the great Roman statesman, orator and writer. Lordy, lordy,
didn't you learn anything here?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The semi-famous Irish playwright George Farquhar may have gotten
it right in Act 5 of ``Love and a Bottle'' when he wrote: ``'Tis
safest making peace with sword in hand.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farquhar, whose name is hard to say once in a row quickly, much
less three or eight times, chose the word sword because he lived
mostly in the 17th century, prior to either the Uzi submachine gun
or the Apache helicopter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   War, as we all have heard, is hell. Actually, Gen. William
Tecumseh Sherman, to whom that line is attributed, said war ``is
all hell.'' But editors often are skittish about overusing the word
``all'' in a family newspaper, so the phrase generally is reported
without the all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this time of loosened standards of profanity, it remains to
be seen whether editors printing reports of this stunning speech
will allow the fullness of this next illuminating quote about war
from Gen. George S. Patton to see the light of day: ``The object of
war is not to die for your country. It's to make the other poor
bastard die for his.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the brighter students among you may wish to investigate
how the papers handle that quote. Maybe you could parlay that
research into a graduate degree. Many degrees, after all, have been
awarded on much flimsier research. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, then, what have we learned today about war and peace that
will help you advance in your profession, fatten your 401(k)
accounts and retire early? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the 15th century Christian ascetic Thomas Hemerken, known
as Thomas A(CQ) Kempis, said it best: ``We should have much peace
if we would not busy ourselves with sayings and doings of others.''
Of course, the down side is we would have fewer graduation
speeches. Now THERE'S finally something you can applaud. Thanks.
Now get on over to law school. Selah. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
