<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORY-OF-TULIPS-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR SEARCHES WORLD FOR TULIP LORE
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of a field of tulips
 Includes a 180-word sidebar
 By SUSAN McCLURE 
 World rights (except Chicago) 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Behind a disguise of vibrant-colored petals, the tulip has a
checkered past that is all but forgotten today. Other bulbs such as
daffodils have been immortalized in legends while roses have
reigned over the Victorian language of flowers. But tulips have
made men into millionaries and then broken them to paupers just as
quickly.
 &HT;    The fascinating tale of the tulip is told in Anna Pavord's ''The
Tulip, the Story of a Flower That Has Made Men Mad'' (1999, $35,
Bloomsbury Publishing, New York). Pavord chronicles tulips, past
and present, in over 400 pages of intriguing text illustrated with
beautiful botanical prints and paintings.
 &HT;    Pavord was drawn to the tulip innocently enough when her husband
gave her a beautiful cream-colored tulip, a peace offering after
returning from a boys-only trip. Intrigued by its stunning beauty,
she shopped around for other bulbs and then began digging into
tulip history. Soon she was hooked.
 &HT;    For seven years she took every opportunity to travel around the
world, peeking into libraries and museums to find tulip history and
gleanings.
 &HT;    ''I wanted to know how the story of the tulip ended up. It was
full of extraordinary adventures that kept me going,'' Pavord said.
''I gathered all kinds of material in notebooks and boxes for my
own enjoyment. I ended up having such a fantastic time, I thought
others would like it too, and that's how the book came about.''
 &HT;    Pavord begins ''The Tulip'' with a tale of hunting for wild
tulips in Crete. In a neighborhood bar, she coaxed locals with
brandy to help her find the haunts of the mauve-purple Cretan
tulip. The drinks led to a ride to a country church and chance
meeting that served her goal.
 &HT;    ''...the small boy, left outside sitting on a rock, had hijacked
a passer-by and showed him the picture of the flower that I was
looking for. 'Omalos,' he said triumphantly as we emerged.
'Omalos', he said again, pointing at the picture and then somewhere
to the west, way over the horizon,'' Pavord writes.
 &HT;    Omalos was a mountain town on a sheep-nibbled plain where Tulipa
bakeri flowered on olive terraces fenced to keep woolly grazers
out.
 &HT;    ''They  Cretan tulips  were growing in thick, poor grassland,
their shiny leaves poking out from sheaves of anemones, with
orchids thrown in for good measure...This was the first time I had
seen tulips growing in the wild. I knew how Galahad must have felt
when he finally caught up with the Grail,'' Pavord wrote.
 &HT;    In the early 1600s, wild species from Turkey were imported into
Europe and, like any new flower, enjoyed for their novelty. But
when ordinary red tulips began changing _ taking on sharply-edged
yellow and cream flames or feathers, tulip growing took a more
serious turn.
 &HT;    While we now know these markings were caused by a virus disease,
in past centuries they seemed miraculous. Conoisseurs would pay
extraordinary prices for flame-flowered bulbs, which due to the
disease, multiplied slowly, limited the supply, and generated much
demand.
 &HT;    ''For hundreds of years, growers were puzzled by this remarkable
trick. Alchemists tried to transform base metals into gold, but
tulips made seemingly spontaneous transformations instantly,''
Pavord said.
 &HT;    Growers even went to such lengths as to lay powdered paint in
varying colors on the tulip bed in hopes the bulbs would pick them
up. Those most successful in generating color breaks often grew
their bulbs near peach orchards, where unknowingly, they submitted
them to attack by the peach potato aphid, the primary virus
carrier.
 &HT;    ''The virus was like a joker in the tulip bed; no one could
control its workings,'' Pavord said.
 &HT;    The thrill, and capital gain, that came from each exotic new
bicolor tulip created a frenzy in France and, 20 years later, made
an even bigger stir in Holland. In 1623 and 1633, certain fabled
bulbs were selling for seven to 100 times the average annual wage.
 &HT;    Wealthy barons, tulip growers, and some common folk invested
lavishly in tulips, hoping for a color break that would make them
richer.
 &HT;    The number of tulip growers naturally expanded, which marked the
beginning of the end of this tulip frenzy. By the mid-1600s there
were more sellers than buyers in the tulip game. Bulbs were
liquidated at fractions of their earlier prices and fortunes, once
counted in bins of bulbs, evaporated.
 &HT;    ''It was inevitable that tulipomania would be followed by an
equally intense hatred of the flower. The professor of botany at
Leiden grew so to loathe them that he attacked them savagely
wherever they stood, thwacking them with his cane,'' Pavord writes.
 &HT;    In 1880, a bulb breeder developed the Darwin hybrids,
long-stemmed tulips in plain colors used as wallpaper flowers for
massing in beds. People bought them by the thousands, making tulips
a common favorite among ordinary people.
 &HT;    Dutch breeders, who have monopolized the industry since then,
have systematically eliminated the virus from modern stocks by
developing resistant varieties. Now bicolor and fringed tulips have
been made to resemble early flamed types, but are very coarse
replications, Pavord said.
 &HT;    When it comes to tulips, it's intriguing to learn, they are much
more than just another pretty face.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Sidebar: Meet Anna Pavord
 &HT;    Anna Pavord's books, including ''The Tulip,'' ''The Border
Book,'' ''The New Kitchen Garden'' and ''Foliage,''
characteristically blend history, vivid descriptive writing, and
intriguing ideas. They go realms beyond ordinary how-to writing.
 &HT;    Pavord was the product of passionate gardening parents, as are
many residents of the British Isles. Once she had her own patch of
ground, childhood gardening experiences shaped her adult life.
 &HT;    ''You can achieve such wonderful things by setting a plant in
the garden,'' Pavord said. ''Gardening is extraordinary in that it
never leaves you at a loss for something to do.''
 &HT;    After first working as newspaper feature writer and a film
maker, Pavord began writing a garden column for the British
Independent newspaper 12 years ago.
 &HT;    ''The paper was brand new and I was expected to write a column
that would draw everyone in. It had to be a good read,'' Pavord
said.
 &HT;    Presently Pavord contributes to Country Life, Country Living,
Elle Decoration, and she is associate editor of the British
magazine Gardens Illustrated.
 &HT;     c.1999 Susan McClure   (This feature originally ran in
<TEXT>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Susan McClure is a free-lance writer based in Chicago.) &LR;
</P>
