<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3408 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTS     04-26 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of home appliances
 By BOB NORBERG 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the clock on the wall rolls past midnight to the year 2000,
don't expect fireworks. The clock will be just fine, as will
virtually every other appliance found in most homes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite appliances relying more and more on computer chips to
brew the coffee before you get up, water the lawns and plants, tape
TV shows and regulate home heating, few will have problems
associated with the Year 2000 computer bug, and any problems that
do crop up are expected to be annoyances at worst.
</P>
<P>
   The computer chips in appliances simply don't care what year it
is, according to technicians, repair workers, manufacturers and
consumer appliance associations.
</P>
<P>
   ''People will still be able to watch TV, still be able to play
back their VCR, still be able to use the cell phone,'' said Jeff
Joseph of the Consumer Electronics Manufacturing Association in
Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are chips in every appliance with digital displays, but
these don't have any date codes, so they won't be affected,'' said
Pat Montague, service manager of TeeVax in Santa Rosa, Calif.,
where appliances are sold and repaired.
</P>
<P>
   And where problems do crop up, such as in older VCRs or
camcorders, users will just get a wrong date, requiring a simple
reset. The device itself will continue to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would only stop you from doing a pre-programmed recording
when you are not at home,'' said Darin Scott, a technician at Alpha
Electronics in Santa Rosa. ''You would just have to reset your
clock. Some VCRs are date-sensitive, some aren't. You would have to
take it on a model-by-model basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Year 2000 problem _ also known as the Millennium Bug _ is
the inability of some computers and computer programs to recognize
the year 2000 because of the past practice of programmers using
two-digit year codes - ''99'' instead of ''1999'' _ to save
precious memory space.
</P>
<P>
   Some older computers, for instance, will think it is Jan. 1,
1900, not Jan. 1, 2000, because of the way the date is stored in
separate areas of the computer, while software programs that use
dates to perform computations, such as amortization programs, will
produce incorrect results unless they use four digits to denote
years.
</P>
<P>
   Most consumer appliances and electronics have been manufactured
with the year 2000 in mind since 1988, Joseph said. And in any
case, the chips that commonly are integrated into appliances are
programmed for cycles, whether the cycle is 24 hours, seven days, a
month or even decades.
</P>
<P>
   Microprocessors are in use in virtually every powered home
product, including refrigerators, ovens, coffee makers, microwaves,
washers and dryers, VCRs, TVs, camcorders, watches and even
automobiles. The more bells and whistles the unit has, the more
likely it has microprocessors controlling its functions.
</P>
<P>
   But the computer chip function doesn't necessarily have a year
programmed in, making it unlikely that the chip will just stop
functioning at the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Thermostats that regulate the temperature, lowering it at night,
usually have a weeklong cycle, unless it is an industrial
application, where holidays have to be taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   They are not date-sensitive _ the day of the week may matter,
but not the year.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, alarm clocks and digital displays on ovens and
microwaves care what the hour is, but not the day, while
controllers for outdoor watering systems care about the hour and
day, but not the month or year.
</P>
<P>
   ''By luck, all of our products are Y2K-compliant,'' said Richard
Macy of Rainbird Sprinklers in Glendora, Calif. ''They only count
the days, from seven to 14.''
</P>
<P>
   Digital watches are programmed with dates covering 40 years,
even though the liquid crystal displays usually solidify long
before then, and calculators are programmed to reach the year 2099.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all use a long date format,'' said Ted Grier, a technician
with Casio in Little Ferry, N.J. ''From 1975 on, you won't have a
problem until the year 2019 or beyond. But the liquid crystal
display only lasts 12 to 14 years before the gelatinous crystal
won't hold an electrical charge. LCDs don't last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Automobiles now commonly use microprocessors in black boxes that
control the air-fuel mixture; monitor sensors for the oil, water
and fuel pressure; and set the clock, but have no functions that
depend on the date.
</P>
<P>
   It's an engine management system that allows some cars to go
100,000 miles before a tune-up and drive as well at sea level as at
6,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a non-issue,'' said Dave Whitgob of San Francisco,
project manager of the California State Automobile Association's
Car Care Plus repair center in Santa Clara. ''They don't know if
it's 1999 or 1899 and they don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario, Whitgob said, is that some luxury cars
will have a clock with an incorrect date.
</P>
<P>
   Most manufacturers have information posted on their company Web
sites, addressing any potential issues.
</P>
<P>
   Some Nokia 9000 cellular phones, for instance, will have a
time-stamp problem after Dec. 31, and the Model 9000 Communicator
will not recognize Feb. 29, so it should be kept plugged in on that
day to keep it from going into a sleep mode, according to the
information on the Nokia Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ''But from a consumer standpoint, overall, they don't have to
worry,'' said Ann Saybolt of the Consumer Electronics Manufacturing
Association.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bob Norberg writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.) &LR;
</P>
