   -- Intense strength training might offer another option to
back-pain patients looking to dodge spinal surgery, according to a
new report. (BACK-STRENGTH-MED)
</P>
<P>
   --Young brass-instrument musicians who feel weakness in their
facial muscles may owe it to more than overexertion. In those who
have a heart defect called a patent foramen ovale, the pressure of
playing may up their already-increased risk for stroke, according
to researchers at the University of Munster in Germany.
(TRUMPET-STROKE-MED)
</P>
<P>
   -- The simple act of watching the mirror image of a healthy limb
may nudge a stroke-damaged limb back into action, according to
California brain researchers. (STROKE-MIRROR-MED)
</P>
<P>
   -- Allowing patients to return to work less than two weeks after
a certain type of spinal-disc surgery is just as safe as the
standard months-long recovery, new research suggests.
(BACK-SURGERY-MED)
