<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
April 27, 1999. If you have any questions, please call The Star's
News Desk at (816) 234-4720.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEB (Washington D.C.) _ Presidential contenders for the first
time are waging political combat on the Internet. By David
Goldstein. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   OLDDRIVE (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Evelyn White, 84, has driven
almost every day since she got her license as a teen-ager. And she
never had an accident _ until one chilly day last December. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White didn't see the pickup as she turned left into traffic. The
crash, which barely dented her fender, jolted her into reassessing
her own driving skills. ``I realized I couldn't hear so good
anymore and, well, little things are going wrong with my body,''
she said. ``It was time for me to stop driving.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While White reached that realization on her own, many of this
country's 17 million drivers over age 75 continue to drive long
after they can safely do so. Missouri has a new law that is
becoming a national role model for creating a safe, effective way
to get drivers with impairments (failing vision, etc.) off the
road. By Lee Kavanaugh. With photos. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   TRANS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Bill Graves will outline his
compromise highway plan today and is calling legislative leaders
together to do a little jawboning on the issue. The Legislature
reconvenes Wednesday, and highways is the biggest cloud hanging
over the session. By John L. Petterson. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTOR (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Growing numbers of doctors, both
employed by hospitals and in private practice, are looking to
unionization as a means to gain more clout. The move coincides with
a growing feeling among the nation's doctors that their power to
make decisions and their ability to relate to patients have been
eroded by cost-conscious managed care companies and government
agencies. By Julius A. Karash (Business desk) with ILLUSTRATION.
Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   PSC (Kansas City, Mo.) _ The staff of the Missouri Public
Service Commission issues recommendations on the proposed Western
Resources-KCP&AMP;L buyout. By Steve Everly (Business desk) Story will
move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Health Midwest names Joseph
Hiersteiner as senior vice president and general counsel. By Julius
A. Karash. (Business desk) Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
