<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR A SHAKEDOWN OF SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The awesome impact of the murderous rampage at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., is measured not only in
the devastation visited on parents who suffered the loss of their
children, and the family bereft of a father, but also upon the rest
of us.
</P>
<P>
   Students of all ages are once again confronted by the insight
that their school, the place that ought to be as secure for them as
their own homes, in an instant can mutate into a pit of terror.
</P>
<P>
   As the wrenching poignancy of dying young is once more
memorialized at the burials of the dead children and their teacher,
the nation searches for ways to prevent the recurrence of another
Littleton. That is just what happened after earlier deadly violence
in schools.
</P>
<P>
   About the only sure thing that can be concluded in the
once-again desperate search for answers to the incomprehensible and
the solutions that would prevent it ever happening again, is that
these kinds of killings are a creature of our own times.
</P>
<P>
   They did not happen until relatively recently. And recently they
have taken place with an episodic regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to comprehend what it is about ourselves that abets these
periodic outbursts of irrational violence is as natural as it is
frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   The existence of cliques within schools, which often lead to a
hierarchy of winners and losers, resulting in the alienation of
those ostracized, is nothing peculiar to our day. Yet this was one
ingredient cited to explain the causes of the Littleton massacre.
But in the distant past, when the same kind of harassment took
place, it did not engender the violent response of Littleton, if
that is what it was.
</P>
<P>
   Another causal factor is deemed to be the relative ease with
which children lay their hands on guns. Although the gun culture
has been a strong theme throughout American history, what is
different today is the vigor with which guns are being marketed by
an industry intensely interested in is own growth.
</P>
<P>
   When ease of acquisition is added to the drug wars fought by
rival gangs in our cities, the consequence in our own time was a
magnitude of everyday violence that was portrayed with regularity
by the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Violence came to be a much larger part of the national
background.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the matter of violence in the media, apart from the
news. Violence in films has existed as long as films themselves.
What is the product of our own times is the technology that permits
violence to be rendered in a bloody verisimilitude previously not
possible. Audiences flock to violent productions, many of which are
targeted to teen-age taste.
</P>
<P>
   The vexing question is how much these entertainments respond to
a basic taste versus how much they help to cultivate it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, television has provided the means for a much greater
distribution of programs marked by violence, and you don't have to
leave your home or pay an admission's price to partake of it.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Internet has extended the ubiquity of violence
with its cultivation of games devoted to it. At least one of the
perpetrators of the Littleton rampage appeared to have been a
devotee of these gothic and virulent pastimes.
</P>
<P>
   But, as has been pointed out, Japanese children are no less
addicted to these fiendish games, yet that country's murder and
mayhem rate is much less than our own.
</P>
<P>
   What this comparison suggests is that American culture itself
compounds media violence in all its forms that in other countries
and their societies registers a lesser malignant impact.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet has gone a step further than merely providing a
new venue catering to already developed taste. It is also the
source of devilish instructions that provide the know-how for the
construction of the kinds of bombs that were taken into Columbine
High School.
</P>
<P>
   That is a function of the new media, which is a revolutionary
new way permitting individuals to communicate without having to
rely on the traditional venues of newspapers, radio or television.
At the same time, the governors that are more or less in place in
the traditional media, that would forswear the dissemination of
such information, are not a factor on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the discussion it comes down to this: There is no
one cause or one remedy for this plague of violence. Yet that
should not keep us from trying to cope, even if we know from the
outset that the solution will be only partial and possibly
temporary.
</P>
<P>
   For openers, schools should be protected with devices to screen
for guns.
</P>
<P>
   Stricter gun controls obviously are necessary, and public
support appears to be building for their imposition.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the new media need to develop standards of
restraint that have evolved in the other news media.
</P>
<P>
   Children should be encouraged to share with teachers and parents
impressions about their peers that they have naturally enough kept
to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The great and proper concern is that anyone who manifests any
differences from the established norm will be unfairly fingered.
But some modality should be devised in the schools to sort out
run-of-the-mill alienation from the violent kind.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tricky undertaking, which needs much study. It is
merited only because to leave matters as they are is intolerable.
Too many children have died at the hands of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large at the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
