<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-FRAUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS TO PROTECT ELDERLY FROM BUSINESS SCAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID STEINBERG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President Clinton recently appealed to Congress
for legislation to stop telemarketers from victimizing the elderly
with fraudulent business deals that he said pose ``the greatest
threat that many older Americans face.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans lose an estimated $40 billion per year to telephone
scam artists, the president said, adding that more than half the
victims are over 50.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to propose federal legislation that would impose
criminal charges on those who victimize the elderly with
``retirement plan rip-offs'' and would toughen penalties against
individuals convicted of stealing pension and retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   These forms of elder abuse and victimization have been reported
frequently in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Aging, the magazine formerly published by the federal
Administration on Aging, reported crimes against the elderly
committed by family members who steal Social Security checks from
their parents and grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation, Clinton said, would also impose
criminal charges against nursing home operators suspected of
neglecting or abusing their patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's long overdue,'' said Patricia L. McGinniss, executive
director of the California Advocates for Nursing Home Reform in San
Francisco. ``Owners and operators of these facilities should be
responsible for providing what they promise. They're often most
concerned with the bottom line. Elderly people may spend all they
have in the belief they will get proper care.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope the president's proposed legislation to protect the
elderly against fraud also targets operators of lotteries whose
mailings promise million-dollar winnings with ``no purchase
necessary.'' Gullible elders clutter their homes with trinkets,
fake jewelry, magazines and unread books they buy to get ``express
handling'' of their entries in ``no purchase necessary'' contests.
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss recounted the story of an elderly man who went to her
office to say he was going to take his wife out of a nursing home
and move into a new house he could buy with the money he had won in
lottery. He had the letter that informed him he had won.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to tell him to be careful,'' she said, ``and to read
the small print on the letter that announced he had won.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by the American Association of Retired
Persons, nearly one in five Americans reported being victims of a
major consumer fraud or swindle, and three in four reported a
``bad-buying'' experience during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted in November and December, found that 17
percent of Americans queried ``identified themselves as victims
when asked if they had been the subject of fraud or a major
consumer swindle. More than one in six linked their problems to
automobile purchases or repairs, and nearly one in 10 cited gross
over-charging or misleading advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Most complained about defective products.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Harvey, director of AARP's program development, said,
``Clearly, there's no level playing field for consumers.'' Most of
those surveyed express skepticism about the practices of specific
industries, including used-car dealers, telemarketers, telephone
companies and home contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Smith Sloan, another AARP official, said businesses should
avoid using fine print and use plain language.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, taking aim at telemarketers, said the legislation he
favors would give the Justice Department authority to terminate
telephone service for companies if federal agents find evidence of
an illegal telemarketing scheme or learn of plans to start one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will send a message to telemarketers: If you prey on
older Americans, we will cut off your phone lines and shut you
down,'' the president said in a recent radio broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Now, what can be done to protect the elderly from mail fraud?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
