<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEEPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY FOR TV ACTION: IT'S SWEEPS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nuclear disasters. Biblical floods. Stake
burnings. A sexually charged head of state.
</P>
<P>
   Death? Destruction? Armageddon?
</P>
<P>
   Nah, it's just May.
</P>
<P>
   Which means ``sweeps,'' critical for advertisers and the
networks who roll out their big movies and series finales before we
ditch the summer rerun season in favor of cable.
</P>
<P>
   And this sweeps season (the period when ratings are taken for
local stations), which actually starts Thursday and runs through
May 26, is especially noteworthy because several longtime shows
will be leaving the air for the great syndication run in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   First, the movie specials, many of them four-hour, two-part
blowouts:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Biblical flood: ``Noah's Ark.'' Film actors Jon Voight,
Mary Steenburgen and James Coburn come to television in this
four-hour drama on ABC May 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   _ The nuclear disaster: ``Atomic Train.'' Rob Lowe returns in
another two-part NBC movie, this one about an out-of-control train
loaded with nuclear weapons and waste making a beeline toward
Denver. May 16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   _ The stake burning: ``Joan of Arc.'' The story of the religious
French peasant girl who fought England airs in this four-hour drama
on CBS. May 16 and 18.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sexually charged head of state: It's not about President
Clinton, it's ``Cleopatra.'' Leonor Varela, Billy Zane and Timothy
Dalton star in yet another two-part drama about the Egyptian queen
and her paramours. On ABC, May 23-24.
</P>
<P>
   In a more up-to-date historical saga, NBC will air ``The Hunt
for the Unicorn Killer'' May 9-10. Kevin Anderson and Tom Skerritt
star in the story of former hippie Ira Einhorn, who was convicted
in absentia and is still fighting extradition in France. On NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Two divas of yesterday and today, Diana Ross and Brandy, team up
in ``Double Platinum'' May 16 on ABC. It is the story of a singer
who gave up her daughter but reunites with her years later after
she, too, enters show business.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we have a quickie NBC bio flick, ``The Jesse Ventura
Story,'' scheduled for May 23. Nils Allen Stewart stars as the pro
wrestler who is now governor of Minnesota. Along with these
one-shots are longtime shows leaving for good:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Home Improvement.'' After eight seasons, Tim Allen hangs up
his tool belt with a 90-minute episode on May 25.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Melrose Place.'' After seven years, the steamy nighttime
soap concludes on Fox on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Mad About You.'' They had a kid. That's killed other shows
before, but this one was on its last legs anyway. The Helen Hunt
and Paul Reiser sitcom ends its seven-season NBC run with a
one-hour episode on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Nanny.'' Six seasons of Fran Drescher is enough, trust
us. The one-hour finale airs May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is an old show making a cameo return. In ``Dr. Quinn,
Medicine Woman: The Movie,'' Jane Seymour and Joe Lando return to
the network that canceled the show last year, CBS, on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His e-mail address
is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
