<SLUG> BC-FUR-CHINA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUR IS FINDING FRIENDS IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL SHUKOVSKY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Seattle Fur Exchange, the largest wholesale
marketer of mink in North America, has found an unlikely market for
its luxurious metaphor for decadent capitalism: the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   That the Fur Exchange is capitalizing on China's astonishing
economic transformation is no surprise for a little-known
institution that is almost as old as Seattle itself. After more
than a century in the cyclic fashion business that began with the
Klondike gold rush, the Exchange has learned to jump on new
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Exchange has come a long way since 1898, when Alaskan
prospectors traded pelts for supplies with grocery merchants who
decided that the best way to make money from the furs was to start
their own auction house. From its first home on Seattle's bustling
waterfront, the early incarnation of the Exchange auctioned off
wild fur like lynx, wolf, beaver, badger, marten, mink, otter and
fox.
</P>
<P>
   The Exchange headquarters, along with tens of millions of
dollars in mink pelts dangling on metal racks in a huge
cold-storage warehouse, is tucked away in suburban Renton's
industrial flats. The building is kept purposefully nondescript to
make it difficult for anti-fur protesters to find. Even the phone
number is unlisted.
</P>
<P>
   People like J.P. Goodwin, executive director of the Coalition to
Abolish the Fur Trade and a vegetarian, professes that using
animals for fur is morally repugnant. Whenever the Fur Exchange
holds an auction, demonstrators are likely to be present.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Brennan, president of the American Legend Cooperative of
farmers, which owns the Exchange, said: ``We are very, very
careful. We have never had a demonstration that has stopped our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   While he acknowledges that animal rights activism hurt sales
beginning in the late 1980s, major fashion designers around the
world have been returning to fur.
</P>
<P>
   Three times a year _ in February, May and September _ buyers
from around the globe converge on Seattle to bid on the pelts sold
on consignment for the 280 fur farmer owners of the American Legend
Cooperative. Brennan said buyers from as many as 15 countries will
be here at the end of next month to bid on the approximately 1.2
million in pelts.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers, who frequently bring their families to watch the
auctions, are nervous and excited, Brennan said. ``Their whole
year's work comes down to one payday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mink breed in early March and give birth to kits in late April
and early May. The animals are killed, skinned and dried at the
farm in December. December, January and February is the busiest
time of year, as millions of pelts come in for grading, sizing and
storage. The full-time work force of 45 swells by 125 seasonal
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Ownership equity by the cooperative members is based on
percentage of total sales attributed to each fur farmer. While the
largest owner has about a 5 percent share, the average mink farmer
has a smaller operation with about 10,000 animals.
</P>
<P>
   Pelt prices are very volatile. At $27 per pelt on average, the
prices so far this year have been a little below the cost of
production, said Kurt Essman, a third-generation employee of the
Exchange who has worked there since 1979. ``It has been tough for a
lot of the farmers to make it over the years,'' Essman said. ``But
they've had good times, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Times were especially good in 1996, with sales of $125 million
and pelt prices about midway between $50 and $60. Prices dropped to
about $35 last season before reaching the current $27 mark. This
year, Brennan anticipates sales of between $90 million and $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian economic crisis is largely responsible for the drop in
prices, Brennan said. When the South Korean economy tanked in
November 1997, North American mink ranchers lost their biggest
buyer. ``One day Korea takes 70 percent of our goods, the next day
they are gone,'' said Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   The Exchange adjusted its grading and sizing to appeal to a
wider range of customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian economic crash last fall reverberated in Renton.
Russia was the world's biggest buyer of furs last year. Some
estimates suggest it consumed up to 40 percent of global ranch mink
and fox production. The Exchange predicts that even if the Russian
economy stabilizes, the fur market there will not recover and pelt
prices will be depressed.
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to spur sales, the Exchange maintains 11 offices
overseas in cities such as Tokyo, Seoul, London, Milan, Helsinki,
Stockholm and Moscow. The Exchange, the third largest fur
wholesaler in the world following auction houses in Copenhagen and
Helsinki, is competing hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been beating the backwoods in China and Russia,''
Brennan said. It's the nature of the business that ``one minute
we're hanging out at Versace eating caviar, and the next were in
Siberia eating dog meat.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brennan see lots of lo mein in his future. ``We had a record
Chinese buyer turnout in February,'' he said. He sees signs that
China, which used to import pelts for re-export as coats, is
beginning to develop a significant domestic retail market.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly telling was that many of the Chinese buyers were
domestic wholesalers and not manufacturing for export. While
Brennan does not have access to Chinese retail sales figures, he
said buyers ``are selling to local consumers in their region.'' And
the co-op, for a few years now, has been doing everything it can to
encourage the trend.
</P>
<P>
   And while it might seem incongruous in the land of Mao and the
Cultural Revolution, the fur farmers' co-op has been sponsoring
swanky fashion shows in China at places like the posh Portman
Shangri-La Hotel in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were telling us we were nuts to be there when we did
the first show,'' Brennan said. But that first event in the 1996-97
season was attended by 2,400 guests and received coverage on
Chinese television.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, there were department store fashion shows in five
Chinese cities over a three-week period. An American Legend
newsletter notes that ``each show drew a large attendance of
government officials and Chinese celebrities, as well as local
shoppers who came to witness the latest designs.'' The garments
were made of American Legend mink by Korean, Hong Kong and local
manufacturers. Each department store followed the shows with a
10-day sales program, Brennan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone can appreciate that the potential of the
Chinese market is mind-boggling,'' Brennan said. ``We're in a niche
market, and all we need is the upper echelon of consumers. I even
had a taxi driver in Beijing who had a leather bomber jacket with
mink trim. He said he paid about $600 U.S.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
