<SLUG> BC-WIRED-HOTEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIN UNVEILS NEW HOTEL CONCEPT FOR BUSINESS TRAVELER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The city's newest major hotel, the W San
Francisco, opens next month in the burgeoning culture and commerce
zone adjacent to the convention center and art museum.
</P>
<P>
   Sheathed in gray marble, with a three-story, glass-walled
octagonal lobby, sleek bar, cafe and restaurant, and guest rooms
created by designers from Banana Republic and Pottery Barn, the W
San Francisco is not the typical big-city hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Operated by Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide Inc. of New
York, the world's largest hotel group, the 30-story hotel is
nothing if not ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Starwood, which also owns the Sheraton and Westin brands
and operates 650 hotels in 70 countries, says it aims to reinvent
the business hotel with the W brand, which it is rolling out
nationally this year.
</P>
<P>
   To serve wired business travelers, W San Francisco executives
say the hotel will provide ``Internet and e-mail access at speeds
up to 100 times faster than through conventional modems. Each room
will have two phones, and for laptop hook-ups, a high-speed, direct
Ethernet modem connection.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is also designed to have the comfort of an upscale
home, with big, comfortable beds with goose-down comforters,
upholstered benches, dark wood desks and rich natural fabrics in
the guest rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first W Hotel opened in New York in December, the second
in Atlanta in February. They were both renovations. San Francisco
is third, and the first to be built from the ground up,'' said
Elias Assaly, the general manager of W San Francisco. W hotels are
also planned for Chicago, Boston, Washington and other major
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood is headed by Wall Street investor Barry Sternlicht, a
Harvard Business School graduate. Sternlicht, 38, has developed a
Donald Trump-like reputation as an artful dealmaker, but has not
yet operated a large number of hotels over a sustained period of
time.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred, Sternlicht is expanding, rolling out the W brand for
a niche market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see ourselves as going for the creative side of the
business market: high-tech entrepreneurs, entertainment industry
executives, journalists and those people looking for personalized
service,'' Assaly said.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel faces competition in San Francisco, which has 31,000
hotel rooms. The W is across from the Moscone Convention Center and
next door to the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art. The Marriott,
Sheraton Palace, a future Four Seasons and the Argent will all be
doing business in close proximity.
</P>
<P>
   Location, location, location is key, according to John Marks,
president of the San Francisco Convention and Visitors Bureau,
whose office is directly across the street from W.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the product and location, there's no reason to think W
will experience anything but success,'' Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco has not been in the mode of adding hotel rooms
in the last few years,'' he said. ``This represents the first hotel
of this magnitude to come in recently.''
</P>
<P>
   The W will have 423 rooms and cost $225-$250 per night, Assaly
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
