<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-ECHINACEA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR ECHINACEA MAY MAKE YOU SICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A study done at one of the nation's leading research
and teaching institutions for naturopathic medicine has shown that
taking the popular herbal supplement echinacea as a preventive
measure might make you sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manufacturer wanted to show that taking it could prevent
symptoms of respiratory illness,'' said Dr. Carlo Calabrese,
co-director of research at Bastyr University, which trains
naturopathic physicians and practitioners of alternative therapies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, the people who took it got sick more often,''
Calabrese said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over a six-month period, people who took echinacea had more
symptoms of respiratory infection than people who took a placebo.''
</P>
<P>
   Calabrese will present his findings on the popular herbal
supplement at the International Conference on Integrative Medicine,
which begins Friday in Seattle. The three-day conference has
attracted more than 100 speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Echinacea is perhaps the world's top-selling herbal supplement.
Many people ingest the herb to fight symptoms of colds or flu, and
countless others take it as a preventive measure to ward off
respiratory illness.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have hinted at the herb's lack of preventive
value, but no studies had yet shown anything to indicate it might
actually increase the risk of illness.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean that echinacea isn't effective for treating
symptoms once you're already sick, Calabrese emphasized. But it
does appear to be worse than useless as a preventive measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results were somewhat surprising,'' he said. ``The
take-home message is you should be very clear about what you're
doing with a botanical and not just take these things
willy-nilly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Integrative Medicine conference, featuring some of the
biggest names in the field of alternative or complementary
medicine, aims to do more than present a promotional smorgasbord of
anything and everything marketed as ``natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers want to chart a path for integrating different
therapeutic disciplines with traditional medicine based on solid
evidence of effectiveness and a common dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the term `alternative' medicine,'' said Bruce Takata,
conference director.
</P>
<P>
   What's needed, he said, ``is more and better information'' that
provides consumers with all legitimate options in health care.
</P>
<P>
   Calabrese, who is scheduled to speak Friday, is a pretty
hard-nosed guy for someone who dabbles in herbs. He demands
evidence before he'll endorse a therapy, which is why a major
European manufacturer of echinacea asked him to conduct a clinical
study at Bastyr on the herb's effectiveness for preventing
respiratory illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results certainly surprised the heck out of the sponsor,''
Calabrese said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's been in negotiations with the manufacturer, which
he declined to identify, over publication of his findings. The
company didn't want the results published, but Bastyr's research
policies assure publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are founded on the concept of science and evidence-based
natural medicine,'' said Dr. Joe Pizzorno, a naturopathic physician
and Bastyr's president. ``We have to publish our findings.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Pizzorno said, no manufacturer would be happy with
such results. He said the institution has lost other sponsors and
donors in the past because of studies that failed to support a
product's health claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to sell as much of their products as possible, of
course,'' Pizzorno said. Negative results can make companies less
willing to support research, he said, which is also true for the
pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Bastyr's credibility and mission of promoting scientific
evaluation of alternative therapies is more important than any one
funding source, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bastyr, based in the Seattle suburb of Kenmore, is the only
non-traditional institution in the United States to receive a
research grant from the National Institutes of Health's National
Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Pizzorno said the value of this week's Integrative Medicine
conference is in recognizing that there's a need for the
traditional and alternative medical camps to help consumers
separate the wheat from the chaff and incorporate the best aspects
of both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are trying to take more charge of their own health,''
said Dr. John Potter, head of cancer prevention at the Fred
Hutchinson Cancer Research Center. ``I don't believe in the
standard dichotomy of traditional medicine vs. alternative
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Look carefully enough at the history of medicine and the
development of pharmaceuticals, Potter said, and you'll often find
at its root the ancient use of herbs or a healing practice based on
folk wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Most people now accept that diet and health are linked, he said,
which is what he will be talking about at the Integrative Medicine
conference. But such acceptance hasn't translated into more people
living healthier lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``One-third of all cancer deaths today are caused by
inappropriate diets,'' Potter said. ``Smoking likely causes another
30 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply knowing that doesn't prevent cancer, he said. It's clear
that most people would rather take a pill than make the dietary and
lifestyle changes needed to prevent disease, Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect magic bullets to solve their problems,'' he
said, and much of our focus in biomedical science today is on
developing pills to treat illness rather than on encouraging
healthy lifestyle changes.
</P>
<P>
   Pizzorno agreed, noting that this mind-set extends into the
alternative medical community as well. Vitamins, herbal capsules
and food supplements, he said, are just more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of what's being pushed today is simply substituting
green drugs for synthetic drugs,'' Pizzorno said.
</P>
<P>
   Pizzorno and Potter said they hope the Integrative Medicine
conference helps foster a dialogue that promotes a new way of
thinking about health.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have today in health care is an end-stage treatment
system,'' Pizzorno said. ``We're still not dealing with the
underlying problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Potter agreed, but said there are too many untested remedies and
theories out there promoting themselves as the best way to cure or
prevent disease. Every claim needs to be tested, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to agree on the rules of science,'' Potter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
