<SLUG> BC-GANG-TUTOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-GANG MEMBER NOW HELPS TROUBLED YOUNGSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHIYO YAMADA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ For as long as he can remember, a blue scarf
has always symbolized freedom for Chandy May.
</P>
<P>
   Blue represents hope and empowerment for thousands of Cambodian
refugees _ those like May who made it to the United States and
those who vanished in the Mekong Delta before escaping the Khmer
Rouge, represented by red.
</P>
<P>
   Every weekday, May arrives at a modest office at the East Bay
Asian Youth Center, a nonprofit organization in Oakland that
provides after-school and adult education programs.
</P>
<P>
   At the center, he has placed a scarf with a blue checker design
over a colorful painting of Angkor Wat, the ancient temple capital
of Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   After years behind bars because of gang-related crimes, May now
helps neighborhood youngsters succeed in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me so long to figure out what to do in life,'' said
May, 30, a bilingual counselor at the youth center, who came to the
United States in 1983. ``I don't want these young kids to follow in
my footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   May, fellow Cambodian San Sun and 27 volunteer tutors from the
University of California at Berkeley help 20 teen-age boys improve
academically in an after-school tutoring program.
</P>
<P>
   As program counselors, May and Sun pick students up at their
schools in the afternoon. For more than 4 years, May and Sun have
sat side by side with students from regional high schools in a
simple classroom with steel chairs and conference tables.
</P>
<P>
   Besides help with homework, students get plenty of lessons in
life to keep them from street crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``May forced me to try harder,'' said Kevin Chea, a 10th-grader
at Oakland High School. For two years, Chea has spent almost two
hours a day at the center doing homework. He said his 1.0 grade
average has climbed to 2.3, and he is working hard to raise it to
3.0. Chea wants to study Asian history at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Staying out of trouble is not easy. Some in the program are
still active street gang members; seven are on probation for past
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   May and Sun said they sometimes have to find students who are
cutting class, smoking marijuana or gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The students involved in the program say they can trust May
because of his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   May's path to his current job was a rocky one. At age 14, he
arrived in Oakland with his mother and other relatives. Seeing the
lights of San Francisco from the airplane window, May thought his
future would be as bright as the glittering scene below.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be as bad as watching his father shot to death by
the Khmer Rouge, the communist rebels who seized control of
Cambodia in 1975 and ruled it ruthlessly four nearly 4 years.
Nothing could be as bad as creeping around the land-mined woods
through tangled branches and trees, for endless miles, to reach
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   But life in America wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year-old had to enroll in elementary school because he
had no formal education in Cambodia. His black friends at Oakland's
Horace Mann School taught him to speak English. He also found a
mentor at the nearby Mormon temple.
</P>
<P>
   In Boy Scout Troop 316, led by his mentor, May befriended many
Cambodians, including Sun, seven years younger, who became his
``little brother.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the mentor left after two years, returning to Salt Lake
City, things began to change. He fought with Khmer, Hispanic and
black gang members. Eventually, May and some of his friends became
the Oakland Town Crips, a Cambodian gang.
</P>
<P>
   May recalls styling his hair slick and driving around in gaudy
cars with pretty girls. The cars were affordable through his
drug-dealing profits. He marched through neighborhoods in
loose-fitting pants and blue shirts.
</P>
<P>
   May became addicted to making money from gang activities, and
lost his incentive to stay at school. Committing crimes for petty
cash became a way of life. He dropped out of school in seventh
grade. Sun, an eighth-grade honor student, never made it to high
school.
</P>
<P>
   What ensued were lots of fights, lots of friends killed, lots of
years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like he was looking for ways not to have to go back
in (to jail) again,'' said David Kakishiba, executive director of
the East Bay Asian Youth Center, who first met May in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard his reputation as a leader on the streets. A leader on
the streets could also be a leader at the youth center,'' Kakishiba
said.
</P>
<P>
   For May, the center was, at first, just a way out. But for
Kakishiba, it was a way to help hundreds of neighborhood teen-agers
get back on track. Kakishiba recruited May to be a peer counselor
in charge of youth outreach and retention. It became May's first
full-time job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a teen-ager, nobody, not in my family, not in
school, helped me to do my homework,'' May said. ``I talked to
nobody but gangsters. My role model was a gangster. But David
talked to me, and I thought, `That man really cares.'''
</P>
<P>
   After learning that his girlfriend was pregnant, May said he was
struck by a sudden revelation: ``I thought, `What if I got locked
up in jail again and get killed from gang bang?' My kid will have
to grow up without his father, like me. I didn't want that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kakishiba said May, now married and a father, had gone through
an incredible transition. But he has to face pressure from old
gangster friends criticizing him for being soft and weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a job that is much more difficult than people even think
it is,'' Kakishiba said. ``Just coming from the streets does not
mean you can do this job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
