A3462 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVIL-TIMES-HNS &LR;      04-26 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVIL-TIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN QUEST TO EXPLAIN SCHOOL MASSACRE, EVIL STANDS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Evil. The word seems archaic, a remnant of a
time when unsophisticated society was focused on such matters as
new frontiers and omnipotent deities.
</P>
<P>
   Whether evil is rooted in the human fiber or whether
environmental influence accounts for its malignant surges is a
debate as old as humanity.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, amid the carnage at a Colorado high school, the
issue arose again.
</P>
<P>
   Was evil there on April 20, homicidally stalking the hallways of
Columbine High School in suburban Denver, spraying terror from the
hands of two teen-age misfits in black trench coats? Or was the
carnage instead the lethal distillation of a troubled subculture
unraveled by teen-age paranoia and societal breakdowns?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so mind-blowing you want to find an explanation for
it,'' said Doug Bandow, a senior fellow at the Cato Institute think
tank in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   To some analysts, the murderous rampage of Eric Harris, 18, and
Dylan Klebold, 17 _ who killed 13 people, wounded a score of others
and planted a minefield of booby traps before turning their weapons
on themselves _ was an act less of youthful disaffection than of
baldfaced evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had an evil intent,'' Bandow said. ``They were old enough
to have some responsibility for it. In the end they had control.
We've seen that face of evil before, we've seen it in Hitler and
Stalin, in Milosevic, in petty dictators. What makes this so
shocking is it is the face of kids. You don't expect to see evil on
the face of the young.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, casting a wide blanket of condemnation, blame a culture
grown increasingly numb to extraordinary violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've depersonalized violence; we accept it into our homes
easily,'' said Michael Kelleher, who studied school killings in his
book ``When Good Kids Kill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence seems more acceptable,'' Kelleher said. ``I think
that is evil. Any time we dehumanize these acts, any time we
diminish the impact of violence, we participate in evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Society is tantalized by the possibilities of wickedness,
whether portrayed on the pages of a novel or in movie images or in
the jolting lyrics of profane shock-rocker Marilyn Manson.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the sinister cacophony facing society today is an
increase in digital spatter.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold represent the first generation to grow up
exposed not only to graphic violence on the cinema and television
screens, but to a daily diet of on-line gore. In one highly popular
genre of games, the aim of simulated combat scenes is to kill _
continuously and as violently as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris was known to be a passionate player of these games,
to the point of apparently designing his own blueprints for a game
that features a trail of marauding creatures, some human, some
alien.
</P>
<P>
   Some counselors believe that chronic exposure to such
head-blasting interactivity desensitizes players to the reality of
actual death.
</P>
<P>
   ``These games are teaching kids about a stance to take in the
world,'' said Carl Goldberg, a New York psychoanalyst and author of
``Speaking With the Devil: Exploring Senseless Acts of Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like gunslingers in the Old West, these games involve waiting
for someone to draw on. Kids are prepped to attack, and anyone can
be drawn into the deadly psychodrama.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The night of the Columbine massacre, Rabbi Marvin Hier, founder
and dean of the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles, was
scheduled to give a lecture on the durable nature of evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evil has great resiliency, if you leave a little crack in the
door, it will always come in,'' Hier said. ``Nobody who predicted
the end of evil has ever been correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Wiesenthal Center, searching six months ago
through Web sites posted by hate groups, came upon Harris' America
Online site. While they did not report the site to the police
because it did not trigger particular alarms, Wiesenthal officials
believe the teen-age gunmen were influenced by hate-mongering on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Taunted and ostracized by their peers, the two young men had
apparently forged a twisted kinship with Nazism, and may have
chosen the timing of their campus blitzkrieg to commemorate
Hitler's 110th birthday on April 20.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who sometimes walked the corridors of school clad in
German insignia and steel-toed combat boots, was fond of
techno-Nazi music and conversed in German with Klebold, his
``Trench Coat Mafia'' cohort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that in the warped minds of those two young men
spraying bullets and bombs they were getting rid of evil,'' Hier
said. ``Humans have a capacity to justify evil, to say people are
mean to us therefore we have the right to slaughter them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we live on planet Earth, evil will be a component
of life. It is part of being a human being.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
