   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ With the Hindu nationalists and the
Congress Party stalemated, India's president dissolves Parliament
and calls new elections. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-POVERTY (Washington) _ World Bank warns that after a
generation of declining poverty, improved life expectancy and
better health for millions of poor people, efforts to further
improve human living conditions are in danger of stalling on the
threshold of the new century. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Investigators are
reportedly questioning a girlfriend of one of the shooters, who
might have bought him a gun. Other developments. By Sam Howe
Vrehovek.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-PARENTS (Undated) _ Both Colorado's governor, Bill
Owens, and Attorney General Janet Reno suggest that parents could
be charged in the school shooting. We look at whether parents have
ever been held criminally responsible for such actions. By William
Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   CICERO-GANGS (Cicero, Ill.) _ What would Al Capone say? After
all, this is the place that welcomed Capone, along with his
bootlegging, betting parlors and bordellos, after Chicago kicked
him out. Now, without an ounce of irony, Cicero has an idea for
tackling organized crime of a different sort. This working-class
city of 70,000 just southwest of Chicago is drafting an ordinance _
the first in the country _ that would evict all gang members from
Cicero _ and punish them if they return, even to visit their
families. While Cicero's proposal is dramatic, it is just the
latest in a spate of anti-gang ordinances cropping up nationally,
from Los Angeles to Chicago, some of which are now being reviewed
by the Supreme Court. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   GRANNY-CAMPAIGN (El Paso, Texas) _ An 89-year-old great
grandmother of 11 celebrated her 1,000th mile last week in her
cross-country walk to Washington to protest the failure of Congress
to pass campaign finance reform. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TOBACCO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court agrees to take a
case on the FDA and tobacco. After the federal agency attempted to
regulate tobacco, and proposed many rules aimed at keeping young
people from smoking, the industry won a victory from an appeals
court that ruled the FDA had no jurisdiction. Now the Supreme Court
will decide. Plus other actions. By Linda Greenhouse. (1100 words)
