<HEADER>
A3477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES2     04-26 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes: Saved by Joe Bob Crowley
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was little that was new as a portrait emerged of life at
Columbine High in Littleton, Colo. There were good kids, doing what
good kids always do, working hard, enjoying life, dreaming of the
future. Then there were the others.
</P>
<P>
   What has dominated the news is life among the others in the
substrata beneath, a complex world of uncertainty, anger and cruel
social distinctions. Only weapons of mass destruction are new.
</P>
<P>
   At James S. Hogg Junior High in Houston, I was one of the
others. I wanted to be a hero. I settled for invisibility. As a
badge of my relentless otherness, I had become a hall monitor,
among the most despised of Hogg's underclasses. I flaunted the
infinitesimal power that came with the job. I picked a fight with a
kid who had no hall pass. Then Joe Bob Crowley wandered by, a
visitor from the upper world.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bob Crowley was what we now call a student leader. There is
a Yiddish word for Joe Bob Crowley. Joe Bob Crowley was a mensch;
it means what every person ought to be -- just, measured, decent.
He may not have known this, people like that frequently don't. He
settled the fight in a minute and walked on. I would like to be
like that, I thought for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Bob Crowley was given the American Legion Award, the
highest to a student, I cheered. Cheering for someone felt good.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Joe Bob Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
