<HEADER>
A3490 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDDLE-OFFICE-HNS &LR;      04-26 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDDLE-OFFICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY SHOOTS FOR `MIDDLE OFFICE' EFFICIENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN BERGER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A business takes orders through its front office
_ a sales force, a Web site, a storefront. It delivers the order
through its back office _ a warehouse, a delivery truck, an
invoice.
</P>
<P>
   CSE Systems Corp. of San Francisco is targeting what it calls
the middle office with a new software product, the Cibon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gap between taking an order and processing an order,
between a service request and the administration of a service,
between a bid's specifications and the selection of a supplier, is
truly an automation gap that has not been filled until now,'' said
Shirish Hardikar, president and chief executive of CSE Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Middle office would be order fulfillment, which means getting
the product together for delivery,'' Hardikar said.
</P>
<P>
   The middle office can encompass a number of different functions,
depending on the type of business: scheduling deliveries or
installations, keeping inventory in stock, ordering parts and raw
materials, handling customer complaints, regulatory and standards
compliance, or bid management.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses handle these tasks using computer programs and
technology tools that have been especially designed for that
business. Others use off-the-shelf database and spreadsheet systems
like Microsoft Office or Lotus Notes. But proprietary systems can
be expensive and complicated, and off-the-shelf ones aren't always
flexible enough to handle special demands.
</P>
<P>
   So CSE, a division of the Austrian company CSE Systems GmbH,
developed the Cibon product, which consists of server and client
software, a graphics-driven tool for organizing information, and
Cibon Developer, a Java-based setup allowing businesses to
customize the suite to meet its special needs.
</P>
<P>
   With proprietary systems, it can be tricky to make changes. With
Cibon, the ability to make changes is part of the package, Hardikar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Such tools aren't cheap. The Cibon Suite starts at $15,000 for a
basic 25-user system (packages include service and training). But
the cost savings, he said, come from the fact that the system is
designed for easy customization and a range of capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage is built-in capabilities to enable changes to be
implemented on a continuous basis, without disrupting the system,''
Hardikar said.
</P>
<P>
   Cibon runs on a variety of platforms and interacts with many
off- the-shelf systems, such as Oracle, Microsoft Outlook and Lotus
Notes. It's designed to fit into a company's existing system for
handling front and back office operations.
</P>
<P>
   The package has been on the market for a few months. The
privately held company doesn't disclose sales figures.
</P>
<P>
   CSE is targeting industries with complex order fulfillment
processes, like telecommunications and financial services.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a company like Amazon.com, taking an order by Web or phone
for a book, it immediately goes to the back office for invoicing
and shipping,'' Hardikar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you're AT&AMP;T and someone places an order for all the
telecommunications lines and equipment for a new office building,
you don't immediately ship it and start the billing. Phone lines
have to be laid, service technicians have to install the lines,
some equipment has to be built-to-order, phones have to be
delivered, traffic has to be monitored, regulatory approvals might
be needed before you can dig trenches to lay the line. All those
activities are performed by many departments and divisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Such coordination between departments is especially important in
areas like banking, large retail operations or agricultural
businesses. But Hardikar said the biggest area for growth was
telecommunications, where deregulation has led to the creation of
hundreds of new companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
