<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUN SITES TO VISIT ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Let's begin this week with a few interesting, helpful
and fun Web sites to check out:
</P>
<P>
   - The respected ``National Geographic'' magazine now has a daily
news site. You can find it at www.ngnews.com. In addition to news,
the site offers several cool features, including a ``Map Machine''
that allows users to tap into the magazine's archive of famous
maps. The service is great, especially for kids working on school
projects.
</P>
<P>
   - Can't get enough of television shows like ``This Old House''?
Now you can experience similar content on the Web. American
Homestyle and Garden is sponsoring Dream Home 2000, a home-building
project in Santa Monica, Calif. Visitors to the related Web site
can follow the construction, view plans and take a chance at
winning prizes. The site is at www.dreamhome2000.com/index2.htm.
</P>
<P>
   - Are you bored? Check out Bill's Games, a Web site that
features a ton of online games for the whole family. The site
offers poker, tic-tac-toe, brain teasers, word scrambles, mazes and
a bunch more. And all the games work whether you connect with a
standard personal computer or WebTV. Find it all at
www.billsgames.com.
</P>
<P>
   - Still hung up on the area code changes? You're not alone. Many
computer users are getting frustrated trying to change all their
online access numbers to reflect the new codes. One site that might
be of help is at www.pamlico.net/changing.htm. The site features
step-by-step instructions for changing dial-up settings in Windows
95 and 98.
</P>
<P>
   - Don't check this one out if you're having trouble falling
asleep at night: ``Nova,'' the popular PBS television series has a
special report online dubbed Bombing of America. It's all about
bombers terrorizing the country and how science is helping law
enforcement officials fight back. Find it at
www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/bombing.
</P>
<P>
   - I'm mad at myself for mentioning this one: Animated Virtual
Beanie Babies. Yep. If you haven't had enough of the real thing,
check out this Web site. Find it at www.virtualbeaniebabies.com.
</P>
<P>
   - Here's a silly one: Some folks have put up a Web site asking
visitors to send them $1. Just for the heck of it. It's an
experiment to see how much money they will make. I'm not suggesting
you send them money, but they're supposed to post results at
mailadollar.com. Might be interesting to see what happens. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Psst, wanna grape iMac? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apple loyalists will be pleased to note that iMacs and the
latest Power Macintosh G3 systems continue to sell well.
</P>
<P>
   But there seems to be a bit of controversy over color when it
comes to the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, Apple's first iMacs were a shade of translucent
blue. Since then, the company has expanded the number of available
colors to five: strawberry, blueberry, grape, tangerine and lime.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers seem to love the color selection, but some retailers
are miffed that they can't get Apple to sell them more of one color
than another. Apple's policy is to distribute all colors of iMacs
in equal numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ZDNet reported that Best Buy Inc. has stopped selling
iMacs until it can sort things out with Apple. Apparently, Best
Buy's customers favor certain colors, leaving the retailer's
shelves full of iMacs with less popular tones.
</P>
<P>
   Just what colors are hot? That seems to vary from city to city.
Generally, grape and blueberry are the most popular and strawberry
and tangerine are the least popular. &QL; 
Streaming video? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer has released QuickTime 4.0 for both the Macintosh
and Windows platforms. You can find it at
www.apple.com/quicktime/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice, and works a bit better than version 3.0. The
interface has been jazzed up, adding features such as balance
control for volume.
</P>
<P>
   I downloaded and installed version 4.0 last week. It works fine.
But I don't see much difference (other than the interface) between
this new QuickTime and my copy of RealPlayer Plus G2, the latest
from Seattle-based Real-Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I'm not sure why makers of these video players keep
trying so hard. None of us will ever enjoy using these products
until somebody does something to improve the Internet bandwidth
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Have you tried watching streaming video lately? They've been
attempting this feat for years now, and it still looks like the
video equivalent of shortwave radio from Kosovo _ scratchy, jumpy
images disconnected from the audio. &QL; 
Faster, faster, faster! &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Go on, admit it. You're tired of your 56 kilobit-per-second
modem. You think it's too slow. You've heard whispers that faster
access is available, and you want to know more.
</P>
<P>
   You're in luck. ``PC'' magazine's online site
(www.zdnet.com/pcmag/) has an article reviewing three of the latest
high-speed access technologies: cable modems, ADSL and satellite
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the reviewers concluded that cable modems provide
the fastest, most cost-efficient way of surfing the Web. ADSL comes
in second, providing somewhat slower service. Satellite hookups
fell to third, with reviewers pointing out that satellite
connections still require the use of a telephone line and standard
modem.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's in the water &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We've still got eight months of 1999 remaining, but my e-mail
box is already beginning to collect humorous lists of the top
reasons why we're supposedly tired of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the funnier reasons:
</P>
<P>
   - You recently tried to enter a password on your microwave oven.
</P>
<P>
   - You haven't played Solitaire with a real deck of cards in
years.
</P>
<P>
   - You chat several times a day with a stranger in South Africa,
but you haven't spoken to your next-door-neighbor yet this year.
</P>
<P>
   - You have a list of 15 telephone numbers to reach your family
of three.
</P>
<P>
   - You get excited when Saturday arrives because it's the one day
your are allowed to wear sweat pants to work.
</P>
<P>
   - You need a PowerPoint presentation to explain what you do for
a living.
</P>
<P>
   - You consider second-day air delivery as painfully slow.
</P>
<P>
   - You have trouble staying in touch with some relatives because
they don't have e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   - You didn't give your spouse a Valentine's Day card this year,
but you found the time to post one for your buddies on your Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   - Your daily ``to do'' list includes bathroom breaks _ but you
never seem to get them crossed off. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
