<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I'D WRITE THIS COLUMN FOR A SONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Used to be the best unrealistic goal most newspaper
columnists could hope for was winning the Pulitzer Prize or seeing
a compilation top the ``New York Times'' bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Schmich has changed all that.
</P>
<P>
   Now a columnist can futilely yearn to write a pop hit as well.
</P>
<P>
   Schmich is a columnist for the ``Chicago Tribune.'' Her name may
not be familiar, but the novelty hit ``Everybody's Free (to Wear
Sunscreen)'' probably is. Schmich wrote the ``lyrics.''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of. She actually wrote a column, in June 1997, in which she
offered graduates life advice in an imaginary commencement address.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderful column, full of the offbeat, simple wisdom
that's so hard to come by, things such as, ``Do not read beauty
magazines. They will only make you feel ugly.'' And, ``Don't mess
too much with your hair, or by the time you're 40, it will look
85.''
</P>
<P>
   (The column wound up as one of the first Internet urban legends;
it showed up online credited erroneously to Kurt Vonnegut as a
commencement address he delivered at Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.)
</P>
<P>
   Australian movie director Baz Luhrmann read the column and
contacted Schmich and the ``Tribune'' about licensing her words for
an album he was making. Australian voice actor Lee Perry read the
column over a dance track, and ``Everybody's Free (to Wear
Sunscreen)'' was born. &QL; 
Pass the M&AMP;M's
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So why should Schmich have all the fun? Why couldn't another
columnist _ let's say, for the sake of argument, me _ hitch a ride
on this gravy train?
</P>
<P>
   What's Schmich's secret?
</P>
<P>
   I asked her these questions by e-mail and received a prompt
response:
</P>
<P>
   ``My only secret is: lots of coffee, lots of M&AMP;M's and a
deadline. That combination was the muse that gave birth to this odd
little hit. I hope you understand that I am drowning in sunscreen
stuff and can barely get my own column written three times a week,
so I'll have to leave it to you to answer the rest of your
questions. A bag of M&AMP;M's will help. Honest.''
</P>
<P>
   (After I e-mailed thanks, she sent another quick reply at no
extra charge: ``By the way, I went to high school in Phoenix, as
did all my seven brothers and sisters. I went to the defunct
Gerard, the others went variously to East, Arcadia and Brophy. I
mention this only because it's the kind of local-angle detail I
would want if I were writing a column.'')
</P>
<P>
   The deadlines I've got. But the M&AMP;M's haven't worked so far, and
I've never had a cup of coffee in my life.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing I write will ever be confused with Kurt Vonnegut except
for maybe grocery lists (and his probably include coffee), so a
wacky Internet misunderstanding is out.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm not discouraged. Instead, I've set my sights on marrying
other writers with well-known tunes. I may not have written a jot
or tittle, but a steady stream of royalties would offer some
comfort. &QL; 
Odd couplings
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Setting George Will to a Rage Against the Machine song might
work _ not only would it make his points more forcefully, but it
would make reading them feel less like reading a thesaurus. Maureen
Dowd over a Nine Inch Nails track perhaps? It would put the
bitterness into context.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Barry set to ``Stairway to Heaven''? Molly Ivins and ``All
My Exes Live in Texas''? Tony Kornheiser and, naturally, Korn?
</P>
<P>
   Nah. The best fit I've found so far couples the tune from Bob
Dylan's ``Subterranean Homesick Blues'' with these words, written
long ago by Robert Benchley (please sing along):
</P>
<P>
   ``A great many people have come up to me and asked me how I
manage to get so much work done and still keep looking so
dissipated. My answer is, `Don't you wish you knew?' And a pretty
good answer it is, too, when you consider that nine times out of 10
I didn't hear the original question.''
</P>
<P>
   Needs work, granted. But remember, when Benchley was writing
there wasn't any sunscreen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
