<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3559 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENACED-MONTENEGRO-EC     04-26 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENACED-MONTENEGRO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTENEGRO: THE LAST OASIS OF SANITY IN WAR-TORN BALKANS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent, ``heads-up'' 700-word separate buy article is from
the current (week beginning 24 April 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA _ Montenegro is a country of breathtaking vistas.
Massive black mountains, streaked with snow, falling into endless
blue chasms, fade into the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been a swashbuckling, Byronesque sort of place,
home to princes, smugglers, poets and, latterly, to a stalwart band
of down-to-earth democrats.
</P>
<P>
   For, amazingly, Montenegro _ poorest, smallest and most feudal
