<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3560 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTMODERN-1-AZR &LR;      04-26 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTMODERN-1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POSTMODERN PRIMER: BUZZ WORD DEFINES OUR TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
(ADV: Editor's note: ``Postmodern'' _ the buzzword of the past 20
years. It started in the arts, spread to academe and now shows up
in virtually every form of popular culture. So what does it mean _
really mean? Republic art critic Richard Nilsen hashes it out.  
Postmodernism in art _ Can you know yourself too well? 
Postmodernism at large _ Is your whole life a media event? 
Postmodernism's fate _ Does anything so now have a future?) 
 
 ByRICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The ground has shifted under our feet and the world
has changed.
</P>
<P>
   At least, the way we see it has changed, as the century comes to
a weary close. The shift was first noticed in the art world, and
for the past 30 years, art has illustrated this change.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, architect and critic Charles Jencks appropriated the
term ``Postmodernism'' to describe the change. He used it mainly to
describe a new type of architecture freed from the boring
restraints of Modernism's International Style: Those steel and
glass monoliths that hover like tombstones over all of the world's
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Postmodern architecture was freed from its purity and
puritanism. The new architects said, in essence, ``Anything goes,''
and they found ways to make buildings fun again. Architects used
ornament again, and borrowed freely from all the styles of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Even architect Philip Johnson, who had been a high priest of the
International Style, signed on to the Postmodernist shift when he
designed, in 1979, the AT&AMP;T Building in New York, and capped it
with a roofline that borrowed the scalloped cutout that tops a
Chippendale highboy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, architects see no reason not to add Greek columns to Aztec
pyramids, or design a building that looks as if it is falling down.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, you can see a mild version of the new style in the
silly ``crown'' that tops the new City Hall, and the vaguely
soap-bar shape of the former Dial building on Central Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   But the word has a wider significance in the art world, and has
become the term of choice for all the new paintings, sculpture and
video and computer art made since the petering out of Pop Art and
Minimalism in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   You are seeing Postmodern art when you see:
</P>
<P>
   _Jenny Holzer's purposefully banal sayings _ ``Abuse of power
comes as no surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   _Barbara Kruger's feminist posters, loaded with political anger
_ ``Your body is a battleground.''
</P>
<P>
   _Jeff Koons' stainless steel cartoon bunny rabbit imitating a
silver mylar party balloon.
</P>
<P>
   _Cindy Sherman posing herself in imitation of Hollywood
publicity stills.
</P>
<P>
   _Mark Tansey's mock-heroic comic grisaille paintings of such
cultural happenings as ``The Triumph of the New York School,''
which shows the New York Abstract Expressionists as field generals
in a World War I battle scene.
</P>
<P>
   _Bruce Nauman's ``Clown Torture,'' an irritating videotape of a
clown laughing hysterically while telling a pointless story that
repeats itself endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   It is all just a big jumble, and styles are mere menu items.
</P>
<P>
   When we were first deluged with Postmodern imagery, it was
confusing. We couldn't really tell what the new art was about. It
seemed to go off in so many directions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the trends written about as Postmodern are:
</P>
<P>
   _A breakdown of the wall that once divided high art from popular
art, high culture from low culture.
</P>
<P>
   _The denial of a coherent historical narrative.
</P>
<P>
   _A call for diversity.
</P>
<P>
   _An increase in political and social content.
</P>
<P>
   _An emphasis on non-traditional materials, including video.
</P>
<P>
   _A hefty reliance on ``text,'' whether in the form of actual
words included in the picture, or on the reading of imagery as
though it (begin ital) were (end ital) words. (The latter comes to
us under the Postmodern category of ``deconstruction.'')
</P>
<P>
   _The proliferation of art-historical references in the art.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these trends even seem to contradict each other: There
is both a suspicion of irony and an ironical use of art's past: On
one hand, New Age art (one branch of Postmodernism) is laden with
sincerity and on the other, Jeff Koons makes an in-joke using
Michael Jackson and the Elgin Marbles.
</P>
<P>
   That is a lot of very different things all going on at once. No
single artist embodies all these directions, but no serious artist
is immune to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   But, a ``metalogic'' for all these diverse strands of
Postmodernism is beginning to come clear. What they all have in
common is an increased self-awareness, a kind of hyper
self-consciousness that lets nothing happen without being
controlled, understood and interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, all art is now an in-joke and both artists and
audiences have to ``get it.''
</P>
<P>
   New Age Postmodern art brings Jungian archetype to the surface,
making conscious what had formerly functioned as unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Koons makes us aware of the kitsch that surrounds us.
</P>
<P>
   Kruger makes us aware of the hidden sexism in art history.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Estes makes us aware of the intense artificiality of
photography.
</P>
<P>
   The artists all are aware of how each medium of art distorts
reality and creates its own meaning. They are so interested in the
distortion, they leave the reality behind. Many even deny the
existence of a common reality. They are aware of the distortion and
revel in it.
</P>
<P>
   Postmodernism began as a revolt against Modern Art. Modern Art _
now more than a century old _ began with Impressionism and
continued seemlessly up to Minimalism. Modern Art was interested in
the reality of pigment, marble, design, shapes _ all the means of
the artist.
</P>
<P>
   Modern art was a break with the art that came before it.
Postmodern art was seen as a break with the Modern.
</P>
<P>
   But more and more, it is seeming like the culmination of
Modernism.
</P>
<P>
   Modernism was concerned with paint or stone, not with love or
poverty. It was art about itself, not art about life. Modern
artists wrote continually of their concern for the interplay of
colors, line, form and shape.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if the central metaphor of art had shifted. Where a
canvas was seen before 1870 as a stand-in for a window we looked
through, after then, it became a screen we looked at. Where the
Baroque painter showed us a horse or a tree, the Modern painter
showed us a blue or a circle. The window went opaque. The real
world ceased to have much importance. The medium became the
message.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this explanation simplifies what in reality was much
more complex, but it catches the central thrust of Modern art.
</P>
<P>
   Postmodernism is a removal one step further in the
window-metaphor. Where the modern artist no longer cared if it were
a tree or a football in the painting, but only if it were brush
strokes and paint, the Postmodernist no longer cares if it is brush
strokes and paint: He has pulled back even further into words and
ideas about the art.
</P>
<P>
   The opacity begins now not at the canvas-window, but with a pair
of eyeglasses, sooted over with self-awareness.
</P>
<P>
   So that what matters is neither tree, nor canvas, but what is in
the mind.
</P>
<P>
   It is the biting of the apple in Eden: Before, Eve and Adam were
unself-conscious, doing what they did spontaneously. After the
bite, everything they came to know only interfered with the simple
living they were born to.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if Hamlet suddenly became aware of playing a part in a
play.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, artists worked in a style and hardly knew it. Their
style was merely either the common aesthetic language of the age,
or, as Hemingway once put it, the sum total of all an artist's
shortcomings. Style happened.
</P>
<P>
   But Postmodernism has bitten the fruit of the tree of knowledge
of style.
</P>
<P>
   And Hamlet, knowing it is a play, breaks out in a song and
dance.
</P>
<P>
   In Postmodernism, style is the very point. You consciously
``choose a style'' and work in it, make fun of it, show its hidden
meanings.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of all this awareness, though, is a loss of connection
with the experience of life.
</P>
<P>
   That part of the story is for next week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Richard Nilsen is online. Send e-mail to him at
richard.nilsen(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
