<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3578 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTMODERN-2-AZR &LR;      04-26 1521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTMODERN-2-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTMODERN-2: WE ARE WHAT WE SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
(ADV: Editor's note: ``Postmodern'' _ the buzzword of the past 20
years. It started in the arts, spread to academe and now shows up
in virtually every form of popular culture. So what does it mean _
really mean? Republic art critic Richard Nilsen hashes it out.  
Postmodernism in art _ Can you know yourself too well? 
Postmodernism at large _ Is your whole life a media event? 
Postmodernism's fate _ Does anything so now have a future?) 
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In the new sitcom, ``It's like, you know . . .,''
Jennifer Grey, a neglected actress with a recent nose job, plays a
neglected actress with a recent nose job named Jennifer Grey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look a lot like the Jennifer Grey (on the series),'' the
actress says on her show's official Web site, ``so we have a lot in
common. We're both actresses. We both were in ``Dirty Dancing.'' We
both had nose jobs. We both don't look anything like we did before.
We share some ex-boyfriends. But aside from that, we're really
quite different _ distinctly different _ people.''
</P>
<P>
   However, with everyone else in the ensemble comedy completely
fictional, we cannot confidently tell where to draw the line
between the fictional Grey and the ``real'' one.
</P>
<P>
   This is Postmodernism in action.
</P>
<P>
   Postmodernism, also called ``Pomo,'' in a hipper context, began
as the name for a current direction in architecture, painting and
sculpture, but it actually names a trend in culture at large: a
self-conscious awareness of ourselves as playing parts, and a
blurring of the lines between genres, and between media and life.
</P>
<P>
   On HBO's ``The Sopranos,'' a show about the Mafia in New Jersey,
the gangsters have a habit of quoting dialogue from ``The
Godfather.'' They get a great kick out of it. One mobster even has
a car horn that plays the music from the older film.
</P>
<P>
   This is also Pomo in action: a bunch of actors pretending to be
mobsters who, in one virtual reality, recognize the fictional
virtual reality of another set of actors pretending to be mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   It is the old reflection of a mirror in a mirror routine.
</P>
<P>
   Pomo blurs the distinction between TV and real life, but instead
of adding verisimilitude to the television series, it makes life
unreal.
</P>
<P>
   Who is more real, after all? ``Murphy Brown'' doing ``60
Minutes'' segments, or Connie Chung playing herself on ``Murphy
Brow''n?
</P>
<P>
   In a Pomo world, everything appears in quotation marks.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Coca-Cola is now ``Classic'' Coke.
</P>
<P>
   And we wonder whether there is a ``real'' Jennifer Grey.
</P>
<P>
   Pomo has been around for about 30 years now, beginning in the
fine arts and spreading to culture at large. Distinctions we used
to make no longer seem true: Is there any reason a professional
wrestler should not become governor of Minnesota? Any reason an
actor shouldn't be president?
</P>
<P>
   Or any reason that an assassination attempt on a former actor
(Ronald Reagan) should not be inspired by an old movie (``Taxi
Driver'') and the assassin's obsession with a starlet (Jodie
Foster) and the whole thing captured by local TV video?
</P>
<P>
   It's the perfect Pomo event.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just that we blur the line between TV and life, but
that we are so familiar with the mechanisms of media that we use
them to describe our lives: We see our lives as ``arcs'' of a story
line; we know our own back stories; our children are our sequels.
</P>
<P>
   We are so aware of the processes, we have forgotten how to react
spontaneously to the content.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, when Alfred Hitchcock _ a pre-Pomo director _
made ``Psycho,'' he expected to scare us out of our wits. He
manipulated his narrative to make the greatest effect. It was
important that Hitchcock knew how he achieved his results, but it
wasn't important that his audience recognize the tricks. They just
had to jump when Hitch went ``boo.''
</P>
<P>
   We are not that naive.
</P>
<P>
   In a Pomo movie, such as ``Scream,'' the audience is in on every
directorial manipulation. It knows that if you open the door to the
dark basement and go down the stairs, there will be a scream at the
bottom. And the characters in the film even comment on the
inevitability of the fright.
</P>
<P>
   When a character asks, ``Who's there?'' the homicidal maniac
answers:
</P>
<P>
   ``Never say `Who's there?' Don't you watch scary movies? It's a
death wish. You might as well come out to investigate a strange
noise or something.''
</P>
<P>
   We are all in on the joke and scream on cue. They've seen it all
before.
</P>
<P>
   And when we get the sequel, ``Scream 2,'' it is about making a
fictionalized version of the first film, called ``Stab'' in the
movies. The cleverness is dizzying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe they got Tori Spelling to play Syd,'' says one
of the characters.
</P>
<P>
   Another says, ``So, you're saying someone is trying to make a
real-life sequel?''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Stab 2'?'' comes the reply. ``Why would anyone want to do
that? Sequels suck.''
</P>
<P>
   The reflexive cleverness is actually stultifying.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a TV watcher in America who doesn't yet recognize that
the standard sitcom interweaves an ``A story'' with a ``B story''?
</P>
<P>
   We have become so aware of the mechanisms of life and media,
that we can hardly function spontaneously.
</P>
<P>
   For instance: We don't just call it grieving anymore; we go
through the seven-step grieving process. And we never simply ``get
over it,'' but we achieve ``closure.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV is so self-aware, it has just begun a campaign in which it
invents, from whole cloth, a new set of slang words for the kids to
use.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, slang was born on the streets and worked its way
upward. In a Pomo world, there is no reason slang shouldn't be
synthesized at the top and sent back down to the streets via the
billboards MTV has bought around New York.
</P>
<P>
   In this synthetic slang, ``Round'' means ``cool;'' ``February''
means ``out of style;'' ``fresno'' is ``classic rock;'' and
``bingo'' is ``sex.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Pomo world, everything is marketing, and consumers not only
recognize the fact, they eagerly participate in it.
</P>
<P>
   We wear billboards on our ball caps and T-shirts. We look for
the swooshes on our jogging shoes. It doesn't strike anyone under
the age of 40 as odd that we should name a stadium after a snack
food or a long-distance telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   And even TV commercials are likely to be about making TV
commercials: a chameleon puts out a contract on a Budweiser frog.
This is not about beer, it is about media.
</P>
<P>
   When we want to know which movies are worth seeing, we don't
consult critics for their opinions as much as we look at the weekly
grosses, reported in the mainstream press, to see which movies are
most popular.
</P>
<P>
   Trade magazines hardly have anything in them anymore that a
mainstream reader might be unfamiliar with.
</P>
<P>
   Even elections are influenced. Pre-Pomo, election coverage was
coverage of issues. In our hyper-aware Pomo days, coverage is of
the horse race. Issues are discussed only when noting the
demographic they are chosen by savvy politicians to play to.
</P>
<P>
   It is a form of cynicism, but not a particularly profound
cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   With such awareness of the details, we hardly keep track of the
big picture. It all breaks into fragments, and we can reassemble
the fragments in any shape or form.
</P>
<P>
   So that when we are more aware of typography than content, we
get ``Wired'' magazine.
</P>
<P>
   And we can cross-over characters from the comic ``Ally McBeal''
on one network into the serious-minded ``The Practice'' on another.
It is as if E.G. Marshall and Robert Reed were defending Jed
Clampett in a lawsuit with Milburn Drysdale.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is dumped into the blender and osterized.
</P>
<P>
   And everything is a hyperlink with a pop-up menu. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MO vs. POMO &QC; 
