<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3590 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTMODERN-3-AZR &LR;      04-26 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTMODERN-3-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN ARTISTS RETREATED INTO A COLORFUL UN REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
(ADV: Editor's note: ``Postmodern'' _ the buzzword of the past 20
years. It started in the arts, spread to academe and now shows up
in virtually every form of popular culture. So what does it mean _
really mean? Republic art critic Richard Nilsen hashes it out.  
Postmodernism in art _ Can you know yourself too well? 
Postmodernism at large _ Is your whole life a media event? 
Postmodernism's fate _ Does anything so now have a future?) 
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The history of art is filled with new ground broken,
horizons opened up, new directions taken. There were periods of
endless possibility when imaginations were fertile, when things
that had seemed outside the realm of art now became central. Art
became exciting and actually led the direction of culture in
general.
</P>
<P>
   But each of those periods was capped by a retrenchment, a period
when the possibilities closed down and the cultural imagination
seemed exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The Renaissance, for example, was followed by the period we call
Mannerism, when only the manner, or style, of the great artists
remained. The ambition and curiosity of Leonardo and Michelangelo
retreated to the stylistic preciosity of Parmagianino and Pontormo.
</P>
<P>
   The Baroque's restless energy settled into its stilted parody,
the Rococco. And Modern art dead-ended in Postmodernism.
</P>
<P>
   The retrenchments in history seem little and meager compared
with their prodigious predecessors. The one opens the gates
confidently, the other timidly shuts them again.
</P>
<P>
   So, the time we are in now, which we call Postmodern, is really
another era of Mannerism. Style has triumphed over substance.
Indeed, style is seen as substance.
</P>
<P>
   It is unfortunate that this should be so, because Postmodernism
actually began as a reaction against style, against Modern art and
Modernism's apparent retreat from reality.
</P>
<P>
   By the '60s and '70s, art seemed to have abdicated its
responsibility to deal with the experience of being alive.
Modernism seemed to be interested only in itself: It played with
shapes and colors and ignored such human questions as suffering,
death, birth and love.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was a mantra of the last cadre of Modern artists in
the '60s that ``Art makes nothing happen,'' that art was a world
separate from everyday reality and existed solely by its own laws.
</P>
<P>
   Modernism white-towered itself to death, and the younger artists
of the '60s and '70s attempted to bring the streets back into the
art.
</P>
<P>
   You can see those attempts in the smaller movements called
Neo-Expressionism, with its emphasis on personal emotion, and
Photo-Realism, with its reconnection with the way the world looks.
But those movements, and all the many others that fall under the
umbrella of Postmodernism, soon devolved. Neo-Expressionists
borrowed the ticks and habits of earlier Expressionists, and
instead of being about personal emotion became about the (begin
ital) look (end ital) of personal emotion, one ironic step removed
from the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Photo-Realism became a parody of Kodachrome.
</P>
<P>
   The artists reacted more to the style than to the world around
them. Indeed, they made a fetish of the ``media-inflected'' look of
the world. TV and photographs were said to (begin ital) be (end
ital) the world modern Americans inhabited. Artists would look at a
TV sitcom the way Corot would look at a real tree.
</P>
<P>
   There is some truth to this, and no art that ignored the welter
of media could be said to be truthful. But neither can art be
truthful if it limits itself only to mediated reality.
</P>
<P>
   If we are aware of the pervasiveness of mediated reality _ in
other words, a world in which, for instance, television becomes the
go-between _ we are also aware of how each mediation is also an
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a whole school of philosophy evolved from the thought
that ``perception is reality,'' ``reality is subjective'' _ or as
it is put now, ``truth is a cultural construct.''
</P>
<P>
   One popular group of thinkers began to look at the hidden
cultural and political meanings of art. What did it really mean
when we see a nude? Isn't it really a means for the politically
dominant males to oppress the females? Or, perhaps, wasn't high art
really just a means for the ruling class to perpetuate its tastes
and use them to create ``membership'' in its numbers?
</P>
<P>
   When artists began to think the same way, they thought they were
bringing reality back into their art. In truth, they headed more
toward what we call ``political correctness.''
</P>
<P>
   And a whole vast dogma of politics and philosophy began to take
over the art. It was a coup d'etat.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the artists believed they were reversing the
shortcomings of Modernism; they believed they were bringing the
world back into the art.
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't. They were bringing (begin ital) ideas (end
ital) about the world into art. They had abdicated one more time.
If all of reality is media-inflected, they thought, there is no
reality but the ideas about reality.
</P>
<P>
   They have been seduced by a trendy, but ultimately shallow,
philosophy. And they have grabbed onto it like a junkyard dog,
sinking their teeth into it up to the gums.
</P>
<P>
   Painters would try to express the hegemony of the patriarchy;
sculptors would try to model the Post-Feminist, Neo-Marxist subtext
of racial and ethnic identity.
</P>
<P>
   And it all became words, words, words. Even the images were
meant to be ``read.'' All images, in the parlance of
Deconstruction, were ``text.''
</P>
<P>
   In Deconstruction's gunsights, everything was subject to
interpretation. We cannot trust an author's intentions. He might be
saying something completely different from what he ``intends'' to
say.
</P>
<P>
   So that, ``Huckleberry Finn'' becomes a story about the
homoerotic fascination the White man has for the Black man, or
``Moby Dick''
</P>
<P>
   becomes a story about Herman Melville's difficulty with
gender-identification.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing an author or artist seems to be saying is valid in the
Postmodern world; only our multifarious interpretations of it
counts for anything.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems hard to take seriously any philosophy that, by its
own rules, is meaningless: Why should we pay attention to the
Deconstructionist's intentions and not Melville's?
</P>
<P>
   Postmodernism also rails against the supposed ``elitism'' of
what has traditionally been called ``high art.'' Art should be
democratic, it says. There is no difference between high art and
popular art. Yet, try to read philosophers Jacques Derrida or
Michel Foucault and you will quickly discover an ``elitism of
jargon.'' Their thinking is not accessible to the common person,
yet they demand that art be.
</P>
<P>
   And the supposed ``diversity'' they champion is rather limited
in its inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   In short, you may say that Postmodernism attempts to
decentralize the art on all levels. White males are no longer in
control.
</P>
<P>
   There are problems, however, as political concerns emerge over
creative ones. One is that the political content is almost wholely
leftist. Diversity has its limits and tends to exclude right-wing
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, however, Postmodernism mistakes the difference
between interpretation and experience. Experience occurs first,
before words, before interpretation, before understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Our understandings may be culturally inflected, but our
experiences are primary.
</P>
<P>
   If we want our art to reconnect with the world, we cannot do so
at the level of philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   No, we must reacquaint ourselves with experience, and our art
must not explain us to ourselves, but offer us experiences. Please,
let's end the PC moralizing and instead discover what it feels like
to walk on hot sand, what it feels like to bite into a crisp apple,
what it feels like to dance. What it feels like to give birth, or
raise a child. Or get old, or fear death.
</P>
<P>
   We should be leaving the interpretation to the critics; that is
their thankless job. Art should show us things, make us hear
things, make us touch things and recognize the body we inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the failure of Postmodernism is that it is stuck
inside our heads. It seems to believe that the brain is the only
organ that exists, and that language is coequal with reality.
</P>
<P>
   I am not here talking about retreating to the past. I don't mean
I want our artists to begin painting like Norman Rockwell. I am
asking for something much more radical.
</P>
<P>
   I am asking artists to open their senses and sensibilities up to
the life they lead and create art that engages that life in the
most direct way conceivable.
</P>
<P>
   There are artists who are doing this. Postmodernism doesn't
comprise the whole of the art world, merely the most trendy part of
it.
</P>
<P>
   But artists such as James Turrell, working in the landscape
north of Flagstaff, are striving to give us genuine experiences,
connected once more with the world and universe.
</P>
<P>
   Turrell's Roden Crater Project is meant to show its viewers the
sky, but seen in such a way as they have never seen it before. His
many light installations are about the experience of glowing.
</P>
<P>
   Such art _ and there are many other artists working to reconnect
us with the world _ has to be the sensible and moral reaction to
the narrow constraints of Postmodernism. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Richard Nilsen is online. Send e-mail to him at
richard.nilsen(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
