<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3596 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-CIVILWAR-SFCH     04-26 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-CIVILWAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER REVIEW: `CIVIL WAR' LOSES THE BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN WINN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK &LR;   &LR; _ Broadway now has a new bombastic hat trickster in
composer Frank Wildhorn, whose ``The Civil War'' opened last week
at the St. James Theatre. With three shows running at once,
Wildhorn joins the august company of England's Andrew Lloyd Webber.
He does so, however, by lowering the bar well below Lloyd Webber's
standards.
</P>
<P>
   This latest and truly appalling effort from the creator of
``Jekyll and Hyde'' and the recently revised ``The Scarlet
Pimpernel'' bathes the U.S. Civil War in more than two hours of pop
songs, gospel, folk, country-and-western and adrenaline-soaked
anthems. There's not a complex emotion or idea _ musical or
otherwise _ to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are there characters in any discernible sense. The show's
would-be innovation involves chronicling the war as a kind of
pageant of the common man. Shreds of story lines _ the hackneyed
brothers fighting on opposite sides, a runaway slave reunited with
her husband, a woman pining for a far-off soldier _ are loosely
stitched between the songs by the composer, author Gregory Boyd and
author-lyricist Jack Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Douglass (Keith Burton Kirk) is the only well-known
historical character; he serves as a quasi-narrator. Abraham
Lincoln turns up in occasional voice-over. Nobody mentions Ulysses
S. Grant or Robert E. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Able Broadway veteran Jerry Zaks (``Anything Goes,'' ``Six
Degrees of Separation'') agreed to direct a show that essentially
doesn't exist. He tries everything from strobe lights and
slow-motion battle scenes to a set frame of ravaged classical
columns and (set ital)lots(end ital) of projections _ Virginia
farmland, battle maps, body counts. None of it works.
</P>
<P>
   Making an evening stand almost entirely on the strength of its
score would be an audacious choice for a great composer. Frank
Wildhorn is anything but that. Melodies pour out in a forgettable
stream. The rhythms thump. Harmonic structures are bolted in place.
The lyrics remain passionately committed to the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after we learn of the brothers separated by their
uniforms, one dies in the other's arms on the battlefield. ``Tell
my father I didn't run or surrender,'' the soldier pleads in a
moment so craven it's probably just as well that the characters are
nothing more than emblems.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Missing You (My Bill),'' a wife complains to her absent
husband that the roof is leaking. We're not meant to laugh. We are,
with a shiver, whenever a grizzled profiteer (Leo Burmester) slinks
onstage to use women, rotgut whiskey or dead soldiers to turn a
buck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil War'' uses slavery and the cruelties of war to cash
in its own cheap sensations. Slaves suffer and hope in gospel
choirs. There's a ``Last Waltz for Dixie,'' a soldier's homesick
ode, a teary reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The St. James was crammed with school groups at a press preview
last week, and a lot of the young listeners seemed to be swallowing
``Civil War's'' syrup gratefully. The wildly popular ``Jekyll and
Hyde'' and ``Pimpernel'' _ and the hit recordings that preceded
those shows _ have made Wildhorn the closest thing to an indigenous
pop sensation Broadway has seen in a long time. (``Rent's''
Jonathan Larson might not have made it even if he had lived longer;
his palette had a lot more shades of gray than Wildhorn's brassy
colors.)
</P>
<P>
   It's regrettable to tromp on anything that attracts a younger
audience to Broadway. In this show's weak defense, the music does
have its moments. A tenderly understated meditation, ``I'll Never
Pass This Way Again,'' is followed by a bloodcurdling war song that
summons some of ``Les Miserables''' power.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the best way to look at Wildhorn's appeal is that he's
getting people into the theater who might not be there otherwise.
It's a start, anyway. Maybe they'll stick around for better
material.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
