<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, April 27:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OBESITY-DRUG (Washington) _ The FDA approves an anti-obesity
drug, the first of a new class, which works by blocking the
absorption of up to 30 percent of fat in the diet. But it comes
with some unpleasant side effects and the committee that advised
the agency on it was divided on approving it. The drug is made by
Roche. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RED-MAPLES (Undated) _ FILM-REVIEW _ The forests of the
eastern U.S. are turning increasingly red, and the growing
brilliance of color signals a historic change in the ecological
character of a vast region stretching from the Great Lakes to the
Atlantic and from Canada well into the South. These arboreal
hard-chargers are red maples, and they are taking over the woods.
If their march continues, it could signal the downfall of the
majestic oaks that have been a mainstay of the deciduous forest for
most of the last 10,000 years. By William K. Stevens. (1750 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-JAPAN-CONTRACEPTION (Tokyo) _ In Japan, after 10 years the
contemporary version of the birth control pill still has not been
approved, but Viagra won approval in a matter on months. Critics
say it's part of the male dominated society, but defenders say it's
simply a matter of protecting women. By Sheryl WuDunn. (1530 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPY-SATELLITE (Undated) _ If all goes well today, years of
planning, delay and debate will culminate in the launching of a
vastly powerful satellite that more than any other will a rival to
military spies in the sky. The satellite is to be hurled from a
California launching pad into an orbit some 420 miles high, where
its camera will be able to record cars, homes, hot tubs, roads,
buildings, bridges, convoys, tanks, jets, missiles and mass graves
_ though not individual people. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-UTAH-DINOSAURS (Undated) _ A site in Utah has yielded a
trove of fossils of some of the biggest armored dinosaurs ever
found, paleontologists announced yesterday, and they said the
discoveries might compel scientists to revise the chronology of
dinosaur migrations. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COLO-LYNX (Undated) _ An ambitious effort to re-introduce
the elusive lynx into southwestern Colorado has encountered an
avalanche of criticism from animals rights advocates and even many
of its proponents in the wake of the death by starvation of four of
the thirteen cats released in February and March, and the emergency
recapture of an emaciated fifth. By Mark Derr. (950 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AYALA-EVOLUTION (Undated) _ A conversation With Dr.
Francisco J. Ayala, who is known in the science world as the
Renaissance man of evolutionary biology. He discusses ways of
teaching evolution to students who are resistant to the concept. A
former Dominican priest, he is also an authority on genetics and a
professor at the University of California at Irvine. By Claudia
Dreifus. (1630 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MIDWEST-QUAKE (Undated) _ Midwesterners who worry about
earthquakes got some good news last week: their risk of catastrophe
may have been vastly overstated. New measurements taken around New
Madrid, Mo. _ the epicenter of devastating earthquakes in 1811 and
1812 _ show that the ground there is scarcely moving. According to
many scientists, this means that it will take 2,500 to 10,000 years
before another very large earthquake could occur in the region,
although smaller, less damaging earthquakes are possible. By Sandra
Blakeslee. (1050 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: On plants that can
protect themselves from sunburn, rubber salmon with electronic
sensors that may help protect some endangered species and a sundial
that will go to Mars. (570 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT (Sydney, Australia) _ The Doctor's World:
Nearly seven months after Clint Hallam got a new hand in France,
the Australian's transplant has progressed faster in some ways than
expected, three of the doctors who performed the procedure said in
interviews here. But Hallam is proving to be a far more difficult
patient than the doctors imagined when they chose him as the first
individual to undergo a hand transplant using microsurgery and
anti-rejection drugs. By Lawrence K. Altman, M.D. (1050 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column. For
about 15 million Americans, heartburn is a daily occurrence that,
if not treated indefinitely on a daily basis, can develop into
something far more serious _ a change in the cells lining the
esophagus that may progress into a very serious cancer. But there
are a variety of ways to head of the heartburn and at least reduce
the risk for this deadly cancer. By Jane E. Brody. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANAVAN-DISEASE (Undated) _ The American College of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists is now recommending that Jews of
Eastern European descent be offered screening to determine whether
they are carriers of Canavan disease, an inherited neurological
disorder that causes most children with the disease to die before
age 10. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOMEN-ATHLETES (Undated) _ If not for a history of medical
myths and a lack of athletic opportunity, It is at least possible,
suggests Dr. Ellis Cashmore, a professor at Staffordshire
University, in a medical journal article that in all sports that
demand skill as opposed to pure brawn, women might have been
competing at levels comparable with their male counterparts. The
article has become a lightning rod for controversy. An essay by
Mary Duffy. (930 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VACCINE (Undated) _ An overload of conflicting and often
alarmist information about vaccinations is leading some medical
experts into new research: not to study the effectiveness and
safety of vaccines, which they consider proven, but to examine the
public's questions, doubts and fears. By Michael Pollak. (1380
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VACCINE-DEATH (Undated) _ A New York family claims the
mandated hepatitis B vaccine killed their child. (325 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Seizure disorders can be controlled by medication, but not for
all patients and not always perfectly. That makes driving a gamble,
which is why most states require epilepsy patients to be seizure
free for a specified length of time before they get behind the
wheel. Now a new study, published in the current issue of the
journal Neurology, will help physicians design safer driving
programs for patients by offering them a tool to evaluate their
risks. (390 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ In a recent presentation, an expert in saving teeth called for
putting a tooth into a glass of milk _ and, once again, the doctors
say, skim or low-fat is best. Another alternative: put the tooth
back in the socket it came out of. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ In an effort to make outdoor playtime more sun-safe, the
Children's Aid Society, the American Academy of Dermatologists, and
KaBOOM, a playground safety group, will build the nation's first
intentionally sun-safe playground on April 30 at the Goodhue Center
on Staten Island. (345 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ In an editorial in the current issue of the journal Heart, a
cardiologist in the Bordeaux region of France, Dr. Jean-Paul
Broustet, recounted three decades of research on the health
benefits of wine, concluding that cabernet sauvignon made from
Bordeaux grapes was the best wine to drink for good cardiovascular
health and longevity. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEALTH-SURVEY (Undated) _ Middle-income African-Americans,
Hispanics and whites have significantly different attitudes toward
health care and follow different healthcare practices, a new
national survey shows, raising concerns among minority leaders that
two separate and unequal systems of the care have developed in the
United States. (550 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: Do bears
hibernate? (300 words)
</P>
