<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAR, ORWELL STILL APPLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In war, the first casualty is truth, an
observation made by the British essayist Samuel Johnson in 1758 and
Hiram Johnson, the California senator, in 1918. In modern war,
language becomes part of the collateral damage.
</P>
<P>
   One of George Orwell's six rules of writing is: ``Never use a
long word where a short one will do.'' In the US armed forces, a
job is not a job, but an MOS, a ``military occupational
specialty.''
</P>
<P>
   Orwell died in 1950, after the world learned about Nazi
concentration camps. He would not be surprised to hear Slobodan
Milosevic diminish that horror by discussing ``demographic
genocide,'' meaning non-Serbs having more babies than Serbs. A
henchman of the Yugoslav president also uses the phrase carelessly.
``This genocidal, flying circus of the NATO alliance has caused
huge destruction,'' said Goran Matic, a government minister. ``But
citizens of Yugoslavia will not give in.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Christine Ammer wrote ``Fighting Words,'' a sprightly
summing up of military terms from ``Achilles heel'' to ``zero
hour.'' In a new book, ``Never Enough Words,'' Jeffrey McQuain
writes that ``War is probably the strongest catalyst for the
formation of euphemisms as examples of indirect wording.''
``Incident'' is an all-purpose dodge. A plan ``to neutralize the
enemy's capability'' means death and chaos.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest description of war's effect on language is Orwell's
essay, ``Politics and the English Language.'' Written in 1946, it
could have been written Thursday, based on briefings in Brussels or
bombast from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our time, political speech and writing are largely the
defense of the indefensible,'' Orwell wrote. ``Defenseless villages
are bombarded from the air, the inhabitants driven out into the
countryside, the cattle machine-gunned, the huts set on fire with
incendiary bullets: this is called pacification. Millions of
peasants are robbed of their farms and sent trudging along the
roads with no more than they carry: this is called transfer of
population or rectification of frontiers. People are imprisoned for
years without trial, or shot in the back of the neck, or sent to
die of scurvy in Arctic lumber camps: this is called elimination of
unreliable elements. Such phraseology is needed if one wants to
name things without calling up mental pictures of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In his time, Orwell criticized both Nazi sympathizers and
Marxists, not only because they were totalitarian but because their
jargon was rooted in sloppy thinking and bad writing:
</P>
<P>
   ``An effect can become a cause, reinforcing the original cause
and producing the same effect in an intensified form, and so on
indefinitely. A man may take to drink because he feels himself to
be a faliure, and then fail all the more completely because he
drinks. It is rather the same thing that is happening to the
English language. It becomes ugly and inaccurate because our
thoughts are foolish, but the slovenliness of our language makes it
easier for us to have foolish thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Orwell had seen war and aggression. He was wounded during the
Spanish Civil War and his studies of totalitarianism inspired
``Animal Farm'' and ``1984.'' A half-century after his death, the
adjective ``Orwellian'' is apt today. He opposed sham, brutality,
and words used to cover up sham and brutality:
</P>
<P>
   ``The inflated style is itself a kind of euphemism. A mass of
Latin words falls upon the facts like soft snow, blurring the
outlines and covering up all the details. The great enemy of clear
language is insincerity. When there is a gap between one's real and
declared aims, one turns as it were instinctively to long words and
exhausted idioms, like a cuttlefish squirting out ink. In our age
there is no such thing as `keeping out of politics.' All issues are
political issues, and politics is itself a mass of lies, evasions,
folly, hatred, and schizophrenia.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
