<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AMERICAN WORKPLACE REMAINS CA DANGEROUS PLACE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the nation and the world focus on the tragic deaths of
teenagers at the hands of other teenagers in Littleton, Colo.,
there is another, less public tragedy occurring across America on
an almost daily basis _ death and serious injury in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   This Wednesday marks the 11th observance of Workers Memorial
Day, a day to remember workers who have been killed or seriously
injured on the job because of lack of safety or unhealthy
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a day when organized labor, health and safety
organizations, and many workers will renew their commitment to
fight for safer jobs and stronger regulation and enforcement of
laws by agencies such as OSHA, the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration. While many employers are trying to take more teeth
out of OSHA enforcement, organized labor and health and safety
groups across the country are trying to put more teeth into the
federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   As the battle between the two sides escalates, so does the high
number of workplace deaths and serious injuries that federal
agencies such as OSHA was created to help prevent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 6,218 deaths occurred in 1997 in the workplace
because of traumatic injuries, a slight increase from the previous
year, according to the latest reports from the US Bureau of Labor
Statistics. Alaska ranked the highest in workplace deaths with a
rate of 17.5 per 100,000 workers (51 total deaths), while
Connecticut was lowest, with a rate of 2.0 per 100,000 workers in
the state (32 total deaths).
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts ranked third lowest with a rate of 2.2 per 100,000
workers (66 deaths). Overall that year, all New England states
ranked among the 15 states with the lowest rates of deaths per
100,000 workers _ Rhode Island came in third, Vermont was seventh,
Maine eighth, and New Hampshire 13th.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even these rankings reflect the reality that there are
still far too many deaths and serious injuries in the workplace.
And these tragedies are occurring even though increased safety
measures and stronger enforcement and regulations have resulted in
a decrease of deaths and serious injuries in many workplaces across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, ``41 Massachusetts workers died on the
job, more than 1,000 died from occupational diseases, 1,200 workers
were diagnosed with cancer caused by their jobs; and over 50,000
workers were seriously injured,'' according to the annual report of
the Massachusetts Coalition for Occupational Safety and Health, or
MassCOSH.
</P>
<P>
   Although these fatalities were fewer than the 66 deaths in 1997,
the ``largest declines were in the areas of on-the-job homicides
and fishermen lost at sea.'' With that distinction, MassCOSH uses
another measurement.
</P>
<P>
   By comparing 1997 and 1998 figures in terms of workers killed on
the job because of employers' failure to comply with required OSHA
regulations, the number of fatalities between the two years are
similar _ 24 in 1997; 21 in 1998. If the number of on-the-job
fatalities that have occurred so far in the first three months of
1999 (17) were annualized, it adds, ``Massachusetts would see 68
fatal job-related injuries occurring this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, OSHA, the one federal agency that was created to prevent
deaths and injuries in the workplace, continues to be under heavy
assault, with major employers and their friends in Congress
attempting to further weaken, if not seriously cripple, the
agency's effectiveness. Legislation has been filed in the US Senate
that would eliminate the workers' right to on-site OSHA
inspections, allow OSHA to issue warnings instead of citations for
violations, and allow overrides of OSHA standards by permitting
employers to use any alternative methods that they deem effective
to protect workers.
</P>
<P>
   There is also legislation pending that would ``immunize''
employers from OSHA penalties so long as they set up a ``health and
safety program and are certified as `in compliance' by an
employer-selected and paid consultant,'' MassCOSH reported.
</P>
<P>
   But the need is for a stronger, not weaker, OSHA. While many
employers complain that current OSHA standards are too high and too
costly to companies, there is little consideration of how increased
safety and health standards lead to a decrease in workplace
fatalities and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A stronger OSHA adds up to more lives saved, MassCOSH and labor
organizations such as the AFL-CIO argue. They report that 200,000
lives have been saved because of OSHA's regulation and enforcement
laws, while stronger laws could sharply reduce the more than 6,200
deaths and 6 million injuries that occur each year in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to employer arguments before Congress, OSHA clearly
needs more funding and more inspections. Currently, for example, it
would take OSHA 118 years to inspect each workplace under its
jurisdiction in Massachusetts _ and that is only one inspection for
each workplace, MassCOSH reported.
</P>
<P>
   To show how much Massachusetts needs more, not less,
inspections, it would take 80 years _ 38 years fewer _ for OSHA to
have one inspection in every workplace across the country. That's
largely because other states have more OSHA inspectors. In Oregon,
for example, it would take only 20 years to inspect all the
workplaces in that state. Florida, the worst state in this
category, would need 291 years to inspect all its workplaces under
OSHA jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason why OSHA needs more funding and stronger
enforcement laws is that many employers simply do not take it
seriously enough. The fines for OSHA violations, for example, are
often too low to have any real effect on an employer who scorns
OSHA regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay State, the average fine paid by an employer whose
OSHA violations resulted in the death of a worker was $19,316.66,
MassCOSH reported. While this is an increase of about $6,000 from
last year, six of the nine employers penalized in 1998 paid less
than $10,000 and four paid less than $5,000 for OSHA violations.
</P>
<P>
   With these low fines, some employers do the math and find it is
less costly to violate OSHA regulations than to comply with them.
MassCOSH and its sister agency, Western MassCOSH in Springfield,
note with concern another growing trend in the industry. Some
employers have been rewarding workers for not reporting any
injuries in the workplace, as well as threatening, if not
disciplining, workers who do report injuries.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, MassCOSH adds, some firms will hide the true number
of injuries and work-related illnesses that are required under OSHA
laws to appear on injury logs. The organization further argues that
``safety incentive'' and ``injury discipline'' programs and
policies should be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   With more than half of the serious workplace injuries in
Massachusetts reported as ``ergonomic'' injuries involving
repetitive motions and/or overexertion, MassCOSH praises OSHA's
efforts to go forward, against strong employer opposition, with an
ergonomic standard that would require all employers, not just ones
in manufacturing, to provide information about signs and symptoms
of ergonomic injuries, and to correct potential ergonomic hazards
before injuries occur.
</P>
<P>
   As this and other reports document, every worker in America
needs a stronger OSHA. Workers know that a strong OSHA increases
their chances of going to a safer workplace every day and returning
home every night not only alive but with their health and all their
limbs attached.
</P>
<P>
   And all employers should be willing to pay the cost of keeping
their workers alive, healthy, and productive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
