<HEADLINE>
TIME MAY BE AT HAND TO FIX YOUR EYES SURGICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laser eye surgery has become so effective and widely accepted
for correcting vision problems that more than 1 million Americans
are expected to have the procedure done this year and next. But
it's no surprise that many people still get squeamish hearing the
words ``eye,'' ``laser'' and ``cut'' in the same sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the US Food and Drug Administration approved
what may be an attractive new option for some mildly nearsighted
people leery of having part of their eye burned off: tiny plastic
rings that are inserted on the edges of the cornea to flatten it
and sharpen up the patient's view of distant things.
</P>
<P>
   European and Canadian doctors have been implanting the Intacs
rings for up to three years already. The main selling point is
that, unlike laser surgery, the procedure can be undone if patients
are unhappy with their new vision.
</P>
<P>
   However, many national eye specialists are skeptical the
implants will ever become more than a narrowly used alternative to
laser surgery. They cite several reasons: The rings cost as much or
more (roughly $2,000 per eye), installation hurts more, and for the
foreseeable future they will fix only a small range of mild
nearsightedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantages are few, and I bet in Boston it's going to be
something that really doesn't take off,'' said Carmen A. Puliafito,
director of the New England Eye Center in Boston and chairman of
the Tufts Medical School ophthalmology department, who performed
Massachusetts' first laser eye surgery in December 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dimitri T. Azar, a top surgeon at the Massachusetts Eye and
Ear Infirmary who has been to Paris to learn the procedure, said,
``Our plan is to start very carefully and not jump into it, because
there could be some hidden surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   At least for the first several months, Azar said, the infirmary
will require patients choosing rings to go to an operating room
with an anesthesiologist assisting, because of the pain of one
motion where the eye is simultaneously pulled and turned. The laser
eye surgeries can be done in a room set up like a dentist's office
with a reclining chair.
</P>
<P>
   The potential market for any of the operations is immense.
According to American Academy of Ophthalmology estimates, a quarter
of all Americans are nearsighted and another 22 percent are
farsighted. Nearly 150 million people, the academy says, wear some
kind of eyewear, including non-prescription reading glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, an estimated 500,000 Americans have paid for laser
surgery _ which virtually no health plan covers _ to reduce or
eliminate the need for contact lenses or eyeglasses. Currently, the
two most frequently performed visual correction surgeries are
called Lasik, which stands for laser-assisted in-situ
keratomileusis, and PRK, for photorefractive keratectomy.
</P>
<P>
   People have trouble seeing either near or far because their eyes
have less than the optimal curvature to focus images on the retina,
the membrane at the back of the eye that receives visual images.
Both Lasik and PRK slightly reshape the surface of the eye, making
it either flatter to improve distance vision or more steeply
pitched to improve near vision.
</P>
<P>
   In PRK procedures, lasers guided by computer calculations shear
off very thin layers of tissue _ a fraction of the thickness of a
piece of paper usually _ from parts of the cornea surface to
produce a shape that yields clearer vision.
</P>
<P>
   Lasik has been dubbed ``flap and zap'' because it involves a
surgeon using an automated cutting device like a carpenter's plane
to slice an ultrathin flap from the surface of the eye, which is
peeled back to allow a laser to vaporize tissue underneath.
</P>
<P>
   The flap is then replaced and patients heal much faster than
with PRK, in perhaps two days instead of a week. Also, immediately
after leaving the operating chair patients see better instead of
having to wait up to 20 days to know how their vision has been
improved, which is the case with PRK.
</P>
<P>
   Neither technique is foolproof, however. Flap complications
occur in about 1 to 2 percent of Lasik cases, but usually can be
surgically fixed. A comparably small percentage of people
undergoing both types of operations complain about blurry vision,
halos, glare, problems seeing at night or are simply disappointed
the procedure didn't yield the improvement they hoped for,
according to several US studies.
</P>
<P>
   Lasik is considered best suited to people with high to severe
nearsightedness or farsightedness. It has boomed to more than 80
percent of all eye surgeries since it was introduced in 1996,
according to Irving J. Arons, managing director of Spectrum
Consulting in Peabody, Mass., a leading authority on the
eye-surgery market.
</P>
<P>
   KeraVision, the Fremont, Calif., company that produces the new
Intacs implants, apparently sees a market among people who dislike
the idea of making a permanent, irreversible change in their eyes
or fear complications, which are rare.
</P>
<P>
   The rings, made of a polymer used for decades in cataract
surgery, are inserted about 1/3 of an inch from the center of the
eye through two small incisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best selling point seems to be the fact that they are
removable, there's a second chance and all your marbles aren't in
one basket,'' said Dr. Richard L. Abbott, codirector of corneal and
refractive surgery at the University of California at San Francisco
Medical Center, who was a principal investigator in Intacs trials
at 11 teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   However, Abbott said that he sees the rings as only ``a niche
product. The idea is that this technology would be expanded'' for
use on more myopics as well as people with hyperopia
(farsightedness) and astigmatism. However, studies are only
beginning overseas on adapting the rings to these uses and it could
be years before they can be more broadly used in the US, Abbott
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting technology, but its use right now is limited,''
said Dr. Ernest Kornmehl, medical director of the Center for Laser
Vision Correction in Brookline, Mass., who is on the faculties of
the Harvard, Tufts and University of Massachusetts medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   In people with especially large pupils that dilate widely at
night, the rings may obstruct vision on the periphery. About 1 in
10 people in early trials complained about seeing halos or glare
after getting the corneal rings, but that figure should drop as
surgeons master the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
