<SLUG> BC-SCI-PICTUREPHONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PICTUREPHONE MAY NOT BE THAT FAR AWAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since AT&AMP;T rolled out the Picturephone at the 1964 World's
Fair in New York, video telephony for consumers has remained an
idea ahead of its time, largely because of its enormous expense and
need for special phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   For business, videoconferencing has won some acceptance as a
less pricey alternative to travelling across the country. At home,
Americans have overwhelmingly shown no appetite for spending
several hundred dollars or more to see as well as hear friends and
family calling.
</P>
<P>
   But a Massachusetts inventor recently patented a device that
could clear the way for affordable video calls from home phones as
well as cellular units. Edward T. Bullister won patent 5,886,735
last month for a device that would work over regular telephone
lines without requiring expensive ISDN or cable-television-based
hookups.
</P>
<P>
   Bullister's system includes a headset with an arm that sticks
out about 4 to 8 inches in front of the wearer's face. The arm
carries a screen about the size of a large postage stamp that shows
the person or people you are calling, plus either a small camera
trained on your face or a convex mirror with a camera on the
headset trained on it.
</P>
<P>
   Key parts of Bullister's patent cover the software by which
images of people's faces are corrected and digitally compressed to
15 to 30 images per second in a way that conserves ``bandwidth'' on
phone lines and makes it possible to transmit a decent image of the
caller's face over basic copper phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Because the image stays trained on the wearer's face from
forehead to chin, the display software needs to change far fewer
pixels each fraction of a second to show caller's expressions than
other systems that use desktop cameras. The patent also contends it
can effectively simulate eye-to-eye conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to amazing advances in miniature surveillance cameras,
some of which are now down to 1/3 of an ounce, the whole thing
could weigh little more than a normal phone headset like operators
or airline reservation clerks wear. Bullister believes the cost
could be only a few hundred dollars, and has also developed a
version that would go on a cellular phone unit and a feature that
can simulate an office-like backdrop if you are calling someone
from the beach or vacation resort.
</P>
<P>
   Bullister, a 41-year-old father of two who won a doctorate from
MIT 11 years ago, works full time for a medical device company. He
has been meeting with several videoconferencing companies about
developing and marketing the system, which in a best-case scenario
might be in stores within two years.
</P>
<P>
   This is his fifth patent, others covering a device for securing
human tissue during surgery, a device to connect computer
peripherals and two versions of computer trackballs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
