<HEADLINE>
DO BIRDS SLEEP? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Do birds sleep at night? Do they close their eyes, sit on a
perch, put their heads under a wing, or what?
</P>
<P>
   B.L., Phoenix &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Finding a scientist who has studied bird sleep is harder than
finding a sleeping bird.
</P>
<P>
   Many species hide when they sleep, to protect themselves. And
they're not asleep for long, in some cases for just a few seconds
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Niels Rattenborg, behavioral neurophysiologist at Indiana State
University, has studied bird sleep. Small perching birds, like
songbirds, only spend several seconds asleep at a time. They sleep,
and wake up, and sleep again, all night. They don't sleep during
the day.
</P>
<P>
   They have two strategies for protecting themselves at night.
Often they'll find a sheltered spot, hidden from predators like
owls, raccoons or cats. Usually it's up off the ground, but
whippoorwills, woodcocks, oven birds and others sleep on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Perching birds of the same species will sometimes roost together
overnight in groups that can number in the hundreds or thousands,
more so in the winter, probably for both heat retention and
protection from predators.
</P>
<P>
   How does Rattenborg know when a bird is asleep?
</P>
<P>
   ``They close their eyes. That's pretty obvious. They're standing
up, but their heads droop. Pigeons and doves kind of hunker their
heads down into their shoulder feathers. Other species tuck their
head into their back feathers. While they're doing all this we see
changes in their brain wave patterns indicative of sleep,''
Rattenborg reports. ``First the large wide waves of slow brain
activity, the kind of sleep that is the deeper physiological
resting period in mammals, and then the short tight waves of what
in humans we call REM sleep, the kind when we dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been able to ask birds if they dream, of course,''
Rattenborg says with a smile. ``But they seem to lose muscle
control during REM sleep, like humans do. Their heads droop or
swirl around, like they're drunk. I've seen ducks (that sometimes
sleep standing on the ground) almost topple over in this kind of
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. How come we never see baby pigeons?
</P>
<P>
   C.M. Maynard, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. By the time you see them on the wing, on the lawn, or on the
sidewalk, pigeons aren't babies anymore. Fledglings of most bird
species are effectively teenagers by the time they're big enough
and strong enough to fly out of the nest and out to where you can
see them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1523EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
