<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RPT-WALKER26-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Resending to change reference to CREATOR in third graf from
bottom.
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: School shooting should remind us of our compassion
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The least of these ...''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase has hardly left my mind since learning of the tragic
shooting at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The two young men who police believe caused their own deaths and
the deaths of 12 of their classmates and a teacher have been
described as outcasts and weirdos, kids at the bottom of their high
school's food chain, least among their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nation was stunned by the brutal and calculated act
and many searched frantically for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Why did this happen, we asked. Why in Colorado, Oregon,
Kentucky, Mississippi, Arkansas? Answers about the young men who
perpetrated the terror in each of these incidents may be found on a
case by case basis, but such violence in the nation's schools is no
longer an aberration. It is
</P>
<P>
   excruciatingly common and there exists no easy fix.
</P>
<P>
   Again, we shed tears and again we grieve. But after the grief,
what then?
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, we live in a country that would rather move away from its
problems, than stand and fight them.
</P>
<P>
   We close our eyes to much of life's darker side because as long
as it's affecting ``those people'' we don't have to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   We have done it with drugs. When it was only an inner city
problem, we moved to the suburbs or to the country. We've done it
with teen pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   When it had not yet touched the middle class, we ignored it. We
did it with AIDS. When it was labeled a homosexual disease, we
refused to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that such things don't recognize geographical
location, race or income level. When we turn our backs on them, we
simply delay the day those problems arrive at our doorstep. More
importantly, when we turn our backs on them because they only
affect those we regard as the least among us, we are dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   We hear young people talk about their schoolmates who isolate
themselves, the kids no one will talk to and who won't talk to
anyone. They are out of the mainstream, not in the cool crowd or
the popular group.
</P>
<P>
   I can't blame our teens for not trying very hard to reach out to
those they see as misfits. We certainly have not given them that
example to follow. We, too, ignore the least among us.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, we in the ranks of today's parents know how hard it is to
break through the walls our children build around themselves at
certain stages in their young lives, but we don't stop trying. We
know that eventually they will feel comfortable with their
independence and will again look to us as sources of strength and
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   If our kids are worth the effort, aren't all the rest?
</P>
<P>
   In these days following this latest and bloodiest school
shooting, many of us turn to God. However we address the Creator,
we ask for comfort and for answers.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps those of us in this country's so-called Christian
majority need only to act on the words spoken by the founder of the
faith to which we lay claim:
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatsoever you do to the least of these, my people, that you
do unto me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal. E-mail:
</P>
<P>
   awalker(at)coxnews. com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
