</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT CASE FILINGS DELAYED
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft and the U.S. Department of Justice on
Monday said they delayed for one week their announcements of who
will be the rebuttal witnesses in the ongoing antitrust trial. Each
side was to have named three witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Settlement talks between the two sides started March 30, but the
delay on the witness lists apparently is related to the possibility
the trial may not resume as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-May was a target for the trial to restart, but no specific
date has been set, according to the office of U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is presiding in the case. Jackson is
also trying a murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Still on schedule in the Microsoft case, however, are the
depositions of Peter Currie, executive vice president of Netscape
Communications, and of Michael Popov, chief operating officer of
Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   Currie's deposition, scheduled Wednesday morning in Washington,
will be the first in the case to be open to the public. (CQ) Popov
is to be interviewed Friday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said Thursday in a statement that planned depositions
of executives from those two companies and from America Online
``are expected to focus on the question of how AOL's acquisition of
Netscape and strategic alliance with Sun affect the government's
antitrust accusations against Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
