A3645 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-JAPAN-CONTRACEPTI     04-26 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-JAPAN-CONTRACEPTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S TALE OF TWO PILLS: VIAGRA AND BIRTH CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan normally takes many years, even decades, to
approve foreign medications. But last year the middle-aged men who
run the Ministry of Health and Welfare decided to rush the process
for an American drug that they apparently deemed so critical that
Japan could not wait another moment.
</P>
<P>
   It is Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   So Japan, which is the only industrialized country that still
has not approved the use of the modern version of the birth control
pill for women, now is in the throes of a mania for the little blue
pills that treat impotence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 60 years old, but I think I'm 16,'' said Shigeharu
Kobayashi, an insurance executive who used Viagra for the first
time after it went on sale in March.
</P>
<P>
   At alumni reunions, golf games and even conference gatherings,
the hottest topic of the moment is Viagra. Men these days often
pull out a couple of tablets from their pockets to show their
friends, as if it had become a new rite of passage into middle age.
</P>
<P>
   But if the issue of sex and impotence has surfaced more openly,
so has the starker political issue about the tilted status of men
over women in this country.
</P>
<P>
   It took just six months for Viagra to win approval from the
Ministry of Health and Welfare, which has six women among its 204
bureaucrats. Meanwhile, the low-dose birth control pill, the most
common form of nonsurgical contraception in the United States,
still has not won approval even though its application was filed a
decade ago, and women's groups are furious.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the older, higher-dose pill is available in Japan,
though it was withdrawn from the American market in 1988 because of
the risk of blood clots and other side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gender issue,'' said Hiroko Hara, an anthropologist
and leading member of Japan's Network for Women and Health. ``The
empowerment of women is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Japanese men do not want Japanese women to become
empowered,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The Ministry of Health and Welfare would not comment on the
pill's application. But Japanese news reports suggest that the
uproar over Viagra's speedy approval may force bureaucrats to
hasten the approval of the pill, perhaps by this summer or fall.
</P>
<P>
   One of the government's deep worries is that the birth rate in
Japan has been falling, and on average, Japanese women now have
only 1.39 babies in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   So, some say, Viagra could help promote population expansion,
while the pill would prevent it. But many women are not buying this
reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind all this is the basic background that Japan is a
male-dominated society,'' said Tomoko Adachi, a gynecologist at
Tokyo Women's Medical University. ``If you look at the issue in
terms of safety, it's strange that Viagra got approved so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, for instance, even before Viagra's approval,
Japanese newspapers reported the death of a Japanese man in his 60s
who was taking medicine for his high blood pressure and diabetes.
Though doctors did not release the exact cause of his death, news
dispatches reported that about two hours after he had taken a
Viagra tablet, his heart stopped and he could not be revived.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the United States, there have been deaths among some men
taking Viagra, though its manufacturer, Pfizer Inc., insists the
deaths are unrelated to the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials in Japan have said unofficially that one
reason they approved Viagra so quickly was to insure proper usage
of the drug, to prevent more deaths. In contrast, those officials
have said that the approval of the pill has been delayed because
they need to minimize the dangers associated with it.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also said that if the pill becomes widely
used, couples will quit using the condom, currently the most
popular contraceptive, and this will trigger the proliferation of
sexually transmitted diseases, including AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the incidence of gonorrhea and chlamydia has been rising
sharply over the past couple of years, up 32 percent and 36 percent
respectively last year among young people compared with the
previous year. In contrast, the United States has witnessed
declines in these sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucrats have complained over the years that Japan's youth
need to be educated sufficiently about sexual diseases before the
pill becomes a common contraceptive. The government has done little
to promote such education, and many women are still afraid of using
the pill for fear of widely publicized side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely silly,'' said Midori Ashida, a top executive at
the Professional Women's Coalition for Sexuality and Health. ``In
Japan, most women believe the pill is dangerous. The pill is almost
a synonym for side effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiaki Kumamoto, a doctor who is president of the Japan
Foundation of Sexual Health Medicine, has a different
interpretation. He said _ only partly facetiously _ that one reason
Viagra was approved so quickly was because many members of
parliament ``want to have that drug.''
</P>
<P>
   These suspicions were so pervasive that last month two former
chief cabinet secretaries filed a suit against a prominent
publisher for printing a report saying that they were Viagra users.
Both denied that they used Viagra or that they had applied any
pressure to bureaucrats to get the drug approved.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra is not exactly new to Japan. For the past year, people
have been discreetly bringing home bags full of it when they
returned from the United States. But Japan has always hidden its
sexual mores behind a veneer of manners and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the legal sale of Viagra in a country that has the
longest average life span of men in the world, there is a sense of
national enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impotence hasn't been considered an illness until now,'' said
Takaaki Minami, a urologist who has experienced a burst of new
business prescribing Viagra. ``But the men who are impotent have
been psychologically saved by public recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Viagra craze hit last summer, when tablets of Viagra were
being sold illegally at pubs and brothels. Middle-aged men were
eager to obtain a sample or two, and men were giving Viagra as
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in Hawaii and San Francisco had a brisk business writing
prescriptions to visiting Japanese men. A single tablet of Viagra
on the black market in Tokyo was selling for $35, and at one point
last summer, it rose to nearly $400, according to Japanese news
reports
</P>
<P>
   Now, the official price is 1,500 yen, including taxes, or about
$12.50, and some clinics have become busier at night because of
Viagra. But not everyone is delighted with Viagra, and there is
growing concern among middle-aged wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Japanese women do not want to have Viagra for their sex
lives, but there is no objective survey or research yet,'' said Dr.
Adachi. ``A considerable number of postmenopausal women who come to
see me complain that they do not like to have sex because it is
uncomfortable and sometimes painful.''
</P>
<P>
   That explains why Kobayashi said, ``I'm afraid of becoming a
constant user.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not that he worries about feeling his youth again. As he
fidgeted nervously with his eyeglasses, Kobayashi explained that
his wife was not particularly eager about his newfound vigor. If he
becomes a frequent user of Viagra, there will be a mismatch in
sexuality in the Kobayashi household, and more generally, among
Viagra users and their more conservative wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very honest and I love my wife,'' said Kobayashi. ``But
I'm just a man.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that if more middle-aged men became sexually active,
they would think of using Viagra for extramarital affairs, and he
worries that the combination of Viagra and the pill, when it is
approved, may be dangerous for Japanese society.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Viagra and the pill both become prevalent, the moral values
of society will deteriorate,'' he said. ``This is a hot topic
now.''
</P>
<P>
   It is thus not surprising that these days there is a joke among
elderly men in which the wife quips: ``Why are you getting so
worked up about Viagra? It doesn't interest me one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a joke,'' said Dr. Minami, the urologist. ``Many
women who have gone through menopause say that Viagra will be a
nuisance to them.''
</P>
<P>
   So Kumamoto has an answer to this problem: Japanese women should
undergo hormone replacement therapy, like their counterparts in the
United States. Kumamoto, who is 70, says that one reason he wants
the pill to be approved is so that it can increase awareness about
hormone usage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usage of the pill would curb public concern over the usage of
hormones, and this would encourage hormone replacement therapy and
then more women would be sexually active,'' he said. ``If both
couples use something, then both sides will be happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
