<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3648 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT &LR;      04-26 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRODY-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: CHRONIC HEARTBURN, AN OMINOUS WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have all had heartburn now and then, if at no other time,
then after consuming a highly acidic or spicy food or when bending
over or exercising vigorously soon after eating a full meal. And in
most cases, if any treatment was needed, an over-the-counter
antacid took care of the temporary discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   But for about 15 million Americans, heartburn is not occasional.
It is a daily occurrence that, if not treated indefinitely on a
daily basis, can develop into something far more serious _ a change
in the cells lining the esophagus that may progress into a very
serious cancer.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds frightening, it is. The incidence of esophageal
cancer precipitated by chronic heartburn is increasing faster than
any other cancer in the nation today, and in nearly 90 percent of
cases it is incurable.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Swedish researchers reported that having frequent,
inadequately treated heartburn increased the risk of esophageal
cancer nearly eightfold. And among study participants who had
particularly severe and longstanding heartburn, the risk of cancer
rose by 43.5 times.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship was so strong that researchers concluded that
chronic heartburn was likely to be the cause of this highly fatal
cancer. Precancerous changes in the esophagus develop in 10 percent
to 15 percent of patients with chronic heartburn, and these
patients face a risk of cancer that is 30 to 40 times as great as
the risk in the general population.
</P>
<P>
   Heartburn is obviously a disease that demands more respect than
it gets.
</P>
<P>
   The widely publicized findings, which were published in The New
England Journal of Medicine, precipitated countless thousands of
inquiries from concerned patients, most of whom were already being
treated by specialists, according to a survey of doctors by the
American College of Gastroenterology.
</P>
<P>
   But at least half the people who suffer from chronic heartburn
are not getting the kind of medical care that may protect them from
the serious consequences found in the Swedish study.
</P>
<P>
   Heartburn results when the acidic contents of the stomach back
up into the esophagus, often because of a weakness in the muscular
valve between the esophagus and the stomach and sometimes because
the contents of the stomach empty too slowly into the intestines.
Patients with a hiatal hernia, in which a part of the stomach
bulges through a weak area of the diaphragm, may also have a
problem with heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   In medical terms, and now in advertisements as well, chronic
heartburn is called gastroesophageal reflux disease, or GERD.
Symptoms can include a burning feeling in the chest, a sour taste
in the mouth, regurgitation of a small amount of partly digested
food, unexplained chest pain, asthma (especially at night), chronic
hoarseness, sore throat or cough and erosion of the teeth.
Heartburn is most likely to occur after a large or fatty meal and
when lying down or bending over after a meal.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that many products and treatments are now
available to alleviate chronic heartburn and prevent stomach acid
from damaging the cells of the esophagus, which are not designed to
withstand a frequent bath of acid.
</P>
<P>
   The first line of defense, however, should be adaptations of
diet and habits, which are often all that is needed in mild cases.
Avoid acidic foods like citrus fruits and juices and tomatoes,
spicy and fatty foods, chocolate, peppermint, coffee and tea
(including decaf), cola and alcohol. Try eating five or six small
meals throughout the day instead of two or three big ones.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after meals, avoid exercising, bending over, lying down or
going to sleep. And do not wear clothes that constrict the waist or
abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   People who are overweight should try to lose excess pounds and
smokers should quit. It may also help to raise the head of the bed
by six to eight inches or sleep on your back on extra pillows or
with a wedge under your pillow.
</P>
<P>
   Acid reflux may also be aggravated by drugs you take for other
conditions, so consult your doctor about the effects of both
over-the-counter and prescription medications you take and ask
whether substitutions may be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   More severe cases that do not respond to diet and habit changes
alone require medication. Over-the-counter antacids (Maalox,
Mylanta, Tums, etc.) and histamine blockers like Pepcid AC, Tagamet
HB, Xantac 75 and Axid AR may not be strong enough to control acid
reflux fully.
</P>
<P>
   Histamine blockers are also available in prescription strength,
and may be taken in combination with more potent acid suppressors
called proton-pump inhibitors, like Prevacid and Prilosec.
</P>
<P>
   Other potentially useful drugs include Carafate, which protects
the lining of the esophagus, and drugs that speed stomach emptying,
like Propulsid, Reglan, Duvoid and Urecholine.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is not yet definitive proof that effective drug
treatment can prevent progression to cancer, preliminary evidence
strongly suggests that it will. And if acid reflux cannot be
controlled through diet, habits and drugs, surgery may be required.
One of the newest procedures, done through a laparoscope, involves
wrapping a defective esophageal sphincter to strengthen it against
reflux.
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree that it is not enough merely to squelch the
symptoms of heartburn. Rather, acid reflux must be prevented and
any cellular damage that has occurred must be healed. Experts also
agree that it is not enough to treat chronic heartburn
sporadically, stopping treatment when symptoms subside.
</P>
<P>
   To protect the esophagus adequately, treatment must be
aggressive, continuous and indefinite.
</P>
<P>
   If you have heartburn two or more times a week, you should see
your doctor and perhaps request a consultation with a
gastroenterologist. If the problem has been longstanding, an
examination and biopsy of the esophagus through an endoscope is the
only good way to assess what, if any, damage has been done to this
organ. If abnormal cell changes, known as Barrett's epithelium or
Barrett's esophagus, have occurred, endoscopic examinations should
be done every year or two to check for possible progression toward
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Should a premalignant condition develop, the esophagus can be
removed and replaced with a piece of intestine or stomach. There
are also experimental treatments that use lasers or other heat to
obliterate the abnormal cells and allow healthy cells to replace
them. Untreated, about 10 percent of patients with Barrett's
esophagus eventually develop cancer.
</P>
<P>
   For More Help
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking more information about GERD can join the 750,000
people who in the last three years have called the American College
of Gastroenterology's hot line, (800) HRT-BURN (478-2876). Or you
can write to the college at 4900 B South 31st Street, Arlington,
Va. 22206, or fax your request to (703) 931-4520. The college
offers a free fact sheet on heartburn, a brochure called ``Is It
Just a Little Heartburn _ or Something More Serious?'', a
nine-minute educational video, several leaflets and a list of
specialists in your state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
