<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALISTA-FLOCKHART-IN-MIDSUMMER-NIGHTS-DREAM-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIM CHANCE: CALISTA FLOCKHART SEES OPPORTUNITIES ON THE BIG
SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Calista Flockhart with Dominic West in a
scene from ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``I thought I would end up walking around wearing a big red `A'
for `Adulteress' and `Anorexic,''' Calista Flockhart says with a
sigh.
 &HT;    The star of the quirky-but-popular Fox series ``Ally McBeal''
has paid a price for her sudden fame that includes a barrage of
media intrusions, including speculation that she suffers from an
eating disorder and a recent, widely publicized rumor that she was
having an affair with ``Ally'' creator David E. Kelley, who's
married to Michelle Pfeiffer, Flockhart's co-star in her next film.
 &HT;    ``My feelings were hurt,'' she admits. ``I was frightened. I
thought it would potentially damage my career. Do I have to tell
you none of it was true? I guess a low point was when I read
something like I was starving my dog Webster so he would become
anorexic, too.''
 &HT;    Clad in a long, fitted, black coat and pants with a matching
sweater, Flockhart appears no more than fashionably thin. Nor does
she seem to have a chip on her shoulder about the press.
 &HT;    ``If you really read the tabloid stories, some of them are
clever and very imaginative,'' she says with a smile. ``I really
found some of them rather funny. I started thinking, `Gee, I should
begin to live vicariously through my own rumors, because they're so
much more exciting than my real life.'
 &HT;    ``I'm just trying to keep my sense of humor and not take it
personally,'' she adds. ``I keep reminding myself how many
opportunities `Ally McBeal' has afforded me.''
 &HT;    The biggest of those opportunities will appear on May 7, when
``William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream'' opens. ``Ally''
fans may be astounded to see the show's smart, savvy and often
insecure young Boston attorney spout Shakespeare, but actually
Flockhart was a stage veteran long before she hit the small screen.
Her credits include Broadway runs in ``The Glass Menagerie'' and
``The Three Sisters.''
 &HT;    ``There's a certain anonymity to the New York stage,'' she says,
``so I guess it's understandable that you get more noticed for
being in prime time. But I'd love to get past that _ I'm an actress
who has played a lot of different roles.''
 &HT;    In director Michael Hoffman's adaptation of ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream,'' which co-stars Kevin Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer,
Stanley Tucci and Rupert Everett, Flockhart plays the hopelessly
love-struck Helena, one of four mortals whose lives are changed by
the fairies who rule the forest.
 &HT;    ``What's so amazing,'' she says, ``is that Shakespeare wrote `A
Midsummer Night's Dream' centuries ago, and yet the Helena he
created is not unlike Ally in 1999. They are both young women who
are ambitious, driven and passionate. They want what they want, and
they lead with their hearts.
 &HT;    ``That commonality is, I think, a tribute to both Shakespeare's
and David Kelley's understanding of the feminine condition.''
 &HT;    She will, however, admit that Helena's obsessive attraction to
Demetrius might play differently in the contemporary world.
 &HT;    ``I hear people attaching labels like `co-dependent' to
Helena,'' she says. ``She's so obsessively fixated on Demetrius
that she can't help herself and she loses her pride. She's so
insecure that she's willing to do just about anything to get his
attention.
 &HT;    ``I couldn't say I've ever been that way,'' she adds. ``I
thought about how far I'd be willing to go for love and how much of
my pride and dignity I'd be willing to give up.
 &HT;    ``I do remember having some fixations on guys when I was young,
and it's not a fun place to be,'' she admits. ``But I've never said
anything close to Helena's line, `I'll be your dog.'''
 &HT;    Which is not an invitation to speculate about her love life.
 &HT;    ``I live with my dog Webster in the Hollywood hills,'' she says.
``I'm not preoccupied with getting married and having a family. I'm
certainly not panicked about it. If it happens, I think it will
happen when it's supposed to _ all in good time.''
 &HT;    Flockhart's two biggest challenges in ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' were mastering the bicycle she had to ride in crazy pursuit
of Demetrius and curbing her embarrassment in a scene where she and
the other lovers awake from their enchantment in a tangle of naked
bodies.
 &HT;    ``The bike was a big, heavy, old-fashioned antique that I had to
struggle with,'' she recalls. ``But it helped my performance,
because I could be sort of funny trying to ride around on it.''
 &HT;    As for the nudity, that wasn't so funny.
 &HT;    ``I made sure that the flowers covering strategic parts of my
body were glued on,'' she says, laughing. ``Thank God for long hair
and flower petals.
 &HT;    ``When you're doing something like that,'' Flockhart adds, ``you
just have to rely on your sense of humor to get you through it.''
 &HT;    Shakespeare is hot in Hollywood just now, which doesn't surprise
the actress.
 &HT;    ``If you think about characters like Hamlet and Juliet and Lady
Macbeth,'' she says, ``they seem very real. They're so human that
we can identify with them.''
 &HT;    Viewers often identify with Ally McBeal. On the other hand, if
they don't identify they're likely to hate her _ which is OK with
Flockhart.
 &HT;    ``Acting for me has always been about communicating and touching
people,'' she says. ``If a character I'm playing provokes a
reaction, even a debate, then it's really satisfying for me.''
 &HT;    One reaction the character provokes is a steady stream of fans
who can impose upon even a generally cheerful actress.
 &HT;    ``Most of them are wonderful,'' she says. ``They'll come up and
say things like, `Tell Ally she has a future. Tell her she'll get a
husband.' It's like they seem certain that I can get a message to
her.
 &HT;    ``The one thing I miss about the theater is the instant feedback
you get from an audience,'' she adds. ``When you're onstage you
have an immediate connection _ you know if they're coughing or if
they're laughing.
 &HT;    ``In television your only experience is doing the acting,''
Flockhart says. ``I rarely have a moment when I'm dying to rush
home and watch a completed episode. Whenever I get a response from
a fan, at least I know how they're reacting.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, Flockhart says, she welcomed the anonymity she
found in Rome while filming ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
 &HT;    ``For the first two weeks it was very freeing,'' she says.
``Nobody over there had ever heard of `Ally McBeal.' Michelle
Pfeiffer got mobbed, but I could go anywhere I wanted to.''
 &HT;    She smiles ruefully.
 &HT;    ``Unfortunately, American tourists arrived and, wouldn't you
know it, a lot of them were `Ally' fans. So my brief moment of not
being recognized was over.''
 c.1999 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf and Shep Morgan are Hollywood-based free-lance
writers.) &LR; 
