<HEADER>
A3662 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAN-HAYES-IN-WILL-&AMP;-     04-26 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAN-HAYES-IN-WILL-&AMP;-GRACE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK DANDY: SEAN HAYES BRINGS A TOUCH OF ZANINESS TO `WILL &AMP;
GRACE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Sean Hayes in a scene from ``Will &AMP;
Grace.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not so unusual for a supporting actor to earn bigger laughs
than a sitcom's leading man. In fact, it's something of a
television tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Art Carney and Don Knotts provided more yuks than headliners
Jackie Gleason and Andy Griffith, and it was Andy Kaufman, not Judd
Hirsch, who tickled us on ``Taxi.'' Jerry Seinfeld spent nine
seasons playing straight man to Michael Richards.
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition to the roster of top second bananas is Sean
Hayes of ``Will &AMP; Grace.'' As the self-absorbed Jack McFarland, the
gay best friend of Will Truman (Eric McCormack), Hayes has earned
across-the-board kudos for his boundless effervescence and saucy
irreverence.
</P>
<P>
   Since Hayes claims that he was ``born with the word `sitcom'
stamped on my head,'' perhaps such success was inevitable. Raised
in the affluent Chicago suburb of Glen Ellen, Ill., he grew up as a
television junkie, particularly influenced by ``Saturday Night
Live's'' revolving ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when people thought it was bad, I thought it was great,''
he says. ``I love the whole concept of sketch comedy. I think it
was made for people like me, because it's a little off and a little
bizarre. That was me growing up _ off-kilter and a little wacky.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting out in regional musical theater, Hayes graduated to
writing music for Chicago's celebrated Steppenwolf Theatre Company.
He spent two years in an acclaimed original work called ``Role
Play,'' and then made the move to Hollywood, where casting
directors were immediately taken with his quirky charm and boyish
good looks.
</P>
<P>
   Steady commercial work followed, culminating with appearances in
two 1998 Super Bowl ads _ as a henpecked husband thirsting for a
Bud Light and as an overeager Doritos fan.
</P>
<P>
   But not every gig was so high-profile. Like every performer,
Hayes has a story or two about the bad old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a funny actor story, right?'' he says, laughing.
``Well, mine is that I was an elf in the `Kenny Rogers Christmas
Show.' Every night we'd play in front of 20,000 people _ and I can
prove to you how little they cared: During our last performance we
were on stage singing our little Christmas songs, running around
like good little elves when, all of a sudden, the other guys
tackled me, sprayed me with adhesive and stuck fake snow all over
me. I looked like a tarred-and-feathered chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know what?'' he says, his eyes widening. ``Nobody
noticed. Nobody gave a crap. They just sat there waiting for Kenny
to come out and sing `Coward of the County.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though it's now evident that the role of Jack fits him like a
pair of spandex bike shorts, when the invitation to try out for
``Will &AMP; Grace'' first arrived, Hayes literally trashed it.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the actor says, he was busy touting his big-screen
debut in ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' at the Sundance Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually they wanted me to read for the part of Will,'' he
recalls, ``but all this exciting stuff was going on at Sundance,
and I didn't want to fly home just for an audition. So even though
I thought the script was great, I tossed it into the garbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when I got back to L.A., they called to say they'd found
their Will, but would I read for Jack? I said I'd love to.''
</P>
<P>
   The perennial problem for even the best second bananas is, of
course, that they tend to remain one-dimensional. That's why, now
that ``Will &AMP; Grace'' has been renewed for a second season, Hayes
is eager to have Jack evolve into more than a font of quips and bon
mots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like the audience to see other sides of him,'' he says,
``to see him in more real situations. I love the fact that Jack
drifts from job to job _ but what about the other people in his
life? Who does he relate to, other than Will? I want to explore
stuff like that, and I know it will come with time.''
</P>
<P>
   In an early episode, Will explained to a colleague that he
couldn't tolerate Jack as a roommate because ``he keeps odd hours,
he's got the energy of a ferret and he's messy.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Jack bemoaned his lack of ``me time,'' Will shot
back, ``all of your time is me time!''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to an oft-raised question: If Jack and Will are so
incompatible, why are they best friends?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting,'' McCormack says, ``because after the third
episode, my sister asked me, `Are you ever going to be nice to
Jack?' She was really concerned, and I told the writers. So now
there are more little moments when they show their affection for
one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really an opposites-attract thing,'' he adds.
``Will is very controlling, very passive-aggressive and, dare I use
the word, anal. He's a lawyer who deals with a lot of conservative
clients, and he doesn't have the opportunity to be flamboyant with
his sexuality the way that Jack can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it seems like Jack is just a setup for Will's
cutting remarks and vice versa,'' McCormack says. ``But I think
Will loves Jack's energy and loves how free he is and how much sex
he has.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack and Will fulfill something that the other doesn't have,''
Hayes agrees. ``Will is like a big brother, even though we're
almost the same age. He kind of looks out for me, and I need that.
For my part, I'm the free spirit that Will wishes he could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitcom stars always worry about being typecast if their show
succeeds, but Hayes says he isn't worrying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too late,'' he says, grinning. ``I already am. I swear to God,
every time I go to the grocery store, people yell out, `There's
Jack!'
</P>
<P>
   ``But am I concerned about that? It's something that's been
preying on my brain,'' he admits. ``There's always worry about
being stuck in TV-land, but there are ways around it. Once people
see me in at least one other light, they'll understand that I
didn't become an actor to play just one role.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hayes is perfectly content to appreciate the ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank God that I enjoy coming to work every day,'' he says.
``There's no attitude, no star trips. It's a very comfortable
atmosphere, with everybody here to help each other _ it's really
friendly and wonderful. It's well-written, well-performed comedy.
That's all we're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, these are characters that America's not used to seeing,
but our sole purpose is to entertain you and make you laugh. If you
like that, then tune in.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of TV Guide Canada.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' consult the
NBC Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; (Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
