<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMES-COBURN-IN-NOAHS-ARK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER OSCAR, THE DELUGE: JAMES COBURN FACES THE FLOOD IN `NOAH'S
ARK' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of James Coburn in a scene from ``Noah's
Ark.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    James Coburn has a new friend named Oscar.
 &HT;    ``He's great!'' Coburn says enthusiastically. ``He's sitting on
my table, and I'm looking at him right now.''
 &HT;    That would be a small golden statuette, of course, the Academy
Award for Best Supporting Actor which the Hollywood veteran won in
March for his performance as Nick Nolte's hard-driving, abusive
father in ``Affliction'' (1998).
 &HT;    The 70-year-old Coburn was overwhelmed when his name was called,
he says. Even worse was the pressure of delivering a thank-you
speech before literally millions of people.
 &HT;    ``You just get up there and start mumbling,'' he says by
telephone from his Los Angeles home. ``The first things that come
out of your mouth are the words you always figured you'd have to
say if you ever got up there.
 &HT;    ``Then the words just keep tumbling out,'' he says. ``For me, it
wasn't like, `Oh boy, am I ... !' There was just a very warm
feeling I got from everyone, and it hasn't stopped.
 &HT;    ``I still get calls from all over the world,'' the actor says,
``and I got so many flowers we started giving them to funeral
homes. Evidently a lot of people wanted me to win.
 &HT;    ``That moved me.''
 &HT;    Coburn's joy was tempered by the fact that Nolte, his
``Affliction'' co-star and close friend, lost the Best Actor
statuette to ``Life Is Beautiful's'' Roberto Benigni.
 &HT;    ``The clown was good,'' Coburn says. ``The film was really a
nice little film _ but Best Actor, for Christ's sake! He didn't
have to act. Put a red nose on him and ... ''
 &HT;    Coburn snorts.
 &HT;    ``Nick carried it with his incredible performance,'' he says.
``There was a subtlety to it, while my role was more of a bravura
kind of thing, with a lot of yelling and screaming.
 &HT;    ``I thought Nick was just dynamite.''
 &HT;    After Oscar, Coburn is remaining as busy as ever. His next gig
is a brief appearance as a chatty peddler in ``Noah's Ark,'' a
four-hour miniseries airing May 2 and 3 on NBC. Jon Voight stars as
the man chosen by God to build an ark, stock it with animals and
sail into the unknown, with Mary Steenburgen as Noah's wife, F.
Murray Abraham as a sinister Lot and Carol Kane as Lot's doomed
mate.
 &HT;    The tongue-in-cheek movie may not seem an obvious follow-up to
an Oscar win, but Coburn doesn't mind.
 &HT;    ``It was a trip to Australia, a chance to work with Jon and
Mary, and an interesting character,'' he says. ``The peddler has
some good lines and talks about things in a way that made me laugh.
The whole movie is not written in a deep, dark, end-of-the-world
way, but with great humor.''
 &HT;    It's not difficult to make an impact in a cameo, Coburn adds. In
fact, in some respects the brevity of the role enhances its impact.
 &HT;    ``It's not too hard if you have an interesting character,'' he
says. ``I tried to give the peddler a playful attitude and a
certain bravura.''
 &HT;    Coburn recently finished another television project,
``Atticus,'' in which he stars as a rancher trying to understand
why his son committed suicide. The telemovie will air early next
year.
 &HT;    Like ``Noah's Ark,'' ``Atticus'' is a role to which the actor
had committed before he won his Oscar. His post-Oscar roles will
have to be chosen carefully, but he says that so far he's simply
been too busy to sort out his next move.
 &HT;    ``We're getting a lot of scripts coming in,'' Coburn says. ``But
I was doing `Atticus,' and I'm suffering from a sinus infection
that has been a bitch to get rid of.
 &HT;    ``I just haven't had time to read anything.''
 &HT;    Coburn has read countless scripts in his day. He's appeared in
scores of films, from classics such as ``The Magnificent Seven''
(1960), ``The Last of Sheila'' (1973) and ``The President's
Analyst'' (1967) to bombs such as ``Convoy'' (1978) and ``Hudson
Hawk'' (1991).
 &HT;    The actor was a favorite of maverick director Sam Peckinpah, for
whom he starred in ``Pat Garrett and Billy the Kid'' (1973) and
``Cross of Iron'' (1977). Perhaps his best-known role, however, was
as a superspy in the James Bond spoofs ``Our Man Flint'' (1966) and
``In Like Flint'' (1967).
 &HT;    Peckinpah was the best director he ever worked with, Coburn
believes.
 &HT;    ``I loved Sam,'' he says. ``Sam would say, `Say that line again.
Say that goddamn line again!' He was like an old-time director in
that sense.
 &HT;    ``Sam wanted everything imperfect, because life was imperfect,''
Coburn adds. ``He hated violence, and therefore he made violence
his trademark.''
 &HT;    On the negative side, Coburn sees the comic caper film ``Hudson
Hawk,'' directed by Michael Lehmann and starring Bruce Willis as a
cat burglar, as probably the worst outing of his career.
 &HT;    ``I said to Michael Lehmann, `Do you know how to do this style?'
and he said, `If I don't, we're really in a lot of trouble,'''
Coburn says. ``As it turned out, we were already in a lot of
trouble, because he didn't know what the f--k to do.
 &HT;    ``Willis wrote the story,'' he says. ``We didn't have a director
_ we had seven directors, because everybody who had an idea was a
director
 &HT;    ``Poor Lehmann,'' the actor says with a sigh. ``He was in over
his head, and the reason he was in over his head was that Willis
and (producer) Joel Silver wanted to direct it themselves. They had
somebody there who'd be the patsy.''
 &HT;    Of all his films, Coburn considers Peckinpah's World War II
drama ``Cross of Iron'' the most underrated. Coburn and Maximilian
Schell starred as German soldiers who disagreed not only about how
to fight the Russians, but also about life in general.
 &HT;    ``Max and I said to Sam, `This scene really sucks. What are you
going to do with it?''' Coburn recalls. ``Sam said, `Well, write a
better one.'
 &HT;    ``I wrote my side and tried to bring some philosophical content
to it,'' he says, ``and Max wrote a tome! He wrote about 20 pages
from a three-page scene. Max was great.''
 &HT;    Lately, Coburn has spent most of his time playing rascals _ some
likable, some not _ in such films as ``Sister Act 2'' (1993),
``Maverick'' (1994), ``The Nutty Professor'' (1996) and ``Payback''
(1999). The roles have been engaging but not especially demanding,
nor particularly challenging for an actor as capable as
``Affliction'' showed him to be.
 &HT;    Doesn't he wish the Oscar _ and the opportunities for meatier
roles it will likely bring him _ had come his way years ago?
 &HT;    Not necessarily, Coburn says.
 &HT;    ``It might have been more valuable 20 years ago,'' he concedes.
``That it came at all is all right with me. Better late than never,
as they always say. It probably would have changed things along the
way, had it happened earlier.
 &HT;    ``I don't know,'' he concludes. ``Let's see if it changes
anything now.''
 &HT;    For the time being, he's simply keeping his eyes on the future.
 &HT;    ``I'm looking for a comedy, and I'm looking for more films that
have some significance,'' he says. ``In a perfect world, I'd love
to do two films a year for the next five or six years and then hang
up my spurs.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
