<HEADER>
A3665 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDAN-QUINN-IN-THIS-I     04-26 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDAN-QUINN-IN-THIS-IS-MY-FATHER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDAN QUINN'S FAMILY AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Aidan Quinn with Donal Donnelly in a
scene from ``This Is My Father.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    To begin with, this isn't his father.
 &HT;    But that doesn't mean Aidan Quinn's new movie, ``This Is My
Father,'' is mere Irish blarney.
 &HT;    It's based on a story that his mother, Teresa Quinn, used to
tell her young sons Aidan, Declan, Paul and Robert around the fire
on cold winter nights, a story about two lovers separated by class
and religion in 1930s Ireland. The young man is sent away, never
knowing that his lover subsequently gives birth to their son, and
the truth is not revealed for decades, until the now-middle-aged
son comes across an old photograph and realizes the truth.
 &HT;    And yes, it's a true story. True, and powerful enough to have
drawn Quinn and his two brothers together on a film for the first
time. ``This is My Father,'' opening on May 7, is a real family
affair.
 &HT;    Quinn plays the exiled Irish lover, whose story is told in
flashbacks, with James Caan as his grown son, an Irish-American
schoolteacher who returns to Ireland looking for answers about his
murky past.
 &HT;    It wasn't their family, but the Quinns could all relate to the
story.
 &HT;    ``My grandfather actually carried the coffin of the young suitor
in the movie,'' Quinn says. ``So he was known to our family. And,
like any good Irish story, it got passed down until it became
lore.''
 &HT;    Paul Quinn wrote the screenplay, which was directed by Declan
Quinn, the Oscar-winning cinematographer of ``Leaving Las Vegas''
(1995). Even younger sister Marian has a cameo.
 &HT;    ``The only people in the family we missed were our parents and
our brother Robert,'' Quinn says with a laugh, over coffee at Los
Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't like as brothers we had this big dream of working
together,'' he adds. ``Even though we're each in the business, we
never even talked about teaming up. It just kind of happened.''
 &HT;    The trigger was his brother's script.
 &HT;    ``He sent it to me,'' Quinn recalls, ``and I just fell apart
reading it. I was so blown away by it, I said, `I'll do anything I
can to help you get this movie made,'''
 &HT;    That almost wasn't enough.
 &HT;    ``Everyone in town turned it down,'' Quinn says. ``We threw
everything into this project _ it became a quest. We wouldn't take
no for an answer.
 &HT;    ``I guess no one thought it was commercial,'' he adds. ``We kept
hearing, `This is too dark.' It was the usual litany of
cowardliness and gutlessness by the major players.''
 &HT;    Finally Sony Classics picked up the film, which became a hit at
the Toronto Film Festival.
 &HT;    ``We knew audiences would love this movie, and we weren't
disappointed by the response,'' Quinn says. ``Afterward, we had so
many people saying, `Let me tell you about my family.'''
 &HT;    The Quinns could probably make 10 films about their own family,
actually.
 &HT;    ``My parents are both from Ireland,'' Quinn says. ``We moved up
and back from Chicago to Belfast. Initially, the first time, we
moved to Ireland because my father couldn't find work in Chicago.
So he sent my mother back to Ireland with the kids while he looked
for a job.
 &HT;    ``The second time we moved to Ireland was a sabbatical leave,''
he says. ``My father was a junior-college teacher, and he got a
leave to study in Ireland. So we'd do a year here, a year there.''
 &HT;    After high school Quinn settled in Chicago, where he found a job
as a roofer. One subzero winter day, however, he paused in
shingling and glanced at his fellow workers who were chugging down
booze to keep warm. Then and there, he decided to change jobs.
 &HT;    An acting workshop got him started, and local plays soon led to
bigger opportunities, including his movie debut in the biker film
``Reckless'' (1984).
 &HT;    ``It was my first time on screen, and I was supposed to look
cool on a motorcycle,'' Quinn recalls. ``The truth of the matter is
that I had white foam on both sides of my mouth from nerves. It got
so bad that, as I was speaking, there were white strings coming out
of my mouth.
 &HT;    ``We had to repeatedly cut while I asked for water.''
 &HT;    ``Reckless'' was a minor hit, however, and Quinn soon found
himself in Hollywood, co-starring with Madonna in ``Desperately
Seeking Susan'' (1985). But despite his leading-man looks and
dreamy, blue-eyed gaze he was still a ways from movie-star cool.
 &HT;    ``I walked into a little sushi restaurant with Martin
Scorsese,'' he recalls. ``When we walked down an aisle, everyone's
face started turning. I thought, `Wow, L.A. is really weird _ even
the directors are so famous that everyone turns and looks at them.'
 &HT;    ``So we sat down,'' he continues, ``and I opened the menu and
said to this woman sitting next to me, `Look, you've got to help
me, because I've never had sushi before in my life and I just don't
know what to order.'
 &HT;    ``I looked up, and the woman was Barbra Streisand,'' Quinn says.
``So I yelled at the top of my lungs, `Oh my God, you're Barbra
Streisand!' And I was so loud that three tables over people were
hysterically laughing.''
 &HT;    P.S., he got the sushi.
 &HT;    ``She ordered for me, and I've been eating sushi ever since,
thanks to Barbra Streisand,'' Quinn says. ``I felt I had arrived.''
 &HT;    A variety of movies followed, with the most successful including
``Stakeout'' (1987), ``Avalon'' (1990), ``Benny &AMP; Joon'' (1993) and
``Legends of the Fall'' (1994).
 &HT;    Along the way, he also got married, to actress Elizabeth Bracco.
That fact has complicated his career, he admits.
 &HT;    ``I do hate to see him do love stories,'' Bracco says in a
separate interview, ``because I want to send Aidan to the Clark
Gable school of movie kissing to teach him not to use his tongue.''
 &HT;    Told of her comment, Quinn whoops.
 &HT;    ``Did she really say that?'' he says, laughing. ``Oh, she's a
pisser.''
 &HT;    He laughs again.
 &HT;    ``I wish you would tell my wife that everyone in Hollywood uses
their tongue _ you can't get away with those old-movie kisses
anymore,'' he says. ``Besides, kissing onscreen is the only fun you
get to have when you're married.''
 &HT;    He chuckles, clearly not serious.
 &HT;    ``She does hate watching the sex scenes,'' the actor adds after
a moment. ``Some actors get the death grip from their wives. I also
get the elbow to the stomach.''
 &HT;    His brothers are even tougher critics, and ``This Is My Father''
had its share of arguments.
 &HT;    ``Aidan is a very internal actor,'' Paul Quinn says in a
separate interview. ``I would go to him and start to say, `You
know, Aidan, we need to do it this way ... ' And he would cut me
off and say, `I know, I know.'
 &HT;    ``But then he would do it exactly as I wanted.''
 &HT;    Actually, Aidan Quinn says, there were moments when he yearned
for the days of childhood, when the Quinn boys would settle things
with a push and a shove and a roll in the dust.
 &HT;    ``I was always older and stronger, so I always won,'' he says
with a laugh. ``Now we're professionals, so we just talk it out.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``This Is My Father,'' consult
the Sony Entertainment Website at www.sony.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
