<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RUSSIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALIA ARGUES THAT RUSSIA IS SLOWER THAN EUROPE, NOT UNIQUE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RUSSIA UNDER WESTERN EYES 
From the Bronze Horseman to the Lenin Mausoleum 
By Martin Malia 
Belknap/Harvard University Press, 514 pp., $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For centuries, observers of Russia have fallen into two grand
camps: those who view the vast country as ``Eastern,'' the land of
Scythians and Tatars, of obscurantism and despotism; and a minority
that views it as part of the outer reaches of Europe, imbued with
aspects of Western culture (though lacking liberal, democratic
institutions), a backwater, to be sure, but not a riddle, mystery
or enigma incomprehensibly alien to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Observers from the first camp subdivide on Russia's Soviet
experiment. Moscow's seven decades of communism are regarded either
as the natural outgrowth of czarist autocracy or as its perversion,
a utopian experiment gone deadly wrong thanks to the legacy of
backwardness left by the czars. Either view of the Soviet Union
configures Russia as irredeemably ``other.''
</P>
<P>
   In an elegant intellectual history that rubs the dust off those
lenses, the historian Martin Malia turns his eye to the European
cultural, political, and social traditions that have produced
assessments of Russia within those two broad molds. ``Russia Under
Western Eyes'' holds up a two-way mirror that sheds light not just
on Russia but on Europe's own cultures and institutions, from the
Enlightenment to fascism.
</P>
<P>
   To Malia, Russia, far from being essentially different from the
West, is part of an West-East cultural gradient, a concept that
posits Europe not as split between East and West but rather as a
single spectrum, with zones from developed to primitive.
</P>
<P>
   A seasoned Russia scholar, Malia considers Peter the Great's
victory over Sweden at Poltava in 1709 as the launch of Russia's
westward trajectory. That triumph, coupled with Peter's founding of
St. Petersburg as a ``window onto the West'' and development of
bureaucracy and policing, marked Russia's birth as a European power
within the Old Regime tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Catherine the Great's accession in 1762, an early
generation of ``philosophes,'' led by Voltaire, fell in love with
Russia and declared the country a model of enlightened monarchy
working to overcome cultural ``backwardness.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Catherine orchestrated two wars with Turkey,
three partitions of Poland, and a proposal to drive the Turks out
of Europe. While the communist-fearing West would later regard
similarly expansionist moves by the Soviet Union as a menace to
civilization, European observers had few problems with Catherine's
forays. Imperialism, whether Russian or European, was regarded as
the civilizing of barbarous lands and the normal course of
statecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Malia thus provides evidence early on that Western responses to
Russia are shaped less by what Russia actually does and more by the
cultural and ideological conditions through which the West views
those actions _ a very different argument from saying that Russia
is inherently expansionist (or inherently anything at all).
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Malia writes that ``Russia's imperial career during
these four centuries was in many ways the Eastern front of what may
be called the European conquest of the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 19th century, most of Europe had been convulsed by the
French Revolution in 1789 and thrown off the Old Regime. Not
Russia. The West viewed Alexander I as underpinning a bankrupt old
order, a despot ruling a barbarous land of serfs. By 1830, when
Nicholas I repressed a major Polish uprising, Russia was seen as
alien and out of step with the liberalizing times. In his widely
read travelogue, the marquis de Custine ignored the flowering of
Russian literature under Pushkin and Gogol and denigrated Russia as
an Asiatic outpost.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the 19th century, the West donned new
spectacles. Russia's intelligentsia, inspired by German Romanticism
and French radicalism, was seen as working to enact European-style
revolution and change. By the time of the Bolshevik Revolution in
1917, Russia is viewed as embodying Europe's most progressive and
egalitarian ideal, Socialism.
</P>
<P>
   That changes with the birth of the Soviet era and its camps and
annihilation of civil society. For most of the 20th century, the
West has viewed Russia as an aberration and a threat.
</P>
<P>
   In an era where liberal economics and static rational choice
models are often the spectacles through which the world is viewed,
Malia offers a reminder of the power of culture to shape ideas and
outcomes. But he falls short by reverting to an essentialistic
determinism about history in general and Russia in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Under Malia's eyes, post-Soviet Russia will eventually produce a
civil society and liberal culture. After arguing that culture
shapes analytical frameworks which in turn shape policies and
actions _ a process hardly teleological or linear _ his seems an
oddly deterministic conclusion. In fact, as it tracks the ebbs and
flows of Western images of Russia and ponders Moscow's recent
failure with market reforms, Malia's analysis points less to a
country converging with the West and more to one always dancing
around its edges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
