<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRDSATRISK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS DEVELOPMENT EDGES OUT RARE BIRDS, AUDUBON PINPOINTS MOST
VULNERABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas is for the birds. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   More bird species nest in, or migrate through, the Lone Star
State than any other state in the Union. Bird watchers have noted
615 species in Texas since records have been kept. The avian
abundance drew naturalist John James Audubon to Galveston in 1837.
</P>
<P>
   But the specialized habitats these birds require are fast
shrinking, primarily due to development, according to
conservationists. To coincide with Earth Day (last Thursday) and
Audubon's birthday Monday, the National Audubon Society has
released 50 state WatchLists calling attention to birds in jeopardy
of becoming endangered or threatened species. (The full reports are
available at www.audubon.org).
</P>
<P>
   National Audubon dubs the effort ``preventative medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't wait until a patient gets cancer to remedy the
situation,'' said Noreen Damude, director of bird conservation with
the Texas Audubon Society. ``You do the HMO thing: You monitor, you
manage, you watch the population and nip things in the bud.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Damude, we chose to highlight nine Texas
WatchList species of high or extremely high priority, plus the
Franklin's Gull, a national WatchList bird that migrates through
Texas in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FRANKLIN'S GULL
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Migrates through central and coastal Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: Common gull of the prairies _ not the
kind picking hot dog buns out of the Dumpster in the beach parking
lot, notes Damude. This gull spends winters as far south as Chile
and summers in Canada and the Northern Midwest, but stops over in
Texas on its annual migrations.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Loss of stopover habitat, such as prairie
wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SWAINSON'S WARBLER
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Hardwood forests, woodland swamps and canebrake along
the Texas coast.
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: ``A skulker, seldom seen,'' notes a
``Field Guide to the Birds of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Brown-headed cowbirds, who lay their eggs in
the warblers' nests. Not recognizing the difference, the warblers
incubate both sets of eggs. Upon hatching, the aggressive cowbird
chicks eat more food and make more noise, causing the warblers to
ignore their own chicks, who eventually die. Also, collisions with
towers and lighthouses. Habitat loss.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   HENSLOW'S SPARROW
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Wet shrubby fields of East Texas (a subpopulation near
Houston is possibly extinct).
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: Low, jerky flight.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Habitat loss due to suburban development and
farming practices.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   AUDUBON'S ORIOLE (formerly called black-headed oriole)
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Tropical bird found in far South Texas brush country.
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: Nests in a pouch of green grass hung
in a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: The bronzed cowbird does the same thing to this
oriole that the brown-headed cowbird does to the Swainson's
warbler. Also, habitat loss.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LESSER PRAIRIE CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: The high and rolling plains of the Panhandle
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: Male has yellow eye combs and a
reddish neck pouch.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Habitat loss.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHUCK-WILL'S-WIDOW
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Woodlands of Central and East Texas
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: Nocturnal insectivores, the bird flies
at night with its mouth open, ``like a vacuum cleaner in the sky,''
said Damude.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Nesting on the ground makes them vulnerable to
predators. Habitat loss.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   REDDISH EGRET
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Shallow, open salt pans of the Texas Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: ``Dances'' while feeding, with wings
spread in a canopy.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Hunted for their breeding plumage in the early
1900s (they went extinct in Florida), they have never quite
recovered. Increased salinity of the waterways where the bird
fishes has damaged its food supply. Also, destruction of wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PAINTED BUNTING
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Low thickets and woodland borders of the Hill Country
to the eastern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: Splendiferous color of the male.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Captured as cage birds. Habitat loss.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BACHMAN'S SPARROW
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Long-leaf pine forests of East Texas. The birds like
forest floors clear of shrubs and saplings _ in other words,
forests that experience fires on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: Its beautiful song, an introductory
note followed by a trill.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Habitat loss due to forest-fire prevention.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN PLOVER
</P>
<P>
   Habitat: Dry uplands of the Davis Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Defining characteristics: A fast runner that rarely flies.
</P>
<P>
   Primary threats: Drought. Habitat loss due to ranching
practices.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   These 75 birds are in jeopardy of becoming endangered or
threatened species:  &QL;
</P>
