</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKEELLINGTON-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100 YEARS AFTER HIS BIRTH, DUKE ELLINGTON'S SWINGING MUSIC STILL
REIGNS
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by ELLINGTON-CENTENNIAL, ESSENTIAL ELLINGTON,
ELLINGTON-CHRONOLOGY) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go back.
</P>
<P>
   Go back to the '40s, the Golden Days; train travel was tops,
doors were left unlocked and radio was king. Go back to find Duke
Ellington and band onstage somewhere in the night; somewhere
perfume and sweat and saxophone solos float side-by-side in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's out front, impeccably dressed and regal as a prince _
behind him, the orchestra goes from unstoppable swing on
``Happy-Go-Lucky Local'' and ``Daybreak Express'' to a soft, satiny
blues and back again. Dancers spin and sweat and fly, and through
it all Duke smiles, taking care of business, the band's sweet,
jazzy hum purring like a sports car. When it's all over, he'll
climb aboard another train, ride to some other town to dream, to
write, always to write, filling the coffers of American song with
some of the most sophisticated, enduring jazz ever heard.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Ellington swung, and the world swung with him _ for more
than 50 years, from high-school dances to Carnegie Hall to
cathedrals to concert halls in London and Paris. And still the
world heeds the call. Still, we want to get out there and shake a
tail feather to ``Take the ``A'' Train'' and ``C Jam Blues'' and
sway with our sweetie to ``Rocks in My Bed.'' Still, the young
musicians learn the charts and pore over the crackly old
recordings, and still the soul is soothed by tunes such as ``Come
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   One hundred years after his birth in Washington, D.C., and 25
years after his death in New York City, the world is loving Edward
Kennedy ``Duke'' Ellington all over again, loving him with an
intensity not seen since the '40s, when he and his crack band
defined big-band, swinging jazz and left the blueprint hundreds of
other groups would follow.
</P>
<P>
   This only makes sense, as Ellington was always resolutely part
of his time and usually well ahead of it. His bands always included
the finest musicians of the day, from trumpeter Cootie Williams to
saxophonist Johnny Hodges to bassist Jimmy Blanton.
</P>
<P>
   And in an era when recordings were defined by three-minute songs
on brittle 78-rpm records, he wrote ``Black, Brown and Beige,'' a
50-minute piece detailing the movement of African-Americans from
the shores of America to the Harlem Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington became a legend and a pivotal figure in jazz before he
was 35 and an ambassador of American music years before he and his
band members could even eat at the same lunch counters or drink out
of the same water fountains as many of the people who bought their
records.
</P>
<P>
   Men admired him, and women loved him: He was a man of the world,
a profile of style, sophistication and success at a time when many
African-Americans were leaving the poverty and oppression of the
Deep South to find new homes, new careers and new freedom in
far-flung cities such as New York, Los Angeles, Chicago and
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no ambition to reach some intellectual plateau and look
down on people,'' he said in 1959. ``I only want what any other
American artist wants _ and that is freedom of expression and of
communication with our audience.''
</P>
<P>
   He got it _ and now homage is paid all over again.
</P>
<P>
   The Ellington centennial is being marked by celebrations from
coast to coast, dozens of performances and workshops by Jazz at
Lincoln Center, a PBS special with live performances by the Wynton
Marsalis-led Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra, and numerous reissues
of much of his classic music.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way is the Tuesday release of the largest boxed set
in jazz history, a 24-CD monster detailing his RCA Victor
recordings, which stretched from 1927 to 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Pulitzer Prize committee gave Ellington a
special citation recognizing ``his musical genius in the medium of
jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   And along with all this comes a real sense of again appreciating
all that the man did: There was, first of all, the enormous number
of compositions _ such as ``Mood Indigo,'' ``Sophisticated Lady''
and ``Daybreak Express'' _ that became absolute jazz standards.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the variety. Ellington wrote everything: popular
dance tunes; suites honoring Harlem, the Deep South and
Shakespeare, among others; soundtracks; ballads; religious music;
and more.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there's his amazing longevity as a band leader.
Ellington kept an orchestra together for 50 years, along the way
employing some of the greatest names in jazz _ Cootie Williams, Ben
Webster, Johnny Hodges, Jimmy Blanton, Louie Bellson and Paul
Gonsalves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jazz is the only American art form _ it originated on American
soil,'' said Rob Gibson, executive producer and director of Jazz at
Lincoln Center. ``If we have a great composer in our art form _ our
Shakespeare, our Goethe _ Ellington is it. He is one of America's
great creative voices. One of our slogans is, `All jazz is modern'
and he's still modern _ he made 20th-century music.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   And it is precisely the variety of what the man wrote that makes
widespread celebrations of his birth so natural. According to jazz
producer and writer Orrin Keepnews, Ellington is so fundamental to
the history of modern music that ``his genius isn't questioned by
anybody, which only happens at the highest level of art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about an Ellington or a Picasso,'' said
Keepnews, coordinating producer of the RCA mega-box. ``And people
in jazz are pleased to have a concrete, universally recognized
opportunity to make a fuss over Ellington. The American public
loves to play numbers games, and here's a perfect opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   That Ellington was such a nice man certainly doesn't hurt. Two
people who worked with him _ gospel singer Queen Esther Marrow and
Dallas composer/band leader Randall Keith Horton _ both recall his
quiet confidence and gentleness as much as his talent.
</P>
<P>
   To Marrow, who performed with him in the '60s, he was ``a very
easy, quiet person _ he didn't say much, but when he did, my
goodness, he said a lot. He had eyes that could look right through
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Horton first met Ellington in the '60s and was his composing and
conducting assistant for three months in 1973. Even then, near the
very end, he was ``very energetic and businesslike,'' Horton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the boss and he was in charge, but there was a lot of
humor,'' said Horton, who will lecture on Ellington at Fort Worth
Country Day School on Thursday. ``I'm gonna tell you, it was like I
was 10 years old _ I'd breathe every three days. Once. But he
talked as though he knew me forever. He had so much vigor and
vitality.''
</P>
<P>
   But what is his importance for young people now? Enormous, when
one considers how popular swing music is these days: Ellington, it
should be remembered, made his name as a leader of a band that
played for dancers, and his music was rooted in the rhythms of New
Orleans as much as the stride piano players, such as Fats Waller
and Willie ``The Lion'' Smith, who congregated in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Ellington was famous for writing for individual band
members, for doing songs (or rearranging songs he'd already
recorded) to fit the strengths of the players in his band at that
moment. Because he kept band members for so long, he could tailor
his music to their strengths.
</P>
<P>
   And this makes his music invaluable to young musicians, said Tom
Burchill, jazz studies director at Weatherford Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you learn one Ellington tune, you learn all about jazz,''
said Burchill. ``With his music, you think about volume and colors.
Everybody in his band had a unique voice _ everybody sounded
different. Cootie Williams was hired just to play plunger on the
trumpet _ that bluesy wah-waaaaaah sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``His band was a community, and when you learn one of his pieces
you have to copy, in a sense, these individual voices. So it gets
kids thinking about the nuances. His music is never above your
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Endlessly accessible and inventive, and evoking a vanished, more
innocent America, his is music that still sounds at home wherever
jazz is played. Duke Ellington created a world unto himself, but
one that we are all still welcome to.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
