<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MOUNTAINS-BOS &LR;      04-26 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MOUNTAINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SIMPLE POIGNANT NOVEL THAT ROAMS WITH ITS CENTRAL CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
EAST OF THE MOUNTAINS 
By David Guterson. Harcourt Brace. 279 pp. $25. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geography is a vast metaphor for some writers and an anchor for
others: Whether sky or river or a rush-hour subway, the physical
palpability of place tells us where, and therefore who, we are. For
David Guterson, place is the point itself: the sine qua non of his
fiction, abundant and overpowering and utterly in charge of
whatever unfolds there. His first novel, ``Snow Falling on
Cedars,'' was admired for its riveting portrait of an entire island
community over two generations, but it was the feel of San Piedro
Island _ its fishing and strawberry industries, its fog-bound
grievances and thwarted hopes _ that made the story so indelibly
haunting.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that Guterson's setting of choice, both in
fiction and reality, is Washington state, where the great frontier
odysseys of American history ended abruptly, halted by an ocean
boundary and no doubt by beauty itself. Now myth and mystique live
there hand in hand, along with ornery, elegant stories of the
people who kept going until they simply couldn't go any farther.
That's a fitting thematic landscape for Ben Givens, who is
terminally ill and seems hellbent and determined to walk half of
the state before he dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``East of the Mountains'' is an ode to the apple country hemmed
in by the Cascades: tattered by strip malls and trailers but still
awesomely lovely; cultivated and reshaped by orchardists but
nonetheless larger than anyone who ever tried to claim it. We don't
often see this piece of the Great Northwest in fiction; it's too
much a jumble of isolation, human aggression, and mountainous
dominion to lend itself to easy translation. If gold indeed has
resided within those quiet peaks, not all that many writers have
been tempted to describe it.
</P>
<P>
   Next to its predecessor, Guterson's second novel is a smaller
story, and its shortcomings will inevitably be compared to the
ambition of ``Snow Falling on Cedars.'' But in focusing upon the
struggles of a man at the end of his days, ``East of the
Mountains'' strips itself clean of some of the overwriting and
suspense-ridden hooks that ``Cedars'' suffered from. This is a
simply derived, mostly poignant novel that roams the remote world
of fruit harvesting in central Washington; because of Ben Givens's
perspective, the land shimmers with a particular vision usually
afforded only those who are having to relinquish it.
</P>
<P>
   A retired heart surgeon in Seattle, Ben is still mourning the
death of his beloved Rachel, to whom he was married for a
half-century, when he is diagnosed with cancer of the colon. He has
a daughter and grandchildren nearby, but he remains stunned by the
implausibility of life without Rachel, and his prognosis _ less
than a year to live, most of it promising terrible pain _ persuades
him to wrest the wheel from death by killing himself. In the
opening pages of the novel, he is organizing this mission with the
careful precision that often anticipates suicide: He plans to take
his two Brittany spaniels and his Winchester rifle into the breaks
on the other side of the mountains, where he'll go bird hunting one
last time, then arrange his shooting death to look like an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   This darkly meticulous plan, which involves freeing his dogs and
saying a veiled goodbye to his family, goes awry almost from the
beginning, as it obviously must in order to provide us with a
novel. His four-wheel-drive packed to the hilt with dogs and
hunting paraphernalia, Ben has an accident on the freeway that
leaves him injured, badly shaken, and without a vehicle. And so
begins his real odyssey, a journey of picaresque mishaps that pave
the way for several wayfaring strangers to appear _ most of whom
will teach Ben something he needs to know about death or the living
that precedes it. His saga unfolds in cross cuts with his memories;
as he makes his way across the orchard lands of his childhood, he's
transported back to the harvest where he fell in love with Rachel,
then the second World War that took them both to the front _ her as
a nurse, him as a rifle infantryman. He has to confront the
equivocal legacy of his family's affection for hunting; his own
skills and limitations as a physician; the reasons he can and
cannot tolerate living one more day. Throughout this hopeless
pilgrimage he carries the humiliations and ironies of his body's
surrender: As a man who devoted a lifetime to the human heart, he
finds his own unequipped to handle the fact of his mortality.
</P>
<P>
   But what ought to be most moving about ``East of the Mountains''
turns out to be its greatest weakness. Ben's ambivalence about
suicide is pain-racked and topsy-turvy; one moment he can't bear
another moment of consciousness, the next he can't imagine leaving
it. While this state of wild uncertainty is not uncommon to
suicidality, here it's delivered with whimsy instead of volatility.
The melodramatic shorthand with which Guterson conveys these mood
swings make Ben seem capricious, rather than tormented, even though
it's plenty evident from his character that he has spent his life
being a deliberate man. A few similar glitches in plot feel
hurried, particularly a predictable denouement that could have been
conceived on ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Such failures seem unnecessary, partly because Guterson is a
writer of some depth: You can feel the thoughtfulness behind this
novel, even when it suffers weaknesses of style and dialogue. He
has a wonderful eye for the arcane fact, as well as the ability to
describe it: The materiel stacked along the roads leading to the
Italian front, for instance, ``resembled a kind of wooden hedge too
high to see over.'' Ben's war memories, in fact, are chillingly
conveyed, as is the terrifying scene when his dogs are attacked by
a coyote-hunting pack of Irish wolfhounds. High-pitched action
scenes are no small victory, and Guterson has a remarkable touch
with them; these moments give us Ben in his aged entirety, and make
him seem all the more heroic in his final battle.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, of course, the way ``East of the Mountains'' begins
and will end _ with a man's last tour of duty, traveling back to
the orchards he cherished as a boy and the memories of the
brown-skinned girl he met there. So east of the mountains, in
Guterson's world of sovereign landscape, really is the other side:
the place that never retreats in the imagination, the place for
which we always yearn. ``And I am become like dust and ashes,'' Ben
reads from Job, having stumbled upon a Gideon's Bible in a bleak
motel. In describing the world of a dying man, Guterson invokes the
ultimate book of suffering _ then, to his great credit, offers it
here as consolation rather than despair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
