<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NATO-KOSOVO (Washington) _ The head of NATO's military arm says
the alliance will not use force in the Adriatic Sea to choke off
oil supplies headed to Yugoslavia. So how a fuel embargo, which
NATO announced last weekend, would be enforced is unclear. During
their three-day summit here, NATO leaders hotly debated the use of
firepower in connection with the embargo. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Amid diplomatic efforts to end the
conflict in Yugoslavia, NATO aircraft attack bridges in a bid to
stem Serbian troop movements into Kosovo. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CAPTIVES (Washington) _ Almost a month into their
captivity, the head of the International Committee of the Red Cross
sees three U.S. soldiers but does not conduct a full interview. The
Red Cross official, Cornelio Sommaruga, gives no detail on the
physical condition of the GIs and says he hopes a doctor can see
them on Tuesday. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-TOBACCO (Washington) _ Days after tobacco billboards were
made illegal, the Supreme Court agrees to hear a case that could
result in a further crackdown on cigarette advertising and
marketing. The justices will examine whether the Food and Drug
Administration has the authority to regulate tobacco products. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-IMMIGRANTS (Washington) _ In a case that pits organized
labor against a noncitizen, the Supreme Court agrees to decide if
federal anti-discrimination law on contract rights protects foreign
nationals living or working in the United States. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Investigators are
questioning a teen-age girl who may have helped Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold buy the weapons they used in last week's mass
killings. A diary belonging to one of the boys may also be
released. By LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GUNS (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush, in the wake of
the Colorado school shooting, endorses legislation that would
require instant criminal background checks of people who purchase
weapons at gun shows. Only hours later, a state House committee
kills such a bill. A similar bill is languishing in a Senate
committee. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PLOT (San Marcos, Texas) _ Three teen-age suspects face a
court hearing in connection with their arrest over the weekend for
allegedly plotting to blow up their middle school. By THADDEUS
HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   SPACESUITS-GIRLS (Houston) _ Two young girls, one from Honduras
and the other from Crosby, Texas, are being presented NASA
spacesuits to help them cope with troublesome skin diseases. By
RUTH RENDON. (Photos will be available on the NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-BILLS (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas Senate is expected to
work on a batch of crime-related bills, including legislation that
would allow the police to confiscate the driver's license of anyone
who refuses a breathalyzer test. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ When you apply for law school or
medical school, you typically have to pay an application fee. But
pay a fee to apply for a job? Several airlines actually charge the
people who apply for jobs as pilots anywhere from $50 to $150 for
the privilege. By L.M. SIXEL
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ With that all Congress has to do
this year, why is it wasting its time on yet another effort to ban
flag-burning? By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ A funny thing has happened to
Gov. George W. Bush on his way to a carefully scripted race for the
Republican presidential nomination. More and more questions are
being asked about his leadership credentials. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ In what likely will be a preview of
their first-round playoff series, the Houston Rockets and Los
Angeles Lakers meet at Compaq Center in a contest between two
struggling teams. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
