<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      04-26 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE COMES A TIME IN LIFE TO SHUN RISK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both 60 and will retire in about a year.
Our assets include various IRAs invested as follows: $390,000 in a
money market fund, $90,000 in Loomis Sayles Bond fund, $280,000 in
Vanguard Star fund, $200,000 in Vanguard Intermediate Bond fund,
and $90,000 in US Treasury strips. We also have $450,000 in stock
that we plan to use for our grandchildren's education. Our cash
reserves are $70,000 in a tax-free money market account. I'd like
to restructure the retirement funds so that we can draw upon the
accounts, but also realize growth. We would need about $70,000 a
year. We both will receive Social Security at age 62. We are
conservative. I see the need for balanced, fixed income,
international, and small cap funds to maintain our asset value.
</P>
<P>
   T.E., Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems to me that you've taken the opposite tack of most
people _ maintaining your savings in conservative income-oriented
holdings while they accumulated, and now contemplating diversifying
into riskier (but potentially more rewarding) investment vehicles
upon retirement. Fortunately, you've saved enough money so that you
can probably make some of the moves you contemplate without
assuming too much risk.
</P>
<P>
   Let's begin with the idea that your first year of retirement
will be an anomalous, during which you will require a $70,000
income stream from your savings. But in the second and subsequent
years, both of you will have Social Security income, so you will
need to withdraw a good deal less. I'll assume here that your
combined Social Security income will be about $25,000 at age 62;
you can plug in the appropriate figure and make the adjustments. By
this reasoning, you'd need a fixed-income portfolio sufficient to
provide you with $45,000 a year, which is to say, a pool of about
$700,000, presuming you would achieve an average 6.5 percent yield
from this side of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the Vanguard Star account to one side, the remainder of
the IRA accounts, all now in fixed-income investments, come to
$770,000. If you follow my line of thinking, you would confine your
diversification into more risky stock-oriented investments to that
extra $70,000. I suggest you withdraw that amount from the money
market fund, putting it in a broadly diversified mutual fund
portfolio. If you were using Fidelity, for example, you might buy
$20,000 worth of Spartan Market Index fund (a Standard and Poor's
Index 500 fund), $20,000 in Puritan (like Vanguard Star, a balanced
fund), and $10,000 each in Fidelity's OTC, Overseas, and Select
Health Care funds.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, you would have a little more than 25 percent of the
retirement portfolio set aside to produce long-term growth to
protect you from the effects of inflation in the later years of
your retirement, and while some of the all-stock funds represent a
level of risk that hasn't been typical of your savings to date,
these are relatively small positions when you compare them to the
dominant holdings in the two balanced funds _ Vanguard Star and
Puritan.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's go back and look at the fixed-income side more
closely. Presuming you followed my suggestion of withdrawing that
$70,000 from the money market fund, at $320,000 it would still
represent the largest single element of your portfolio. I know
you're conservative, but I think you're being over-cautious -- and
you won't get a portfolio average 6.5 percent yield with more than
45 percent of the portfolio in the money markets. I would design
the fixed-income portfolio so that about half of it is in
traditional bond funds such as Loomis Sayles and Vanguard
Intermediate bond funds, putting 25 percent into riskier holdings,
such as Vanguard High-Yield Corporate Bond fund, and the final 25
percent in less risky holdings, such as Vanguard Short-Term
Corporate Bond fund. If your fundamental conservatism dictates that
you hold onto some of the money market position, you could
substitute that for the Short-Term Bond fund, but the important
thing is to reduce it to 25 percent of the fixed-income portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   If you follow these suggestions, the plan would require that you
reduce your cash reserves by $25,000 during the first year of your
retirement, but after that you could leave that account alone and
it would slowly -- very slowly -- rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 36 years old and am currently enrolled in my employer's
401(k) plan, to which I contribute $280 a month and my employer
matches up to $500 a year. Until recently I had been putting 25
percent in Vanguard Wellington, 25 percent in Vanguard Windsor, and
50 percent in Vanguard Primecap funds. I withdrew all of the money
from the Wellington and Windsor funds and divided it between the
Primecap account and Vanguard's Index 500 funds. The balance is now
$18,300 in Index 500 and $19,600 in Primecap. I am allocating 50
percent of ongoing contributions to each of the funds. Should I
continue on this track or should I be more diversified? Can you
estimate what I would have if I retired at age 60 or 65?
</P>
<P>
   J.H., Mansfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the result of your un-diversification is that you have
all of your retirement money in funds which fall in the same class
_ large-cap stock funds with portfolios representing a blend of
value- and growth-oriented stocks. It is, indeed, a category which
has done remarkably well in recent years, but my strong bet would
be that over the long run you would go a great deal better if you
went back to the idea of diversification. I don't know what the
menu of your 401(k) plan is, so I'll draw a general plan presuming
that all of Vanguard's funds were available, and you can see how
close you can come with the specific menu that's offered to you.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, I agree that the large cap stocks should dominate
the portfolio, but I'd limit the category to 60 percent of the
total, using either Primecap or Index 500 or both. I would look for
10 percent each in the following funds: Vanguard Mid-Cap Index,
Small-Cap Index or Small-Cap Value Index, International Growth or
International Value, and Select Health Care (which is closed to new
retail investors, but members of 401(k) plans may be able to enter
it). If Health Care is not available, you'll find nothing that
represents a close approximation, so I would put that money either
in Windsor II or Index Value. If Windsor II is not available, I
would not compromise with Windsor, which has been having all kind
of troubles and undergoing major changes recently, but go to Index
Value.
</P>
<P>
   As for the likely accumulation, these calculations can sound
very precise, but they are nothing but rough projections. For a
very long-term program such as yours, I usually estimate average
annual total returns of 10 percent for stock-dominated portfolios.
With that presumption, the computer shows that if you (and your
employer) continue contributions at current levels, you would have
$730,511 after 24 years and $1,125,952 after 29 years. But you
should do much better if you adopt this discipline: Every time you
get a raise, increase your contribution to the 401(k) by the same
percentage. Over the course of the many years that this account
will be building, that move could make a tremendous difference.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Years ago I opened a Uniform Gift To Minors account for each
of my twin grandsons. The money was invested in Putnam Voyager fund
and it has done well _ each account now amounts to about $26,000.
When I opened the accounts, I named my daughter as custodian. Now
the twins are approaching their 18th birthdays, and even though
they are very good boys and excellent students, I don't really want
them to have full possession of this money. They are now juniors in
high school, and soon will be seniors. California law says they
will be entitled to their money when they reach 18. They are going
to college in a little over a year. We have allowed them to make
some withdrawals, such as for the cost of SAT tests. What would be
a good solution?
</P>
<P>
   I.K., Bonita, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. As a matter of law, I don't think there is a solution, but as
a matter of practicality, it seems to me that if they want to go to
college, they should be willing to go along with any program that
you and their parents lay out. You don't specify whether you intend
this to be used for their education, or whether their parents have
established accounts on their own to fund their education. But if
your daughter sees things the same way that you do, you and your
daughter could sit down with them and spell out your financial
plans for college. As gently as possible, you could suggest that if
they don't treat this money the way you desire, they needn't expect
further financial aid from either of you. Since I presume that by
now they realize how important college will be for them, they're
likely to go along with whatever you spell out. And if they don't?
I'm afraid theres not much you can do about it. Gift means gift,
and although the UGMA status tied strings around it, those strings
are about to come loose, whether the donor likes it or not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
