<HEADER>
A3687 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLINGTON-CHRONOLOGY-     04-26 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLINGTON-CHRONOLOGY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DUKE ELLINGTON TIME LINE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies DUKE ELLINGTON) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   APRIL 29, 1899: Edward Kennedy Ellington is born in Washington,
D.C., to James Edward and Daisy Kennedy Washington. He grows up
near the White House and begins taking piano lessons at 7.
</P>
<P>
   1914: Writes his first song, ``Soda Fountain Rag.''
</P>
<P>
   1922: Visits New York for the first time, playing with Wilbur
Sweatman. He will return the next year, working clubs and
recording.
</P>
<P>
   1926: Records ``East St. Louis Toodle-oo,'' later covered by
Steely Dan.
</P>
<P>
   1927: The pivotal year of the young Ellington's career: He
begins working the famed Cotton Club, writes ``Black and Tan
Fantasy,'' and welcomes baritone saxophonist Harry Carney, who will
remain with Ellington until the latter dies.
</P>
<P>
   1928: Johnny Hodges joins the band. He will remain until he dies
in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   1930: The band makes its first trip to Hollywood, to appear in
``Check and Double Check.'' Throughout the decade, the group would
become extremely popular in both the United States and Europe. It
is during this period that the band premiers many of the
compositions it would be known for, including ``It Don't Mean a
Thing If It Ain't Got That Swing,'' ``In a Sentimental Mood'' and
``Caravan,'' the last co-written with trombonist Juan Tizol.
</P>
<P>
   1939: Pianist/composer/arranger Billy Strayhorn and tenor
saxophonist Ben Webster join the band. Both will be integral parts
of Ellington's band for years; Strayhorn would write ``Take the `A'
Train'' and ``Lush Life,'' among many others.
</P>
<P>
   1940-1942: A period many critics say was the Ellington band's
best; the band featured bassist Jimmy Blanton and trumpeter Ray
Nance. Songs that debuted during this period include ``Take the `A'
Train,'' ``Harlem Air Shaft,'' ``Perdido'' and ``Warm Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   1941: Ellington's musical ``Jump for Joy'' debuts in Los
Angeles. Featuring Dorothy Dandridge and Herb Jeffries and bluesman
Joe Turner, it flies in the face of ugly racial stereotypes of the
day with some pointed social commentary, such as ``Uncle Tom's
Cabin Is a Drive-In Now.''
</P>
<P>
   1943: Ellington plays Carnegie Hall for the first time and
debuts his epic suite ``Black, Brown and Beige.''
</P>
<P>
   1956: The Ellington band causes a sensation at the Newport Jazz
Festival; tenor saxophonist Paul Gonsalves' long solo during
``Diminuendo and Crescendo in Blue'' becomes one of the most famous
in jazz history. Ellington appears on the cover of Time magazine.
</P>
<P>
   1959: Ellington is the first African-American to be commissioned
to write the soundtrack to a movie, ``Anatomy of a Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   1965: Ellington performs his first sacred concert, at Grace
Cathedral in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   1967: Ellington is given an honorary doctorate in music at Yale
University. Billy Strayhorn dies.
</P>
<P>
   1969: Presented with the Medal of Freedom by President Nixon at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   1970: Johnny Hodges dies.
</P>
<P>
   1971: Ellington writes his final major work, ``he Afro-Eurasian
Eclipse.''
</P>
<P>
   MAY 24, 1974: Duke Ellington dies of cancer in New York.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
