<HEADLINE>
FAMILY TO BURY LONG-LOST VIETNAM VETERAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Navy Cmdr. John C. Mape, father of seven, was 40
when he died flying a mission over North Vietnam in the spring of
1966.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the family will bury the remains _ identified late
last year through DNA testing _ of the father who perished so long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Mape's death, his wife, Patricia, and their
children, ages 2 to 14, were eagerly awaiting his homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his death, the family posed for a photograph for a
local newspaper. As one daughter held a framed photo of her father,
the youngest could not contain her joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the cameraman posed the group, the youngest of the children
_ 2-year-old Sally _ suddenly spied her father's face,'' the
article said. ``Daddy, she cried delightedly, kissing the
photograph full on the lips. Daddy ...''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three years have passed since the day John Mape's
Skyraider tumbled out of control over North Vietnam, after a
surface-to-air missile exploded beneath the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``No parachute was observed, and no emergency-beeper signals
were detected,'' a Navy report said about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilots of the other two aircraft made a visual inspection
of the wreckage and reported their belief that Commander Mape could
not have survived the impact.''
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, the Mape family has celebrated
birthdays, graduations, weddings, the birth of grandchildren, and
the arrival of the first great-grandchild. Family members have
buried John Mape's mother, his twin sister and older brother.
</P>
<P>
   The journey that brought Mape home began in 1991, when a team of
American and Vietnamese investigators interviewed villagers living
near the crash site. They returned again in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the team returned in 1994, they learned that the
Vietnamese government had arrested some people for excavating
remains from that site,'' said Larry Greer, a Defense Department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, Vietnamese officials returned those remains to the
U.S. government in a solemn repatriation ceremony in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   A military honor guard stood at attention as a special case
bearing the remains was reverently placed into a polished metal
coffin. An American flag was then stretched across the top.
</P>
<P>
   When the coffin arrived at Hickam Air Force Base in Hawaii, it
was welcomed by an honor guard.
</P>
<P>
   The precious bone fragments inside were later identified in the
base's laboratory as belonging to Mape.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, two of Mape's five daughters _ Judy Palhegyi and
Sue Gray of Sonora, Calif. _ accompanied the remains of their
father home from Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really, really happy,'' Palhegyi said upon their return.
``We feel very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Air Force base, they were shown into a room with their
father's coffin. His remains _ 55 tiny bone fragments _ had been
wrapped in a special blanket and placed in the coffin. On top of
the remains was a carefully laid out dress uniform, pinned with the
nine medals Mape had earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent some time in the room alone with my father,'' said
Palhegyi, who was 9 when he died. ``We brought my rosary beads, my
father's missal and a pair of cuff links Mom had gotten for him
years ago as a gift. We placed them in the casket with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Mape Sarris, Mape's only surviving sibling, is relieved the
long search for her brother has ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sorry my sister Joan and brother Vance aren't living
to see this,'' said Sarris, 76, who lives in Santa Rosa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   As a youth, Sarris said, Mape had planned to become a priest,
and enrolled at a seminary boarding school as a teen-ager. He
continued his priesthood studies at St. Patrick's College in Menlo
Park, and graduated in 1948 with a degree in philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   While still in college, he changed his mind about becoming a
priest, after a period of intense reflection, Sarris said. But he
remained devoted to his faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic chaplain aboard the USS Ticonderoga said Jack
would go to Mass aboard ship every morning,'' Sarris said. ``He
always ended his letters `Love and Prayers, Jack.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sarris said Mape, who became the commanding officer of his
squadron in 1965 in a ceremony aboard the Ticonderoga, was devoted
to his men.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did so much work building morale among the men in his
squadron,'' she said. ``He was someone special to follow. He moved
in a quiet way, but he did so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarris said one of Mape's most fervent wishes came true _ all of
his men returned home safely from the war.
</P>
<P>
   The burial on Friday in San Mateo will be a time of mixed
emotions for the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out the DNA test was positive, I realized we were
going to be planning a funeral,'' said another daughter, Teresa
Mape, 47. ``Even though the good part is having closure, it's still
pretty sad.''
</P>
<P>
   There is sadness, but there are also happy memories _ of the dad
who taught her to ride a bike, who brought home a French doll in
19th-century clothing from a Mediterranean cruise, whose postcards
and letters she will always treasure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to daughters Teresa, Judy Palhegyi and Sue Gray, and
sister Mary, Mape is survived by his widow, Patricia Carothers, of
Reno, Nev.; sons Christopher of Olympia, Wash., and Michael of
Tracy, Calif.; daughters Mary of Aurora, Colo., and Sara of San
Francisco; nine grandchildren and one great-grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
