u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WOMEN-ATHLETES-60     04-26 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WOMEN-ATHLETES-600&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAILTY MYTH HAUNTS WOMEN IN SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By MARY DUFFY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a recent article published in The British Journal of Sports
Medicine, a sociologist proposed a theory that could launch a
thousand hours of talk-radio discussion.
</P>
<P>
   If not for a history of medical myths and a lack of athletic
opportunity, it is at least possible, suggested Dr. Ellis Cashmore,
a professor at Staffordshire University in Stoke-on-Trent, England,
that in all sports that demand skill as opposed to pure brawn,
women might have been competing at levels comparable with their
male counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   That the genetic advantage men have in strength could, perhaps,
in some sports, be overcome by women's skill or endurance, strikes
many as heresy, reported Cashmore, who first discussed medical
myths and female athletes in ``Making Sense of Sports'' (Routledge,
1996). This in spite of the fact that in head-to-head competition
with men, women have sometimes won ultramarathons, as well as
long-distance cycling and swimming races.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the Berlin Wall has crumbled in the Cold
War against women's sports. But the lingering view of the ``weaker
sex,'' said Cashmore, is a hurdle female athletes still have to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, girls' and women's physical activity at all ages
has been strictly circumscribed by doctors and physical educators,
explained Dr. Patricia Vertinsky, a professor at the University of
British Columbia in Vancouver. She has written extensively on what
she calls the medicalization of the female body.
</P>
<P>
   Cashmore observed, ``While we've come a long way from the days
when physicians warned that running could cause a woman's uterus to
drop, the legacy of that kind of medical discourse is the view we
still hold that women are more susceptible to damage, they are
somehow more precious.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Don Sabo, a sociologist and author of ``Men's Health and
Illness'' (Sage, 1995), said: ``Society has always used sport as a
vehicle to proclaim men's physical superiority over women. While
boys were exerting their superiority on the playing field, girls
were learning that their bodies weren't made for sports.''
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the century, doctors said women did not have the
physical stamina to take part in athletics, and any attempt would
endanger their mental and physical health. Attention was usually
focused on the damage athletics could have on their reproductive
organs, while a man's more exposed organs were never an issue.
Until the 1970s, Sabo said, the predominant view was ``Keep women
out of sports to protect them from their own frailty.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sea change in attitude about women and girls in
sports, among doctors today there are still vestiges of the once
pervasive attitude that strenuous exercise is bad for a woman's
health, in particular her reproductive health, said Dr. James
Clapp, an obstetrician in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   He has done research on pregnant athletes for 15 years and says
the exercise guidelines endorsed by most obstetricians are ``very
conservative for an active, fit woman.'' Instead, he said, most
forms of moderate exercise benefit both the woman and fetus.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side of this overprotective attitude toward women is
the expectation that men should ignore the pain and persevere.
After all, at the turn of the century, in an increasingly
industrialized age, we institutionalized sports as a way to toughen
up boys, test their masculinity and train them for military service
or business. To this day that stoicism is reflected in the way we
cast a blind eye to risks and injuries that sports pose for young
men.
</P>
<P>
   Vertinsky added: ``When we do focus attention on sports injuries
with boys or men. Most often we measure the impact in terms of
future play or career, not long-term health.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With a boys-will-be-boys-attitude, we expect young men to get
roughed up in sports. It is part of the game. But girls venture
onto the field with the subtle message, be careful, don't get hurt.
When any child is injured playing sports, it is frightening. But
when the athlete carried off the field sports a ponytail, people
are more likely to question why she was there in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Cashmore's argument that progress of
women in sport has been handicapped, not by their own frailty or
bodily deficiencies but by myths about their physical abilities.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the many physiological differences between men and
women, Cashmore said, various studies have shown that both bodies
respond similarly to training and diet. ``Women cannot close the
strength gap entirely,'' Cashmore said, ``but they can get to
within 5 percent of an equivalent body-weight male.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at 35 years of marathon records, Cashmore found that
women's best times had improved by an annual average of 2 minutes
and 47 seconds, as against just 66 seconds for men.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that women were virtually banned from sports until
the last half of this century, Cashmore said, the real question is
not why are women so far behind men in record setting, but how have
they managed to make up so much ground so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there needs to be a middle ground between the
overprotective view of female athletes and the cavalier attitude
toward the risks sports pose for boys. Once that balance has been
struck, the debate can begin about whether women could ever
outshoot, outhit, outkick and outscore men on an even playing
field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
