<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PERSON'S TRASH IS ANOTHER'S VALUED COLLECTIBLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Kovel says she and her husband, Ralph, have seen it all.
Pencil erasers. Barbed wire. Coffin markers. Wire hangers. Plumbing
fixtures. False teeth. Tractors. Foundation garments. Parimutuel
tickets. You name it, no matter how unusual, obscure, or banal the
item may seem, the Kovels know of somebody who collects it.
</P>
<P>
   I told her I was glad to hear somebody else collects parimutuel
tickets. I'm not a collector, but I live with one, and I marvel at
the collector mentality, never more so than when I consider my
husband's cache of parimutuel tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Have the Kovels ever been surprised by an odd collectible? ``The
Smithsonian ran an exhibit about the strange things people collect,
and there was one I'd never heard of,'' Terry Kovel said from their
home near Cleveland. ``Paintings on spider webs.''
</P>
<P>
   The delicate art of spider web painting was popular in Victorian
times, the Kovels learned. ``They're very attractive, as a matter
of fact,'' she said, ``but extremely fragile. '' ''
</P>
<P>
   We are a nation of collectors, and The Kovels are the leading
arbiters of what we collect. They have written more than 70 books
about antiques and collectibles, everything from valuable furniture
and jewelry to not-so-valuable but nevertheless highly coveted
items such as product labels and kitchen utensils. Their latest
book, ``Kovels' Yellow Pages,'' is a directory of resources for
collectors. The Kovels also publish a monthly newsletter, write a
syndicated newspaper column, and maintain a Web site:
http://www.kovel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Leafing through ``Kovels' Yellow Pages'' I was struck by some of
the names of clubs and organizations that have sprung up around
various collectibles. The American Credit Card Collectors Society.
The International Swizzle Stick Collectors Association, publishers
of Swizzle Stick News. The Doodyville Historical Society. The
Buttonhook Society. The Feedsack Club. The Mid-American Reamer
Collectors, publishers of Juicy Journal. Hotwires, the club for
toaster collectors. The Association of Coffee Mill Enthusiasts.
Thimble Collectors International. The Universal Coterie of Pipe
Smokers.
</P>
<P>
   I like that last one especially. There's something very
appealing about joining a universal coterie, even if it is composed
of pipe smokers.
</P>
<P>
   The Kovels are always on the lookout for new collectibles,
especially items in the $3 to $10 range. White-knob wind-up toys
are hot items, Terry Kovel said. Fast food-related memorabilia is
another growth area. There's a McDonald's Collectors Club, and
Burger King, Wendy's, and Taco Bell also have their enthusiasts.
And potholders are hot, so to speak. A recent issue of the Kovels's
newsletter featured decorative handmade potholders, including
potholder ``erotica'' with hidden anatomic details.
</P>
<P>
   Collectibles may be silly, but collectors are very earnest. I
was reminded of this when, on a recent ``Martha Stewart Living,'' a
viewer called and asked The Queen of All She Purveys if she had any
advice about attending the Brimfield Antiques and Collectible Show.
I've been to the show. I thought it was merely a matter of showing
up and looking around; that's why I'll never be a collector.
</P>
<P>
   Martha told her to go to the gym and work out to build stamina.
Acquire a truck, or at least a station wagon. Bring along a lot of
old newspapers, bubble wrap, tape, twine, and canvas bags for
wrapping things, an umbrella and rubber boots in case it rains, a
hat and sneakers in case it's sunny and dry and dusty. There was
more. A flashlight. A pen. Sunblock. Some other stuff. Soldiers
have gone into battle with less preparation than Martha advises for
Brimfield. But that's Martha. And that's collecting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
