<SLUG> BC-TV-SHOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO LET GO OF ``HOMICIDE''   AND A FEW OTHER HOARY SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turn off the fax machines, put away those
the-tube-is-going-down-the-tubes lecture notes, and consider this:
Maybe ``Homicide'' should be offed.
</P>
<P>
   Now that NBC has threatened to cancel the drama, whose already
low ratings have dipped, the true-blue viewers are sure to mount
one of those red-hot campaigns to keep the show on the air. But let
us remember that ``Homicide'' is seven years old now and, like dog
years, TV-show years count for a lot more than human years. Once a
jittery view of social despair and personal struggle, ``Homicide''
is aging into just another gritty cop series about perps, pimps,
and pairs of pretty police people. We should let it go now.
</P>
<P>
   Spring is here, that time of year when the network suits put on
their thinking caps and choose the fates of favorite electronic
friends, like ``Homicide.'' But while they make their decisions
about whether to renew shows _ pondering Nielsen ratings and
programming blocks and the absolute demographic necessity of
reviving ``Two Guys, a Girl, and a Pizza Place'' _ they usually
overlook the ever-changing creative lives of series.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER,'' for instance, is the No. 1 drama in the country, and NBC
has announced that it will, of course, bring it back in September.
But creatively, the frenetic medical show has been on a downward
spiral for more than a year, halfheartedly introducing plot turns
and then abandoning them abruptly in between intubations. With
scripts revolving around Mare Winningham's psycho doctor or the
cliched flirtation between Carter and Lucy, the writers are clearly
stretched thin. ``NYPD Blue,'' too, is past its freshness date,
with crime plots that go thud in the night, trumped-up internal
precinct drama, and, alas, the unending, egocentric mumblings of an
annoying fella named Sipowicz. Although they have been renewed,
both shows could use an appointment with an effective doctor named
Kevorkian.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't television be a better place if we could honor the
distinct life span of each sitcom and drama? A movie, of course,
arrives and departs in one condition: great, good, bad, very bad,
or, in the case of a ``Patch Adams,'' very, very bad. But TV is a
fluid medium, and the condition of the shows changes _ sometimes
radically, as in the case of ``Mad About You'' _ during their
first-run existence. TV shows can shift from promising to perfect
to passe in the course of five years, like ``ER,'' or in the course
of two years, like ``South Park.'' ``Friends'' has taken five years
to reach its comedic peak, after weathering the distortions of
media overhype and the tedious back-and-forths of Ross and Rachel.
Finally, it has exceeded its original identity as a ``Seinfeld''
clone to become a witty vehicle for five characters. It's also one
of the few sitcoms that's learned not to bury moral lessons in its
denouements. How long will its high point last?
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Seinfeld's finest moment may have been his decision to ax
``Seinfeld,'' despite the NBC offers that he supposedly couldn't
refuse. Seinfeld knew his show was exhibiting all the symptoms of
sitcom infirmity: characters that are parodies of their former
selves, plots that look strangely similar, jokes that sound
dangerously alike. What Seinfeld realized was that there's no shame
when a show loses its edge; it's natural and inevitable. But
there's plenty of shame in keeping a production going for years
past its maturity _ the shame of ``Murphy Brown,'' for instance,
which bowed out in 1998 after too many seasons of mediocrity.
``Frasier'' needs to guard against the ``Murphy Brown'' syndrome,
as it nears the end of a terribly uneven season marked by forced
episodes about Frasier's unemployment. The show's trademark gags _
Niles's fixation on Daphne, the brothers' competition, their
disastrous parties _ are showing their wear, and we can only hope
the once top-notch show will bow out at the right moment.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it has been on the air for only two seasons, ``Ally
McBeal'' may already be low on fuel, as its fresh quirkiness is
starting to seem formulaic. What was whimsical 30 episodes ago _
John Cage's courtroom stunting, for example _ is becoming
predictable and coy. David E. Kelley's show arrived on our doorstep
fully developed, with a wonderfully distinct point of view, and it
may have had only one direction in which to go: downhill. Of
course, Fox will probably keep the series on life support until
long after fans have defected. Look at how it has propped up
``Melrose Place'' for approximately three years after its brain
left the building. (The nighttime soap is finally being euthanized
on May 24.)
</P>
<P>
   Some series have ups and downs based on the Hollywood ``heat''
of their creators. In other words, Kelley is a popular guy. He has
three hours on the air _ ``The Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal,'' and
``Chicago Hope'' _ and one called ``Snoops'' is in production for
the fall. When he turns his attention away from any one of these
shows, which depend so entirely on his vision, it suffers. Part of
the reason ``Chicago Hope'' has declined is the absence of Kelley,
and CBS knows this: The network agreed to renew the drama for
1999-2000 largely because Kelley has promised to be involved again.
(That could be bad news for ``Ally'' and ``The Practice.'')
Similarly, the dissolution of ``ER'' can be timed to John Wells's
preoccupation with his now-canceled ``Trinity,'' and it's hard not
to wonder if ``Frasier'' has been hurt by its creators' involvement
in the late ``Encore! Encore!'' Once ``South Park'' became a hit,
creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone made two movies
(``BASEketball'' and the forthcoming ``South Park: ``Bigger, Longer
&AMP; Uncut'') and may have neglected their TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Ally,'' some freshmen series, such as ``That '70s
Show'' and ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' may need a year or two to find
themselves. ``Seinfeld,'' for instance, spent its first two years
hammering out the characters and sensibility that made its next few
seasons into classic TV. ``That '70s Show'' is a smiley-faced goof
on the decade and its youth sitcoms, and next season it could grow
into a TV-sized ``Dazed and Confused.'' And the wittily written and
snappily acted ``Will &AMP; Grace'' needs to gain enough confidence to
let go of its weekly message moment. But as cable gives us more and
more channels, viewers _ and networks _ may have less patience with
series that need nurturing. It was a surprise when ABC recently
opted to renew ``Sports Night,'' its first-year dramedy, despite
mediocre ratings. Let's hope ABC is also sensible in the case of
the new ``It's like, you know,'' which needs time to move beyond
its ``Seinfeld''-ian rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know where to place ``Just Shoot Me'' and ``The
Practice,'' both two years old, in their life arcs. Both feature
extraordinary ensemble work, and when they are good, they are
great. But both have been uneven lately, with obvious shifts in
quality from week to week. ``Just Shoot Me'' can turn comeuppance
into a high art, but some episodes _ notably the two-parter about
Finch's father _ have rung hollow. ``The Practice'' has delivered
the year's best drama, with dynamite legal twists and turns. But
the law firm's penchant for winning unlikely cases, as well as the
lawyers' self-loathing, is starting to inspire rolling of the eyes.
And what to make of that slugfest between Ellenor and Lindsay?
These shows seemed to get better, and then worse, 10 times in the
past season.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to TV, more is not always better. A longing for
the good old days of ``NYPD Blue'' or ``ER'' is no reason to keep a
failing show in production. It's a reason to turn to cable, where
repeats of these and other series, such as ``The X-Files,'' have
found homes on FX, TNT, and Nick at Nite. Even ``Homicide'' is
repeated on cable. Court TV has become its eternal savior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
