<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3701 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESSENTIALELLINGTON-TE     04-26 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESSENTIALELLINGTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ESSENTIAL DUKE ELLINGTON
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies DUKE ELLINGTON) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Duke Ellington wrote his first song, ``Soda Fountain Rag,'' in
1914, and was still composing until just before his death in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   In between were more than 2,000 songs _ jazz standards, ballads,
suites, soundtrack pieces _ and literally hundreds of albums.
</P>
<P>
   Picking the top half-dozen or so Ellington releases, then, is a
daunting task; there is almost no end to the music he made. Here,
though, is one critic's highly subjective list of where to begin to
start to appreciate the man and his legacy. Emphasis on the
``begin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Early Ellington (1926-1931)'': A three-CD set released by
Decca, it features most of his best early work for the Brunswick
and Vocalion labels. ``OKeh Ellington,'' a two-CD set that profiles
his work on that label between 1927 and 1930, is also well worth
getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Carnegie Hall Concerts (January 1943)'': A two-CD set that
features ``Black, Brown and Beige'' in its entirety. The band (with
the legendary saxophone section of Johnny Hodges, Ben Webster and
Harry Carney) is at its absolute peak, and the song selection is
excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ellington at Newport'': Ellington's dramatic 1956 comeback,
highlighted by Paul Gonsalves' famous 27-chorus solo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Paris Concert'': From 1963; an excellent profile of
the Ellington band in its fourth decade, featuring ``Rockin' in
Rhythm'' and ``Harlem Suite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His Mother Called Him Bill'': A 1968 tribute to Ellington's
right-hand man, Billy Strayhorn, who had died of cancer the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
