<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILLS' LANDMARK AMERICAN OPERA RECORDING REISSUED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beverly Sills wasn't the first Baby Doe, but the title role in
Douglas Moore's opera ``The Ballad of Baby Doe'' became one of the
soprano's most beloved portrayals. Sills had everything it took to
portray the irresistible heroine _ the vocal range, the sweetness
of tone, the all-American sincerity and strength of character.
</P>
<P>
   She first sang the role in the New York premiere in 1958 and
recorded it later that year. It was her very first recording eight
years before the production and recording of Handel's ``Giulio
Cesare'' that vaulted her from the category of valuable company
artist into that of national and international superstar. The
``Baby Doe'' came out on the MGM label, and after MGM records
folded, Deutsche Grammophon acquired the rights and reissued the
performance in the last days of LP. It has not been available on
CD, although representatives for Deutsche Grammophon report that in
this country it has been their most-requested back-catalog title.
</P>
<P>
   Now DG is issuing ``Baby Doe'' on CD in honor of Sills's 70th
birthday, explaining that the long delay was caused by the search
for lost paperwork. It wasn't clear who owned the rights to the
original tapes and where they were.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Sills appeared at a New York press conference to
publicize the rerelease of the recording; conference call and
speaker phone extended the event to media all over the country. The
diva sounded cheerful, radiant, racy, and entirely herself, and
even over the phone, one knew that red head was bobbing.
</P>
<P>
   The young soprano had been a candidate to create Baby Doe for
the world premiere in Central City in 1956, but word got back to
Sills that conductor Emerson Buckley had ruled her out because she
was ``too big.'' Two years later the memory still rankled when she
was asked to audition for the New York City Opera premiere that led
to the recording.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was living in Cleveland at the time, and I was called and
asked to come to New York to sing for the composer Douglas Moore.
It was already after the first of January, and the premiere was in
April. After auditioning 103 sopranos, they still didn't have a
Baby Doe. I asked myself, `Why should I knock myself out for this?'
I was quite sensitive about my size. But my husband and I were
coming into town to see a Broadway show with Lena Horne, so I let
myself get talked into auditioning. I went to Berdorf Goodman and
bought 2-inch high heels and borrowed a white mink hat that was 8
inches high from my mother, and walked out onto that stage. Dr.
Moore, who was such a soft-spoken gentleman, came down to greet me.
I said, `Dr. Moore, this is how big I am before I sing, and I will
be just as big when I finish.'. . . Actually, from the minute those
arias arived in the mail, I understood that role and knew how to
play it. Over the years I probably sang 60 operas, but I felt that
way about only six of them. The minute I looked at it, I just knew
that this was my part. So I am very pleased that the records are
coming out again _ was it really 40 years ago?''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Baby Doe'' recording was made straight through in the
Manhattan Center. ``There was no money for retakes _ `just keep
singing, honey' _ so we stood there and sang it. I was pregnant
during the performances, but the costumes covered it up; when the
recording began I felt I no longer had to hide this, so I came in
wearing a maternity dress. People asked me, `When did you get
pregnant? Thursday?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sills remembers her City Opera colleagues with particular
affection. ``Working with Walter Cassel, who sang Horace, was a
revelation to me. I had never seen someone who could take on
someone else's skin like that. When he talked to me onstage, which
was a lot, it was as if it were a part of life, and then he died in
my arms. It was all I could do not to give in to tears, and I
didn't dare, because I had another 10 minutes of singing to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Sills' acting of the final scene, where the faithful Baby Doe
sits by the entrance to Horace's worthless mine for more than 30
years until her own death, immediately became a permanent part of
American oepratic legend. ``We never staged that, because we had
run out of money by then. But they darkened the set and there was a
pinpoint light from above, and as the snow began to fall, the
shadows cast on my face from above made me appear to age. At the
first performance, I panicked and said to the stage director, `What
do I do at the end?' `Don't worry,' he said, `Just look at
Emerson.' So when we got to the `Leadville Liebestod,' and that
last long note, Emerson signaled me to back up. I kept backing up
until my leg hit the chair; he signaled me to sit down, so I did,
then to take the scarf off, and I did, and the snow came down and
the curtain came down. The next day my husband and my three
stepchildren were going back to Cleveland. We had the papers in the
car on the way to the airport, and I was disappointed that there
wasn't anything about `Baby Doe' on the music page of the Herald
Tribune. My husband said, `I think you missed the best part.' They
had put the review on the front page.''
</P>
<P>
   The soprano says that the part of Baby Doe was easy for her to
sing. ``This was one role where I just couldn't wait for the arias
to come. The trick to this part is not letting the women in the
audience hate her. Augusta, the wife that Horace leaves for Baby
Doe, is such a sympathetic character that your heart breaks for
her, and when Frances Bible did the part, you could feel waves of
sympathy coming from the audience. As Baby Doe you never have the
luxury of being aggressive or slutty; you have to play her like a
little fluffy kitten.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ballad of Baby Doe'' continues to hold the stage without
ever having won the esteem of the musical establishment. Sills has
scant patience for this attitude. ``It's a piece of Americana, and
as such, it's perfection. The text is wonderful, and there's
nothing obscure about it. John Latouche, the librettist, really
captured the twang of these women. Think of the last line of
Augusta's aria when she looks at her own work-hardened hands, `Not
like these.' That's a theatrically perfect text.''
</P>
<P>
   All through her career as a singer, Sills fought snobbery, and
she's still fighting it. ``There is always a hue and cry in the
press that American operas should be performed, and when they are
performed, at enormous expense, the same people treat it in a
condescending manner. This has just happened with Carlisle Floyd's
`Susannah' at the Met, which deserves to be treated with more
respect _ after all, it's not a new opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Sills confesses she hasn't listened to the ``Baby Doe'' CDs yet.
``I love opera, but I don't have time to sit and listen to it
unless I've bought tickets and gone to the theater, and then I
always stay to the end because once it got reported in New York
magazine that I had `walked out.' I just don't listen to music at
home _ I read, I do crossword puzzles.'' Sills is pleased to learn
during the press conference that recent corporate mergers have
brought her famous and long-unavailable recordings of Donizetti's
``Three Queens'' _ ``Roberto Devereaux,'' ``Maria Stuarda,'' and
``Anna Bolena'' _ into Deutsche Grammophon's orbit. ``I know there
are some of my recordings I would never listen to again, but there
are a few I am curious about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sills explains that when she stopped singing in 1980, she had
already embarked on a second career running the City Opera; now she
has another big job as chairwoman of Lincoln Center. ``Now to me it
seems as if my singing career had happened to somebody else. Since
I retired, I've sung `Happy Birthday' to Isaac Stern and Lynn
Fontanne, and `Jingle Bells' with President Reagan, and that's it.
The last time I heard myself sing I was 50, and it was OK, but that
was 20 years ago. I'm not curious about what I sound like now. My
children are very proud of whatever it was I accomplished, but they
are not the least bit interested in it because there are always
more and more things to do. And my attitude is that I did that
already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
