<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are considering
for Page 1, Tuesday, April 27. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Sam Weiss; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The status of the Russian negotiating
effort, and what Belgrade has agreed to. Parts exclusive. By
Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHILDREN (Brazda, Macedonia) _ The chaotic nature of the
exodus from Kosovo, the unusually high number of children, and the
complicated international aid and evacuation programs here have
helped make efforts to reunite families particularly daunting.
Adding to the potential problem, half of Kosovo's 1.8 million
ethnic Albanians were teen-agers and young children. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Tel Aviv) _ In the mold of Yitzhak Rabin, Ehud
Barak _ the the Labor Party candidate for Prime Minister and a
former general who is the most decorated soldier in Israeli history
_ is a kind of hawkish dove whose animosity toward the Palestinians
has dissipated over the decades. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ An 18-year-old woman,
described as Dylan Klebold's girlfriend, is questioned about
whether she had purchased two of the four firearms used by Klebold
and Eric Harris in last Tuesday's massacre, a 9 mm carbine rifle
and a TEC-DC9 semiautomatic pistol. For now, the woman has not been
named as a suspect and no arrests are said to be imminent. The two
teenagers who had planned to kill 500 students, destroy the school
and commandeer a plane to crash it into New York City,
investigators said. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-JONESBORO (Jonesboro, Ark.) _ When Gretchen Woodard
heard about the school shootings in Colorado, her reactions echoed
those of everyone else. She thought, ``Where were these boys'
parents?'' But she had to stop short of taking comfort in the next
thought on most people's mind, ``My child would never do anything
like that.'' Ms. Woodard's child, Mitchell Johnson, and a friend
murdered four classmates and a teacher last year. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   CICERO-GANGS (Cicero, Ill.) What would Al Capone say? After all,
this is the place that welcomed Capone, along with his bootlegging,
betting parlors and bordellos. Without an ounce of irony, this
working-class city of 70,000 southwest of Chicago is drafting an
ordinance that would evict all gang members. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-BRIDGE (Buffalo, N.Y.) _ Since Prohibition, the Peace
Bridge has been the infrastructural equivalent of a warm handshake
between Canada and the United States: an economic, recreational and
cultural lifeline for people on both sides of the Niagara River.
But these days, there is anything but peace at the Peace Bridge. By
David Chen.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-TOBACCO (Washington) _ The Supreme Court offered itself
as the next battleground in the tobacco wars, announcing today that
it would decide whether the Food and Drug Administration has
authority to regulate tobacco products as drugs and cigarettes as
``drug delivery devices.'' By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
