<HEADLINE>
STARVATION INTRUDES IN A BID TO REINTRODUCE THE LYNX 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By MARK DERR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ambitious effort to reintroduce the elusive lynx into
southwestern Colorado has encountered widespread criticism from
animal rights advocates and even many of the plan's proponents
since the death by starvation of four of the thirteen cats released
in February and March and the emergency recapture of an emaciated
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have questioned the scientific and organizational
underpinnings of the effort, a $1.4 million project sponsored by
the Colorado Division of Wildlife and originally designed to shift
100 lynxes (Lynx canadensis) from Canada and Alaska to the rugged
San Juan Mountains over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   While defending the project as an experiment to see whether
lynxes, which were trapped and poisoned for decades and became
extinct in Colorado in 1973, could once again roam freely in their
state, biologists expressed shock at the recent deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The project's lead biologist, John Seidel, who is retiring this
month, said the team had expected about half the animals to die,
but mainly from motor-vehicle or hunting accidents, not starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reintroduce the Eurasian lynx in the Swiss Alps and
the Canada lynx in the Adirondacks had largely failed, and under
the best of circumstances, success for the Colorado project was
uncertain, critics and proponents agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lynx is the type of specialist carnivore that is toughest
to reintroduce,'' said Robert Ferris, director of the species
conservation division for Defenders of Wildlife, the lead advocacy
group in a lawsuit that forced the federal government to consider
protecting the cats under species preservation laws.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing 20 to 40 pounds, with hind legs slightly longer than
its forelegs, and with tufted ears, a tawny coat and large feet
that keep it from sinking into deep snow, the Canada lynx mainly
preys on snowshoe hares.
</P>
<P>
   With snowshoe hares and lynxes now at their peak in western
Canada and Alaska, biologists decided the time was right for
reintroduction.
</P>
<P>
   But the area they chose was at the southern end of the lynx's
historic range, where the hare population was uncertain and perhaps
as low as 0.4 per hectare (2.4 acres). By most accounts, lynxes
were never abundant there.
</P>
<P>
   Moved from hare-rich habitats, the newcomers were expected not
only to learn to hunt different prey, like marmots and grouse,
which is problematic for specialist carnivores, but also to compete
with bobcats and coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   A warm winter may have made that more difficult for animals
adapted to deep snow, said Dr. Richard Reading, director of
conservation biology at the Denver Zoological Foundation and
co-chairman of the advisory team for the lynx project. ``We may
need a more typical winter before we can decide whether this thing
can fly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Reading and the advisers have urged a temporary halt to
the project to determine whether there are enough hares to support
the lynxes.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths appear to have confirmed the worst fears of critics,
who had charged for months that the plan was poorly conceived and
executed. And even many proponents have complained of inadequate
scientific analysis by project biologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have done intensive modeling of the habitat and
confirmed the results on the ground to reduce the risks of
mortality and suffering,'' said Dr. Reed Noss, chief scientist of
the Conservation Biology Institute in Corvallis, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   After the first few deaths, project managers decided to hold the
lynxes from Canada and Alaska in pens for at least three weeks
after receiving them, rather than releasing them almost
immediately. They hoped to reduce stress on the cats and allow them
to regain weight, while waiting for the annual spring rebounding of
the hare population.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 30 lynxes from Canada and Alaska, including the one rescued
from starvation, are awaiting release soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fattening the lynx up merely means it will take longer for
them to starve,'' said Dr. Marc Bekoff, professor of biology at the
University of Colorado at Boulder and a leading critic of the
project. ``The Division of Wildlife rushed this project without
fundamental study of the social ecology of the lynx and how they
would survive in what is marginal habitat.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bekoff said the lynxes now in pens should be returned to their
home territories and the project suspended until it has been
re-evaluated. ``They should start over,'' he said, ``and if that
means cats won't be in Colorado, that's too bad, but it's better
than having animals suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   But wildlife officials say they can neither return the lynxes
nor continue to hold them without putting them at risk of injury.
But they have taken steps to strengthen the project's management.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still something of an experiment to determine whether
lynx can survive here,'' said Rick Kahn, wildlife management
supervisor for the Division of Wildlife. ``We think there is a
reasonable chance of success, but we won't have proof until around
the end of August. After that, we'll decide whether to continue
with more releases next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Such statements do little to mollify critics, but Ferris urges
them to be patient while pressing for changes. ``Expectations have
been raised with the successful wolf re-introductions in
Yellowstone,'' Ferris said, ``and we expect all programs to work as
well. But they won't. We have to support things that are slower to
succeed and recognize failure is part of the process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
