A3714 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-OKLAHOMA-BOS &LR;      04-26 1863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-OKLAHOMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CRITIC'S GUIDE TO THE LONDON THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The sad joke has been that American theater fares so
much better on this side of the Atlantic than our own. Think of the
National Theatre's jaw-dropping production of ``Carousel'' that
played in Boston a few years ago. Or the same company's staging,
after Vanessa Redgrave's discovery, of Tennessee Williams's early
``Not About Nightingales'' that is currently playing in New York. A
couple of years ago the Royal Shakespeare Company did what was
previously considered to be undoable _ make a convincing case for
Williams's surrealistic ``Camino Real.'' (The Williamstown Theatre
Festival in the Berkshires is having its own go at it this summer.)
</P>
<P>
   This year's reclamation project is another Rodgers and
Hammerstein musical, ``Oklahoma!,'' and if it doesn't inspire the
awe that Nicholas Hytner's ``Carousel'' did, it may be that there
just isn't as much meat on poor Jud's bone to chew on. ``Oklahoma''
is, though, a thoroughly enjoyable, often inspiring night of
musical theater, light-years ahead of the current Andrew Lloyd
Webber monstrosity, ``Whistle Down the Wind.'' (See accompanying
article.) It's also light-years ahead of anything that Broadway is
likely to come up with as an ``Oklahoma!'' revival but,
unfortunately, this one won't be crossing over, because of failed
union negotiations concerning casting.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes ``Oklahoma!'' a top priority for musical theater
fans. Once again the organization responsible is the National
Theatre, which Trevor Nunn now oversees. Nunn, who directed
``Oklahoma!'' and ``Not About Nightingales,'' has done a
magnificent job for the National, perhaps as atonement for bringing
``Cats'' and ``Les Miserables'' into the world. Whatever the
motivation, Nunn has been overseer of an extremely rich period for
the National. ``Oklahoma!'' joins ``Copenhagen'' and ``An Inspector
Calls'' as successful commercial transfers to West End theaters,
while ``Not About Nightingales,'' ``Closer,'' and ``Amy's View''
are Tony contenders in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma!'' goes about as fur as it can go to join that elite
company. The opening overture is a powerful mood- and scene-setter,
with the orchestra shown through a scrim as if suspended in clouds
before the scenes through the scrim dissolve into opening credits,
cornfields, farmhouses.
</P>
<P>
   After Hugh Jackman as Curly enters singing ``Oh, What a
Beautiful Mornin','' Nunn has the audience eating out of his hands,
thanks also to a set design that emphasizes an open horizon. I saw
an understudy as Laurey, but by some accounts the drama in this
production is more between Curly and Jud (Shuler Hensley), the two
Sooners who are fighting over Laurey. They won't displace Gordon
MacRae and Rod Steiger of the 1955 movie in your memory bank, but
they're both compelling actors and singers.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Stroman's choreography is more athletic, though not as
strong, as Agnes DeMille's, and along with the production itself
underlines a slightly darker tone to the proceedings. I don't know
if it was just me, but during the rigged trial that freed Curly at
the end of the musical I couldn't help thinking of the all-white
juries that let Klansmen off throughout most of the country's
history. Not that the incident here was comparable, but the
``independent spirit'' that's being celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   This was probably a personal reaction. ``Oklahoma!'' is designed
to be more entertaining than revelatory and does what it sets out
to do. Alas, the same can't quite be said of the
National's``Candide.'' The Leonard Bernstein musical with any
number of lyricists and writers has had a troubled history. Most
productions emphasize the music, which is fabulous and upbeat, and
turn Lillian Hellman's original downbeat McCarthy parable of a book
into a kind of carnival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candide,'' codirected by Nunn and John Caird, boldly pushes
the music to the background with a chamber orchestra, and pushes
the story to the front, making use of a cast that has stronger
acting than singing chops. It works to an extent. Bernstein's music
with new and old lyrics by Richard Wilbur and Stephen Sondheim,
along with originals by John LaTouche and Dorothy Parker, can take
care of itself. Simon Russell Beale is a fine Voltaire/Pangloss,
and Hugh Wheeler's adaptation of the book is goosed up with
references that bring to mind contemporary horrors like the
Balkans. The problems remain, though. What do you do with
characters who are such Howdy Doodys (and Doodettes) as Candide and
Cunegonde? Or a story that repeats on itself like indigestion?
Maybe the way to go is to cast singing comedians like Martin Short
or Bernadette Peters in the roles or find a director with a tougher
mind-set than Caird. This ``Candide'' is entertaining enough, but
it still leaves you yearning for more. The best version still
remains the home-video concert recording conducted by Bernstein,
which emphasizes the music and leaves the story's contortions
mainly to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geometry of Miracles,'' which closed Saturday (April 24) at
the National but is bound to resurface, is something of a musical
as well. It's also about dance, architecture, Frank Lloyd Wright,
Georgi Gurdjieff, and Stalin. It's all from the wild and crazy mind
of Robert Lepage, a Canadian director, who previously imported mud
into the National for his staging of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   As the play opens, Wright is visited by a naked Beelzebub (the
terrific actor-dancer Rodrigue Proteau, also Gurdjieff), who dares
him to create a three-dimensional form out of a single line.
``That's easy,'' says Wright, who draws a spiral. This isn't a play
about architecture as much as it is a fanciful, nonrepresentational
exploration into the meeting point of architecture, dance, and
theater. (An arrogant Herbert F. Johnson, of Johnson Wax fame,
tap-dances memos to his secretary.) One doesn't need to know
anything about architecture or geometry, and one probably won't
learn much about either. With my limited knowledge of the subject
matter, I found it more amusing than affecting, although the same
could be said of ``Candide.'' For both, try the previously reviewed
``Copenhagen,'' Michael Frayn's play in which quantum physics and
Heisenberg's uncertainty principle make for one of the most
unsettling and compelling nights of theater you'll have in London,
no matter how little you know about physics. (No wine before the
play, though.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The RSC
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Shakespeare Company seems to be making up ground it
has lost to the National in recent years with London critics. ``The
Winter's Tale'' with Antony Sher, Marivaux's ``The Dispute,'' and
the contemporary ``Roberto Zucco'' have all been winning raves. I
can second the verdict in two of the three.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dispute'' is a coproduction of the RSC and Lyric Theatre
Hammersmith, directed by Neil Bartlett, who also wrote the
spectacularly successful adaptation that mixes contemporary
Anglicisms into Marivaux's 18th-century mix. Whether it's Bartlett
or the amazing young actress Hayley Carmichael who's more
responsible for making this philosophical speculation about the
things we do for love more entertaining than anything you'll see on
``Friends'' and more germane than anything on ``Ally McBeal'' is
academic.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing academic about this production, in which two
young people are isolated until adolescence and then released into
an Eden-like situation where they gurgle incessantly over each
other _ until another pair of lovers are released into their
environment. The humor is riotous, although Marivaux's serious
concerns about love and power emerge without benefit of the easy
catharsis of ``Candide.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Winter's Tale,'' Sher's ferocious, growling King
Leontes is one of those defining performances destined to stay in
the memory as he grabs this Shakespeare problem play by the throat
and drags it into ``Othello'' and ``King Lear'' territory. Not that
it's a single-handed accomplishment. British critics take for
granted the ease with which the RSC speaks and moves, but in a
season that hasn't seen much Shakespearean acting of note in
Boston, it's a pleasure to simply look at and listen to RSC
stalwarts like Ken Bones and Ian Hughes. (The company's coming to
New Haven in ``Troilus and Cressida'' and ``A Month in the
Country'' in June.)
</P>
<P>
   Whatever pleasures others have found in ``Roberto Zucco,''
though, eluded me. (``The Winter's Tale'' is on the Barbican
mainstage and ``Zucco'' in the Pit small stage.) Martin Crimp's
adaptation of Bernard-Marie Koltes's play, James Macdonald's
direction, and Zubin Varla's performance strip all affect out of
the story about a psycopathic killer, as if matters of motivation
and morality are middlebrow considerations to be dispensed with.
What's left in its wake is a void more boring than terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Donmar
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's more to British theater, even serious British theater,
than the National and RSC, of course. The Almeida, which produced
``The Iceman Cometh'' with Kevin Spacey, now has Cate Blanchett in
a revival of David Hare's ``Plenty'' (in previews last week).
</P>
<P>
   The Donmar Warehouse has become almost as hot as the National.
Specializing in revivals, the Donmar is responsible for the
productions of ``The Blue Room'' with Nicole Kidman and ``Cabaret''
(about to come to Boston with Teri Hatcher). I've seen some fine
revivals of Tom Stoppard, Peter Shaffer, and Harold Pinter by the
Donmar, but there also seems to be a tendency to get by with
attitude as much as art, as witnessed by ``The Blue Room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' CP Taylor's story of a ``good'' German's seduction by
the Nazis, has its champions as a good and even great play. To me
it's a two-dimensional play about a one-dimensional man featuring a
one-dimensional performance by Charles Dance. The terror in such a
play would be in showing us ourselves in the person of a good
German, but Taylor and Dance keep this professor of literature
wrapped in such a cocoon of self-centeredness that the audience
emerges far too satisfied with its collective self.
</P>
<P>
   And lest we think that the Brits have any particular lock on
doing right by American playwrights, there is Tennessee Williams's
``Suddenly Last Summer'' by the Donmar at the Comedy Theatre. This
isn't supposed to be a comedy, but you might have trouble keeping a
straight face at the ludicrous ``Little Shop of Horrors'' set and
the even more ludicrous acting onstage. (Rachel Weisz emerges
better than most.)
</P>
<P>
   Williams's attempt to exorcize the demons of an overbearing
mother, mentally troubled sister, as well as the sneering at his
homosexuality, would have a difficult time in the best of
circumstances. This production is so far from that best of all
possible worlds that the only reason to see it is to remind
yourself that sometimes American actors _ like Katharine Hepburn,
Elizabeth Taylor, and Montgomery Clift in the ``Suddenly Last
Summer'' movie _ really could be the best friends of American
playwrights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
