<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Adultery: And Other Diversions'' by Tim Parks (Arcade,
$23.95). Essays by the novelist, on the tension between freedom,
necessaity, and mortality. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect'' by Sara Lawrence-Lightfoot (Perseus, $23). Six
vignettes illustrating the complex power of a simple idea. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Making Peace'' by George J. Mitchell (Knopf, $24). The man who
brokered Northern Ireland's peace agreement writes a fair and
quietly balanced account of the process. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Prayer for the Dying'' by Stewart O'Nan (Holt, $22).
Highbrow terror: a spare, ominous fictional portrait of a small
Wisconsin town struck by diphtheria in the years after the Civil
War. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Morgan: American Financier'' by Jean Strouse (Random House,
$34.95). A thoroughly documented, consciously nonpartisan biography
of that colossus of capitalism J. P. Morgan. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
