<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3721 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      04-26 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
!! 1/2 ``eXistenZ'' David Cronenberg, in a more cerebral than
visceral mode, sends Jennifer Jason Leigh's game diva and Jude
Law's corporate nerd on a roller-coaster ride that blurs the line
between virtual and existential reality. Merging biology and
technology, it extends his view of the body's frailty, but in
lightweight fashion. (R) 
 
!!! ``Hideous Kinky'' More sweet than searching, this film is
centered by Kate Winslett's hippie mom dragging her two young
daughters to Morocco to search for her bliss in 1972. The film is
an alluring travelogue that admirably refrains from judgments and
spotlights the generosity they encountered. (R) 
 
! 1/2 ``Lost &AMP; Found'' Lame comedy in which David Spade's
brab-spouting tries to score points with Sophie Marceau's pretty
neighbor by dognapping her terrier, intending to return it, only to
find he's got to conceal it in his apartment after it swallows an
expensive ring. Plays like an ineffectual ``There's Something About
Mary'' wannabe. (PG-13) 
 
!!! ``Metroland'' Well-acted and thoughtful, this film considers
the nagging question of how one reconciles their youthful dreams
with their sadder-but-wiser adult selves. It's a very familiar
theme, but intelligent performances by Christian Bale and Emily
Watson carry the film beyond the cliches of its well-worn story.
(Unrated) (Renee Graham) 
 
!!! ``Prdita Durango'' Rosie Perez is a torrid pistol-packin' mama
in a surrealistic blood-drenched Tex-Mex landscape that she prowls
with Javier Bardem's black leather-clad witch doctor and all-around
outlaw. It means to take a few shots at tacky American pop culture,
and does, but goes soft in the home stretch. (R) 
 
(FU) !! 1/2 ``Pushing Tin'' John Cusack and Billy Bob Thornton play
NYC air traffic controllers engaged in a king-of-the-hill macho
struggle when they aren't busy sorting out the blips on their radar
screens. The film veers off course and becomes ordinary when each
guy chases the other's wife, although Angelina Jolie is appealing
and Cate Blanchett is amazing, seguing from Queen Elizabeth to
Queens without missing a beat. (R) 
 
!!! ``Relax . . . It's Just Sex'' An often-funny look at the
pursuit of love and happiness among a racially and sexually diverse
group of friends in present-day Los Angeles. Sure, it runs too
long, and gets a little light-headed at times on top of its
soapbox, but writer-director P.J. Castellaneta has a keen ear for
dialogue which well-serves his deftly drawn characters. (Unrated)
(Renee Graham) 
 

