<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by SLANG partners --) HED: Noahs two by two _ and  more  
SUBHED: Come what May, along with flowers, it's  time (again) for
 TV's sweeps surrender 
 
 
By  Marla Matzer 
Daily News Staff Writer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Each May, TV gets a lot more interesting. It's no
coincidence: It's a ``sweeps'' period, when ratings will determine
how much money individual networks will be able to charge for ads
in upcoming seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the end of the season for TV shows, so there are
guaranteed to be a number of high-profile stunts and curtain calls
_ this year, most notably from the long-running series ``Mad About
You'' and ``Home Improvement.'' Made-for-TV movie events include _
pay close attention _ ``Joan of Arc,'' ``Noah's Ark'' and ``The
Simple Life of Noah Dearborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliffhanger endings seem more popular than ever this year for
shows that want to make sure fans tune back in next season. On
``Walker, Texas Ranger'' (May 22), Walker and Sheree are trapped in
a plane crash. Tune in next fall for the exciting conclusion! ``The
X-Files'' predictably ends the season with a question mark _ with
Mulder and Scully's alien quest continuing _ and ``Felicity'' has
the title character agonizing over whether to go to Europe with
Noel, or to Silicon Valley with Ben (note to Felicity: Vienna waits
for you). Meanwhile, ``Spin City's'' Mike (Michael J. Fox) has to
choose between true love Nikki and supermodel Heidi Klum. We hate
when that happens.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a listing of some special events in store during
sweeps, which officially kicks off on Thursday. You may want to
tape a few things _ summer is often a long, dry spell when it comes
to good TV.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
April 29
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Kneivel: Grand Canyon Jump Live (Fox, 8 p.m.) The show's
executive producer, Jeff Androsky, says this death-defying
motorcycle jump is something Evel's son has ``wanted to do all his
life.'' What a coincidence, so did we _ it's on our list right
after sticking our arm in a shark tank.
</P>
<P>
   WWF Smackdown! (UPN, 8 p.m.) Robbie Kneivel smackdown, more like
it. This bit of counter-programming is being touted as the return
of professional wrestling to network TV. Oh, come on, guys ... it's
just UPN.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
April 30
</P>
<P>
   A Celebration: One Hundred Years of Great Women, With Barbara
Walters (ABC, 9:30 P.M.) Gee, we knew Barbara was getting up there,
but ... La Barbara chats up and recaps ``the most interesting,
influential and intriguing women of the century.'' All in 90
minutes _ half an hour less than she gave that modern-day Great
Woman, Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 2
</P>
<P>
   Noah's Ark (NBC, 9 p.m.; second part airs at 9 p.m. May 3) From
``Midnight Cowboy'' to savior of the species is about as far as an
actor can stretch. Jon Voight co-stars with Mary Steenburgen
(funny, you never hear anything about MRS. Noah, do you?) in this
two-parter based loosely _ VERY loosely _ on the Bible story. F.
Murray Abraham, Carol Kane and James Coburn also come along for the
ride.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 4
</P>
<P>
   Down Will Come Baby (CBS, 9 p.m.) Meredith Baxter stars in this
TV movie about a family's struggle to stay together after a fatal
accident. The network touts it as ``an unpredictable suspense
thriller''; that should make it a refreshing change from all those
predictable suspense yarns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 5
</P>
<P>
   The 34th Annual Academy of Country Music Awards (CBS, 8 p.m.)
Awards season is almost over, we promise. For country music lovers,
this one features performances by Garth Brooks and the Dixie
Chicks; for lovers of the (slightly deflated) female form, Pamela
Anderson co-hosts, with funnyman Damon Wayans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 8
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche: The White Death (NBC, 8 p.m.) If this show were on
Fox, instead of having been produced for NBC by National
Geographic, it probably would be titled ``When Snow Attacks!''
Instead, Peter Coyote narrates a more highbrow special on deadly
avalanches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 9
</P>
<P>
   The Simple Life of Noah Dearborn (CBS, 9 p.m.) Sidney Poitier
stars as a simple man of dignity: a carpenter who stands up to a
greedy developer. ``They call me Mr. Drill Bits!'' Dianne Wiest,
Mary-Louise Parker co-star.
</P>
<P>
   The Hunt for the Unicorn Killer (NBC, 9 p.m.; 9 p.m. May 10.)
What would sweeps be without at least one dramatization of a
real-life crime? This one's about Ira Einhorn (played by Kevin
Anderson), who skipped the country after his murder arrest in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 16
</P>
<P>
   Atomic Train (NBC, 9 p.m.; 9 p.m. May 17.) This Rob
Lowe-starring thriller goes head-to-head with France's teen-age
hero (see following) on its first of two nights. A train loaded
with nuclear explosives comes between Lowe and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Joan of Arc (CBS, 9 p.m.; 9 p.m. May 18.) Teen-ager Leelee
Sobieski is an age-appropriate Joan, perhaps history's first riot
grrrrrl. Jacqueline Bisset, Peter O'Toole, Powers Booth are among
the many co-stars; Shirley MacLaine makes a cameo appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Double Platinum (ABC, 9 p.m.) The torch is passed from one diva
to another, as songstresses Diana Ross and Brandy star in ``a
poignant and dramatic story of a mother and daughter's bond amidst
the pressures of superstardom.'' Once again, we learn that nothing
is harder than being young, pretty and talented.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 17
</P>
<P>
   Half a Dozen Babies (ABC, 8 p.m.) Ah, the roar of the greasy
hands, the smell of the diaper pail! If this is your idea of
excitement, live vicariously by watching this dramatization of the
lives of Keith and Becki Dilley, who became the parents of six kids
all in one day. Scott and Melissa Reeves, soap opera stars who are
married in real life, star.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 18
</P>
<P>
   Thumb Wars (UPN, 9:30 p.m.) We're not making this one up: a
``Star Wars'' send-up featuring a cast of dozens _ of dressed-up,
digitally made-up thumbs. Senor Wences goes high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 19
</P>
<P>
   The Nanny (CBS, 8 p.m.) Fran and Maxwell are set to have twins
on this, the hourlong final episode of the sitcom about a nanny
straight outta Brooklyn. To stave off withdrawal from not hearing
Fran Drescher's voice any more on a regular basis, buy a chalkboard
and periodically run your nails down it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 23
</P>
<P>
   Cleopatra (ABC, 9 p.m.; 9 p.m. May 24.) Raven-haired beauty
Leonor Varela steps into some pretty big slippers. Following in the
footsteps of Claudette Colbert and Elizabeth Taylor, she plays the
legendary ruler of Egypt and seducer of men. Timothy Dalton
(formerly known as Bond) and Titanic survivor Billy Zane co-star.
</P>
<P>
   The Jesse Ventura Story (NBC, 9 p.m.) The governor formerly
known as the Body gets the TV movie treatment. As Ventura, Nils
Allen Stewart gets fed up with wrestling and decides to go into the
only profession that makes it look like a clean, honest game:
politics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 24
</P>
<P>
   Mad About You (NBC, 9 p.m.) Don't cry for Helen Hunt and Paul
Reiser: they've had a good run during the last seven seasons. In
the meantime, she's won an Academy Award and he has that
high-profile AT&AMP;T gig.
</P>
<P>
   Melrose Place (Fox, 8 p.m.) It's been alternately sublime and
ridiculous _ often in the same episode. The Aaron Spelling evening
soap opera about beautiful people with weird problems comes to an
end after seven seasons. Fans of ultra-short skirts will have to
make do with ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
May 25
</P>
<P>
   Home Improvement (ABC, 8 p.m.) It's one of those shows that's
been consistently high-rated during the last eight years, even
though you may not know anyone who admits to watching it. The Tool
Time gang gets an hour and a half to say goodbye, including
highlights from shows past. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3724 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-UTAH-DINOSAURS-NY     04-26 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-UTAH-DINOSAURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSSILS OF ARMORED TANKLIKE DINOSAURS FOUND IN UTAH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Ohio)   (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A site in Utah has yielded a trove of fossils of some of the
biggest armored dinosaurs ever found, paleontologists announced
Monday, and they said the discoveries might compel scientists to
revise the chronology of dinosaur migrations.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Kirkland, state paleontologist for Utah, said that
ankylosaur dinosaurs found recently near Price, Utah, were at least
25 million years older than any similar dinosaur type previously
found in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Ankylosaurs, or ``fused lizards,'' were comparable in size to
army tanks, and were sheathed in bony armor plates studded with
horns. They had powerful tails tipped with clubs of solid bone.
Paleontologists speculate that ankylosaurs used the clubs to batter
large attackers like Tyrannosaurus rex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ankylosaurs are believed to have originated in Asia,''
Kirkland said. ``It seems that when land masses collided 100
million years ago to create what is now Alaska, these ankylosaurs
were among the first immigrants to North America from Asia. Later,
the Asian dinosaurs coming across the land bridge replaced most of
the North American dinosaurs. We've dated these fossils to 98.4
million years old _ significantly older than previously known North
American ankylosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the fossils, discovered by Sue Anne Bilby and Evan Hall
of the Vernal Field House Museum in Vernal, Utah, was that of an
armored ankylosaur about 30 feet long. Another fossil found at the
site was that of a 30-foot-long nodosaur _ a primitive version of
ankylosaur lacking a tail club. Kirkland said it may be the largest
nodosaur ever found.
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists who examined the fossils were surprised to
discover that ankylosaur skull armor appeared to be an outgrowth of
the skull bone itself, not an array of external plates fused to the
skull as had been thought.
</P>
<P>
   Excavation of the Utah site, which began two years ago, is being
conducted by paleontologists from the College of Eastern Utah
Prehistoric Museum, the Denver Museum of Natural History, Utah
State University and the Cleveland Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ankylosaur and nodosaur fossils, Kirkland said, the
Price excavation has revealed other dinosaurs, ``all of which
appear at this time to be new to science.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
