<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKAN-ALBANIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISOLATED NATION NOW IMPORTANT STRATEGIC PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If any country in modern times rivals North Korea
as a strange and isolated place in Western minds and media, it is
Albania, a dirt-poor backwater that has lurched from Stalinism and
Maoism in communist times to crime and chaos since the Cold War
ended.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Albania and Albanians are crucially important to US
military objectives and foreign policy, a profound indication of
just how much more deeply and complexly America and its NATO allies
are entangled in the Balkans than they imagined possible on March
24, when they began bombing Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, NATO leaders said they intended to stop Serb-led
persecution of ethnic Albanians. Now, according to a broad range of
scholars and government officials, the alliance owns a host of
other difficult problems in the region, and must stay whether it
wants to or not.
</P>
<P>
   NATO cannot withdraw, they said, without destroying its own
credibility and allowing the conflict to spread to a much broader
area.
</P>
<P>
   So the alliance has little choice but to confront problems that
are of blinding complexity, ranging from if, when, and how ground
troops should be sent to drive the Serbs from Kosovo to what to do
if civil war begins in Montenegro, if Macedonia disintegrates, or
if Bulgaria and Greece come into conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``This warfare has made things much more difficult'' for the
struggling economies and fledgling democracies of the region, said
John Lampe, a former Foreign Service officer who was stationed in
Belgrade and has specialized in the region as a scholar at the
Woodrow Wilson Center in Washington and at the University of
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bulgaria, Macedonia, and Albania all are going to go down if
they are not connected to the European economy and assisted,''
Lampe said. ``Greece is threatened, too, in the long run. This is
fateful stuff, and boy are we in the molasses.''
</P>
<P>
   But before those problems can be approached, he and other
specialists said, basic questions about Albania and the ethnic
Albanians elsewhere in the region must be answered.
</P>
<P>
   Will Albania, a country of 11,100-square miles that is a bit
bigger than Vermont, take a place alongside Okinawa, Guam, and
Guantanamo as a platform for projecting American power?
</P>
<P>
   Will the nationalist aspirations of the Albanian people, the
most militant of whom live not in Albania but in disputed Kosovo
province, be the catalyst for a much wider Balkan war?
</P>
<P>
   Most political leaders still hope bombing will force Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to retreat from Kosovo, allowing the
half-million ethnic Albanian refugees to return. Those who doubt
the air war alone will succeed are confident that the use of ground
troops could finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The path we should go down is to use overwhelming force, drive
the Serbs out, and then have a peacekeeping force there,'' said
Senator John McCain, a Vietnam war hero who is a leading advocate
of using ground troops. ``If we can't beat this army, with its
antiquated Russian equipment, we've wasted billions. We will take
casualties, and I will grieve, but I have no doubt that we will
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to beat Mr. Milosevic and beat him good,'' he said,
``and then we won't have to worry about him anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Albania and Macedonia are important, added the Arizona
Republican, but they should not prove to be problems as long as
Milosevic is under control. After meeting with Albania's president
Thursday, McCain said that nation will ``do anything necessary'' to
assist the NATO effort, and the Macedonians, too, realize it is in
their interest to support the allied campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But doubts about NATO's ability to win a clear victory and then
successfully manage the region are spreading among Balkan
specialists, former officials, and to a lesser degree, government
sources. Some warn that, to NATO's particular peril, it has little
understanding of Albania and the Albanians who will be key to the
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``American policy makers think they can somehow create some sort
of military protectorate leading to an independent Kosovo, and they
are sadly mistaken,'' said Steven Burg, a Brandeis University
professor of politics and an authority on the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albanians of all types,'' who live in Kosovo, Albania proper
and northwest Macedonia, ``do not think they are fighting for a
little autonomous state,'' said Burg, author of a recently
published book on ethnic conflict and foreign intervention in the
Balkans. ``They think they are the cutting edge of the effort to
create a greater Albania,'' unifying those three regions.
</P>
<P>
   Burg also warned that NATO appears not to have done a good job
of analyzing Yugoslav defense policy before the conflict started,
and consequently may be in for some nasty surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav military's entire strategic defense philosophy''
since the country broke with the Soviet bloc in 1948 ``is that they
would be invaded by a superpower, the Soviet Union, with massive
air and ground superiority,'' he said. ``I think they have been
completely prepared for everything we have thrown at them and are
just waiting for the real show to start. Just substitute US for
Soviet Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if NATO is able to achieve its objectives in Kosovo and the
Serbs withdraw, said MIT political scientist Barry Posen, a
specialist in the history of war, ``if we're not there to beat the
snot out of them, they'll move right back in. We're going to be
sitting with a lot of troops there for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to holding the Serbs at bay, scholars and analysts
said, the alliance will have to prevent the union of the three
Albanian areas: Kosovo, Albania and western Macedonia. Failure to
do so would doom Macedonia as an entity and set off a new struggle
over the remnants of that fledgling republic.
</P>
<P>
   A large majority of Macedonians are Slavs, but most observers
said they are closer, culturally and linguistically, to the Slavs
of Bulgaria rather than those of Serbia. Greece also has
territorial claims there. Macedonia provided an important smuggling
route for the Serbs when they were subjected to international
sanctions, and Serbia might not tolerate either Bulgarian or Greek
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without us sitting on it,'' Posen said, ``it is not going to
be pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   The need to restrain Albanian nationalism, to service armed
forces in Kosovo for the indefinite future, and, probably, to
manage several hundred thousand skittish refugees on the borders of
Kosovo until they believe it is safe to go home, all point to the
development of extensive NATO support facilities in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government has been signaling its willingness to
host a US or NATO base for years. That's not surprising in light of
the economic and security benefits this would bring to a country
that is now Europe's poorest, and the least-qualified applicant for
NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, said Joseph Nye, who was assistant secretary of
defense for international security when the offers were first made,
``there was not the kind of flaming crisis we have in Kosovo now,
so we were discouraging. . . . But that was then, and this is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe we are going to have to make a credible threat
about land forces to be able to get the refugees back, and then we
have to have a credible capability to protect them, you are
probably going to need major help from Albania to pull that off,''
said Nye, now dean of Harvard University's Kennedy School of
Government. ``Would I have got involved in the first place?
Probably not. From where we are now, it's probably necessary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
