<HEADER>
A3756 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-VIOLENCE-BO     04-26 1465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIC VIOLENCE WRACKS INDONESIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAMBAS, Indonesia _ While world attention is fixed on Kosovo,
ethnic violence is blazing another horrifying trail, thousands of
miles away, in a country with 20 times the population of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Here on the Indonesian side of the fabled island of Borneo,
``ethnic cleansing'' has taken a particularly grisly twist. In the
last month, mobs have chopped off their enemies' heads and paraded
them on the streets. Some have even eaten victims' hearts and
livers to underscore the message scrawled in blood on some victims'
homes: ``Bakayo'' _ ``Get Out.''
</P>
<P>
   The rural coastal road here in West Kalimantan province
resembles a war zone; thousands of houses belonging to a hated
minority _ migrants from Madura island _ have been reduced to ash
and charred planks. In several villages, grimacing, mutilated heads
of Madurese men and women were displayed on oil drums and wooden
stakes in recent weeks, and flung triumphantly out of cars at the
feet of outnumbered soldiers unable or unwilling to control the
mobs.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three months, hundreds, perhaps thousands, of people
have been killed, and tens of thousands have been driven from their
homes in several parts of the world's fourth most populous nation.
Last week, a mosque bombing, church burnings, and a handful of
killings rocked the Bandas chain in the Moluccan islands, the
island of Sulawesi, and the capital, Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has seen isolated ethnic clashes and attacks on houses
of worship before. But the attacks in the Moluccas and West
Kalimantan have claimed well over 500 lives since mid-January,
putting them among the worst episodes of religious and ethnic
bloodletting in Indonesia's modern history.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, such outbreaks could endanger national
elections less than two months away, and a planned transition to
democracy. In the long run, unresolved disputes over resources,
power sharing, and cultural differences could fundamentally
destabilize this country of 200 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts attribute the violence to old resentments long
suppressed by a dictatorial state. Others blame the worst economic
crisis in decades. But many Indonesians _ from unschooled villagers
to academics to opposition politicians _ accuse agitators linked to
the old regime who they say are intent on undermining democratic
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In West Kalimantan, the conflict began in January, but turned
ugliest last month, when the Malayus _ indigenous ethnic Malay
Muslims as well as Muslims from several other islands _ clashed
with Muslim migrants from the island of Madura. Descendants of
nomadic Dayak tribes, now mostly Christians, allied with the
Malayus. Even the ethnic Chinese minority quietly sided against the
Madurese, giving refreshments to hungry mobs of attackers.
</P>
<P>
   The stereotypes about Madurese reek of prejudices against
immigrants almost anywhere: that they are hard-working and thrifty,
but also aggressive, insensitive to local customs, and criminal.
Some Madurese have prospered visibly in Kalimantan's few large
towns, but most are farmers or laborers who may be slightly better
off than their neighbors, but are hardly rich.
</P>
<P>
   Madura is a tiny, overcrowded, and infertile rock island whose
inhabitants were moved to other islands early this century by Dutch
colonial rulers, and in recent decades by the Indonesian
government. They have roused the ire of Kalimantan's natives by
accepting menial jobs at lower wages, by laboring on plantations
created from government-expropriated land, and, according to
locals, by settling their disputes with physical violence.
</P>
<P>
   Minor disputes _ over a robbery and an unpaid bus fare _
escalated into revenge campaigns that have claimed more than 200
lives since January, officials say. Community leaders and aid
workers suspect that the true number is 10 times that.
</P>
<P>
   A charred patch on the main street of the sleepy town of Sambas
marks the spot where a mob burned a man alive. A tiny bridge in
Tebas, a 45-minute drive away, is where attackers played soccer
with another victim's head. Malayu men with machetes and rifles are
still patrolling villages and sleeping in shifts, manning nighttime
checkpoints to search cars for weapons and Madurese.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want is for them to leave West Kalimantan
altogether,'' said Fauzi, a farmer in Pemangkat village who smiled
jovially while brandishing a sickle at his guard post. ``If they
are moved from this area to refugee camps, it makes it seem safe,
but they're still among us. We've been under their thumbs for 50
years. They've robbed us, killed us, and we've done nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there are nice ones,'' he allowed. ``But 80 percent
are bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Madurese make up only about 6 percent of West Kalimantan's
population of 3.5 million, according to a government survey, and
physically, much resemble locals.
</P>
<P>
   Haji Sulaiman, a wealthy Madurese who is head of West
Kalimantan's Chamber of Commerce and a member of the provincial
assembly, says a small number of Madurese ``steal, gamble, and rob,
and we condemn this behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's also a social envy,'' he said. ``Madurese live
better, we're hard-working. Say there's unproductive land; Malayus
neglect it, but the Madurese take it over and make it productive.
They also say Madurese are stingy. Well, we save and in the end, we
can buy nice houses, wear gold, and go on hajj,'' the annual Muslim
pilgrimige to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   Yuslizar, a Malayu farmer patrolling Pemangkat village with a
rifle taken from the abandoned home of a Madurese neighbor, snorts
at the suggestion of jealousy: ``Of course they're rich _ from
stealing from us. We plant seeds; they harvest. We raise chickens;
they take them from the coop.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignorance of native customs, on the part of the government as
well as the Madurese, has fueled animosities. Dayaks practice
slash-and-burn agriculture, leaving patches of land fallow for
years while they grow back to forest. The central government has
ignored indigenous land claims and seized the land for timber and
palm oil plantations, and for migrants. Madurese have reputedly
settled on fallow land and refused to move. The tradition among
some Madurese of carrying knives _ a symbol of the hero in Madurese
culture _ has fed the perception that they are violent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, chopping off heads and eating organs seems an extreme
reaction. Adi Sunarso, a hotel employee who is Malayu and Javanese,
says he hasn't seen anything like it in his 34 years. ``What if
that were my wife and child?''
</P>
<P>
   The violence is not the first between Madurese and locals; since
1967, eight conflicts have broken out between Madurese and Dayaks,
and one between Madurese and Chinese. In 1997, a Madurese-Dayak
clash claimed 300 lives by official count, though aid workers
estimated the toll at 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Madurese refugees say army trucks and boats were waiting for
them this time when they were chased out of their villages, raising
suspicions that the military was forewarned of attacks or chose not
to prevent them. Second Lieutenant Suparyana, the Javanese
commander of an army base in Sambas, scoffs at the notion. ``The
only way of protecting them was to get them out. There was nothing
else we could do. I had only 25 men _ not even a full platoon _ and
there were thousands of attackers. At least we tried to prevent it
from spreading to other villages.''
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, not even the Roman Catholic bishop of Pontianak has
called for reconciliation. ``The only solution is that the Madurese
are moved, and they should not come back,'' said Bishop Hieronymus
Bumbun, a Dayak. ``Maybe we have to find an empty island for them.
We have 17,000 islands; surely we can find one.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the short-term fix seems to be refugee camps and offers
of passage to Madura. Hedy Sukarsono of Volunteer Relief Center
says he has registered 63,000 Madurese refugees, and estimates
17,000 more are living with relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Madurese huddled under tarpaulins in muddy fields and
foul-smelling stadiums hardly seem the dangerous ogres described by
their former neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Sarijan, 60, a farmer and third-generation Madurese from
Sendoyan village, was on the verge of tears describing his eviction
from his home. ``When my father got there, it was a jungle. He cut
down trees, built a house, and made a field, and I want to go back
and enjoy what my father worked hard for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I go to Madura? I feel Indonesian first,'' he
declared. ``If they stop calling this place Indonesia, I'll happily
go to Madura. But as long as this is Indonesia, I think I have a
right to stay here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3758 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VACCINE-850(2TAKE     04-26 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VACCINE-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS FIGHTING BACK ON VACCINE FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(See also: SCI-VACCINE-DEATH) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An overload of conflicting and often alarmist information about
vaccinations is leading some medical experts into a new field of
research: not the effectiveness and safety of vaccines, which they
consider proven, but the public's questions, doubts and fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we're doctors doesn't mean we don't also look at
the Internet,'' said Dr. Bruce G. Gellin of Vanderbilt University,
staff director of the Vaccine Initiative, a special project of the
Infectious Diseases Society of America. Some Web sites about
immunization, he said, ``focus to a large degree on concerns about
safety that are far more hypothesis than fact.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, the society created the initiative, which is
using focus groups, surveys and other marketing tools to explain
immunization to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But Gellin and other experts are not the only ones who feel
defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, them,'' said Barbara Loe Fisher of Washington, referring
to the experts, adding, ``They have been attacking parents who have
been talking about vaccine safety concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher is president of the National Vaccine Information
Center, which she and another woman founded after their children
had what they called severe reactions to
diphtheria-pertussis-tetanus shots. She said the children, both
boys, also were found to have learning disabilities and attention
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not anti-vaccine,'' Ms. Fisher said. ``We believe a
humane vaccination and health policy should be in place. We are
against forced vaccination.''
</P>
<P>
   The group pushed for federal legislation in 1986 that created a
no-fault compensation system for vaccine-related injuries, and for
changes in the pertussis vaccine. The organization also promotes
informed consent: parental awareness about vaccination risks and
the right to refuse shots, which puts them at odds with most public
school regulations. Ms. Fisher said she believed her son was
injured by the vaccine and expressed resentment that anyone might
consider such an outcome tolerable. ``Parents are saying, ``Hey
wait a minute, my child is important, too!''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that question or oppose vaccination include many people
besides concerned parents _ some are advocates of alternative
medicine, some are political conservatives and some are
libertarians, to name a few. They have become more visible for
several reasons: the Clinton administration has increased aid for
vaccine research and distribution, including immunization
registries; new vaccines have been recommended for preschool
children, including vaccines against hepatitis B since 1991 and
rotaviral diarrhea since December; and the Internet has grown,
allowing groups to create Web sites and to communicate their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the vaccine critics agree that groups like Ms.
Fisher's have helped raise useful questions. The problem, some
officials say, is that by discounting safety data and accepting
sometimes unverified accounts as fact, they may drown out the real
answers.
</P>
<P>
   To public health experts, vaccination is one of the century's
triumphs. Smallpox has been eradicated, and last year the federal
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported only 1 case
each of diphtheria and polio, 34 of tetanus and 89 of measles.
</P>
<P>
   But as illness from vaccine-preventable disease has plummeted,
illness from the vaccines themselves, however rare, looms larger in
the minds of some.
</P>
<P>
   Groups like Ms. Fisher's do not attribute a specific total of
injuries and deaths to vaccine _ some assert that vaccine-related
cases are frequently misdiagnosed, and so there are no reliable
data _ but they allege that the risk is much higher than mainstream
physicians and the government say. For example, Ms. Fisher's group
says on the Internet that it is calling for government financing of
independent researchers ``to investigate the reported links between
vaccines and neurological and autoimmune disorders.'' The site
lists problems that group members say may be associated with
vaccination _ including learning disabilities, attention deficit
disorder, autism, asthma, diabetes and ear infections.
</P>
<P>
   Many medical authorities warn against paying too much attention
to these reports. The CDC says vaccines cause so few ill effects
that the risks cannot be reliably measured. The agency says that
the risk of encephalitis or severe allergic reaction from
mumps-measles-rubella vaccine is 1 in 1 million. It says the risk
to unvaccinated children is one death in 3,000 measles cases, one
encephalitis case in 300 cases of mumps, and one case of congenital
rubella syndrome for every four mothers infected early in
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in danger of becoming a victim of our own success,''
Dr. Louis Sullivan, the former Secretary of Health and Human
Services, told the annual National Immunization Conference in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our citizens cannot remember seeing a child with
measles or polio,'' he continued, ``but they are constantly reading
and hearing about the adverse reactions linked to the vaccines that
have nearly vanquished these threats in the United States.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In a report in January favoring community and state immunization
registries, the National Vaccine Advisory Committee said that fear
of misuse was strong, privacy should be enforced and use of a
registry by tax, immigration or other agencies must be prohibited.
It opposed a national registry and said that parents should be
allowed to keep their children from participating.
</P>
<P>
   A central data base ``is in no way what we're talking about,''
said Dr. Robert W. Linkins, chief of the systems development branch
of the CDC's National Immunization Program.
</P>
<P>
   In Idaho, a state immunization registry for preschool children
was approved last month after the Idaho Christian Coalition
initially opposed it but later endorsed it after changes in the
language.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Parents Requesting Open Vaccine Education, a group
that uses the acronym PROVE, insisted that the state's immunization
registry include only children whose parents approved of their
being included in the registry in writing. The group also asked
that the data not be shared with other states.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Brad Dacus, the director of the Pacific Justice
Institute, a network of politically conservative lawyers,
questioned the need for a childhood vaccination for hepatitis B,
which is often spread by sexual contact or intravenous drug use.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC, however, notes that about 25 percent of all people
infected with hepatitis B have no known risk factor. Hepatitis B,
which infects 200,000 Americans a year, is acquired by exposure to
blood or body fluids from an infected person. It is about 100 times
easier to transmit than is HIV, the agency says.
</P>
<P>
   Universal vaccination, the agency says, is not only easier to
achieve with young children, but protects low-risk children from
accidental infection by others. Besides, the CDC adds, no one can
predict which children will grow up to become high-risk adults.
</P>
<P>
   Experts add that some critics ignore what would happen if their
advice was taken and vaccination programs were curbed _ if laws
requiring vaccinations for measles and other diseases for entry to
school were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can credit largely the school laws with the
near-elimination of measles from this country in the last few
years,'' said Dr. Neal A. Halsey, a professor at the Johns Hopkins
School of Public Health and the director of its Institute for
Vaccine Safety.
</P>
<P>
   A January 1998 article in The Lancet detailed the sharp rise in
pertussis rates in the 1970s and 1980s in countries where popular
accounts of adverse reactions led to sharp drops in vaccination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
