<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS MUST HAVE KNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ They are the most frequent targets for blame
in the aftermath of the shooting and bombing rampage that left 15
dead at Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   Where were those boys' parents?
</P>
<P>
   You can hear the question on the muddy hillside overlooking the
high school library, where mourners have erected a large wooden
cross to mark the scene of one of the worst schoolhouse massacres
in history.
</P>
<P>
   You can hear it on radio call-in shows that have set aside all
comment about Clinton and Kosovo to talk nonstop about the carnage
at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Even the president, in his weekly radio address to the nation,
said Saturday that ``parents come first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They should turn off the television and pay attention to
what's on the computer screen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed too soon, too cruel, in the last few days to ask how
much an abdication of parental responsibility contributed to the
apocalyptic acts of Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, the heavily
armed students suspected of storming their suburban high school,
bent on murder and suicide. Those parents are grieving, too.
</P>
<P>
   But how can we not ask now, after Jefferson County Sheriff John
Stone has said that the plot to blow up Columbine High and gun down
its student body was not some clandestine scheme, hatched away from
prying adult eyes in an Internet chat room?
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, Stone said Saturday, ``police recovered hate
literature, Nazi books and propaganda, and bomb-making materials in
plain view in at least one of the suspect's homes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really question this,'' the sheriff said. ``A lot of people
have stuffed animals and baseball mitts, not pipe bombs'' in their
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Could Harris or Klebold really have kept a detailed, handwritten
diary for more than a year outlining plans for the siege of
Columbine _ complete with diagrams of the school and estimates of
the hour an attack would yield maximum casualties _ without a
mother or father knowing?
</P>
<P>
   Could teenagers really build pipe bombs in the family garage, as
this pair apparently did, without a parent becoming alarmed? Could
two intact, financially secure families really miss the mounting
rage their misfit sons felt in the face of the ridicule to which
they were subjected in a school dominated by jocks and preppies?
</P>
<P>
   How could these parents not have known?
</P>
<P>
   There is not a parent among us who does not fear the dark side
of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard enough, with inadequate screening software, to shield
our children from pornography. How do we protect them from the
violence and the proliferation of hate sites on the Web?
</P>
<P>
   It is hard enough to monitor the video games our children play
at the house next door. How do we know which Web sites they are
surfing at the town library?
</P>
<P>
   In truth, many of our children live in a benign enough universe
parallel to our own. We see them at breakfast, their ears encased
in headphones, the faint sounds of their favorite CD leaking from
their headgear into our kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   We reconnect after work and school at home, where we find them
tying up the computer, chatting with friends on line as we once
yakked with ours on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   We do not monitor their e-mail any more than we would eavesdrop
on their phone conversations. Teenagers have privacy rights, too.
</P>
<P>
   But respecting an adolescent's need for independence and
supporting his right to choose to wear a black trenchcoat or a polo
shirt is not the same as surrendering parental guidance and
authority.
</P>
<P>
   These are still children, after all, lacking the maturity or
perspective to know that the hero in high school might well be the
goat in middle age.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Harris and Klebold have sequestered themselves in
their homes, hired lawyers, and turned their attention, as have
their neighbors, to burying their children.
</P>
<P>
   They are likely to have their lawyers longer than their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Said a visibly angry Stone, ``I think parents should be held
responsible for their kids' actions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
