<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3765 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MIDWEST-QUAKE-ART     04-26 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MIDWEST-QUAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CENTURIES LATER, GOOD NEWS FOR QUAKE AREA, MAYBE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Tenn., Mo. Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By SANDRA BLAKSLEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midwesterners who worry about earthquakes got some good news
last week: their risk of catastrophe may have been vastly
overstated.
</P>
<P>
   New measurements taken around New Madrid, Mo., _ the epicenter
of devastating earthquakes in 1811 and 1812 _ show that the ground
there is scarcely moving. According to many scientists, this means
that it will take 2,500 to 10,000 years before another very large
earthquake could occur in the region, although smaller, less
damaging earthquakes are possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motions are small to zero,'' said Dr. Seth Stein, a
professor of geological sciences at Northwestern University in
Evanston, Ill., who made the new measurements. Earlier evidence
showing rapid regional ground motion, a geologic sign that large
quakes are probable, ``was based on honest scientific errors,''
Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   But other scientists challenged Stein's findings, reported in
the current issue of the journal Science. ``We see evidence for
very strong ground shaking over the past 2,000 years,'' with great
earthquakes recurring as often as every 500 years, said Dr. Eugene
Schweig, the Central United States coordinator for the United
States Geological Survey's Earthquake Hazards Program at the
University of Memphis in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Schweig said he believed Stein had gone too far in calling the
hazard overstated, and cautioned, ``We need to exercise great
caution when presenting interpretations of our results to the
general public.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stein took issue with the criticism. ``This is a classic
example of a geologic argument,'' he said. ``We have to wait
hundreds or thousands of years for real answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of ground motion means that regional building codes
should be relaxed rather than strengthened, Stein said. It is even
possible, he said, that Missouri will never experience another
large earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Geologists do agree, however, on what is happening in the region
at present. Small earthquakes are occurring regularly in the
region, although most are too small to be felt.
</P>
<P>
   Also, evidence for past earthquakes continues to accumulate.
</P>
<P>
   But neither side can say for sure what causes earthquakes in New
Madrid. This part of the country is in the middle of the North
American plate, one of a dozen floating on hot, molten rock deep
inside the planet. When these plates collide, scrape or dive past
one another, earthquakes occur.
</P>
<P>
   According to every current model of earthquake dynamics, the New
Madrid region should be unceasingly immobile, stuck as it is in the
middle of a large plate.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began in the 1980s when geologists found signs
that there had once been massive upheaval in the New Madrid
landscape. Whole forest tracts sank. Soils liquefied. The
Mississippi River changed course temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Using carbon dating and other techniques, scientists concluded
that catastrophic earthquakes occurred there in A.D. 500, 900 and
1530. Two or perhaps three earthquakes were centered there in 1811
and 1812, causing widespread damage in the Midwest and parts of the
East Coast. All these events, the scientists said, were probably
magnitude 8, among the most powerful earthquakes in the world.
</P>
<P>
   So geophysicists began to study ground motions in the area, and
found that the ground beneath New Madrid was moving almost as fast
as the ground in California, where earthquakes are relatively
common. The scientists calculated that a magnitude 8 earthquake
could occur in New Madrid every 500 to 800 years.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Geological Survey identified the New Madrid
area as one of most dangerous places to live in the nation.
``Memphis is said to be more dangerous than L.A. or San
Francisco,'' Stein said. ``I think this is unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying the numbers ``just didn't make sense,'' Stein and
colleagues from four institutions re-did the ground motion
measurements using far more accurate satellite techniques. ''It
hardly budged,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   It might be, he said, that the ground is not moving very fast.
Or, he said, it might be that previous earthquakes, which were 500
years apart, were much smaller than thought.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Segall, a geophysicist at Stanford University, has also
gone back to New Madrid and is re-doing his previous measurements
using the advanced satellite technique. ``Although we are still
analyzing our data,'' he said, ``we are comfortable in revising
down the rates of strain of what we observed.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Segall and his colleagues also see little if any
ground motion in New Madrid. But he said that did not necessarily
mean a reduced earthquake risk. After a large quake, strain can
build rapidly for several decades and then slow way down. Thus, the
lack of motion today would not rule out the possibility of a large
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Schweig said standard models of strain accumulation based on
plate motions should not be used in New Madrid. ``This is an
intraplate region,'' he said. ``We don't know or understand why
these quakes happen, let alone when or why they might occur
again.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stein said the answer was simpler. ``We can concoct a
variety of complicated explanations for why we see no motion,'' he
said, ``but the simplest explanation for nothing moving is that
nothing is moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein agreed that the New Madrid earthquakes were a mystery.
Since there is little evidence of earthquakes in the region before
2,000 years ago _ and no mountains built up in the wake of seismic
forces _ it is possible that the seismic activity is temporary, he
said. Perhaps there is an ancient fracture in the North American
plate and somehow geologic forces are causing it to rupture, Stein
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be dying out or already dead,'' he said. ``The risk
is not zero, but it's much lower than the maps say.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, are not ready to turn off the alarm. ``I would
hate for people to think they don't have to take any precautions,
to not worry about their foundations or water heaters,'' Segall
said. ``In my mind, there are too many uncertainties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
