A3766 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-HARMONY-BOS     04-26 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-HARMONY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENFORCED HARMONY UNDONE, HATREDS FLARE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   JAKARTA _ Why, after decades of relative harmony, has group
hatred and separatism taken such a bloody turn here?
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts attribute it to the boiling over of cultural
differences long suppressed by an authoritarian state. The currency
crisis, runaway inflation, and food shortages that began last year,
have fueled animosities and shortened tempers. Finally, there is a
conspiracy theory espoused by many Indonesians: that troublemakers
from the military or the regime of President Suharto, who was
forced out last year, are provoking incidents to prevent a smooth
transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia was left with a power vacuum last May, after decades
of autocratic rule. The fall of military strongman Suharto
unleashed long-suppressed resentments across this archipelago of
17,000 islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a country emerges from a long period of autocratic rule,
all the problems come to the fore. What's going on is the result of
32 years of suppressing dissatisfaction,'' said a Western diplomat
in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Under Suharto's model of enforced harmony, ``people couldn't do
reconciliation, because they couldn't admit there was a problem.
Wildly different groups were able to live together as long as they
feared the military and police. But now that fear is gone, and it
hasn't been replaced by a respect for law.''
</P>
<P>
   The national motto _ ``Bhinneka Tunggal Ika,'' or ``They are
many; they are one'' _ goes a long way toward explaining the
refusal to acknowledge differences among the nation's 300 ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Since modern Indonesia formed after winning independence from
the Dutch in 1949, power has been centralized on the main island of
Java, in the hands of an elite. Javanese leaders exploited the rich
resources of a 3,100-mile string of islands and made little effort
to understand local problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are now trying to get local grievances addressed,'' the
diplomat explained _ but are doing so in an immediate and violent
way.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to meet those grievances and alleviate separatist
demands that some fear could splinter the nation, the parliament
passed a bill last Wednesday granting Indonesia's 27 provinces more
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has some observers talking of the ``Balkanization'' of
Indonesia, but others say it would be dangerous to draw too close a
parallel with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Andi Mallarangeng, a member of the national election committee,
admits that pockets of Indonesia are now plagued by violence or
separatist demands. But, he cautions, that doesn't mean the country
is on the verge of splitting apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The formation of Indonesia was not by force like it was with
Tito and communism in Yugoslavia. We've got a much more widespread
belief in Indonesia as a nation,'' Mallarangeng said. ``Even before
independence, there was a movement for unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Syarif Ibrahim Alqadrie, dean of social and political sciences
at the University of Tanjungpura in Pontianak, also draws a
distinction between government-sponsored ``ethnic cleansing'' in
Yugoslavia and what he believes are grass-roots ethnic conflicts in
his province of West Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
   Any long-term solution, he says, will require leaders from
various groups to discuss problems and educate their communities
about cultural differences, conflict-resolution, and coexistence.
``For 32 years, we were not permitted to talk about ethnic groups
and conflicts openly. . . . Now the problem is different: Everyone
wants to say and do anything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   But many swept up in the local conflicts aren't so sure they can
be resolved. ``It's the same here as Bosnia or Kosovo,'' said the
Sultan of Sambas, Haji Raden Winata Kesuma, the traditional ruler
of West Kalimantan's Malayus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
