<HEADER>
A3769 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-HISTORY-BOS &LR;      04-26 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUESTIONS ABOUT NATO HAVE BEEN AROUND A LONG TIME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN LUPO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, there actually were times in the old Alpha
Epsilon Pi fraternity house at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst when some of us stopped discussing the unfairness of exams
and the frustration of being ignored by certain women of great
beauty and engaged in conversations worthy of college students.
</P>
<P>
   In one such session, a couple of us admitted that, skepticism of
our youth to the contrary notwithstanding, we believed in the
ability of such outfits as the Strategic Air Command and NATO to
protect us.
</P>
<P>
   Such conclusions were comforting to young men who had vivid
childhood memories of World War II and who were destined to serve
in the armed forces during the height of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   We were less likely then than we would become in later years to
question authority, but even through the tumultuous '60s and
onward, many Americans held fast to the belief that the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization was to military security what the
Marshall Plan had been to economic security.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as aging citizens, we witness NATO in serious combat for
the first time in its half-century history, and we wonder how it
will acquit itself.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Yugoslavia's remnants is, of course, not the fight
for which NATO had prepared itself all those years. Its purpose was
to stop the Soviet armies from taking over more of Europe should
Stalin or his successors try to do so. There is no longer a Soviet
army. There is still a Russian army, many of whose members now
scrounge the countryside for money or food.
</P>
<P>
   There is, instead, Slobodan Milosevic thumbing his nose at the
collective power of the grand alliance. What we college students of
the 1950s did not know and what we adults of the 1990s ought to
know is that NATO, like all organizations, was never perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alliance was in `disarray' of one sort or another from the
day the NATO treaty was signed because the partners always had
different expectations and different visions of what they were
doing, '' Richard J. Barnet, a foreign policy analyst, wrote in his
1983 book, ``The Alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Confusion always centered on the NATO military forces,'' he
wrote. ``The stated function of the troops _ to keep out Russian
divisions which military analysts doubted were coming in any event
_ caused people to forget the real political purposes they were
intended to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnet contended that initially, NATO's real purpose ``was to
breathe new life into the European integration movement which by
that time showed signs of running out of steam.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, there were issues that would linger for NATO's
history, such as how much was the United States expected to fork
over in money and manpower, compared with the Europeans, and which
nations deserved membership?
</P>
<P>
   Back on this side of the Atlantic, we generally paid little
attention over the years to the pulls and tugs within NATO. As
recently as last year, as Clinton administration officials, US
senators, and foreign policy specialists hotly debated whether to
add Hungary, Poland, and the Czech Republic to NATO, few citizens
seemed to care one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   In fall 1997, the Pew Research Center found that 63 percent of
those surveyed supported NATO's expansion, but only 10 percent
could name so much as one of the three nations being proposed for
alliance membership.
</P>
<P>
   So, when increasing numbers of politicians, journalists and
interested citizens assert that most Americans could not find
Kosovo on a map, they are asserting the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   This observation is usually made in a discussion of how
important or unimportant Kosovo is to the United States and whether
it is worth the life of any American servicemen or women. But while
accurate, the comment seems pretty useless for two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the sad fact that most Americans can't find much of
anything on a map, because geography has not been a required course
for a few decades. Find Kosovo? Some citizens can't find well-known
American cities and states on a map.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason is that Americans tend to be isolationist and
generally refrain from the desire to get involved in pretty much
anything overseas short of a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   History, like geography, is often not taught, or, at the least,
not taught well, but most Americans probably know that their
grandparents and great grandparents prayed mightily during the
1930s that the United States stay out of the already ongoing
conflicts in Europe and the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   Pure isolationism took a beating after World War II and during
the Cold War, but there remains in America a stubborn belief that
the nation can absent itself from foreign entnglements, global
economy or no global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Kosovo conflict has reopened the closet door for
those who question whether the United States has any business
endangering its sons and daughters, especially, if, as many
military experts argue, ground troops are needed to neutralize
Serbian troops and keep at least part of Kosovo for the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   How America answers that question will determine if NATO, which
is celebrating its 50th anniversary in Washington this weekend, has
any function or future. Already, serious questions have been raised
as to NATO's ability to respond quickly and effectively.
</P>
<P>
   How long does it take to get Apache helicopters in position and
then to get permission to use them?
</P>
<P>
   If ground troops are committed, how much planning is needed, and
is not time the enemy?
</P>
<P>
   Should NATO infantry, artillery, armor, and airborne troops
enter Kosovo, who will lead them? Have they had sufficient practice
in training together? Will they have better luck than the Nazi
troops whom the Serbs, fighting in their mountains, held at bay for
much of World War II?
</P>
<P>
   The questions recall one posed in 1948 by Robert A. Lovett, one
of President Harry Truman's key foreign policy advisers and a man
instrumental in creating the foundation that year for NATO's formal
coming-out in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   In their 1986 book, ``The Wise Men: Six Friends and the World
They Made,'' authors Walter Isaacson and Evan Thomas quoted Lovett
saying, ``The United States had sought peace through weakness. . .
. After many heartbreaks, it had reversed its policy and was
seeking to deter aggression by proof of determination. The only
question was how its determination should be implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-century later, the same question is frighteningly
current.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
