<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3775 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIAN-04     04-26 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIAN-0427-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PALESTINIAN STATE ON HOLD, BUT GAINING SUPPORT
 &HT;    575&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In recent weeks, frequent flyer Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat has traveled from Burkina Faso in Africa to the
dining room of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright seeking
support for statehood for the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
   He has brought his cause a long way, but is still short of its
goal.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday he apparently won U.S. promises that America will host
an Israeli-Palestinian summit meeting within six months and
increase pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (peace process) should not be open-ended,'' said White
House spokesman Joseph Lockhart. ``This can be done and should be
done with the framework of sometime over the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for those final diplomatic victories, Arafat is
expected to make clear in a meeting of PLO leaders back home in
Gaza Tuesday that the time is not right for a Palestinian
declaration of independence.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian parliament gave a nod in that direction Monday
by passing a nonbinding resolution -- adopted 41-1 with two
abstentions -- that does not mention a declaration of statehood on
May 4.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's meeting, 124-member Palestinian Central Council is
to decide what they will do on May 4, the date they see as the
expiration of the Oslo peace process and the day Arafat had vowed
would be the start of the Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians say the meeting may run for days and could result
in a reaffirmation of their right to statehood, along with
committees to prepare for eventual statehood under better
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Palestinians are limited to the crowded Gaza Strip
and more than 150 small pockets of land in the West Bank. With
Israel still controlling their movement and surrounding their
cities, many Palestinians say that statehood now would be only
symbolic, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian people understand that a meaningful state
cannot be declared with the situation as it is now,'' said
Palestinian legislator Marwan Kanafani. ``They will understand that
the time is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to their desire for better conditions, Palestinians are
hesitant to make any moves that could frighten Israelis into voting
for hard-line Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the May
17 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has been signaling for weeks that he will postpone the
declaration of statehood, instead seeking international support for
statehood at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   That diffused growing tension in the region. A year ago, many
predicted that the declaration could bring open warfare between the
Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Though most Israelis expect the formation of a Palestinian state
on their border someday, they want it to be the result of
negotiations and include restrictions against the formation of a
Palestinian army.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu considers a declaration a violation of the beleaguered
Oslo process and his aides have threatened to retake by force lands
already turned over to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians assert that they can declare statehood when the
term of the 1993 Oslo accords comes to an end, May 4. They note
that Israel has delayed land transfers and other provisions
expected under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Israel maintains that the date was just a target and the accords
stay in effect. Israelis blame the delays in Oslo on Palestinian
refusals to fight terror and enter negotiations on the hefty, final
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But, the statehood dispute appears to have been diffused by the
requests and promises of leaders in the U.S. and dozens of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   American officials, opposed to a unilateral declaration of
statehood, have recently increased their criticism of Israeli
home-building in areas that the Palestinians still claim as theirs.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lockhart said President Clinton was preparing to send
a letter to Arafat praising his work in the Oslo process, but
withholding support for a statehood declaration. American officials
said the letter will likely promise that the U.S. will lead a
summit meeting of Israeli and Palestinian leaders within six
months, and seek a resolution of the many issues remain under Oslo
within a year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials also promise to issue tougher statements against
controversial Israeli building in the disputed lands. All of the
promises will bring more pressure on Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, on Monday Netanyahu appeared to be salvaging a
political victory from the postponement by Arafat. He issued stern
warnings against a declaration and seemed ready to campaign on his
success in holding back Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
