<SLUG> BC-ELLINGTON-CENTENNIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLINGTON IS EVERYWHERE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies DUKE ELLINGTON) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Duke Ellington centennial is being celebrated by just about
everybody, from Down Beat magazine to the 22-year-old Carolina Jazz
Festival to local bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter of all this activity, though, is Jazz at Lincoln
Center, which in 1999 is focusing every single event, both in New
York and around the country, on Ellington.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights are the Essentially Ellington high school
jazz band competition and a five-month tour undertaken by the
Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra, which will visit Europe, Russia and
China.
</P>
<P>
   JALC has teamed with PBS for ``Swingin' With Duke: Lincoln
Center Jazz Orchestra With Wynton Marsalis,'' a 90-minute
documentary that premiers May 12.
</P>
<P>
   Featuring footage of Ellington and his band, interview segments
with Marsalis and footage of the LCJO taped live in a New York club
over three nights last August, ``Swingin' '' evokes both the fun
and sophistication of Ellington's music.
</P>
<P>
   The band is in top form, and several guests (saxophonist
Illinois Jacquet on ``Cottontail,'' vocalist Dianne Reeves) do a
commendable job. ``Swingin' '' is relatively light on hard-and-fast
biographical information, and it severely downplays Billy
Strayhorn's contributions, but it's a loving and well-assembled _
if not definitive _ tribute nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying CD, ``Live in Swing City,'' features many of
the cuts from the special, including ``Cottontail,'' Reeves singing
``Bli Blip,'' and strong takes on ``C Jam Blues'' and ``Black and
Tan Fantasy.'' It's a good CD, but it should have been longer: Some
of the best songs on the special, such as ``Dual Highway'' and
Reeves' performance of ``Rocks in My Bed,'' are missing.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz at Lincoln Center is also celebrating the centennial with
its first publication. ``Jump for Joy'' is a handsome 160-page book
with a 1947 essay on jazz by Ellington, two Wynton Marsalis
interviews, essays by Albert Murray and Ralph Ellison, rare photos,
photos by Gordon Parks, and artwork by, among others, Tony Bennett,
Paul Davis and Al Hirschfeld. The book is $25 and available at
select bookstores or by calling (212) 875-5299.
</P>
<P>
   There are also numerous Ellington reissues coming to your local
CD store. The big daddy is ``The Duke Ellington Centennial Edition:
The Complete RCA Victor Recordings 1927-1973,'' a 24-CD look at
Ellington's career. There are six CDs detailing the legendary
1940-1942 band that featured Ben Webster and Jimmy Blanton, and all
three of Ellington's sacred concerts from the '60s and '70s are
brought together for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Records is also reissuing a mess o' Duke: Four CDs are
being reissued: ``Such Sweet Thunder''; ``Black, Brown and Beige'';
``First Time! The Count Meets the Duke, Ellington at Newport 1956 _
Complete'' and the soundtrack to ``Anatomy of a Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   All will be out by mid-May and will be followed in July by ``The
Duke,'' a three-CD box surveying his work for Columbia, OKeh and
various American Record Company labels from 1927 to 1962.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
