A3794 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-26 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE TOO QUICK TO JUMP ON MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever it's time to start bashing the media for their excesses
_ especially the electronic media _ you'll usually find me near the
front of the line. For my money, there are few sights more annoying
than that of a TV news crew shoving a camera into the face of a
victim or a victim's loved one at the scene of some disaster or
other.
</P>
<P>
   I have long predicted that TV news will bring about the end of
civilization as we know it. TV news is simply too rude, too
intrusive, too intimidating, too irreversibly ubiquitous to coexist
with _ much less subjugate itself to _ the process of civilized
news-gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm being unfair to the hard-working folks who populate
the electronic media, but that's the way I feel about it. If I
didn't have an opinion, I'd be unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   So. My initial reaction was negative when the TV news hordes
started swarming all over Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., to report on the shooting-and-bombing rampage that left 15
people dead. Maybe it was the frenzied tone of the coverage, or the
cell-phone interviews with students trapped inside the building and
terrified that they would never leave the place alive.
</P>
<P>
   At first it just seemed like too much _ especially when the
networks began unveiling their ``Tragedy in Colorado'' logos and
their mournful theme music. They seemed to be turning mass murder
into entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   As the coverage continued, however, it became perfectly obvious
that this was a story of earth-shattering significance _ not just
to those involved and to the people of Colorado, but to all of
America. These schoolhouse slaughters have been occurring all too
often in this country; the American people are alarmed, and they
want every ounce of information they can get their hands on.
</P>
<P>
   The music and graphics were offensive, no doubt about it, but
that's the world we live in. The media _ all media _ are obsessed
with marketing nowadays. It surely didn't escape readers' attention
that the Fort Worth Star-Telegram labeled pages that carried
stories and photos from Littleton: ``COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTING.''
</P>
<P>
   When a caller to Mark Davis' talk show on radio station WBAP
complained about the overwrought packaging on CNN and other news
outlets, Davis replied that such things used to bother him but that
he ``got over that a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, too.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have been criticizing the incessant TV interviews
with students who survived the attack, with loved ones of those who
were killed, with friends and acquaintances of the teen-age gunmen
who carried out the attack and apparently committed suicide when
they were finished killing others. The interviews were jarring,
that's for sure, and it was sometimes hard to understand why these
people were subjecting themselves to the spectacle of live
television.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is, they were subjecting themselves to it. The TV
folks weren't shoving cameras and microphones in front of unwilling
participants.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the students, in fact, seemed to be eagerly making the
rounds, from CNN to ``Today'' to ``Good Morning America.'' If there
was any exploitation going on, the exploiters may have been
star-struck teens grabbing a once-in-a-lifetime chance to talk on
network television.
</P>
<P>
   You could criticize the networks for letting them get away with
it, I suppose, but let's get real: What self-respecting news
organization would turn down an interview with an eyewitness to
mass murder?
</P>
<P>
   Viewers ought to be smart enough to understand that some of
these witnesses might be less-than-reliable sources of information
_ and to evaluate the interviews in that context.
</P>
<P>
   It always strikes me as ironic when critics of the media accuse
TV news of exploiting such stories to boost ratings. If in fact
these stories do increase ratings, it means that the public is
clamoring for the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   That's not exploitation. It's supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, covering big stories like the Colorado massacre is
the media's job. They have to do it.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, they did it well.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
