<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE TO HEALING THAN JUST MEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If my people who are called by my name will humble themselves,
and pray and seek my face, and turn from their wicked ways, I will
hear their prayer, and will forgive their sin, and will heal their
land.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 Chronicles 7:14
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Healing is a process as old as Adam and Eve, and as necessary as
breathing. From infancy until death, we're repeatedly in need of
physical, mental or spiritual healing. And I'm convinced that they
are inseparable. Each affects the others.
</P>
<P>
   One frequent observation is that the healing process seems to
respond favorably to a strong will on the part of the patient to be
well. Still, even if we accept this as axiomatic and credit fully
the marvels of medicine, I believe that there may be other elements
involved as well.
</P>
<P>
   For the past month, plagued by a slow-healing leg and forced to
re-enter M.D. Anderson hospital for a second effort at a skin
graft, I've become keenly aware of one ingredient of healing:
humility.
</P>
<P>
   Being physically immobilized and dependent on the help of
others, even temporarily, is a humbling experience _ particularly
for guys like me whose self-image has been fed for years by others
coming to us for help.
</P>
<P>
   Some days in Congress, I'd have 50 or more pleas for
intercession of one sort and another. That role is exhilarating _
ego-inflating. Maybe I needed this experience to pierce my pride of
self-sufficiency like a punctured balloon.
</P>
<P>
   These days I've been nursed, wheeled around, fed, medicined,
chauffeured, pampered and made to feel virtually helpless. The
worst is being pushed through busy hospital halls in a wheelchair
by a family member or slender nurse and hoping that nobody
recognizes me. False ego, that's what this is!
</P>
<P>
   Well, the time comes when somebody else has to be the helper and
you the helpee. It never occurred to me before that for me to get
that intoxicating buzz of helping someone who needed it, there had
to be somebody willing to be helped.
</P>
<P>
   There is a socially redemptive role, then, in accepting help
graciously and being grateful for it. That's humbling, and a
necessary part of healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humble themselves.'' That's the way Solomon put the
providential mandate in 2 Chronicles. In other words, admit that we
need help. For individuals and nations in search of healing, it can
be the necessary first step.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a second ingredient of healing is patience, a virtue
with which I've had only a nodding acquaintance. Waiting comes hard
for me. If I were a crocus, I'd be breaking ground in February. Or,
a migratory duck, I'd probably head south in midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   So it was natural enough that I chafed at the slow recovery of
my leg, from which a bone was removed to make a new jaw. The
original skin graft on the leg did not take, requiring a second
effort. Meanwhile, immobilized, I grew impatient.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone conversation with my old friend Jake Pickle, I
expressed my feelings of frustration. ``Yes, it's understandable,''
said Jake, ``that you would feel that way. But let me tell you what
has happened to my relative.''
</P>
<P>
   A young man in Jake's family _ a remarkably gifted attorney
approaching the prime of his career, the head of an active law firm
_ had been seized by a stroke that has left him partially paralyzed
and (for the time being, at least) stripped of the capacity of
speech.
</P>
<P>
   I realized that my impediment was much less disabling, far more
easily endurable and infinitely less frustrating than his. A sudden
pang of reality reminded me that my temporary misfortune did not
rank mention in the same paragraph with his.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with impatience. It is, in one dimension,
egocentric and mindless of reality. Physical healing proceeds, for
the most part, at its own pace, assuming only our cooperation. It
stands to reason, therefore, that we abet its benign processes by
an awareness of our blessings and an empathetic consciousness of
the afflictions of others.
</P>
<P>
   Our needs for healing transcend the physical. For individuals
and for nations, they sometimes demand a letting go of the agents
of our irritation. Too often this is the hardest task of all. We
cherish the very resentments that, by agitating our ills, keep us
from being whole.
</P>
<P>
   An unwillingness to forgive the past _ just let it be and let it
go _ lies at the heart of much (and maybe even most) of our
suffering. Innocent people are harassed, uprooted and put to
senseless death in the Balkans today because of tortured memories
of things that happened five centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   To most Americans, the fear and hate that separate adherents of
different faiths are virtually incomprehensible. But are they any
more irrational, really, than some of the things that keep us angry
and can actually make us ill?
</P>
<P>
   Every psychiatrist is aware of the difficulties in exorcising
the demons of old, half-buried hurts and resentments that can eat
away at our inner selves and debilitate us. Feelings of guilt and
blame, left unresolved, produce all manner of physical symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Enter an old-fashioned word: ``forgiveness.'' To find healing,
we must be willing to forgive. Forgive ourselves. And forgive
others. Recognize it. Forgive it. And let it go. The sense of
relief as the burdens slip away can be palpable _ liberating.
</P>
<P>
   Healing can be a lot of things. It's part medical, part
mystical. We can influence it up to a point. Somehow I think it's
part humility, part patience, part gratitude and empathy, and part
forgiveness. And sometimes the most necessary healing is a healing
of the memories.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
