<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILT-IN SUNBLOCK  
 MARTIAL SUNDIAL  
 PROTECTING SALMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like someone who stays too long at the beach, plants can
occasionally overdo it in the sun. While they do not turn red from
sunburn, some plants can suffer irreversible damage to their
chloroplasts, the energy-producing structures within the cell, when
exposed to too much sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers in Britain and Sweden have discovered how one
plant, in effect, loads up on sunblock. Writing in the journal
Science, they describe a system in which too much light produces a
chemical that travels throughout the plant, activating genes that
have an antioxidant effect, protecting the cells from damage from
the excess energy.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists studied a variety of Arabidopsis, a common
research plant, that had been adapted to grow in low light
conditions. When one part of the plant is exposed to high-intensity
light, the chemical messenger, which the researchers suggest is
hydrogen peroxide, diffuses throughout the plant, even into shaded
portions, and switches on the genes. The whole plant thus becomes
acclimated to the higher light levels. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is not your typical garden ornament, the sundial that is to
be carried aboard a spacecraft due to land on Mars in January 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The sundial, a three-inch square of anodized aluminum with a
center post, will have a ring pattern arranged to represent the
orbits of Mars and Earth, the word ``Mars'' in more than 20
languages, including ancient Sumerian, and a message wishing future
explorers, human or other, ``a safe journey and the joy of
discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   The sundial is partly intended to enable space enthusiasts to
track the hours and seasons as the sun moves around the Martian
sky. Because no one knows exactly how the spacecraft, a Mars
Surveyor mission to be launched in 2001, will land, sundial lines
will be determined once the craft's orientation is determined, and
will be superimposed on photographs of the sundial to be posted on
a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The device's other function will be to help calibrate a
panoramic camera on the Mars lander, with the rings and colored
tiles in the corners serving as a test pattern. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may not taste like much grilled on the barbecue, but a rubber
salmon developed by researchers at the Department of Energy may go
a long way toward helping to save real fish.
</P>
<P>
   The six-inch fish, which contains electronic sensors to measure
motion and pressure, is designed to give researchers an idea of
what happens when a real salmon travels through a turbine at a
hydroelectric plant. Newly spawned salmon heading toward the sea on
the Snake and Columbia Rivers in the West must travel through many
such turbines at dams along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates are that up to 4 out of 10 fish do not survive the
trip, battered by the huge blades of the turbines that turn the
power generators.
</P>
<P>
   Experts within the hydropower industry say that by changing the
shape of turbine blades, the survival rate of salmon may increase.
With 16 salmon species in the Pacific Northwest now considered
threatened or endangered, any improvement in survival would be
welcome and may help the industry avoid what environmentalists have
suggested is the ultimate solution to protect the fish, the removal
of some of the dams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
