<HEADER>
A3824 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-TOBACCO-HNS &LR;      04-26 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-TOBACCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO DECIDE WHETHER FDA CAN REGULATE TOBACCO ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Days after the nation's last tobacco billboards
were taken down, the Supreme Court agreed Monday to hear a case
that could result in a further crackdown on cigarette advertising
and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The justices will examine whether the federal Food and Drug
Administration was correct in 1996 when it declared that it had the
authority to regulate nicotine as a drug and cigarettes as
drug-delivery devices.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA's decision became the cornerstone of the Clinton
administration's push to curb teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But last August the U.S. 4th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that
the FDA lacks such authority. In a 2 to 1 decision, the court said,
``Congress has reserved for itself the regulation of tobacco
products rather than delegating that regulation to the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration appealed that ruling, arguing that the FDA's
decision was justified by new evidence that the tobacco industry
intended its products to feed consumers' nicotine habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court of appeals was simply wrong,'' Solicitor General
Seth P. Waxman wrote in the government's appeal petition, which is
supported by 39 states. ``Unless reversed by this court, the
panel's ruling will deprive the public of an unparalleled
opportunity to prevent millions of children from beginning a highly
addictive habit that often leads to premature death.''
</P>
<P>
   But an industry coalition, in a brief filed by Richard M. Cooper
of the powerful Williams and Connolly law firm in Washington,
argued that the appeals court's decision was correct and that
Congress should decide how much authority the FDA should be
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FDA usurped Congress' authority to make policy to the
point of making it a federal offense for a service station or
convenience store to sell cigarettes without verifying the
purchaser's age,'' wrote Cooper, who represents R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co., Philip Morris, Lorillard, Brown and Williamson, U.S.
Tobacco, convenience store owners, grocers and tobacco
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry already has had to curtail certain types of
adverstising as part of an agreements reached last year with all 50
states.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements, which require the industry to pay $246 billion
over 25 years to settle state claims, ban cartoon characters in ads
and, effective last Friday, all tobacco billboards nationally.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the federal government plans to sue the industry to
recover federal health-insurance costs, and the industry faces
individual and class-action lawsuits by smokers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Following the high court's decision Monday to hear the case,
R.J. Reynolds General Counsel Charles A. Blixt said, ``We believe
the (appellate court) correctly interpreted and applied the laws
regarding FDA authority, and we believe that court's opinion will
be upheld by the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   If the FDA prevails in the case, several proposed regulations
could become law, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring retailers to check the photo identification of
anyone who appears under age 27;
</P>
<P>
   _ Banning vending machine sales and self-service displays,
except in places where minors are not allowed;
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibiting the sale of single cigarettes and giveaways of
tobacco products;
</P>
<P>
   _ Banning outdoor ads within 1,000 feet of schools and
playgrounds, and limiting other outdoor ads;
</P>
<P>
   _ Limiting ads in publications with high youth readership to
black-and-white print only.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton praised the court's decision to hear the case.
``Every day, 3,000 young people become regular smokers and 1,000
will have their lives cut short as a result,'' he said. ``I remain
firmly committed to the FDA rule, which will help stop young people
from smoking before they start.''
</P>
<P>
   After the court's announcement, anti-smoking activists cited the
importance of the FDA case, arguing that last year's industry
agreements with the states did not go far enough to restrict
tobacco marketing.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling on the FDA case is expected by summer 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
