<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3827 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EDGE-BOS &LR;      04-26 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS DEMONSTRATE LIFE ON THE EDGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not a moment to breathe around here.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Bill and Hillary came to town. Not since the Clinton
years started with Coast Guard and Navy ships ringing the Haitian
coast to assure that thousands of refugees didn't crowd onto
American shores. Not since the furor over Zoe Baird's baby sitter,
the controversy over a big inaugural bash for high-rolling
Democratic contributors, Clinton's suggestion he might be able to
reach some normalization of relations with Saddam Hussein, and
administration indications that there wouldn't be a tax cut for the
middle class after all.
</P>
<P>
   And all that was only the first few days of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   These may be years of peace and prosperity _ and yet they are
also the Frantic Years.
</P>
<P>
   Because after the first few days of tumult in the Clinton's
Washington came the fight over gays in the military. Two more
efforts to find an attorney general. Air strikes against Iraq.
Furious battles over an energy tax. Budget struggles. New crises in
Haiti. The Clinton health plan. Peace efforts in the Middle East.
More air strikes against Iraq. Continuous staff upheaval in the
White House. Whitewater. Travelgate. A firestorm over White House
entrance passes. Another one over FBI files. Sleepovers in the
White House. The 1992 campaign fund-raising scandal. The China
influence-buying scandal. The Cisneros scandal. The Espy scandal.
</P>
<P>
   And we haven't even mentioned the name Monica S. Lewinsky yet.
Or Kenneth W. Starr. Or Linda R. Tripp. Or Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crisis follows this guy around,'' says Leon Panetta, who was
Clinton's chief of staff. ``He cannot sit still, and as a result,
neither can we.''
</P>
<P>
   Crisis is, of course, the currency of the realm in the news
business, but history might remember the Clinton years as unusually
full of crisis for a period that, on the surface, might be regarded
as a time of serenity. But the fact that we regard this period as
The Frantic Years offers insights into the character of the
president and the nature of the American political culture at
century's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `crisis' suggests instability, and from the beginning
Clinton was under attack and under question,'' says William E.
Leuchtenberg, a University of North Carolina historian. ``He never
had a honeymoon, he never had a moment of peace. And a lot of it he
brought on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The frantic pace of the past six years is a reflection of the
frantic pace of Clinton's life _ and his outlook.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, he was a young man in a hurry. He has his own
explanation: His father died before he was born, on a wet swath of
highway in Missouri, and from the beginning Clinton was in a race _
to cram as much in before he died, to do as much as possible before
he reached his father's age. ``I had been living with the idea of
my father's death and therefore my own mortality since I was a kid,
and that's maybe why I competed so hard and wanted so much,''
Clinton said in a conversation in the autumn of 1991, before he
even entered the presidential race. ``By the time I was governor, I
had already lived three years longer than my father. To me I wasn't
a young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hurried through the beginning of his presidency, the way
he hurried through everything, making stormy a time that even his
critics were willing to grant him for a honeymoon. Seven days
before he was even inaugurated, Donald Devine, a Reagan
administration official and devout conservative, mused
sympathetically about how ``the poor guy doesn't seem to get a
honeymoon.''
</P>
<P>
   There was never a moment to waste, or even to rest; indeed the
greatest character flaw of the president might not be his weakness
for women but his inclination to see rest as a waste. There was
always something to do, maybe a policy that needed to be formed,
maybe an all-night bull session on welfare that couldn't be put
off, maybe (and here is another problem) a poll finding that needed
to be exploited. The result was a president, and a presidency, that
couldn't say no. It was a promiscuity of a political sort.
</P>
<P>
   Though an Oxford scholar and a lawyer, the president tends
toward the impulsive and not the introspective: He sees a problem
and he wants to do something about it, right this minute if
possible, tomorrow at the latest if not. Last week, after the
massacre in the Colorado high school, the president's instinct was
to fly west, perhaps to share the mourners' grief, perhaps to make
a presidential statement of outrage, perhaps only to share an
important moment in the life of the nation. In the end he didn't
go, deciding instead to visit a Virginia classroom to discuss
school violence, but the impulse provided an important insight into
the president's character.
</P>
<P>
   That impulsiveness, of course, sent him flying into trouble of
the gravest sort during his relationship with Lewinsky, a onetime
White House intern with a taste for dangerous liaisons to match the
president's. ``The man is addicted to risk in all its forms,'' says
Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political scientist at Claremont Graduate
University. In that regard, as in so many others, the character of
the presidency has taken on the character of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Many Clinton skeptics criticized the president for offering an
endless menu of suggestions (school uniforms, curfews) instead of
larger policy prescriptions. But perhaps the real danger of the
suggestion-box presidency was its tendency toward motion _ at the
very least, the impulse seemed to be, say something _ instead of
action, as if the president would be measured by the quantity of
his proposals rather than by the quality of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an exhausting president,'' says Richard Norton Smith, a
presidential historian. ``But a lot of it is the media. This is the
presidency under which the 24-hour news cycle has come of age.''
Indeed, Clinton's tendency to be engaged at a high level _ to be
``on'' _ matched the needs and inclinations of the era in
television and cable news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he's `on' all the time,'' Smith says, ``it's not
surprising how much he's on.''
</P>
<P>
   Television and the presidency both existed before Clinton;
before the current administration it was often said that television
came of age during the John Kennedy administration between 1961 to
1963. But in the last several years we have witnessed the
convergence of interests between Clinton, who is inclined toward
constant action like no president of recent memory, and the modern
electronic media, which constantly need new material.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year that convergence produced trouble for the
president, who faced an investigation and then impeachment, even as
it provided high ratings for cable television.
</P>
<P>
   But together the president and the electronic media that
tormented him ended up exhausting the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausting the American people _ and alienating them, too.
Throughout his difficulties, the president retained high
public-approval ratings, but interest in national affairs and in
Washington news flagged. That may be understandable _ readers and
viewers have the right to get tired, too _ but readers and viewers
are also voters, and the danger of the Frantic Years isn't that
Clinton got away with something, or that Clinton was unfairly
accused, but that the public _ the people who hire the politicians
to do their work for them _ has turned away. It's their government,
after all, not the president's, or the Congress's, or the press's.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the end of the Frantic Years, it is not only Washington
that is exhausted. We all are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
