<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS MUST PAY TO LAND INTERVIEW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ when you apply for law school or medical school, you
typically have to pay an application fee.
</P>
<P>
   But pay a fee to apply for a job?
</P>
<P>
   Several airlines actually charge the people who apply for jobs
as pilots anywhere from $50 to $150 for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines, for example, charges its pilot applicants
$100, while America West Airlines charges $50.
</P>
<P>
   To apply at Delta Air Lines, the applicant must register with a
online resume service and fork over $150 (annual renewals are
$100). That's the only method Delta uses to select its pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Continental Airlines doesn't charge pilots to
apply but those it wants to interview must pay $50.
</P>
<P>
   Several employment experts were surprised to hear that airlines
charge pilots to apply for jobs instead of considering recruitment
a regular cost of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on,'' said an incredulous Joe Ahmad, a Houston employment
lawyer. ``I used to think you had the right to work. Now I guess
you have to pay for the privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   So many pilots are drawn to work in what many consider a
glamorous job that airlines can run the show.
</P>
<P>
   They say that it's expensive to do an investigation of a pilot's
background, including a check of training records and criminal
court records, and that they're only trying to recoup some of their
costs.
</P>
<P>
   That rankles an out-of-work pilot who isn't exactly flush with
cash. It's expensive to apply, and as America West points out,
paying the $50 nonrefundable fee ``in no way obligates'' the
airline to interview the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   He said he keeps putting off his decision but has only until
April 30 to send his application and his $50 to America West.
</P>
<P>
   The jobs don't exactly pay a lot of money in the early years,
either, he said, asking not to be identified. He said a pilot's job
with America West would pay about $30,000 a year, a figure that
could not be confirmed because America West did not return repeated
phone calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But the salary figure appears to be in line with what other
airlines pay for their first-year pilots. Continental, for example,
pays its pilots $30,000 for their first year on the job, a
Continental spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AIRLINE SAYS IT'S NOT FOR PROFIT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are so used to making money from consumers, what with
sophisticated yield management systems and cutbacks in food
service, that they apparently got the idea to make money on job
applicants, Ahmad said.
</P>
<P>
   So are the application fees a new profit center for airlines?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely not, said John Hotard, spokesman for American in Fort
Worth. It costs several hundred dollars to check out a pilot
applicant, he said, adding American wants to make sure it gets only
serious candidates. He said applicants who can't afford $100 can
request a waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Continental doesn't automatically check out everyone who
applies, so that's why it charges $50 just to the pilots it picks
to interview, said spokesman David Messing.
</P>
<P>
   Delta uses the Universal Pilot Application Service to screen its
pilot applicants. The service, in turn, charges $150 to pilots to
list their resumes
</P>
<P>
   It's actually better for the pilots because instead of paying
$50 at one airline and $100 at another, they can pay just one fee
and get reviewed by several airlines, said Judy Tarver, president
of the online service in Leesburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EMPLOYEES LOST FOR LACK OF CASH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fees certainly run counter to the idea that it is important
to cast your net as wide as possible during the application process
in hopes of attracting the best employees, said John Challenger,
chief executive officer of Challenger, Gray and Christmas, the
outplacement firm in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The fees, he added, knock out people who may be strapped for
cash but would be great employees.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly why California passed a law last year prohibiting
employers from charging an application fee.
</P>
<P>
   What prompted the legislation was a lawsuit filed by the labor
commissioner of California against Northwest Airlines for imposing
a $25 application fee. After the commissioner lost the case, the
California Legislature passed its law forbidding the practice.
</P>
<P>
   There was fear that employers in other industries would begin
charging, said Jose Millan, assistant labor commissioner in San
Francisco, who also said application fees would inhibit people from
applying for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines used to charge its California pilot
applicants a fee but cut that out when the law changed. It was an
administrative nightmare, said Southwest spokesman Ed Stewart, and
eliminated good pilots who didn't want to pay.
</P>
<P>
   That's the last thing the expanding airline wants now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
