<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By C.CLAIBORNE RAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bears in Winter
</P>
<P>
   Q. Help settle a family dispute: do bears hibernate, or not?
</P>
<P>
   A. Bears do hibernate, though not as deeply as some other
hibernating animals.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the hibernation of ground squirrels has been found
to be much deeper than that of bears, Wayne Lynch writes in
``Bears'' (The Mountaineers).
</P>
<P>
   Ground squirrels do not sleep straight through the winter,
however, but rouse themselves every couple of weeks to urinate or
defecate, presumably with complex metabolic triggers. Bears can
spend up to five long months without eating, drinking, defecating
or urinating.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have recently suggested that recycling is what
permits bears to engage in what seems like a physiological
impossibility and emerge healthy. They seem to be able to make use
of bone degradation products to build new bone and urinary wastes
to make protein.
</P>
<P>
   Bears' hibernation, which is also called ``denning,'' is
different from that of deep hibernators, which spend most of the
winter with drastically lowered body temperatures. Bears lower
their body temperatures only slightly and continue to burn about
4,000 calories a day, resulting in a Zen-like state of watchful
rest. They can quickly rouse themselves in response to intruders
and can even nurse their young during hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   Readers are invited to submit questions by postal mail to
Questions, Science Times, The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New
York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to: Question(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Questions of general interest will be answered in this column,
but requests for medical advice cannot be honored and unpublished
letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
