<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEALTH-SURVEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CARE SYSTEM IN U.S. CALLED SEPARATE AND UNEQUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Middle-income blacks, Hispanics and whites have significantly
different attitudes toward health care, a new national survey
confirms with a range of new statistics. This research raises
concern among minority leaders that two separate and unequal
systems of care have developed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted by Morehouse College of Medicine, a
predominantly black institution in Atlanta, and the New American
Wellness Group, a communications and marketing company that focuses
on minority health care issues.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Louis W. Sullivan, president of Morehouse and former
secretary of health and human services, said, ``Everybody believes
that because we are all human beings, we are all the same.'' But
the survey shows that ``when we get sick we are very different.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Thorne, managing director of New American Wellness,
attributed this difference in part to the health care industry's
not having done a better job of developing treatment and education
programs ``that are culturally appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The random-sample survey was restricted to people from 21 to 65
years old with health insurance and incomes of $20,000 to $60,000.
Half were women.
</P>
<P>
   Among the significant findings was that far fewer blacks and
Hispanics than whites had a doctor of their own race or ethnicity.
Among whites, 90 percent had a white doctor; 40 percent of blacks,
a black doctor, and 50 percent of Hispanics, a Hispanic doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Other medical authorities have long stressed the general
importance of a patient's having access to a doctor of the same
racial or ethnic background in helping the doctor fully understand
the patient and in building confidence on the part of the patient
in the doctor and the entire health-care process. A chief aspect of
the problem has been a shortage of minority doctors, a condition
that is growing worse. Minority enrollment has been declining
steadily at medical schools in the United States since 1994, as
affirmative action programs aimed at expanding it have been cut
back.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the survey shows that blacks sought medical
advice more often than whites, or Hispanics. Eighty-five percent of
blacks surveyed had seen a doctor within the past year, compared
with 76 percent of whites and 70 percent of Hispanics. But the
higher visitation rate among blacks was found not to be a measure
of confidence in the system but rather a lack of information about
the system, about health care in general and about health
maintenance. And the lower rate among Hispanics was attributed to
an unfamiliarity with available services, as well as the lack of
access or a cultural focus on the needs of the family rather than
the individual.
</P>
<P>
   Another cause for concern was that compared with whites and
Hispanics, a higher percentage of blacks _ 36 percent _ did not
take their medicine. Among whites and Hispanics, the rates were 18
percent and 15 percent. The reasons cited among all groups included
forgetting to do so, fear of possible side effects, inconvenience,
cost and a disbelief in effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The overall findings, Sullivan said, are reflected ``in the
number of minorities who contract illness, and in the number who
die for those illnesses.'' Blacks, according to the National Center
for Health Statistics, for example, have a life span seven years
shorter than whites.
</P>
</TEXT>
