<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S POLITICAL ROAD STARTING TO GET ROUGHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A funny (but not to him) thing has happened to
Gov. George W. Bush on his way to a carefully scripted race for the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   More and more questions are being asked about his leadership
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine! Some people actually want to know how strong a leader
is this popular Texan who aspires to be the next leader of the Free
World.
</P>
<P>
   The question is beginning to nag at Bush partly because, in his
effort to snuff out controversy at home before it can damage him in
a national campaign, he is picking his legislative fights very
carefully this session and is having trouble with some of those.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has made his wishes publicly clear on only a
handful of bills, and one of the most visible measures that he is
supporting, a pilot program for tax-backed vouchers for private
schools, is in serious trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he is watching his proposed $2.6 billion tax cut
being whittled down by Republican and Democratic lawmakers a alike.
</P>
<P>
   People expect more of Bush _ and rightfully so _ because of his
presidential aspirations, but it's been a long time since the Texas
governor's office resembled anything close to a hotbed of
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The last strong governors that Texas had were Allan Shivers,
Price Daniel Sr. and, to a lesser extent, John Connally in the
1950s and 1960s, when Texas was making a painful transition from a
rural to an urban state.
</P>
<P>
   Texas governors' formal powers were as weak then as they are
now. But those governors used their bully pulpits, lobbying skills,
personalities and, sometimes, sheer threats against lawmakers to
force new programs and long-overdue improvements in many state
services.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent governors also have had their programs and
priorities, but their leadership has been inconsistent. Stronger
leadership has come from legislative leaders, particularly from the
lieutenant governor's office during the 26 years that Bob Bullock
and Bill Hobby held the job.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's immediate predecessor, Democrat Ann Richards, earned some
strong marks during her first legislative session in 1991. She
lobbied lawmakers for a new state lottery, pushed for reforms in
insurance regulation, ordered her appointees to the Board of
Pardons and Paroles to sharply reduce early releases from
overcrowded prisons and backed a huge prison expansion program.
</P>
<P>
   But she almost disappeared during the 1993 session, apparently
to avoid controversies that could hurt her 1994 re-election bid,
which she lost to Bush anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, who preferred jetting around the country to the more
mundane task of dealing with legislators, lost some of the
insurance reforms during that second session. One of the few times
she did surface in 1993 was to threaten to veto a bill to let
private citizens carry concealed handguns. Her threat killed the
bill that session, and it also helped kill her re-election chances.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Mark White was in a hurry when he moved into the
governor's office in 1983. His confrontational style angered many
legislators, Democrats as well as Republicans, before Ross Perot
and legislative leaders helped White win passage of some major
educational reforms.
</P>
<P>
   White was more low-key during the 1985 session, perhaps trying
to save political capital for his re-election race. But he had to
take a distasteful leadership role in 1986, after the bottom fell
out of oil prices. Two months before Election Day, he had to urge
the Legislature to raise taxes and cut spending to balance the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature did, and the voters booted White out of office,
partly because of the tax increase, partly because of the poor
economy and partly because teachers were still angry at him over
some of the education reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clements made history in 1978, when he was elected Texas'
first Republican governor of modern times. He made some strong
appointments during his first term but also spent a lot of time
learning what the Legislature was all about.
</P>
<P>
   After Clements staged a comeback in 1986, he spent most of his
second term fighting Democratic legislators over tax bills _ and
losing _ as Texas struggled to pull itself out of a recession.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got high marks during his first legislative session in 1995
for winning approval of his four top priorities _ civil justice
changes, welfare reform, educational improvements and tougher laws
against juvenile offenders. But getting those bills passed didn't
require much heavy lifting because Democratic legislative leaders
and most lawmakers shared his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush faced a more difficult test in 1997, when he tried to
overhaul state taxes but was able instead to salvage only a meager
amount (per taxpayer) of property tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's 1997 tax reform failure obviously didn't hurt his
re-election last year against a weak Democratic challenger. His
next political race, however, will be more difficult, and his
leadership will be increasingly questioned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
