<SLUG> BC-COURT-TOBACCO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO DECIDE WHETHER FDA CAN REGULATE TOBACCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: FIXES headline and changes 10th graf, removing the word an
and correcting a typo in the word advertising)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Days after the nation's last tobacco billboards
were taken down, the Supreme Court agreed Monday to hear a case
that could result in a further crackdown on cigarette advertising
and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The justices will examine whether the federal Food and Drug
Administration was correct in 1996 when it declared that it had the
authority to regulate nicotine as a drug and cigarettes as
drug-delivery devices.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA's decision became the cornerstone of the Clinton
administration's push to curb teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But last August the U.S. 4th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that
the FDA lacks such authority. In a 2 to 1 decision, the court said,
``Congress has reserved for itself the regulation of tobacco
products rather than delegating that regulation to the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration appealed that ruling, arguing that the FDA's
decision was justified by new evidence that the tobacco industry
intended its products to feed consumers' nicotine habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court of appeals was simply wrong,'' Solicitor General
Seth P. Waxman wrote in the government's appeal petition, which is
supported by 39 states. ``Unless reversed by this court, the
panel's ruling will deprive the public of an unparalleled
opportunity to prevent millions of children from beginning a highly
addictive habit that often leads to premature death.''
</P>
<P>
   But an industry coalition, in a brief filed by Richard M. Cooper
of the powerful Williams and Connolly law firm in Washington,
argued that the appeals court's decision was correct and that
Congress should decide how much authority the FDA should be
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FDA usurped Congress' authority to make policy to the
point of making it a federal offense for a service station or
convenience store to sell cigarettes without verifying the
purchaser's age,'' wrote Cooper, who represents R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co., Philip Morris, Lorillard, Brown and Williamson, U.S.
Tobacco, convenience store owners, grocers and tobacco
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco industry already has had to curtail certain types of
advertising as part of agreements reached last year with all 50
states.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements, which require the industry to pay $246 billion
over 25 years to settle state claims, ban cartoon characters in ads
and, effective last Friday, all tobacco billboards nationally.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the federal government plans to sue the industry to
recover federal health-insurance costs, and the industry faces
individual and class-action lawsuits by smokers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Following the high court's decision Monday to hear the case,
R.J. Reynolds General Counsel Charles A. Blixt said, ``We believe
the (appellate court) correctly interpreted and applied the laws
regarding FDA authority, and we believe that court's opinion will
be upheld by the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   If the FDA prevails in the case, several proposed regulations
could become law, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring retailers to check the photo identification of
anyone who appears under age 27;
</P>
<P>
   _ Banning vending machine sales and self-service displays,
except in places where minors are not allowed;
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibiting the sale of single cigarettes and giveaways of
tobacco products;
</P>
<P>
   _ Banning outdoor ads within 1,000 feet of schools and
playgrounds, and limiting other outdoor ads;
</P>
<P>
   _ Limiting ads in publications with high youth readership to
black-and-white print only.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton praised the court's decision to hear the case.
``Every day, 3,000 young people become regular smokers and 1,000
will have their lives cut short as a result,'' he said. ``I remain
firmly committed to the FDA rule, which will help stop young people
from smoking before they start.''
</P>
<P>
   After the court's announcement, anti-smoking activists cited the
importance of the FDA case, arguing that last year's industry
agreements with the states did not go far enough to restrict
tobacco marketing.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling on the FDA case is expected by summer 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3844 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0427-     04-26 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0427-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALBANIAN AUTHORITIES DEMANDING THAT KOSOVO REFUGEES LEAVE,
DISPERSE
 &HT;    560&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0427.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Nearly 100,000 Kosovo refugees are getting what
may be a last chance Tuesday to voluntarily move away from this
tenuous border region, before Albanian authorities order them to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been negotiating to prevent the use of force,'' said
Jacques Franquin, spokesman for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) here.
</P>
<P>
   An Albanian government official said in an interview Monday that
authorities would not forcibly remove the refugees, but he also
said that they simply must get out.
</P>
<P>
   Besides fearing the danger of massive numbers of deaths should
the conflict between U.S.-led NATO and Serb-led Yugoslav forces
expand, authorities see their region buckling socially and
physically under the burden of so many refugees, said special
government envoy Kristo Mertiri.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian government officials were prepared Sunday to issue the
humanitarian groups a deadline for moving out masses of the Kosovar
Albanian refugees who began coming here a month ago to escape Serb
ethnic cleansing in Yugoslavia's southern Kosovo province, Franquin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But long discussions led the Albanians to give the UNHCR another
opportunity to convince the refugees to go voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday refugee leaders are to be flown on NATO helicopters
to the sites where the government wants them to be relocated in
cities more distant from the border. They will report on the
conditions there, and recommend to their people whether they should
depart or stay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so difficult, because they will feel for the second time
that they have been expelled from their houses. The first time in
Kosovo and the second time from these tents,'' said Shaip Hajdari,
37, one of the leaders who was selected to take the helicopter
excursion Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Hajdari, speaking Monday outside his tent camp where rain
persisted and mud approached ankle level, pulled from his pocket a
rumpled notebook in which he had recorded the names of every family
in the 104 tents in his camp. The camp leaders had visited each and
polled them on whether they want to go or want to stay here, closer
to their homes and to relatives who have not yet managed to escape
from -- or been forced out of -- Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all said, 'If it is up to us, no,''' he said, showing the
column of names and responses in his ruled notebook.
</P>
<P>
   Hajdari said he thinks the helicopter site inspection will be
useful. If the conditions are good, he said, he believes the people
can be convinced to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the conditions are not suitable, we shall refuse,'' he
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   He also said refugees are unwilling to go if the aim is simply
clearing space for an expected influx of more Kosovo exiles. They
wonder why the authorities don't take incoming refugees directly to
the new sites, rather than relocate the people already settled in
these tents.
</P>
<P>
   They are more sympathetic to the argument they have heard that
NATO may need this as a staging area for raids across the border
into Yugoslavia, he said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO commanders have not announced any plan to use this area as
a base or a route for the Apache attack helicopters expected to be
operational some time soon. But it is assumed that the Apaches will
need some forward base closer to Yugoslav targets than is the main
NATO military concentration near the Albanian capital of Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The UNHCR's Franquin acknowledged the talk that NATO may want
this area cleared of refugees as badly as do local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely would facilitate a NATO deployment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Serb shelling already a fact of life just 25 miles from
here, the possibility of an attack is not alarmist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Albanian officials) have to evacuate the population
because of a war situation exploding, they will put priority on
their own population before the refugees,'' Franquin said. ``Then
we will be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Mertiri, who is part of a special team the central government
sent as liaison here, said relocating the refugees is the number
one priority for his government. Security is the first reason, but
not the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be total destabilization in this country,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the stress of having 100,000 refugees -- an estimated
350,000 to 400,000 Kosovo exiles have arrived here since the end of
March -- in a city of less than 25,000 located in one of the poorer
regions of a poor country. Families that have taken in 40,000 of
them are feeling the strain, and they are not getting enough help
from international relief agencies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have problems of living, problems of food, problems of
health,'' he said. ``There are more than 30 humanitarian
organizations here, but their help is not sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
