<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, April 27, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The disturbance that spawned severe thunderstorms Monday across
parts of the western Gulf States will weaken Tuesday as it lifts
slowly east-northeast toward the middle Mississippi Valley.
Nonetheless, potent thunderstorms, some with hail, gusty winds and
downpours, will erupt over parts of Arkansas, western Tennessee and
Missouri. Storms may develop southward into Mississippi and Alabama
as humid air from the Gulf of Mexico converges along of a cool
front associated with the disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   On the system's northern flank, steady rains, some with thunder,
will douse parts of the southwest Great Lakes and lower Ohio
Valley. Rainfalls could be moderate to heavy in spots. Meanwhile,
an expansive, stationary high pressure system centered over Hudson
Bay will block the advance of rain into the eastern Great Lakes and
northern Middle Atlantic States.
</P>
<P>
   Puffy clouds and isolated showers will sprout over parts of New
England as a high-level pool of cold air, which will continue to be
wedged between the high over Hudson Bay and another stagnant high
centered over the north Atlantic, combines will the sun's heating
of the ground to destabilize the atmosphere. Showers will be mainly
restricted to the mountains of northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, air temperatures at 18,000 feet off the coast of British
Columbia fell toward minus 33 degrees as a high-altitude pool of
frigid air sank southward. Tuesday, scattered showers and
thunderstorms, some with small hail and gusty winds, will develop
over parts of Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Oklahoma Downpour
</P>
<P>
   A deluge engulfed Oklahoma City on Sunday. Torrents of rain
poured on the city and when the rain tapered off to drizzle, most
sections had measured over 3 inches. At Will Rogers World Airport,
a daily record of 3.79 inches was noted. This rain tally was a mere
.01 inches shy of the 24 hour record for April. A very mild, moist
flow ahead of a sluggish storm exiting the Rockies was lifted by a
ribbon of strong winds just above the surface. This produced a
cluster of thunderstorms on Sunday. The same thing occurred on
Monday, but this time, the heaviest rain fell just east of the
city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
