<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     04-26 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA ABUSES ITS POWER TO DEFEND MEDIEVAL PRISON POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c. 1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state of California is harassing a respected freelance
journalist because he has advocated changing the state's prison
policy in regard to interviewing inmates. The California Justice
Department ordered Peter Sussman to produce editorial, financial,
phone, computer records and tapes relating to anything the
journalist has written, posted on the Internet (including e-mails),
or said regarding prison access policies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the state's assistant attorneys general, Jane Catherine
Malich, also subpoenaed Sussman for a deposition _ the deposition
lasted 14 hours over several days, according to Sussman.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 to 1997, Sussman was the president of the Northern
California Chapter of the Society of Professional Journalists.
During that period, the California Department of Corrections issued
new rules disallowing all face-to-face interviews with specified
prisoners and eliminating the confidentiality of inmate mail to the
news media. Sussman worked to oppose the new regulations and then
to reverse them legislatively. He has written extensively about
media access to prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep of the subpoena also requires him to produce all
notes, writings, tape recordings of interviews, news clips, diary
notes, electronic exchanges on an Internet bulletin board called
the WELL, contracts with publishers, drafts and any of his
published work that might relate to California regulations
regarding access to prisoners. It includes anything related to his
``opposition, either as individual or as an officer or former
officer'' of SPJ to changes in prison policies that restrict news
media access to inmates. He is also required to produce all
documents relating to contacts with lawyers over the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   It would take hundreds of hours just to log the thousands of
materials the subpoena demands so that Sussman can claim reporter's
privilege on each item and record why he claims privilege. If the
court decides an item falls under a reporter's privilege, that item
presumably would not actually have to be produced. But Sussman
works alone and acceding to the subpoena will put a halt to his
work as a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Kirtley, executive director of the Reporters Committee for
Freedom of the Press, called the actions by the California attorney
general's office, ``astonishing,'' and ``an abuse of the subpoena
process.'' She ended her interview by saying, ``This is a `thought
police' kind of thing that is indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sussman got sucked into this nightmare because a California
prisoner, Robert Woodard, filed a civil rights lawsuit against the
warden and other prison officials of the California Men's Colony in
San Luis Obispo where he was incarcerated. Woodard had only heard
of Sussman and had not talked to him prior to the alleged
infractions that got Woodard in trouble with prison officials.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard was the editor of the prison newspaper, The
Communicator, from 1993 to Feb. 1996, when he wrote a letter to
another journalist about new regulations regarding prison
interviews. David Newdorf represents Woodard. He said Woodard had
invited a journalist to come to the prison to interview his rock
band. The drummer for the inmate band had once played with Eric
Clapton. That invitation caused Woodard to be punished for
``circumventing policies.'' He was removed from the newspaper
staff, charged and found guilty of violating prison rules. Newdorf
claims the so-called ``unwritten change of policy'' did not exist
prior to Woodard's invitation to the journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Newdorf, of the law firm O'Melveny &AMP; Myers in San Francisco, had
an interest in prison access policies, too, and decided to
represent Woodard after seeking out Sussman to discuss the issues.
Later, Newdorf asked Sussman to be an unpaid consultant. According
to Newdorf, Sussman knows more about prison access policies than
anyone except for officials at the California Department of
Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Newdorf listed Sussman as a likely witness in his lawsuit. At
this point, Newdorf said in an interview Friday that he doesn't
know whether he will actually call Sussman as a witness.
Nevertheless, the AG's subpoena goes far beyond what Sussman could
be asked as the plaintiff's witness. Much of the materials demanded
by the subpoena are simply not relevant to Woodard's claims.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Barankin, a spokesman for the California attorney
general's office, said that Sussman is ``very involved in the
litigation and has been working closely with the plaintiff,
Woodard.'' The AG's office, according to Barankin, has the
impression that Sussman will be called as an ``expert witness.''
Not so, says Newdorf, noting that the deadline for naming expert
witnesses has already passed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, April 29, there will be a hearing on whether
Sussman must produce a privilege log indicating which of the
voluminous records the AG's office wants that he thinks should be
confidential. Creating such a log will consume hundreds of hours,
since collecting and reviewing the materials themselves would take
months.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another political wrinkle in this legal farce. The
newly elected California attorney general is Bill Lockyer, a former
state legislator known for his deep commitment to First Amendment
freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Barankin said Lockyer is reviewing the case.
</P>
<P>
   California has one of the most restrictive policies regarding
news media access to prison inmates. These policies severely hamper
the news media's watchdog role in regard to how prisons are run.
</P>
<P>
   It should be no surprise that prison officials in Corcoran, one
of California's prisons, were pitting inmates against each other,
as if they were gladiators in the Roman Coliseum. Prison guards bet
on who would win the matches. Seven inmates were shot and killed by
a prison guard, according to Los Angeles Times stories, because the
guards didn't want those inmates to win.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of its Medieval prison policies, the AG's office has
turned its enormous power against a journalist who has been
eloquent in his advocacy for more enlightened prison policies. This
is clearly an abuse of power used to shield an abusive policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3859 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITALSIGNS-NYT &LR;      04-26 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
 SIGNS-NYT   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PREVENTION: A Plan to Keep Drivers Free of Seizures &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seizure disorders can be controlled by medication, but not for
all patients and not always perfectly. That makes driving a gamble,
which is why most states require people with epilepsy to be
seizure-free for a specified length of time before they get behind
the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Now a new study, published in the current issue of the journal
Neurology, will help physicians design safer driving programs for
patients by offering them a way to evaluate their risks.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gregory Krauss, a neurologist at Johns Hopkins University in
Baltimore who led the study, said the project was organized because
so many patients in the university's epilepsy clinic crashed after
having seizures while driving.
</P>
<P>
   While seizures account for only a tiny portion of the nation's
auto fatalities each year, and only 10 percent of crashes involving
epileptics are attributed to sizures, it is still a subject of
great anxiety to patients weighing the risks of driving.
</P>
<P>
   The study, undertaken by researchers at Johns Hopkins and the
University of Maryland looked at the driving and medical histories
of 100 epilepsy patients, half of whom had been involved in
seizure-related crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor in predicting risk was the length of time a
patient had been seizure-free. Those who had gone a year or more
were 90 percent less likely to crash than those with shorter
intervals.
</P>
<P>
   Another finding was that patients whose seizures were preceded
by auras _ an odd sensation or movement _ were less likely to
crash. But Krauss cautioned that auras gave only limited
protection: some patients were unable to get off the road in time
to make use of the warning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Krauss said he was surprised by the number of patients who were
not reporting seizures to motor vehicle authorities, as required by
law. More than half of the drivers who crashed were driving sooner
after a seizure than the law allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Krauss suggested doctors make these points to patients: Take
rules regarding waiting periods after seizures seriously; keep up
with medication and have it adjusted as needed, and act fast if a
warning sign occurs.
</P>
<P>
   REMEDIES: For Broken Teeth, It's Low-Fat Milk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Pour a glass of milk and see me right away.
</P>
<P>
   Question: What is a dentist's advice in the event of a
knocked-out tooth?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the very best thing to do is put the tooth right back
in the socket it came out of. But few people are willing to try
that, especially when it's their child's tooth they're holding,
said Dr. Leif K. Bakland, a professor of dentistry at Loma Linda
University in California. ``Parents are often squeamish about doing
that and they worry about doing it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bakland made a presentation last week to a conference in Atlanta
of the American Association of Endodontists, root canal
specialists, on a new approach to educating the public about steps
to take to help insure successful reinsertion of displaced teeth.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest threats to the tooth are dehydration and
infection, he said. Putting a tooth in water is better than letting
it dry out, but there the tooth faces the opposite problem _ cells
in the root may absorb so much water that they burst, sometimes
within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Milk, on the other hand, is not only free of harmful bacteria,
Bakland said, but is also absorbed slowly enough to pose far less
of a threat than water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skim or low-fat milk is best for the tooth, but don't waste
time looking for it if whole milk is the only type available,'' he
said. ``The difference isn't significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the tooth is safely doused, call a dentist or head to an
emergency room, he advised.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the emergency room, ask whether there is a
dentist on staff, Bakland added. In most cases, a root canal will
be performed to remove damaged tissue, and the tooth crowned.
</P>
<P>
   But time is of the essence, he said. So get a glass and go.
</P>
<P>
   SAFETY: Applying Sunscreen to a Playground &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to protect children from damaging ultraviolet rays,
three agencies plan to build what they describe as the nation's
first intentionally sun-safe playground.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Aid Society, the American Academy of
Dermatologists, and Kaboom, a playground safety group, will
undertake the project on Friday at the Goodhue Center on Staten
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun produces rays of ultraviolet light that can enter the
skin and cause a variety of changes,'' said Dr. Roger Ceilley, a
dermatologist who is a past president of the academy and
co-chairman of the National Coalition for Sun Safety. ``Damage to
DNA can lead to skin cancer, damage to collagen and to elastic
tissue can lead to premature aging, and sunlight that goes
unfiltered into the eyes can lead to cataracts and other eye
problems,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The dermatologists academy estimates that children get 80
percent of their lifetime sun exposure by the time they turn 18,
and that a child born in 1999 has a 1-in-5 risk of developing skin
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``While kids are at school, they go out to play in the late
morning, noon or early afternoon,'' Ceilley said. ``The sun is the
most dangerous then. Through volunteer efforts, people have been
installing equipment-safe playgrounds around the country. Why not
make them safe for sun protection?''
</P>
<P>
   Ilene Pappert, director of the Goodhue Center, said the
playground would have swings, a seesaw, covered bridges and
tube-encased slides, and the entire structure would be shielded
from the sun by a special cover that is like a tarpaulin. Benches
will be shaded with roofs to protect the adults watching the
children.
</P>
<P>
   Ceilley also offered the following sun-safety guidelines:
``Avoid midday sun. If you are out in it, wear a hat with at least
a four-inch brim, protective clothes, a minimum of No. 15
sunscreen, and make sure it's reapplied if you're in and out of
water.''
</P>
<P>
   LONGEVITY: Cabernet Sauvignon, the Healthy Toast? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almost 30 years ago, researchers discovered that Europeans in
Mediterranean countries were less likely to suffer from heart
disease than people elsewhere. This better health was attributed to
the Mediterranean diet, one low in meat and high in fruits,
vegetables, olive oil and wine.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial in the current issue of the journal Heart, a
cardiologist in the Bordeaux region of France, Dr. Jean-Paul
Broustet, recounted three decades of research on the health
benefits of wine, concluding that cabernet sauvignon made from
Bordeaux grapes was the best wine to drink for good cardiovascular
health and longevity.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote that the highest concentrations of resveratrol, a
compound that is said to reduce cholesterol in the body and help
prevent clogged arteries and blood clots, was typically found in
Bordeaux grapes. He also noted that good amounts of quercitin,
which helps to break up clots and to dilate blood vessels,
increasing circulation, were also present in his native crop.
</P>
<P>
   But Broustet warned against the dangers of overindulgence,
including high blood pressure, cirrhosis of the liver and car
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   He advocated a regimen of a daily consumption of a half bottle
of red wine with food.
</P>
</TEXT>
