<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3862 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT-A     04-26 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROLE MODEL' WITH A PAST CLOUDS MEDICAL TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, France, Great Britain, Italy)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ In the seven months since an Australian man
received a new hand and forearm in France, he has defied medical
dogma. His body has not rejected the graft, and nerves are
regenerating faster than his doctors expected. Yet the relationship
of the transplant pioneer, Clint Hallam, 48, and the doctors is
strained over his lack of further progress.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam is gaining feeling in his new fingers and hand. He has
clipped new fingernails, and hair is growing on the forearm below
its point of attachment. Hallam, who said he is a former computer
consultant, looks trim and healthy. He also said he was going to a
gym at least four hours a day and was taking lessons to resume
playing the piano and flying an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   That degree of success has come despite the extraordinary way in
which doctors have carried out the first hand transplant performed
with microsurgery and anti-rejection drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam flew halfway around the world from his home in Perth to
get a dead Frenchman's hand from a team of doctors from Australia,
England, France and Italy that Dr. Earl Owen, a microsurgeon in
Sydney, assembled at the Edouard Herriot Hospital in Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors chose an unusual patient for the experiment, and
that has caused embarrassment to all parties. Only at the time of
surgery, Owen said, did doctors learn that Hallam, who underwent
extensive psychological testing in Australia and France, had lost
his hand to a saw while in a prison in New Zealand in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Hallam said that eight months before the
transplant he told Owen and his wife the precise circumstances, but
Owen said that Hallam had told him he was a carpenter, omitting the
part about prison.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam has gained some hand function. But progress has been
erratic. He said he has lost dexterity in the six weeks he has been
back in Australia, and the patient and the doctors offer differing
explanations. The doctors attributed it to Hallam's not following
prescribed supervised physical and occupational therapy. Hallam
disagrees, arguing that Australian doctors are less demanding and
creative than their French colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a first and they do not want to do anything that could
damage it, which results in less progress,'' Hallam said.
</P>
<P>
   A hand transplant depends on public appeals for organ and tissue
donors. Thus, doctors say, a transplant recipient, particularly in
a landmark case, has social and moral obligations to make such an
experiment succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam agreed, saying he wants ``to make it work and to show
that it is not a Frankenstein operation and not a freak of
medicine.'' Hallam views himself as a role model for people with
lost limbs who look to a day when they can safely receive
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   But his doctors feel let down. ``We doctors are disappointed in
him, but we're not disappointed in his medical condition,'' which
is a ``fantastic result,'' Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that this particular person was picked, but
we have to go along with it, and try to treat him in a humanitarian
way however he treats us because he's a role model,'' Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam was chosen for the experiment in part because he
convinced the doctors of his dedication and ability to pay for much
of it, and because he assured them he could leave Australia at a
moment's notice when the team was assembled in France, Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   Owen said he was not aware of what Australian and New Zealand
newspapers later reported: that Hallam, who had been convicted of
fraud, was wanted on fraud charges in Australia and bankruptcy
matters in New Zealand. (Officials have not pressed charges.) Owen
also said he did not initially know that Hallam was classified as
an illegal immigrant in Australia because he had failed to
acknowledge his prison record.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his experience with Hallam, Owen said last week,
``The whole thing is a nightmare of friendly deception,'' and ``in
retrospect, I was being conned.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors believe Hallam's physical rehabilitation has been slowed
by his stopping supervised therapy. Hallam argues that he knows his
body best and has long struggled with visa problems with Australian
officials. A spokeswoman for the Australian Embassy in Washington
said laws prohibited it from commenting on individual visa
applications.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Instead of returning directly to Perth to continue supervised
rehabilitation, Hallam said he visited friends and relatives in
Europe and the United States. In London, Hallam went to a pub with
a member of the transplant team, Dr. Nadey Hakim, and used his new
hand to lift a pint of beer and drink from it.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam said he took charge of his own rehabilitation during the
six-week odyssey, stopping his supervised physical and occupational
therapy and performing what the French physiotherapists had taught
him. He continued taking anti-rejection drugs. Hallam said he was
confident that any rejection problem ``would be clearly visible''
because he was the world's first transplant patient who could ``see
how the operation is proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the lack of supervised therapy was like having his hand
immobilized in a plaster cast and held back Hallam's progress,
Hallam's doctors said. Hallam said he had ``lost 40 percent of the
strength in my hand'' at the time he returned to Perth, and more
since then. Now, Hallam said, he ``can barely hold an empty glass
tumbler.'' Owen said Hallam could flex each digit a little and bend
back his wrist about 20 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In many experiments, participants are not responsible for the
medical costs but do have to pay to get to where their progress is
monitored, which may be far away from their homes. For Hallam, it
means traveling 2,024 miles across Australia to Owen's office in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Videotapes of Hallam's last examination in Sydney in late March
show that sensation has reached the tips of two of Hallam's new
fingers. Pin pricks elicit pain in his little and ring fingers.
Hallam can distinguish between hot and cold objects applied to his
palm and feel an object pressed deep into the palm. Hallam cannot
feel the brush of a feather against his skin, which is the last
sensation he is expected to gain.
</P>
<P>
   In mapping the areas where a patient has feeling, doctors often
insure objectivity by putting eye patches and blindfolds on the
individual. At times, they trick such a patient by saying they are
going to apply a light touch when they stick a pin into a hand.
</P>
<P>
   In Hallam's case, Owen said they did it because ``we do not
believe this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tests show that, as expected, Hallam has no feeling in the area
from the site of attachment in the forearm to the wrist because in
the operation the surgeons could not connect the nerves serving
that area.
</P>
<P>
   Skin biopsies have shown that Hallam's only rejection reaction
occurred about two months after the surgery and was easily
controlled by adjusting the amount of immunosuppressive drugs.
Although a skin biopsy showed no evidence of rejection last week,
such a reaction can occur at any time. ``But even if he rejects it
now, it has been a great success,'' said Dr. Marco Lanzetta, a hand
surgeon on the team from Milan, Italy, who was waiting in Sydney
two weeks ago to examine Hallam at an appointment the patient
canceled at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Owen expressed confidence that with more supervised physical
therapy Hallam could get a good handshake, a stronger pinch between
his fingers and thumb to hold a pen, a stronger grip to drive a car
and more. If Hallam ``carries out good physiotherapy, in three
months he should know what he is feeling with his eyes shut,'' Owen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam says that he attends hourlong physiotherapy sessions
three times a week in Perth but that the Australian program is not
``as tough or punishing'' as the schedule of five to seven times a
week that he followed in France.
</P>
<P>
   Owen said he talked several times a week to a team in Perth
headed by Dr. Tony House, the chief of transplantation at the
University of Western Australia, who supervises Hallam's care. The
team is ``happy with his progress,'' Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam said his expectations were exceeded the day he used his
new hand to write a thank-you note to the doctors in their presence
in Lyons. The writing was ``a little bit childlike, but certainly
very legible,'' Hallam said.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam, who speaks convincingly, said: ``Let me assure you, this
hand will work, and it will have very good function by the first
anniversary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
