<HEADER>
A3864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DUKE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-26 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DUKE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PATTY DUKE SHOW': IDENTICAL COUSINS, FASCINATING AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Be honest. Are you really expecting much from the ``Patty Duke
Show'' reunion movie?
</P>
<P>
   This was a television series best known for its loopy theme song
(``Here's Cathy, who's lived most everywhere, from Zanzibar to
Berkeley Square''), which a remarkable number of American baby
boomers can sing by heart from start to finish and was probably the
first reference most of us heard to the Ballets Russes. The movie
is exactly in tune with the original series, which ran on ABC from
1963 to 1966, and that is not meant as praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patty Duke Show: Still Rockin' in Brooklyn Heights,'' to
be shown Tuesday night on CBS, is now about two identical
52-year-old cousins who are constantly mistaken for each other. The
plot is unlikely: Patty and Cathy's alma mater, Brooklyn Heights
High School, is going to be closed and turned into a shopping mall.
So Patty has to raise $500,000 in a week to save the school by
staging various events. This allows Ms. Duke to speak teen-age
lines like ``The gym! We have to decorate the gym!'' and ``Without
the dance we're sunk.'' Patty works at the school but must not have
heard any new slang in the last three decades. Doesn't she know how
to say, ``How totally not cool is this?''
</P>
<P>
   But the point of television reunion movies, which are nearly
always dreadful, is to see how the old cast looks and to learn what
the writers have decided has happened to the characters over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duke looks harried and worn as Patty Lane but serene and
mature as Cathy. Patty, it seems, married her high school boyfriend
Richard (Eddie Applegate) and divorced him after 27 years, but the
attraction is still there. They have a son who's 33 (which means
Patty had to be secretly pregnant throughout the final season of
the series), and a 14-year-old granddaughter. Cathy, a recent widow
living in her native Scotland, apparently waited longer to start a
family; she has a 14-year-old son, Liam.
</P>
<P>
   William Schallert, who played Patty's newspaperman father, looks
great. Jean Byron, who played Patty's mother, looks pretty good,
too. Everybody else is a little puffy. The only new face is Cindy
Williams, playing Sue Ellen, Patty's high school nemesis, now an
evil real estate broker who wears animal prints.
</P>
<P>
   The flashbacks to the old show are the best part of the two-hour
movie, of course. In the present, viewers are treated to Patty
wearing a strapless evening gown to an arts and crafts fair, Patty
throwing architects' blueprints out a window like a naughty child
and Patty frozen with stage fright in the school production of
``Romeo and Juliet.'' There are pies in the face, a Riverdance
moment and, heaven help us, a Viagra joke.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE PATTY DUKE SHOW'
</P>
<P>
   Still Rockin' in Brooklyn Heights
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Tuesday on CBS
</P>
<P>
   Jim Green and Allen Epstein, executive producers; Mark Bacino,
producer; Christopher Leitch, director; script by Neal Israel.
Produced by Green/Epstein Films in association with MGM Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Patty Duke (Patty/Cathy Lane), William Schallert (Martin
Lane), Jean Byron (Natalie Lane), Eddie Applegate (Richard), Paul
O'Keefe (Ross Lane), Cindy Williams (Sue Ellen) and Kent Riley
(Liam).
</P>
</TEXT>
