<HEADER>
A3866 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSTAND27-COX     04-26 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Struggling to make sense of the nightmare
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as CNN turned to 24-hour-a-day coverage of the killings at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., the massacre also
dominated the newsstand this week, while newsmagazines scrambled to
cover the story and struggled to make sense of the nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   How did smart kids from stable, affluent families turn
themselves into killing machines? This was the big question, and
Time ($3.50) and Newsweek ($3.50) try _ but fail _ to come up with
answers.
</P>
<P>
   What they and others do best, however, is provide chilling
moment-by-moment accounts of the rampage, in the voices of the
students who were trapped under desks and behind barricaded doors.
We hold our breath along with them, stifling a collective scream as
killers prowl the halls.
</P>
<P>
   Time introduces us to ``The Monsters Next Door,'' with
attractive half-page portraits of the violent teens, Dylan Klebold
and Eric Harris. Time visits their homes and interviews friends,
including one who just ``hung out'' with the two boys, and reveals
that, along with the bloody video game Doom, the two enjoyed such
inane kiddie cartoons as ``Pinky and the Brain'' and
``Animaniacs.''
</P>
<P>
   With its cartoonish graphic tracing the movements of the
shooters through the school (red figures stand for dead students,
blue figures are survivors), Newsweek builds a more clarified
timetable of the killings and the SWAT team's response. Newsweek
also tries to answer recurring questions about the agonizingly slow
3 1/2-hour effort to roust the attackers, a delay that allowed
wounded business teacher William David Sanders to bleed to death in
an upstairs classroom, despite the fevered efforts of students to
save his life.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. News &AMP; World Report has more abbreviated coverage of
the disaster, its clumsily written lead paragraph did more than
most to capsulize the frenetic horror of that Tuesday: ``In a whole
lot of ways, this was the worst so far. The death toll, the easily
made bombs, the possible conspiracy, the lunatic rage fueled by a
nihilistic teen culture, the sadism.''
</P>
<P>
   People (2.99) also placed Littleton on its cover, and relied on
first-person accounts from survivors such as 17-year-old Zak
Cartaya, who helped herd students into the office of a choir room,
then barricaded the door with a filing cabinet to protect them from
the shooters.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines try to deepen their reportage with story packages
including sidebars on violent pop culture, the so-called ``Goth''
connection, school safety and other issues that the calamity has
brought to the national round table. The results are uneven.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek delves into brain chemistry in a companion story trying
to explain ``Why the Young Kill'' but fails to prove the premise
established in the headline that ``how these kids are raised can
either save them or push them over the brink.''
</P>
<P>
   A stronger contribution comes from Time essayist Amy Dickinson.
In ``Where Were the Parents?'' Dickinson asks, ``Were the Harrises
aware of the pipe-bomb factory that was in their two-car garage?
The kid down the street was aware of it, and he's 10 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   But Time stumbles in a wrongheaded report on ``A Curse of
Cliques'' when it opines that ``There really is a `Lord of the
Flies' dynamic at work among kids,'' but then fails to distinguish
between schoolyard razzing and quasi-gang warfare.
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to point the finger at video game makers,
longtime media critic John Leo notes in U.S. News and World Report:
``We are now a society in which the chief form of play for millions
of youngsters is making large numbers of people die.''
</P>
<P>
   That little sentence must give even the most serious fan of Doom
and Quake a moment's pause.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More school violence: On Jan. 8, a suicide pact between a
young Carrollton couple came to its deadly conclusion in a girl's
bathroom at Central High School. Teen People ($2.99) tells how
Andrea Garrett, 15, and Jeff Miller, 17, decided that the only way
they could remain together was in death.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Off the path: Time-Warner will disassemble its foundering
Pathfinder Internet site, which served as the online entryway to
its many magazines (including Time, People, Sports Illustrated and
Forbes) and set up separate ``vertical hubs'' for its various
publications.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
