<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3867 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTYDUKE-Q&AMP;A27-COX     04-26 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTYDUKE-Q&AMP;A27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patty Duke reunites her identical cousins
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   `` 'Cuz they're cousins, identical cousins . I . I .''
</P>
<P>
   And now they're back. Everyone's back, in fact, in tonight's
two-hour reunion movie, ``The Patty Duke Show: Still Rockin' in
Brooklyn Heights.'' From Jean Byron and William Schallert as Mom
and beloved ``Poppo,'' to Eddie Applegate and Paul O'Keefe as,
respectively, Patty's hapless boyfriend, Richard, and her
incorrigible little brother, Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Duke reprises her dual role as look-alikes Patty Lane (the
all-American impish one) and her cousin Cathy (the refined Scottish
lass) from the show, which aired from 1963 to 1966 on ABC. It's
doubtful that many people knew then about Duke's hellish home life
with her managers, a domineering married couple who convinced
Duke's unstable mother to let her live with them. In her 1986
autobiography, ``Call Me Anna,'' she wrote about how they changed
her name, refused to let her watch herself on TV and introduced her
to booze and pills. Duke, 52 and a grandmother, recently spoke
about reuniting with her beloved TV family and confronting her
past.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whose idea was it to make this movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: Remember that nostalgia craze about 10 years ago? I was asked
every other Thursday would I do this. And every other Friday I said
no. There were life issues for me that I had all ``mushed''
to-gether with the show. I was still working on ``Was it the fault
of the show that my life was horrible at the time? Or was it my
horrible life?'' I finally determined that not only was it not the
show and the people, but they were my safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Besides the fun of seeing everyone again, did any good come
out of this experience?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Oddly, not as much for me as for Jean and Bill. For all
these years, they carried some sense of responsibility that they
didn't ``save'' me from the situation (with her managers). So one
very long evening, we sat around the dinner table in a restaurant
(and) really thrashed it out. I said, Jean, if you had said to me,
``Honey, is something wrong at home?'' I would've given you 15
minutes on how wonderful it is. Never, ever, did I feel that (Jean
and Bill) had let me down. In fact, those hours that I spent with
them were the only relief I got. And, I witnessed _ even though
they weren't really married to each other and they weren't really
parents _ I witnessed a healthy relationship between a man and a
woman. It was a very emotional conversation. Both of them cried. I
cried.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a sense, you even reunited with yourself, since you played
two characters. What was that like?
</P>
<P>
   A: I only liked playing Cathy as a kid. Patty was stupid and
ridiculous. I had to put up with it so I could get to Cathy, who
was rational, kind, quiet and respected. Well, this time I fell
into Patty quite fast, and I couldn't find Cathy for love or money.
I said to Jean and Bill, ``Help me. How does she talk?'' And both
of them almost simultaneously said, ``Honey, she, too, is 35 years
older. She doesn't sound the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: With technological advances, was it easier now playing two
people in the same scene?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it used to take me only 15 minutes to change from one
character to the other. Now it takes 2 1/2 hours. But you could see
(the result) immediately. I was, for one of the few times in my
life speechless, to see me hug me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the enduring love people have for the show?
</P>
<P>
   A: One thing I feel very strongly about is that theme song. The
other thing was, back then there weren't a whole lot of other
teenage people on television. So it was a place for my compatriots
to go, and for parents it was a weapon. One of my favorite things I
hear is, `My mother wouldn't let me watch it until after I did my
homework.'
</P>
<P>
   Q: Logically, should Patty and Cathy have been twins instead of
identical cousins?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But how would you have had the whole culture clash thing
then?
</P>
<P>
   A: One of them would've had to be evil!
</P>
<P>
   x-mates that I'm very friendly with.
</P>
<P>
   TV PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patty Duke Show: Still Rockin' in Brooklyn Heights''
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
