<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ In a rare sign of dissent within
Yugoslavia's leadership Monday, Yugoslav Deputy Premier Vuk
Draskovic, appearing on local television Sunday, called on state
leaders to stop lying to the people of Serbia. He said the people
should be told that world opinion is against them _ an apparent
reference to state propaganda boosting anti-NATO feelings.
Draskovic, considered a moderate and once the main opposition
leader, said Yugoslavia should accept a U.N. force in Kosovo and
allow the return of ethnic Albanian refugees. His comments, along
with the three U.U. POW's being seen by the Red Cross and alleged
visit the Rev. Jesse Jackson and other clerics, may provide a new
opening for a diplomatic way to end the bombing _ now in its 34th
day. Developments. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ Ethnic Albanian refugees
continued to flow out of the embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo,
and the U.N. refugee agency said Monday there were credible reports
that Kosovar Albanian women and children were being held as human
shields by Serbian soldiers at an ammunition depot in Kosovo.
Developing. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA-0427 _ DURRES, Albania _ Feature about KLA soldiers _
young, poorly trained and armed Kosovo Albanians _ who are flooding
back to fight in the hills from their jobs in Germany and
elsewhere. Whether we like it or not, these KLA fighters will be
our allies in any ground operation and the beneficiaries of any
NATO victory. (Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WOLFE-BULGARIA _ Richard Wolfe of Palm Beach, Fla., and
Portland, Maine, knows firsthand of the place where America is
``dropping books, not bombs.'' Wolfe is on the board of directors
of the American University in Bulgaria, where Serbs and Kosovars
study side by side. Among the memories he and wife Rosemarie
brought back from their last trip to Bulgaria is a stray dog they
rescued and named Miss America. (Gelormine, Palm Beach Daily News),
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ The two students who killed 13
people at Columbine High School wanted to kill at least 500
classmates and teachers, attack neighborhood homes and then hijack
a plane and crash it into New York City, investigators said. They
also said today they planned to question an 18-year-old girl about
whether she purchased any firearms used in the rampage. Three more
students and the slain teacher are buried today. (MWilliams,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/ALIENATION _ The murdered children are only the most obvious
tragedies when kids open fire on their classmates. Squinting
through the horrific gunsmoke, experts on the feelings of children
can also see teenage alienation, loneliness and depression in
frightening numbers. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) 35.
</P>
<P>
   TEENVIEWS _ The Columbine shootings highlighted how foreign high
school culture - with its own peculiar rules, standards and codes
of conduct - can to parents, teachers and counselors. We transcribe
interviews with a handful of metro Atlanta teens who reflect, in
their own words, on everything from alienation, violence, media
influences, the ``in'' crowd and achievement. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
