<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-JONESBORO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JONESBORO, FROM AN EARLIER SHOOTING, THE ECHOES HAVE YET TO DIE
AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (mb)  
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ark. _ When Gretchen Woodard heard about the two
gun-toting boys in Colorado who murdered classmates and a teacher
in another gruesome school shooting, some of her reactions echoed
those of everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   She thought, ``Where were these boys' parents? How could they
not have known these kids were building bombs in their garage? Why
didn't they pay attention to the trench coats and other warning
signs of trouble?''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Woodard had to stop short of taking comfort in the next
thought on most people's minds, ``My child would never do anything
like that.'' Because, in fact, Ms. Woodard's child did, just last
year, here in Jonesboro.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Mitchell Johnson, then 13, was the older of the two
friends who murdered four classmates and a teacher in the Jonesboro
school massacre on March 24, 1998. In the year and a month since
that day, she has had to stop short a lot, learning to monitor
herself at every turn, trying not to say, do or even think anything
that might cause anyone any more pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has made me very humble,'' Ms. Woodard, 43, said on Monday,
from the living room of her tidy, modest home at the end of a
country road, about a mile from Westside Middle School where her
son did the shooting. As Ms. Woodard talked, her 3-year-old
daughter played with a lady bug. ``I am the last person to sit in
judgment of other people. But it is human nature to have questions
and point your finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Her younger son, Monte, 12, has also had to learn to compensate
for living in his brother's shadow. When Monte, a sixth grader,
walks down the halls at Westside Middle School, where pictures of
the shooting victims adorn the walls, he carries all his books and
supplies in his arms, in full view. Early on after the shooting,
Monte decided not to carry a backpack, because he thought it would
scare the other students every time he reached inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first Monte was angry at his brother for doing something so
stupid, so senseless,'' Ms. Woodard said. ``He cried and I just
held him and he kept asking why. I couldn't begin to explain. I was
too overwhelmed with the horror of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry, a youth minister at Central Baptist Church in
Jonesboro, where Monte attends a youth group meeting every
Wednesday night, has seen Ms. Woodard and her sons through some of
that horror. Many times in the past year, Perry has counseled
Mitchell Johnson in jail. ``That family feels a whole buffet of
emotions,'' he said. ``Fear of retaliation. Social shame. A
struggle to maintain their own dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodard said she does not try to defend or explain her son's
behavior. ``For so long afterward I blamed myself,'' she said.
``You question everything _ your sense of right and wrong, even
your TV. And all of a sudden, your whole life, whether it be good
or bad, is put under a microscope and everybody is saying, `Well,
you watched that television show two months ago, and it's because
you played a video game, it's because your son listens to rap
music.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Who amongst us can hold up for very long under that pressure?
That is something I know those parents in Littleton will have to
deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodard has heard people blame her son's participation in
the shooting on her divorce from his father after a 15-year
marriage. Soon afterward, she remarried. She has been faulted for
teaching her son to shoot a rifle so he could go hunting, just as
she did when she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the sexual abuse of her son and his brother by a
neighborhood teen-ager when they lived in Minnesota, which she
learned about only when her ex-husband revealed it to Barbara
Walters on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too easy to point your finger and blame the family,''
Perry, the youth minister, said. ``Is Gretchen a good parent? Yes.
Is she flawless? No. Is she evil? No. Does she care for and love
her kids? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, both Monte and his mother have been buoyed and a
little surprised by the kindness of the Westside students and
teachers. ``I mean, I wouldn't have been surprised if people had
wanted to spit on me or yell at me,'' Ms. Woodard said. ``But that
hasn't ever happened. It has been our blessing that this community
has let us go on.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of school this fall, 12-year-old Candace
Porter, 12, who survived a bullet that ballistics tests proved came
from the gun of Monte's brother, sat down next to Monte in the
cafeteria, hugged him, and told him she would always be his friend.
</P>
<P>
   Another person wounded in the shooting, Lynette Thetford, is
Monte's social studies teacher. ``I really thought at first, `Why
doesn't his mother take him away from here?''' she said. ``Now I
know why she didn't. He fits in well with the kids here and they
accept him. And he seems to be handling it well. He is a strong
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Monte is learning to play the trumpet and Ms. Woodard is vice
president of the band boosters at Westside. On his last report
card, Monte got all A's. And for a citywide Saturday honors program
for which each school in the Jonesboro area can sponsor one pupil,
Westside picked Monte.
</P>
<P>
   Still, each good thing feels bittersweet. Whenever Ms. Woodard
referred to the day of the shooting, her normally warm and open
face froze into a stunned, pained look and she whispered, ``March
24th of '98.
</P>
<P>
   As she talked, Ms. Woodard struggled to hold back tears. Her
daughter, Jessie seemed used to that. She put down the French fries
she was eating, hopped onto her mother's lap, gave her a huge hug,
took her mother's face in her hands and said, ``Please mama, don't
be sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodard is careful to point out that even her daughter's
love reminds her that the families of her son's victims cannot hold
their children that way. ``No amount of `I'm sorry's' can make up
for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynette Thetford, the teacher who was shot, said she felt for
Ms. Woodard. ``There is no closure for her, and not many people to
comfort her,'' she said. ``I truly believe I would rather have my
child die than do something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Ms. Woodard and Monte have learned to do, Ms.
Thetford stopped herself short, and then tempered her words: ``Of
course, if I had lost my child, I might feel a different way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
