<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-ORLEANS-JAZZ-ART-     04-26 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ORLEANS-JAZZ-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ORLEANS JAZZ FESTIVAL STRUTS INTO ITS 30TH YEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ In a tradition that is older than jazz, a parade
was on the march on Sunday afternoon. Members of the Revolution
Social Aid and Pleasure Club swaggered in fluorescent-green suits,
carrying big feather crests emblazoned with peace signs, crowns and
the letter R. Joining them were the Untouchables, strutting in
purple and gold. The beat came from the New Birth Brass Band,
huffed out of a battered sousaphone and tapped on cymbals with wire
loops bent from coat hangers. As in any New Orleans parade there
was also a second line: spectators and stragglers who turned into
dancers as the music grabbed them.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a funeral or a neighborhood party on the march. It
was just the 4 p.m. parade, one of 14 processions that wound their
way through the New Orleans Fair Grounds during the first weekend
of the 30th annual New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival, which
continues through May 2. Jazzfest, as it is widely known, now
attracts half a million people every year, making it a New Orleans
institution second only to Mardi Gras. After three decades Jazzfest
has become inseparable from the culture it presents.
</P>
<P>
   Jazzfest's producer and director, Quint Davis, has a distinct
artistic paradigm; he calls the festival ``the world's largest
backyard barbecue.'' While musicians perform on a dozen stages,
hand-picked food vendors offer muffulettas and oyster po' boys,
crawfish etouffe and alligator sausage, gumbo and jambalaya and
pralines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have a food festival that was equal to the music
festival, it wouldn't be an authentic New Orleans experience,''
Davis said. ``When you're having the best music and having
something down in your soul, you're supposed to have something in
your gut that matches.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a festival built on time-tested music with Louisiana roots:
jazz from traditional improvisation to modern modalities, zydeco
and Cajun songs, gospel, blues, rhythm-and-blues and rock. And in
Louisiana, home to the most joyously provincial musical culture in
the United States, holding on to those styles is not the kind of
archival preservation that seals off the past from the present. It
is a matter of continuity because the old styles are still heard in
clubs and on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   When Fats Domino, Sunday's headliner, sang ``Blueberry Hill,''
the audience started waving handkerchiefs and napkins like Mardi
Gras marchers. In New Orleans brass bands play for jazz funerals,
people two-step to zydeco accordion tunes, and young musicians play
jazz styles from 80 years ago because they love them and because
that's where the jobs are.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians who performed over the weekend said that unlike Mardi
Gras, which puts revelry before culture, Jazzfest brings music
lovers to town. To provide an immersion in New Orleans and
Louisiana music the festival mixes a handful of nationally known
performers _ this year's lineup includes Willie Nelson, Ray Charles
and Cassandra Wilson _ with neighborhood parade groups and
musicians who are usually heard in clubs, streets and churches.
</P>
<P>
   One stage at the festival is a gospel tent, where galvanizing
groups like the Crown Seekers or Spencer Taylor and the Highway
QC's make musical converts all day long. Doreen Ketchens, a
34-year-old clarinetist who played traditional jazz with pearly
tone and ebullient, curlicued solos on Friday afternoon, generally
performs outdoors in Jackson Square. ``Unless it rains,'' she said,
``or the police run us off.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year New Orleans has generated bigger hits than it
has in decades, in the form of Top 10 hip-hop albums from Master P
and his stable of gangsta rappers on No Limit Records. Jazzfest
tried last year to book Master P and his fellow rappers but was
turned down, Davis said; No Limit concentrates on studio
productions, not concerts.
</P>
<P>
   While Jazzfest has presented Mystikal, a No Limit rapper, in the
past, the festival isn't dependent on current hits. ``There are a
number of musics in the big commercial mainstream that we don't
have,'' Davis said, citing heavy metal. ``We don't book something
just because it comes from Louisiana.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most popular-music productions, Jazzfest does not depend
on current hits or revolve around youth. Warren Storm, a drummer
and singer in the swamp-pop alliance Lil' Band o' Gold, drew a roar
of approval when he announced he would sing his hit, ``Prisoner's
Song,'' which grazed the charts back in 1958. But neither is
Jazzfest an oldies festival; the first weekend included younger
performers, like the bluesman Corey Harris and the zydeco band
leader Geno Delafose, for whom down-home traditions are current.
</P>
<P>
   There were also bands whose music was, like a Kurt Vonnegut
hero, unstuck in time. The Dirty Dozen Brass Band went
somersaulting through musical eras when it performed on Friday
afternoon, with tunes that mutated from swinging two-beats to
wrangling modern-jazz dissonances to calypso to funk, taking roots
and connections for granted. La Bottine Souriante, from Montreal,
took a parallel approach to traditional Quebecois music, with
intricately madcap arrangements that called for trombones,
saxophone, jazzy keyboard harmonies and even salsa rhythms behind
its Celtic fiddles and accordions.
</P>
<P>
   Jazzfest started small but ambitious in 1970. The New Orleans
city fathers first approached George Wein, the producer of the
Newport Jazz Festival and the Newport Folk Festival, in the early
'60s. But at the time New Orleans' Jim Crow laws prohibited black
and white musicians from sharing a stage and did not allow
integrated audiences indoors. Wein could not accept such
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   After the federal Civil Rights Act was enacted in 1964, he was
asked again, but it was not until 1970 that Wein finally took on
the job; he is the festival's executive producer. (This year, he
was also a performer, playing limber swing piano on Friday with an
all-star jazz band that included Ken Peplowski on clarinet and Lew
Tabackin on tenor saxophone.)
</P>
<P>
   His inspiration was to pattern the festival not on the Newport
Jazz Festival with its concerts for seated audiences, but on the
multiple informal events of Newport Folk Festival. The first
Woodstock rock festival had taken place in 1969; Wein believed that
the young audience he hoped to attract did not want reserved seats.
And he insisted from the start that the festival needed local food
and local performers like brass bands and Mardi Gras Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can hire some artists for concerts,'' Wein recalled
telling the city. ``But if you want to do the fair, that's where
the future is.''
</P>
<P>
   The first New Orleans Jazz Festival and Louisiana Heritage Fair,
its ungainly original title, had more employees than audience. But
Wein persevered, and by the mid-'70s the festival was breaking
even. Its earnings, about $1 million in 1998, are administered by
the nonprofit New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made them realize what their own culture was and how much it
meant to the rest of the world,'' Wein said. ``It wasn't that we
revived anything or saved anything. We just made more people aware
of it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jazzfest has been a model for other festivals, notably the
Festival International de Louisiane, a free festival that took over
downtown Lafayette, La., a center of Acadian (or Cajun) Louisiana,
last week. The Festival International is dedicated to
French-speaking Creole culture, and 80 percent of its performers
speak French or Creole. It shared some of them _ including La
Bottine Souriante; the Acadian band Beausoleil; the accordionist
Regis Gizavo, from Madagascar, and the singer and songwriter
Angelique Kidjo, from Benin _ with Jazzfest, since both were
celebrating the 300th anniversary of the French presence in
Louisiana. At the festival in Lafayette audiences had room to
dance; on Saturday some were two-stepping not only to the steaming
zydeco of Chris Ardoin's Double Clutchin' but to the African rock
of Amadou and Mariam, from Mali.
</P>
<P>
   Bookings at the New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival can take
performers from local clubs to the international circuit.
``Promoters come from Europe and go to our festival and hire groups
as they come off the stage,'' Wein said. Eddie Bo, an exuberant
rhythm-and-blues belter and florid barrelhouse pianist who had a
modest hit in 1962 with ``Check Mr. Popeye,'' has a regular gig
playing happy hours at Tipitina's in New Orleans, but he also tours
Europe with his band.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz and Heritage Foundation supports a public radio
station, WWOZ, that plays jazz and other New Orleans music full
time, putting the local culture on the air. The station broadcasts
on the Internet (www.wwoz.org), and it has members from as far away
as China, allowing the Party line to meet the second line. The
foundation also supports the Heritage School of Music where
children learn to play New Orleans jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The festival has decisively changed the annual calendar for New
Orleans' Mardi Gras Indians, the carnival marching societies that
create towering costumes of feathers and beads each year and who
used to dispose of them on Ash Wednesday, the day after Mardi Gras.
Now tribes like the Wild Magnolias and the White Eagles keep their
costumes to parade at Jazzfest. In between they have also started
their own ``super Sundays,'' gatherings of the tribes in March and
April. The tribes, like the brass bands, are hardly an endangered
tradition; Davis said he kept finding out about new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here heritage is not just something you see in the rearview
mirror,'' Davis said. ``It's also shining brightly through the
windshield.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
