<HEADER>
A3883 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHWEST-CHANGE-TEX     04-26 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHWEST-CHANGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH SPURS CHANGE AT SOUTHWEST, INCLUDING A WASHINGTON LOBBYING
OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Herb Kelleher can hardly be described as
conventional.
</P>
<P>
   When the flamboyant chairman and chief executive officer of
Southwest Airlines was lobbying against an aviation tax in 1997, he
dropped to his knees and begged Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., not to
support it.
</P>
<P>
   The episode soon became part of the folklore surrounding the
Harley-riding, chain-smoking, Elvis-impersonating, practical-joke
loving aviation chief.
</P>
<P>
   But in buttoned-down Washington, the free-wheeling ways of the
Dallas-based low-cost carrier have not always sat well with the
rest of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   So, it was with some satisfaction that Washington insiders
watched last year as Southwest bowed to convention and opened a
lobbying office. Just recently, the ``outsider'' company took
another bow to convention and started a political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest has gone corporate. Or has it?
</P>
<P>
   ``We set up a Washington office because we grew from three
cities to 53 cities and from one state to 28 states,'' said Ron
Ricks, Southwest's vice president of governmental affairs. ``With
our growth, we had more issues.''
</P>
<P>
   And that has meant paying more attention to politicians. A
three-person Washington office has been up and running _ with Ricks
calling the shots from Dallas _ as has an Austin office, also set
up last year, to handle state and legislative issues.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the corporate circle was complete with creation of a
PAC.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kelleher and other officers of the company had made
contributions on their own, this is the first time the company has
created a political action committee. By contrast, Fort Worth-based
American Airlines has had a PAC since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``A PAC is supposed to protect the interests of shareholders,''
Ricks said. ``Our growth finally got to the point it was
inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest Airlines' Freedom Fund reported $84,234 in
available cash early this year, according to the Federal Election
Commission, a healthy start for a new PAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're no longer a small, little, insignificant airline,''
said Ed Faberman, executive director of the Air Carrier
Association, which represents small airlines, but not Southwest.
``Candidly, I could never understand how they could not have an
office in Washington.'' The reason was largely Kelleher himself,
whose larger-than-life presence made him a popular and successful
lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest's low fares average $78 each way, and the carrier's
irreverent ways _ pilots have been known to invite passengers to
clean the restrooms _ make it a lightning rod for attention.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing like a threat to those low fares to get
Southwest's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher's fight against an aviation tax in 1997 certainly
forced his attention to Washington where he maintained that a tax
proposal gaining momentum was structured against his carrier
because it was based on flight segments. Southwest flies segments
and does not operate hubs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the industry ended up with a tax that included levies
on tickets and segments, Southwest redirected its energy to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Southwest is focused on stopping a proposal in a
House aviation bill that would double the so-called passenger
facility charge from $3 to $6.
</P>
<P>
   But will Southwest's lobbyists begin wearing wingtips?
</P>
<P>
   No, laughed Ricks, and they still plan to carry bags of peanuts
around with them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
