<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-VACCINE-COX     04-26 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-VACCINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New vaccine shows promise against virus like AIDS
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An Emory University researcher has created a vaccine
that appears to substantially protect monkeys against a virus
similar to the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   A three-year study by Dr. Harriet Robinson that involved 32
rhesus macaque monkeys indicates the vaccine prevents most monkeys
from becoming sick after being repeatedly exposed to a ``challenge
virus,'' a blend of HIV and SIV called SHIV. HIV does not reproduce
or cause illness in monkeys, but SIV does.
</P>
<P>
   The study is promising news for HIV vaccine research, which has
lagged behind efforts to discover and develop new AIDS drugs. A
working AIDS vaccine is still years away, vaccine experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet, but it's an important step,'' said
Robinson, chief of microbiology and immunology at Yerkes Regional
Primate Research Center at Emory University. Robinson performed the
study, to be published in May's issue of Nature Medicine, while at
the University of Massachusetts Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson tested several versions of the vaccine, the most
successful of which uses a series of shots. First, an inoculation
consisting of SHIV genes ``primes'' the animal's immune system,
helping it mount an initial defense against the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent ``booster'' immunizations that use the same genes
inserted into a pox virus, administered at 46 and 66 weeks, help
maintain the immune response.
</P>
<P>
   This version of the vaccine was given to four out of the 32
macaques in the study; the other monkeys received different
versions of the vaccine, which were not as effective.
</P>
<P>
   Those four monkeys were later exposed to SHIV three times: twice
with a strain identical to the type used to make the vaccine, and a
third time with a different, much more virulent strain. Several
different strains of HIV exist, so a vaccine that is effective
against more than one strain would be most useful.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four macaques showed no detectable virus after the
first two exposures. The fourth monkey had extremely low levels of
the virus.
</P>
<P>
   After the third exposure, two of the remaining three monkeys
stayed healthy; the third became sick.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the study, all 32 monkeys were euthanized.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS vaccine advocates expressed enthusiasm for Robinson's
findings, but stressed the need to quickly develop a product
applicable to humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly an advance,'' said Wayne Koff, vice
president for science of the International AIDS Vaccine Initiative.
``The AIDS vaccine field should look at this candidate in a serious
way, in trying to move it into clinical trials as fast as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Avrett of the AIDS Vaccine Advocacy Coalition agreed,
saying, ``The evidence is very tantalizing, and it's a very good
example of why we need faster research and more applied product
development in clinical trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson plans further vaccine testing in macaques at Yerkes.
Human trials are at least a year away, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one potential AIDS vaccine has progressed to large-scale
human testing. The AIDSVAX vaccine, developed by VaxGen, a company
based near San Francisco, is being tested in 5,000 people in North
America and another 2,500 in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
