<HEADER>
A3898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH27-COX     04-26 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth in strong position, officials say
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A week after announcing a $3.5 billion deal with Qwest
Communications, BellSouth officials assured shareholders Monday
that the company is well-positioned to take on rivals.
</P>
<P>
   F. Duane Ackerman, chairman and chief executive of the $23
billion-a-year BellSouth, reminded those attending the 15th annual
shareholders meeting that the Atlanta-based company produced an 80
percent return to shareholders last year. Company stock last year
jumped from about $28 to nearly $50 a share. BellSouth closed
Monday at $43.56 1/4 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more importantly, the numbers show the firm is preparing
for the future by being ``transformed from a traditional utility to
a top-flight, consistent-growth company,'' Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   That change has taken BellSouth from having one of the least
efficient payrolls among similar firms to one having the most
revenue per employee _ $261. For years, reaching that meant
dramatic cuts in the work force, mostly in the phone unit, although
BellSouth in 1998 began expanding again.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the lost jobs had been positions represented by the
Communications Workers of America. CWA official Noah Savant
reminded shareholders and directors Monday of workers'
contributions to BellSouth success, asking that company prosperity
be used in part to further reward retirees.
</P>
<P>
   During 1998, BellSouth earnings per share rose 16.3 percent,
capping five years in which BellSouth enjoyed a 12 percent compound
annual rate of growth. The company has predicted earnings growth of
19 percent to 21 percent during this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because brand awareness is critical, the company has in recent
years doubled its budget for advertising, tagging a number of
sports teams with BellSouth sponsorship, Ackerman said. ``We're
investing in advertising wherever we operate.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth expects data to become central to all operations. Last
year, BellSouth revenue from data services jumped 42 percent to
$1.9 billion, and BellSouth expects data revenue to surge to about
$5 billion within three years.
</P>
<P>
   Buying 10 percent of Qwest, which is both a long-distance and a
high-speed data carrier, is key, Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   While the bulk of BellSouth's revenue comes from the nine
Southeast states where it offers local service, the company
continued to extend that core phone business. Of 3.6 million
customers, about 75 percent come from businesses in which BellSouth
has competition. For example, the company's U.S. wireless business
has grown to 4.8 million and its Internet business is expected to
hit 1 million subscribers this year. Investments overseas,
especially Latin America, also continued to grow in importance.
</P>
<P>
   In other business, shareholders re-elected a slate of directors
and rejected proposals to trim incentives paid to top executives.
Ackerman last year was paid a $900,000 salary and a $2 million
bonus. BellSouth officials say executive compensation is average
for companies of similar size.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
