<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENVIEWS-COX     04-26 1696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta teens speak out about life in their world
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Diane Lore and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For adults, understanding teenagers can be like a
visit to their high school: It's recognizable from the outside but
a strange new territory on the inside. Some of the familiar
benchmarks are still there _ the cliques and the classes _ but
teens say it's impossible to understand their world unless you're a
part of it _ or at least listen closely. We talked with metro
Atlanta teens about their lives. Their commentary paints a
compelling portrait of teen fears, hopes and insights in the wake
of the Columbine High School massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Vallorie Chappel, 16
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Smyrna, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: Robert Osborne Senior High School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Junior
</P>
<P>
   People can be so mean, especially when you're younger and you're
the odd kid out.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe those (Colorado) kids were teased for a long, long time
because they were different. And then over the years, they became
different because they didn't know what else to do, they didn't
know how else to turn.
</P>
<P>
   I was teased for years for being a chubby kid; I would end up
crying every day to my mom. That's probably why, in part, I became
a Christian. I know I have a relationship with someone who will
always accept me, no matter what color my hair is.
</P>
<P>
   Why do I dress this way? Well, because I like the music, I like
punk music, and this is part of it. The two are interwoven, it's
part of the style. Some would say this is my way of getting
attention, but it's not. It's a way of fitting in with the group of
friends I have. When we are together, we look the same. For me to
dress preppy would look odd.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, people stare at me when I'm in a mall, at Rich's or the
grocery store, but when I'm with my friends, I fit right in. People
don't understand that. They start saying that you must be this way
or that way if you dress like this. They think you're a bad person,
you're a troublemaker, you do drugs. And that's not necessarily
true.
</P>
<P>
   At my school, there's been kids who have worn trench coats for
years, and in the past week they've been searched _ with the only
reason being that some kids in another state killed people and
happened to be wearing the same things. Now, that's not right.
</P>
<P>
   I'm lucky because I've always been very close to my mom, who
went through some of the same things in high school. And I became a
born-again Christian when I was 9, so I don't feel alone.
</P>
<P>
   What leads to things like the shooting is people don't realize
how much kids are hurting. They don't see how much they need help.
They may look different, but everyone needs to be accepted by
someone.
</P>
<P>
   Tani Gaan, 18
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Peachtree City, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: McIntosh High School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Senior
</P>
<P>
   My dad got me into the whole athletic thing.
</P>
<P>
   I was living with him and he was a single parent for a while and
I think this is one way we bonded. He was my first coach. We
started out with basketball, and then I branched out from there. My
main sport is basketball, but I also do cross country, track and
golf. He told me to remember three things about sports: Have fun,
work as a team and learn about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's definitely the athletic crowd. But we're just one
of a bunch of groups in school. There's the Christian group, the
smart kid group, the group who are the skaters _ that includes
white people who try to act black. There's the outcast group _
where even the guys wear black eyeliner _ and the extreme outcast
group. There's about 10 to 15 people in that category and they
don't interact with anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   I think the biggest change in high school is women in sports.
You can't have a pure ``jock'' group because too many girls are
playing on teams. And I think there's a difference in attitude. And
for me, I've always seen sports as my ticket to college. So I don't
see it merely as a way to spend my social time. Sports also helps
me stay focused and develop more discipline. I don't have the
chance to take other roads like kids with more time, I don't have
the time to be introduced to other things like drinking or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, jock types sometimes do pick on smaller kids, but usually
not at this level. When I was younger, I saw a lot more of it. But
I think by high school, most of us are more mature and we've moved
on. I don't see kids at my school worried about it.
</P>
<P>
   David Issa, 18
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Dunwoody, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: Dunwoody High School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Junior
</P>
<P>
   I spent a year as a foreign exchange student in Japan. And life
in Japan, especially high school life, is so much more innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the biggest problem they had was kids not wearing their
uniforms right. It was like a different planet. Parents let their
children play outside and didn't worry about them at all. They just
weren't very street-smart _ and they didn't need to be.
</P>
<P>
   Here (in America), we have a public school life that includes
fights, drug searches, security guards. In Japan, it was a very
homogeneous structure. Everyone belonged and adhered to the same
social structure, and here that's just not the case.
</P>
<P>
   We have diversity, which I think is a good thing, but it makes
getting along more complicated. I've never really paid attention to
how little I noticed diversity until this interview.
</P>
<P>
   I was born in Washington, D.C., lived in Geneva, Switzerland,
when I was 2 and moved to Atlanta when I was 8. I've always
interacted with different kinds of people.
</P>
<P>
   I think people tease (other people) because they're not
comfortable with differences _ and because they're still searching
for their own identity. I see the worst teasing in junior high
school, where kids are suddenly exposed to the real world.
</P>
<P>
   You're thrown out there and everything is so big and you feel so
small. The bullies don't want to feel small, so they attack others.
But by high school, I think that eases, because people gain a
better sense of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Adana Onyejekwe, 18
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: Marietta High School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Senior
</P>
<P>
   To make it through high school, you have to remember why you're
there. You're not there for a social life, you're there for an
education.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of pressure. Right now, I'm taking
advanced-placement statistics, advanced-placement French,
international baccalaureate English and international baccalaureate
history. And I've often been the only black kid in the class,
although it's not that hard because most of the kids _ the girls _
I've known since elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   I think another key to coping with high school is you also need
to find a group of people who are like you and find a mentor. But a
lot of kids still fall through the cracks. There are so many who
started with me but won't finish with me. It hurts me, and I worry
about them. But they did have the exact same opportunity as I did,
and for some reason they have thrown it away.
</P>
<P>
   I still see so many students with nothing in their hands. No
bags, no books, no papers. Just a pencil stuck behind their ear. I
keep thinking, if you're going to come to school like that, why
come?
</P>
<P>
   But I'm lucky because of my mom and my Nigerian background.
She's been a single parent since I was in the eighth grade, and we
are very close. I'm very independent, but I still keep her posted.
And although I was born here, my mother raised me with a Nigerian
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   The discipline is much higher, things are a lot stricter. But I
think it's helped me succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Dorfman,17
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: Paideia School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Junior
</P>
<P>
   Numerous television reports have produced psychologists and
others who claim factors such as violent video games and
influential films caused the gunmen to act as they did. The two
films that have been commented on the most are ``The Basketball
Diaries'' and ``The Matrix.'' They seem to closely resemble what
happened in Colorado. Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Basketball Diaries,'' the main character is shown
shooting students with a shotgun in a dream sequence. ``The
Matrix'' contains similar violence, but the movie is based on a
very fictional, alternate reality.
</P>
<P>
   Most teens I know regard these movies with the attitude ``that
looks so cool'' or even ``it would be so awesome if we could
actually do that.'' Most people don't tag on the end, ``Let's go
try that.''
</P>
<P>
   People may seem to be influenced by movies nowadays more than
ever. It's probably because many films cater to more diverse and
sometimes controversial groups. There is a movie out there for
everyone now.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has at least one character they can relate to. Will
Hunting in ``Good Will Hunting'' can inspire us to live up to our
highest potential. William Wallace from ``Braveheart'' can inspire
us to have more courage. Even a character like Kenny Fischer from
``Can't Hardly Wait'' can inspire us to be ourselves and maybe
learn something about love.
</P>
<P>
   These movies all have extreme in-your-face styles. ``Good Will
Hunting'' had its excessive, questionable language. ``Braveheart''
had its extremely violent war scenes and ``Can't Hardly Wait'' had
its very raw yet comical look at a teenage graduation party.
</P>
<P>
   They all had material that could possibly inspire inappropriate
behavior. The truth is, no matter how long people search for an
answer, we will never know. The only people that know the motives
were the actual shooters.
</P>
<P>
   And while psychologists and other experts search for a reason,
they give inspirational and entertaining films a bad name.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I see a report on what movie the shooters might have
watched or what video games they played, I get so furious that I
feel like reaching into the television and slugging them in the
stomach for their naive and desperate analysis. But perhaps that's
the result of me watching the film ``Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore and Bob Longino write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENVIEWS-COX     04-26 1696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta teens speak out about life in their world
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Diane Lore and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For adults, understanding teenagers can be like a
visit to their high school: It's recognizable from the outside but
a strange new territory on the inside. Some of the familiar
benchmarks are still there _ the cliques and the classes _ but
teens say it's impossible to understand their world unless you're a
part of it _ or at least listen closely. We talked with metro
Atlanta teens about their lives. Their commentary paints a
compelling portrait of teen fears, hopes and insights in the wake
of the Columbine High School massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Vallorie Chappel, 16
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Smyrna, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: Robert Osborne Senior High School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Junior
</P>
<P>
   People can be so mean, especially when you're younger and you're
the odd kid out.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe those (Colorado) kids were teased for a long, long time
because they were different. And then over the years, they became
different because they didn't know what else to do, they didn't
know how else to turn.
</P>
<P>
   I was teased for years for being a chubby kid; I would end up
crying every day to my mom. That's probably why, in part, I became
a Christian. I know I have a relationship with someone who will
always accept me, no matter what color my hair is.
</P>
<P>
   Why do I dress this way? Well, because I like the music, I like
punk music, and this is part of it. The two are interwoven, it's
part of the style. Some would say this is my way of getting
attention, but it's not. It's a way of fitting in with the group of
friends I have. When we are together, we look the same. For me to
dress preppy would look odd.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, people stare at me when I'm in a mall, at Rich's or the
grocery store, but when I'm with my friends, I fit right in. People
don't understand that. They start saying that you must be this way
or that way if you dress like this. They think you're a bad person,
you're a troublemaker, you do drugs. And that's not necessarily
true.
</P>
<P>
   At my school, there's been kids who have worn trench coats for
years, and in the past week they've been searched _ with the only
reason being that some kids in another state killed people and
happened to be wearing the same things. Now, that's not right.
</P>
<P>
   I'm lucky because I've always been very close to my mom, who
went through some of the same things in high school. And I became a
born-again Christian when I was 9, so I don't feel alone.
</P>
<P>
   What leads to things like the shooting is people don't realize
how much kids are hurting. They don't see how much they need help.
They may look different, but everyone needs to be accepted by
someone.
</P>
<P>
   Tani Gaan, 18
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Peachtree City, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: McIntosh High School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Senior
</P>
<P>
   My dad got me into the whole athletic thing.
</P>
<P>
   I was living with him and he was a single parent for a while and
I think this is one way we bonded. He was my first coach. We
started out with basketball, and then I branched out from there. My
main sport is basketball, but I also do cross country, track and
golf. He told me to remember three things about sports: Have fun,
work as a team and learn about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's definitely the athletic crowd. But we're just one
of a bunch of groups in school. There's the Christian group, the
smart kid group, the group who are the skaters _ that includes
white people who try to act black. There's the outcast group _
where even the guys wear black eyeliner _ and the extreme outcast
group. There's about 10 to 15 people in that category and they
don't interact with anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   I think the biggest change in high school is women in sports.
You can't have a pure ``jock'' group because too many girls are
playing on teams. And I think there's a difference in attitude. And
for me, I've always seen sports as my ticket to college. So I don't
see it merely as a way to spend my social time. Sports also helps
me stay focused and develop more discipline. I don't have the
chance to take other roads like kids with more time, I don't have
the time to be introduced to other things like drinking or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, jock types sometimes do pick on smaller kids, but usually
not at this level. When I was younger, I saw a lot more of it. But
I think by high school, most of us are more mature and we've moved
on. I don't see kids at my school worried about it.
</P>
<P>
   David Issa, 18
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Dunwoody, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: Dunwoody High School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Junior
</P>
<P>
   I spent a year as a foreign exchange student in Japan. And life
in Japan, especially high school life, is so much more innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the biggest problem they had was kids not wearing their
uniforms right. It was like a different planet. Parents let their
children play outside and didn't worry about them at all. They just
weren't very street-smart _ and they didn't need to be.
</P>
<P>
   Here (in America), we have a public school life that includes
fights, drug searches, security guards. In Japan, it was a very
homogeneous structure. Everyone belonged and adhered to the same
social structure, and here that's just not the case.
</P>
<P>
   We have diversity, which I think is a good thing, but it makes
getting along more complicated. I've never really paid attention to
how little I noticed diversity until this interview.
</P>
<P>
   I was born in Washington, D.C., lived in Geneva, Switzerland,
when I was 2 and moved to Atlanta when I was 8. I've always
interacted with different kinds of people.
</P>
<P>
   I think people tease (other people) because they're not
comfortable with differences _ and because they're still searching
for their own identity. I see the worst teasing in junior high
school, where kids are suddenly exposed to the real world.
</P>
<P>
   You're thrown out there and everything is so big and you feel so
small. The bullies don't want to feel small, so they attack others.
But by high school, I think that eases, because people gain a
better sense of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Adana Onyejekwe, 18
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: Marietta High School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Senior
</P>
<P>
   To make it through high school, you have to remember why you're
there. You're not there for a social life, you're there for an
education.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of pressure. Right now, I'm taking
advanced-placement statistics, advanced-placement French,
international baccalaureate English and international baccalaureate
history. And I've often been the only black kid in the class,
although it's not that hard because most of the kids _ the girls _
I've known since elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   I think another key to coping with high school is you also need
to find a group of people who are like you and find a mentor. But a
lot of kids still fall through the cracks. There are so many who
started with me but won't finish with me. It hurts me, and I worry
about them. But they did have the exact same opportunity as I did,
and for some reason they have thrown it away.
</P>
<P>
   I still see so many students with nothing in their hands. No
bags, no books, no papers. Just a pencil stuck behind their ear. I
keep thinking, if you're going to come to school like that, why
come?
</P>
<P>
   But I'm lucky because of my mom and my Nigerian background.
She's been a single parent since I was in the eighth grade, and we
are very close. I'm very independent, but I still keep her posted.
And although I was born here, my mother raised me with a Nigerian
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   The discipline is much higher, things are a lot stricter. But I
think it's helped me succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Dorfman,17
</P>
<P>
   HOME: Norcross, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH SCHOOL: Paideia School
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: Junior
</P>
<P>
   Numerous television reports have produced psychologists and
others who claim factors such as violent video games and
influential films caused the gunmen to act as they did. The two
films that have been commented on the most are ``The Basketball
Diaries'' and ``The Matrix.'' They seem to closely resemble what
happened in Colorado. Or do they?
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Basketball Diaries,'' the main character is shown
shooting students with a shotgun in a dream sequence. ``The
Matrix'' contains similar violence, but the movie is based on a
very fictional, alternate reality.
</P>
<P>
   Most teens I know regard these movies with the attitude ``that
looks so cool'' or even ``it would be so awesome if we could
actually do that.'' Most people don't tag on the end, ``Let's go
try that.''
</P>
<P>
   People may seem to be influenced by movies nowadays more than
ever. It's probably because many films cater to more diverse and
sometimes controversial groups. There is a movie out there for
everyone now.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has at least one character they can relate to. Will
Hunting in ``Good Will Hunting'' can inspire us to live up to our
highest potential. William Wallace from ``Braveheart'' can inspire
us to have more courage. Even a character like Kenny Fischer from
``Can't Hardly Wait'' can inspire us to be ourselves and maybe
learn something about love.
</P>
<P>
   These movies all have extreme in-your-face styles. ``Good Will
Hunting'' had its excessive, questionable language. ``Braveheart''
had its extremely violent war scenes and ``Can't Hardly Wait'' had
its very raw yet comical look at a teenage graduation party.
</P>
<P>
   They all had material that could possibly inspire inappropriate
behavior. The truth is, no matter how long people search for an
answer, we will never know. The only people that know the motives
were the actual shooters.
</P>
<P>
   And while psychologists and other experts search for a reason,
they give inspirational and entertaining films a bad name.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I see a report on what movie the shooters might have
watched or what video games they played, I get so furious that I
feel like reaching into the television and slugging them in the
stomach for their naive and desperate analysis. But perhaps that's
the result of me watching the film ``Rocky.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore and Bob Longino write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
