A3913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0427-COX     04-26 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0427-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OUTMANNED, OUTGUNNED KOSOVAR ALBANIAN GUERRILLA FIGHTERS FIGHT
ON
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0427.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURRES, Albania _ The part of his scalp where the Kosovar
guerrilla fighter who calls himself ``The Wolf'' was hit by a Serb
rifle bullet while fighting in Yugoslavia embattled Kosovo province
just 16 days ago is not fully healed.
</P>
<P>
   But he is about to catch a bus back toward this country's
northern border. From there, The Wolf and his unit of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, or KLA, are likely to walk across the border into
Kosovo to resume his personal war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not afraid at all,'' said The Wolf, who is 29 and asked
that his real name not be used. ``Whatever happens, it is foreseen
by the gods. If you are going to die, you are going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking like a skinhead in his aviator glasses, The Wolf was
hanging around in his fatigues under a pink tile roof at the Cafe
Drenica. It is the seaside hangout that is the KLA's main transit
station for busing out fresh recruits and the recovering wounded
who are headed for the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   Like nearly every guerrilla movement of this century, the KLA is
made up of cold-blooded fanatics who don't much mind dying. They
are split among factions espousing extreme anti-communism and
others that believe in a variant of Marxist-Leninism.
</P>
<P>
   What's different about this bunch of guerrillas is that thanks
to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's intransigence, the
fighters of the KLA have become America's fanatics in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, this secretive, relentless band of anti-Serb
guerrillas is poised to inherit the fruits of any victory the
U.S.-led NATO forces can wrest from Milosevic. Yet the outside
world knows very little about their ideological leanings, their
sources of funding or their leadership.
</P>
<P>
   There could not be a sharper contrast between the passionate
dedication of men like The Wolf and the laconic professionalism of
the American troops who have flown in to fight in an uncomfortable,
unstated alliance with the KLA guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to do a mission, and then we are all going home,
every one of us,'' says U.S. Army Sgt. Jeffrey Landry, 34, of
Lincoln, Neb. He is the crew chief of a high-tech Avenger
anti-aircraft battery.
</P>
<P>
   Victory doesn't mean the same thing for fighters like The Wolf.
For him, Kosovo is home. He means to live long enough to get
married by this coming September in the liberated Kosovo capital of
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   His problem is he doesn't know whether his fiancee has been
killed in a month of Serb ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   From 1987 to 1999, The Wolf lived in Germany and earned good
money at an automobile factory. He heeded a KLA summons on March 1
for young Kosovar Albanians to join the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded for three days by Serb forces on April 10, the fresh
recruit had gone into battle with only 10 days training. Like a lot
of the KLA frontline troops, he was obeying a worldwide KLA call
for fighting volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   He and his 13 fellow volunteers were sent into Kosovo, just
north of the Albanian district of Tropoje. They were without
helmets or flak jackets.
</P>
<P>
   They were supposed to protect a column of Kosovar refugees on
tractors. Instead, The Wolf and his KLA unit was surrounded by Serb
police and soldiers after they had been in action just four days.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the 14 KLA guerrillas were killed, most by Serb
rocket-propelled grenades. The Wolf and two others were wounded. It
was a battle the outside world never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   When The Wolf is asked why he wants to go back to war, he talks
of patriotism and of reclaiming the land from the Serbs. ``Maybe
I'm crazy, I don't know,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Binac, 20, a fresh recruit who arrived at the Cafe Drenica on
Sunday from Germany, is even more gung-ho. ``I am ready to die for
the future of Kosovo,'' he says. ``Am I afraid? No, not even a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Binac says that a NATO ground invasion would be superfluous.
``We can liberate Kosovo ourselves,'' he says. ``Of course we will
need mortars, grenade launchers and anti-tank grenades.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Albanian Army's Military Hospital in Tirana, there are
rooms full of wounded amateur soldiers like The Wolf who say they
cannot wait to get back into battle.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
