<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO RULES OUT USE OF FORCE IN EMBARGO, SAYS MILITARY OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of NATO's Military Committee said
Monday that the alliance will not use force in the Adriatic Sea to
choke off oil supplies headed to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Even though NATO leaders agreed Saturday at a summit here to use
warships in enforcing an oil embargo, German Gen. Klaus Naumann,
who heads the alliance's military advisory group, said sailors on
the ships will not be allowed to fire warning shots at freighters
or forcibly board them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A visitation-and-search regime does not give us the right to
force anyone to abandon his course; so we cannot stop a merchant
vessel by the use of force,'' Naumann told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   His comment left unclear just how the fuel embargo, announced by
the European Union and then by NATO, will be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea declined to discuss how the alliance
will respond if a freighter does not agree to be searched.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't yet have the initial concept of operations from the
military authorities,'' Shea said, adding that the alliance's top
military commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, is scheduled to
brief NATO leaders in Brussels Tuesday on the proposed naval
operation.
</P>
<P>
   NATO planners, said Shea, ``are not seeing this (embargo) as a
panacea, which in itself is going to reduce or eliminate all oil
deliveries.'' The alliance also is stepping up the aerial bombing
of roadways to prevent Yugoslav oil trucks from resupplying
military units, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting off Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's outside oil
supplies is a key strategy in NATO's month-long air war. Aerial
attacks have shut down Yugoslavia's two oil refineries and
destroyed about 70 percent of its reserves, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann said that the ships ``visiting the (Montenegro) port of
Bar are to some extent European Union ships. So I think we will see
a certain impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend NATO leaders debated what to do about ships
from Russia, Yugoslavia's main oil supplier, and other ``third
nations'' that might seek to make shipments to Yugoslav ports.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann predicted that even without the threat of force, the
embargo will have a deterrent effect on oil shipments. Freighters
bearing oil ``will be very, very cautious'' about approaching
Yugoslav ports with NATO ships prowling the waters, he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   NATO planners opted against authorizing warships to use force
after concluding that the alliance lacks the legal authority _ a
mandate from the United Nations Security Council _ to do so,
Naumann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As things stand, we have no choice, and we have no chance to
get a United Nations embargo,'' he added, referring to expected
vetoes by Russia and China if the Security Council were to take up
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   F. Stephen Larrabee, a senior military analyst with the Rand
Corp. think tank here, said that if NATO is not allowed to use
force to stop oil shipments, the embargo will have no teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of blockade is it if you can't force any vessels to
stop?'' Larrabee asked.
</P>
<P>
   The countries honoring the embargo include the NATO nations:
Belgium, Canada, the Czech Republic, Denmark, France, Germany,
Greece, Hungary, Iceland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Norway, Poland, Portugal, Spain, Turkey, the United Kingdom and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Also honoring the embargo are Austria, Finland, Ireland and
Sweden, which are European Union members along with 11 NATO
countries: Belgium, Denmark, France, Germany, Greece, Italy,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal, Spain and the United
Kingdom.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NATO has been careful not to use the term ``blockade'' in
describing the emerging naval operation. Instead, officials say
they will ``visit and search'' commercial ships bound for Yugoslav
ports to ensure there are no oil shipments.
</P>
<P>
   W. Bruce Weinrod, former deputy assistant secretary of defense
for European and NATO policy, said that for legitimacy under
international law, a naval blockade typically requires a formal
declaration of war, something the NATO nations have declined to do
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Also, international law may not recognize a naval blockade
erected by NATO unless it is sanctioned by the United Nations,
Weinrod added.
</P>
<P>
   Using force to enforce the embargo has been a sticking point
with some NATO leaders. French President Jacques Chirac stressed at
the NATO summit that while his country supports an embargo,
forcibly boarding a ship challenges a nation's sovereignty and is
an act of war.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Russia
would ignore any NATO decision to impose an oil embargo against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
