<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN-COX     04-26 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Saturation frenzy feeds emotion, not facts
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Images of violence and terror gobbled up
television this past Tuesday, as the carnage of another school
shooting took center stage and stayed there all week.
</P>
<P>
   As the siege at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.,
unfolded, TV cameras were everywhere. The unblinking eye showed us
time and time again the frantic efforts of a wounded boy trying to
escape through a second-story window, the tearful faces of
survivors, the hysterical parents awaiting news of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Hours and hours of live coverage were followed by days and days
of follow-up. As awful and newsworthy as the shootings in Littleton
were, many of us (perhaps with a bit of guilt) wondered if the
coverage didn't hit the saturation point by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   What did we learn from a two-hour ``town hall'' edition of
``Nightline'' on Thursday night? What was gained from having
residents of Jonesboro, Ark., the site of a previous school
shooting, join the still-shocked residents of Littleton in an
electronically connected group therapy session? I found myself
alternately bored and appalled by my boredom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to ask ourselves, does this have any value beyond
emotional impact, and very often it doesn't,'' said Dan Amundson,
research director for the Center for Media and Public Affairs in
Washington, D.C. ``TV news should be in the news business, not
trying to put on good drama. Our main purpose should be
information. . . .I think the media needs to put a lot more filters
between what they're getting and what they're showing.''
</P>
<P>
   When television airs live, raw footage of breaking news, viewers
get an emotional rush but not much more. Reporters thrown on the
air live often are unable to offer context or long-term
perspective. The result can be senseless speculation and,
unintentionally, danger.
</P>
<P>
   Two Denver stations were criticized for airing live footage of
the SWAT team's movements while students were still trapped inside
the school. If the shooters had been watching TV, they would have
seen the escape routes that were being prepared. The stations also
were criticized for airing a whispered cell phone call from a
student begging for help. Both CNN and MSNBC picked up the footage
and aired it while the situation was unstable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready for someone to start a network called `Where Really
Bad Things Can Happen Live,' `` said Linda Ellerbee, a former
network news reporter who now produces programs for ``Nick News.''
``I don't think they had to go on and stay on so long live. We're
just not at our best live. A lot of it is irresponsible and
erroneous. In one sense, what TV does best is convey the
experience, but I think we're at a place now where we have to start
relying on common sense in individual situations. The public's
right to know is not always in the best interest of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we were better off before the technology allowed TV to go
live instantly and stay live indefinitely. When news stories had to
be reported and packaged for the evening news, we didn't have to
worry about killers watching and ``eyewitnesses'' giving bad
information.
</P>
<P>
   With time to fill in the aftermath of live coverage, mistakes
and bad judgment can be compounded. In reality, police
investigations are slow and dull. Television needs things to move
faster, so news people assemble parallel cases, bringing in their
own witnesses and experts. But the result is little more than
emotional displays and speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much we learn from interviewing the 14th
student and parent,'' Amundson said. ``There's a point where you
say, let's put together a more traditional news story and
synthesize the experience. I'm not sure all these one-on-one
interviews advance our knowledge so much as keep a raw wound
open.''
</P>
<P>
   All of us are concerned about our children and the violent world
they live in. We wonder about the impact of television, movies,
music and video games, and we ask lots of questions. Did the two
boys in Colorado base their murderous plan on a video game, a
Marilyn Manson song . . . or TV's coverage of a previous school
rampage?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no easy answers in any of this,'' Ellerbee said.
``There are lots of good questions. I don't think the fact that we
covered the other events where children were shot is what caused
the kids in Littleton to do this, but I'm not sure it's not some
part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of an interrogation of the shooters, we'll never
know why they did what they did. Nor will we know if the TV
coverage will inspire copycatters.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these shootings have had their own unique psychological
dramas,'' Amundson said. ``Yes, similar types of people seem to be
doing similar things, but that doesn't mean they're doing it for
the same reason. They can be aware of other instances but not
necessarily copying them.''
</P>
<P>
   What do supposedly normal kids get from watching real-life
mayhem on TV?
</P>
<P>
   We know from surveys that children have a heightened sense of
paranoia and fear from watching crime coverage on TV. They are
usually far more fearful than they need to be. We can assume that
the events in Littleton will have a similar effect.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean TV shouldn't cover such shootings? No, but it
does mean we should think about what we see, ask thoughtful
questions and remember that not everything on TV news is necessary,
accurate or helpful.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Diane Holloway at dhollowaystatesman.com or
445-3608.
</P>
<P>
   PBS serves up another meaty chat Tuesday at 10 p.m. with ``Bill
Moyers in Conversation with Archbishop Desmond Tutu'' . . .
Christine Baranski, an Emmy winner for ``Cybill,'' guest stars as a
hostile radio shrink on ''Frasier,'' Thursday at 8 p.m. on NBC . .
. A barrel of fun for kids of all ages, Nickelodeon hosts the 12th
annual ''Kids' Choice Awards'' at 7 p.m. Saturday . . . And if you
don't mind a little levity and creative license in your Bible
stories, take a gander at Part One of the first big May miniseries,
''Noah's Ark,'' at 8 p.m. Sunday on NBC. TUNE OUT: Omigosh! Some
old, dead shows should stay dead and buried, but CBS has
resurrected a couple of tired stars in a weary reunion movie. To
avoid depression, stay away from ''The Patty Duke Show: Still
Rockin' in Brooklyn Heights,'' Tuesday at 8 p.m. . . . And if you
don't want to hurl, don't watch Fox's``Guinness World Records,''
which features a worm-eating contest Friday at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway is the TV critic for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
