<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECRUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta leaders look to Glasco
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: TEXAS EDITORS.)
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta Chamber leaders hope that Darrell Glasco
can show the resourcefulness here that he did in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president for economic development at the Greater Austin
Chamber, Glasco didn't just aim for big companies. He looked for
companies with promising products that could grow in Austin. That's
why he went after Trilogy Software Inc. five years ago, then a
five-person software company in Palo Alto, Calif. Enticed by the
area's quality of life, inexpensive housing and the University of
Texas, the company moved to Austin, and now has 1,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the best companies are the smallest ones,'' said
Glasco. ``You can't just look at size. You have to look at
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Glasco will become a vice president and the
number-two economic development executive at the Metro Atlanta
Chamber.
</P>
<P>
   State and metro economic development officials have said they
want to recruit high-tech companies by growing the number of
technology workers in the area. They hope to do that by increasing
the number of university students majoring in high-tech fields and
by bringing in experienced technology workers from other parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Glasco established a reputation in Austin for recruitment
innovation. For example, two years ago he organized a job fair in
Boston to recruit technology workers for companies in Austin. Over
the next month, Austin will unveil a national marketing campaign
aimed at technology workers and an Internet site listing available
technology jobs in the Austin area.
</P>
<P>
   Glasco's own decision to move to Atlanta came after he received
a phone call from former mayor Andy Young. ``The fact that they
would have someone like that call me meant a lot to me,'' Glasco
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his initial evaluation of metro Atlanta, Glasco says he
doesn't know enough about the area yet to comment on its
weaknesses. For strengths, he lists Hartsfield International
Airport, the community's energy level and local leadership's focus
on technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have the leadership to back the effort it doesn't
happen,'' he said. `` It's not from anything other than the
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kempner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
