Jeanette Chang, Bazaar's publisher, of Tilberis's cancer fight.
``It has been a miracle for six years. She was always going to pull
through and be here.'' Tilberis used her high-profile position to
bring attention to the cause of ovarian cancer. As president of the
Ovarian Cancer Research Fund, she convinced retailers to host
events in their stores and manufacturers to donate proceeds of
special products to the organization. Just this week, Sebastian
announced it would give 100 percent of the profits of a new Berry
Bazaar Trucco Divinyls lipstick to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Tilberis published a memoir, ``No Time to Die: Living
With Ovarian Cancer.'' In it, she wrote: ``I never wanted to be a
cancer spokesperson. But cancer has become an immutable part of my
persona. I don't run from it. I study, anticipate and confront
it.'' But Tilberis never let the illness get in the way of her job.
Colleagues at Bazaar said she remained involved with the
publication until the last days of her life. ``The last
conversation I had with her about five or six days ago,'' said
creative director Fabien Baron, ``she said, `Wait for me at the
magazine.' She loved her husband, kids and the magazine. She loved
the job. She was asking me all about the June issue and I was
telling her how great it was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Liz could have had meetings on the June issue as late as
last Thursday,'' said Cathleen Black, president of Hearst
Magazines. ``She's directing traffic and pushing and cajoling. She
loved this magazine so much that throughout all this amazing battle
she made light of it most of the time.'' Black said Tilberis' love
of fashion, art, architecture and literature, celebrities, artists
and musicians was reflected in Bazaar. ``Those were the kinds of
things she tried to infuse the magazine with to make it more than
just a fashion magazine,'' Black said. ``It took people places. It
was a statement; it was aspirational, yet it was approachable.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bazaar's future issues, Chang said: ``Thankfully, Liz has
a lot of senior captains: Karen Johnston, managing editor], Tonne
Goodman, fashion director and Annemarie Iverson, beauty and fashion
news director. Photographer Patrick Demarchelier has been here for
years. All the stories have been going on while she's been ill.
It's not as though anything is coming to a halt by any means. The
next four issues were planned with her blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis seems to have been one of those rare, unusually focused
people who identify their life's calling at an early age. Fashion
has always been her passion. Tilberis was born in Shirehampton,
England in 1947. She won a fashion essay writing contest _ one of
her topics was on costume historian James Laver, of whom she wrote,
``It was from him that I learned that hemlines are tied to the
wider world.'' The prize: a summer internship at British Vogue in
1969. At the same time, she edited a weekly fashion page in a local
newspaper, the Bath &AMP; Wiltshire Evening Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Leicester Polytechnic in 1970, Tilberis
joined the British Vogue staff as a fashion assistant. She was
promoted to fashion editor four years later, and in 1984 became
executive fashion editor, rising to editor of the entire magazine
in 1987. Tilberis' big coup at British Vogue came in 1990, when she
snagged the Princess of Wales for the December 1991 cover. Two
years later, she was on her way to New York to become editor of
Harper's Bazaar, which at the time was celebrating its 125th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis was known to joke about the change in her life when she
moved to New York from London. In her homeland she was a chic
matron, favoring size 14 suits and a simple bob for her straight
gray hair. After a short time in New York, she began to adopt
sophisticated, minimalist looks from the likes of Calvin Klein and
Gucci. ``I even have my own publicist now,'' she once said
self-deprecatingly in a speech in London, adding she would never
have dreamed of such self-promotion when she was editor of British
Vogue. But longtime colleagues stressed that Tilberis never lost
sight of what was most important in her life _ her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing is when she went to America she didn't stop
being a Mum,'' said Anna Cryer, who was Tilberis' executive
assistant when she was editor of British Vogue and moved with her
to Harper's Bazaar. ``She always remained grounded. She'd have
lunch with Karl Lagerfeld, tea with Donna Karan and still go home
at 6 p.m. to make dinner for her kids. It was a huge gap between
those two worlds but she bridged it because being a parent was so
important to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis always made people want to be part of her gang, Cryer
said. ``Someone once said to me that Liz was so nice she could call
you into her office, fire you and you'd walk out thanking her for
it,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Tilberis arrived, Harper's Bazaar was in need of a
makeover. She and Baron conceived of a magazine that was elegant
yet playful, with floating, overlapping graphics the likes of which
had not been seen in a contemporary fashion publication. ``We were
very nervous, but we knew Bazaar was a beautiful magazine,'' Baron
said. ``We called it `Sleeping Beauty.' '' Tilberis said she had
always wanted to produce a cutting-edge magazine. ``I suppose
creativity is pushing the envelope forward in a very constructive
way,'' she told WWD in an interview last October. ``All my life,
I've loved creativity in people. I like the idea that a magazine
offers creativity to readers, particularly in the styles. When we
launched with Fabien's graphics, it kept Harper's Bazaar on the
cutting edge,'' she said. `
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis had an affinity for American fashion. In the October
interview, she said, ``American designers invented sportswear. They
introduced pants and sweaters for women.'' Klein said when he saw
Tilberis' first issue of Harper's Bazaar, he thought, ``How great.
It takes a Brit to make a great American fashion magazine. She
understood what was American more than most American editors.''
</P>
<P>
   While the publication has not always been universally well
received, it did shake up the industry when it launched and set the
stage for a legendary _ at least as it was played up by the press _
rivalry between Tilberis and her British Vogue mentor, Anna
Wintour. In 1987, Wintour was named editor of HG, formerly House
and Garden, and Tilberis became her successor at British Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Liz was a very formidable competitor,'' Wintour said
on Wednesday. ``I think she had an incredibly strong fashion
esthetic and put out a very elegant magazine. When we were working
together at British Vogue, she always struck me as being an
amazingly strong person with an incredible love of fashion. A
fashion editor par excellence. ``She was passionate about her
sittings and her work,'' Wintour continued.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis's talent was evident to many others. Both Ralph Lauren
and Klein said they tried to hire Tilberis away from British Vogue
when she was a fashion editor. ``When she was at British Vogue,
about two or three years before she came to America, I had hired
her and she was all packed,'' Lauren said. ``She was going to work
with me as an assistant in design. It was all set. But British
Vogue didn't want her to leave, and gave her a promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually even tried to bring her into my organization,''
Klein said. ``She was clearly a great talent and we all knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Lauder, chairman and ceo of Estee Lauder Cos., said:
``Liz Tilberis was a woman of enormous grace, charm and courage.
Any normal person, when faced with this serious illness, would have
retired or just gone home to lick their wounds. Not Liz. She fought
not only for her own life but for the lives of countless others. We
owe her a great deal of debt of gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Many industry veterans were too distraught to discuss Tilberis
over the phone. Karl Lagerfeld, in a fax, wrote, ``I am so sad
about the death of dear Liz Tilberis that I can hardly talk. She
was such a marvelous friend _ so optimistic, so like sunshine and
so courageous. She was so special and human in our tough fashion
world. Nice with everybody, but strong. That's a very rare gift.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a very courageous woman,'' said Giorgio Armani.
``She lived and worked up until the end, as if she were never
affected by the terrible pain. I saw her last in January. We talked
about work, but most of all, we talked about life. She never
betrayed any signs of pain on her beautiful face or in her
intelligent words.''
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, people spoke of Tilberis' kindness and ability to
transcend the cutthroat fashion industry. ``She was a real lady in
the truest sense of the word,'' said Emanuel Ungaro. ``Liz gave a
sense of welcome to new people. She was not just following the
megastars of fashion. She was trying to understand the young
designers. For me, her curiosity was her greatest contribution.
``She was never judging you,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost more than a great editor,'' said Valentino. ``We lost
a special friend. She was a real woman. Real as fashion rarely is.
She was courageous and very sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her bravery was unbelievable,'' said Oscar de la Renta. ``She
was always so gracious and at the same time created great awareness
for the terrible thing that cancer is. She was able to raise a
tremendous amount of money using her own suffering. She never first
thought about herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis in 1994 received a special award from the Council of
Fashion Designers of America, which was presented by the Princess
of Wales. The CFDA said Wednesday it will present Tilberis,
posthumously, with its humanitarian award at its June 2 gala.
Tilberis was notified of the award March 24, and Fern Mallis, CFDA
executive director, said ``We're really so happy that she knew
about it. She was moved to tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis is survived by her husband, Andrew; two sons,
Christopher and Robert; her mother, Jane Kelly; a sister, Lois
Stuart-Black and a brother, Dr. Grant Kelly. A spokeswoman for
Hearst said funeral services will be private. A memorial service is
planned.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sharon Edelson is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
