<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-700&AMP;AD     04-26 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA MAKES WAY FOR THIRD ELECTION IN THREE YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ After the collapse of the government led by
Hindu nationalists and the failure of opposition parties to put
together a majority, President K.R. Narayanan dissolved the lower
house of Parliament Monday night to make way for India's third
general election in three years.
</P>
<P>
   The election has not yet been scheduled, but it must take place
within six months. The chief election commissioner, M.S. Gill,
strongly suggested that it would not be possible to hold the
election before late July, when a national drive to update the
voting rolls is finished. Monsoon rains that peak in July and
August may cause further delay.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it is months away, the Herculean task of organizing
an election in a democracy with a staggering 600 million voters
will begin immediately. Election officials must see to it that
800,000 polling stations staffed by 4.5 million workers are ready
to go.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-page memorandum released to reporters, Narayanan laid
out his painstaking efforts to consult leaders in Parliament since
the government led by Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee lost a
confidence vote on April 17 by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president could not but observe that the ruling alliance
had lost its majority because of a lack of cohesion within its
ranks, and those who voted out the alliance showed the same lack of
cohesion when trying to form an alternative government,'' the memo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the two main national parties, the Bharatiya Janata
Party and the Congress Party, met feverishly to plot strategy. The
Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party now has about a third of
the votes in Parliament, while Congress has about a fourth. Both
hope that they can turn this debacle into an opportunity to
increase their strength.
</P>
<P>
   But political experts said the failure to form a new government
was an unmitigated loss for the woman who pulled the thread that
unraveled the old one: Jayalalitha Jayaram, a former actress who
leads a party in Tamil Nadu and who reduced the government to a
minority when she withdrew her support. Jayalalitha, who is known
by her first name, is desperate to avoid conviction on numerous
corruption charges, but now she has no guarantee of a friendly
government in New Delhi anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The jockeying for political advantage was well under way Monday,
with both sides portraying themselves as victims of betrayal. The
Congress Party, whose leader, Sonia Gandhi, acknowledged on Sunday
that she had failed to form a government, turned its ire on Mulayam
Singh Yadav, the leader of a party in Uttar Pradesh, whose refusal
to support a Congress government doomed it to failure _ and whose
Muslim supporters Congress covets for itself.
</P>
<P>
   One Congress leader, Arjun Singh, condemned Yadav as a spoiler
who had blocked the effort to get rid of a Hindu nationalist-led
government that Congress has portrayed as anti-Muslim and
anti-Christian.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress attack on Yadav appeared to be part of a concerted
strategy to improve its long-sagging fortunes in Uttar Pradesh,
India's most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, which
led the coalition government, described itself as the casualty of a
cynical power grab by the Congress Party. Congress, which governed
the nation for most of the last half century, is led by Sonia
Gandhi, the Italian-born inheritor of the Nehru-Gandhi political
mantle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an anger in the people of this country for dislodging
Vajpayee for no reason,'' said Pramod Mahajan, a spokesman for the
ousted government, which is now serving as a caretaker. ``And we
are very sure this anger wil be ventilated at the ballot boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to catch a wave of sympathy from voters angry about more
political instability, Bharatiya Janata Party officials pressed for
quick elections in June, but it appears unlikely that they will get
their wish.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the party's optimism, some political experts say the
odds are stacked against the Bharatiya Janata Party. While
incumbency is regarded as an advantage in many countries, it is
more often a curse in India.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the last quarter century, only one national government has
been returned to power, and that was controlled by the Congress
Party under Rajiv Gandhi in 1984. He was elected in a landslide
after his mother, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalists were trounced by Congress in state
elections in November when prices of staple vegetables soared.
Prices have since come down, and Vajpayee had been governing with a
more confident hand, but very public squabbling in the government
coalition may well have undermined his reputation for effective
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be quite extraordinary if they came back to power,''
James Manor, a political scientist at the University of Sussex in
England, said of the Hindu nationalists. ``They think they're
different from all these other parties. But every BJP state
government has been thrown out of office except once in Rajasthan
in '93. They don't have any special magic that gets them
re-elected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
