A3960 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEEPINGVIRGIN-TEX     04-26 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEEPINGVIRGIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE VIRGIN LIVES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TEXAS-MONKS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLANCO, Texas _ The ``Weeping Virgin'' icon is kept in a special
chapel on the grounds of Christ of the Hills monastery.
</P>
<P>
   At the door to the chapel, and again inside before the icon,
Father Pangratios performs several elaborate genuflections. Many
converts to Orthodoxy from Roman Catholicism or the Episcopal
Church cite their admiration for the ``bells and smells,'' the
elaborate ceremony associated with all Orthodox religious
practices. Pangratios is even happy to repeat the bows, kneelings
and icon-kissings when a photographer admits his roll of film ran
out at a crucial moment. The exercise seems to tire the monk; he
pants noticeably when he finishes for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin weeps real tears of myrrh,'' Pangratios says,
opening the glass casing. ``She doesn't weep at specific times.
Sometimes she weeps for an extended period. She's not weeping now,
but she did earlier. If you lean in at just the right angle, you
can see faint traces of oil on the icon's surface. And, of course,
you can smell the myrrh.''
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen cotton balls are jammed into the bottom of the
icon's frame. These, Pangratios says, will be left until they
absorb miraculous tears. Then they will be reverently wrapped in
aluminum foil and given to any true believers who request one. The
scent of myrrh is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Most visitors have come to see the icon, but their tour often
includes several other places of interest on the monastery grounds.
</P>
<P>
   There's a separate sanctuary where daily services are conducted
(visitors are asked to remove their shoes to spare unnecessary wear
on a very torn and faded rug); a graveyard bristling with high,
elaborate crosses marking the final resting places of Russian
Orthodox members who ``requested the honor of burial here''; crude
classrooms for religious instruction of the novices; a series of
tiny hillside structures serving as individual cells for
established monks; a gleaming 2-story dormitory for novice monks; a
small solar power station; a deserted workshop where, Pangratios
says, the monks make their various spices for sale (it, too, smells
strongly of myrrh); and a small structure whose sign announces
``St. Anna's Cafe'' and offers ``Espresso-Food-Snacks-Juice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of our visitors requested snacks that we went ahead
and put this in,'' Pangratios says. ``We monks ourselves eat much
plainer food. Vegetables, mostly. Fish on certain holy days. And we
fast during other holy periods.''
</P>
<P>
   The monastery gift shop would rival any at Disneyland. Its walls
display a variety of souvenirs. Some _ candles, pins _ cost only a
few dollars, but other elaborate hand-painted boxes and carved
statuettes cost as much as $475. There are books and icons and jars
of honey and pens and Mother Seraphima, who comes in on crutches
and beams when asked to pose for a picture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Guinn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
