<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3961 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACESUITS-GIRLS-ART-     04-26 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACESUITS-GIRLS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE COMES THE SUN: SPACESUITS ALLOW GIRLS TO PLAY OUTSIDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif., Mich. and Va.) 
(Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By RUTH RENDON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Erica Lemus picked wildflowers and ran through the
lawn Monday, while Amanda Clanton sat in a wheelchair, her moving
head conveying her delight in seeing sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Erica, 6, and Amanda, 9, suffer from a rare skin disorder called
xeroderma pigmentosum.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the first day they were able to sit or play in the
sun without the risk of getting skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   They were presented specially designed NASA suits, which will
allow them to abandon the days of having to stay indoors with the
shades drawn or travel in a car with a blanket or towel draped over
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very excited and nervous,'' said Amanda's mother, Angie
Calloway, 31, a teacher's aide from nearby Crosby. ``We're finally
going to be able to take her to places that I've longed to do. I
want to take her to the park. I'd like to be able to take her to
SeaWorld one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda, who had not been in the sun since she was 11 months old,
clapped as about 20 family members at NASA's Rocket Park surrounded
her. The girl, who suffers from numerous neurological problems
associated with the skin disorder, will be able to go outside for
recess Tuesday for the first time at Barrett Primary School, where
her mother is a teacher's aide.
</P>
<P>
   Erica, whose family moved to Houston from Honduras two years
ago, is planning to attend Chambers Elementary School in the Alief
school district next month.
</P>
<P>
   Diagnosed after she came to this country, Erica, unlike Amanda,
does not suffer from any neurological problems and has been taught
at home by a homebound teacher, Carole Harrel.
</P>
<P>
   Harrel said Erica was dying when her mother, Tomasa Silva,
sneaked across the border to bring Erica to Houston for medical
attention. The girl's father, Regoberto Lemus, stayed behind to
sell their possessions before joining them.
</P>
<P>
   The family is now going through steps to become legal U.S.
citizens. Erica's father, a 33-year-old air-conditioner repairman,
ran outside with his daughter after she put on her special suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants to go outside and play with other children,'' he
said, ``and she wants to go to the beach in Galveston.''
</P>
<P>
   They watched during the ceremony as Erica, their only child, was
fitted with her light blue cotton and Lycra-blend suit.
</P>
<P>
   The suits are made of machine-washable fabric that contains a
chemical that blocks ultraviolet light, said Robert L. Dotts. He is
assistant director of NASA's Technology Transfer and
Commercialization Office, which designed the suits.
</P>
<P>
   The suits will protect the girls from 99.9 percent of UV rays,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The office worked with Solar Protective Factory in California to
develop the fabric and the Microclimate Systems Inc. in Michigan to
provide the cooling systems for the suits, Dotts said.
</P>
<P>
   The suits, which include pants and a loose-fitting, long-sleeve
top, socks and gloves, are worn over regular clothes. Also included
are a neckband and hooded cap with built-in dark, tinted goggles.
Over the suits, the girls wore a white cooling vest equipped with
four gel packs,
</P>
<P>
   which last for two to three hours. The vests can be recharged in
a refrigerator in 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After the girls received the suits during a presentation at
Space Center Houston, they put them on and boarded a tram for a
short visit to Rocket Park.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither spoke _ Erica is shy and Amanda is unable to talk
_ their enjoyment was evident.
</P>
<P>
   To date, 21 children throughout the world who suffer from the
disease, as well as from other conditions that prevent them from
going outside, have been fitted with the special outfits, Dotts
said. Thirty others are on a waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration got involved
in creating the suits after being contact by Hampton, Va.,
homemaker Sarah Moody in 1986. She requested help for her nephew
who was born without sweat glands. Moody went on to found the HED
(hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplastia) Foundation. With money donated
to the foundation, the $2,000 suits are given to ailing children.
</P>
<P>
   ``These children without NASA would still be confined to their
homes,'' Moody said Monday during the ceremonies in which the girls
received their suits. ``It will give them a quality of life they
could never have had without NASA. We've opened the door from
darkness to sunlight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really going to get to go outside,'' said Amanda's
stepmother, Veronica Clanton, 29, of nearby Kenefick in Liberty
County. ``It's kind of scary to think that for the past 9 years
Amanda has never gotten to go outside and now they're saying this
suit is going to enable her to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda's mother and her father, John Clanton, 32, a centrifuge
mechanic, knew something was wrong with their daughter when she was
5 months old and was not growing at a normal rate. She was
diagnosed with the life-threatening disorder at 13 months of age.
</P>
<P>
   Caused by a genetic disorder, the disease has been identified in
less than 1,000 cases known worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Persons with xeroderma pigmentosum have no pigmentation and no
defense against ultraviolet light. The slightest exposure to the
sun can cause skin cancer. A range of symptoms are associated with
those inflicted with the ailment _ including blindness and
deafness; blistering or freckling on minimum sun exposure;
developmental disabilities; dwarfism and hypergonadism; increased
skin and eye cancers; and mental retardation.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no cure, those with the disorder can only curtail
it by avoiding the UV radiation by staying indoors with sunlight
blocked out or by using protective clothing, sunscreens and
sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda, who has 17 different doctors, is non-verbal, 90 percent
blind and 85 percent deaf. She wears glasses and a hearing aid and
is in a wheelchair since she has not been able to walk since age 4.
Because of poor muscle tone she is unable to eat and is fed through
a gastric tube.
</P>
<P>
   For day-to-day activities, Amanda's life will not change that
much, said her stepmother, Veronica Clanton, who works for an oil
and gas company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still going to be very hard for her and very hard for her
mother at all times. But we are so appreciative for everybody who
has made it possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Amanda's stepsisters, Shelby, 8, and Katilyn, 7, found out
their sister was going to get a special suit that would allow her
to go outside, they suggested that their parents take them all to
Disney World in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
