<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Thirty refueling airplanes will
be sent immediately to Europe and reservists will be called up as
early as Tuesday to staff them, the Pentagon announced Monday. The
Pentagon also announced it was constructing a refugee camp in
western Albania to house the 20,000 Kosovar Albanians who were
originally to be sent to Guantanamo base in Cuba. The camp in Fier,
Albania will be able to house 2,500 refugees as early as next week.
By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ As a high ranking American envoy
arrived in Moscow for talk over Kosovo, Igor Ivanov, Russia's
foreign minister, said Monday that NATO, as well as Belgrade, would
have to bend if the conflict was to be brought to an end. In an
interview, Ivanov insisted that progress was being made on two
fronts: the withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo and an
international force to police a settlement. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Republicans are preparing to add
$5 billion to $7 billion in Pentagon programs to President
Clinton's emergency request for $6 billion in spending on the
Balkans, key members of Congress said Monday. Seeking to make
President Clinton's performance as commander-in-chief a political
issue in next year's elections, they have seized on Pentagon
spending as a hot issue. The extra spending would come from the
budget surplus. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POWS (Belgrade) _ The Red Cross sees the three American
soldiers held in Yugoslavia. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ A Yugoslav deputy prime minister,
Vuk Draskovic, vowed to lead street protests against President
Slobodan Milosevic if military control over Belgrade's Studio B
television station is not lifted immediately. Draskovic, the most
liberal member of the weak federal government, said a military
officer had come to the station, Studio B, Monday evening and
prevented the rebroadcast of an interview Draskovic gave on Sunday
evening. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JACKSON (Washington) _ Jesse Jackson is having a hard
time arranging for a trip to Belgrade to visit prisoners. By Susan
Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   MACEDONIA-CHILDREN (Brazda, Macedonia) _ In Macedonia alone, the
International Committee of the Red Cross has found 276 children who
arrived here with no adult relatives. They are now in the care of
strangers, and aid workers have posted photographs of lost children
in refugee camps here hoping parents will come forward. Another 600
parents are searching desperately for missing children. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RAPE (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Her tormentor told her she was
chosen for her beauty. But it is her determination that sets her
apart. Sherife Elshani, 18 years old, is one of a small group of
ethnic Albanian women willing to say openly that they were sexually
assaulted by Serb soldiers during the chaotic exodus from Kosovo.
By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Berlin) _ A month of war in Europe has already
brought deep changes to the continent, awakening a new sense of
European patriotism, rekindling tensions over ``American
imperialism,'' and reviving the sagging fortunes of some leaders.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-OIL (Undated) _ NATO's anticipated oil embargo on
Yugoslavia is certain to be tested by adventurous oil suppliers
from Russia, China, Greece, Macedonia and Western Europe, all eager
to cash in on the lucrative fees associated with smuggling. Oil
traders from across Europe say they have already been contacted by
expatriate Serbs ready to finance a continued supply of gasoline
and diesel fuel at premium rates to the Yugoslav military through
porous land and water borders. By Youssef M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   This story, budgeted earlier, is now scratched:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS.
