<HEADLINE>
LEARNING SCIENCE FROM `ER'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   A biology professor at Purdue University is offering a class
based on the TV series ``ER'' this summer. Students will watch an
episode and then prepare questions based on that show's medical and
ethical questions.
</P>
<P>
   Professor  &UR; Edward Simon &LR;  said that he was inspired by students
who regularly asked him questions after viewing weekly installments
of the program. ` `ER' raises questions about AIDS in the
workplace, the ethics of drug trials, medical economics and
euthanasia,'' he said. ``There is never a shortage of issues to
research further and discuss in greater detail.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONICA'S FEELINGS HURT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; , who at first wasn't going to do a book
publicity tour in the United States,; &LR;  then, &LR;  had such a swell time
in Europe that she decided to give it a go here, has changed her
mind again.
</P>
<P>
   After rough outings late last week talking with  &UR; Terry Gross &LR;  of
NPR and  &UR; Matt Lauer &LR;  of the ``Today'' show, her book publicist
announced the U.S. tour would wrap up early this week.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky left ``Fresh Air,'' Gross's &LR;  show, in mid- &LR; conservation
after the host inquired about her assertion that she and Clinton
had ``clicked at an incredible level'' during a sexual diversion in
which he was also discussing Bosnia on the phone with a
congressman. ``I certainly am not going to go through and re-enact
for you verbally what was going on and what my feelings and
emotions were at the time,'' said the author of a book on just that
subject.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lauer, he had the nerve to ask why, despite her
assertions that she didn't want to ``make a career out of being
Monica Lewinsky,'' she turned up at the Vanity Fair Oscars party.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jamie Brickhouse &LR;  of St. Martin's Press said that Lewinsky felt
``emotionally drained'' and would do no more interviews in the
United States.
