A3984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-IMMIGRANTS-HNS     04-26 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-IMMIGRANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TO HEAR ANTI-BIAS IMMIGRANT CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Monday agreed to decide
whether a 19th-century civil rights law prohibits discrimination
against immigrants in the awarding of private employment contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The justices and lower federal courts have long held that the
law prohibits discrimination against blacks. But the high court has
never addressed whether the statute, Section 1981 of the 1870 Civil
Rights Act, bars private employers from discriminating based on
immigrant status.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to hear the case this fall or early
next year and render their decision by July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The case arose five years ago, when the United Brotherhood of
Carpenters and Joiners of America fired Linden Anderson, a Jamaican
citizen living in the United States, from his position as a
business representative for the union. The group's constitution
prohibited non-U.S. or non-Canadian citizens from serving as
business representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson sued, claiming he was dismissed in violation of Section
1981. The U.S. District Court for Southern New York dismissed the
case, ruling that the federal law prohibits discrimination based on
race, not immigrant status.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed, ruling that
the statute protects immigrants as well as racial minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In successfully urging the justices to hear its appeal, the
union argued that Congress enacted Section 1981 in the aftermath of
the Civil War to protect the newly freed black slaves from
discrimination. The law was not intended to protect immigrants, the
carpenters' group said.
</P>
<P>
   The union also said that Congress subsequently passed the
Immigration Reform and Control Act to protect immigrants from
discrimination, an indication that the 1870 law provided them no
safeguard.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government, with Congress' blessing,
discriminates against immigrants in hiring insofar as federal
civil-service regulations state that a ``person may be admitted to
competitive examination only if he is a citizen of or owes
permanent allegiance to the United States,'' the union said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, in his unsuccessful request that the justices reject
the union's appeal, argued that Section 1981 does prohibit
discrimination against immigrants in private contracts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
