</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 CAPTURED AMERICANS APPEAR TO BE SOUND, RED CROSS OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas, Mich.)  (With Kosovo package) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Three American soldiers, captured by
Yugoslav forces a month ago, appeared to be in good condition
Monday during a brief visit by the president of the International
Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelio Sommaruga, the Red Cross official, said he had a short,
normal conversation with the three men in the presence of Yugoslav
authorities. He refused to comment on their condition, saying that
a full visit by a Red Cross doctor would take place on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But a White House spokesman was more forthcoming after American
officials were briefed by the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is good news that they appear in good condition,''
the spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said in Washington. ``I emphasize the
word `appear,' because they were not able to speak privately or
have doctors examine the three.''
</P>
<P>
   The men were shown on Yugoslav television with bruised faces and
cuts immediately after their capture on March 31 near the
Macedonian border. Yugoslav officials said then, a week after the
NATO bombing campaign began, that the three had resisted capture.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross had previously been denied access to the soldiers
_ Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Spc. Steven
Gonzalez, 21, of Huntsville, Texas; and Staff Sgt. Christopher
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the occasion to see them and shake their hands and I had
a short talk with all three,'' Sommaruga said at a news conference
Monday. ``But further than that,'' he said, ``I really cannot say.
I had no knowledge of what they feel. I had no doctor with me to
analyze their health.'' He did not specify where the meeting on
Monday took place, but it was believed to be somewhere near
Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   Sommaruga had a separate meeting with the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, who authorized the visit, to seek permission
for the Red Cross to resume relief work in Kosovo and throughout
Yugoslavia. The government in Belgrade has been reluctant to allow
any foreigners free access to Kosovo, where many thousands of
Albanians have fled or have been driven from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Television showed the two men meeting in a rustic office,
sitting on worn armchairs and a sofa, clearly not the usual
reception room Milosevic uses in the Beli Dvor, or White Palace,
which is his ceremonial residence. The meeting was believed to have
taken place in Milosevic's country residence at Dobanovci. But
given the stormy, cold weather here, which made a rural weekend
uninviting, it also appeared to indicate that Milosevic, whose
Belgrade residence was bombed by NATO last week, is altering his
habits.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic told Sommaruga that the only obstacle to Red Cross
access is the danger posed by NATO bombing, according to the
official news agency, Tanjug. ``In an open conversation, referring
to important humanitarian problems caused by NATO bombing,
Milosevic said that the Yugoslav side imposed no obstacles for
International Red Cross teams to operate on the whole territory of
Yugoslavia,'' Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said, according to Tanjug, ``The only obstacle could
be the continuous bombing of civilian facilities, which was the
reason why people in Kosovo had fled their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommaruga said later: ``I was glad to establish, and get
assurances at the highest level, that we would receive full
assistance from the federal government in carrying out our programs
without difficulties, particularly as to the delivery of
humanitarian goods.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said his staff would have to sit down and discuss
security arrangements both with the Yugoslav army and with NATO in
order to work safely in Yugoslavia, particularly in the Kosovo
province.
</P>
<P>
   So it was not immediately clear whether the Red Cross would have
access to Kosovo, or how soon. Refugees cannot return, Milosevic
said, as long as the bombing continued.
</P>
<P>
   Sommaruga said he was not optimistic that the three soldiers
would be released before the war ended. ``International
humanitarian law says prisoners of war would be liberated only at
the end of active hostilities,'' he said. ``Regrettably, we are not
at this point at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, the American politician and minister, is
hoping to come to Belgrade to meet with Milosevic and to try to
secure the release of the soldiers. Jackson, who is a confidant and
emissary of President Clinton, has organized a group of
Serbian-American clergy, Muslim clerics and rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials said the Americans they are holding had
strayed into Yugoslav territory when they were captured and would
be treated as prisoners of war. American officials at first
insisted that the men were kidnapped from Macedonian territory,
then said they were unsure, but demanded their immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier effort to secure their release by a Greek Cypriot
politician failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
