A4004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-A&AMP;P-ATLANTA-COX     04-26 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-A&AMP;P-ATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A&AMP;P to close stores in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A&AMP;P confirmed Monday it is closing or selling all of
its stores in metro Atlanta. The grocery chain has agreements to
sell 14 of its 34 stores here and will close the remaining 20 by
the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Great Atlantic &AMP; Pacific Tea Co., which operates stores here as
A&AMP;P, will also close its distribution center and administrative
office in Atlanta. About 2,000 employees will lose their jobs, said
A&AMP;P spokesman Andy Carrano. Eligible full-time employees will
receive severance pay, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Teeter, which has seven supermarkets in metro Atlanta,
will buy three A&AMP;P stores. Harris Teeter said it expects to close
the deal by June 3, remodel the stores and reopen them early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   According to a memo distributed to A&AMP;P employees on Monday,
Publix Super Markets and Staples Inc. have also expressed interest
in stores. The companies refused to confirm the memo, however. ``We
have not signed anything yet,'' said Publix spokeswoman Rita Owens.
``That's not to say we're not talking to them.'' Staples, a new
player in the Atlanta office supplies superstore market, looked at
some of the A&AMP;P sites but does not intend to buy any, said Staples
spokeswoman Shannon Lapierre.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;P's exit from Atlanta is part of an overall retreat from
competitive cities as the Montvale, N.J.-based parent chain focuses
on its core markets in Detroit, New York and Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is to achieve a No. 1 or No. 2 market share
position in every market we serve. The Atlanta market is already
highly concentrated and we therefore could not see ourselves
achieving a top position,'' said Christian Haub, A&AMP;P's president
and chief executive. In terms of sales, A&AMP;P is the No. 6 chain in
metro Atlanta, according to the Shelby Report of the Southeast, a
trade newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;P has tried several competitive rallies in Atlanta after
hitting financial trouble in the 1970s. In the late 1980s, A&AMP;P
rolled out its ``Futurestores'' concept to challenge Kroger. At
that point it held a 9 percent market share of metro Atlanta sales,
compared to Kroger's 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But A&AMP;P's chances were squelched in 1992 when Publix entered the
Atlanta scene, snatching a 10 percent market share in a couple of
years with shiny, bigger stores. The metro Atlanta supermarket
competition is now largely defined by Kroger and Publix, which
together have more than half the market share and dominate the
northern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A&AMP;P underinvested in new stores. They failed to make their
stores bigger and add services like the competition did,'' said Tom
Agan, a principal with retail consulting firm Kurt Salmon
Associates. In its new strategy for core markets, Great Atlantic
plans to open up to 200 superstores over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, A&AMP;P's exit is bad news for its shopping center
neighbors because they're largely dependent on the grocery store to
bring in traffic, Agan said. ``A strip center implodes when a
supermarket bails,'' he said. ``The center typically converts from
primary retail to secondary retail and services, like chiropractic
offices or veterinary clinics.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent grocers may pick up some of the A&AMP;P sites, said
Chuck Gilmer, editor of the Shelby Report. ``Some mom-and-pops have
a strategy of going into closed chain operations because they can
get a good lease and lower overhead,'' Gilmer said. Wayfield, which
has 10 Atlanta stores, is a good example, he said. Save-A-Lot,
which features a limited assortment of goods at steep discounts,
has a similar strategy. It currently has two stores in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;P isn't the only chain recently to get run off by Atlanta's
fierce supermarket competition. Bruno's pulled out of Atlanta in
1998, when it sold 13 stores to Ingles. A couple of stores
re-opened as Ingles, while others were sold to Kroger and Cub
Foods.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
