<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4007 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSING-COX     04-26 0220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta real estate boom continues
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta could set a record for housing permits this
year and lead the nation, according to projections by a real estate
industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by U.S. Housing Markets newsletter projects that
housing permits here will increase 9 percent, to 62,600, in 1999.
That would also make Atlanta number-one in the nation in permits.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is expected to rank fourth _ behind Texas, Florida and
California _ in total number of new permits. Texas, now the
nation's busiest homebuilding state, might register 175,000 new
permits this year, while Georgia is expected to record 94,000.
</P>
<P>
   The predicted year-over-year percentage increases for both
states are close _ 12 percent for Georgia and 11 percent for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Permits in Florida will reach a 10-year high if the 5 percent
increase expected by U.S. Housing Markets materializes.
</P>
<P>
   Given a robust economy, good job growth, consumer confidence,
low mortgage rates and good weather, ``the housing market is
holding strong cards,'' according to the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
