<SLUG> BC-MUSTANG-MUSEUM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brakes put on Mustang museum plans
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A proposed Mustang museum, which had selected Atlanta
as one of two finalists for its site, has hit a wall because of
fund-raising problems.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the board is exploring the option of joining with an
existing museum or attraction to house a Mustang collection.
</P>
<P>
   High costs for real estate, construction and operations for the
proposed $30 million facility _ as well as competition in the
tourism industry _ made a stand-alone museum ``economically
unfeasible,'' officials said. Orlando was the other location under
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reopening the site process,'' said William Dillard, a
Calhoun insurance claims specialist and president of Mustang Museum
Inc. ``We have a lot to offer an established automotive museum.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the fund-raising effort would have consumed too
much of enthusiasts' time and energy. ``In the end, we decided we'd
rather devote our passion to the cars, not to fund-raising,''
Dillard added.
</P>
<P>
   He said the museum would fit best with a similar not-for-profit
museum or attraction. He said a number of facilities in Georgia or
the Southeast might be a good fit but declined to single out any of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. has continued its pledge of $1.5 million toward
the project.
</P>
<P>
   A 100,000-square-foot interactive museum and attraction was
planned as a testament to the popular pony car introduced in 1964.
More than 7 million Mustangs have been sold, generating more than
400 Mustang clubs with about 70,000 members worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Ritzler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
