<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-734&AMP;ADD     04-26 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-734&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EUROPE, TENSIONS AND PATRIOTISM OVER KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ A month of war in Europe has already brought deep
changes to the continent, awakening a new sense of European
patriotism, rekindling tensions over ``American imperialism'' and
reviving the sagging fortunes of some leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Raised after World War II to reject military violence but also
to insure that the barbarism of Hitler and Stalin never be
repeated, a generation of Europeans has been abruptly forced by
events in Kosovo to a painful choice between these principles.
</P>
<P>
   In general, they have come down in favor of using military power
to try to stop the ``ethnic cleansing'' of Kosovo and have
increasingly portrayed the fate of the province as a decisive test
of Europe's commitment to a continent freed in the 21st century of
the mass deportations and killings that marked this one.
</P>
<P>
   Ludger Volmer, Germany's deputy foreign minister and a member of
the once pacifist Green Party, said: ``We have to fight for our
Europe where boundaries no longer matter, against old notions of a
Europe of ethnic identity and race-based violence. An integrated
Europe with an open wound in the Balkans is unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unconvincing results of more than four weeks of NATO
bombing and the failure of past appeals to rally to a European
rather than national ideal, such ideas have had a surprising
resonance as image after image of desperate ragged refugees hounded
from Kosovo have filled newspapers and television screens.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of people in Britain, France, Germany and Italy
support the military campaign. A poll last week in France showed 70
percent in favor of the NATO intervention. Support for Gerhard
Schroeder, the German chancellor, has surged as his chief
preoccupation has become war rather than unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, such is the popular support that the British and French
governments have felt able to go further than President Clinton in
suggesting the use of ground forces, although the allies' summit
meeting in Washington over the weekend suggested that support for a
land war is limited and that the air campaign will persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be ready to die for Pristina,'' Kosovo's capital,
``because to die for Pristina is to die for the future of Europe,''
said Andre Glucksmann, a leading French philosopher. ``Americans
have died for Europe twice. Now we have to make sacrifices to show
this continent will no longer tolerate policies that recall
Stalin.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, Europeans have been looking to their own future. Many
see the conflict as a decisive moment for the internal politics of
the continent _ one that could give Europe the political and
military identity it has lacked even as economic ties have
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   Images of trainloads of deportees, of stunned refugees with
unseeing eyes, have stirred terrible memories. In a Europe no
longer divided by the Cold War, the images have prompted a
determination to act, and to establish a continent-wide respect for
human rights that will serve as the basis for the Europe of the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   But this bold new determination to salvage Europe's pride after
a wounding century, a determination embodied most emphatically in
the oratory of Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, is by no means
shared by everyone.
</P>
<P>
   With an American general directing the NATO military campaign,
deep concern or outright anger over European dependency on
Washington and over what some see as America's control over the
post-Cold War world has surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Deploring Europe's premature decision to cash in the ``peace
dividend'' and cut military spending, Lamberto Dini, the Italian
foreign minister, said: ``The United States cannot be the gendarmes
of the world, nor the mercenary soldiers for countries that do not
intend to assume military responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In a distinctly anti-American tone, some French intellectuals
have portrayed the war in Kosovo as the latest attempt by
Washington to satisfy the appetites of its military-industrial
complex, undermine Europe and bolster the unilateral power that the
United States has enjoyed since the Soviet Union collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The undeclared war in the Balkans is not a war against the
Serbs,'' Guy Declos, a French sociologist, wrote in the French
daily Le Monde. ``It is a war against Europe.'' Disguised as a
fight for a certain morality, it is in reality a struggle to
``stamp out definitively any hope of a multi-polar planet,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such anti-Americanism is not new in France; but its
tone has been sharpened by events in Kosovo, and found strong
echoes among small left-wing European parties, though not with the
dominant center-left forces led by the likes of Blair and the
French premier, Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, it appears that a crisis of European-American
relations has been averted, although one could develop if the
current confusion turned into an irreversible debacle.
</P>
<P>
   A rupture in relations with Russia has also been avoided, and
Western governments now seem determined to back a Russian-led peace
bid because President Boris Yeltsin's influence in Belgrade is
considerable. Whatever the outcome of this diplomacy, concern is
strong, particularly in Germany, that Moscow not be alienated.
</P>
<P>
   After Europe's profound failure in Bosnia, a war the European
Union initially volunteered to stop and much later saw halted by a
``Pax Americana,'' the desire to assert a political and military
identity with a success in Kosovo is strong.
</P>
<P>
   And with the arrival this year of the common European currency,
the euro, the continent has been casting around for some new
catalyst for the political and military integration that has been
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo could be our military euro, creating a political and
defense identity for the European Union in the same way as the euro
is the expression of economic and financial integration,'' said
Ulrich Beck, a professor of politics at Munich University.
</P>
<P>
   But the attainment of a ``military euro'' is evidently a long
way off. A month of bombing has failed to bring any of the results
NATO had sought, and the longer the war continues, the sharper the
tensions in Europe are likely to become.
</P>
<P>
   Volmer, the German deputy minster, said he thought his Green
Party, the junior partner in the governing coalition, would be
unable to accept the dispatch of ground troops if NATO moved in
that direction to break the impasse. ``This could bring down the
German government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens are to hold a congress on May 13 at which they are
likely to vote on this issue. The tensions in the party reflect the
way the conversion of Volmer and of the foreign minister, Joschka
Fischer, to supporting military force against Yugoslavia has by no
means been followed by all members of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Similar tensions may emerge in Italy's coalition government,
where the former Communists are very uneasy about ground forces,
even as the British and French governments push the view that a
long war fought only with air power may risk losing public support.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly a war in which the only victims are civilians does not
appear likely to command widespread support indefinitely in a
continent where the idea of ``body bags'' is more acceptable as a
price of war than it is in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
