<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Top of order not sorry to leave April behind
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Hidden beneath a heap of runs the Braves offense has
been scoring is a bad vibe at the top of the order. Leadoff hitter
Otis Nixon has had another rough April and No. 2 man Bret Boone has
been the unlucky hitter in the Braves order.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon is hitting .170 and Boone is hitting .235 and together
that adds up to a .206 batting average and an on-base percentage of
.290, which is not the kind of setting up that will keep this
offense chugging.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon is figuring he just needs to get out of April, a month in
which he's hitting .232 in his career. That and as hitting coach
Don Baylor is suggesting, don't be in such a hurry to get out of
the batter's box as he finishes his swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants me to keep the ball out of the air,'' Nixon said.
``As long as I can keep hitting hard groundballs, I'll be OK...I've
played long enough to know what's going to happen, to trust
yourself, stay within yourself and you'll be all right. You play
good defense and manufacture some runs and it's as good as getting
a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon has still found ways to be productive, like on Sunday when
he reached twice an error, stole two bases and scored a run and in
Tuesday's game in L.A. when he drew a pair of bases loaded walks.
</P>
<P>
   Boone has been the bad luck hitter of the order, starting the
first couple days of the season. It's resurfaced lately, like in
the 5-4 April 20 loss in L.A., when with Gerald Williams at third
base, Boone would have tied the game had his line drive been just
about anywhere but right at third baseman Adrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   So Boone's not making any big adjustments at the plate, he's
just trying to stay patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know with this approach (at the plate) and if I continue to
work, it's just a matter of time,'' Boone said. ``It's hard, but
I'm not going to walk around moping. It happens to everybody. It
just so happened to me it happened at the start of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury Update
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones missed his first start of the year on Monday with
a strained adductor muscle in his left thigh, which he injured
running from first to third on an error in Sunday's game. Keith
Lockhart replaced him at third base Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I improve as much between today and tomorrow as I did
yesterday to today, I can play, but I can't do anything today,''
Jones said before Monday's game. ``Yesterday I was about 40-50
percent. Today I'm probably 70 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko said he's nearly ready after being out for almost
two weeks with a high hamstring pull. Manager Bobby Cox wasn't
ready to put him in the lineup on Monday. Klesko's last time in as
a pinch hitter, he pulled up hurt after running out an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be 100 percent probably for another few weeks,''
Klesko said. ``Maybe giving it extra time will be good for
something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing touches
</P>
<P>
   Reliever John Rocker took his work on Sunday _ recording four
outs against four batters in a non-save situation against the
Marlins _ and used it to continue regaining his confidence after
the blown save in Colorado. Rocker said he figured out in Denver
that he can't count on blowing his fastball by hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I learned no matter how hard you throw, you can't
throw stuff down the middle,'' Rocker said. ``Guys are looking for
one pitch (the 97-plus MPH fastball)....I'll have to be a little
smarter with it. I won't just try to blow a fastball right down the
middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The most consistent reliever the Braves have had so far this
season is Rudy Seanez, who's pitched scoreless ball in six of his
first seven outings with good hard stuff and even better control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not pinpoint, but it's better than it's ever been,''
Seanez said. ``I've never been able to paint the black or divide
the plate up into thirds...I'm not trying to throw hard, not trying
to make the perfect pitch all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
