<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hot Hawks pushing up button in East
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Someone's knocking on the door; somebody's ringing the
bell.
</P>
<P>
   If they look around in Orlando, Indiana and Miami, they'll see
the Hawks, and they won't want to let them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning cures a lot of things,'' Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Hawks were staggering in sixth place, as
close to ninth in the Eastern Conference _ out of the playoffs _ as
they were to fourth and home-court advantage in the first round.
Now they're fourth, the hottest team in the East with six
consecutive wins, and the three teams above them each lost its last
game.
</P>
<P>
   With a reasonably secure grip on No. 4 _ two losses better than
Philadelphia, three to the good of Milwaukee and Detroit with five
games to play _ the Hawks have their eyes on better things.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the picture:
</P>
<P>
   _ The No. 1 Miami Heat appears to be out of reach. Miami had
three fewer losses than the Hawks entering its game Monday night at
Cleveland. Miami also won the season series, so a tie doesn't help.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 2 Indiana is intriguing, because the Hawks are one game
out of first in the Central with the division-leading Pacers here
Friday night. Because the Hawks are 3-0 in the season series, a tie
would work to Atlanta's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Slumping No. 3 Orlando, losers of five straight, leads by only
a half-game. If the Hawks can't take second seed, third is
consolation. The teams split four games this season, but the Magic
has a better record in the East, so Orlando gets the tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Either No. 2 or No. 3 will lose tonight, with the Magic playing
at Indiana. The Hawks are off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys, 'Take care of business and things have a way
of falling into place,' `` Wilkens said. ``This has been the best
possible result for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach is refining his offense and defense and honing his
player rotations to take full benefit of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game is so important, I want our best guys on the
floor,'' Wilkens said. ``Plus, we have a lot of off days so (the
veteran starters) will get their rest.''
</P>
<P>
   With Alan Henderson returning Wednesday at the Georgia Dome
against the Knicks from a bruised back _ ``I can't stand sitting
around any more,'' Henderson said _ the Hawks will be at full
strength. That means Roshown McLeod, Jeff Sheppard and Ed Gray will
become game-time cheerleaders unless there are blowouts.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens will continue a pattern that started in Washington on
Friday and continued Sunday against Milwaukee, with Anthony
Johnson, Mark West, Ty Corbin and either Grant Long or Henderson
rotating off the bench in relief of Mookie Blaylock, Dikembe
Mutombo, Steve Smith, Chris Crawford and the starting power
forward, Henderson or Long.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and West play as needed in the second half, but Wilkens
essentially will use a tight seven-man rotation. When the games are
close in the fourth quarter, expect to see Corbin, who is
refreshed, playing the small-forward minutes for Crawford, Wilkens
said, ``Because Ty is such a smart player, and I want a veteran
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens can employ that strategy easily through the first round
of the playoffs, because the Hawks play consecutive games only once
more, on the final day of the season against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have our best guys out there,'' Wilkens said. ``This is
the time for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
