<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4023 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS &LR;      04-26 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON ANNOUNCES INITIAL CALL-UP OF U.S. RESERVISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon announced the initial call-up of Air
Force Reserves on Monday to help in NATO refueling operations amid
the first serious signs of a split in the Yugoslav leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials said they were encouraged by Yugoslav Deputy
Premier Duk Draskovic's comments on Serb television over the
weekend calling on President Slobodan Milosevic to end his
``intransigence'' on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, who has been a strident nationalist, said it was time
for his government to face reality and to begin telling the Serbian
people the truth about the Kosovo situation.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNN Monday, Draskovic said Serbia ``has no
chance except to build up democratic institutions in our country.''
He added that his goal ``is to reform Yugoslavia ... into a Balkans
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Reacting cautiously, White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart
said the remarks might represent ``some breaking of the Yugoslav
political structure'' in face of a firm allied commitment to drive
Serb forces out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's stunning remarks came amid signs that the Milosevic
government might be easing its hard-line stance. Three members of
the International Committee of the Red Cross were allowed to visit
briefly with the three U.S. servicemen being held as prisoners of
war, even though the visits were not permitted to be private.
</P>
<P>
   They were, however, allowed to give messages to the three Army
soldiers _ Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Spc.
Steven M. Gonzalez, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, and Staff Sgt.
Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich. _ from their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelio Sommaruga, head of the ICRC who also met with
Milosevic, said he was told that a Red Cross doctor would also be
allowed to return for a longer, private visit Tuesday with the
three soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   There were also indications Monday that the Belgrade government
would allow the Rev. Jesse Jackson and a group of clergymen into
Yugoslavia to visit the Americans and meet with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO planes continued to be hampered by increasingly
bad weather in the Balkans, but were successful in carrying out
several bombing runs on key targets in Kosovo and in northern
Yugoslavia. One of the targets destroyed was the last remaining
railroad and highway bridge over the Danube River at Novi Sad,
which served as one of the main resupply and refueling routes for
Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Allied bombs had hit the bridge last week but apparently failed
to make it impassable.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, allied officials also announced that the 23
U.S. Army Apache attack helicopters and their support forces are
now in place in Albania and are undergoing final preparations for
deployment against Yugoslav ground troops and tanks inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said that an Apache helicopter had apparently
crashed on a routine training run near its Albanian base. The crash
at its base at Tirana airport apparently was an accident and that
the two crewmen aboard had escaped without serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   The incident will have to be investigated before the Apaches are
sent into combat.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache contingent, complete with ground-based missile
launchers, Black Hawk helicopters and support troops, represents a
combat-ready unit made up of 3,400 U.S. personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also announced that 30 more KC-135 and KC-10 tanker
refueling aircraft will be deployed by this weekend to help
``increase the tempo'' of the NATO bombing mission dubbed Operation
Allied Force. The tanker pilot and support crews will consist of
both active-duty and Air Force Reserve and Air National Guard
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the initial call-up of
reserve and national guard personnel to assist in the tanker
mission would include crews from Arizona, California, Michigan and
one other unspecified state.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Pentagon officials indicated that up to 33,000
reservists and national guardsmen could be called to active duty.
Defense Secretary William Cohen is expected to provide that figure
Tuesday when he makes the official announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon described the new deployment of tankers as a
``downpayment'' on about 300 additional U.S. aircraft requested by
NATO Supreme Commander Gen. Wesley Clark to augment a force of NATO
planes that is already more than 600 strong.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO continued to beef up its air operations, it also made
plans for an oil and fuel embargo on Yugoslavia. The allied leaders
approved a ``visit and search'' plan during their weekend NATO
meeting in Washington that would allow allied ships to stop vessels
from entering the port of Bar near Montenegro, a main supply route
for oil and other products into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon and a top NATO general seemed to disagree over
whether force would be used if necessary to stop ships, and whether
NATO would attempt to block Russian vessels from entering the port.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot stop a merchant vessel by the use of force,'' German
Gen. Klaus Naumann told reporters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Pentagon, Bacon said the United States takes the
position that the ``so-called (international) rules of armed
conflict'' would allow the use of firepower to enforce a maritime
blockade.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO operation has destroyed Yugoslavia's oil-refining
capability and most fuel reserves. Land routes over which oil can
be brought in have also been disrupted. But oil can still be
brought in by sea through Montenegro, which is autonomous but still
a province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   On the diplomatic front, Vice President Al Gore spoke with
Russian special envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin for an hour by telephone.
Chernomyrdin met with Milosevic last week in an attempt to broker a
deal between Belgrade and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The two ``reviewed'' the discussions Chernomyrdin had with the
Yugoslav president Thursday in which he reportedly said he was
willing to accept an international security force in Kosovo, a Gore
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   That position was rejected, however, by NATO leaders who said it
didn't go far enough toward accepting all the terms laid down by
NATO, including a complete pullout of Yugoslav forces from Kosovo,
the return of ethnic Albanians driven out by the Serbs, and a
NATO-led force to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also met Monday at the White House with
Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov to talk about the Kosovo
conflict, the refugee problem in Macedonia and the allies' role in
helping to rebuild the region when the conflict ends.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also spoke to congressional leaders about his $6 billion
emergency request to help pay for the U.S. portion of the NATO
operation. House Republicans want to increase the requested amount
by at least another $5 billion to $14 billion, but administration
officials are concerned that it could get bogged down in
contentious debate about what kind of programs ought to be funded.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is also preparing for possible votes this week on
whether to declare war against Yugoslavia or to end U.S.
involvement in the NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., is demanding a vote on a
declaration of war, which he said would fulfill Congress' duty
under the War Powers Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point I think it is important for us to express
ourselves again. I don't think that it's necessary to declare
war,'' said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
