turning increasingly red, and the growing brilliance of color
signals a historic change in the ecological character of a vast
region stretching from the Great Lakes to the Atlantic and from
Canada well into the South. These arboreal hard-chargers are red
maples, and they are taking over the woods. If their march
continues, it could signal the downfall of the majestic oaks that
have been a mainstay of the deciduous forest for most of the last
10,000 years. By William K. Stevens. (The story has moved in ``a''
news file.) With photo and graphic.
