<HEADER>
A4028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRANNY-CAMPAIGN-ART-4     04-26 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANNY-CAMPAIGN-ART-472&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT-GRANDMOTHER TREKS CROSS-COUNTRY FOR CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(kd) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ The morning sun had barely crested the low,
tawny mountains to the east of this city when Doris Haddock hit the
road.
</P>
<P>
   She was worried about the temperature, which was likely to rise
above 70 by noon, and wanted to finish her walk before then.
</P>
<P>
   Ten miles was her goal, or rather her daily requirement, a
distance that might be less impressive if Mrs. Haddock had not done
it more than 100 times already _ heading east from Pasadena,
Calif., more than three months ago _ and if she was not 89.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have arthritis in both hands, and sometimes my legs hurt at
night,'' Mrs. Haddock said in a chirpy voice as she catalogued the
health problems that hamper her cross-country odyssey, which was
taking her past strip clubs, shacks selling fireworks and countless
tufts of scrub brush along Route 62.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' she said, ``the emphysema has greatly improved with the
walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Mrs. Haddock logged the 1,000th mile of her one-woman
trek to protest the failure of Congress in recent years to pass
several bills that proposed an overhaul in campaign finance
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   That meant she had a little more than 2,000 to go until she
reached Washington, probably in January. Initially, she had hoped
to get there by late November, but complications arose.
</P>
<P>
   She woke up one morning near Salome, Ariz., with difficulty
breathing and spent the next four days in the hospital, being
treated for dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Now she was resting for two days every week and carrying on her
back a bag of water with a long plastic tube that works like a
straw. As a piece of sophisticated supplemental equipment, it
joined the steel corset that she wears to support her
intermittently aching back.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Haddock shared her plans with her sister last year,
her sister cried. Her son-in-law told her, only half kiddingly,
that she might be a candidate for institutionalization.
</P>
<P>
   But she had time on her hands, adventure in her heart and an
issue that she wanted to publicize. She figured, rightly, that
reporters and local politicians would be unable to ignore a woman
of so many years, her stooped shoulders giving her a forward tilt,
marching across the formidable breadth of America.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Haddock, who takes frequent stops to proselytize, there
is no problem in this country more significant than the prevalence
of ``soft money,'' or largely unregulated and unlimited
contributions to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just infuriates me!'' she said over dinner in a Mexican
restaurant here on Saturday night. She balled her hands into fists
and struck the table so hard that the tortilla chips jumped a few
inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we are losing our democracy,'' she said. ``The
corporations are taking over and deciding who gets elected.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many political pilgrims have preceeded Mrs. Haddock, and they
have traversed America, on foot and on bicycles, for a myriad of
causes. But, given her age, Mrs. Haddock may be the most audacious.
</P>
<P>
   She has assumed a catchy moniker, Granny D, which actually sells
her short, because she is in fact a great-grandmother of 11. She
advertises her agenda on a reflective vest that says, ``Granny D
For Campaign Finance Reform.'' Motorists who have seen her on local
TV often honk.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site, www.grannyd.com, gives the details of her itinerary
and enables supporters to join her for a day or two. Many have,
including a 65-year-old man from Arizona with what she described as
``a personality problem'' _ ``he was enrolled in a course to
control his violent temper,'' she said, ``but he didn't finish it''
_ and a 25-year-old man from California who insisted on dragging
any road kill, with his bare hands, into the desert for a proper
burial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walking's OK,'' Mrs. Haddock said, ``but personnel has
been the biggest problem.''
</P>
<P>
   She is never alone: the advocacy group Common Cause, having been
informed of her intentions, helped to organize partners to
accompany her, a van to trail her and hosts to give her places to
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little nervous,'' admitted Matt Keller, a lobbyist
with Common Cause, ``mainly because she's a very old woman. Did we
want to support something that may turn out to be tragic?''
</P>
<P>
   They took the chance, and off she went, starting as an
unofficial straggler behind the Rose Bowl Parade on New Year's Day.
After each day's walk, the van carries her backward or forward to
her lodging, then returns her to the spot where she left off,
marked at times by yellow spray paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't exactly tell one cactus from another,'' explained
Jean Higgs, 69, a good friend of hers along for the El Paso leg.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Haddock, a widow who lives on Social Security and a
secretary's pension in Dublin, N.H., said that her activism until
now had been mostly local. But about a year ago, when her best
friend died, she found herself in desperate need of a real mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was bereft,'' she said. ``I felt like a withered oak leaf on
the bough. There's always one left.''
</P>
<P>
   From that grief came this endeavor, for which she trained with
daily hikes and a few experiments in hitchhiking, in case her legs
suddenly failed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly young people came to pick me up, 30 to 50 years old,''
she said. ``I talked to them about campaign finance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
