<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUTE ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neanderthals are back _ not that we ever doubted their presence
in the gene pool. But some DNA research reported two years ago by
scientists at the University of Munich shook the long shadow of the
cave man and purported to prove that he was a species apart from
modern humans, no matter how many knuckle-draggers still seemed to
be thumping through life in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Now science, fascinating for its fluidity, has new evidence to
bolster what human beings have long felt in their bones. In fact,
those very bones tell the story, according to Portuguese and
American researchers who studied the 24,500-year-old skeleton of a
boy discovered last December in the Lapedo Valley north of Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Erik Trinkaus, a paleoanthropologist at Washington
University in St. Louis, told The New York Times that the boy had
the facial features of modern man but a thick-set body and short
legs that were unmistakably Neanderthal, even though he was born
4,000 years after Neanderthals had become extinct.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation: interbreeding between the relatively
sophisticated early European humans, known as Cro-Magnons, and the
low-browed, slow, brutish personalities that have been a favorite
stereotype for at least a millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The research proves something else that human beings have known
intuitively, even though many are loath to admit it: the
Neanderthal stereotype is not without charm. The Cro-Magnons
obviously thought so, for the Lapedo Valley boy appears to be the
product of generations of interbreeding. Perhaps this melding of
tool culture cool with chest-pounder is the source of that ancient
axiom of romance _ ``Opposites attract.''
</P>
<P>
   Having science confirm what we think we know is always
comforting, for the typical discovery today usually makes us gasp.
But the Neanderthal just makes us sigh. Knowing that research
appears to be solidifying his standing as a blood relative may help
us get through the tension of the next family reunion. ``I'm a
Cro-Magnon,'' someone might explain, ``but your Uncle Harry, well,
he's from the other side of the family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
