<HEADER>
A4039 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMEX-APPOINT-ART-450&AMP;     04-26 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMEX-APPOINT-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSOR IS SELECTED TO RUN AMERICAN EXPRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Express Co. said Monday that Kenneth Chenault would
succeed Harvey Golub as chief executive in 2001. That move would
elevate a black executive into the ranks of the country's top
corporate leaders.
</P>
<P>
   If the succession takes place and no other black executives
secure a key to the chief executive's suite before then, Chenault
would join Franklin D. Raines, head of the mortgage-financing giant
Fannie Mae, as the only black leaders of Fortune 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Chenault, 47, the company's president and chief operating
officer, has earned a reputation as a savvy marketer and a
determined revenue builder, qualities American Express will
continue to need as it navigates the brutally competitive straits
of the credit and charge-card businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken's influence has been felt at Amex for some time now,''
said David Robertson, president of the Nilson Report, an Oxnard,
Calif., newsletter covering the credit- and charge-card industry.
``He has proven leadership skills, and he's an executive people
look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of American Express' succession plan came as no
surprise, though the timing was unexpected. Chenault was first
designated as Golub's successor two years ago, but Golub said at
the time that he intended to stay until 2004. Golub, 60, said
Monday that he would cede the chief executive post to Chenault
earlier, in April 2001, to ensure an orderly succession, often a
difficult proposition in corporate America because chief executives
are notoriously loath to relinquish the power and perks that come
with their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   People close to both executives and to the board of American
Express confirmed that reasoning, saying that Golub had not been
asked to relinquish his title earlier than originally planned.
Golub said he would stay on as chairman for a year after stepping
down as chief executive. After that, Chenault will become chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no agenda here other than this being an action that
was purely logical, rational Harvey,'' said one adviser to American
Express and its board. ``Harvey is viewed as the guy who fixed it
up, and Ken is viewed as the revenue generator and marketer.''
</P>
<P>
   Prominent black members of the business community praised the
decision, including the president of Time Warner Inc., Richard
Parsons, who is also a longtime friend of Chenault's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny is clearly an enormously talented guy who has worked for
everything that has come his way,'' Parsons said. ``Of course it's
significant, but these seeds were sown back in the '60s when Jim
Crow laws were dismantled. Some of those flowers are starting to
bloom now. It's never enough, but something is better than
nothing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chenault, the son of a dentist and a graduate of Harvard Law
School, joined American Express as strategic planning director in
1981 after stints at Bain &AMP; Co. as a management consultant and at a
law firm. After arriving at American Express, he snared a
succession of high-profile jobs in the company's lucrative
charge-card business. By the early 1990s, he had also won oversight
of most of the company's travel-related services. He was named vice
chairman in 1995 and president and chief operating officer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In Chenault's early years with American Express, the ubiquitous
green card enjoyed unequaled cachet among status-hungry consumers,
and the company appeared to be poised for growth. But the company's
high-profile chief executive, James Robinson, led American Express
on a series of costly and ill-considered forays into brokerage and
investment banking services that left the company weakened and its
work force demoralized. Moreover, American Express' market share in
the card business was severely diminished by other more creative
and competitive companies that issued credit and charge cards under
the Visa and Mastercard logos.
</P>
<P>
   Those blunders led to Robinson's replacement as chief executive
by Golub in 1993. Under the leadership of Golub and Chenault,
American Express became a very different company than it was during
Robinson's reign. American Express belatedly refocused its efforts
on its core card business and maintained a studied devotion to
profitability. The company's net income was $2.14 billion in 1998,
up from $578 million in 1992. Shares of American Express have
soared since December 1992, climbing from about $22 to $134.3125 at
Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
   But Chenault, despite his proven abilities and the rebound he
and Golub have engineered, will still have to wrestle with some
daunting challenges. American Express lost market share to Visa and
Mastercard again last year, slipping to 17.7 percent of purchase
volume from 18.43 percent in 1997. Visa and Mastercard raised their
respective shares last year to 50.61 percent and 25.44 percent of
the market, according to the Nilson Report.
</P>
<P>
   Chenault, known to be an extremely competitive manager who does
not like to lose, disputed the Nilson Report's data and said that
it was still ``inconclusive'' that American Express lost market
share last year. Even so, he said in an interview that the company
``would like to more aggressively grow market share.'' Specifically
citing the Internet and enhanced forms of direct marketing,
Chenault added that ``the challenge is understanding how to use
different distribution channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Chenault has pushed for greater access to banks and the merchant
network dominated by Visa and Mastercard, an effort that may prove
fruitful depending on the outcome of an antitrust investigation of
those two companies by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   American Express failed to complete a merger it pursued with
Citicorp, now Citigroup, in 1996, and Golub said in an interview
Monday that the company did not rule out a big merger if it made
financial sense. But he said he favored partnerships with smaller
companies that help build American Express' brand name. Still, some
analysts and bank advisers see American Express as a logical
company for Citigroup to acquire if it successfully carries out
last year's merger of Citicorp and Travelers Group.
</P>
<P>
   Chenault, who was born and raised in Mineola, N.Y., is married
and has two children. Besides his law degree, he holds an
undergraduate degree in history from Bowdoin College.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his American Express board seat, Chenault also
sits on the boards of IBM, Quaker Oats and several charitable
concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
