<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4048 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-GUNS-HNS &LR;      04-26 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER THE GUN: BUSH URGED TO TAKE ACTIVE ROLE IN REVIVING PROPOSAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, in the wake of the Colorado
school shooting last week, endorsed a controversial gun control
proposal that had been killed only hours earlier by a Texas House
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, before his public comments, apparently hadn't
lifted a finger to get the bill passed, people on both sides of the
issue said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel chairman, who voted against the bill, said the
governor had never told him he supported it. Bush's statement also
surprised supporters of the measure, which would require instant
criminal background checks of people buying firearms from
unlicensed sellers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control is a hot-button issue in Republican Party politics.
And the governor's presidential aspirations have subjected him to
increasing criticism this year for failing to take stands on
specific pieces of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Although he endorsed the concept of instant criminal background
checks at gun shows, he didn't say he supported a specific bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, the House sponsor, laughed when a
reporter asked if the governor had made any effort to advance her
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   She said she learned of Bush's interest only when she read about
his comments ``after the vote to kill the bill occurred in
committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas, the Senate sponsor of a similar
measure languishing in a Senate committee, challenged the governor
Monday to take an active role in trying to revive the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor, given his popularity in the state of
Texas, has the power to resurrect that bill,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said the governor's office was
monitoring Danburg's bill, which ``had some flaws in it and died in
committee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our priority in this area this session is a bill that would
require automatic detention for juveniles who commit crimes with
guns,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   That measure has been approved by the House and is pending in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Butts, spokeswoman for Texans Against Gun Violence, also
called on the governor to lobby for the background check measure,
which also is supported by a number of law-enforcement agencies but
is opposed by the National Rifle Association and the Texas State
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vote in the House Public Safety Committee was 6-2
against the bill, with one member absent, and an attempt to reverse
the vote would be difficult, Butts said her group isn't giving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough vote for some of the people on that
committee,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There was ``no doubt'' the governor could have swayed some votes
the other way if he had called committee members, she added. All
but one of the votes against the bill were cast by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The House Public Safety Committee rejected Danburg's gun show
bill, House Bill 1199, late Tuesday night, the same evening that
news of the school shooting in Littleton, Colo., which left 15
people dead, was rocking the country.
</P>
<P>
   The next afternoon, Bush held a news conference to comment on
the Colorado shooting, which he called a ``tragic moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Answering reporters' questions, Bush said he supported instant
criminal background checks, which the federal Brady Law already
requires of people who purchase firearms from licensed dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The Brady requirement, however, doesn't apply to purchases from
unlicensed people at gun shows, a loophole that Danburg's and
West's bills would attempt to close in Texas. The background checks
wouldn't be required of buyers who are law-enforcement officers or
who hold state handgun licenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think about instant background checks at gun
shows?'' one reporter asked Bush in a follow-up question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support that,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation say it is necessary to clamp down
on felons who purchase weapons at gun shows. According to some
reports, one of the guns used in the Littleton shooting may have
been purchased at a gun show in Colorado by a friend of one of the
two students who shot up the school.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents argue that the proposal is an unnecessary
infringement on gun ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation is simply another step toward the desire by
those who oppose law-abiding citizens the right to own firearms,''
said Randy Gibson, executive director of the Texas State Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Turner, D-Coleman, chairman of the House Public Safety
Committee, said the governor's post-Littleton comments were ``a bit
of a knee-jerk reaction probably.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To this moment, the governor has never talked to me about the
bill,'' said Turner, who voted against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bush) never called me. His staff here who work with us in
the House every day, all day have never visited with me at all
about the bill,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said background checks at gun shows would take too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few enough phone lines, usually, at a gun show until
a two-day gun show could run into a two-week gun show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Butts said background checks usually don't take much time. They
would have to be conducted by someone with a federal firearms
license in a phone call to a computerized data center. She said
each gun show usually includes several licensees who could place
the calls.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said he still opposed the bill. But he said he would
allow the committee to reconsider the measure if Danburg convinces
him enough members have changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ken Armbrister, D-Victoria, chairman of the Senate Criminal
Justice Committee, said he also opposed the gun show proposal. And,
in light of the House committee vote, he said he didn't plan to
grant West a hearing on his companion measure, Senate Bill 1566.
</P>
<P>
   Armbrister said he hadn't heard anything about the bill from the
governor's office either.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Turner, other Public Safety Committee members who voted
against Danburg's bill were Reps. Leo Berman, R-Tyler; Bill Carter,
R-Fort Worth; Suzanna Gratia Hupp, R-Lampasas; Phil King,
R-Weatherford; and Terry Keel-R-Austin, a former Travis County
sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Roberto Gutierrez, D-McAllen, and Manny Najera, D-El Paso,
voted for the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Driver, R-Garland, was absent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
