<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WARNS ARAFAT AGAINST DECLARING PALESTINIAN STATEHOOD
</HEADLINE>
   (With ISRAEL-BARAK) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of a meeting of the Palestinian
policy-setting body in Gaza, President Clinton on Monday warned
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat against unilaterally declaring
Palestinian statehood but edged toward support for eventual
independence for the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
   In a public statement and a private letter, Clinton said that a
Palestinian call for full independence that was not the product of
negotiations with Israel was certain to set back the already
faltering Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton went further than he has before toward endorsing an
eventual Palestinian state. ``We support the aspirations of the
Palestinian people to determine their own future on their own
land,'' Clinton said in a letter to Arafat that was delivered on
Monday night. Previously, the president has said only that he
supports the right of Palestinians to ``live free today, tomorrow
and forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also set a one-year target date for completion of
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians on fundamental
issues of security, territory and the disposition of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, speaking to reporters in Gaza on Monday night, called
the Clinton letter ``more than positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli leaders, nearing the end of a bitter national election
campaign, issued a threat on Monday to annex territory slated to be
turned over to the Palestinians if the Palestinian Central Council
issues a statehood declaration at its meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Netanyahu, facing a fierce challenge from Ehud Barak,
the Labor candidate, has made opposition to Palestinian statehood a
central plank of his re-election platform.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted on Monday that the transitional period of autonomy
for the Palestinians of the West Bank and Gaza will expire on May 4
with many of the most difficult issues dividing Israel and the
Palestinian people still unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the United States was prepared to convene a new set
of peace talks within six months after the Israeli elections are
completed in early June in order to address outstanding questions,
including the status of Jerusalem, security relations between
Israel and the Palestinian entity and regional water rights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on both sides to abide by existing agreements and
to complete the so-called final status talks within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Israelis and Palestinians are to reach an agreement, it is
essential that they do their part to create a serious, fair and
credible environment for negotiations,'' the White House said in a
statement on Monday afternoon. The document called on Palestinians
to curb terrorism, and on Israelis to cooperate with Palestinian
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furthermore, Palestinians and Israelis must avoid unilateral
acts and declarations that prejudge or predetermine issues reserved
for permanent status negotiations,'' the statement continued.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the document was an unambiguous
message to both sides to abide by agreements already signed, cool
their rhetoric and return to the bargaining table immediately after
the Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
   David Bar-Illan, Netanyahu's chief spokesman, said that
Washington had offered little of substance at a delicate time. And
that is perfectly fine with Jerusalem, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very satisfactory, and there is not much new in it,''
Bar-Illan said on Monday night. ``It reaffirms many things we've
been insisting on. There's nothing here that we can raise an
objection to. There's nothing here that exceeds what's been said
before and has been accepted by Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House statement and Clinton's letter to Arafat were
seen in Israel as an American ladder that will enable Arafat to
climb down from his threat to declare independence on May 4.
Israeli officials expressed the hope that Arafat would refrain from
calling for a declaration of statehood in return for the American
commitments to hold Israel to its pledges under agreements reached
at Madrid, Oslo and Wye Mills, Md.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
