<HEADER>
A4053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-COX     04-26 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shooting suspect wrote of kamikaze-type suicide, police say
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo._Police released a friend of one of the
Columbine High School shooting suspects on Monday after questioning
her about whether she helped purchase guns for the deadly attack.
Officials said that she is not a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also said that a diary kept by one of the teen
killers indicated they hoped to murder as many as 500 people at
their school and in their neighborhood, then hijack an airplane,
which they would crash into New York City in a fiery kamikaze act.
</P>
<P>
   The chilling revelations came as this shaken town approached the
one-week anniversary of the nation's deadliest school shooting, in
which Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, gunned down 12
classmates and a teacher before taking their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Monday that toxicology tests on the suspects
indicated neither had ingested drugs or alcohol before the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of investigators continued scouring the school building
and grounds for clues, interviewing the suspects' friends and
witnesses and reviewing tapes from the school's security cameras.
</P>
<P>
   But questions about police handling of the rampage also
continued to surface.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of Harris said police did nothing after they filed a
March 1998 complaint that Harris had threatened to kill their son.
</P>
<P>
   The Brown family told a deputy that Harris made verbal threats
and posted messages on his Internet site that named their son and
read: ``I am the Law. If I don't like what you do, you die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The police department was handed this on a silver platter and
they did nothing,'' said Judy Brown, whose son Brooks was a boyhood
friend of Harris but grew distant when they reached high school.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns, who kept a copy of their official police complaint,
called deputies eight separate times to follow up after Harris made
the threat and threw ice that broke their son's car windshield, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County Sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis said he was
aware of the complaint, but that deputies receive hundreds like it
each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it was overlooked,'' Davis said. ``We receive
so many calls like that. We try to check out the ones we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis also addressed criticism that police acted too slowly and
did not pursue the killers aggressively enough.
</P>
<P>
   The family of slain teacher Dave Sanders, who bled to death in a
classroom where he lay for three hours despite frantic cell phone
calls from students with him, have questioned whether he might have
been saved by quicker police action.
</P>
<P>
   Davis admitted that the gunmen may have killed themselves a
short time after the melee began at 11:15 a.m. Police did not find
their bodies until around 4 p.m., after more than three chaotic
hours. A detailed time line of the incident is still being
prepared, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very possible it was a short time from when the shooting
started to when the suspects killed themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis also said he believes police saved many lives, perhaps
hundreds. The school's police resource officer returned fire within
minutes of the attack, and officers acted heroically to get
hundreds of kids out of the school. In light of the killers' diary,
police may also have saved lives in the surrounding neighborhood by
keeping the suspects from expanding their rampage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that perhaps a major catastrophe was averted by the
police actions that were taken,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis would not reveal the name of the suspect's friend who was
questioned. He confirmed local media reports that the 18-year-old
woman was Klebold's girlfriend and that she was questioned about
buying a machine pistol and a semi-automatic carbine rifle for the
boys.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the day, Sgt. Jim Parr, another spokesman, wouldn't
say whether she was a girlfriend or what the questioning was about.
</P>
<P>
   Both spokesmen said the woman is not a suspect and that no
arrests are imminent.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities said more arrests may follow, especially if they
find that others helped by buying weapons or building or
transporting bombs. The helpers would've had to be aware of the
plotters' criminal intent, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly believe that more than two were aware of it,''
said Jefferson County District Attorney David Thomas. ``Whether or
not more than two were involved, that's the essence of our
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   As the investigators worked, more funerals were held for the
victims, including students Cassie Bernall, Lauren Townsend and
Daniel Rohrbough.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend was an honor student and the school's volleyball team
captain. Rohrbough reportedly was killed as he held a door open for
other fleeing students. Bernall was singled out when she told the
killers she believed in God.
</P>
<P>
   A service for teacher Dave Sanders was also held, drawing
several thousand tearful mourners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have positively influenced more lives than we can ever
count,'' said Angela Sanders, recalling her dad's long teaching
career and his heroism in herding students to safety during the
rampage. ``You are truly a hero and will never be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
