<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-PARENTS-2     04-26 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-PARENTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY IT WILL BE HARD TO CHARGE PARENTS OF GUNMEN WITH A
CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (With COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING) 
(sw) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno and Gov. Bill Owens of Colorado have
suggested that if the parents of the teen-age gunmen at Columbine
High School had any hint of their plans and had failed to act, the
parents might be held criminally responsible for the young men's
actions.
</P>
<P>
   But if the parents were criminally charged for the killings,
legal experts say, such a case would be extremely difficult to
prove. American law generally holds people responsible for crimes
only if they actively participate, aiding and abetting in a
homicide, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every tragedy like this there is always the instinct to
find someone to blame, but the reality is there are serious legal
obstacles to simply venting community outrage,'' said Peter
Arenella, a professor of criminal law at the University of
California in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those principles,'' Arenella continued, ``is that
parents are not legally responsible for the criminal acts of their
children unless they were aware they were going to commit such acts
and failed to stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson County sheriff, John P. Stone, highlighted the
attention on the parents of the two gunmen, Eric Harris, 18, and
Dylan Klebold, 17. Stone said on Saturday that a sawed-off shotgun
and bomb-making materials were found in plain sight in one of the
boy's rooms. ``Parents should be held accountable for their kid's
actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Russell, a spokeswoman for the Jefferson County district
attorney, David J. Thomas, said on Monday that investigators ``will
look at everyone.'' But Ms. Russell added that there was no
evidence that the parents of the teen-agers were involved and that
they were not suspects at this point. Because homicide and similar
crimes are generally state crimes, the decision on whether to
charge the parents would most likely be made by Colorado
law-enforcement officials, not by federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   American legal rules generally require prosecutors to prove that
a defendant had the intent to participate in a crime in order to be
found guilty of a crime. Although there is a special relationship
between parents and their children, legal experts say, the courts
have not said that parents should be held criminally responsible
for their children's acts simply because they are parents.
</P>
<P>
   The facts that are known so far about the two Columbine killers'
families, several legal experts say, do not suggest that the
parents had enough specific knowledge that a massacre was being
planned to make an obvious case against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just too complicated a world to begin blaming parents
under criminal statutes for the behavior of their children,'' said
Martin Guggenheim, an expert in juvenile justice at New York
University School of Law. ``There isn't the kind of direct
connection between parental behavior and a child's wrongdoing to
justify punishing parents criminally for a child's wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   To impose such criminal responsibility, Guggenheim and other
experts said on Monday, would bring government into family
relationships and could press parents to become informers on their
own children.
</P>
<P>
   Charles J. Aron, a juvenile justice lawyerin Chicago, said that
in 25 years of law practice he had not heard of an effort to hold
parents criminally responsible for an act like the Columbine
attack. That, Aron said, was because prosecutors recognize that
teen-agers are often well beyond the control of their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``At what point do you draw the line?'' Aron asked. ``If Charles
Manson's parents are still alive, should they be imprisoned?''
</P>
<P>
   Owens and Reno each said over the weekend that law-enforcement
officials should determine what the gunmen's parents knew or should
have known and ``take appropriate steps,'' as Reno said. Owens said
the parents could face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no shortage of signs'' of what the two teen-agers
were planning, the governor said. There are many possible legal
claims under both civil and criminal law that could be lodged
against the parents. Across the country in recent years, increasing
numbers of suits have sought to impose civil damages on parents of
children who commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say such suits in Colorado could seek unlimited civil
damages claiming that the parents of the two teen-agers were
negligent in their supervision of the young men and ``knew or
should have known'' about the stockpile of arms and bomb-making
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Many states, including Colorado, have parental responsibility
laws that make parents liable for moderate damages even if they did
not know about malicious acts of their children, like vandalism.
Colorado limits damage verdicts under that law to $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   About half the states have enacted such parental responsibility
laws. In some states, thousands of parents have been fined,
sentenced to counseling or to a few days in jail for failing to
supervise their delinquent children.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado lawyers said on Monday that there are several state
criminal laws under which charges could be filed against the
parents for crimes less serious than responsibility for the
killings. Those laws include a provision that makes it a violation
for an adult to permit a juvenile to possess a firearm if the adult
knows there is a ``substantial risk'' that the youth will use it to
commit a felony. Such charges could subject the parents to
imprisonment for two-to-six years if they were convicted.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said that it was theoretically possible for a
parent to be charged with more serious crimes, like accessory to
murder or reckless homicide when a child commits a crime.
</P>
<P>
   But they said prosecutors would need much more evidence than a
shotgun or explosives found in a boy's room to charge the parents
with culpability for the deaths. Because of the pervasiveness of
guns in Colorado, several lawyers said, the presence of the shotgun
might not cause a reasonable parent to conclude that a crime was
being planned.
</P>
<P>
   H. Richard Uviller, a professor of criminal law at Columbia
University Law School, said prosecutors would have to prove that
the parents actually knew about whatever explosive materials were
discovered among their son's possessions. In addition, Uviller
said, information that Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold were involved
with violent Web sites would not necessarily help a prosecutor make
a case against their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Uviller said, ``is a long way from presenting an
immediate threat to another human being.''
</P>
<P>
   In Denver on Monday, some lawyers said that they, like many
people, were wondering about the responsibility of the parents of
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. Something must have gone wrong in
those relationships, several of them said. But whatever went wrong,
they said, the questions raised by the Columbine attack were not
necessarily questions for which the criminal law could provide
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How this could happen is to me outrageous and inexplicable,''
said Jeffrey Springer, a Denver criminal defense lawyer. ``But is
that a crime? Not in this state. Being an irresponsible parent who
has blinders on is not a crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
