A4068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBERS-COX     04-26 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teens arrested after taking bomb to Atlanta schoolyard
 &HT;    By Will Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three boys arrested for possession of a pipe bomb on
school property learned how to make the explosive by browsing the
Internet, according to testimony at a court hearing on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident prompted some parents to keep their children out
Mt. Bethel Elementary School in suburban Atlanta, and authorities
to send a bomb-sniffing dog through the building.
</P>
<P>
   While the youths still face harsh penalties for making the
device, authorities said they intended no harm. ``I don't want this
to be a knee-jerk reaction to the events in Colorado,'' said Cobb
County District Attorney Pat Head.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors agreed to allow the boys to return home with their
parents and be placed under house arrest rather than spend the next
few weeks in the Cobb County Youth Detention Center. They must
remain under constant adult supervision, have no access to the
Internet and may not communicate with each other while the case is
still pending, Juvenile Court Judge James F. Morris ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the boys are 14, and one is 15. They made their court
appearance dressed in shackles and orange jail overalls that were
too big. One of the three is a high school freshman in Cobb County
and has been suspended pending an investigation by school
administrators. The other two attend Atlanta Country Day School in
nearby Sandy Springs, a private school.
</P>
<P>
   The pipe bomb was one of several ``copycat'' incidents in metro
Atlanta that have drawn increased attention since the school
killings in Colorado. Four high school students from North Atlanta
have been arrested for blowing up a mailbox at a nearby elementary
school. The milk-jug bomb used water and dry ice and exploded
shortly after midnight Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the incident at Mt. Bethel, two people walking on a path
noticed what appeared to be a pipe bomb about 30 yards from the
school building. The bomb was made from half-inch diameter PVC pipe
six to eight inches long. Packed inside were small, black
brickettes the detective identified as rocket motor fuel. Finishing
nails were scattered on the ground near the pipe. The bomb had no
cap on it, but the end of the pipe was burned as if someone had
tried to detonate it.
</P>
<P>
   While walking the grounds in search of other devices, Det.
Dwayne Morris came upon the three boys huddled around a tree stump.
``They had stuff in their hands and put it right back down on the
stump,'' Morris said. ``They said, `We just found this stuff.'''
</P>
<P>
   The ``stuff'' turned out to be two sets of rocket motors
identical to the fuel found in the PVC pipe, two bottles of nail
polish remover _ which can be used as an accelerant in a bomb
because it is so flammable _ a box of cigars, a yo-yo and a
cigarette lighter.
</P>
<P>
   When questioned, one of the boys admitted that they had tried to
detonate the pipe bomb the previous day and left it.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,130 students at Mt. Bethel Elementary School, about 280
failed to attend Monday _ three times the normal absentee rate. To
allay parents' fears, Cobb County police took a bomb-sniffing dog
to the campus after students were dismissed for the day. No more
explosives were found.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, between 50 to 75 parents attended a meeting with
school administrators. ``It was three kids doing a stupid thing at
a real stupid time,'' said Mt. Bethel PTA president Bonnie Brand.
``Two weeks ago it probably would have been written off as a very
bad prank.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Anderson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
