<HEADER>
A4072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-     04-26 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS COURT SOUTH AFRICA'S TRIBAL CHIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TZANEEN, South Africa _ Tony Leon, the head of South Africa's
liberal Democratic Party, a man with the slight lockjaw accent of
those educated at this country's best English-style boarding
schools, came here recently to pay homage to Chief Samuel Mpumulana
Muhlava II and to make his pitch to the Tsonga people who live
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign bus rattled up the dirt road and stopped before the
run-down meetinghouse where a group of traditional dancers with
drums and sheepskin anklets were ready to greet him here, 225 miles
northeast of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Leon's speech was thick with deference to Muhlava and skirted
the rather thorny issue of how exactly you reconcile democracy with
chieftainships, which are, after all, usually passed from father to
son.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa, said Leon after he had removed his suit jacket and
striped tie in the sweltering heat, needed to ``carve a niche'' for
traditional leaders where they could continue to be ``the voice of
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon is not the only South African politician rushing down
unpaved roads to see the chiefs these days.
</P>
<P>
   With little time left before the second post-apartheid elections
on June 2, the newspapers are suddenly awash with pictures of
politicians wearing beads and emphasizing the importance of
protecting ``the old ways.''
</P>
<P>
   For many chiefs, the sudden attention is more than welcome.
Since the 1994 elections, traditional leaders _ many installed and
sustained by apartheid authorities because they did what they were
told _ have hovered at the margins of the new order, grumbling at
their lack of official status, power and pay.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling African National Congress continues to study what
exactly its policy will be regarding the 700 traditional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But it did decide last month, in time for the election, that
they were entitled to hefty raises, pensions and medical benefits.
They will all be paid about $1,000 a month, a very good salary by
South African standards and about twice what they were getting
before, though salaries varied widely.
</P>
<P>
   While their role in a democracy may be hard to figure out, there
can be little doubt that the chiefs continue to hold enormous sway,
particularly in the rural areas, where they function much as they
did before democracy: doling out land, settling disputes and
punishing those who break traditional law.
</P>
<P>
   They are no doubt capable of delivering hundreds of thousands of
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last four years, the government has basically tried
to avoid the problem of traditional leaders,'' said Sean Jacobs, a
political analyst with the Institute for Democracy in South Africa,
a nonprofit research group. ``But now they are out talking to them,
and it's all about the election.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to raise the chiefs' salaries touched off protests
from some of the opposition parties, including Leon's. ``The DP
finds this transparent move a dishonest ploy at taxpayers'
expense,'' proclaimed Wessel Nel, a Democratic Party Member of
Parliament, shortly after the announcement. ``In our opinion, the
very idea of remunerating individuals merely by virtue of cultural
status is objectionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon, however, did not bring this up with Muhlava, who soon made
clear that he expected Leon to insure that he and his subchiefs got
their money. He also made clear that he wanted some running water
and electricity in the ramshackle settlement his people live in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just now, if Tony Leon wants water, this is the last I have,''
the chief said, pointing to a pitcher beside the podium. ``I had to
go 10 kilometers for that. I pity for you if you all be thirsty
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the intense focus on the chiefs is that
South Africa's newest party, the fast-growing, multiracial United
Democratic Movement, has been wooing them for months. The party is
led by Bantu Holomisa, who was thrown out of the African National
Congress for insubordination, and Roelf Meyer, who was pushed out
of the largely white-supported former National Party because of his
reformist views.
</P>
<P>
   Holomisa comes from the Eastern Cape province, much of which is
still under the control of Xhosa chiefs, and he is said to use his
skills well there. When polls began to show that Holomisa was
making huge inroads in this area, ANC officials began to fight
back. A recent poll suggests that the Congress, which is expected
to win the election but is pushing for a two-thirds majority, may
have reclaimed some of its support.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, both Mandela and his deputy, Thabo
Mbeki, who is virtually certain to become the next president, have
visited tribal leaders and attended showy ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Mandela once again married Graca Machel, the
former first lady of Mozambique, whom he married at his
Johannesburg home last year. This time he went through a
traditional ceremony in his own Eastern Cape village, Qunu. Mrs.
Machel, who is a lawyer and is active in children's rights, wore a
traditional Xhosa outfit with face paint and underwent rituals to
make her a full member of Mandela's Tembu clan.
</P>
<P>
   Well-wishers included at least a dozen Cabinet members. ``Any
great man who is not in touch with his culture is like a thin piece
of paper dangling in the air,'' said the sports minister, Steve
Tshwete.
</P>
<P>
   The following weekend Mandela and several other top ANC
officials were present as Patekile Holomisa, a half brother of
Bantu Holomisa and a member of the Congress, was installed as chief
of the Gebe.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela told the crowds that South Africa needed to marry its
traditional authority and its newfound democracy if the country was
to be successfully rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has demonstrated its faith in traditional
leaders,'' Mandela said, ``and acknowledged the role they could
play in building a nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But some experts expect the oratory to fade away after the
elections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The chiefs, in part because they were dependent on the money
that the apartheid machinery doled out, do not have a long history
of supporting the liberation movement and are often looked at with
some suspicion by the African National Congress. In some parts of
the country, like KwaZulu/Natal, they have also traditionally
supported another black-led party, the Inkatha Freedom Party.
Moreover, the traditional leadership does not sit well with many of
the young.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1994 elections, the chiefs have been given a national
council, which has advisory powers and is supposed to promote the
role of traditional leadership within a democratic constitution.
But what their future role will be in local community government
and in distributing farming and water rights on tribal land remains
in question. A draft bill could be ready by next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ANC is not really embracing `Let's protect our
traditions,''' said Lew Elias, the news editor of Daily Dispatch,
the biggest daily newspaper in the Eastern Cape. ``They are just
trying to make the best of it in an election year. Holomisa was
talking to the chiefs months ago, and suddenly they realized the
damage he had done, so they got moving.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
