<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTH-BALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Darkness is beauty: That's all, Goths say
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Want to get a handle on a party's
patrons? Ask the bartender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the crowd,'' said Kelley Howley, scanning a room full
of black-clad people wearing chokers and eyeliner. ``They're good
tippers and very friendly, although scary-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   The occasion: the Bewitching Hour Ball, held Friday night at
Respectable Street Cafe as part of the night club's 12th
anniversary activities.
</P>
<P>
   The event drew several dozen Goths, followers of a lifestyle
that was connected _ unfairly, they say _ to the two young men in
last week's Littleton, Colo., shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Those guys weren't Goths, and we're nothing like them, said Ken
Collins, a 23-year-old chef from Lake Worth, Fla. with black
lipstick and a smile. ``We're peaceful, quiet, calm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The partygoers did the normal club thing _ drinking beers,
gabbing in groups in the courtyard and taking over the dance floor.
They danced dreamily by themselves to a growly, male version of
Madonna's ``Like a Prayer'' and moshed mildly to Iggy Pop's ``Lust
for Life.''
</P>
<P>
   A 45-year-old woman, a horse trainer who would not give her
name, took a short break and sat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I'm in a nightgown,'' she said, pointing to her white
lace dress. ``No one bothers me. But if I go to (another local bar)
dressed like this, the guys would be humping my leg like a dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last group to see a fight in, you know what I
mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some were nervous after the week's events. Angelina no
last name, owner of the Sepulchre boutique in Lake Worth and the
ball's sponsor, decided, for the first time, to leave her 1972
hearse at home.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Spear, 19, of Jupiter, Fla. came in a black outfit and
found himself, like others, trying to explain the Goth culture in a
breath or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like any other group out there,'' he said. ``I was gonna
wear a trenchcoat to prove a point, but I was afraid I was gonna
get my (rear end) kicked.''
</P>
<P>
   And what group would the Littleton shooters fit into? ``I would
say ... freaks?''
</P>
<P>
   Defining a typical Goth is as tough as defining, say, a long
black coat, a popular clothing choice because, while women can find
long dark dresses, it's hard for a guy to find clothes that fit the
Goth image, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Mormon greatcoat,'' one said of his outerwear. ``A
military jacket,'' said another. Or ``a velvet opera coat.''
</P>
<P>
   So what do Goths stand for? ``I just like dressing up,'' said
Cassandra Croy, 21, of Boynton Beach, wearing a full-length ball
skirt and a cropped, beaded bodice. ``I find beauty in darkness,''
said Spear, who says he particularly likes cathedrals. ``There's
just an attitude to it, an artistic point of view,'' said Reza
Beha, a 27-year-old computer programmer from Deerfield Beach. ``I
like the way it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrieann Preston, a 19-year-old waitress from Wellington,
walked up. ``Goths are not about hatred,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She started describing a recent Goth convention she attended in
New Orleans. About 1,000 people were there for music (try Bauhaus
and The Cure), author signings (Anne Rice is good Goth reading) and
a masquerade ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there was a Goth Easter-egg hunt,'' she said. ``They gave
away stuffed bunnies with vampire teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Goth humor,'' Collins explained.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's main event, a best-dressed contest, was
interrupted when a guy climbed on stage and drew a razor blade
several times across his stomach in a promotional stunt for his
band.
</P>
<P>
   The staff at Respectable's immediately kicked him out. Goths on
the sidewalk looked at him in disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Said one, ``You might want to get some Bactine for that ... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bactine is for wusses,'' the guy said.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... and some help, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
