<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY ISSUES PUSH NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P TO RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rising technology shares pushed the Nasdaq and the
S&AMP;P 500 to records Monday, but the activity was sedate compared
with last week's hectic pace.
</P>
<P>
   Computer shares helped to lead the charge, as stocks like IBM
rose for a fifth consecutive session after an industry report
showed that first-quarter shipments of personal computers rose more
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   IBM was responsible for nearly half of the 28.92 point gain in
the Dow Jones industrial average. The blue-chip index closed at
10,718.59, up three-tenths of a percent. The gain in the Dow left
the average below its record of 10,727.20, set on Thursday. But the
other two market gauges rose to new peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Led by a surge in America Online, the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index gained 3.19 points, or two-tenths of a percent, to
1,360.04. And the Nasdaq composite index, lifted by companies like
Microsoft and Intel, jumped 61.36 points, or 2.4 percent, to
2,652.05. The Nasdaq, which sustained one of its worst sell-offs
ever a week ago, is up 21 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market was very quiet, but technology had a good bid due
to IBM and anticipation of earnings from a number of Internet
companies,'' said Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I continue to believe that technology will be a strong
leadership factor in our market,'' Clark added. ``Without a strong
technology sector, it is hard to imagine a strong overall market.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action provided mixed signals about market breadth, an
indication that stocks outside of a few key sectors are doing
better.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, the number of stocks that fell
in price outnumbered those that rose. But on the Nasdaq, more
stocks gained than fell in value. But there were positive
indicators.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller-company stocks gained 3.24
points, or seven-tenths of a percent, to 434.97. And a leading
small-cap analyst said conditions in the sector might be on the
verge of improving.
</P>
<P>
   In a fresh report, Satya Pradhuman, director of small-cap
research at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., noted that there had been a sharp
increase in mergers and acquisitions since the start of the year,
driven in large part by low market valuations for companies with
market capitalization of less than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, more than 200 deals involving companies of
that size were announced, Pradhuman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On average over the last decade, about 160 deals a year were
done in this part of the small-cap market,'' he said. ``The last
time we saw this much activity was in 1988 and 1989, which was at
the tail end of another small-cap bear market. This is very
positive, because it suggests that valuations have become relevant
again. If you have corporate clients looking for value, that
creates a floor'' under stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's session, however, was again dominated by technology.
Computer shares rose after a report from International Data Corp.,
a market research firm, said worldwide shipments of personal
computers rose 19 percent in the first three months of the year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   IBM jumped 10[, to a record 209~. The stock also gained on
speculation that Big Blue's board will approve a higher dividend
and a stock buyback program before its annual meeting, scheduled
for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism about earnings at America Online helped to power the
stock higher. The company, which is expected to report results for
its third quarter Tuesday, saw its share price surge 15, to 162.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, the biggest maker of software for personal computers,
gained 2, to 88. Intel, the big chip maker, gained 2 11/16, to 64
7/16. And Dell Computer rose 1 13/16, to 44 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in technology prices masked a sharp drop in
pharmaceutical and financial service company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, a Dow component, fell 1 1/16, to 134 5/16.
J.P. Morgan, another Dow stock, lost 5[, to 134 7/16. Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter slumped 4|, to 100]. And Merrill Lynch lost 3
3/16, to 87].
</P>
<P>
   Among drug stocks, Merck fell 1|, to 74. Johnson &AMP; Johnson
declined 1 9/16, to 100 3/16. And Pfizer lost 3, to 123 13/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
