u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATHFINDER-SHUTDOWN-N     04-26 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATHFINDER-SHUTDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME WARNER TO CLOSE ITS PATHFINDER WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that symbolizes a passage from the early experimental
era of the World Wide Web to a mature publishing platform, Time
Warner will shut down Pathfinder, its pioneering outpost in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   During the last five years the company's Time Inc. unit has
lumped together all of its magazines, including Time, Fortune,
Money and Entertainment Weekly, in Pathfinder, a single, massive
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The site will be phased out over the next six months, to be
replaced by so-called hub sites that combine related magazines,
features and links with the Web sites of other Time Warner
properties like CNN, CNNfn and other information and entertainment
properties. Each new hub will go after a more precisely targeted
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines will retain their individual home pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an evolution, and it follows the way consumers have
been using our sites,'' said Jeffrey Coomes, vice president of
marketing at Time Inc. New Media. Coomes said the decision to
dismantle Pathfinder was based on the fact that most consumers go
directly to the individual magazine sites and skip the Pathfinder
home page. He said the move was part of a long-term strategy
already in place. ``Now we're working on promoting individual
brands, like Time.com and Fortune.com, and their features and
functions,'' Coomes said.
</P>
<P>
   But the move, first reported Monday on CNET's News.com Web site,
comes late, industry analysts said. Lisa Allen, a senior analyst at
Forrester Research, a market research firm in Cambridge, Mass.,
said that Pathfinder's demise was about two years overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' she said. ``It is repurposed print content
online, and that just doesn't work. The success of a site like
Pathfinder is about creating a specific online entity. It doesn't
mean throwing up a group of magazines on one home page and having
people drill down to the magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1994, Pathfinder was one of the first corporate sites
to open on the Web. But it was dogged by problems, from the merely
technical _ like the initial lengthy download time that users found
frustrating, and a cluttered layout _ to those of a constantly
shifting management.
</P>
<P>
   Like any pioneer, Pathfinder bore a number of scars as the first
major publisher to face issues like intellectual property rights in
a free-for-all medium and the gamble of offering print content
online at the risk of hurting newsstand and subscription sales.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Pathfinder underwent a flurry of changes in management
and focus when it named as president Linda McCutcheon, a Time Inc.
vice-president of sales and marketing. Ms. McCutcheon resigned
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner spent more than than $15 million a year in
developing the site, said a former staff member. It was unclear how
much, if any, of that investment was recouped. No one at Time Inc
would comment on the costs or cash flow, said Graham Cannon, a
spokesman for Time Inc. New Media.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mooradian, a senior analyst at Jupiter Communications, said
Pathfinder had made a number of missteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them was burying all those wonderful consumer brands
like Time magazine and Fortune magazine under the URL Pathfinder,''
he said, referring to the Web address pathfinder.com. ``That was a
terrible mistake, because people had to learn what Pathfinder
was.''
</P>
<P>
   The bright side, Mooradian said, was that the demise of
Pathfinder ``is paving the path for much more editorial control and
the empowerment of the individual properties.''
</P>
<P>
   One way in which that individual empowerment may come about is
through electronic commerce. Most of the success on the Web is
attributed to sites that offer a combination of content and
commerce _ for example, when a user can read about the new Britney
Spears' CD on the Teen People Web site, then click on a picture of
the album cover and purchase it.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Time Warner announced in January the formation of
Time Warner E-Commerce to consolidate the company's current
direct-marketing efforts on the Web and introduce other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Pepe, the former president of the Time Inc. Business
Information Group _ which includes Fortune, Money, Your Company and
Mutual Funds magazine _ was named president of the e-commerce unit.
At the time, Pepe said he expected the magazine group's growth in
e-commerce to be big. ``We're beginning to create parallel,
complementary Web sites for our magazines that will provide new
ways to talk to our consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web audience, said Ms. Allen of Forrester Research, has ``a
different set of expectations. They look for utility and
convenience and savings, as well as content.'' She said that Time
Warner had recognized that the old publishing model of magazines is
different on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Online publishing blends content and commerce increasingly, as
if the old lines between edit and advertising are disappearing,''
she said. ``I'm sure that's a very tough nugget for traditional
publishers like Time Warner to stomach, but that's what's happening
on the Web.''
</P>
</TEXT>
