<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4088 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REYNOLDS-PRESIDENT-CO     04-26 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REYNOLDS-PRESIDENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reynolds and Reynolds announces hire of new president
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton-based Reynolds and Reynolds Co. said
Monday it has hired a senior IBM executive as its new president,
chief operating officer and likely successor to Chairman, President
and Chief Executive David R. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd ``Buzz'' Waterhouse headed International Business
Machines' new e-business services unit, a $700 million operation
with 3,000 employees that is being heavily advertised on television
and in print by Big Blue.
</P>
<P>
   Waterhouse officially joins Reynolds on Saturday and is in line
to succeed Holmes within five years when his employment contract
expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes with a lot of people on his side (to become chief
executive)'' of the $1.5 billion business forms and information
management company, said Holmes, 58.
</P>
<P>
   Waterhouse, 47, said, ``My plan is to learn more about Reynolds
and Reynolds and get my feet on the ground in Dayton and take it
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes is relinquishing the president's title he has held for
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analyst Greg Gieber, who follows Reynolds for Brown
Brothers Harriman, said ``On paper (Waterhouse) looks like a superb
choice . . . (The company) needs somebody who can take them into
the digital age.''
</P>
<P>
   In 26 years with IBM, Waterhouse has been IBM's general manager
for marketing and business development, director of strategy,
president of IBM's Asia Pacific Services Corp. and senior managing
director of IBM Japan. IBM's e-business unit is considered a key
part of the $78 billion company's growth strategy.
</P>
<P>
   IBM officials said the company's policy is to not comment on
personnel issues. But information technology industry analyst Sam
Albert of Sam Albert Associates said Waterhouse's departure is a
big blow to IBM. ``He was a key player in the services business,''
Albert said.
</P>
<P>
   Waterhouse said he was not job hunting or even interested in the
job when first approached. But after learning more about Reynolds,
he found it attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get phone calls two or three times a day from Internet
companies. I decided I didn't want to go into the Wild West or a
risky company or a direct competitor of IBM. Reynolds and Reynolds
is none of that,'' Water house said. He said he believes Reynolds
has a tremendous future.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said he started looking for a successor late last year.
Waterhouse's general management, international and e-commerce
experience makes him a good fit for Reynolds and he is capable of
turning the company into a real powerhouse information management
company, Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, who is building a house in Maine, said he might leave
the company before his employment contract expires. Holmes came to
Reynolds in 1984 after working for Nabisco Brands Inc. as general
manager and vice president of the snack food business.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said Waterhouse's arrival will not free up his schedule
for more community work. Holmes and his wife, Nancy, spearheaded a
fundraising campaign to transform Dayton's downtown riverfront into
a community showpiece. Holmes serves on the board of directors of
both NCR Corp. and DP&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   Waterhouse said he will move his wife, Lorraine; daughter, Lynn,
14; and son, Brian, 12, here this summer. The Erie, Pa., native
said he is looking forward to returning to the Midwest. He began
his IBM career 26 years ago in Youngstown.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
