<HEADER>
A4091 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-RESERVISTS-COX     04-26 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-RESERVISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reservists put in hours, keep planes going to conflict
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Two more military cargo jets left
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base Monday to support NATO's air
campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane crews are Air Force reservists volunteering for
extra duty, but even more reservists have been working quietly
behind the scenes at Wright-Pat to support the stepped-up activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more to it than the eight men and women in the
airplane,'' said Brig. Gen. Robert Duignan, commander of the 445th
Airlift Wing. ``For every one of them, there's probably a dozen''
working on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's departures _ one on a trip staying inside the United
States, the other bound for an unidentified staging base in Europe
_ brought to 16 the number of flights the wing has made since
February to haul military supplies for the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   For every flight, reservists have put in extra time scheduling
missions, fixing the big jets, and rigging their cargo holds for
whatever payloads are assigned to them.
</P>
<P>
   The wing is authorized for 18 C-141s, although it usually has
fewer in its fleet. Spokeswoman Sharon Erli said the wing has about
350 full-time workers and about 1,850 reservists.
</P>
<P>
   The full-time workers keep the wing operational and train the
reservists. But the Air Force has been turning to its reserve units
for extra airlift during the Kosovo conflict, and that has prompted
Duignan to ask reservists to put in extra duty.
</P>
<P>
   In a maintenance hangar, Tech Sgt. Steven Stiger and Senior
Airman Robert Caskey stood under the wing of a C-141 and drove
rivets into a pylon where an engine had been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Stiger works full-time for the wing as an Air Reserve
Technician, but Caskey is a reservist who works for Airborne
Freight Corp. in Wilmington. But for the last two months, Caskey
said, he's been been wearing his reserve stripes full-time.
</P>
<P>
   This duty is in addition to his usual 15 days of annual reserve
training, Caskey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go back to my civilian employer for two weeks, then come
back for my two weeks'' of reserve training, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the flight line, Staff Sgt. Nelson Scott was
troubleshooting a radio in one of the C-141Cs, the newest model
with upgraded avionics, a term for aviation electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, an avionics technician, said he's here from Glouster in
southeastern Ohio for his regular annual duty, but he's being
trained on the new electronics so he will be fully qualified in
case the wing is activated.
</P>
<P>
   Scott showed a quiet, serious pride in his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really glad that people are dying, but that's why
we're here. The ethnic Albanians are pretty defenseless,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is in the second month of its air attacks on Serb forces
that have routed hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians from
their homes in Kosovo. Refugees have said the Serbs are raping and
killing helpless civilians, destroying their documents and burning
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen Monday ordered 30 more Air Force
refueling aircraft deployed, and Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon
said reservists would be ordered to active duty within a few days
to fly the refueling planes and perform other support duties for
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The only refueling wing in Ohio is the Ohio Air National Guard's
121st Air Refueling Wing at Rickenbacker Air Force Base near
Columbus. Spokeswoman Denise Varner said no Ohio guard units have
been alerted to expect a callup.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
