<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ANCHOR-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOST OF BBC CRIME PROGRAM AND TV EVENING NEWS IS SLAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Jill Dando, a well-known BBC television news
broadcaster, was found murdered on Monday outside the front door of
her home in London.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dando, 37, had been a host of the BBC's ``Six O'Clock
News,'' a travel program and a show called ``Crimewatch'' that has
had success solving cases by graphically reconstructing crimes and
then enlisting the public in solving them by helping the police
identify suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Through her four-year association with the show, Ms. Dando had
become closely identified with crime fighting. Last year, she
reported being stalked by an obsessive fan, but the police on
Monday night discounted him as a suspect, saying he was working in
his garden at the time of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening, she had introduced a series called ``Antiques
Inspectors,'' and a picture of her standing in front of a
collector's-item car is on the cover of the current Radio Times.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland Yard said Ms. Dando died from a single gunshot wound in
the head. Two neighbors found her covered in blood on the doorstep
of her $700,000 home on Gowan Avenue in Fulham, Southwest London,
shortly before noon. She had just arrived in her car when she was
attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the street said they saw a man dressed in a suit
and carrying a mobile telephone rush away from the house at the
time of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   She was taken to Charing Cross Hospital where she was pronounced
dead early on Monday afternoon. Her body was identified by Dr. Alan
Farthing, a medical doctor she was to marry on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the police searched a stretch of the River
Thames, including the shoreline and shallow water near Putney
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1961 in Weston-Super-Mare in Southwest England, she
joined her hometown paper after high school graduation and five
years later moved into local radio and television. She came to
London in 1988 and began work for the BBC on its ``Breakfast Time''
news program.
</P>
<P>
   A BBC news reader, Jennie Bond, a friend and colleague who
specializes in covering the royal family, went on the air to
announce the slaying in a bulletin early Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a completely horrible thing to have to do,'' she said.
``I have never seen the BBC newsroom in a more somber state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
