<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CAPTIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED CROSS OFFICIAL MEETS WITH CAPTURED U.S. SOLDIERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Red Cross official met briefly Monday with three
U.S. soldiers held captive by the Serbs, and was promised a longer
meeting Tuesday that would include a medical examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to talk to them only a few minutes,'' Cornelio
Sommaruga said at news conference. ``We looked into each others
eyes and shook hands very warmly.''
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers _ Spc. Steven Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas;
Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; and Staff Sgt.
Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich. _ appeared to be
in relatively good condition, according to U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   Sommaruga, head of the International Committee of the Red Cross,
was allowed to see the soldiers before a meeting with Yugoslav
president Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, Milosevic had denied Red Cross access to the
soldiers, who were captured March 31 as they patrolled the
Macedonia-Kosovo border as part of a NATO unit stationed in
Macedonia. They were captured in the early days of the NATO air
campaign against Milosevic's Serb forces operating in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Red Cross chief had not been given advance notice
that he could see the soldiers, he clearly was prepared. A
spokesman for the International Red Cross, based in Switzerland,
said Sommaruga gave the POWs letters from their families.
</P>
<P>
   Both Red Cross and U.S. officials noted, however, that Monday's
meeting did not fulfill the Geneva War Conventions governing
prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   To comply with those rules, Red Cross doctors must be allowed to
give the soldiers a quick medical exam. Furthermore, Red Cross
officials must be permitted to interview the soldiers without
Yugoslav officials present.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said that Sommaruga had been assured that he could
return Tuesday and conduct a visit with the soldiers that complied
with the Geneva rules.
</P>
<P>
   It was anticipated that the soldiers would be allowed to reply
to the messages from their families.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers' families expressed relief about the first outside
contact with the men since they were captured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that we do have confirmation that
everyone appears to be in good condition,'' said Larry Fitzgerald,
speaking on behalf of Gonzales' parents, Gilbert and Rosie Gonzales
of Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gonzales family is very heartened by this news,'' said
Fitzgerald, a spokesman at the Texas Department of Criminal Justice
where the Gonzales also are employed. But Fitzgerald said the
family was awaiting additional details from the expected medical
examination.
</P>
<P>
   The Stone family also was buoyed by the news. Stone's wife is
from San Antonio,
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they are all right and they are doing well. The Red
Cross told us that Chris was very coherent,'' Lisa McKinney,
Stone's mother-in-law, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Stone's wife, Tricia, and their 4-year old son are living in San
Antonio with McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   While welcoming the initial contact, U.S. officials remained
firm that Milosevic comply with the rules regarding prisoners of
war.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin said ``our initial report
is that they were not permitted to meet privately with the
prisoners, as would be their normal practice. They were not
permitted to conduct a medical examination of the prisoners, but
that the prisoners appeared to be in relatively good condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said U.S. officials expect Tuesday's promised meeting with
the soldiers ``to take place in accordance with the Geneva
Conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon Spokesman Kenneth Bacon noted that a Serb soldier in
NATO custody has been allowed two visits by the Red Cross. That
soldier was captured April 16 by the Kosovo Liberation Army and
turned over to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there's been a radically different treatment by the allied
governments on the one hand, who have worked hard to comply with
the terms of the Geneva Convention, and the Yugoslav government,
which has not complied,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
