<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Lost Records Can Be Taxing
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I own some stock, but have lost the confirmation slip
showing when I bought it and what I paid. I tried to get the
information from my brokerage firm, but they didn't have it in
their records. I want to sell these shares, but I don't know how to
report the capital gain when income-tax time rolls around. Is there
any solution to this problem?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Internal Revenue Service spokesman Joe Calderaro
advises you to make ``the best reasonable estimate'' of your
purchase price and date. ``If the taxpayer makes that effort,
chances are we will go along,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   If you can pinpoint an approximate purchase date, your broker
will supply you with the stock's price range on that date.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, you won't have to figure the purchase date or price
if you decide instead to give your stock to charity. If you do
that, it won't matter _ to the charity, the IRS, or you _ how much
you paid or when. The only tax consideration will be the value of
your charitable deduction. That will be the market value of the
stock at the time it is transferred to the charity. You can claim
that amount as a deduction on your tax form.
</P>
<P>
   However, you can't eliminate the tax problem by giving the stock
to a family member or other individual, rather than to charity. If
you do that, you will merely be transferring the problem to the
recipient. That's because the recipient's cost basis for the stock
would have to be the same as yours _ whatever that may be.
</P>
<P>
   If you change your mind about selling the stock and hold the
shares until you die, the cost-basis problem will disappear along
with your other earthly woes. When the stock is passed to your
heirs, the cost basis changes to the value of the stock on the day
you died.
</P>
<P>
   IRA Contributions
</P>
<P>
   Q: I opened a Roth Individual Retirement Account last year.
Recently I also began participating in a 401(k) plan through my
employer, and I contribute the maximum allowable amount. Can I
continue contributing to the Roth IRA if I am maxing out my 401(k)?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Yes. Your 401(k) and any IRA you hold are independent.
What you contribute to one doesn't affect how much you are
permitted to contribute to the other.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you have more than one IRA account, you may
contribute a total of no more than $2,000 per year to all of them.
</P>
<P>
   You probably will want to contribute the entire $2,000 to your
Roth, because for tax purposes it is better than any other kind of
IRA. Any earnings from your Roth will accumulate tax-free. With
traditional IRAs, the earnings are taxed as ordinary income when
you withdraw the money.
</P>
<P>
   Stock Distribution
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently received shares of a company that was spun off
from another company. The parent company stated that this was a
``tax-free distribution.'' However, I have now sold the spun-off
shares. How do I report the proceeds from the sale on my tax form?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unfortunately, there isn't a simple answer to this question.
Every case is different, depending on the relative sizes of the
spun-off company and the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   A certain portion of the amount you invested in the parent
company became your cost basis for the spun-off company. What that
portion is I can't say, because you don't identify the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, when a company does a spin-off, it sends a letter to
its shareholders spelling out the proper tax treatment. If you
don't have any such letter, call the company headquarters and ask
for the investor relations department.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: You will have to report either a capital
gain or loss on the sale of the spun-off shares.
</P>
<P>
   If the value of the parent-company shares rose since you bought
them, then you will automatically have a capital gain on the
spun-off shares. If the value has gone down, you will report a
capital loss.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase date you should report on your tax form is the date
on which you bought the parent-company shares. If you owned the
parent-company shares for more than a year before selling the
spun-off shares, then your gain (or loss) qualifies as long-term.
If you invested in the parent company less than a year ago, then
your sale was short-term.
</P>
<P>
   For tax purposes, it doesn't matter how long you held the
spun-off shares themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
