<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP WANTS ADDITIONAL $5 BILLION FOR KOSOVO OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans are preparing to add $5 billion or more
in Pentagon programs to President Clinton's emergency request for
$6 billion in spending on the Balkans, key members of Congress said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to make Clinton's performance as commander-in-chief a
political issue in next year's elections, they have seized on
Pentagon spending as a hot issue.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked for $5.1 billion to pay for military operations,
and about $900 million in other funds, most of which would help
refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans contend the Pentagon faces other emergencies,
like the need for munitions and spare parts and for money to
maintain military depots and to conduct an expanded recruiting
drive. Many also want to add a pay increase for Pentagon personnel
to the emergency package.
</P>
<P>
   The additional billions would come from surplus Social Security
revenues, which both parties have said should be sacrosanct. The
use of an emergency appropriation allows lawmakers to add billions
of dollars from the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, has said
he wants a total package of no more than about $11 billion,
including a proposed Pentagon pay raise of more than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Jerry Lewis of California, who leads the defense panel
of the House Appropriations Committee, said in an interview that
the emergency bill being drawn up by House Republicans could reach
a total of $12 billion _ ``and it could go higher'' if a pay raise
is included. The raise would add between $2 billion and $3 billion
to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are real dollars, and they can be justified as an
emergency circumstance,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee, David
Obey of Wisconsin, said the Republican effort to add funding for
the Pentagon was ``the opposite of patriotism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Patriotism,'' he said, ``is taking what soldiers need and
getting it to them immediately. It's not pouring money into
military contracts for items we can't take off the shelf for two or
three years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate minority leader, Tom Daschle of South Dakota, said
the emergency spending bill might not pass if it becomes a
carry-all for other Pentagon programs. ``How you get from $6 to $12
billion is something that has a lot of us interested,'' he said.
``Until we see the specifics, I guess we won't decide on a
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   A proposed House bill for emergency spending will be drawn up by
Thursday, Lewis said. The final bill probably will emerge from a
conference next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
