<HEADER>
A4100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TROUTMAN-COX     04-26 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROUTMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business dispute between rock-funk pioneers may have lead to
deaths
 &HT;    By Lou Grieco and Wes Hills
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Roger and Larry Troutman, pioneers of the
rock-funk ``Dayton sound'' of the 1970s who died Sunday in a
murder-suicide, were involved in a family enterprise that had been
struggling financially for most of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Troutman Enterprises rode a wave of success with the family's
band Zapp, whose self-titled debut album hit the pop top 20 in
1980, then scored a major hit with the song More Bounce to the
Ounce. Roger Troutman eventually went solo, recording under the
name ``Roger.'' He hit No. 1 in 1987 with the single I Want to Be
Your Man.
</P>
<P>
   The company was established in 1980 by the five Troutman
Brothers _ Larry, Rufus, Roger, Lester and Terry.
</P>
<P>
   The business expanded in 1982 into rehabilitating older
properties and building new homes by hiring and training unskilled
people.
</P>
<P>
   The company suffered a downturn in the early 1990s when funding
fell through for a deal to build 25 homes, putting the corporation
in a ``cash crunch,'' according to U.S. Bankruptcy Court files.
</P>
<P>
   The company plunged into bankruptcy April 23, 1992, listing $3.8
million in debts and $414,800 owed in delinquent taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy case remains open. The last filing of Oct. 12,
1998, listed $7,299.72 in a money market account.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Betz, director of the Montgomery County Coroner's Office,
said the office did not know why the shooting occurred.
</P>
<P>
   However, Coroner James Davis said at a news conference the
shooting may have involved a business dispute between the brothers,
with Larry objecting to ``Roger going out on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger had recently jump-started his career, finding new
audiences with the song California Love , a Grammy-nominated
collaboration with hip-hop superstars Tupac Shakur and Dr. Dre. He
released a greatest-hits album in 1996 and apparently planned to
tour this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Roger was shot four times as he tried to leave Larry's car
Sunday morning, according to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Troutman then drove off and killed himself minutes later
with a single shot to the head, using the same. 357 Smith &AMP; Wesson
revolver whose shots killed his brother, the coroner's office
determined. The gun was recovered in Larry's Lincoln, which crashed
into a tree on the 2100 block of Harvard Boulevard. Larry Troutman,
54, was pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Troutman, 47, was found in an alley behind Catalpa Drive,
near the music studios his family owned, about 7:20 a.m. He died
later at Good Samaritan Hospital and Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered four gunshot wounds to the torso, two in the front
and two in the back, said Betz.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Troutman, brother of Roger and Larry, said Monday morning
he did not have any idea what happened between the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have none,'' he said, ``None whatsoever. We'll just have to
put it together and depend on the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester Troutman thanked the city of Dayton for support for the
family, both during its musical heyday and following Sunday's
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are grieving,'' he said. ``It's very, very hard for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements will not be made until today, Lester
Troutman said. He would not discuss the family's business affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy file showed a company with high aspirations
struggling to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troutman Enterprises maintains that the black community is a
vital resource that is often overlooked by both the private and
public sectors,'' states a brief filed by Dayton attorney Ruth A.
Slone. ``They have demonstrated that commitment by the hiring and
training of unskilled, and often hardcore, unemployed blacks into
all endeavors of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Moves to cut payroll and sell some real estate fell short.
</P>
<P>
   The $3.344 million in secured claims included $2.18 million in
mortgages on more than 50 parcels of real estate valued at $2.319
million, according to court records
</P>
<P>
   Creditors included Time Warner - $360,000; Warner Brothers
Records Inc. _ $870,000; First National Bank of Dayton _ $245,000;
and First National Bank of Southwestern Ohio _ $1.221 million. It
was also listed in 12 pending lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the U.S. government sought to have the bankruptcy
converted from reorganization to liquidation, citing delinquent
taxes, including $159,806 owed to the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 4, 1996, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Thomas F. Waldron
approved the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Originally part of Zapp, Larry left the band to devote himself
full-time to business matters. He was president of Troutman
Enterprises, and used the nickname ``Dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   He also got in trouble with the law in 1968, when he served 29
days of a 30-day sentence for assault and battery in his native
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Larry was fired in 1969 from the Frigidaire division of General
Motors, where he worked as an assembler, following a brawl with
company guards. He later said he fought with guards because they
wanted to search him as he left the plant, but wouldn't allow other
black workers to witness the search. ``Incidently, I won the
fight,'' he said in 1972, one year after he lost an appeal of the
firing.
</P>
<P>
   The company's report to an umpire said Troutman bit one guard's
hand, hit a second in the nose, and broke a plant foreman's
eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Troutman was one of seven people _ as was his brother
Rufus _ who were fired from the Shawen Acres Children's Home in
1975 following a Montgomery County Sheriff's Office investigation
into allegations of child abuse and excessive discipline. The seven
were reinstated in 1976. Larry Troutman was head of youth leaders
at the home.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Grieco and Wes Hills write for the Dayton Daily News,
Dayton, Ohio. Carol Simmons contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
