<HEADER>
A4105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNITED-MARKETPLACE-AR     04-26 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-MARKETPLACE-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: DISGRUNTLED SHAREHOLDERS UNITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Del., Mich.)  (Eds.: Please note that EQ in parentheses has been used in the 13th
graf instead of the equal sign, which is non-transmittable to some
newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic of is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a long way from cyberspace to Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   On an electronic message board on the Internet, shareholders of
United Companies Financial Corp. have been engaged for weeks in an
emotional ether-world debate over how to save their faltering
company, a high-risk lender in Baton Rouge, La., that filed for
bankruptcy protection on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for them, the company's fate is actually being
decided in the real world of U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington,
where a committee of powerful creditors _ banks and bondholders,
mostly _ is trying to retrieve the $1.3 billion the company owes
them.
</P>
<P>
   And however outspoken they may be in virtual reality,
shareholders typically stand at the end of the line in bankruptcy
court. By law the company's first obligation is to satisfy the
valid claims of its creditors. Frequently, stockholders can do
little but watch as their shares are canceled and new stock is
distributed to settle the company's debt.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet may be about to change that balance of power.
At least that is the hope of the group of United Companies
shareholders who have banded together in cyberspace to seek a voice
in the real-world negotiations in Delaware, where many companies
are incorporated because of its light regulatory touch and
efficient courts that enforce a well-established body of corporate
law.
</P>
<P>
   Their effort, being hailed by some as a first in shareholder
activism, could set the stage for a mammoth collision of cultures,
said Michael J. Venditto of Kensington &AMP; Ressler, a New York law
firm that does both bankruptcy work and Internet company
financings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bankruptcy doesn't proceed at the pace of cyberspace _ just
the opposite,'' Venditto said. While the Internet celebrates speed
and instant information, the slow and stately bankruptcy process is
deliberately designed to give a struggling company breathing space
to plan and meet with creditors. ``The two arenas are entirely
incompatible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Stoller, a professor of rhetoric at Northwestern
University in Evanston, Ill., and a leader of the message-board
activists, acknowledged that bankruptcy court was alien territory
for him. But he argued that the Internet's lightning pace was
exactly what allowed small shareholders to find one another quickly
and seek out the expertise they needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the electronic manifestation of Ben Franklin's famous
line that we must all hang together or we will surely all hang
separately,'' said the professor, who owns just under 60,000 shares
of United Companies stock.
</P>
<P>
   United Companies, a fixture in Baton Rouge, was a major player
in the once-exuberant ``subprime'' loan market, lending money at
high rates to borrowers who could not get more affordable loans
elsewhere and then selling packages of those loans to Wall Street
investors hungry to earn high yields.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's own cost of borrowing skyrocketed after Russia
defaulted on its debt last summer, which prompted investors to flee
the riskier corners of the credit market. By March, its cash-flow
problems were so severe that it filed for reorganization under
Chapter 11, reporting assets of about $1.3 billion and liabilities
of $1.25 billion. Now, its liabilities have risen to roughly $1.3
billion, while the realizable value of the company's assets has
probably shrunk.
</P>
<P>
   The company's increasingly visible problems have demolished the
price of its stock, some of which was owned by its employees
through an employee stock ownership plan. Shares that fetched as
much as $76 apiece in 1993 can now be had for less than 25 cents,
wiping out many employees' retirement savings and igniting a
firestorm of anger and suspicion among shareholders and employees
alike.
</P>
<P>
   That hostility flooded into a Yahoo message board, at
http://messages.yahoo.com/?action(EQ)q&AMP;board(EQ)UC. There,
investors and employees met to trade angry opinions, alarming
rumors and minute dissections of the latest news. But in the weeks
since the bankruptcy filing, the message-board participants have
done something far less common: Guided by Stoller, they have formed
what he calls an ``ad hoc alliance'' and persuaded a bankruptcy
lawyer, Michael D. Warner of Fort Worth, Texas, to represent the
group _ free, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Warner formally asked the Office of the U.S. Trustee
in Philadelphia, which oversees the Delaware bankruptcy process, to
give the shareholders a voice in the negotiations. He asked the
trustee to approve the formation of an equity committee, which
would be entitled to legal representation and could apply to the
court to recover its legal fees from the debtor.
</P>
<P>
   In his petition, Warner noted that he represented the holders of
2.1 million of the company's 28 million outstanding shares _ or
about 20 percent of the 10.4 million shares that are not owned by
insiders. According to Stoller, more than a hundred people have
stepped from behind their message-board aliases to enlist in the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Warner said he did not expect a decision until next week at the
earliest. If the answer is no, the shareholders can appeal to U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Mary Walrath in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, Warner arranged for a Delaware lawyer to appear on
behalf of the shareholders at a court hearing before Ms. Walrath
Monday in Wilmington to raise objections to the procedures the
company has proposed for auctioning off some of its assets. The
outcome of that hearing could not be determined Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Warner said that he was not aware of any other Internet chat
room or message board that has organized itself to play a formal
role in a bankruptcy case. ``I just wish the group had acted
sooner,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stoller acknowledged that shareholders waited too long to make
the shift from ``a purely cyberspace medium to one in which we were
starting to pull the levers that the three-dimensional world
provides.''
</P>
<P>
   But delay is just one of the hazards that lawyers and bankruptcy
experts see in the approach taken by Stoller's alliance. There's
also the risk of running afoul of federal securities laws.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a staff lawyer at the Securities and Exchange
Commission telephoned Aaron Brown, another leader of the ad hoc
alliance and a finance professor at Yeshiva University, to instruct
him about the disclosure requirements the SEC imposes on
shareholders who take collective action. Such groups typically are
required to file a form 13-D to inform the marketplace of their
agenda and their strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very friendly and helpful,'' Brown said. ``My
conclusion after talking to him is that we should file, and I'm
working on that now.''
</P>
<P>
   And a close reading of the message board in the weeks after the
bankruptcy shows that such forums provide an abundant opportunity
for misinformation and even manipulation, given the complexities of
bankruptcy and the highly illiquid market for bankruptcy stocks.
</P>
<P>
   United Companies was kicked off the New York Stock Exchange
after its bankruptcy filing, and its shares now trade only in the
electronic ``pink sheets,'' the OTC Bulletin Board. Posted messages
show that investors who were unfamiliar with this intensely
speculative and illiquid marketplace were nevertheless encouraged
by others in the group to buy more shares _ shares that their
anonymous advisers might actually have been selling.
</P>
<P>
   Many other investors have posted messages that reveal a profound
misunderstanding of the risks of buying stock in any bankrupt
company _ the chief one being that the shares will be rendered
worthless by the bankruptcy settlement. Moreover, United Companies,
like most bankrupt corporations, has not been able to file its
financial statements in a timely fashion, leaving investors to rely
on outdated quarterly statements from last September.
</P>
<P>
   Stoller and his supporters are not blind to these risks but say
that they are far outweighed by the way the Internet empowers the
shareholders of troubled companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we are not successful in Delaware, we will have done
something very important,'' Stoller said. ``We will have put this
management on notice that its actions are being closely observed.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the troubled company engaged the prominent
turnaround advisory firm of Jay Alix &AMP; Associates in Detroit and
hired Deborah Hicks Midanek, a seasoned turnaround manager, to
serve as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Midanek has been scrambling to find ways to cut the
company's overhead, complete its necessary financial audits and
preserve the value of the $6.5 billion portfolio of securitized
subprime loans in which it has a residual stake. She simply did not
have the time, she said, to monitor and respond to the outraged
postings on the message board.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Ms. Midanek had been a frequent target of angry
message board participants, including Stoller, who complained
bitterly that she did not respond to the group's demands for
information.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as shareholders are trying to step from cyberspace into
the courtroom, management apparently has become more conciliatory.
Indeed, Brown was scheduled to attend a meeting Tuesday in Baton
Rouge with Ms. Midanek and the company's top officers.
</P>
<P>
   The financial outcome of this campaign is still uncertain, and
some smart players in the takeover market are betting that there
will be little, if anything, left for shareholders after United
Companies settles its creditors' claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is struggling to keep body and soul together,''
said Christopher Beard, the publisher of the Turnaround &AMP; Workouts
newsletter in Washington. ``If that effort fails, there is nothing
left to fight over.''
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the outcome of this particular case, bankruptcy
experts are intrigued by its implications for organizing
shareholders in the bankruptcy process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to become the norm,'' Warner, the
lawyer, said. ``Thanks to the Internet, I think you'll see more
publicly traded cases where an equity committee is going to be
formed.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, several bankruptcy lawyers agreed, bankruptcy
negotiations could become longer, more complicated and more
expensive. But they also may become fairer, at least for a bankrupt
company's shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have someone looking out for a group that usually
doesn't have anyone looking out for them,'' Warner observed.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, Stoller's campaign is already being talked
about, at least in cyberspace. Last Wednesday, an anonymous
correspondent known as ``Stinger707'' posted a notice on the
message board for followers of United Companies. ``Word of your
hard work to have a voice in the affairs of your company is
spreading,'' the correspondent wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The writer said he was visiting from the message board for the
lackluster Sunshine Mining and Refining, whose participants have
grown frustrated with the company's puny stock price but who were
unsure how to make themselves heard. He invited someone from
Stoller's group to visit the Sunshine message board to ``outline
the steps that we should take to gain the attention of our
management.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
