<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, APRIL 27
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-SCI-FOSSIL-MAN-NYT (moved on Saturday, Apr. 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Apr. 24,
about evidence of interbreeding between Neanderthals and modern
humans omitted a passage at the continuation in some copies. The
affected paragraph should have read:
</P>
<P>
   ``The new discovery could, at long last, resolve the question of
what happened to the Neanderthals, the stereotypical stocky,
heavy-browed `cave men.' They may have merged with modern humans,
called Cro-Magnons, who appear to have arrived in Europe with a
superior tool culture. In that case, some Neanderthal genes survive
in most Europeans and people of European descent.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-ARIZ-DRUGS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Apr. 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Apr. 20,
about Arizona's policy of ordering nonviolent drug offenders into
treatment instead of jailing them misstated the cost. The state
spends $16.06 a day for probation supervision for each nonviolent
offender, but that figure does not include the cost of drug
treatment. The article also misstated the year voters approved the
policy. It was 1996, not 1998.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AUDREY-HEPBURN-IMAGE-NYT (move on Friday, Apr. 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Apr. 23,
about Audrey Hepburn's enduring influence on style and fashion
misstated the age at which she won an Academy Award as best actress
for her role in ``Roman Holiday.'' She was 24, not 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
