<HEADER>
A4111 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2TAKES-     04-26 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN MINISTER SAYS MILOSEVIC WILL MAKE CONCESSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mb) 
 By MICHAEL GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As an American envoy arrived here for talks on Kosovo,
Russia's foreign minister said Monday that President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia was prepared to make concessions, but that
NATO would also have to bend if the conflict was to be brought to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks of the foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, came a day
after President Boris Yeltsin of Russia telephoned President
Clinton about Kosovo, and coincided with the arrival of Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott to pursue the possibilities of
Russian mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ivanov did not proclaim any major breakthrough in an
hourlong interview, he laid down the cooperation that Russia
expected from both sides if it was to proceed as interlocutor. With
Milosevic still unbowed after more than a month of intensive
bombing, NATO and the United States have been seeking to involve
Russia, a country with traditional links to Yugoslavia, in the
search for a diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't serve as a postman. We won't deliver NATO's
ultimatums to Belgrade,'' Ivanov said. ``That is not our mission.
If there is an ultimatum from one side and then an ultimatum from
the other side there is no maneuver for negotiation. There should
be cooperation on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Offering a preview of what Milosevic was prepared to concede,
Ivanov said that the Yugoslav president was ready to reduce his
forces in Kosovo to the level they were at in October, before the
Serbian military began preparing for its offensive against ethnic
Albanians there. Ivanov said that Milosevic had also agreed in very
general terms to allow an international presence to police a
settlement in Kosovo, though crucial details remain to be worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Foreign Minister acknowledged that the Yugoslav
proposals, which were made in recent talks with former Prime
Minister Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy on Kosovo,
fell well short of NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
   But he said they represented a starting point for serious
discussions on ending the Kosovo conflict, and warned that a
political settlement would not be achieved if the Western alliance
refused to negotiate on its demands.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Yugoslav proposals outlined by Ivanov on Monday
suggested that there is still an enormous gap between NATO and
Belgrade. Negotiations to bring the fighting to an end appear to be
at a very early stage and it remained far from clear that Russia
would prove to be the successful mediator the West is hoping for.
</P>
<P>
   The West's decision to welcome Russia's diplomatic involvement
stands in sharp contrast to the 1991 conflict in the Persian Gulf,
when Yevgeni Primakov's efforts at shuttle diplomacy were regarded
by Washington as a meddlesome effort to protect Saddam Hussein from
defeat. Primakov, now prime minister, was then director of Russia's
foreign intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   This time, NATO seemed anxious to give the Russians a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott's mission, American officials said, is to learn the
details of the proposals Milosevic made to Chernomyrdin. It is
also, they say, to explain NATO's demands to the Russians so that
they can continue their mediating role with a better understanding
of what the Western alliance can and cannot agree to.
</P>
<P>
   French President Jacques Chirac telephoned Yeltsin on Monday and
urged him to keep up the political pressure on Yugoslavia, French
officials said. U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan is also scheduled
to arrive this week for talks with Russian leaders on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For all the diplomatic movement, nobody denied that NATO and
Yugoslavia are far apart. Belgrade's offer to slash it troops is a
case in point.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov portrayed Milosevic's readiness to reduce his forces in
Kosovo to their October level as a significant concession, hinting
that Belgrade might we willing to make still further cuts.
According to NATO estimates, Yugoslavia had about 22,500 military
and interior ministry troops in Kosovo in October, compared with
some 40,000 now.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yugoslav proposal does not come close to meeting NATO's
demands. The alliance has insisted that Yugoslavia withdraw
virtually all of its forces from Kosovo, saying that ethnic
Albanian refugees will never return as long as the Serb units that
attacked them remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that those Serb military forces, police or
para-military units who are responsible for the ethnic cleansing
and war crimes in Kosovo can stay is a non-starter,'' said James P.
Rubin, the State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of an international force is even more difficult, the
Russian official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started from a position where Belgrade refused to accept
any foreign military presence, including a Russian one,'' Ivanov
said. ``After our official talks, Belgrade has officially confirmed
its readiness to accept an international presence under the
auspices of the United Nations. For now, this question has not gone
any further. Talks are under way about its composition and other
things, but this work is in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov said Russia was prepared to send peacekeeping troops, but
that it would be very difficult for Milosevic to accept a force
that was essentially under NATO's control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put yourself in the place of Yugoslav's leaders,'' he said.
``Would you allow the same people who destroyed your country to
carry out the peacekeeping operation?''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, NATO has insisted that it play the major role in
any peacekeeping operation. Thousands of British soldiers are now
assembling in Macedonia for precisely this mission and Britain's
Defense Minister has said that it is just a matter of time before
they are deployed. Lightly-armed U.N. peacekeepers, NATO says, will
not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of a credible military presence, Kosovo
refugees cannot come back, and we are determined to create the
conditions for them to come back,'' Rubin said. ``A force with NATO
at its core will provide the magnet for them to return.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Beyond negotiating proposals and tactics, Russia and NATO have
issued wildly divergent accounts of how the war is going.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have insisted there are signs that political and
economic elites in Belgrade have grown unhappy with the war and
that the Milosevic regime might crack soon under the strain. Senior
British officials have even argued that the air strikes are so
punishing that an allied ground force might be able to move into
Kosovo in several months against minimal resistance.
</P>
<P>
   But Ivanov insisted this is a misreading of the situation.
Foreign Minister said Moscow had warned alliance officials that its
air strikes would plunge the region into chaos and asserted that a
ground war would have horrific casualties for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We warned that as soon as the bombing started there would be a
flow of refugees,'' Ivanov said. ``It was also clear that the
strikes wouldn't undermine Milosevic's position. On the contrary,
his position has strengthened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we still warn that if the ground operation begins, it will
lead to large casualities, including on the side that carries out
this operation,'' Ivanov added. You should know the history of
World War II. There won't be a quick ground operation just as there
has not been a quick air operation.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials argue that they put off air strikes for months as
they pursued a diplomatic solution. They say that the conflict in
Kosovo might have been avoided had Moscow had more leverage over
Belgrade and been willing to use what leverage it does possess to
induce Milosevic to agree to the autonomy accord for the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov, however, argued that Russia can cajole, press, but not
force Milosevic to agree to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for whether Russia can persuade Milosevic, I must ask
another question: can the United States persuade the Israeli
government to implement what was signed in Washington in the
presence of the United States president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia has done nothing to bring the situation to what it is
today,'' he added. ``Russia is ready, not alone, but together with
others, to solve this political conflict. Everybody must
participate in the process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
