<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS LEADERS DETERMINED TO GO TO BELGRADE TO SEEK SOLDIERS'
RELEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A combination of canceled flights, logistical
problems and antagonism from administration officials stalled the
plans of religious leaders to travel to Belgrade on Monday to seek
the release of three captive American servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, the organizer of the mission, said the
group will try to get to the Yugoslav capital by an overland route
this week to take advantage of a written promise from the
Yugoslavian mission to the United Nations that the group of
Christian, Jewish and Muslim clergy could visit the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that if we could see them and make a humanitarian
appeal for their release, it could be a kind of circuit breaker,''
Jackson said. ``We want to break this cycle of bomb and cleanse,
cleanse and bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   The mission, which began to take shape last week, has run into
stiff resistance from the administration. Several of the 14 people
scheduled to take part in the trip said they had received calls
over the last few days from White House officials urging them not
to go.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the message was that the trip was not safe. In
other cases, the officials argued that the trip would provide a
propaganda bonanza for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
without producing much in the way of credible evidence that the
Serbs are ready to meet NATO demands for an end to ethnic cleansing
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dr. Joan Campbell, the general-secretary of the
National Council of the Churches in Christ in the United States,
said the pressure from the White House on different religious
organizations to derail the Belgrade visit has been intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a really impressive and unique delegation of religious
leaders,'' she said, adding that its efforts to search for a way to
stop Serb atrocities in Kosovo and bring an end to the NATO bombing
campaign should be allowed to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Among the participants in the mission are Nazir Uddin Khaja,
president of the board of the American Muslim Council; Steven
Bennett Jacobs, a Los Angeles rabbi; the Rev. Raymond Glen Helmick,
a Roman Catholic priest from Boston; Bishop Marshall L. Meadors,
Jr., of the United Methodist Church in Jackson, Miss.; the Rev.
Leonid Kishkovsky, an official of the Orthodox Church in America;
and Rt. Rev. Kodic Mitrophan, bishop of the Eastern American
Diocese in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's private missions to war zones and international
conflicts have produced results in the past. In 1990, after meeting
with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, he negotiated the release of
several hundred hostages who were being held by the Iraqi
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``My contention, then and now, is that wherever there are
releases, it gives a breathing space, a window for talks,'' he
said. ``You're looking to break the no-talk policy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Jackson helped arrange the release of a Navy pilot, Lt.
Robert O. Goodman Jr., who had been shot down over Syria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
