<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ZAMBRANO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAMBRANO SAYS NO HARD FEELINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Answering questions for the first time since
he was fired last week as coach of the Los Angeles Galaxy, Octavio
Zambrano wished the team luck and said, ``I harbor no ill feelings
toward anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, who had refused comment since his firing Thursday, set
up his own conference call with reporters and avoided comments
critical of team management or new coach Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Sigi and his players the very best,'' said Zambrano,
who left Major League Soccer with the best career winning
percentage (.684) and record (39-18) among MLS coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the last game (a 1-0 victory over San Jose) and I
rooted for the Galaxy. They will always be a sentimental team for
me because this is where I got my break.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, fired after his team started the season 2-3, said he
had heard rumors for some time that Galaxy president Tim Leiweke
coveted Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dismissal came as a complete surprise because it was so
early in the season,'' Zambrano said. ``I thought we were well on
our way to achieve the desired level. It was only a matter of time
for that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I believe that management wanted the present coach from
the beginning and as soon as he was available, he was put in
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the change is what bothered Zambrano the most.
Leiweke had a chance to hire Schmid in October. Many people felt
Schmid wanted to finish the UCLA season and his commitment with the
U.S. U-20 national team before moving on.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Schmid finished his U-20 commitment a week ago, he
was named head coach.
</P>
<P>
   If Zambrano was the man Leiweke wanted from the beginning, he
could have offered Zambrano a multiyear contract. Instead, he gave
a three-year deal to Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano, showing his loyalty to the end, promised Leiweke he
wouldn't make a statement until after Schmid's press conference. In
return, Zambrano said Leiweke told him he would be thanked for his
time served.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he would handle it with dignity and respect,''
Zambrano said. ``It was supposed to be more about Sigi, not about
me.''
</P>
<P>
   That hardly was Leiweke's explanation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had asked Octavio to work on creating a better relationship
and a better style of communications within the players,'' Leiweke
said. ``It became pretty obvious in the past week that was still an
issue. The players wanted to be coached. They wanted to be told
what they're doing right and what they're doing wrong and that
wasn't happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Upset with the personal attacks, Zambrano declined comment over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no need for any of that (personal attacks),''
Zambrano said. ``I think I have always handled myself with fairness
and integrity. I don't want to create an ambience of confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach I have to respect their decision. Whatever reasons
they had I have to accept it. Soccer is such a small circle and my
intentions are to coach again in this country and I don't want to
be in a situation where I'm in a confrontation with anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   He did say during a prepared statement that his teams were
always prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``My record should speak for itself,'' Zambrano said. ``We had a
game plan and we executed it most of the time. At halftime, we
would talk about key tactical issues needed to be emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took steps to correct any problems that we may have had when
I became aware of them. I brought our captains, both Robin (Fraser)
and Cobi (Jones), to talk about issues. I don't know why anyone
would say something to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano said he has other offers outside the country but he
will take a few weeks to clear his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a coach and that's definitely what I do,'' he said. ``I'll
let a little time go by and make some decisions later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
