<HEADER>
A4121 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-     04-26 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-729&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE OF THE KILLERS ENVISIONED A FAR BIGGER SLAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to insert new grafs 7, 8 and 9; drops previous 7th graf,
`Nothing has been confirmed...')  
(An overview; see also COLO-SCHOOL-JONESBORO) 
(ART ADV: 2 photos, NYT19 and NYT10, are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mb) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ As he planned the assault on Columbine High
School, Eric Harris wrote in a diary that he envisioned killing as
many as 500 students, going on to attack neighboring homes and then
hijacking a jet and crashing it in New York City, police
investigators said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that Harris or his accomplice, Dylan
Klebold, took any steps to carry out this grander scheme, but Steve
Davis, a spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department,
said, ``If in fact they were able to carry out their entire plan,
there could have been quite a bit more damage and quite a few more
fatalities.'' The officials did not release the contents of the
diary.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a week after Harris and Dylan Klebold brought guns and as
many as 30 pipe bombs to school, killing 12 students and one
teacher before taking their own lives, the police on Monday
questioned and later released an 18-year-old girlfriend of one of
the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a female who I believe had access to this weapon
prior to Tuesday,'' Dave Thomas, the Jefferson County district
attorney said, referring to a semiautomatic TEC-9 pistol recovered
with the suspects' bodies. ``We are looking into how she got access
to that weapon, and what involvement she may have had.''
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney and the police spokesman emphasized that
no arrests were imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not called her a suspect at the time, by any means _
there is no arrest warrant either,'' Davis said. Responding to a
reporter's question about the four guns found in the school, he
answered, ``She was questioned on the handgun and the rifle, not
the shotguns.'' The authorities here say most of the victims'
wounds were appear to have been caused by two sawed-off shotguns
the pair carried rather than the TEC-9 or a 9-millimeter
semiautomatic carbine rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four guns recovered, Davis has said that the two shotguns
appear to have been manufactured more 25 years ago. He added that
records indicate the pistol and the carbine were purchased recently
from a Colorado gun dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Under Colorado and federal law, a minor cannot own a handgun,
and it is illegal to give or sell a handgun to someone under 18. It
is legal for someone 18 or older to buy a handgun through a private
sale, reached through a classified advertisement or a gun show. In
contrast, federally licensed dealers are not allowed to sell
handguns to someone under 21.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, where surveys indicate that almost half of
households have guns, there are gun fairs almost every weekend. At
these shows, private sellers do not have to conduct background
checks on buyers. Bob Glass, a federally licensed firearms dealer
in Boulder, said of the fairs, ``It's cash and a handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation continued into last week's rampage,
funerals were held Monday for the teacher and three of the students
slain. The teacher, William Sanders, 47, was shot twice in the
chest as he led students down a hallway to safety. Services were
also held for Lauren Townsend, 18, the captain of the girls'
varsity volleyball; Daniel Rohrbough, 15, who was shot while
holding a door open for fleeing students; and Cassie Bernall, 17.
</P>
<P>
   With bomb squad investigators continuing to search the grounds,
Davis spoke to reporters outside the cordoned-off school. There
remain ``many, many lockers to go through, many, many backpacks to
go through,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold, who were both seniors at Columbine, had
apparently pinned their hopes on blowing up their school to a
25-pound propane bomb in the school's kitchen that they had planned
to detonate. When the timing device failed, Davis said, ``there
were indications that they had possibly tried to fire on that
bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Jefferson County Coroner's Office said
Monday that toxicology tests on the bodies of the two youths did
not show traces of drugs or alcohol. In addition, Davis said that
investigators had not found any illicit drugs or drug paraphernalia
at their homes.
</P>
<P>
   He said the parents of the two youths had hired lawyers and had
not spoken with investigators since last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Since last Tuesday's attack, the parents of Brooks Brown, a
classmate of the suspects, have disclosed that they notified the
Jefferson County Sheriff's Department eight times last year with
complaints that Harris, a neighbor, had threatened their son. The
couple, Randy and Judy Brown, said that after Harris chipped the
windshield of their son's car, he created a computer game that
revolved around destroying the Brown house and created a web site
that featured a death threat against their son and accounts of
manufacturing and exploding pipe bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harris and Klebold were on probation at the time,
Jefferson County detectives never followed up on the complaints,
the Browns have said. On Monday, Davis said that a ``suspicious
incident'' report had been located. Later, he added, ``This is part
of the ongoing investigation and I do not want to make any comments
about that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said, ``As far as I know, nothing was ever brought to my
office.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While trading at the nation's four busiest stock exchanges came
to a halt for one minute at noon Monday in memory of the 13
victims, this Denver suburb endured a numbing marathon of funerals.
About 2,500 people turned out for the funeral of Sander's, who had
taught and coached at the school for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday as shots rang out at lunch, Sanders, a grandfather,
jumped on a table in the school cafeteria and shouted for students
to duck, and then to get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was running around, and I remember seeing him jumping over
the chairs and yelling `Everybody get down!''' Lindsay Dowling, a
student recalled. ``I truly believe he saved my life and many other
people's.''
</P>
<P>
   As he ran through the halls, herding students to safety, the
teacher was shot twice in the chest. After taking him into a
barricaded classroom, students tried to keep his spirits up by
showing him wallet photos of his wife and three daughters. But he
died shortly after being freed by the police, the only teacher to
die in the siege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to thank him for saving my life,'' Laurel Salerno,
another student who escaped the cafeteria, said in a church
overflowing with students. ``Mr. Sanders, I thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, at the same time, another 1,000 mourners attended the
funeral of Bernall, a junior, who often wore a bracelet inscribed
``WWJD'' _ shorthand for `What would Jesus do?'
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, one of the attackers cornered her in the library,
trained a gun on her, looked in her blue eyes, and asked if she
believed in God. After a pause, surviving students have recounted,
Bernall, a born-again Christian, answered deliberately, ``Yes, I
believe in God.'' He then shot her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cassie died a martyr's death,'' Pastor George Kristen, of the
West Bowled Community Church said. ``She went to the martyr's hall
of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, a funeral was held for Townsend, a National
Honor Society scholar, She was to have been the class valedictorian
at graduation ceremonies next month.
</P>
<P>
   The last funeral of the day was for Rohrbough, a freshman. He
was last seen alive running from his stalkers and screaming for his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   As temperatures warmed in Denver, hundreds of people continued
to make somber pilgrimages to a memorial site in a park near the
high school. Many parked a half-mile away to add flowers to the
thousands of bouquets already there.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 students from other high schools marched up to nine
miles to the site. Referring to the killers, one held a placard to
passing cars, ``There are more of us than there are of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a teen-ager,'' said one marcher, Morgen Warner, a junior
from Jefferson County Open School. ``This affects me more deeply
than any adult could even begin to comprehend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
