<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON SET TO BEGIN CALLING UP RESERVISTS, OFFICIAL SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon will begin calling up reservists as
early as Tuesday, a top official said on Monday, and will
immediately send in 30 refueling aircraft to support the air
campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In the first training accident of the campaign, an Army Apache
helicopter crashed on landing at the airfield in Tirana, Albania.
Both crewmen escaped, according to a Pentagon spokesman, but it was
not known whether they were injured. There were no reports of
hostile fire and no information on damage to the helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   The training accident came just as all but one of the 24 Apache
helicopters, including the troops and ground-based rocket launchers
needed for their operations, had arrived in Tirana. Preparations
were under way for the helicopters to begin action against the
Yugoslav army in Kosovo, which the Pentagon said could begin at any
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday morning Belgrade time, one of the NATO-launched
cruise missiles struck the headquarters of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's Socialist Party, one of the tallest buildings
in central Belgrade, blowing off part of the roof. Repairs were
under way on the building, which was hit last week and houses
television studios and transmission facilities as well as political
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The strike at the USCE Business Center failed to stop Serbian
television from broadcasting. The transmitters for Radio and
Television Kosava are owned by Milosevic's daughter, Marija.
</P>
<P>
   During the last 24 hours, NATO forces also hit a third bridge
across the Danube River and stepped up attacks on the Yugoslav
forces in the field with combat jets destroying several tanks,
trucks and armored personnel carriers in Kosovo, according to the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also said on Monday that it is building camps in
Fier, Albania, to house 20,000 Kosovo refugees now living in
neighboring Macedonia. The United States has already said it will
bring 20,000 Kosovo refugees to this country from Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   In asking President Clinton to authorize the use of as many as
33,000 reservists, the Pentagon said on Monday it would stagger the
call-up in phases, to avoid too great a disruption across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to be as accurate as possible so we don't have all the
reservists hanging by a thread worrying whether they will be
next,'' said Col. Richard Bridges, a Defense Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But with a call up of this size, disruption is inevitable,
especially in the aviation industry because most of the reservists
will be pilots or aircraft crew members.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, the Air Force was able to rely on volunteer
reservists to provide the crews needed for the air operations,
especially for the increasingly valuable refueling tankers. There
are already 120 tanker aircraft in Europe supporting NATO
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 300 planes requested by Clark, at least 100 will be
refueling tankers, according to Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 200 planes will be combat jets to expand the air
attacks and suppress the Yugoslav air defense system. The pilots
and crews for these planes will be drawn largely from the reserves.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been small reserve call-ups in recent years for
the Bosnia peacekeeping operation and the air patrols over Iraq,
the 33,000 reservists called up for Kosovo will be the largest
since the 1990 call up for the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 refueling tankers are the most urgently needed of the 300
American aircraft requested by NATO's supreme commander, Gen.
Wesley Clark, earlier this month to intensify the air war in the
Kosovo conflict, according to Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers from the U.S. Army will be detailed to build the new
refugee camp in Fier, Albania, near the port of Durres. They expect
to have the camps ready for the first several thousand refugees
within 10 days, according to Lt. Gen. John McDuffie.
</P>
<P>
   These are the refugees who would have been sent from Macedonia
to the U.S. base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba. But after fierce protests
from aid and refugee groups, the Clinton administration scrapped
that plan in favor of setting up a camp within the region to house
these refugees, all of whom have said they want to return to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   McDuffie said the U.S. military will build the camp and manage
it for about one month before it is turned over to the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, which is charged with the care of all of
the camps.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Vice President Al Gore announced that the United
States would bring 20,000 Kosovars to this country for temporary
placement with their families. There are many Albanian-American
communities here, with especially large groups in Detroit and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is one of more than 16 countries that have
agreed to give asylum to these refugees now housed in Macedonia,
always with the intention of returning them to Kosovo once the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, retreats from their
province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
