<SLUG> BC-BBA-A's-WATSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATSON MAY GET ANOTHER FIRST: TEAM OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (kd) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Watson is proud of his accomplishments in baseball, but he
has grown weary of one aspect. ``I would like to get rid of the
distinction of being first,'' he said. ``I am really tired of being
the first of anything in baseball _ first assistant general
manager, first general manager, first African American to win a
World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, of course, will never shed the distinctions because
first is first. From the day in 1988 when John McMullen, then the
owner of the Houston Astros, hired him as his assistant general
manager, Watson has worked his way through a series of firsts. He
was the first black general manager, and no one can take that
distinction from him. What he really wants, though, is not to be
the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see all those firsts turned into second, third,
fourth and fifth,'' Watson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the former general manager of the Yankees and the Houston
Astros has yet another first he could attain. He could become the
first member of a minority group to be a club owner who is involved
in the day-to-day operation of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, out of baseball since he left the Yankees 15 months ago,
is part of one of two groups that are trying to buy the Oakland
Athletics. Each group has submitted a $12 million down payment on
the designated purchase price of $122.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum Authority will select one of
the groups by May 11 as the Athletics' owner, subject to approval
of Major League Baseball and its club owners. Watson and Steve
Stone, the former Cy Young award winner, are members of one group;
Joe Morgan, the Hall of Fame second baseman who is also black, is
involved with the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been talking to Steve for some time,'' Watson related by
telephone from Houston. ``About three weeks ago, he called and said
he had something he wanted to run by me. It was the Oakland
situation. I told him I'd be interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Their group, Watson said, wants to expand its partnership, which
is currently led by Lyle Campbell, a Phoenix banker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to bring in a number of other investors, mainly
local minorities,'' Watson said. He mentioned those who are
Hispanic, Asian, black. ``That's basically the fan base in
Oakland,'' said Watson, a former coach with the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   While baseball has lacked black and Hispanic officials in
decision-making positions, it has experienced an even greater void
in ownership. There is a difference, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the proliferation of black and Hispanic players, there
are very few black and Hispanic general managers, managers or
directors of player development and scouting because white owners
don't hire them. There are no black and Hispanic owners because
they don't step forward with $122.4 million or $173 million or
whatever a franchise costs.
</P>
<P>
   But are there members of minority groups in Oakland who will
join an ownership group as minority partners? ``We're going to find
out,'' Watson said. ``We'd like to see that work in Oakland.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a better question to pose is, will the Athletics work in
Oakland, no matter who owns them? Steve Schott (no relation to
Marge Schott) and Ken Hofmann have owned the team for less than
four years. Under their agreement with the coliseum authority, if
the authority cannot broker a deal for the team, Schott and Hofmann
are free to sell the team for a move elsewhere or move it
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose has been mentioned as a location, but it is in the
Giants' territory. Sacramento is not and would be a possibility.
But the two competing groups for the Athletics are serious, and a
deal with one of them is likely. A new owner would have to keep the
team in Oakland through the 2004 season.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Giants and another half-dozen teams, the Athletics do
not have a new revenue-raising park in their future. New owners
wouldn't have any easier time making it than past or current owners
and in fact would face the existence of a brand-new park across the
bay in San Francisco beginning next season.
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 15,733 fans a game, the Athletics are at the bottom
end of the attendance totals. They compete in a division whose
other teams average at least 10,000 more fans a game.
</P>
<P>
   The bright side for a new owner is the rich player development
program the Athletics have. This season's lineup is filled with
homegrown products _ Jason Giambi, Scott Spiezio, Miguel Tejada,
Eric Chavez, A.J. Hinch, Jason McDonald and Ben Grieve. It's a crop
that would make a new owner buy the team with an optimistic
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Long-range planning has Watson running the baseball operation if
he and his colleagues get the team, but Watson said it's premature
to make plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were fortunate enough to get the club, we'd sit down
with the current administration and do a complete evaluation,'' he
said. ``The bottom line is to get the right people in the right
jobs. I don't want to stand here today and tell you I'm going to be
doing X, Y, Z.''
</P>
<P>
   It would only be fitting, though, for Watson, as a minority
owner, to head the baseball operation. It would be another first
that would crown his career and enable him to extend his role as a
baseball pioneer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
