<HEADLINE>
HARRICK MASTERS THE BAD GOODBYE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mineral baths and massages and stress-reduction therapy, that's
what you figured Jim Harrick would be looking for after a job offer
at a prestigious institution had unglued him.
</P>
<P>
   For two excruciating days, his pathos played out in public. He
was a baseball player caught in a rundown, a driver lurching into
the intersection as the light turned yellow, a suitor torn between
the one who loves him and the one he loves.
</P>
<P>
   His indecision paralyzed two college basketball programs and
tacked on another bizarre chapter to his travelogue.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Harrick quit his hemming and hawing, and absolutely,
positively accepted the University of Georgia men's basketball job,
he had created a tributary of hard feelings that flowed from
Kingston, R.I., to Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick's not the first coach to change his mind, merely the
latest. Harrick's former UCLA cohort Terry Donahue did it, when the
Atlanta Falcons courted him in the late 1980s. And just the other
week Buzz Peterson left Southwest Missouri State at the altar,
accepting its basketball head-coaching job one day and changing his
mind the next, but not before a news conference had been announced
to trumpet his move from Appalachian State.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, is in the details.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue reconsidered the Falcons' head-coaching job after
sleeping on his initial decision, leaving no one the wiser outside
his intimate circle. And Peterson didn't have a few hundred
appreciative boosters on campus, waiting for him to keep the
appointment he had scheduled so they could applaud his decision to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Say this about Harrick: From his precipitous fall from grace at
UCLA in 1996 to his messy breakup not quite three years later from
a Rhode Island program that worshiped him, he has become the master
of the memorable exit.
</P>
<P>
   In a dizzying span of 48 hours during Easter week, Harrick, 60,
announced he was leaving the University of Rhode Island for the
University of Georgia, called a press conference in Rhode Island to
proclaim he had changed his mind and then, egregiously, left his
players and 300 excited boosters in the lurch, a no-show at his own
party because he was on the midnight train to Georgia (or something
like that) after another change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a while for you to catch up with Harrick, but when you
finally track him down at his office in Athens he said: ``I'm sure
I left some people in Rhode Island feeling betrayed. I went back
there, I was going to meet with them. I was just very emotional at
the time. It was very difficult to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all about family (he left behind a Rams coaching staff
that includes his son and namesake, whom he won't be able to hire
at Georgia because of nepotism rules). And family, you know,
supersedes everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after taking the Georgia job, Harrick was out of town all
week but not regrouping at some chichi spa as you suspected. The
signing period arrived the week after Harrick arrived in Georgia.
So he had been hard on the recruiting trail, trying to make up for
lost time.
</P>
<P>
   The trail led him to the tiny burg of Cuthbert, a one-stoplight
town tucked away in the southwestern part of the state, not far
from the Alabama border. A 6-foot-8 manchild resides there who
Harrick's gotta have. Donnell Harvey is the best player in the
state _ and, arguably, the country.
</P>
<P>
   After some initial waffling _ Lord knows Harrick can relate to
that _ Harvey considered Georgia but chose Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick could have used him; four of Georgia's six primary
players this past season were seniors and the Bulldogs' best
player, sophomore forward Jumaine Jones, also is expected to leave
for the NBA, though Harrick has appealed to him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Harrick's got two scholarships to give, unless some of
the recruits who've already committed can't get their grades and
test scores up. In which case, he said, ``I don't know what I'm
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When he said that, there's a fervor in his voice rather than
frustration. Understand this: Harrick could have lived happily ever
after in Kingston. His players respected him and responded to him
and, in a vast departure from his UCLA days, so did the athletic
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick coached Rhode Island to one Atlantic-10 Conference title
and guided the Rams to two NCAA appearances, including an Elite
Eight showing in 1998. It certainly wasn't security or subsidies
that lured him away from Kingston (when he got the Georgia offer,
Rhode Island countered with an offer that he said blew him away).
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the opportunity to coach in one of the most
competitive conferences in the country that proved irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going up against Kentucky, Tennessee, Auburn and Alabama every
week is a challenge,'' Harrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it might have been a thrill to stay in Kingston to
usher through the building of a new, privately financed arena.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick bristles when you ask if he's motivated by a desire to
prove himself on the big stage, the inference being that his
appetite for approval is so voracious his successful stints at
Pepperdine and UCLA and Rhode Island somehow weren't filling
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. I don't feel like I have anything left to prove,'' he
said. ``I've just always been the kind of person that likes to
compete against the best. The excitement for me is in the chase.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good. It's only bad when your pursuit leaves
good people behind, hugging air.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
