<HEADLINE>
OWNER OF DERBY HOPEFUL SUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Ky.)  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The owner of Valhol filed suit in Arkansas
Monday demanding that the state's racing commission release the
$300,000 purse his horse earned for winning the Arkansas Derby,
money that may determine whether the 3-year-old qualifies to run in
the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, lawyers for the owner, Jim Jackson, contend that
the Arkansas Racing Commission was required by state law to
distribute the purse within 96 hours of the race on April 10 at
Oaklawn Park in Hot Springs, Ark. The commission has directed track
officials to withhold the money while the racing stewards
investigate whether the jockey Billy Patin used an illegal
electrical device on Valhol during the race.
</P>
<P>
   The stewards have set a hearing for Patin on May 5, which is
four days after the Kentucky Derby. Pulaski County Circuit Judge
John Plegge will hold a hearing on Jackson's petition Tuesday at 1
p.m. in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
</TEXT>
