<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-SURGERY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL `BATISTA PROCEDURE' HEART SURGERY PERFORMED IN
SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Bigger isn't really better when it comes to hearts.
</P>
<P>
   So Dr. Randas Batista, a controversial Brazilian cardiac
surgeon, cut a chunk out of Donald Stringfellow's heart Monday to
make it a smaller and more efficient pump.
</P>
<P>
   Stringfellow, who had an enlarged heart and congestive heart
failure, is the first person in the Pacific Northwest to have the
``Batista procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided I was a good candidate,'' the 76-year-old Marin
County and former Chehalis resident said the day before surgery.
``I have a big heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The experimental operation, performed at Providence Medical
Center in Seattle, was broadcast live on the Internet to at least
300 physicians worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Batista and Dr. Kim Jett, a cardiovascular surgeon at
Providence, answered questions while performing the surgery on
Stringfellow. The focus of the operation was the heart's left
ventricle, the largest and most powerful pumping chamber in the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make the ventricle smaller,'' Batista said.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that simple, he repeatedly told the audience. The
medical profession tends to seek hi-tech and complicated solutions,
Batista said, but he was forced out of necessity to find low-tech
and simpler alternatives for his patients in rural Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Attributing his medical motto to President Franklin D.
Roosevelt, Batista said: ``You do what you can with what you have
where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the Batista procedure is of interest
because more than 3.5 million people have congestive heart failure.
About 400,000 Americans die of congestive heart failure annually.
Some 50,000 people with the condition qualify for a heart
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are only about 2,000 heart donors per year,'' Jett
said. Jett said the alternatives to transplantation include drug
therapy, heart valve repair, mechanical devices that assist the
heart in pumping or the heart-reduction surgery approach pioneered
by Batista.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reducing the workload on the heart,'' the Brazilian
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after Jett and the Providence cardiac surgery team
opened Stringfellow's chest, Batista cut into the left ventricle of
the beating heart with his scalpel.
</P>
<P>
   During most of the surgery, a heart-lung machine took over the
task of pumping Stringfellow's blood.
</P>
<P>
   Batista and Jett discovered a weak area in the septum _ the wall
that separates the four chambers of the heart _ which prompted a
small change in plans.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than simply cut a large piece out of Stringfellow's
ventricle, Batista opted to cut and remove a smaller section near
the weak area and fold out or ``exclude'' the faulty portion of the
ventricle.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons also repaired a defective mitral valve _ the valve
between the upper left atrium and the lower left ventricle in the
heart that is supposed to regulate blood flow in one direction.
Stringfellow's valve had been allowing some ``regurgitation,'' or
back flow.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of about an hour, the Brazilian and the Providence
cardiothoracic team had cut out a piece of Stringfellow's
ventricle, repaired a faulty heart valve, fixed a weak spot in the
septum and sutured it all back up.
</P>
<P>
   So why's this guy so controversial?
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't like what I'm doing because it's so simple,''
Batista said after the surgery in the Providence operating room
locker. ``I developed this in a small village in the jungles of
Brazil. These people in the universities say I'm crazy rather than
admit that what I'm doing actually works.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's the question. Even some of Batista's supporters say
it's not clear how often this works and why it works for some but
not others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some patients do well and others don't do well,'' said Dr.
Robert Lazzara, Jett's colleague in cardiac surgery at Providence.
``The results are equivocal so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Lazzara said, after Batista and his surgical
procedure were featured on a television show, ``A lot of surgeons
jumped on to this and started doing the procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't done as a formalized clinical study, he said,
and some surgeons were discouraged that they weren't getting the
results Batista said he gets in Brazil with his patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tim Icenogle, a heart surgeon at Sacred Heart Hospital in
Spokane, was taught how to do the Batista procedure but he doesn't
offer it to his patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country, most of these procedures have been done at
the Cleveland Clinic,'' Icenogle said. ``The results there so far
have been questionable so I've decided not to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacred Heart, like the University of Washington Medical Center,
does heart transplants for some patients with heart failure. For
those who don't get transplants, Icenogle has been implanting
left-ventrical assist devices to improve the heart's pumping
ability.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association provides information on the
Batista procedure but takes no position on its effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Jett and Lazzara said the Providence Foundation decided to
sponsor a clinical study of the Batista procedure in 10 patients
because of the need to offer better alternatives for people with
heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Stringfellow had no other option,'' Jett said.
</P>
<P>
   He was too old for a transplant and he has not been able to
tolerate the drugs often used to treat congestive heart failure.
These drugs improve blood flow by inhibiting a hormone that
constricts arteries and raises blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Batista said he has performed about 700 of these surgeries in
the past 15 years. He said survival is about 60 percent after two
years and 57 percent after three years.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he didn't offer any specifics on longer-term survival
rates. In the past, he's said these are difficult numbers to obtain
because many of his patients move out of the area and don't
maintain contact with his hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very poor environment,'' Batista said. ``I began doing
this because these patients had nothing else, nothing to lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
