<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Air Jordan's Agent Offers `3-Pointers' on Building
a  Winning Brand 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The ballrooms and salons of the Westin St. Francis hotel yesterday
were teeming with cell-phone-toting institutional investors,
hunting for the next great brand &UR;  &LR; _ such as America Online,
Amazon.com or Yahoo _ &UR;  &LR; in which to invest.
</P>
<P>
   But while the armies of Italian-crafted, midnight blue suits
buzzed around the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist technology stock conference,
uber-agent David Falk was up the hill at the Ritz Carlton Hotel
revealing the secrets behind a brand more dominant than those
darlings of the Net: Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   As Jordan's agent, Falk has been largely responsible for helping
the former Bulls superstar forge a brand that is arguably one of
the most pervasive in the world. And Falk thinks some of the
lessons he and Mike have learned since his client was drafted out
of the University of North Carolina in 1984 can be deftly applied
to corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   But first let's put the evolution of Jordan as a global brand
into context. The then-skinny kid from Carolina arrived on the
scene just as the National Basketball Association was starting to
rise, shoe contracts were paltry and, lastly, Jordan was different.
He could fly.
</P>
<P>
   His emergence as a brand name ``had more preponderance than just
its financial impact. It was almost a cultural phenomenon,'' said
Falk in an interview. Falk was in town to speak at the Venture
Strategy Group's annual brand building conference at the Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is worshipped like a rock star. His endorsements and
personal preferences shape fashion and pop culture. What's more,
marketers and social scientists haven't seen mass popularity like
his since the Beatles left Liverpool, Falk says.
</P>
<P>
   Falk hasn't been too shabby as an adviser. Nike, McDonald's and
Oakley are just a few of the companies that pay Jordan millions to
tout their products. In fact, Fortune magazine estimated that
Jordan's branding power is worth around $10 billion. Of course,
such an intangible value is nearly impossible to determine. But,
heck, if online auctioneer eBay has a market value of $261.44
billion, then why can't Jordan's brand be worth $10 billion?
</P>
<P>
   No one, not even Falk, could have anticipated that Jordan would
become as great of a basketball player as he is. If the agent could
have been more prescient, he says, ``we probably would have done
some things differently.''
</P>
<P>
   While Michael Inc. was quite careful in selecting Jordan's
corporate alliances, Falk says he and his client might have picked
companies and products with more synergy. ``I think I would have
done a better job of integrating the companies'' and cross-branding
their products using promotional tie-ins with the other
Jordan-backed products, Falk says.
</P>
<P>
   The agent is still getting a chance to try such things. ``That
has been our game plan we've tried to bring to (Detroit Pistons
star) Grant Hill,'' Falk says.
</P>
<P>
   Falk thinks that technology companies and the rest of corporate
America could take pointers from his experience as an architect of
Michael Inc. Here are his three tenets to successful brand
building:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quality products.  &LR; ``You have to have a great product to have a
great brand.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Consistent message.  &LR; ``You can't be all things to all people.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Be genuine.  &LR; ``You can't gussy up a Chevrolet and sell it as a
Mercedes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jordan's dogged pursuit of excellence earned him top
personal accomplishments, a national collegiate championship, two
Olympic gold medals and six NBA championships. So I guess that
takes care of the quality part of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   As for the second point, Jordan was the epitome of consistency.
He earned top scoring and defense honors year in and year out. He
simply never coasted.
</P>
<P>
   But it might be the third point that catapulted Jordan to
international fame and fortune. He has been himself. He has
delivered on most of his promise, which is what you expect from any
great name. For instance, consumers pay more for Sony because the
name is synonymous with high quality.
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems with Los Angeles Lakers star Shaquille
O'Neal, who Falk cites as a ``great guy,'' is that his too-cool
rapper persona comes off as disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq has made a lot of money, but the products (he endorses)
haven't sold well,'' Falk points out.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his retirement from basketball earlier this year, Jordan
still sells.
</P>
<P>
   And the hyper-competitive athlete is reportedly looking to buy a
stake in an NBA franchise, namely the Charlotte Hornets. Jordan
wants to buy roughly half of the franchise, but he doesn't want to
pay half of what the team is supposedly worth. Instead, he wants
the amount that his brand value will add to the business to be
deducted from the price tag.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the Hornets are worth $160 million now, they
could be worth $180 million or more once Jordan's brand becomes
associated with the team. That's the argument Falk is making.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has increased the value of most any product he has
endorsed or has been affiliated with, whether they are Chevys,
hamburgers, telephone services or shoes, Falk says.
</P>
<P>
   ``His track record (as a value builder) is unprecedented,'' says
Falk, who declined comment on the status of Jordan's bid for a
stake in the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   But he did offer this observation about many of today's
professional athletes: ``Every player is too worried about trying
to be a brand and not concentrating on being a product first.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds similar to half of the Internet companies out there
racing to go public.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; YOU'VE GOT EARNINGS: &LR;  If America Online's absence from the H&AMP;Q
stock conference this week is a precursor to some sort of earnings
surprise, the market is oblivious to such prospects. Last week,
Street Smarts pointed out that AOL was skipping the conference and
that it planned to report quarterly earnings after the market
closes today. AOL soared almost $13 to close yesterday at $159.88
as news wires reported that investors anticipated the Internet
portal to beat Wall Street consensus earnings estimates for the
sixth quarter in a row.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4143 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EBAY-SFCHRON &LR;      04-26 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EBay Will Purchase Butterfield
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jamie Beckett &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
EBay, the online auctioneer that got its start selling Pez
dispensers, yesterday agreed to acquire venerable fine arts auction
house Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield for about $260 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, eBay announced first-quarter earnings yesterday.
Profits rose more than twelvefold, beating analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   EBay said the acquisition of Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield allows it
to expand to pricier offerings and a more affluent target market.
Just as importantly, the deal gives eBay the cache of the
134-year-old San Francisco auction house, which has sold everything
from 17th century armor to Elvis Presley's American Express card to
rare art pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the potential to take eBay out of the Waldorf Astoria
parking lot and into the lobby,'' said Jae Kim, an analyst at Paul
Kagan Associates. ``The $260 million price may be cheap when you
consider the impact (an association with Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield)
will have on its public image.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal also helps eBay keep pace with Amazon.com, which
recently launched its own online auction service.
</P>
<P>
   For Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield, joining forces with the San Jose
Internet commerce pioneer provides instant, electronic access to
eBay's 3.8 million users.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more than the top 10 auction houses put together,''
said John Gallo, president and chief executive of Butterfield &AMP;
Butterfield. ``EBay is redefining the auction industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield is the nation's No.3 fine arts
auctioneer but trails far behind leaders Sotheby's Holdings Inc.
and Christies International Plc. Gallo said the company will
continue its existing auction business at houses in San Francisco,
Los Angeles and Chicago. EBay plans to keep current management at
Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield in place, Gallo said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Butterfield was set to go public, selling 1.5 million shares
for about $15 each. That would have valued the entire company at
about $94 million _ less than half of what eBay will likely pay.
The exact purchase price will be based on the average price of
eBay's high-flying stock before the transaction is completed, which
it expects this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   EBay's stock closed yesterday up $8.88 at $209 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies recently revealed plans to team to offer
online fine arts bidding.
</P>
<P>
   While eBay auctions typically result in winning bids of $200 or
less, Butterfield's auctions focuses on items selling from $300 to
$10,000, with some items selling for more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield had net revenues of $21 million last year and profit
of $1.5 million, according to a statement filed with federal
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended March 31, eBay said its profit rose to $7
million (5 cents a share) from $569,000 (1 cent) a year earlier.
Analysts expected eBay to earn 2 cents, according to First Call
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose more than fivefold to $34 million from $6 million.
Analysts said they'd expected revenues of about $25 million to $27
million.
</P>
<P>
   EBay's number of registered users rose to more than 3.8 million
at the end of the quarter, up from more than 2.1 million on
December 31. In addition, eBay hosted more than 22.9 million
auctions, up from 13.6 million in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will be accounted for as a tax-free pooling of
interests, the companies said, with the number of eBay shares
issued to be determined by its average stock price in a period
prior to the closing of the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   EBay also said it might take a one-time charge in the quarter
related to the deal. It said the size of the charge had not yet
been determined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
