<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4145 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-RUMBLINGS-     04-26 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-RUMBLINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO REPORTS SOME YUGOSLAVS VOICE DISCONTENT WITH MILOSEVIC'S
POLICIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO leaders reported growing ``rumblings of
discontent'' Monday within Yugsolavia, as one of the country's top
officials sought a peace deal, warning that the bomb-ravaged Serb
republic soon ``will look like Hiroshima and Nagasaki'' after the
nuclear strikes on Japan in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   As the Pentagon prepared to call up as many as 33,000 reservists
this week to bolster NATO's aerial siege of Yugoslavia, one of the
country's deputy prime ministers, Vuk Draskovic, said his
government is ready to accept a UN peacekeeping force that would
include NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal came as a US Army Apache helicopter, poised for
combat in Kosovo, crashed and burst into flames near an airfield in
Tirana, Albania. The two crewmen escaped without serious injuries.
The Pentagon said the aircraft was on a training mission and was
not hit by enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter is the second US aircraft to be destroyed in the
conflict, the other being an F-117 Stealth fighter shot down last
month near Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter crashed on the day the Pentagon announced that
all 23 Apaches in Albania are ready to launch a risky offensive
against Serb ground forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, meanwhile, Draskovic said he believed his call for
peace reflected the views of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
though there was no evidence to support his assertion. There also
was no support among allied leaders for a peacekeeping operation
run by the United Nations rather than NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But the plea for peace was enough in itself to buoy NATO
leaders, whose airstrikes have failed to prevent Milosevic's forces
from killing, raping, or driving more than 1.4 million Albanians
from their homes in the Serb province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that inside the system the facade of unity is
cracking wide open,'' said British Defense Secretary George
Robertson. He said there is ``deep discontent inside the military
high command'' in Yugoslavia and ``deep concern'' in the business
community ``about where Milosevic is dragging the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as Red Cross officials were permitted
to visit for the first time three US soldiers who have been held in
Yugoslavia since March 31. Escorted by Serb authorities, members of
the International Committee of the Red Cross met briefly with the
soldiers in Belgrade and reported that all three appeared to be in
good condition.
</P>
<P>
   There were these other developments Monday and early Tuesday in
the Kosovo conflict:
</P>
<P>
   --The Pentagon deployed 30 Air Force refueling jets, the first
wave of 300 US aircraft that will join the massive air campaign.
More than 600 US warplanes are already engaged in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   As early as Tuesday, Defense Secretary William S. Cohen is
expected to order tens of thousands of Air Force reservists to
active duty to support the NATO effort, the largest call-up since
the war with Iraq in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   --Vice President Al Gore spoke for an hour by telephone with
Russia's envoy to the Balkans, Viktor Chernomyrdin, who is trying
to mediate a peaceful resolution to the conflict. Chernomyrdin,
Russia's former prime minister, met last week in Belgrade with
Milosevic and is scheduled to meet Tuesday in Moscow with US Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Chernomyrdin reached no accord but agreed to talk again
about the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   --As many as 30,000 ethnic Albanians in Kosovo were fleeing
toward the Macedonia border, an exodus that is expected to
aggravate the humanitarian crisis in the region's clogged refugee
camps.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600,000 refugees, mostly Albanians, have fled Kosovo,
whose population was 2 million before Milosevic launched his
campaign of ``ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the exodus Monday, there were reports that Serb troops were
using ethnic Albanian women and children as human shields at an
ammunition depot in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO forces early Tuesday destroyed a TV transmitter at the
business center housing Milosevic's party headquarters in Belgrade,
residents said. The transmitter collapsed on top of the badly
damaged building housing the headquarters of Milosevic's Socialist
Party of Serbia, which was hit by NATO last Wednesday. Some debris
had hit the nearby Hyatt Hotel where some foreign journalists,
including employees of CNN, were staying.
</P>
<P>
   --The Rev. Jesse Jackson said he will lead a delegation of
religious leaders to Belgrade to issue a direct ``moral appeal'' to
Milosevic to release the captured US soldiers. Jackson said he
hoped to leave as early as Tuesday, even though the White House
said NATO could not guarantee his safety and expressed little
support for his mission.
</P>
<P>
   As a Democratic presidential candidate in 1984, Jackson traveled
to Syria and secured the release of Navy Lieutenant Robert O.
Goodman Jr., whose jet was shot down during a raid over Syrian
antiaircraft positions in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart, when asked about Jackson's
``freelance diplomacy,'' said, ``There are certainly those who are
moving forward outside the context of the United States government
and NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the Red Cross officials were not allowed to speak
privately with the captive American soldiers or to fully assess
their mental and physical health, as the Geneva Convention
requires. ``I was able to talk to them only a few minutes,'' said
Cornelio Sommaruga, president of the International Committee of the
Red Cross. ``We looked into each other's eyes and shook hands very
warmly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross delivered letters from home to each soldier: Staff
Sergeant Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Specialist Steven
M. Gonzalez, 21, of Huntsville, Texas; and Staff Sergeant
Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   But Sommaruga said the Yugoslav government blocked ``a
full-fledged ICRC visit in accord with the provisions of the Geneva
Convention.'' He said Milosevic promised to permit such a visit
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO's crackdown on Milosevic was bolstered by the
European Union's ban Monday on fuel shipments to Yugoslavia. NATO
military leaders also were devising a plan aimed at cutting off
most other oil shipments to Yugoslavia, although they said they
would not use force to halt the deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to not use force was seen as a concession to
Russia, which opposes a military blockade of oil and other goods to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, where Serb troops continue to clash with the
Albanian Army along the Kosovo border, the foreign minister, Paskal
Milo, called on NATO to send in ground forces. ``We support the
idea that it's necessary now to start ground operations from
NATO,'' Milo said.
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson, the British defense secretary, reiterated NATO's
opposition to a ground war. ``There is no intention to mount a
wholesale, organized, opposed invasion of Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press and Reuters was used in the
preparation of this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
