<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUPREME COURT TO CONSIDER FDA RULES ON TOBACCO
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court said it would decide whether the Food and Drug
Administration has authority to regulate tobacco products as drugs
and cigarettes as ``drug delivery devices.''
</P>
<P>
   In accepting an appeal by the Clinton administration, the court
kept alive the prospect that restrictions the federal agency issued
in 1996 aimed at deterring smoking by minors may still take effect.
A federal appeals court had rejected the restrictions on the
grounds that Congress had not given the FDA the authority to
regulate tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY TO ACQUIRE AUCTION HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   The electronic auction service Ebay agreed to buy Butterfield &AMP;
Butterfield, San Francisco's largest auction house, for $260
million in stock. It was one of the first acquisitions by an
Internet company of a traditional rival.
</P>
<P>
   ARGUMENTS BEGIN IN DISNEY SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney created a secret ``Project Snowball'' in 1991 to
deprive Jeffrey Katzenberg, its film studio chief who left in 1994,
of a bonus if he left the company when his contract ended, his
lawyer said in opening statements of the $250 million
breach-of-contract lawsuit brought by Katzenberg. A top Disney
lawyer denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P 500 HIT RECORDS
</P>
<P>
   Rising technology shares pushed the Nasdaq composite index and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index to records. Nasdaq jumped
61.36 points, or 2.37 percent, to 2,652.05. The S&AMP;P 500 gained 3.19
points, or two-tenths of a percent, to 1,360.04. And the Dow Jones
industrial average rose 28.92 points, or three-tenths of a percent,
to 10,718.59.
</P>
<P>
   GE OF BRITAIN TO BUY FORE SYSTEMS
</P>
<P>
   General Electric Company PLC of Britain agreed to acquire Fore
Systems for $4.5 billion in cash. Fore, of Warrendale, Pa., is a
developer of an advanced technology for data networking.
</P>
<P>
   FDA APPROVES ANTI-OBESITY DRUG
</P>
<P>
   The FDA approved a news class of anti-obesity drugs that block
the absorption of fat, unlike appetite suppressants, which trick
the brain into ignoring hunger. The drug, orlistat, by
Hoffman-LaRoche of Nutley N.J., was approved for seriously
overweight people.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST UNION TO BUY EVEREN CAPITAL
</P>
<P>
   First Union, the nation's sixth-largest bank, agreed to buy
Everen Capital in Chicago for $1.1 billion in stock, its second
acquisition of a securities firm in a year.
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS PLANS RIVAL TO BOEING 737
</P>
<P>
   Airbus Industrie announced that it would build the A318, a
107-seat, $37 million passenger jet that is considered a potential
threat to Boeing's best-selling 737. Airbus, the four-nation
European consortium, said it had $4 billion in commitments for the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-LAMBERT PROFIT UP 36 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert said that its first-quarter profit rose 36
percent as sales almost doubled for Lipitor, the nation's
best-selling drug for reducing cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   ERNST &AMP; YOUNG SETTLES LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young, the big accounting firm, agreed to pay $185
million to settle a lawsuit contending that advice it gave
Merry-Go-Round Enterprises during its bankruptcy to reorganize
rather than liquidate drained cash that could have paid creditors.
</P>
<P>
   FORD PLANS AN AUTO RECYCLING UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor plans to become the world's largest automotive
recycler by buying recyclers and building its own recycling centers
to sell used car and truck parts to body shops, insurers and
consumers. It expects revenue of $1 billion within a few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
