<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENERGY-SFCHRON &LR;      04-26 1448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Life Pumped Into Energy Sector
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Rebecca Smith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Nobody has ridden the stock market bronco with more gusto than
``new economy'' stocks like Microsoft, America Online or Yahoo. And
no ``old economy'' stocks have gotten bucked off more often than
energy companies.
</P>
<P>
   But, with crude oil prices up 60 percent this year and electric
and natural gas industry prospects brightening due to deregulation,
the energy sector is back in the saddle again.
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to say if it will be a stable ride, but some stock
analysts and mutual &LR;   &LR; fund managers are cheered by what they see
some 97 months into a bull market when many other industries appear
overvalued and due a comeuppance.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these facts:
</P>
<P>
   _Crude oil futures surged past $18 a barrel last week, up from a
market price of $11.37 just two months ago. OPEC's decision last
month to cut production is a key reason for the surge.
</P>
<P>
   _There are signs that Asia is emerging from recession, a trend
favoring oil companies and firms that sell energy to businesses
with goods to export.
</P>
<P>
   _Natural gas prices, depressed by two warm winters that produced
slack demand, are rising again. The futures price, for delivery of
contracts next February, is up 15 percent indicating the market
expects firming demand.
</P>
<P>
   _Interest rates remain low, making dividend yields of 7.7
percent for Sempra Energy, formed through the merger of San Diego
Gas and Electric Co. and Southern California Gas Co., attractive.
They also are enticing when compared with the zero-dividend (and,
sometimes, zero-profit) profiles of many Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   _Stock prices for energy sector companies look reasonable by
historic measures. In general, the energy sector has a collective
price-to-earnings ratio (a yardstick of value calculated by
dividing the stock price by earnings per share) that's
three-fourths the size of the P/E ratio for the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index. Currently, it's only half as great as the P/E
ratio of the broader index.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say this may be a good time to put money in a grizzled
sector that, until now, has looked very uncertain. It's not for
everyone, of course. It likely will appeal primarily to ``value''
investors who fear technology stocks are a bubble about to burst
and who are content with returns of 10 to 15 percent per year from
companies in basic, understandable industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many investors got caught up in the Internet frenzy that
there was a lack of excitement last year about anything that didn't
end with `dot.com,''' said Doug Christopher, energy analyst for
Crowell Weedon &AMP; Co. in Los Angeles. ``What I like about this
industry is that what it sells is a necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others sense a shift in the market. In the past two
weeks, some investors have been moving out of technology stocks and
into ``value'' stocks, including those in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
   For most investors, there are three options: Buy stock in
individual companies; buy mutual funds owning some energy stocks;
or buy shares in mutual funds focused exclusively on the oil, gas
or utility sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the energy sector is a tremendous investment right
now,'' says David Kiefer, manager of the nation's largest utility
mutual fund, the Prudential Utility Fund in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Kiefer stuck his neck out last year, repositioning the $4.4
billion fund by putting two-thirds of its assets in electric and
natural gas companies and de-emphasizing telecommunications stocks
even though they &UR;  &LR; have performed well. The fund finished the year
with an anemic 8 percent return. Kiefer is disappointed but not
apologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel strongly that the positioning is correct though I made
the shift a little too early,'' says Kiefer. ``There's tremendous
value there.''
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 is on track to grow 8.5 percent this year, compared
with 6.9 percent for electric utilities and 13.9 percent for
natural gas companies. But electric and gas company stocks sell for
much lower multiples of earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Other fund managers agree there's a golden opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energy has been a contrarian investment until now,'' says
Lawrence Rakers, director of energy funds for mutual fund giant
Fidelity Investments of Boston. ``We're in the early stage of a
rally now.''
</P>
<P>
   His group manages three natural resources and energy mutual
funds that show solid growth this year after a terrible 1998. The
best performing fund _ Fidelity Energy Service Fund _ is up 40
percent so far this year after losing 32 percent of its value last
year. Other Fidelity energy and natural resources funds are up 22
to 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the sector rebounds this year, it will create momentum that
will attract index fund investments. More than $600 billion is
invested in index funds pegged to the S&AMP;P 500, whose stocks
includes most major U.S. energy companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, energy companies comprised 26 percent of the
value of the S&AMP;P 500. But as stock prices and market
capitalizations fell, the energy sector lost ground in the S&AMP;P 500.
Today, energy stocks make up only 5 percent of the value of the S&AMP;P
500.
</P>
<P>
   What significance does this have for energy sector investors?
</P>
<P>
   If the sector rebounds, market valuations will rise and index
dollars will flow back into the stocks, propelling them forward.
That will happen because index funds don't spread their dollars
evenly across a market. They replicate market capitalization.
Companies with high stock prices and lots of shares outstanding get
more attention than companies with lesser market capitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, technology stocks have benefited from the
market-weighted purchases of index funds. America Online, whose
stock gained more than 700 percent last year, joined the S&AMP;P 500
last year.
</P>
<P>
   It now has a market capitalization of $150.5 billion _ nearly
triple that of General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The index fund phenomenon cuts in both directions. It lifts
rising stocks and kicks down falling stocks. For example, PG&AMP;E
Corp.'s stock dropped from a peak of $36.75 in fall 1993 to a low
of $22 in fall 1994 amid uncertainty about deregulation. As its
market capitalization fell 38 percent, index funds reduced their
holdings, adding to PG&AMP;E's weakness.
</P>
<P>
   As PG&AMP;E's price has risen _ it closed yesterday at $31.31 _ it
has attracted more investment from index funds as well as active
fund investors that are looking for good values.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts see room for further growth, though many consider
Sempra Energy or Edison International, the Rosemead (Los Angeles
County) parent of Southern California Edison, a better value right
now.
</P>
<P>
   For all three California companies, the deregulation strategy is
similar. Make the highest return permitted by the California Public
Utilities Commission on their regulated utilities. (A PUC decision,
expected May 13, will set that rate of return at somewhere between
8.6 and 10.6 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   And expand other energy subsidiaries as aggressively as possible
to take advantage of a natural gas market deregulated a decade ago
and an electric generation business only recently deregulated in
many states.
</P>
<P>
   Only 5 percent of PG&AMP;E's revenues now come from nonregulated
businesses. It wants the unregulated side of the house to supply 30
percent of revenues in five years since there's no limitation on
their profit.
</P>
<P>
   For the oil industry, rising crude prices mean better profits.
Equally significant, it is coming in an industry that operates much
more efficiently than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, Chevron spent $15 to $17 to replace each
barrel of oil it took out of the ground. Today, technological
improvements mean it costs only $5 to add a barrel of oil to
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Based on total return, the natural resources sector is up 18.9
percent so far  &LR; this year, second only to the science and
technology sector that's up 23.5 percent. That's a startling
reversal of last year when natural resources _ oil, timber and
paper products, metals and natural gas _ lost 16.3 percent of their
value, propelling marriages like the Amoco-British Petroleum merger
and the Exxon-Mobil merger.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities are lagging as a sector, up 2.6 percent this year,
compared with 10.9 percent growth last year.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, not everyone thinks an uptick in energy will be
lasting.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Kepes, a research director at the energy consulting firm
of Petroleum Finance Group in Washington, D.C., thinks oil prices
are unsustainable at $18 a barrel and will slip to $14 to $17. He
thinks the ``cheater syndrome'' will set in fairly soon, with OPEC
members breaking production limits to reap windfall profits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
