<SLUG> BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 
Need reasons to ink Batesole? Here are 152 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the four years Mike Batesole has been the head
baseball coach at Cal State Northridge, the Matadors have averaged
almost 44 wins per season. He almost took CSUN to the College World
Series in 1996 and he regularly lands some of the area's top prep
players despite playing on a field that is below the standards of
some top high school programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Batesole doesn't have a contract beyond this season. By the
middle of June, the man who has guided CSUN to a 152-83-1 record in
almost four seasons could be coaching somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Senior pitcher Jim DeBiase said he doesn't really understand how
this could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a huge mistake,'' DeBiase said. ``(Batesole) has
given this school national exposure. I don't know why he would want
to put up with this headache anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Batesole is more diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some pretty big things on this university's plate,''
he said, mentioning the search for a new president, athletic
director and a site for a football stadium. ``I think it would be
pretty selfish for me to start waving Mike Batesole's _ or the
baseball program's _ flag.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN interim athletic director Sam Jankovich said he is
confident Batesole will have a new contract by the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we want to get done,'' Jankovich said. ``It's
something we're working on and hopefully we'll get it done. I don't
see a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   If CSUN doesn't keep Batesole beyond June, he will be on a lot
of school's lists for head-coaching vacancies. Fresno State and Cal
might be searching after this season is over.
</P>
<P>
   Batesole was working on a new contract last November when
athletic director Paul Bubb was forced to resign. The Matadors have
won 58 games since the program was cut in 1997, then hastily
reinstated four months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be working for free for a few months this summer,''
Batesole said. ``I hope my contract is done before then because
I'll be working here for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Batesole's first season, CSUN was 52-18 and won the
Western Athletic Conference. A loss to perennial powerhouse Florida
State in the regional final cost him a trip to the College World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were 42-20-1 in '97 and then 37-19 last year
despite the transfers of top pitchers Erasmo Ramirez, Benny Flores
and outfielder Termmel Sledge. Ramirez and Flores were a combined
23-5 for Cal State Fullerton last year. Sledge was the Big West
Player of the Year at Long Beach State.
</P>
<P>
   Batesole also lost the commitment of top recruit Michael
Schultz. The Cleveland High right-hander signed with Loyola
Marymount instead and went on to earn freshman All-America honors
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Collegiate Baseball magazine recognized Batesole's
accomplishment and picked him its coach of the year in '98. Even
though the Matadors are under .500 (22-26) entering today's home
game against Cal Lutheran, his team has overachieved.
</P>
<P>
   __ CSUN has played a strong schedule; last week's win over Cal
State Los Angeles was its first game of the season against a
non-Division I program. Because it is an independent, CSUN has
played against USC, UCLA, Loyola Marymount and Washington in
scheduled series and faced Michigan, UNLV and Texas A&AMP;M in a
tournament in March.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the Matadors' losses have come to three of the country's
top pitchers: Washington's Jeff Heaverlo (twice), Texas A&AMP;M's Casey
Fossum and USC's Barry Zito.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Matadors are inexperienced. Batesole started three
freshmen infielders against Cal State L.A., and the two pitchers
who threw that day _ Michael Rainer and Mike Frick _ are both
freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Loyola Marymount head coach Frank Cruz said Batesole's success
should mean a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think they would want to keep Mike around,'' Cruz
said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oozing talent: One reason Batesole would love to stay at CSUN
is the talent coming out of the San Fernando Valley and its
surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball America recently published its All-America checklist,
and four former high school standouts from the area were listed:
UCLA's Bill Scott (Alemany) was a sophomore first-team selection,
Pepperdine's Woody Cliffords (El Camino Real) was named to the
freshman second team, Stanford's Joe Borchard (Camarillo) was named
to the sophomore second team and Sledge (Granada Hills) was on the
senior second team.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN alumni can only wonder where the program would be if the
Matadors played in a better facility and even half the top recruits
stayed in the Valley. (Batesole did land Granada Hills pitcher
Kameron Loe, ranked by Baseball America as one of its top 100
recruits.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get a stadium and they take us from eight scholarships
to 11.7,'' Batesole said. ``That's kind of what keeps you hanging
on. We don't need the fourth-best stadium in America, but how about
the 100th? How about something you can be proud of?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
