<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLORADO-SHOOTING-HNS     04-26 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORADO-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN'S DIARY REVEALS PLOT TO KILL 500 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The two gunmen in the Columbine High School
massacre intended to kill 500 schoolmates, then take their killing
spree into the neighborhood before commandeering an airplane to
crash into New York City, journal entries indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Police, revealing only some details of the plot, said a diary
kept by gunman Eric Harris described plans that were a year in the
making and called for an extended rampage. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Investigators also said Monday they have questioned and
released an 18-year-old girl who may have helped Harris, 18, and
Dylan Klebold, 17, obtain two of the guns used in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a carbine rifle, a TEC-DC9 assault pistol, two
shotguns and more than 30 homemade bombs, Harris and Klebold
stormed the school April 20. They apparently killed themselves as
SWAT teams surrounded the suburban school southwest of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   During the attack, the two killed 12 students and a teacher and
injured 23 others.
</P>
<P>
   Complete autopsy reports have not been released, but the
Jefferson County coroner said Monday that neither Harris nor
Klebold was under the influence of drugs or alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend of memorials in the community, the mourning
continued Monday with funerals for the teacher and three students.
Mourners gathered at the Trinity Christian Center for teacher
William ``Dave'' Sanders, 47, who was shot twice in the chest as he
helped students to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Services also were held for Lauren Townsend, 18, captain of the
girls' varsity volleyball team; Daniel Rohrbough, 15; and Cassie
Bernall, 17.
</P>
<P>
   According to the handwritten diary investigators found in
Harris' home, the two students, members of a social group called
the ``Trenchcoat Mafia,'' planned their attack for about a year.
Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone described the journal entries
as ``calculated and cold-blooded plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris fantasized in the diary that he and Klebold would kill as
many as 500 students by beginning their attack during lunch when
most students would be in the cafeteria or studying in the library.
About half of the school's 1,900 students were in the cafeteria
when the pair began spraying gunfire and detonating bombs at 11:15
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   But their grander plans were thwarted by the fast action of
police officers in the area, said Jefferson County Sheriff's
spokesman Steve Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have indications in the diary that make us believe that if
in fact they were able to carry out their entire plan there could
have been quite a lot more damage and quite a few more
fatalities,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   He lauded the police response, suggesting ``perhaps some major,
major catastrophies were averted by the action that was taken.''
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen were met with return fire from a sheriff's deputy,
Neil Gardner, who was working security at the school. Other
officers responded to the scene quickly, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a perimeter set up around that school literally
within minutes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities did not release specific excerpts from the diary
showing how Harris and Klebold intended to escape the school campus
to continue with their plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my understanding there was plenty of ammunition with
them,'' Davis said. ``That (killing themselves because they had no
more firepower) wasn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   While investigators believe Harris and Klebold acted alone
during the attack, they have said others may have been involved in
the planning and possibly helped the pair obtain weapons or make
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old girl, described as the girlfriend of Klebold,
was questioned by authorities because they believe she may have
helped the pair get the carbine rifle and semiautomatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
   She was released without charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not enough evidence that we're aware of to classify
her as a suspect,'' Davis said. ``There is no arrest imminent
either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If, through our investigation, it is shown that she, or anyone
else for that matter, either supplied those weapons to the
suspects, especially with knowledge of their intent, the district
attorney has informed us that certainly he's leaving open the
possibility of charging not only her but anyone for that matter
that could be shown that they knew,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said Monday his office had not ruled out the
possibility that one of the gunmen may have shot the other, then
committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great possibility,'' Davis said. ``Obviously we want
to do some ballistic tests, especially with the number of officers
that were returning fire. But none of the officers that returned
fire, at this point, have indicated to us that they actually felt
like they hit any of the suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Jefferson County deputies and at least one Denver officer
shot at the suspects, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said it has not been determined if a 20-pound propane tank
bomb found in the cafeteria had been deliberately fired at by the
gunmen in an attempt to detonate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were indications that they had possibly tried to fire on
that bomb,'' Davis said. ``Whether it was a coincidence that some
of the rounds hit close to it or whether they were trying to
detonate it by firing at it, we may never know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
