<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4162 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GUNS-NYT &LR;      04-26 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO PROPOSE CHARGING PARENTS OF CHILDREN WHO COMMIT GUN
CRIMES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton plans to announce a package of
anti-gun proposals on Tuesday, including measures to halt the
importation of clips that allow assault weapons to fire more than
10 shots at once and to charge parents with a felony if their
children commit crimes with guns.
</P>
<P>
   The package, which would require approval by a Congress that has
fiercely spurned efforts at gun control, would also require people
who sell explosives to conduct the same kind of background check on
buyers that gun dealers must now conduct. Current law prohibits the
sale of explosive devices and ingredients to convicted felons,
fugitives and stalkers, but it does not require the kind of check
that might turn up such a history. The ingredients include TNT,
dynamite, blasting caps and the black powder that is often used in
pipe bombs, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The president is also proposing to extend such checks to people
who buy guns at gun shows. He would make it a felony for adults to
knowingly or recklessly allow children to have guns, and he would
ban violent juveniles from ever being able to buy guns, even when
they turn 21.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes measures that the president has discussed
publicly before, including reinstituting a waiting period before
someone could buy a gun. A five-day wait had been required under
the Brady Act, but it expired last November. The administration is
now calling for a three-day cooling off period, even though most
checks now are instant. He will also propose that gun manufactures
be required to include child-safety locks.
</P>
<P>
   Although the president's proposed legislation comes a week after
the deaths of 15 people in Littleton, Colo., in the biggest school
shooting in the nation's history, administration officials said its
announcement had been been planned for weeks and was not in direct
response.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concern expressed by many in Congress about the
shootings, it is not at all clear that the president's package will
be welcomed on Capitol Hill. Republicans and even some Democrats
have indicated that the emotional gun-control issue is too hot to
handle, particularly as the parties brace for an intense struggle
next year over control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders, House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert of
Illinois and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, are
planning to announce on Tuesday that they want to hold a national
conversation on youth and culture, a clear indication that they
want to focus less on guns and more on social factors that can lead
children to shoot children.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader,
threw cold water Monday on a focus on guns. ``I'm not sure that gun
legislation is what we need,'' he told reporters. Citing the
Internet, the media and a lack of attention paid to students, he
said: ``I think those are the kinds of things we'd better be
looking at if we're going to try to solve what is an increasingly
serious societal problem today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the president's many comments on the Colorado shootings since
last week, he has generally avoided discussing what role the
availability of weapons _ and his long-time nemesis, the National
Rifle Association _ might have played in Littleton. He too has
ruminated over several other possible factors, including the
American culture of violence and the role of the Internet, the
media and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Monday how much Clinton held the gun lobby responsible
for the Littleton shootings, Joe Lockhart, the president's
spokesman, said it was ``premature to somehow try to assign
blame.'' But he went on to say: ``I think there is a consensus in
this country that we need to do more. The president will propose
doing more. And it's time for the NRA to get out of the past and
get on the right side of this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the president's advisers had urged him to hold
back on a discussion of guns in the immediate aftermath of the
Littleton shootings. ``To turn a human tragedy into a political
debate was a mistake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is as aware as anyone of the political risks in taking
on the gun lobby. In 1994, after he forced a ban on assault weapons
through Congress, the Democrats lost control of the House and
Clinton subsequently ascribed the loss to the gun lobby's campaign
against those Democrats who had supported the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fight for the assault-weapons ban cost 20 members their
seats in Congress,'' Clinton said at the time. ``The NRA is the
reason the Republicans control the House.''
</P>
<P>
   The ban on assault weapons included a ban on the importation of
the clips, but had grandfathered in those manufactured before
September 1994. But the administration said that the provision had
failed to work because it was difficult to determine the age of
most imported clips, so it wanted to end the exemption.
</P>
<P>
   The gun lobby had no comment on Monday on Clinton's proposals.
``We will make no public comment until after our annual meeting of
members on May 1,'' said Bill Powers, an NRA spokesman. The meeting
this year is in Denver, just 10 miles from Littleton.
</P>
</TEXT>
