<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4168 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-JONESBORO     04-26 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-JONESBORO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JONESBORO, FROM AN EARLIER SHOOTING, THE ECHOES HAVE YET TO DIE
AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for new lede and new 5th graf; moves up an edited 9th graf,
beginning `Chris Perry...')  
(mb) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ark. _ When Gretchen Woodard heard about the two boys
in Colorado who had shot 12 classmates and a teacher to death, some
of her reactions were those of everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   She thought, ``Where were these boys' parents? How could they
not have known these kids were building bombs in their garage? Why
didn't they pay attention to the trench coats and other warning
signs of trouble?''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Woodard had to stop short of taking comfort in the next
thought on most people's minds, ``My child would never do anything
like that.'' Because, in fact, Ms. Woodard's child did, just last
year, here in Jonesboro.
</P>
<P>
   Her older son, Mitchell Johnson, then 13, was the older of the
two friends who murdered four classmates and a teacher in the
Jonesboro school massacre on March 24, 1998. In the year and a
month since that day, she has had to stop short a lot, learning to
monitor herself at every turn, trying not to say, do or even think
anything that might cause anyone any more pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has made me very humble,'' the 43-year-old Woodard said in
the living room of her tidy, modest home at the end of a country
road, about a mile from Westside Middle School, where her son and
Andrew Golden, 11, staged a false fire alarm and then began
shooting from nearby woods as children exited the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the last person to sit in judgment of other people,'' Ms.
Woodard said, her 3-year-old daughter, Jessie, beside her, playing
with a ladybug. But she knows it would be easy for others to judge
her, because ``it is human nature to have questions and point your
finger.''
</P>
<P>
   Her younger son, Monte, 12, has also had to learn to live in the
shadow of his brother's deed. When Monte, a sixth-grader, walks
down the halls at Westside, where pictures of the shooting victims
adorn the walls, he carries all his books and supplies in his arms,
in full view. He decided soon after the shooting not to wear a
backpack, because he thought it would scare the other students
every time he reached inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, Monte was angry at his brother for doing something
so stupid, so senseless,'' Ms. Woodard said. ``He cried and I just
held him and he kept asking why. I couldn't begin to explain. I was
too overwhelmed with the horror of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry, a youth minister at Central Baptist Church, where
Monte attends a youth group meeting every Wednesday night, has seen
Ms. Woodard and her sons through some of that horror. Often in the
last year, he has counseled Mitchell Johnson in jail, both here and
at the juvenile detention center in the town of Alexander, a
three-hour drive to the southwest, where both Mitchell and Andrew,
convicted of murder in a juvenile court, may be held until they are
21.
</P>
<P>
   ``That family feels a whole buffet of emotions,'' he said.
``Fear of retaliation. Social shame. A struggle to maintain their
own dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodard said she does not try to defend or explain her son's
behavior. ``For so long afterward I blamed myself,'' she said.
``You question everything _ your sense of right and wrong, even
your TV. And all of a sudden, your whole life, whether it be good
or bad, is put under a microscope and everybody is saying, `Well,
you watched that television show two months ago, and it's because
you played a video game, it's because your son listens to rap
music.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Who amongst us can hold up for very long under that pressure?
That is something I know those parents in Littleton will have to
deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodard has heard people blame her son's participation in
the shooting on her divorce from his father after a 15-year
marriage. Soon afterward, she remarried. She has been faulted for
teaching her son to shoot a rifle so he could go hunting, just as
she did when she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the sexual abuse of her son and his brother by a
neighborhood teen-ager when they lived in Minnesota, which she
learned about only when her ex-husband revealed it to Barbara
Walters on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too easy to point your finger and blame the family,''
Perry, the youth minister, said. ``Is Gretchen a good parent? Yes.
Is she flawless? No. Is she evil? No. Does she care for and love
her kids? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, both Monte and his mother have been buoyed and a
little surprised by the kindness of the Westside students and
teachers. ``I mean, I wouldn't have been surprised if people had
wanted to spit on me or yell at me,'' Ms. Woodard said. ``But that
hasn't ever happened. It has been our blessing that this community
has let us go on.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of school this fall, 12-year-old Candace
Porter, 12, who survived a bullet that ballistics tests proved came
from the gun of Monte's brother, sat down next to Monte in the
cafeteria, hugged him, and told him she would always be his friend.
</P>
<P>
   Another person wounded in the shooting, Lynette Thetford, is
Monte's social studies teacher. ``I really thought at first, `Why
doesn't his mother take him away from here?''' she said. ``Now I
know why she didn't. He fits in well with the kids here and they
accept him. And he seems to be handling it well. He is a strong
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Monte is learning to play the trumpet and Ms. Woodard is vice
president of the band boosters at Westside. On his last report
card, Monte got all A's. And for a citywide Saturday honors program
for which each school in the Jonesboro area can sponsor one pupil,
Westside picked Monte.
</P>
<P>
   Still, each good thing feels bittersweet. Whenever Ms. Woodard
referred to the day of the shooting, her normally warm and open
face froze into a stunned, pained look and she whispered, ``March
24th of '98.
</P>
<P>
   As she talked, Ms. Woodard struggled to hold back tears. Her
daughter, Jessie seemed used to that. She put down the French fries
she was eating, hopped onto her mother's lap, gave her a huge hug,
took her mother's face in her hands and said, ``Please mama, don't
be sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodard is careful to point out that even her daughter's
love reminds her that the families of her son's victims cannot hold
their children that way. ``No amount of `I'm sorry's' can make up
for it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynette Thetford, the teacher who was shot, said she felt for
Ms. Woodard. ``There is no closure for her, and not many people to
comfort her,'' she said. ``I truly believe I would rather have my
child die than do something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But just as Ms. Woodard and Monte have learned to do, Ms.
Thetford stopped herself short, and then tempered her words: ``Of
course, if I had lost my child, I might feel a different way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BERKOW-COLUMN-ART     04-26 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BERKOW-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PERSEVERANCE PAID OFF BIG FOR ELWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As quarterback for the Denver Broncos for the last 16 years,
John Elway has lost two miles and maybe three city blocks during
football games, or 3,780 yards. This is a National Football League
record for going backward.
</P>
<P>
   He has had more people pounce on him more frequently than any
other quarterback in NFL history, having been sacked 516 times.
Another record. This means that no one wearing the livery of an NFL
team has ever had to rise _ head inside his helmet ringing like the
Liberty Bell, bones jiggling like a Halloween skeleton in the wind
_ and wobble to the huddle to try again, and again.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the notorious Super Bowls. His first was in
1987, when the Broncos lost to the Giants. His second was in 1988,
when the Broncos lost to Washington. His third was in 1990, when
the Broncos lost to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He may have been excused for thinking at times, ``I should have
stayed with baseball.'' He was the Yankees' first draft choice in
June 1981. He played one year in the Yankee minor league system,
after his junior year at Stanford, and surely learned valuable pro
lessons about disappointment and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   John Elway, who will be 39 years old on June 28, has announced
that he will officially retire Sunday. It would have come already
but for the high school tragedy in the Denver suburb of Littleton.
He believed rightly and sensitively that his announcement might
draw attention at a totally inappropriate time.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, not only did Elway return to games in which he was
repeatedly knocked down, physically and otherwise, but he also
became the winningest quarterback in history, with a record of 148
victories, 82 losses and 1 tie, a .643 winning percentage, just
ahead of the Dolphins' Dan Marino in victories and percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not always play my best,'' he said after the third Super
Bowl, and looking for some light at the end of the tunnel, ``but I
always play my hardest. I'm competing all the way until the
scoreboard clock reads zero-zero-zero.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is no secret that he returned for a fourth time to the
Super Bowl, in 1998, and won it, at the tender age of 37, risking
loin and limb, to scramble and dive for a crucial first down late
in the 31-24 victory over highly favored Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' owner, Pat Bowlen, was so moved by Elway's
professionalism, resilience and, well, dotage, that when handed the
1998 Super Bowl trophy after the game, he said, ``This one's for
John.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder if you're going to run out of years,'' Elway said.
``But fortunately I hung on.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Elway came back to lead Denver to a second straight Super
Bowl championship over Atlanta in January.
</P>
<P>
   If a sports figure can legitimately be viewed as a model of
something positive _ an increasingly difficult stance in today's
sports world _ John Elway is a prime candidate. Elway has become a
living symbol of refusing to be defeated by defeat. As a pro, it
began in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Elway was an outstanding outfielder and hitter for Stanford, and
with, not surprisingly, a bazooka for an arm. In the summer of '82,
after his junior year in college, he signed with the Yankees for a
$140,000 bonus. He would return that fall to again play football at
Stanford. But at Oneonta, N.Y., the 6-foot-3-inch, 205-pound
all-America quarterback wondered early on what he had got into, a
kind of harbinger for his football career.
</P>
<P>
   For the first week and a half he had just 1 hit in his first 22
at-bats. ``And the fans were on him _ some of it was pretty
vicious,'' Suzanne Nader, then the team general manager, said,
``and the paper here, The Daily Star, each day had a `Where's Our
Golden Boy?' story.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Boy showed up. He played an excellent right field,
throwing runners out with the accuracy of his touchdown tosses. And
he wound up batting a a promising .318 in 42 games, with 4 homers
and 25 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The question after his senior year was: Would it be baseball or
football? ``It's a thrill to throw a touchdown pass,'' he said,
``but there's nothing like hitting a home run.'' He was the No. 1
pick in the 1983 NFL draft, and decided on football. Perhaps that
was where his heart was, and his dad's _ Jack Elway was head
football coach at San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hated to lose John,'' George Steinbrenner recalled
yesterday. ``He was a good ballplayer and a good citizen. While he
didn't have all the tools of a Derek Jeter, he had the right ethics
and the right understanding, and he would have made himself a star
in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he believe Elway made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding!?'' Steinbrenner asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
