<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4171 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KINGS-WILLIAMS-AR     04-26 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KINGS-WILLIAMS-ART-397&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS GAME, AND NAME, CREATE STIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(kd) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ It began innocuously enough, with a media
relations assistant asking a rookie point guard if he had a
nickname yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about White Chocolate?'' Stephanie Shepard said while
putting together a player biography in January for the Sacramento
Kings media guide.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Williams laughed. He is white. His game had been called
sweet. Why not? he figured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up with that name because of his style,'' Shepard, who
is black, said. ``He has flash and pizazz. The way he does things
with the ball is incredible to me. It reminds me of, like,
schoolyard street ball when I go to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of some footage I've seen of Pistol Pete
Maravich, I've never seen any white kid play like Jason. John
Stockton is wonderful in his way. But Jason is like every kid I've
seen on the playground.''
</P>
<P>
   From that point, the phenomenon of the flashy playmaker and the
not-so-subtle nickname took off and created their own little
two-on-one break against stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Everything has not unfolded smoothly, though. Williams, who
embraced the nickname early on, has lately come to regard it more
warily, worried that the attention surrounding the nickname has
become a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' organization, made uncomfortable by the nickname's
highlighting that a white player has what is perceived as a black
game, has discouraged it. And Williams' agent prays for it to fade
away altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Still, White Chocolate is out there, growing to be as much a
part of the National Basketball Association lexicon as Mailman or
Magic. And so Williams' nickname as much as his game _ complete
with stutter steps, no-look passes, behind-the-back flourishes _
has the league buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   Many young black youngsters who turn up to see Williams play _
youngsters who might not have seen Maravich play before he retired
in 1980 _ say he is the coolest white player they have ever seen,
and they view White Chocolate as evidence of Williams' embrace of,
and acceptance in, the hip-hop culture. The Kings, through their
public relations director, have recommended that local broadcasters
not use it, and the team's play-by-play announcer has generally
done so.
</P>
<P>
   One consequence of the unease was a contest to replace the name
conducted on ESPN's Web site. The winner? Thrilla in Vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, that did not solve the matter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Williams' game, though, is not merely about flair. He is
averaging 13 points, 6 assists and 3 rebounds a game, and his
production as a first-year player is rivaled only by Toronto's
Vince Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Full of confidence, Williams, the seventh selection in last
year's draft, often launches 3-pointers within two dribbles after
he crosses midcourt. He takes flight and then does not decide what
to do until he begins to come down. According to a recent sales
survey of NBA apparel, Williams' No. 55 jersey is among the
league's top five sellers this season.
</P>
<P>
   And in a lockout-ruptured season, the Kings have experienced a
13 percent increase in attendance _ tops in the NBA _ and the club
is currently in position to make the playoffs for only the third
time since the franchise moved to Sacramento from Kansas City in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   And so it might be reasonable to ask how a 23-year-old from
Belle, W.Va., has keyed a team's revival and unintentionally
initiated a kind of informal, often uncomfortable conversation
regarding long-held assumptions about basketball and race.
</P>
<P>
   Inventing passes and shots that seem to materialize more out of
his imagination than his body, Williams effectively parachuted into
the NBA from nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Williams grew up in rural Belle (pop. 1,421), which is adjacent
to the predominantly black town of Rand. To get the best
competition growing up, he ventured to the Rand playground and to
the Charleston recreation center.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say I've got a game like a black person,''
Williams said. ``Guarding those guys was more of a challenge to me
'cause they talked more trash, especially with me being the only
white player on the court playing with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day I went out, I was scared. I'm not going to lie
to you. There was a different person coming at me, picking on me,
every day. People said so many things to me. There was a couple
other white guys that would show up, but they struggled to get on
the court, so I was pretty much the only one.''
</P>
<P>
   Two memorable plays this season are at the heart of the hype
around Williams.
</P>
<P>
   There was his cross-over dribble to get by a stunned Gary Payton
of the Seattle SuperSonics earlier in the season, a move endlessly
replayed on the highlight shows.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the move he executed on Feb. 25. At the MCI
Center in Washington, Williams drove to the basket and faked a
behind-the-back pass in midair. With the defense frozen, he brought
the ball back around to the front of his body and lofted a soft
layup toward the rim. The shot rolled out, but the crowd ultimately
gave Williams a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason deserves the attention because he's one of best
ballplayers out there, regardless of color,'' Chris Webber,
Williams' teammate, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when Allen did it his rookie year, he was viewed as a
thug,'' Webber said, referring to Allen Iverson, the NBA's leading
scorer and most improvisational player. ``That's all I'll say. It's
just society. I don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has tried not to spend too much time analyzing it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me if it bothers me,'' Williams said of his
nickname. ``It doesn't bother me because I've been stuck with
nicknames all my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever look at a person because of their color. I judge
a person on who you are, how you act.''
</P>
<P>
   Others feel differently. Some worry that the nickname reinforces
the stereotype of black athleticism. Others think it is doing to
whites what hurtful racial stereotyping has long done to blacks in
this country: broadly implying what a racial group is supposed to
be capable of doing and what it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, as Williams warmed up before a game against the
Clippers at the Los Angeles Sports Arena, several young black
teen-agers shouted his name.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Mitchell, 15, of Ontario, Calif., said, ``He got game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
