<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD CURB ONLINE WEAPONS SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As an aide sitting at a computer clicked through Web
sites showing automatic handguns, assault rifles and other weapons
for sale on the Internet, Sen. Charles Schumer on Monday urged
Congress to enact a law to further regulate the online gun trade.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, a New York Democrat, introduced the bill, The Internet
Gun Trafficking Act of 1999, in March and received little
attention. But Monday he said the high school shooting in
Littleton, Colo., had given urgency to the bill, and he hoped it
would win swift support.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication that two students responsible for the
Colorado shooting purchased their guns online, but Schumer said he
believed the Internet offered children the easiest means for
circumventing state and federal gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two glaring loopholes that allow kids and criminals
to get guns,'' Schumer said, ``and those are gun shows and the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure would require Web sites dedicated to gun sales to be
maintained by a federally licensed firearms dealer. The sites would
have to be registered with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms, and would prohibit the sites from transmitting
information that might encourage transactions without a licensed
dealer.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law was denounced Monday by gun dealers who said
that nearly all of Schumer's concerns were addressed by existing
laws. Richard Feinberg, a licensed dealer in Norton, Mass., who
operates We Are Guns, one of the Web sites discussed by Schumer
Monday, said he was required to follow all state and federal laws
for sales by computer and in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``The laws are already in place,'' Feinberg said, adding that
the lack of consistent laws nationwide was a more important
concern.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law is also likely to come under attack from free
speech and free trade advocates who do not see any difference
between a gun sold online and a gun sold through a newspaper or
magazine advertisement or by mail-order catalog. ``It's hard for me
to understand why the Internet would make in essence an illegal
transaction easier or harder to do,'' said Eric J. Johnson, the
director of the Forum for Electronic Commerce at the University of
Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer said his measure would insure that licensed dealers
and gun purchasers meet in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are 14 years old and you want to buy a gun directly
through the Internet, right now, no one is going to know your
age,'' Schumer said. ``But under my legislation, you would have to
show up at the gun shop and a licensed dealer would have to give
you the gun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
