NYT-04-26-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0427-1     04-26 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0427-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: recasts lede to reflect Clinton calling up reservists;
updates throughout
 &HT;    APACHE CRASH DOESN'T SLOW NATO BOMBING, NEW OPENING FOR
DIPLOMACY
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0427.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is expected to announce Tuesday
the call-up of 30,000 reservists from all services of the military
in the single largest escalation yet of NATO's attack on
Yugoslavia, now in its fifth week.
</P>
<P>
   It would likely be several days before the first of the
reservists receive formal orders to report for duty, but Clinton
was poised to announce his backing for a request from the NATO
commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, for the reservists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing will be signed, sealed and delivered,'' on
Tuesday, said a senior Pentagon official, speaking on background.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the need for aircraft crews and support staff, the
Pentagon has not specified what sorts of reservists might be called
up, but there is also a broad array of Army capability that relies
heavily on reservists -- experienced military personnel no longer
serving full-time but retained for contingency purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In a harrowing reminder of the perils the continuing campaign
poses, a U.S. Army Apache attack helicopter crashed and burned in
Albania Monday night during a training flight in preparation for
combat missions inside neighboring Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot and co-pilot escaped serious injury, were rescued and
flown in an army medical helicopter to a temporary military
hospital at the makeshift NATO airfield near the Albanian capital
of Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial reports indicate that they're in good condition,''
said Pentagon spokesman Bryan Whitman. He did not release the names
of the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The $60-million Apache, built to fly low and fast in the pursuit
of tanks, was the second U.S. aircraft to be lost since NATO
launched air strikes against Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The crash occurred two miles north of the base built over the
past week for the Apaches at the Rinas Air Field outside Tirana,
said Whitman. He said he had no details on the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 24 Apaches has been assembling in Tirana in recent
days as Task Force Hawk. They have yet to fly combat missions
inside the embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo, but were expected
to be ordered soon to strike at Serb troops deployed there.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced Monday that an additional 30 large
refueling tankers would be flown to NATO bases this weekend. They
are the first of a total of 300 warplanes and support craft Clark
requested earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The additional tankers will help NATO step up attacks on
bridges, oil and ammunition storage facilities, Serb troops and
tanks in the field and other military targets, all part of a
campaign designed to coerce Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, the
president of Yugoslavia, into agreeing to NATO's terms for peace
with Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to press that goal forward through diplomacy, U.S. Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott is in Moscow for a Tuesday
meeting with Russian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's special envoy to Yugoslavia and former prime minister
Victor Chernomyrdin held extensive talks with Milosevic last week
in Belgrade, amid signs that the Serb leader might be prepared to
make some concessions to end the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In a faint but welcomed ray of hopeful news, Milosevic allowed
International Committee of the Red Cross chief Cornelio Sommaruga
to meet for 15 minutes with three American soldiers held captive in
Yugoslavia since March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked into each other's eyes and shook hands very
warmly,'' Sommaruga told reporters. A Red Cross doctor and
representative were scheduled to meet for a longer period with the
three Americans on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the Red Cross meeting was welcomed, but
still did not meet the standards set forth in the Geneva Convention
for the treatment of troops captured amid hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty five days late, they have had a chance to review the
Geneva Convention and have found a way to, in however bare and
minimum form, start the process of doing what the Geneva Convention
demands,'' said White House spokesman Joseph Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of possible cracks in Milosevic's regime, Yugoslav
Deputy Premier Vuk Draskovic called on the government to ``stop
lying to the people in Serbia,'' and admit that it can no longer
sustain further NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people should be told that NATO is not facing a breakdown,
that Russia will not help Yugoslavia militarily and that the world
public opinion is against us,'' Draskovic, a former opposition
leader co-opted by Milosevic, said on local Studio B television.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference later Monday, Draskovic said his country
should accept the presence of a NATO peacekeeping force in Kosovo,
if it is approved by the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of such a force is a key NATO demand for halting
the bombing. So far, Milosevic has refused to permit such a force,
saying it would amount to a military occupation and a violation of
Yugoslav sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal right is to wish no participation of NATO
countries in U.N. peacekeeping forces in Kosovo,'' Draskovic said.
``But if the Security Council of the U.N. says the U.N. mission
must composed on the basis of part of NATO countries, we must
respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials were skeptical and unsure whether the
remarks were meant to signal that Milosevic was seeking a
face-saving way out of the conflict or whether they meant nothing
at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vuk Draskovic is no friend of NATO,'' said NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea. ``But at least, the statements that he made . . . show
that there are senior members of the Yugoslav government that are
beginning to recognize the reality of the situation that Yugoslavia
is in.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin said it was Talbott's
mission to try to ferret out any possible diplomatic openings --
provided the solution meets NATO's key demands. Those are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  an end to Serb repression in Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the admission of an international peacekeeping force with NATO
at its ``core'';
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the guarantee of safe return for more than one million ethnic
Albanians estimated to have been run from their homes by Serb
forces;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  a political settlement that guarantees autonomy for Kosovo's
majority ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We and Russia have agreed on many of the objectives . . . they
basically entail getting the refugees who were expelled back and
creating a situation where the Serb forces, the military police and
paramilitary forces are out,'' said Rubin. ``With respect to what
an international force would look like, we have not yet agreed with
Russia. We believe that it must be a credible international force
with NATO at its core.''
</P>
<P>
   Absent that, said Rubin, ``we do not believe the Kosovar
Albanians will return.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows).
</P>
<P>
   The Apache that crashed Monday followed the loss of an American
F-117 Nighthawk stealth fighter-bomber -- the Pentagon has yet to
state the cause -- on March 27 outside of Belgrade. The pilot was
rescued and wasn't seriously harmed.
</P>
<P>
   During nearly 10,500 sorties, the NATO air campaign has had an
overall loss rate ``well below what we've sustained in training
missions,'' Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald told reporters at the
Pentagon on Monday, several hours before the crash of the Apache.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred at around 10:30 p.m. local time, Whitman
said, as the helicopter -- the army's most advanced -- was
returning from what he described as ``a routine training mission.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 22 other Apaches based in Albania as part of Task
Force Hawk. Another Apache -- the 24th -- developed mechanical
problems en route to Albania from its base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches are built to fly fast and low -- training exercises
are often carried out at treetop level and below -- to enable them
to destroy tanks, artillery and military forces in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The additional refueling tankers the Pentagon announced Monday
will bring to roughly 650 the number of U.S. aircraft involved in
Operation Allied Force, the air campaign that began more than a
month ago to combat Serb repression targeting the majority ethnic
Albanians of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces struck up and down the length and breadth of
Yugoslavia on Monday, dropping the last of five major bridge across
the Danube River at the country's second largest city, Novi Sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bridge is now destroyed, and there is no longer any
traffic across the Danube there,'' said Shea.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NATO forces attacked the Sombor airfield in
northeast Yugoslavia, two early-warning radar systems near Belgrade
and roughly a dozen Serb tanks, armored personnel carriers and
military trucks deployed across Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Wald showed military imagery of a full range of U.S. warplanes
lambasting targets across Yugoslavia over the past several days,
including an F-117 destroying a television and radio transmission
tower in southern Serbia and an F-15 dropping the last railroad and
highway bridge in Novi Sad into the Danube with an optically-guided
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Milosevic's) forces are starting to take a pretty good hit in
the field, particularly,'' Wald said. ``But you add that up to the
fact that he can't sustain the force, he has no ammunition, his
command and control is going down -- all, in the meantime, while we
add forces -- it's
</P>
<P>
   starting to hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite nearly five weeks of NATO bombing, however, Serb troops
and police continued to be active across much of Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   NATO military spokesman, Col. Konrad Freytag of Germany, told
reporters here that Serb troops shelled civilians and homes in
southwest Kosovo on Sunday, and continued to loot villages and
terrorize ethnic Albanians elsewhere across the province.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990426.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-26 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
