<HEADER>
A4186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOD-FASHION-ART-NYT &LR;      04-26 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOD-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EMPIRE OF LEATHER GOODS STILL DRIVEN BY A DRIVING SHOE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shoes and bags, not clothes, are the status symbols
of the moment. Think Fendi. Think Gucci. Think Prada.
</P>
<P>
   Think J.P. Tod's, another line of leather goods from Italy that
has entered the fashion consciousness much more recently than those
venerable brands. Although the Della Valle shoe company was founded
75 years ago by a cobbler named Filippo Della Valle, it took his
grandson Diego to build it into an international presence.
</P>
<P>
   It was about 15 years ago that Diego Della Valle came to New
York with shoe samples in a trunk and set up a temporary showroom
in a hotel room. He spoke not a word of English, but the shoes
spoke for themselves, and soon stores like Bergdorf Goodman and
Bloomingdale's were selling them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, he opened a store and showroom in SoHo for his own
shoes and those he manufactured for designers like Gianfranco Ferre
and Azzedine Alaia. A small table in the store displayed a driving
shoe _ a soft leather moccasin with rubber pebbles on the sole that
continued up the heel. He christened it with the American-sounding
name J.P. Tod's.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, the Tod's were so successful, spawning imitations, that
they overshadowed the classic Della Valle shoes. The original line
was phased out and the driving shoe inspired offshoots. The SoHo
store was closed and replaced with one just for J.P. Tod's at 41
East 57th St. Two years later there was a Tod's on Rodeo Drive to
cater to a growing contingent of Hollywood stars like Sharon Stone,
Denzel Washington and Michael Douglas who had become customers
after having been given pairs.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, a J.P. Tod's bag that resembled an elegant
leather shopping tote appeared, and soon it was draped over the
arms of Catherine Deneuve, Princess Caroline of Monaco, Kristin
Scott Thomas and Diana, Princess of Wales (further examples of
``Send it and they will wear it''). The bag, too, soon inspired
copies, and other styles were added.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years or so, Bergdorf's, Neiman Marcus and Saks
Fifth Avenue have found their customers requesting Tod's products.
``It's a new kind of status,'' said Nicole Fischelis, the fashion
director of Saks. ``It's about quiet luxury and comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Kaner, vice president and fashion director of Neiman's,
said Tod's was a key source. ``I think it's typical of what's
happening in fashion at Neiman Marcus,'' she said. ``Our customer
insists on luxury, and Tod's are luxury. The products have an
off-handed elegance and timelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the celebrity quotient, not to be ignored
today. Both the shoes and evening versions of the bags make regular
trips to the Academy Awards and the Golden Globes _ the shoes on
men like Matt Damon and Tom Hanks, the bags on Madonna, Candice
Bergen and Charlize Theron. The shoes themselves have appeared on
screen in ``The Horse Whisperer,'' ``Great Expectations'' and will
be seen in the forthcoming ``Entrapment,'' with Sean Connery, and
in the remake of ``The Thomas Crown Affair.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Della Valle has never been shy about promoting his products.
The company's public relations staff includes people whose job it
is to court celebrities and stylists, offering to make them shoes
or bags for special occasions and to work with movie studios for
product placement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the driving shoe is the cornerstone of the company,
Della Valle doesn't claim to have invented it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty, 35 years ago, there were shoes people used for
driving,'' he said. ``They were similar to Tod's. We studied all
the technicalities to make the shoes very good for walking. For
driving it's like a joke, but people know them for walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Della Valle recently bought another handbag factory because, he
said, he can't keep up with demand. The popular tote, which starts
at $1,200, has waiting lists of customers: both the tanning process
and the manufacture are time consuming. Those waiting lists, of
course, add to the mystique and increase desirability. Shoulder
bags in other shapes have been added for fall in a range of colors
and materials.
</P>
<P>
   Small leather goods and belts are recent additions, with a line
of luggage in the works. (The company also makes less expensive
casual shoes called Hogan, which have their own stores in 20
cities, but not yet in New York.) Annual wholesale volume last year
for all Della Valle's products was about $500 million, the company
says.
</P>
<P>
   Della Valle recently turned over the day-to-day operation of the
business to Andrea, his younger brother, leaving him free to think
big for the future. The easing of some responsibilities has given
him more time to enjoy the homes he owns in the Italian countryside
and on Capri, not to mention his yacht, helicopter and airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Tod's isn't the only company he is involved with. A few years
ago Della Valle entered into partnership with a friend, Luca di
Montezemolo, the president of Ferrari. Together, they have bought
Web eyewear and, more noteworthy, Acqua di Parma, which they
transformed from an obscure line of luxury bath products to an
international success story. ``It's No. 1 in our men's store,'' Ms.
Mello reported.
</P>
<P>
   Every other major leather goods company has entered the
ready-to-wear field in recent years, but Della Valle said he had no
such plans. But he does own Fay Outerwear, a line of coats and
jackets that is sold only in Europe. So far, anyway. As Ms. Mello
said, he's never standing still.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
