<SLUG> BC-BBN-HUNDLEY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY FEELS GREAT, BUT HIS NUMBERS ARE HURTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Todd Hundley aches and it has nothing to do with
his surgically reconstructed right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers catcher's pain comes from his
performance, not his health, which was the biggest question coming
into the season.
</P>
<P>
   The question now centers on Hundley's ability. He's hitting just
.160 and as bad as that is, he's even worse when it comes to
throwing out runners (9.1 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got bad mojo working right now,'' Hundley said. ``Every
year I start kind of slow. But to be honest with you, physically, I
haven't felt this good in years. That's the frustrating part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley remains businesslike on the field, but the personality
that's made him one of the most popular players has been muted by
his slump. He's not as active in the clubhouse and he's quieter
around the batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little brief chat (Sunday),'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``He wanted to let me know he was feeling really good
physically, and not to worry about the problems he's having behind
the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too early for the team to panic, but when one of the team's
primary power sources isn't producing and the defense is slipping,
eyebrows become raised.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said it all dates back to Hundley not being available
most of the spring. He said Hundley was in ``terrible'' shape when
spring training began.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was probably 50 percent or 60 percent at the start of the
season _ baseball, timing and skill-wise,'' Johnson said. ``I just
couldn't give him any innings (in the spring). He had to get it in
at the start of the season. That's not the way you want to do it,
but we had no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the team could have kept him in extended spring
training or sent him on a minor-league rehab assignment. Neither
the Dodgers nor Hundley wanted to do either, so Hundley began the
year in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers pitchers said Hundley is calling games well and he's
blocking pitches in the dirt. But his throwing is an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   He's thrown out two of 22 base stealers, and both of those were
San Diego Padres who overslid second base. Often, his throws sail
into center field _ he's already made four errors in 13 games. In
his prime with the New York Mets, he averaged less than seven
errors a season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Hundley isn't being aggressive enough throwing the
ball, waiting back for the ball instead of moving forward to meet
the pitch and make the throw to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's pressing,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
said. ``I feel for him because I know how much he cares. He's
working his butt off. Catching and calling a game, I think he's as
good as anybody. We also have to hold runners better. I see arm
strength, but it's more mechanical when he throws.''
</P>
<P>
   At the plate, he hasn't been much better. The switch-hitter who
set the major-league record for homers by a catcher with 41 in
1996, has two homers and four RBI. When he was acquired from the
Mets in December, there was talk about Hundley hitting in the
cleanup spot and how his left-handed bat would break up the row of
righties that's been part of the Dodgers' lineup seemingly forever.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's fallen to eighth in the batting order. He hasn't
started against a left-hander since opening day and is 0 for 7 from
the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, there have been signs Hundley is close to breaking out
of his batting funk. He's working pitchers deep into the count,
fouling pitches straight back (a sign his timing is better) and
he's hitting the ball hard more often. All of which gives Hundley
hope that the end of the slump is near.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game of baseball can be very humbling and right now I'm
being humbled,'' Hundley said. ``When you're going through bad
stretches like I am, you have to keep your head up. It's
frustrating, but with what's going on in Colorado and what's going
on in Kosovo, there's a lot worse things in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Put in those terms, it seems trivial to wonder why Hundley can't
hit a horsehide-covered ball or throw someone out at second.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it's what he is supposed to do. And he knows he's not
performing well right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
