<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO KILL A SCRUB JAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, April 28)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have always been a big fan of mockingbirds.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1, they are one of the few birds I can identify without the
help of a bird book. Trim. Gray. Conspicuous white wing patches
visible in flight. (Actually, I got that last part out of a bird
book, but let us not quibble.)
</P>
<P>
   No. 2, mockingbirds often build nests in one or more of the low
trees in my yard, which gets me out of the chores of pruning and
mowing, at least for a short time.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3, and most important, mockingbirds have more voices than a
U.N. debate. I have heard the sounds of a piano, siren, squeaky
gate and barking dog emerge from the same mockingbird at different
times.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, a mockingbird reminded me of the conversations I
often have with my car mechanic. It was going, ``Doohicky!
Doohicky! Doohicky!''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that all these voices inside their heads make
mockingbirds a little crazy. Despite its slender build, a
mockingbird is fearless and will wade in with a blue jay, crow or
even a cat. If you are careless or unwise enough to disturb its
nest, a mockingbird will attack you, too. I have seen smokers throw
down their cigarettes to escape a dive-bombing mockingbird, which
should tell you all you need to know about their ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   I come in praise of mockingbirds because there was a move afoot
(aflight?) to dethrone the mockingbird as the official state bird
of Florida, an office it has occupied competently if not
necessarily quietly since 1927. The proposed change does not have
the support needed to pass in either the House or the Senate this
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   The upstart challenger was the Florida scrub jay, a threatened
species and poster bird for environmentalists. (There are only
about 2,100 scrub jays in Florida today, or approximately one scrub
jay for every mockingbird voice impersonation.)
</P>
<P>
   Many Floridians, myself included, have never seen a scrub jay,
most of which live in the central part of the state and on land
surrounding the Kennedy Space Center. Mockingbirds, on the other
hand, can be found in every back yard from Key West to Pensacola.
When the grandchildren come to visit, you can just stab your
liver-spotted finger in the direction of the ficus tree and croak,
``Lookee there, kiddies! It's the mockingbird! The state bird of
Florida!'' (This will be of no interest to your grandchildren, of
course. But I still think abundance and widespread distribution
work in favor of the incumbent.) Score one point for the
mockingbird.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of the scrub jay show it to be smaller and less boldly
colored than its cousin, the blue jay, but still more flashy than
the mockingbird, which has all the eye appeal of a trench coat.
Score half a point for the scrub jay.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the scrub jay say it is a friendly bird that will
light on your shoulder and even eat a seed out of your hand. I do
not take this as a particularly good quality in a wild bird; it
could help explain why the species is threatened. I know people who
have made friends with a mockingbird, but most of the time the only
reason a mockingbird will land on your shoulder is to get a clearer
shot at your eyes. Point: mockingbird.
</P>
<P>
   Insects, berries and seeds comprise the diet of both birds. But,
since mockingbirds outnumber scrub jays a zillion to one,
mockingbirds eat a zillion times more insects. Point: mockingbird.
</P>
<P>
   The mockingbird is the state bird in four states besides Florida
(Arkansas, Mississippi, Tennessee and Texas). Enthusiasts of the
scrub jay, which is found only in Florida, see this as a bad thing.
To me, it just shows that a lot of other states recognize a great
state bird when they see one. Point: mockingbird.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the song part. (See ya, scrub jay.) I have listened to a
recording of a scrub jay's song and it sounds, to me, like the
tines of a rake scratching on a sidewalk. A mockingbird could copy
the sound, and probably do it better, while taking a drink of water
or coughing up an acorn. Game, set, match: mockingbird.
</P>
<P>
   I wish the scrub jay nothing but the best of luck. It will need
that and more if it is to survive. But it's people, not
mockingbirds, that are the cause of the scrub jay's plight. Let the
mockingbird remain the official state bird of Florida. It is, after
all, the only bird that can imitate the sound of a bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
