<SLUG> BC-JASPER-SLAYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL SETS STAGE FOR MOVING SECOND JASPER TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Texas) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUMONT, Texas _ In a surprise development Monday, the
prosecutor and defense attorneys involved in the second capital
murder trial in the brutal dragging death of a black man agreed on
moving the trial, possibly to the Central Texas town of Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Although a judge ruled last Thursday that the trial of Russell
Brewer Jr., 32, of Sulphur Springs, would not be moved, Jasper
County District Attorney Guy James Gray said Monday he is agreeing
to move the trial out of an abundance of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reversible issue they have in this thing is the
change of venue,'' Gray said. He said he favored the move as long
as it didn't significantly delay the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's trial was set last week for May 17, but Gray said it
would be put off until July or August if moved to Georgetown,
because that is when a courtroom would be available there.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the trial to Georgetown, 25 miles north of Austin, would
offer a significantly larger jury pool. It is the county seat of
Williamson County, one of the nation's fastest-growing counties
with a population of more than 190,000, compared to Jasper County's
population of 33,000. Both counties are predominantly white, 80
percent in Jasper County, and 87 percent in Williamson.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jasper offers a larger percentage of black residents _
nearly 20 percent _ compared to Williamson County's black
population of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Monte Lawlis has scheduled a hearing on the
proposed change for Wednesday in Jasper. Gray said the matter won't
be settled until the judge rules on the move.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential sites being considered, Gray said, are New
Braunfels and Kerrville, small towns also near the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's attorneys, Douglas Barlow and Layne Walker of Beaumont,
had argued that many residents of Jasper County believe that the
best way to show the world that Jasper is not racist would be to
secure convictions of the three white men accused of killing James
Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony and evidence in the first trial showed that Byrd, 49,
who was intoxicated and walking home from a party, accepted a ride
from three white men in a pickup in the early morning hours of June
7. He was beaten, his face spray-painted black, and his ankles
chained to the back of a pickup. He was dragged for almost three
miles on back roads outside Jasper until he was decapitated.
</P>
<P>
   Last month a jury in Jasper handed a death sentence to Bill
King, 24, of Jasper, the first defendant to go on trial. A third
man, Shawn Berry, also 24, of Jasper, still awaits a trial date.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said his decision to accept a change of venue for Brewer
should not affect King's appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's lawyers would prefer the trial in Beaumont, where the
defendant could be brought in and out of court through a secure
corridor from the former Jefferson County Jail. He would not have
to be paraded in handcuffs and a bulletproof vest as King was
during his trial in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care where it is tried, just so it is out of
Jasper County,'' Barlow said. He said that while jurors in Jasper
County may believe they are being fair, they may feel pressured to
secure a conviction to redeem their community.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he wouldn't agree to move the trial to Beaumont
because the local television stations serving Jasper are
headquartered there, as is The Beaumont Enterprise newspaper, which
is also widely circulated in Jasper County.
</P>
<P>
   After Byrd's death, Jasper was visited by the Ku Klux Klan and
armed black militia groups, and some civic leaders worried that
outside troublemakers would pour in to their town of 8,000 during
the murder trials.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the appearance of one black group's leader during
about two hours of King's trial, none of the groups appeared while
the trial was under way.
</P>
<P>
   The East Texas town, however, did experience an influx of news
reporters from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
