<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-TRIAL-358&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S BREACH-OF-CONTRACT TRIAL BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Walt Disney Co. created a secret ``Project
Snowball'' in 1991 to deprive Jeffrey Katzenberg, its former film
studio chief, of a huge bonus if he left the company when his
contract ended, a lawyer for Katzenberg said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In opening statements in the $250 million breach-of-contract
lawsuit brought by Katzenberg against Disney, the lawyer, Bertram
Fields, offered a series of letters and memorandums to bolster his
contention that Disney had sought through subterfuge to deny
Katzenberg his bonus.
</P>
<P>
   A top Disney lawyer, Lou Meisinger, vigorously denied the
accusations. ``If we were in a movie theater, I think this would be
the point where a responsible film maker would put up a disclosure:
the story you have just heard is fiction.'' He said there was
``nothing sinister'' about the project.
</P>
<P>
   During Katzenberg's decade as chairman of Walt Disney Studios,
which ended bitterly in 1994 when Michael D. Eisner, the company's
chairman and chief executive, passed him over for the No. 2 job at
the company, operating income rose to $186.3 million in 1988 from
$2.3 million in 1984. He oversaw the development of about 700
projects, including television shows and films like the lucrative
animated hits ``The Lion King,'' ``Aladdin'' and ``Beauty and the
Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields argued that Katzenberg was entitled to 2 percent of the
estimated income generated by the projects he developed at Disney,
including music and merchandising spinoffs. The money _ estimates
run as high as $250 million or more _ was to be paid in a lump sum
two years after he left the company.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner initially contended that Katzenberg had essentially
forfeited his bonus if he left in 1994 or if Disney dismissed him.
But Disney and Katzenberg reached a partial settlement in November
1997 in which Disney conceded that Katzenberg was owed something.
</P>
<P>
   Since then both sides have failed to reach an agreement. Fields
said that Eisner's ``personal animus'' toward Katzenberg had
thwarted any agreement. Meisinger, the Disney lawyer, dismissed the
assertion before Judge John W. Ouderkirk of Los Angeles Superior
Court.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Arguments in the case could run for several weeks. Within
Hollywood there has been surprise that the case, which has the
potential to embarrass Disney and perhaps Katzenberg, has not been
settled. It is highly unusual for two moguls like Eisner and
Katzenberg to publicly air a dispute over money and contracts.
</P>
<P>
   At issue, Meisinger said, was Katzenberg's contention that the
bonus owed to him was not limited to the years he ran Disney
studios but after that, too. Accordingly, the financial differences
could be huge. Katzenberg, for example, could seek a portion of the
receipts of the Broadway hit ``The Lion King,'' which opened after
he left Disney and was based on the film that he helped shape.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Fields said that the ``secret project''
involving top corporate executives, including Eisner, was designed
to ``discuss and investigate the possibility of claiming that
Katzenberg is forfeiting his contract if he leaves in 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Fields, a top Hollywood litigator, said, ``We've got a
real credibility problem with this fellow,'' referring to Eisner.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Fields said that Eisner, Sanford M. Litvack,
Disney's senior vice president, and Irwin E. Russell, a board
member and Eisner's personal lawyer, told ``palpably untrue''
stories about what Katzenberg was entitled to.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Meisinger said heatedly, ``The notion that there was some
form of deceit visited on Katzenberg is totally and utterly
fatuous.''
</P>
<P>
   Meisinger added, ``Contrary to the statement by counsel,
`Project Snowball' wasn't how we could figure out how to gyp
Katzenberg out of his payments.'' Rather, he said, the term was
coined by an accountant who was assigned to calculate Katzenberg's
bonus. Meisinger said the term was meant to show how the project
was getting bigger and bigger.
</P>
<P>
   The session was held in the law offices of Greenberg, Glusker,
Fields, Claman &AMP; Machtinger in Century City, Calif. Fields, who
represents numerous movie stars, is a partner in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner was not at the session. But Katzenberg sat and listened
intently all day, flanked by his wife, Marilyn Katzenberg, and
Helene Hahn, the top lawyer at Dreamworks, who worked for him at
Disney. After leaving Disney, Katzenberg helped establish
Dreamworks SKG with Steven Spielberg and David Geffen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
