<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: HIGHS AND LOWS OF THE ANNUAL MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a look at some of the highlights, lowlights and
sidelights of the 1999 management conference and annual meeting of
the American Association of Advertising Agencies, held last week in
Amelia Island, Fla.:
</P>
<P>
   BE A PEPPER: One of the best parts of the conference was an
enthusiastic speech by John E. Pepper Jr., chairman of Procter &AMP;
Gamble Co., the world's largest advertiser. P&AMP;G has recently
modified its ultrastrict rules on account conflicts, raising the
hopes of agencies that have worked for companies that compete
against P&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   Just how relaxed is P&AMP;G these days? Twice, Pepper praised Ogilvy
&AMP; Mather Worldwide, the unit of WPP Group PLC that has long handled
accounts for P&AMP;G's principal rival, Unilever. At one point, in
recounting how he learned about advertising when he joined P&AMP;G in
1963, Pepper said he had read the writings of David Ogilvy, the
founder of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wished he'd worked for us,'' Pepper declared.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, in asserting that ``superior product
performance'' is as important as ``great advertising campaigns,''
Pepper cited Unilever's Dove soap, long promoted by Ogilvy &AMP;
Mather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't we think of that?'' Pepper asked.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper also drew laughs when he mused that after he retires from
P&AMP;G on Sept. 1, he would ``start my own advertising agency'' with
an especially timely name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've learned something over the last year about
increasing market capitalization,'' Pepper said, his imaginary
agency would bear the name ``Pepper.com.''
</P>
<P>
   ADTALK: In keeping with the spirit of the conference, the
parlance of Madison Avenue found its way into other forms of
communication. For instance, during a flight down to the conference
from New York with many top agency executives as passengers, a
flight attendant announced that a pager had been found ``in the
forward part of the cabin'' _ i.e., in first class, where the
executives were congregated.
</P>
<P>
   And a restroom at the Ritz-Carlton hotel, the site of the
conference, boasted a ``Colgate-Palmolive Liquid Soap System.''
</P>
<P>
   FLIGHT OF FANCY: At one general session, attendees watched
excerpts from a taped conversation with Herbert D. Kelleher, the
outspoken chairman, president and chief executive of Southwest
Airlines, who discussed the value of advertising. Kelleher modified
an old joke, much to the delight of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want to make a small fortune?'' Kelleher asked. ``Start with a
large fortune _ and then hire an advertising agency.''
</P>
<P>
   OVERTAKEN BY EVENTS: A discussion on Friday, devoted to
``running a profitable independent agency,'' had three panelists,
but one turned out to be a ringer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we put the panel together,'' said the moderator, John F.
Mennis, senior vice president for management services at the
association, ``all of them were independent.'' But in a change
indicative of the industry's merger mania, one had since been taken
over: Citron Haligman Bedecarre in San Francisco is now Citron
Haligman Bedecarre/Euro RSCG, part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit
of Havas Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Mennis turned his lemon into lemonade, promising that Tom
Bedecarre, the agency's chairman, would discuss what he and his
colleagues did ``to make themselves attractive to Euro RSCG.''
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE CLASH: The Ritz-Carlton was busy with other functions
besides the conference. One, prominently promoted on signs around
the hotel, was the subject of many japes: an Anti-Fungal Regional
Advisory Meeting sponsored by Janssen Pharmaceutica on behalf of
its Sporanox brand of capsules. (No doubt the podiatrists had their
own jokes about advertising hucksters.)
</P>
<P>
   Another function was a ``bachelorette'' party whose attendees
mingled with attendees of the conference late one night. One young
woman invited Donny Deutsch, chairman and chief executive at
Deutsch Inc. in New York, to join her party as the, um,
entertainment. Though Deutsch has a newly toned physique, thanks to
workouts with a personal trainer, he declined the offer.
</P>
<P>
   KEY DETAIL: The annual Washington report of the association was
presented at breakfast by Hal Shoup, executive vice president and
director of the Washington office. He began the breakfast by asking
if anyone present had lost a hotel room key, which he held aloft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Washington report,'' one attendee said to
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   OH OH! Larry Miller, the comedian, who performed at the annual
dinner on Friday, prepared for his gig by reading biographies of
the top executives of the association.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up a sheet of paper about O. Burtch Drake, president and
chief executive, Miller asked: ``What's the deal with the `O'? How
bad could the `O' be?'' Debbie Drake, Drake's wife, called out from
the audience that it stood for ``Owen''; Drake said later that it
was the first time the meaning of the ``O'' had been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   After the ``O'' was outed, as it were, Miller called Drake ``a k
a Owen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
