<HEADLINE>
VINTAGE FABRICS MAKE THEIR WAY EAST  
 CUSTOM-MADE SANDALS  
 ROCK 'N' ROLL STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Style From Vintage Fabrics
</P>
<P>
   Her name is so wholesome and fake-sounding that you'd think
Libbie Lane was a columnist for the love-stricken, not a Beverly
Hills, Calif., designer to the chic and restless. Rare is the week
that an actress doesn't wander into her Burton Way boutique, pore
over the organza blouses and rare vintage prints and die a little.
Madonna and Helena Bonham Carter are fans. So is Roseanne.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not dwell on celebrity. Ms. Lane's clothes suggest a
garden party where the guests go crazy and turn the chintz
draperies into cool car coats. Many of her fabrics are vintage. She
does everything herself, from designing and scouting flea markets
to running her four-year-old business. ``I'm not one of these
designers who says they're doing it for art,'' Ms. Lane said with a
laugh. ``I like the money.'' She has help, of course _ namely, her
husband, Andy, a writer and producer of the 1983 film ``Valley
Girl,'' and a team of workers, including a few of James Galanos'
former beaders.
</P>
<P>
   East Coast editors have picked up on Ms. Lane's style. (Elle's
fashion director, Marin Hopper, wore her red pony coat during the
March shows.) This spring, Saks Fifth Avenue is selling Ms. Lane's
clothes. ``They're different, collectible, seasonless,'' said
Nicole Fischelis, the fashion director of Saks. ``It's about
individual pieces that are not part of a trend.'' Prices range from
$300 to $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   That Ms. Lane uses scarce vintage fabrics doesn't seem a problem
for stores like Saks or Harvey Nichols, in London, which has placed
an order for fall. ``They just ask me how many pieces I can make,''
she said. Next up: shoes and maybe handbags.
</P>
<P>
   One-of-a-Kind Sandals
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It goes with the atmosphere of the East Village that
when people go to Jutta Neumann's shop on Ninth Street, near First
Avenue, for custom-made sandals, they step barefoot on white paper
while she traces around their toes. It tickles.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Neumann has been making sandals for 11 years, the last five
in her tiny shop. She stocks sizes, but it's the fit and novelty of
her custom sandals that have drawn the attention of designers like
Anna Sui and Marc Jacobs. Last summer, Isaac Mizrahi wore a pair of
her thong sandals on ``The Tonight Show,'' and though Mizrahi
mentioned only that they were from the East Village, it was enough
of a clue to cause Ms. Neumann's phone to ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandals have to fit,'' Ms. Neumann said, explaining the virtue
of custom, ``because they don't have the support of shoes.'' Her
styles are basic, from Mizrahi's slip-on thong to thick slides with
a wide band across the top. She and her staff of eight work in all
kinds of leather and exotic skins, including snake and sting ray.
Custom sandals range from $140 to $300 and take about three weeks
for delivery.
</P>
<P>
   It's Only Rock 'n' Fashion
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Costume Institute of the Metropolitan Museum of
Art announced last week that it plans to recognize the influence of
rock 'n' roll _ and none too soon. ``Icons of Rock Style,'' as the
exhibition is tentatively called, is to open on Dec. 9, three days
after the institute's annual dinner-dance. The exhibition will pay
homage to about 20 rock artists from the 1950s to the present, with
clothes mainly from the Metropolitan and the Rock 'n' Roll Hall of
Fame and Museum in Cleveland. Tommy Hilfiger, who's never made a
secret of his fascination with rock and hip-hop _ or the attention
they bring his label _ is the chairman of the gala. Anna Wintour,
the editor in chief of Vogue, and Aerin Lauder, the director of
creative productive development at Estee Lauder, are the
co-chairwomen.
</P>
<P>
   Although a number of designers have been way ahead of Hilfiger
and the institute in acknowledging the influence of rock 'n' roll
on fashion, the exhibition may do for the Met what motorcycles did
for the Guggenheim Museum last year _ bring in the people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
