<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FNB-ELWAY-MONTANA-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELWAY'S GREAT BUT MONTANA WAS BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BOB PADECKY   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Absence may make the heart grow fonder, but when it comes to
remembering who was the best quarterback in NFL history, it also
dulled the shine, yellowed the scrapbook and dropped what once was
clear out of focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the game was on the line,'' said Atlanta Falcons coach
Dan Reeves, ``John Elway was like Michael Jordan. He wanted the
football. In those situations, I don't know if I know anyone who
did a better job of handling that than John did.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Reeves does. His name is Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Montana retired five years ago. Elway is going
out now amid plenty of gush. Football coaches are like the rest of
us _ we can remember what we had for lunch today but don't ask us
to describe that trout almondine we ate last month.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves could remember back to five years ago _ when Elway was
leading the Denver Broncos to all those comeback victories. It was
Montana who still had the premier reputation. It was Montana who
set the standard. It was Montana who was the answer to this
question: ``With the game on the line and 80 yards to go for a
touchdown, what quarterback you would pick?'' There was no debate.
Sure, Elway had great skills but when it came to choosing someone
to make a team supremely confident, it was Montana. We all bowed in
that direction, even the great Elway did.
</P>
<P>
   You will hear the argument about Elway's ``tools.'' He could
throw harder than Montana. He could run farther. He was more
durable.
</P>
<P>
   So? Minnesota quarterback Randall Cunningham is probably a
better athlete than either of them, and look where his ``tools''
got him.
</P>
<P>
   You will hear the argument that Montana had better teams behind
him than Elway. Then how do you explain Joe winning the 49ers'
first Super Bowl with Ricky Patton as the running back and Earl
Cooper as the tight end? When it comes to an offensive supporting
cast, no Super Bowl winner ever had a weaker one than Montana had
that year.
</P>
<P>
   You also will hear the argument that if Elway had been the
quarterback of the 49ers instead of Montana, Elway would have
enjoyed more success than Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, and if Mickey Mantle didn't drink and have two bum knees,
he might have hit more home runs than Hank Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Or if Paul Warfield, Larry Csonka and Jim Kiick hadn't left the
undefeated Dolphins in 1975, Miami would have won more Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Or if Jordan hadn't left the NBA for baseball, the Bulls would
have won more championships.
</P>
<P>
   Or if hockey could score more goals and the puck could be seen,
the game would be more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   If. If. If. You could drown in a sea of ``if's.'' It's wonderful
to speculate. Makes a beer go down faster down at the neighborhood
bar. Whittles away a slow afternoon. And that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of wasting time wondering what might have happened,
remember what did happen. Montana won four Super Bowls; Elway
participated in two Super Bowl victories. Montana was the key
ingredient in all four Super Bowls; Elway used running back Terrell
Davis masterfully to take control of both Bronco victories.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Bradshaw also won four Super Bowls, but Bradshaw will be
the first to tell you that Lynn Swann and John Stallworth and
Franco Harris made him a great quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you take everything into consideration,'' said New York
Giants coach Jim Fassel, ``the Super Bowls, the arm strength and
the length of his career, you can build a case that John's the best
that ever played the position.''
</P>
<P>
   But that Elway played a long time and played in five Super Bowls
and that he could throw the ball through Dennis Rodman's thick
head, well, so what? I have a lot of chest hair, too, and that
doesn't make me the best quarterback who ever lived.
</P>
<P>
   This is what matters: When it came to seeing the entire field,
when it came to instinctively making the right play, when it came
to playing through pressure, when it came to finding a way to win,
no one did it better than Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it has been five years since Montana last did that.
In sports that might as well be 1930.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
