<HEADER>
A4218 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2T     04-26 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CODE-SHARING: CLUING IN FLIERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you want a view of the world turned upside down and inside
out, study the airline practice known as code-sharing. The general
theory of relativity is not too much more complex.
</P>
<P>
   The short of it is that you can buy a ticket from Chicago to
Warsaw on American Airlines and you will fly the whole nonstop trip
on LOT, the Polish airline, because American does not have
Chicago-Warsaw service and LOT is its partner in a code-sharing
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Your ticket will show your flight as American Airlines 6102, but
the itinerary attached to the ticket or provided by the travel
agent should indicate that the flight is being operated by LOT,
which lists it as Flight 2. The code being shared is the airline's
own code name, in this case ``AA'' for American and ``LO'' for LOT.
</P>
<P>
   Listings in airline guides and on computer screens, depending
where the travel agent looks, can either show the code of the real
airline and its flight number, or the code of the sharing airline,
plus an asterisk or other mark, plus its number.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines sell tickets on each other's flights, either by
buying a block or by simply dipping into the other line's
inventory. And each can sell the ticket at whatever price it
elects. It means that an airline can advertise destinations it does
not fly to, and at the least, get the passenger's business for any
flights that feed into the other line's flight.
</P>
<P>
   On the trip to Warsaw, getting to the right place at O'Hare
Airport in Chicago, Terminal 5, probably depends on how well your
travel agent prepared you. If you began your trip in Des Moines on
American, you would fly to Chicago on another code-shared flight,
this one operated by American Eagle, an American subsidiary. It
would bring you into O'Hare Terminal 4, where American has domestic
gates, and the monitor would show the departure from Terminal 5,
and you would take the airport train.
</P>
<P>
   All major United States airlines now share codes with other
lines. It is hard to get an airline to denounce the practice these
days although less than 10 years ago, some of them considered it
deceptive _ paying for Airline A's suave service while receiving
Airline Z's frightful service.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as is the case now, you can be expecting a domestic
airline's nonsmoking trip and find yourself in a cabin filled with
smoke, as would be the case if you wound up an Alitalia code-shared
flight to Rome from Kennedy in New York when you booked
Continental.
</P>
<P>
   Code-sharing is of particular concern right now because the
Department of Transportation, after years of poking at the issue,
has enacted regulations to improve the likelihood that consumers
learn which line will carry them. These regulations affect not just
code-sharing, but also a practice obscurely known as ``change of
gauge,'' which is what happens when you take a one-stop flight and
discover that at the stop you also have to change planes, even
though your travel agent said you could sleep through.
</P>
<P>
   These flights are often described as ``direct'' flights, which
sounds like nonstop, but they are far from it. Now, passengers must
be told if they are to be shifted to another plane, even if it is
the same model.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations take effect July 13, although the airlines
themselves have long been directed to disclose code-sharing
arrangements to customers. The new regulations require travel
agents as well as foreign airlines to get this information to the
traveler before the sale is complete, and require the notice of
``change of gauge.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating a shared code requires negotiation between the
airlines, but not necessarily a lot more. New names are not painted
on airplanes, departure terminals are not necessarily changed,
menus are not adapted. In the word of David Messing, spokesman for
Continental Airlines, shared flights that were formerly flights
where passengers could make a connection on their own are simply
``relabeled.''
</P>
<P>
   A substantial change may appear if the passenger misses the
code-shared connection. Meals and accommodations at a midpoint are
nominally the responsibility of the airline that arrived late,
whereas on a connection selected by the passenger or an agent, the
problem is the passenger's own.
</P>
<P>
   However, I am among the legions who have taken flights that
connected to the same airline, only to be told my night's
accommodation, meals and the rest are my problem. So there is no
guarantee of being coddled on a code-shared flight either.
</P>
<P>
   There are some other benefits: frequent-flier miles can usually
be earned or spent on the flights of the partner airline, although
the award may be less than 100 percent of the miles on the original
airline. If passengers have memberships in a lounge club of one
partner, they can have access to the lounges of the other.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A single ticket, albeit with more than one coupon, is provided,
and boarding passes with seat assignments for each segment can be
printed out at the first boarding.
</P>
<P>
   Code-sharing partners may not consult and fix ticket prices
between them. The partner airlines thus may not necessarily sell
their tickets on the same flight for the same price. For example,
the Chicago-Warsaw flight, on a 21-day advance purchase valid to
the end of last month, was offered at $409 by LOT, $469 by
American. This is the kind of thing probably only a travel agent
has the patience to sort out.
</P>
<P>
   And as in the Chicago example, sometimes the partners do not
have conveniently arranged departure gates, although they all work
toward it. In a recently created code-sharing, Delta joined hands
with China Southern, a major airline that has been flying into Los
Angeles from Guangzhou since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 28, China Southern has been taking Delta pasengers
to Guangzhou on Wednesday, Friday and Sunday from Delta's Terminal
5 at Los Angeles. The flight also returns to this terminal, where
Customs agents are available. Part of the reason for this
convenience is that Delta provided ground service for China
Southern before they shared codes.
</P>
<P>
   Delta is a major code-sharer. Of its 5,316 daily flights,
according to Todd Clay, a spokesman, 1,638, or about 30 percent,
are code-shared. In addition to China Southern, it has 13 partners.
This number is in constant change: the airline has now asked the
United States government for permission to put the Delta code on
Finnair flights to Moscow and St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Delta does something that not all airlines do: It shares codes
with other airlines even when it serves the same city. It has a
flight from Atlanta to Zurich at 7 p.m., and it also offers
Swissair's flight at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent reigning champion in getting partners is American
and its subsidiary American Eagle; together they have 22. United
now has 18.
</P>
<P>
   USAirways, which was a lion in the field when it shared codes
with British Airways, now has only one partner, Deutsche BA, an
internal German line.
</P>
<P>
   The government believes that code-sharing will continue to
increase. At least once a week, an airline applies for approval of
another code-shared flight.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the government made an investigation by anonymously
calling airlines and agencies and reported that on a third of the
calls, the caller got no information that the flight would be flown
by another line. That started the work on the new rule.
</P>
<P>
   The major changes from the earlier rules require that travel
agents and foreign airlines, as well as domestic airlines, tell
clients in advance that the flight is a code-shared flight and the
name of the other airline. Written notice with the ticket is also
required, although the rule does not require that the ticket itself
give this information. Part of the reason for that is the advent of
the electronic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   No penalties are specified in the new regulation; the department
already has the authority to issue restraining orders and to fine
offenders up to $1,100.
</P>
<P>
   How this rule is enforced will depend upon complaints. The
Department of Transportation receives complaints _ not very many at
the moment _ at this address: Aviation Consumer Protection
Division, Room 4107, Department of Transportation, 400 Seventh
Street, S.W., Washington, D.C. 20590.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony in Congress by Nancy E. McFadden, the
department's general counsel, the department may get only one
complaint for the many that the airlines get, which they are not
compelled to pass along, except for mishandled-luggage complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McFadden said that one airline got 400 complaints of various
sorts for every one the department received about the line.
Complaints about lack of information, violation of rules, failure
to deliver what was promised or discrimination are all received by
the department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
