</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SULAWESI-3TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC SULAWESI AWAITS THE WORLD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sulawesi, a disheveled starfish of an island that came to rest
on cerulean seas between Borneo and the Moluccas, has long been
home to people at ease with the wider world. But lacking expansive
beaches and great historical monuments, Sulawesi has not had much
chance to demonstrate its uncomplicated worldliness to tourists,
who flock instead to other Indonesian islands: mystical,
introverted Java or the nonstop arts festival that is Bali.
</P>
<P>
   Sulawesi _ once known as the Celebes _ is the homeland of
Indonesia's boldest sailors, the Bugis and Makassarese, who roamed
Southeast Asian seas long before explorers from the West nosed into
the territory. Since the 16th century, the island's people have
also welcomed outsiders and adopted their diverse religions _
Shiite Islam in the south and Christianity on the Minahasa
Peninsula in the north, where Dutch colonialists also enjoyed their
most congenial sojourn in the age of empire.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, the Portuguese, Spanish, Dutch, Indochinese and
Chinese _ adventurers, soldiers, traders, naturalists and
missionaries _ came and marveled at Sulawesi's natural beauty,
dense green hills reaching down to bays and lagoons edged in coral
reefs of astonishing variety and color, abundant with marine life.
Valleys and plateaus were richly fertile.
</P>
<P>
   In the mountains and rain forests were birds and animals unknown
anywhere else in the world. Enormous butterflies in psychedelic
colors roamed the glens, attracting the great 19th-century British
naturalist Alfred Russel Wallace, who made meticulous studies in
the East Indies, evolving a theory of evolution similar to
Darwin's.
</P>
<P>
   Sulawesi, especially South Sulawesi, commanded the lucrative
spice trade routes, making its major port, Makassar _ now Ujung
Pandang _ an important, much-fought-over place. Pepper, cloves,
nutmeg, vanilla and the many useful derivatives of coconuts still
build fortunes here.
</P>
<P>
   Though anthropologists and adventure-seekers made their way into
the island's interior, Tanatoraja (Toraja land), and divers came to
explore still-pristine reefs, Sulawesi remained largely unknown.
When the island finally got around to thinking of tourism a couple
of years ago, the Asian financial crisis struck, followed by riots
in Jakarta and the fall of the Suharto government.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists fled the country, and only Bali has since recovered.
The future had to be postponed. As a result, travel in Sulawesi is
a bargain and service is very attentive in the new, large hotels in
Ujung Pandang in the south and Manado in the far northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Ujung Pandang, capital of South Sulawesi province _ Sulawesi
Selatan or Sulsel to Indonesians, who love to short-circuit proper
nouns _ is an acquired taste. At first view, the city, strung out
along the Makassar Strait, seems relentlessly ugly. Two dirty,
traffic-clogged commercial streets converge along the scraggly
seafront.
</P>
<P>
   But after dark, an unkempt waterside promenade comes to life, as
dozens of wheeled food stalls arrive and set up shop, end to end,
creating a necklace of lights along the water. Fish sizzles, beer
flows and Ujung Pandang takes on a different air.
</P>
<P>
   South Sulawesi's coastal people, Mandarese, Makassarese and
Bugis (or Buginese) are overwhelmingly Muslim, but their relaxed
attitude toward religion and modernization belies Western
stereotypes. In Ujung Pandang, young women prefer short skirts and
those who wear Muslim headscarves may also cover the rest of
themselves in T-shirts and jeans.
</P>
<P>
   South of the city, at Somba Opu, an old fort and park for
displaying regional architecture, my husband, David, and I, on a
visit in March, met an artist, Bachtiar Hafid, whom local Shiah
leaders recognize as a mystic. Unencumbered by strictures against
figurative art, Bachtiar paints historical or mythical people _
kings and queens, some pre-Islamic _ directed by a shadow or spirit
that guides his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Great kingdoms flourished here. It was near Ujung Pandang that
the Dutch finally defeated the last of them, Gowa, under Sultan
Hasanuddin, in the late 1660s.
</P>
<P>
   The tomb of Hasanuddin, in a small grassy cemetery that also
contains a pre-Islamic royal mausoleum, can be visited on the
southern outskirts of Ujung Pandang, on the way to Sungguminasa. At
Sungguminasa, the reconstructed royal palace of Gowa, a huge
rectangular wooden building on stilts, looms over a small park.
</P>
<P>
   Next door, a small museum displays royal regalia and
memorabilia, along with a detailed ``family tree'' of Gowa rulers
leading back to a marvelous woman, Tomanurunga, who descended from
heaven equipped with a golden crown to begin the royal line. There
is no entry fee, but a contribution is expected. A gift of at least
10,000 rupiah (about $1.15, at 8,650 rupiah to the dollar) to the
enthusiastic caretaker would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Ujung Pandang is Fort Rotterdam, the best
preserved Dutch fort in Asia. It belonged to the kings of Gowa when
the Dutch arrived and enhanced its large interior space with a
collection of Dutch-style buildings, including an austere church
(now a conference center). A climb onto the sturdy ramparts is
rewarded with views of the low-slung city and its magnificent
harbor. Again, at the fort a contribution is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Of some interest inside the walls is the La Galigo museum, named
for an epic poem telling the story of the early Buginese. The
museum is not well lighted, ventilated or labeled other than in
Indonesian, but it contains good models explaining the construction
of the complex, some fascinating pre-Islamic, pre-colonial statuary
and a small collection of old Chinese and Indochinese celadon and
porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   A landmark of the more recent past is the town of Malino, about
45 miles east of Ujung Pandang along a pleasant winding road
through farming villages into the cool hills. Here in the 1920s,
the Dutch created a hill station for themselves, planted with
flowering shrubs and fruit trees. In 1946, a conference was held
here to discuss creating a federation of Indonesian islands linked
to the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, rejected by the Indonesians, who had proclaimed
independence the previous year, is enjoying a revival _ minus the
Dutch _ as the nation looks for ways to keep its diverse
populations together under one flag.
</P>
<P>
   In Ujung Pandang, everyone considers it essential to visit the
Bantimurung waterfall, about an hour northeast of town. Here, the
naturalist Wallace fell into raptures over the butterflies that
flourished in a gorge formed by limestone cliffs. The area is a
nature reserve but, alas, that doesn't always mean much in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fenced areas set aside for butterfly breeding have been
vandalized, and visitors are besieged by peddlers offering glorious
specimens pressed into cellophane envelopes. It is a horrible
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Ujung Pandang, we visited Paotare quay, where the
seagoing vessels known as pinisi dock. The prahu pinisi, the
signature Bugis sailing vessel, can be a soaring three-masted craft
for hauling timber, like those whose prows arc dramatically over
Jakarta's Sunda Kelapa harbor, or smaller ones, with a single mast
and engine.
</P>
<P>
   Pinisi, modeled originally on Portuguese schooners, are still
built on Sulawesi's southern coast, near Bira, where a small beach
resort is taking shape. Sea voyages inspire timeless folk music and
romantic myths about sailors and the women they leave behind to
send their love on the winds that propel the ships.
</P>
<P>
   But at Paotare, the pinisi are tethered like workhorses to be
loaded with tons of flour, grains or other cargoes for outer
islands. Men, young and old, hoist sacks weighing 50 or 100 pounds
or more and stagger up narrow gangplanks. They are paid less than
$1 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Fly almost anywhere in Indonesia for a hour or two, and there is
another world to discover. From Ujung Pandang, a flight of less
than 90 minutes brings the traveler to Manado, a much slower-paced
town, where church steeples dominate the skyline and the brilliant
aquamarine sea belongs to fishermen in outrigger canoes. Ujung
Pandang is urban. Manado, and the Minahasa region, is all outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Most Westerners come to Manado, capital of North Sulawesi _
Sulawesi Utara, or Sulut _ to dive or snorkel along its exceptional
reefs. This is serious diving territory, with underwater cliffs
that drop 1,000 feet or more. But so abundant is the sea life here,
that even a lazy afternoon on a jetty is enlivened by a parade of
marine life.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Santika Manado, where we stayed, is built at the edge of a
tidal mangrove swamp, through which a long pier has been
constructed to connect the low-rise hotel with the sea. Millions of
crabs and dense schools of small fish arrive with the tide to
forage among the mangroves rooted in mud.
</P>
<P>
   Farther out, a sandy bottom provides pools for countless
starfish and brightly colored zebra angel fish, dramatic batfish,
trigger fish, sea snakes and other species, along with an
astounding variety of coral formations and shells. At low tide, a
reef emerges just offshore.
</P>
<P>
   The Santika is the base for a Dutch-run diving center and
school, Thalassa, which can also arrange glass-bottom boat trips
along the reefs near Bunaken Island, about 25 minutes away and the
heart of much of the diving activity in the Celebes Sea. As an
alternative, the hotel will find a local boatman to make a less
strenuous tour of the outer reefs and islands, not only Bunaken,
but also Manado Tua (a dormant volcanic cone) and Siladen, an
island of narrow but empty white beaches and fishing hamlets.
</P>
<P>
   This coast, its offshore islands and hundred of thousands of
acres inland are all nature reserves, and here there is some
measure of protection, though local environmentalists say that
patrols are inadequate, especially to deter spear-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   In the forest reserves of North Sulawesi, some of the island's
unique animals and birds still survive, but precariously, as nature
reserves open to tourists and local people expand hunting into
areas that are only lightly guarded. The rare maleo bird, which
buries its eggs in the sand, has no defense against villagers who
collect and sell the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of bird species are found only in Sulawesi, where forests
also shelter the remaining endangered anoa, a small buffalo no
bigger than a large dog, and the babirusa ``pig deer,'' with tusks
that curl back above its eyes. There are tailless monkeys, tiny
tarsiers and huge snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, the Victorian naturalist, noted the dramatic changes in
flora and fauna between this island and Borneo, Indonesian
Kalimantan, to the west. On the map, he drew a scientific line,
still called the Wallace Line, between these islands, and also
between Bali and Lombok to the south.
</P>
<P>
   North Sulawesi is the homeland of the Minahasa people, who are
culturally Malay, have a language related to those of the
Philippines and a strong Protestant religious faith _ which
contributes to their great love of singing. A Minahasa male chorus
is a robust sound.
</P>
<P>
   Manado town mixes a number of racial and cultural groups, with a
considerable Chinese population, most of them Christians or
Buddhists. During attacks on the Chinese in Java last year, many
families fled to Manado, resident say, pointing to new homes being
built with the money the fearful migrants brought with them.
</P>
<P>
   In the interior hill towns, each with at least a church or two _
lately more of them Pentecostal or Seventh Day Adventist than Dutch
Reformed _ the Minahasa farm upland valleys and plateaus and build
their distinctive wooden houses high on stilts. Coconut and spice
plantations provide a good livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most pleasant forays to be made in North Sulawesi is
a trip to Tomohon, a hill town nestled between two still-active
volcanoes. Tomohon is famous for its flower markets and fresh
foods, as well as a good hospital and the Christian University of
Indonesia. It also has the nicest hill station hotel in Indonesia,
the Gardenia, a rambling collection of cottages among flower beds.
</P>
<P>
   From the coast around Manado, an easy day trip into the hills
can include Lake Tondano, North Sulawesi's largest freshwater lake;
World War II Japanese caves nearby, and a 1,000-year old collection
of stone tombs at Sawangan. That tour would still leave time for a
late lunch at the Gardenia, and a trip of less than an hour back to
the coast in time for a fiery Manado sunset. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans traveling as tourists in Indonesia do not need visas
for visits of up to 60 days. The best months for Sulawesi are April
to October, the dry season. Temperatures are in the 80s and 90s all
year, cooler in hill towns.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia holds a national assembly election on June 7, preceded
by weeks of intense political activity and followed by a
presidential election in the fall. The State Department advises
caution when traveling to Indonesia during the political
transition.
</P>
<P>
   What to Read
</P>
<P>
   ``Sulawesi: Island Crossroads of Indonesia'' is a Passport
Regional Guide published in 1995 by Passport Books, a division of
N.T.C. Contemporary Publishing Group, Lincolnwood, Ill.; $17.95.
Telephone orders: (847) 679-5500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indo-Pacific Coral Reef Field Guide,'' by Gerald R. Allen and
Roger Steene, published by Tropical Reef Research, Singapore, is
available for $42.95 from Sea Challengers Natural History Books,
Danville, Calif., (925) 327-7750, and by back order from Amazon.com
for $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   Silk Air, the regional subsidiary of Singapore Airlines, flies
nonstop from Singapore to Manado and to Ujung Pandang. Excursion
fares are available from the United States on Singapore Airlines
from New York to either Manado or Ujung Pandang via Singapore,
beginning around $1,300 round trip; (800) 742-3333.
</P>
<P>
   Garuda Indonesia Airways, (310) 348-9577, the national carrier,
flies to Ujung Pandang and Manado daily from Jakarta and Denpasar,
Bali. Discount fares on its Airpass program are $150 each way from
Jakarta to Ujung Pandang and $75 from Denpasar to Ujung Pandang.
From Jakarta, regular economy class fares are $389 one way to
Manado and $234 to Ujung Pandang. From Bali, one way to Manado is
$229 and to Ujung Pandang $109. Flights between Ujung Pandang and
Manado, also on Garuda, are $171 one way. Lower fares in rupiah may
be available locally.
</P>
<P>
   Places to Stay
</P>
<P>
   Because of the 1998 economic crisis and continuing fluctuation
in value of the Indonesian currency _ the rupiah is now worth only
about a quarter of its 1996 value _ international-standard hotels
are bargains. Prices below, based on 8,650 rupiah to the dollar,
include 21 percent service charge and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In Ujung Pandang, where most hotels are on the Makassar Strait,
the Radisson, at 235 Jalan Somba Opu, (62-411) 333-111, fax
(62-411) 333-222, charged $35 a night for a double room normally
priced at $150. The Sedona, at 297 Jalan Somba Opu, (62-411)
870-555, (62-411) 870-222, was asking $145, but discounts are
available.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotel Makassar Golden, at 50-52 Jalan Pasar Ikan; (62-411)
314-408, fax (62-411) 320-951, is an old establishment undergoing
renovations; $25 to $40 double. The Hotel Pantai Gapura, 10 Jalan
Pasar Ikan; (62-411) 325-791, fax (62-411) 316-303, in addition to
discounted standard rooms (at about $25 to $40 double), has
handsome wooden cottages built on stilts over the sea, with luxury
interiors and small outdoor porches, for $41.
</P>
<P>
   In the hill town of Malino, the Resort Hotel and Villa Celebes,
1 Jalan Hasanuddin; (62-417) 21023, fax (62-417) 21388, has basic
rooms for about $20 double, or a family-size villa for $60.
</P>
<P>
   In Manado, the two-year-old Hotel Santika Manado, Post Office
Box 1644, Manado 95000; (62-431) 858-222, fax (62-431) 858-666, is
about 15 miles northeast of town in a sheltered seaside valley in
the village of Tongkeina. By far the best place to stay, it had
reduced a $100 room to about $49, double, including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   In Manado town, there is a Novotel on Jalan Piere Tendean,
(62-431) 855-555, fax (62-431) 851-245, with doubles for $60 to
$75.
</P>
<P>
   The Singapore-based Sedona chain expects to open a luxury beach
hotel next year southwest of Manado, near the Manado Beach Hotel, a
once-grand resort that is deteriorating. Rates have not been set.
</P>
<P>
   Bunaken Island, the center of the offshore marine reserve, has a
few very cheap but also very, very basic cottage hotels. The Papa
Boa Cottages, (62-431) 850-434, has twin-bedded cottages without
toilets at $4; with private toilets, about $5.20.
</P>
<P>
   Inland from Manado in the hilly Minahasa heartland, the Gardenia
Hotel, Kakaskasen II, Tomohon, (62-431) 351-282, fax (62-431)
351-363, has wood-paneled cottages set in flower and herb gardens
facing the Lokon volcano. A two-room chalet is $65 for twin beds
and a small dining-sitting area.
</P>
<P>
   Getting Around
</P>
<P>
   In Ujung Pandang, a car with part-time guide and excellent
driver cost $160 for three days, arranged through Bagus Indonesia,
at 30-34 Jalan Haji Bau; (62-411) 872-324. There are metered taxis,
and fares to most places in town rarely rise above $1 to $2. Manado
also has taxis, but fewer of them, and the drivers may want to
bargain rather than charge the meter rate, which begins at 21
cents. Manado and Tomohon also have horse-drawn taxis, known as
bendis. A rental car with driver in Manado cost $29 a day.
</P>
<P>
   What to Eat
</P>
<P>
   Intestinal parasites and waterborne bacterial diseases are
endemic in Indonesia. Ask a doctor for advice on what medications
to take, just in case. No unbottled water is safe. Soft drinks are
available and Indonesia makes good beer, a legacy of Dutch
colonialism. Bir Bintang and Anker are the best known; Carlsberg is
also produced.
</P>
<P>
   Fish _ including garoupa, red snapper and tuna _ is probably
safe to eat grilled along the beach. But with hotel dishes not
likely to cost over $4 or $5, saving money by eating in the street
may not make sense. Meals for two, with beer, juice or soft drinks
and dessert, rarely reach $20, including tax and service.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian specialities include a rice porridge called bubur _
bubur ayam if cooked with chicken. Indonesian fried rice, nasi
goreng, is available everywhere, usually for about $1 to $1.50. At
its best, nasi goreng is served as a mound of plain or aromatically
flavored steamed rice crowned with a fried egg and surrounded by a
piece of fried chicken, a stick or two of satay (beef, chicken or
fish) and some spicy sauces and condiments.
</P>
<P>
   In North Sulawesi, a local dish is ayam tuturuga, chicken cooked
in a spiced coconut milk sauce. Desserts often feature bananas,
fried as pisang goreng or pureed into puddings and cakes. Pizza is
very popular, and mixes well with spicy Indonesian garnishes. At
the Santika, a 12-inch pizza with mushrooms, ham, cheese and a
thick tomato sauce cost about $3.30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
