<HEADLINE>
PATAKI SEEKS STRONGER PENALTIES FOR VIOLENCE IN SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Citing the Colorado school killings in his effort
to push for new laws in New York, Gov. George E. Pataki presented a
package of proposals Monday that would stiffen penalties for
violence in schools and make it easier to remove disruptive
students from classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also require school districts to draw up codes of
conduct, establish a statewide system for collecting information on
violent incidents in schools and step up public education campaigns
intended to reduce student violence.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has often spoken about the importance of improving
school safety, and many of his proposals were not new. The State
Senate, which is led by his Republican allies, has approved
legislation in recent years that includes several of the proposals
but the bills have died in the Democratic-controlled Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Democrats have their own school safety plan, which
does not go as far as the Republicans' proposal in toughening
punishment and also focuses on setting up programs that its
sponsors say will help prevent violence.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Monday, Pataki took a conciliatory approach
to the Assembly Democrats and emphasized that he was not trying to
use the high school shootings in Littleton, Colo., for political
advantage. He said that after years of impasse, he hoped that the
two sides could reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time for politics and partisanship,'' he said.
``This is not the time for pointing fingers or passing blame. This
is the time for us to come together as New Yorkers and parents.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He added that he would probably announce further proposals in
the coming months based on the work of a task force that he
created, which is led by Lt. Gov. Mary O. Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Democrats responded that they, too, would like to
arrive at a compromise, but such deferential comments do not
necessarily suggest that a deal is at hand. In previous years, the
bargaining over school safety has become entangled in the
horse-trading over other measures, including the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Still, both the assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, and the Senate
majority leader, Joseph L. Bruno, signaled that they were ready to
form a conference committee to negotiate legislation, a step that
did not occur last year.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and legislative leaders were able to agree last
year on a law that allows 14- and 15-year-old students who have
loaded firearms in school to be prosecuted as adults in criminal
court and subjected to greater penalties.
</P>
<P>
   This year, while there is some agreement on new legislation,
there are three major areas of disagreement. Pataki and the Senate
Republicans want some crimes that are now misdemeanors, like
possession of unloaded firearms on school property, to become
felonies. The Democrats favor increasing penalties, but not as much
as the Republicans do.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are seeking to give teachers more authority to
remove disruptive students from classrooms, while the Democrats
express concern that such a move would lead to students in the same
schools receiving different penalties for similar offenses. They
want this authority to remain largely with principals.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republicans call for no new financing, the Democrats
want to allocate money for counseling and other programs that they
say will help limit school violence, though they decline to give
exact amounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does the families of the victims little good to know that
after the fact, we have taken harsh steps against the
perpetrators,'' said Assemblyman Steven Sanders, a Manhattan
Democrat who is chairman of the Education Committee. ``We need to,
to the extent possible, have resources in the schools to identify
youngsters who are at risk and intervene before the tragedies
occur.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
