<HEADER>
A4226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TAGLIABUE-PATRIOT     04-26 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TAGLIABUE-PATRIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON SPORTS BUSINESS: TAGLIABUE FAKES OUT THE PATRIOTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Pa., Calif.)   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From November through last week, the National Football League
did nothing publicly to upset the proposition that the New England
Patriots would move from the team's creaky old home in Foxboro,
Mass., to a $375 million stadium in Hartford, Conn., that would be
fully subsidized by Connecticut taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue met in Boston
with Massachusetts business leaders, now energized by the urgency
of the Patriots' situation. Tagliabue said he wanted to take a look
at how the team might remain in Foxboro, in a new $225 million
stadium paid for by the league and the team, with up to $75 million
being provided by Massachusetts for roads, exit ramps and parking
lots.
</P>
<P>
   What a fancy stutter-step the lanky commissioner executed,
letting Hartford think it had snagged the Patriots with a giveaway
so rich that it made sweetheart deals nationwide seem modest by
comparison. In fact, the timing of Tagliabue's trip to Boston
seemed calculated to stir up a crisis: On the day of his visit, the
Patriots filed an official application to move to Hartford, which
owners will consider at NFL meetings in Atlanta on May 25 and 26.
Approval of the move requires a yes vote from three-quarters of the
32 owners.
</P>
<P>
   By resurrecting Foxboro as an option, the league has set the
stage for the possible undoing of a signed agreement between Robert
Kraft, the Patriots' owner, and the state of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the league makes its presentation about the Patriots to
the owners, we have to be able to say that we've explored every
alternative in Massachusetts,'' said Joe Browne, a league
spokesman. ``We have to be able to tell owners, even if they don't
like it, that there is no option but Hartford. We're doing what the
owners authorized us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The league did not consult Kraft about Foxboro, Browne said.
``Kraft can't talk about anything but Connecticut,'' Browne
explained. ``He has an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft can escape his Connecticut deal if he does not sign a site
status report by May 2. But Dean Pagani, a spokesman for
Connecticut Gov. John Rowland, said, ``We've been assured it's not
an out option.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft surely knows what is cooking in Massachusetts, but how can
he not have developed a deep affection for Connecticut, which
presented him with a deal he never asked for but would have been
crazy to reject? In an era of whopping government subsidies for
privately owned teams, Kraft won the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Except that now, maybe he hasn't, because the NFL, after
focusing on the still unfinished Washington Redskins sale and the
potential placement of a new franchise in Los Angeles, has clearly
lost its shyness about intervening in the Patriots' move. What
happened?
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on Dan Rooney, the Pittsburgh Steelers' owner. Last
December, Rooney and Paul Kirk Jr., former chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, were at a reception honoring the
Irish winners of the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize. They spoke about
``what a tragedy it would be if the Patriots left the area,''
Rooney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said it didn't look like anybody was doing anything,'' he
added, ``and Paul said it looked like a foregone conclusion that
they're gone. I said, `They still have to take it to the league.'
Paul took it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne said, ``Kirk had a job to do to gauge enthusiasm and to
question whether the Patriots' move to Connecticut was a bluff or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk knew Tagliabue and once worked with him on antitrust
legislation. Kirk assembled a group of business leaders who went
public with their Foxboro plan on April 16, after which Tagliabue's
public enlistment was made possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made very clear our seriousness of purpose,'' Kirk said.
``Many people feel it's very helpful if the NFL commissioner says
what he hears is good. The timing of his visit was great. I feel it
made a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   But there would be a difference between how much richer Kraft
would get in Hartford than in Foxboro. ``We're not coming up with a
plan with the same economic benefits for the owner,'' Kirk said.
</P>
<P>
   You never know what owners will do at an owners' meeting. Will
they vote for what Kraft wants, which is Hartford? Will Kraft, a
league insider and chairman of its finance committee, surrender his
fight for Hartford if Tagliabue twists arms to consider Foxboro?
Are owners truly fearful of losing another large-market team, after
losing teams in Los Angeles and Houston?
</P>
<P>
   Rooney showed little awkwardness in having laid the early
groundwork that might undo the Patriots' deal in Hartford. ``I'm
not saying it's easy, but we have to do the right thing and what's
in the best interest of the NFL and our television partners,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   With 2.2 million television households, Boston is the
sixth-largest television market in the United States. Hartford, the
27th-largest market, has 909,930 TV homes.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue's Boston visit fostered a public-perception problem
for Hartford, not a real one, Pagani said. The burst of positive
talk in Massachusetts is no different from what Kraft heard in the
past, Pagani said, while there is legislation and site preparation
going on in Hartford. ``Our deal hasn't changed,'' he said. ``In
Massachusetts, it's all talk.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Tagliabue is the guest emcee of the talk, Hartford
cannot feel entirely safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
