<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOL-BOARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ABOLISH THE BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, April 27.
</P>
<P>
   Education issues have now risen to the top of the agenda for
some of New York's most powerful and ambitious politicians,
offering an opportunity both to strengthen New York City's school
system and reform it for the future. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Gov.
George Pataki and City Council Speaker Peter Vallone have all
decided that public schools, especially in the city, are in a state
of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The most important long-term reform has been proposed by
Giuliani and Vallone, who are now crafting state legislation to
abolish the city's Board of Education and give the next mayor
direct control of city schools. The bill faces strong opposition in
Albany, but the concept is sound. The current board is a
semi-autonomous body with a representative from each borough and
two mayoral appointees. It approves budgets, sets general policy
and technically picks the schools chancellor, although mayors have
traditionally muscled the board into choosing someone of their
liking.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the schools are of central importance to the city and
the current system has failed to fix their chronic problems, it
makes sense to lodge responsibility for their performance in some
future mayor's office rather than in an entrenched education
bureaucracy. Voters would still exert political control through
citywide elections. Chicago has already made its mayor responsible
for the schools, with promising early results, and Detroit has
followed the same path.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Chancellor Rudy Crew, who has criticized the
mayor's unfortunate comment that the school system should be
``blown up,'' should be a part of this discussion. Crew has
suggested that any new system should work more like a university.
But whatever a new system looks like, Giuliani, Vallone and Pataki,
whose positions on education reflect their various political
ambitions, must recognize that such a long-term reform does not
absolve them of responsibility for today's schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
