<HEADLINE>
PLANS FOR NEW POWER PLANTS LURE INVESTORS, BUT ALSO OPPONENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time in more than two decades,
companies are asking permission to build large power plants in New
York City and the Hudson River Valley, all spurred by the
deregulation of the electric power industry.
</P>
<P>
   Eight proposals have been filed with the New York state Public
Service Commission since August. They include plans for a
520-megawatt, 800-foot-long floating power plant to be moored along
the waterfront in the Sunset Park section of Brooklyn, two separate
1,100-megawatt plants in Ramapo, in Rockland County, and _ furthest
along _ a 1,080-megawatt plant in Athens, 30 miles south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   A 1,000-megawatt plant produces roughly enough power for 1
million small homes. The plants, to be built with money from
private investors instead of ratepayers, are projected to cost from
$350 million to $500 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the plants would cut power bills by increasing
supplies of electricity and generating it more efficiently, fueled
by natural gas, which produce little pollution, instead of oil or
coal, the dirtier fuels burned at the state's older plants.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents say the power is not needed, the giant structures
would mar the landscape, and cooling systems would threaten water
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, as part of the statewide restructuring of the
industry over the past few years, existing older power plants are
being sold by utilities like Consolidated Edison Co. and Central
Hudson Gas &AMP; Electric to independent companies that plan to compete
with the new plants. Some environmental groups say that by
modernizing or expanding the existing plants, the air and water
would be protected without pocking the horizon with new smokestacks
and steam plumes.
</P>
<P>
   All this activity is part of a broader effort to encourage
competition in an industry dominated by local monopolies for a
century. ``While not trying to pre-decide the environmental issues
involved in some of these sites, I think having eight plants here
with applications to build is very good news for customers,'' said
Frank Herbert, the director of the office overseeing the
restructuring of the power industry in the state's Department of
Public Service.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first proposal under consideration is by US Generating Co.,
an arm of Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric, to build a plant powered by
natural gas in Athens. The plant is supported by most elected
officials in Greene County, who say it would be in a lot zoned for
industrial use and would generate taxes and jobs. It is opposed by
private historic preservation and environmental groups, who say it
would ruin the view from several parks and historic homes across
the river in Columbia County.
</P>
<P>
   One view that would be affected is that from Olana, the ornate
Moorish mansion built by Frederic E. Church, a 19th century artist
whose work epitomized the Hudson River School of landscape
painting.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the proximity of the plant to the state-owned mansion,
the state parks commissioner, Bernadette Castro, wrote a letter in
February to the Public Service Commission opposing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the plant, set back two miles from the Hudson,
would be largely hidden from view and many times cleaner than
nearby oil-fired plants. The plume of steam from its cooling
systems would be limited with special equipment, said Daniel J.
Whyte, the director of government relations in the Northeast for US
Generating.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plant would help improve both the river and the air.
Niagara Mohawk, a power company with older plants nearby, projects
that it would have to reduce the amount of power generated at its
plants because of the cheaper power coming from the new competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Scenic Hudson and Riverkeeper Inc., two environmental groups,
dispute the predictions of cuts in pollution and say the plant has
the right technology, but is planned for the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials expressed frustration with the continued
opposition on environmental grounds. ``If there's not a problem
with the air and not a problem with the fish, you've got to find a
problem,'' Whyte said of the environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a floating plant on the Brooklyn waterfront is so
new that it has not become an issue yet. It is being developed by
Sunset Energy Inc., a Manhattan company that is also building a
small gas-fired plant at the Brooklyn Navy Yard.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to put the power plant on huge barges was easy,
said Jerry Montrose, chairman and chief executive officer of Sunset
Energy. There are simply no tracts of industrially zoned land
inside the city big enough to house a plant, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at companies that are buying some of the old power
plants say they should not be counted out in the race to sell
power. For around $480 million, Southern Energy is buying a group
of old Hudson Valley power plants totaling 1,776 megawatts in
generating capacity from Orange and Rockland Utilities Inc. The
company is going to spend $390 million at the existing sites to
increase efficiency, cut pollution and add more natural-gas
generators, Mould said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not predict which strategy would win, saying that they
were all experimental. ``They're different paths to the same end,''
Mould said. ``Price will drive everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
