<HEADLINE>
WELL-SUITED FOR A MUSEUM LUNCH 
NO-SHOW FORGIVEN 
JACKSON UNMASKED 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 BY JAMES BARRON with COREY KILGANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm looking for a friend,'' said Mary Stewart Allen, who was
on the committee that organized Monday's lunch for the Museum of
the City of New York, ``and we all look alike.'' She was right
about that: There were a lot of women in pastel Chanel (or
Chanel-like) suits in the auditorium at the Academy of Medicine, on
Fifth Avenue at 103rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   After a lecture by the art historian Olivier Bernier, the Chanel
(or Chanel-like) suits were seen heading across the street for
lunch at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   At one table, Mario Buatta, one of eight designers who received
awards from the museum, said that his latest project had been a
``big motor yacht in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now on the high seas, where, I hear, the lamps are
falling over, even though they're screwed down,'' he said. ``Those
must have been some swell swells.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he handed David C. Clapp, the president of the museum, a
fake $1 million bill, as if he were making a donation. Zibby Tozer,
a trustee of the museum, and Wendy Moonan, an editor at large at
House &AMP; Garden magazine, both said simultaneously, ``Oh, look, it's
a million-dollar bill'' _ and went back to their conversation.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd was leaving, Suzette de Marigny Smith, another
organizer of the event, found a corner and changed out of her
high-heeled shoes. ``I brought flats, so I can go across the street
and walk,'' she said, referring to the conservatory garden in
Central Park. ``The flowers are at their peak right now.''
</P>
<P>
   No-Show Forgiven
</P>
<P>
   His name was on the invitations, but Mike Espy, the former
Secretary of Agriculture, will not be at a dinner Tuesday night at
Tavern on the Green for the Black Leadership Forum, a confederation
of 26 civil rights and public-service groups that will toast
cabinet members, including Labor Secretary Alexis M. Herman and
Secretary of Veterans Affairs Gen. Togo D. West Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Espy bowed out two weeks ago, saying that he would be on on his
honeymoon. The executive director of the Black Leadership Forum,
Yvonne Scruggs-Leftwich, did not complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriage is a very important commitment,'' she said Monday.
``People who have been there before, as I think he has, at least
want to start out doing it better.''
</P>
<P>
   At Espy's law firm in Jackson, Miss., an aide said that the
wedding took place on April 17. He married Portia D. Ballard, who
had been a senior human resources analyst for Shell Chemical Co.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Unmasked
</P>
<P>
   In case you have ever wondered about the surgical mask that
Michael Jackson wears in public, he wears it in private too.
</P>
<P>
   At least, Rudy Gonzalez says that Jackson was wearing it when he
arrived for dinner in Jackson's suite at the Waldorf-Astoria on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He only took it off when we started eating,'' said Gonzalez,
who added that he got to know Jackson while working as a bodyguard
for Mike Tyson in the early 1990s, an experience he described in
his book, ``The Inner Ring'' (Oliver Publishing Group, 1995).
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said that Jackson offered support for Tyson and even
took down the address of the jail in Maryland where Tyson is an
inmate, along with his release date.
</P>
<P>
   During the dinner Jackson's two young children romped with their
nannies in the suite, which Gonzalez said was heavily guarded.
``You'd think the president was in there,'' he said. ``I don't
think Mike ever leaves the hotel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
