<SLUG> BC-CAR-MARTIN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA SOUNDS GOOD TO MARTIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Having survived 500 miles at Talladega
Superspeedway on Sunday without a major crash, Mark Martin is
heading west, which is just fine with him. After all, he is the
defending champion of the NAPA California 500 set for Sunday at the
California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The race will mark the 400th career NASCAR Winston Cup Series
start for the Batesville, Ark., native. Thanks to Sunday's
third-place finish in the DieHard 500 at the Alabama track, Martin
has moved into the third spot in Winston Cup points. He trails only
Roush Racing teammate Jeff Burton, by 84 points, and fellow Ford
driver Dale Jarrett, by 44.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has never won a Winston championship but has finished
second three times, including last year when he won seven races.
Failure to score major points at Talladega cost him last year in
the scramble with Jeff Gordon for the title and accompanying $2
million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to lose points going into Martinsville (Va.) and
Talladega, and I especially expected to lose points at Talladega,''
said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   He earned 170 points Sunday, more than the 152 he earned in two
races over the same speedway in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel like I've been let out of a cage now,'' Martin said.
``I know that my car will be fairly competitive, in a worst-case
scenario, and if it's as good as it usually is, then we should be a
contender to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has excelled over the two-mile speedway in Fontana. He
dominated the field in 1998, leading 159 of 250 laps en route to a
1.287-second victory over Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   In the inaugural race at Fontana, Martin was leading until he
ran out of gas with 11 laps to go and had to be pushed into the
pits. Gordon took the victory and Martin returned after refueling
to finish 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't exactly put my finger on it,'' the 40-year-old Martin
said about his success at Fontana. ``It's a situation that we have
a beautiful, nice, big, open speedway, and it suits my driving
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seemed to have adapted to it quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Martin has three total wins. In addition to the
California 500 victory last year, he's also won two International
Race of Champion (IROC) races at Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a race track that you can go out there and let it
all out,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Which was not the case over the weekend in Alabama. NASCAR
mandates restrictor plates on carburetors at Talladega, which tends
to bunch up the pack and often results in spectacular crashes. In
1998, Martin was involved in such wrecks in both races there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's truly a relief to not only get out of Talladega without
getting hurt at all but with a race car in one piece,'' said
Martin, who has won 30 Cup events since he started racing in 1981.
``We scored some points, we did well. Some of the competitors that
seem to be fortunate to not get caught up in that stuff, it seems
like bad luck went their way instead of our way this time. So I'm
relieved and ready to go racing, real racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's confident the Roush crew will have his car set to go.
In the nine Winston Cup races thus far, Martin has scored seven
top-10 finishes, including a win at Rockingham (N.C.), and six
top-five showings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to say that I know going to California that we're
going to run good,'' said Martin. ``I know that. If that mentally
helps me run good, then it does. But when we go to Michigan or
California or Charlotte or Las Vegas, there's no question in my
mind that we're going to be very competitive because those are
tracks we do real well on.''
</P>
<P>
   But just don't tell him that winning at Fontana is more special
than any other venue on the Winston Cup schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that you can just say one race (stands above
another). You have to realize how hard it is to win a race,'' said
Martin. ``I mean, they're all huge. They're all incredibly hard to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're coming to California and there are gonna be 50 cars
there and the only race in the whole wide world to them is
California, until the checkered flag flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's over, there's going to be a winner and all the rest
are going to pack up and focus on the next race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
