<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BE FAIR ABOUT SCHOOL FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, April 27:
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens with vouchers and governance, New York City's
schools most urgently need to gain their fair share of funding from
the state. The annual battle over state school spending is
aggravated this year by Gov. Pataki's reneging on an earlier
commitment, made when he was running for re-election, to increase
aid for preschool and reading programs. The city and other large
urban school districts were counting on the money to pay for
teachers, remedial programs and new classrooms. Now those plans are
in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki backtracked because he and the Legislature enacted not
only big school-aid increases but also big property tax cuts. Now
the governor is worried that the money may not be there to pay for
both programs as they grow. But by cutting school aid, while
leaving the property tax cuts intact, he is once again hurting
cities and helping residents of the wealthier suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's schools have been punished enough. With 38
percent of the state's pupils, they would get only 35 percent of
overall state aid under the latest Pataki budget proposal. The
governor had pledged to correct that imbalance, but his new budget
is moving in the opposite direction. His effort to collapse myriad
state programs into block grants has been put forward as a
smokescreen to cut aid to the students who need it most. The
Legislature, the governor and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani should set
aside their disputes over other matters and enact school aid
programs that would help the urban school systems that need it the
most.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-26-99 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
