<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CREW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCELLOR ASSAILS MAYOR'S REMARKS ON SCHOOL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew on Monday accused Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani of dismissing the city's school system and
everyone in it ``as no good and beyond redemption,'' sharply
escalating the recent series of disagreements between the two men
and raising questions anew about whether the chancellor intends to
remain in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent late Monday to 600 political, civic and
educational leaders in New York and Albany, Crew replied in tones
of anger and dismay to the mayor's comment last week that the
school system was ``dysfunctional'' and should be ``blown up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the mayor declares that the whole school system should be
blown up, he tells 1.1 million children and thousands of parents,
teachers and administrators that they are wasting their time,'' the
chancellor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Giuliani had urged him not to take last week's
remarks personally, Crew added, ``It is hard to tell these
thousands of people not to take it personally when the mayor is
implying that their achievements have amounted to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Crew felt compelled to defend his record and the
school system in light of Giuliani's determination during the last
five days to press ahead with his campaign for vouchers and for the
abolition of the Board of Education in favor of a commissioner who
would report directly to the mayor. The chancellor's office faxed
copies of the letter to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, Giuliani, apparently unaware that the letter
was being faxed as he spoke, repeated that he did not mean his
criticism of the system to be interpreted as a personal insult to
the chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't say anything about our relationship other than I
don't understand it,'' Giuliani told reporters at a police
graduation ceremony. ``I mean, the things that I've said last week,
I've said over and over again, and I've said to Rudy Crew
directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has proposed a voucher program using tax dollars to pay
the private school tuition of 3,000 children from low income
families. He says the plan would provide an escape from failing
public schools and create competition that would improve the public
school system.
</P>
<P>
   Like previous mayors, Giuliani has argued that the Board of
Education serves the political interests of the five borough
presidents more than the schoolchildren it should represent. He has
proposed putting the schools directly under the control of the
mayor and the council.
</P>
<P>
   Both proposals face an uncertain future in the City Council and
the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Chiara Coletti, the chancellor's spokeswoman, said Crew
agreed that the seven-member Board of Education is overly
political, but believed that a commissioner appointed by the mayor
would be even more subject to political whims. On Saturday, Crew
said he would resign if the board was replaced with a city
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor did not return telephone requests Monday seeking
comment on Crew's letter. Crew was returning from a conference in
Roanoke, Va., on Monday, his spokeswoman said, and did not want to
comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Coletti said that although Crew had been mentioned as a
candidate for the superintendent's job in San Francisco, which is
vacant, she denied that he was interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not on the way out,'' she said. ``When he really thinks
his honor is at stake, and the honor of public schools _ he sees
New York as the symbol of the country _ he's the kind of person who
digs in his heels.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said Crew's vehemently public reaction to the mayor's
comments hardly seemed calculated to dampen speculation about his
commitment to the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually these things are worked out behind closed doors,''
said Frank J. Macchiarola, the schools chancellor from 1978 to
1983, who is now president of St. Francis College in Brooklyn.
``What does it mean? It may mean the chancellor will be looking for
another job. I wouldn't put that out of the realm of the
possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
