<SLUG> BC-CAR-CARNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENSON PENALIZED FOR HIS BAD TIMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ When the NASCAR Winston Cup drivers finally
get on the track at the California Speedway on Friday morning,
don't look for the No. 26 Cheerios Ford driven by Johnny Benson.
</P>
<P>
   Benson has been given the NASCAR equivalent of a timeout. He
will miss the first 20 minutes of the opening practice session for
the NAPA California 500 on Friday as a penalty for being late to
the pre-race inspection last Sunday at Alabama's Talladega
Superspeedway for the DieHard 500.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark the second straight race in which Benson has missed
practice time because of a rules infraction. Friday's initial
practice for Winston Cup drivers starts at 10:30 a.m. and runs 55
minutes. A second session, an hour in length, will begin at 12:30
p.m. and will precede the Bud Pole qualifying runs at 2:30.
</P>
<P>
   The late arrival of a rear gear caused the Roush Racing team to
be late. The team waited for the part Sunday morning, but the plane
carrying the part was late. Benson's team pulled out of the
inspection line when the part arrived and took the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In the first practice for the DieHard race, Benson sat out the
first 10 minutes for not having his car at the cut-off point for
pre-race inspection the week before in Martinsville, Va., for the
Goody's 500.
</P>
<P>
   __ Back to Fontana: Stanton Barrett, a Hollywood stuntman, is
returning to Southern California, this time behind the wheel of the
Busch Grand National series ChanneLock Chevrolet. He competed in
the inaugural Busch race in 1997, qualifying seventh before a
series of problems dropped him to 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far this season, the 26-year-old Bishop native has driven
for two different Winston Cup teams, including his own and one for
veteran car owner Junie Donlavey. He was hired as a full-time
driver for the ChanneLock car just three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran at California two years ago and it was a strange but
kind of rewarding experience. If nothing else, I learned how to
pass there,'' said Barrett, who has appeared in such films as
``Batman,'' ``Free Jack,'' ``Mars Attacks'' and ``Last of the
Mohicans,'' in addition to television shows ``Beverly Hills 90210''
and ``Baywatch.'' ``I passed a lot of cars all day long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had been able to add them all together and counted that,
it might have been a heck of a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's banking on his past for Saturday's Auto Club 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has the experience I have at California. I don't know
of anybody who has been in every single different position during a
race there,'' he said. ``I've been in every single different
position two or three times in a lot of cases. I've been in the
back, I've been in the front and I've been in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front is a lot better, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ NASCAR channel? The recent announcement by NASCAR that the
sanctioning body would consolidate its future television rights has
created plenty of speculation as to how much the package would be
worth and who's interested.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, there were estimates the entire package could be
worth around $200-400 million per year. The money would be split 60
(track promoters), 25 (drivers), 15 (NASCAR).
</P>
<P>
   Televising races has long been the domain of ESPN, Turner and
TNN, with occasional races on CBS and ABC. NBC joined the party
this year after losing football and picked up the Homestead race.
Other possibilities include Fox and an all-NASCAR Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a work in progress; we're working hard on the whole
program,'' NASCAR president and CEO Mike Helton said recently.
``It's not something we're prepared to talk a whole lot about.
There are many details to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do the right thing. We hope it'll be fun,
exciting and a lot of new elements that come out of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
