<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NRA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN ILL-TIMED NRA MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, April 27:
</P>
<P>
   After the Littleton school shootings, the National Rifle
Association said it would shorten its annual meeting in Denver next
weekend from three days to one, and cancel exhibits by gun dealers
and manufacturers. The NRA should listen to Denver's mayor and
cancel the conference altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, which is fiercely opposed to sensible gun laws, has
urged its members to attend as a show of unity, if only for a day.
On a purely emotional level, this is an insult to grieving families
and to a city still shaken by tragedy. Mayor Wellington Webb
bluntly told the group last week, ``We don't want you here.''
</P>
<P>
   On a practical level, the mayor worries that anger over the
shootings may cause confrontations between the gun group and local
residents. A large anti-gun protest is planned during the NRA
meeting. Although the protest is expected to be peaceful, the
convention raises security concerns that the city should not have
to deal with right now.
</P>
<P>
   About the only good thing that can be said for the NRA's
insensitivity is that it has reinforced the opposition already
generated by the Littleton shootings to the NRA agenda in the
Colorado legislature. Several NRA-supported bills that were
expected to become law just days before the shootings have been
derailed. Among other things, these bills would have gutted
municipal gun-control ordinances and made it easier for citizens to
carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The gun lobby can hardly be counted out. In the past it has
shamelessly bounced back after devastating events to continue
fighting even modest laws, like those requiring safety devices on
weapons. But for now, the NRA should at least allow Denver to mourn
in peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
