<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SCHOOL-THREAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN IN TEXAS DISCUSSES OWN SCHOOL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBERLEY, Texas _ Three days after four eighth graders were
charged with plotting to blow up Danforth Junior High School here,
more than 400 teachers, parents and students crowded into the
school cafeteria on Monday night to ask law-enforcement officials
about the case.
</P>
<P>
   But with the presiding judge having prohibited lawyers and
officials from talking about the case, the meeting became a
discussion of the community and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Morales, who came with his eighth-grade daughter, Desiree,
said: ``We moved here six months ago from McAllen because of the
crime situation with gangs down there. We were even home schooling
her to keep her away from that situation. The news of this blew us
away.''
</P>
<P>
   But several parents said the crisis should be an impetus to get
more involved in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had only been the shooting in Littleton, we might not
have had the motivation to act,'' said Lee Williams, the mother of
two students in the district, referring to the attack last week on
a school in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth reopened on Monday with 90 percent of its 400 students
attending, said David Simmons, superintendent of the Wimberley
Independent School District.
</P>
<P>
   The four boys, who were taken into custody on Friday after other
students told school officials they had heard them talking about
their plan, appeared on Monday afternoon before Judge Howard Warner
of County Court at Law. Warner ordered them held until a later
detention hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators think that the boys, who are being held on
juvenile charges of conspiracy to commit murder and arson and to
manufacture explosives, began planning the attack in January and
that the plot was not connected to the shootings in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Searches of the homes of the boys, all 14, turned up several
explosive devices, gunpowder and bomb-making instructions that had
been downloaded from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Classmates described them as ``good kids'' who played football
and ran track. Gary S. Smith, an eighth grader who said he was a
friend of the four boys, sat at a folding table in the cafeteria on
Monday night shaking his head in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this thing has been blown out of proportion,'' Smith
said. ``I didn't think they would have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was clearly in the minority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
