<SLUG> BC-TEX-DEADKIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officers talk to man who was with Cornelius
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Williamson County sheriff's investigators on
Monday interrogated a man who says he was with the missing mother
of two slain children hours before their bodies were pulled from
Brushy Creek near Hutto.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Austin man, who claims Tina Marie Cornelius told
him her son and daughter fell to their death from a cliff while
visiting one of their fathers, is cooperating with the
investigation, sheriff's Capt. Linda Bunte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did come up here,'' Bunte said Monday afternoon. ``He's
talking to us now.''
</P>
<P>
   The man, who asked to remain anonymous because he says he fears
for his safety, contacted an American-Statesman reporter last
Thursday just before midnight and said he had information about
Cornelius. Investigators spent the weekend looking for the man, who
agreed Monday to talk to deputies.
</P>
<P>
   The man, an El Paso native who works as a glass installer, says
he met Cornelius on Saturday, April 17 at the Bob Marley Festival
at Auditorium Shores and that he shared a weekend fling with the
topless dancer. He said that the next day he was with Cornelius at
Mansfield Dam on Lake Travis when she told him her children had
died.
</P>
<P>
   A Round Rock couple found the bodies of 3-year-old Amanda Lee
Miller and Dominick Logan Cornelius, 2, shortly before 5 p.m. on
April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe Miller, who died of suffocation, and her
brother, who suffered a fatal skull fracture, were dumped in the
creek near County Road 137 just hours before the discovery.
Officers have been trying to locate Cornelius, but by Monday night
had not been able to find her. Several sources have said she was
last seen a week ago today dancing at Expose, an adult
entertainment club on South Congress Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's officials have said Cornelius is not a suspect in her
children's slayings and that they fear for her safety.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have obtained a receipt from a Ramada Limited
hotel that indicates someone using Cornelius' name stayed in the
hotel a week ago Sunday. The man who claims he spent the weekend
with Cornelius has said he was with her at the hotel until around
7:30 the following Monday morning _ the day the bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Smith, a Round Rock woman who says she baby-sat
Cornelius' children from October 1997 until January, said she fears
Cornelius may be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's not alive. I think something happened to her
also,'' Smith said. ``I don't think she's somewhere hiding.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she has not seen Cornelius in the past two months and
called Cornelius a ``very good mom,'' who worked several jobs to
take care of her children.
</P>
<P>
   Smith remembers Dominick and Amanda getting excited each day
when their mother picked them up after working at the Wal-Mart
automotive center on RM 620 near U.S. 183.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd come in and they could see her from the window and
they'd get very excited,'' Smith said. ``She'd pick them up and
she'd take them to the park and play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
