<HEADER>
A4389 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-BANKROBBER-CO     04-26 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-BANKROBBER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man, 78, held in bank robbery
 &HT;    By Matt Mossman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A 78-year-old Pompano Beach man who once
kayaked his way to freedom from prison and picked his way out of
leg irons in a hospital was captured on a bank robbery charge last
week after deputies forced him to drive into a palm tree.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest, after a Jupiter bank robbery, is the latest chapter
in the criminal epic of Forrest Silva Tucker, a lifelong bank
robber and escape artist and once the head of a silver-haired band
of South Florida crooks dubbed the ``Over-the-Hill Gang.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuckerlast made headlines in 1983 when he led authorities on a
spectacular chase and shootout on Palm Beach Lakes Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   He was seen last Thursday leaving the Republic Security Bank on
S. U.S. 1 with about $6,000, Broward County sheriff's Detective
James Chinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, acting on a tip, deputies parked near his
girlfriend's home. They watched him leave and tried to pull him
over, but he wouldn't stop.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his earlier escapes, this one ended quickly. Deputies
forced him into the parking lot of an elementary school west of
Pompano Beach and made him crash into a palm tree. They found guns,
burglary tools, police scanners and a large amount of cash in his
vehicle, the sheriff's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker remained Monday without bond in the Broward County Jail
on a federal bank robbery charge. Chinn said he suspects Tucker in
at least four bank robberies in Broward County. The FBI also is
investigating Tucker for other Palm Beach County bank robberies.
</P>
<P>
   The chase Thursday was less of a spectacle than the wild ride on
June 10, 1983. Tucker, a suspect in several robberies, opened fire
on FBI agents approaching his Buick Riviera near Palm Beach Lakes
Boulevard. The car sputtered during the getaway, so Tucker took the
car of a mother driving with her two children, according to news
reports. The chase down Palm Beach Lakes evolved into gunfire, and
eventually Tucker and partner Ted Green, then 69, were caught.
Tucker was sentenced to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was first arrested in 1935 as a 15-year-old bicycle
thief. In 1951 he picked the lock on leg irons holding him in
Miami's Jackson Memorial Hospital, then strolled away unnoticed. He
was there recovering from appendicitis before he was to start
serving a five-year prison sentence for robbing a Miami bank of
$475. He was caught two years later after a Berkeley, Calif., bank
robbery. He's been in and out of prison since then.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's most daring escape came at the maximum-security prison
at San Quentin, Calif., in 1979. Tucker and two other inmates built
a 14-foot kayak from wood scraps and rowed to freedom from the
peninsula. They painted the craft with the logo of the Marin County
Yacht Club, and named it the Rub-a-Dub-Dub.
</P>
<P>
   After the escape, Tucker resurfaced in South Florida, leading
the Over-the-Hill Gang, which specialized in robbing banks. Victims
described Tucker and Green as polite and sharply dressed.
</P>
<P>
   Often resourceful, Tucker disguised a police radio as a hearing
aid and once got a reduced sentence after representing himself
before the U.S. Supreme Court, according to a 1983 story in The
Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker hasn't lost his driving edge, either, Detective Chinn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was really impressed with his driving, since it was
rush-hour traffic,'' Chinn said. Nonetheless, Tucker got a citation
for reckless driving.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Mossman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Lynne Palombo contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
