<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-729&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE OF THE KILLERS ENVISIONED A FAR BIGGER SLAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS to ADD in lede that dairy was kept for more than a year,
sheriff's spokesman saying he has `no idea' why New York was
mentioned at a target, details from later funerals; CORRECTS name
of church in graf bgng, ``Cassie died a martyr's death ...', to
West Bowles, sted Bowled.) 
 (An overview; see also COLO-SCHOOL-JONESBORO) 
(ART ADV: 2 photos, NYT19 and NYT10, are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mb) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ As he planned the assault on Columbine High
School, Eric Harris wrote in a diary that he envisioned killing as
many as 500 students, going on to attack neighboring homes and then
hijacking a jet and crashing it in New York City, police
investigators said Monday after reviewing a diary that he had kept
for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   There is no evidence that Harris or his accomplice, Dylan
Klebold, took any steps to carry out the full scheme, but Steve
Davis, a spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department,
said, ``If in fact they were able to carry out their entire plan,
there could have been quite a bit more damage and quite a few more
fatalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he had ``no idea'' why Harris ahd New York in mind.
The officials did not release the contents of the diary.
</P>
<P>
   As funerals were held Monday for four of the 13 victims of the
suicide assault last Tuesday by the two seniors, who apparently
brought four guns and as many as 30 pipe bombs to school,
detectives questioned an 18-year-old girlfriend of one of the
gunmen in an effort to determine whether anyone else knew of the
plot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a female who I believe had access to this weapon
prior to Tuesday,'' Dave Thomas, the Jefferson County district
attorney said, referring to a semiautomatic TEC-9 pistol recovered
with the suspects' bodies. The manufacture of the assault-style
semiautomatic pistol has been banned since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking into how she got access to that weapon, and
what involvement she may have had,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney and the sheriff's spokesman emphasized
that no arrests were imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not called her a suspect at the time, by any means,''
Davis said. ``There is no arrest warrant either.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a reporter's question about the four guns found in
the school, Davis said, ``She was questioned on the handgun and the
rifle, not the shotguns. Nothing has been confirmed as far as her
supplying those weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said that of the four guns recovered, the two shotguns
appear to have been manufactured more 25 years ago. Records
indicate the pistol and the rifle were purchased recently from a
Colorado gun dealer, he has said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Colorado and federal law, a minor cannot own a handgun,
and it is illegal to give or sell a handgun to someone under 18. It
is legal for someone 18 or older to buy a handgun through a private
sale, reached through a classified advertisement or a gun show. In
contrast, federally licensed dealers are not allowed to sell
handguns to someone under 21.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, where surveys indicate that almost half of
households have guns, there are gun fairs almost every weekend. At
these shows, private sellers do not have to conduct background
checks on buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Bomb squad investigators continued to search the grounds Monday.
Speaking with the cordoned-off school behind him, Davis said there
remained ``many, many lockers to go through, many, many backpacks
to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold, who were both seniors at Columbine, had
apparently pinned their hopes on blowing up their school to a
25-pound propane bomb in the school's kitchen that they had planned
to detonate. When the timing device failed, Davis said ``there were
indications that they had possibly tried to fire on that bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Toxicology tests on the bodies of the two youths did not show
traces of drugs or alcohol, the coroner's office said Monday. Davis
also said that investigators had not found any illicit drugs or
drug paraphernalia at their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the two youths had hired lawyers and had not
spoken with investigators since last Wednesday, Davis said..
</P>
<P>
   Officials Monday also briefly addressed complaints that the
authorities had been made aware of threats by Harris, but did
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Brooks Brown, a classmate of the suspects, have
disclosed that they notified the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department eight times last year with complaints that Harris, a
neighbor, had threatened their son. The couple, Randy and Judy
Brown, said that after Harris chipped the windshield of their son's
car, he created a computer game that revolved around destroying the
Brown house and created a web site that featured a death threat
against their son and accounts of manufacturing and exploding pipe
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Harris and Klebold were on probation at the time,
Jefferson County detectives never followed up on the complaints,
the Browns have said. On Monday, Davis said that a ``suspicious
incident'' report had been located. Later, he added, ``This is part
of the ongoing investigation and I do not want to make any comments
about that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said, ``As far as I know, nothing was ever brought to my
office.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While trading at the nation's four busiest stock exchanges came
to a halt for one minute at noon Monday in memory of the 13
victims, this Denver suburb endured a numbing marathon of funerals.
Three students and the one teacher who was killed, William Sanders,
were buried.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,500 people turned out for the funeral of Sander's, who
had taught and coached at the school for 25 years. Last Tuesday as
shots rang out at lunch, Sanders, a grandfather, jumped on a table
in the school cafeteria and shouted for students to duck, and then
to get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was running around, and I remember seeing him jumping over
the chairs and yelling `Everybody get down!''' Lindsay Dowling, a
student recalled. ``I truly believe he saved my life and many other
people's.''
</P>
<P>
   As he ran through the halls, herding students to safety, the
teacher was shot twice in the chest. After taking him into a
barricaded classroom, students tried to keep his spirits up by
showing him wallet photos of his wife and three daughters. A
teacher spent hours on a cell phone getting advice for how to care
for him, and many students have said they took off their shirts to
help mop up blood. But he died shortly after being freed by the
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to thank him for saving my life,'' Laurel Salerno,
another student who escaped the cafeteria, said in a church
overflowing with students. ``Mr. Sanders, I thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, at the same time, another 1,000 mourners attended the
funeral of Cassie Bernall, a 17-year-old junior, who often wore a
bracelet inscribed ``WWJD'' _ shorthand for `What would Jesus do?'
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, one of the attackers cornered her in the library,
trained a gun on her, looked in her blue eyes, and asked if she
believed in God. After a pause, surviving students have recounted,
Miss Bernall, a born-again Christian, answered deliberately, ``Yes,
I believe in God.'' He then shot her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cassie died a martyr's death,'' the Rev. George Kristen of the
West Bowles Community Church said. ``She went to the martyr's hall
of fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, a funeral was held for Lauren Townsend, an
18-year-old senior who was captain of the girls varsity volleyball
team and a National Honor Society scholar. She was to have been the
class valedictorian at graduation ceremonies next month. Monday, a
letter arrived at her home here, offering her a college
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   The last funeral of the day was for Daniel Rohrbough, a
15-year-old freshman who was shot holding an exit door open for
other students. He was last seen alive running and screaming for
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   As temperatures warmed in Denver, hundreds of people continued
to make somber pilgrimages to a memorial site in a park near the
high school. Many parked a half-mile away to add to the thousands
of bouquets.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 students from other high schools marched up to nine
miles to the site. Referring to the killers, one held a placard to
passing cars, ``There are more of us than there are of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a teen-ager,'' said one marcher, Morgen Warner, a junior
from Jefferson County Open School. ``This affects me more deeply
than any adult could even begin to comprehend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
