<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HARTSBRG-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTSBURG IMPRESSES PLAYERS, MANAGEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ For four seasons, the Mighty Ducks followed
Ron Wilson down his Yellow Brick Road. In the 1997-98 season,
Pierre Page's ramblings left them on the road to nowhere. But the
team is back on the straight and narrow under coach Craig
Hartsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Ducks stand one game away from elimination at the
hands of the Detroit Red Wings, Hartsburg's competitive juices
continue to flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys have shown a lot of pride all year and we want to go
out battling and fighting,'' Hartsburg said Monday of tonight's
game. ``We have built some things with our work ethic and I don't
want anything to slip. We want to make it tough on Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg, 39, won't settle for anything but a maximum effort
tonight, but then again that's what he's demanded of the Ducks
since day one of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was all business and we knew there's nothing wrong
with that,'' said Anaheim center Steve Rucchin. ``All he wants is
the best out of his team and that basically comes down to hard work
and dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   Directness and a good work ethic are among the traits that
Hartsburg said he learned early on from his father Bill and his
mother Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do your best, don't accept anything but your best,'' Hartsburg
said when asked their influence. ``If you can't do something to the
best of your ability, then you are cheating yourself. It doesn't
matter what it is, coaching, playing or raising my own kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks floundered to a 26-43-13 record in a confusing '97-98
season that featured numerous system changes by Page, along with
Paul Kariya's holdout and concussion. They were picked to be among
the worst teams in the league this season but surprised many by
finishing 35-34-13 and qualifying for the playoffs despite a
late-season slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be blamed for last year,'' said goalie Guy
Hebert. ``But I don't know if it would have got any better (by
maintaining the status quo).''
</P>
<P>
   Having Kariya healthy for 82 games certainly helped the cause,
as did a lack of serious injuries, but Hartsburg's simple, direct
approach was a big factor as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to win, everybody has to be on the same page
and that comes from Craig and the coaching staff (assistants Newell
Brown and George Burnett),'' said Rucchin. ``He's done a great job
of drilling into our heads how we want to play as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wilson was a media darling and big on motivational
speeches _ like the Wizard of Oz one he used late in the '96-97
season _ and Page struggled for answers from the time he was hired,
Hartsburg has stoically gone about his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team comes first (with Hartsburg),'' said Ducks general
manager Pierre Gauthier, who inherited Hartsburg after former GM
Jack Ferreira hired him on July 21, 1998. ``I'm not a big fan of
prima donna coaches because sometimes they come first. He's an
organization guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg was a loyal organization guy in Chicago, but that
didn't prevent him from being fired after the less-than-talented
Blackhawks failed to make the playoffs last season for the first
time in 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not much fun because you feel you've let a lot of people
down,'' he said of being fired.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg said he went through stages of anger and
self-evaluation, but in keeping with his approach to life, he tried
to turn a negative into a positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stay angry too long, you won't progress and learn the
lesson you need to learn,'' he explained. ``Anytime you go through
adversity you learn a lot. But it's not like I had any doubts about
myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
