<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MEET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING STRESSES ITS VALUE TO STOCKHOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The top leadership of The Boeing Co. sounded what
has become a very familiar theme here Monday when they faced
shareholders at the company's annual meeting _ value, value value.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of struggling to build a lot of airplanes and
make money at the same time, executives said Boeing is committed to
a new way of doing business that will return the aerospace giant to
the ranks of the most profitable manufacturing companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a new team totally focused on creating value for you,
our shareholders, for our customers, for our employees,'' Chairman
Phil Condit told shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing is a very different company from one year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   But apparently many shareholders, well aware that Boeing's stock
was the worst performer on the Dow last year, are impatient with
the pace of change. That sentiment was reflected in a vote on a
shareholder proposal that called for the annual election of
Boeing's entire 12-member board.
</P>
<P>
   The same proposal was voted down by shareholders at the last two
annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the proposal was supported by 49.9 percent of shares
voted, with 47.8 percent against. The remainder abstained.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing management said later that the proposal was not approved
because it did not receive more than 50 percent of the vote. Even
if it had, Boeing said, shareholder proposals are not binding. That
would require a 75 percent approval vote to change company bylaws.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the annual meeting, Condit did say
the issue was something the company would ``look at'' in light of
the vote. But he stressed Boeing's long-held position that it is
important to have continuity on the board, and annual elections
would interfere with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a business that has a very important long-term piece
to it,'' he said. ``Continuity on the board has a real advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Other shareholder proposals were soundly defeated, including one
that would have required Boeing to adopt human rights criteria
before doing business with China, and another that would have
established criteria in bidding for military contracts. Both were
submitted by church groups and both have been defeated at past
annual meetings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the somewhat surprising vote on the proposal for
election of board members, the mood of shareholders also was
reflected in the applause that several received from fellow
shareholders when they stood to ask Condit questions during a
question-and-answer portion of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   They asked tough questions, but most were generally supportive
of the company's new focus on value.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholder Joe Bishop was applauded as much as anyone who spoke
when he told Condit:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious I'm not alone in being disappointed with the
performance of the company's stock the last couple of years. But
the reason I'm still here today and haven't bailed out yet is that
I still hold the same promise for Boeing that I did when I invested
a couple years ago. From a pure business standpoint, Boeing has the
best business opportunity of any company in the entire world.''
</P>
<P>
   That message of value also was stressed by Debby Hopkins,
Boeing's new chief financial officer. She was the only other
executive to address shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made changes. We've moved forward with new business
opportunities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Boeing has posted a solid first quarter and
its stock is up 21 percent, which is better than the Dow averages.
But Condit and Hopkins said the company must do even better.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives announced early this year they would eliminate
``value destroying'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   One of those programs that is getting a close look is the 717,
Boeing's new 100-seater passenger jet that is built in Long Beach,
just down the road from the site of Monday's annual meeting at Los
Angeles International Airport's Westin Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is ending production in Long Beach of the McDonnell
Douglas line of planes _ the MD-90, MD-80 and MD-11. That leaves
only the 717 and the C-17, the Air Force cargo plane. The C-17 is
one of Boeing's most profitable programs.
</P>
<P>
   But there is growing concern in Long Beach the company will kill
the 717 because orders have so far been disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Condit said there is a good market for a
100-seat plane, but the question remains whether the 717 program
can be profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make it up as you go,'' Condit said. ``Either you
are able to sell the airplane or you are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing must attack costs on the 717, he said. ``It is one of
those programs where we need to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong emphasis on value and cutting costs did raise
concerns with the leaders of the union that represents many Boeing
engineers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its cost-cutting measures, Boeing plans to reduce
companywide employment by 50,000 by the end of next year. The
company later this year must negotiate new contracts with its two
largest unions _ the 51,000-member Machinists union and the
24,000-member Seattle Professional Engineering Employees
Association, or SPEEA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must balance the interest of shareholders, customers and
employees if we are to retain our position as aerospace leader,''
Stan Sorscher, SPEEA chairman, told Condit.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bofferding, the union's executive director, said it is
time for the union to have a seat on Boeing's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to battle shareholders or customers for
limited resources,'' he said. ``Our goal is to fight hard to
finally balance the interests of all stakeholders (employees,
customers and shareholders.)''
</P>
<P>
   During the question-and-answer session, Condit was asked about
the upcoming union negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   He said he remains optimistic agreements can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   This marked only the second time Boeing's annual meeting has
been held outside of Seattle. It was held in St. Louis last year.
It will be held in Seattle next year. Boeing is rotating the
meeting sites to better reflect the breadth of the new Boeing Co.
following the 1997 merger with defense giant McDonnell Douglas. In
1996, Boeing also acquired the aerospace business of Rockwell
International.
</P>
</TEXT>
